<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: HUNDLEY COMES MARCHIN' HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On this first day after the All-Star Game break, the
Mets' clubhouse was filled with music and the chatter of players
back at work after three days off. There was news, too, with
manager Bobby Valentine having to deal with the fact that John
Franco, the ace closer, would be suspended for three games for
bumping an umpire during a disputed game-ending play at the plate
last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension wasn't the first news a manager wanted to hear
coming off the all-star break. ``At least they didn't ruin my three
days off,'' Valentine joked. But the bigger buzz was all about the
impending return of Todd Hundley to the Mets' slumping lineup on
Saturday night. Where will he play? Whose place will he take?
Bernard Gilkey, the slumping left fielder? Brian McRae, the center
fielder? Butch Huskey, the right fielder? Each is hitting below
.250.
</P>
<P>
   The general consensus among the outfielders was that if Hundley
arrived and the Mets won, everything would work out. ``If we win,
everyone will be happy,'' McRae said. The taciturn Huskey simply
said, ``The name of the game is win. W-I-N.'' Gilkey took a larger
view. Win or lose, he said, the team needed a jump start.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a boost,'' Gilkey said. ``We've been playing flat. We
need something to pick us up.'' The 31-year-old veteran was being
honest. For all the talk about Hundley coming and platooning,
Gilkey was looking forward to remaining an everyday player. ``I've
been an everyday player for eight years.'' he said. ``That is what
I want to cultivate.''
</P>
<P>
   But if duty calls? ``I'm ready to change positions, if that's
what it takes,'' he said. ``I'm ready to sit down, then fight my in a company videotape a few years ago, ``and
you ought to use them in the same proportion.''
</P>
<P>
   A typical telephon call from Calloway might go on for two
hours, Enrico added, with only about five words actually being
spoken by Callway. One Pepsi executive, summoned to lunch alone
with Calloway one day, spent the entire time struggling to think of
ways to break the silence. As the coffee was being served, Calloway
finally spoke, saying, ``Why don't we finish this conversation in
my office?''
</P>
<P>
   Calloway was a director of General Electric, Exxon and Citicorp
when he died, in addition to Pepsico. He was also chairman of the
board at Wake Forest and an enthusiastic supporter who often
interviewed student applicants from the New York area in his
office, said the president, Thomas Hearn. About five years ago, the
university's School of Business and Accountancy was named for
Calloway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I always admired about him was his insight into
people,'' said GE chairman John Welch, who called Calloway ``a
beautiful man'' who displayed great courage during his long
illness. ``He could really read people. People we had known for
years and knew little things about, he would glean in two meetings.
It was an amazing talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Calloway is survived by his mother, Lether Smith of
Winston-Salem; his wife, Janice, of Greenwich; a son, David, of
Austin, Texas; a daughter, Jennifer, of Manhattan; two stepsons,
Ross Smythe of Dallas and Boyd Smythe of Boston, and two
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
