<SLUG> BC-NY-COLUMN-BRAWLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: 3 BRAWLEY DEFENDANTS DEFTLY JUGGLE THE FACTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ The Tawana Brawley defamation case may
deserve to be called the trial of the century, but only because it
looked as though it might last that long. For all the attention
that it has drawn through eight insufferable months, it has had
about as much redeeming social value as a Jerry Springer episode.
</P>
<P>
   If you wanted significance and not sideshow, you'd have done
better to skip the second-floor Brawley courtroom and walk another
two flights in the Dutchess County Courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   That is where Dalkeith McIntosh was found guilty Wednesday of
first-degree murder. In little over a month, New York state has
seen two criminal defendants face possible execution, the first two
under the 1995 capital-punishment law. Expect death row to keep
growing.
</P>
<P>
   But to give the Brawley trial its due, it has provided a useful
lesson or two, especially about the meaning of truth.
</P>
<P>
   It is up to six jurors, who finished their first full day of
deliberations Thursday, to decide whether the Rev. Al Sharpton and
two co-defendants showed a reckless disregard for the truth when
they accused Dutchess County prosecutor Steven Pagones of raping
Ms. Brawley in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The key word in this defamation lawsuit brought by Pagones is
``reckless.'' But that's from a legal perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Common sense does not require a jury verdict to conclude that
Sharpton and his Brawley-advising mates, C. Vernon Mason and Alton
Maddox, had shown a regard for the truth so slight that it would
not be detectable on any known scale.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven years later, Mason and Maddox continue to label Pagones a
rapist and even a murderer, while Sharpton does verbal dances
around the question. Have they backed up any of those smears with
hard evidence? Don't be ridiculous. They have yet to offer anything
but innuendo and knowing smirks _ absolutely nothing to refute a
1988 grand jury report that essentially branded the Brawley affair
a hoax. A racially explosive hoax at that.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton said on the witness stand here that his purpose was to
speak up for a black teen-ager who had hollered ``rape'' at a group
of white men. Finding out whether there was any reality to her
accusations never flashed on his radar screen, he acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   And that attitude toward the truth _ certainly cavalier, whether
or not the jury calls it reckless _ might be worth bearing in mind
the next time Sharpton asks New York voters to put him into public
office. His political ambition gives this case whatever scant
significance it may have.
</P>
<P>
   Mason and Maddox have long overstayed their allotted 15 minutes
of fame. Thursday, a Poughkeepsie man walking near the courthouse
expressed annoyance at Pagones for pressing his lawsuit. All it
did, he said, was to give these two discredited men more time in
the limelight, more time to scream ``racism'' at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   When Pagones' lawyer, William Stanton, called the defendants
evil self-promoters this week, Mason stayed true to form. ``Why
don't you just use the N word, you racist, because you did it
impliedly,'' he said later. Of course, Stanton neither used nor
implied the N word. He did, however, use the L word: liars.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton stays above this fray. Verbal excesses of the
Mason-Maddox variety are not his style anymore. He has not only
cleaned up his act but he has also proved himself to be a
formidable political figure: smart and funny, a man who can charm
the birds out of the trees when he wants to.
</P>
<P>
   But he also has a penchant for likening himself to no less than
the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. He did it again when he
testified in this trial, carrying with him a book on King's jailing
for civil-rights protests. ``I've been indicted, I've been stabbed
and now I've been sued,'' Sharpton said. ``I have every base
covered being a great civil-rights leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Every base, however, except one.
</P>
<P>
   Ask yourself whether King would have repeatedly denounced a man
as a rapist without making any serious effort to find out if the
charge contained a milligram of truth.
</P>
<P>
   If your answer is no, then you are entitled to reach your own
verdict when the man who would be King says that nothing the jury
decides will ``interfere one iota with the future and intentions of
Al Sharpton.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
