<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-510&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGERIA ANXIOUSLY AWAITS RESULTS OF PRISONER'S AUTOPSY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Inserts new graf (after original 10th graf) on commuting 6
prisoners' death sentences)  (bl)  
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAGOS, Nigeria _ Stores were shuttered Thursday, isolated fires
burned and streets were unusually empty as Nigeria anxiously
awaited a verdict on the sudden death of its main opposition
leader, Moshood K.O. Abiola, and a timetable for the promised birth
of a democratic system.
</P>
<P>
   Abiola, who had been imprisoned since 1994 after asserting his
right to the nation's presidency, died Tuesday in Abuja, the
capital, shortly after meeting with high-level U.S. officials. The
apparent cause was cardiac arrest, but the death has raised
suspicion here and set off violence, which continued sporadically
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Abiola's body was transported secretly to Lagos on Thursday for
fear that any public sighting could ignite tumult. In a further
effort to prevent unrest, the Lagos state government imposed a
dusk-to-dawn curfew.
</P>
<P>
   The international doctors, including three Americans, who are to
conduct the autopsy on the leader, who died a political prisoner,
also arrived here and Western officials said they would almost
certainly examine Abiola's body Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everything goes according to plan we should have the
preliminary findings by the weekend,'' said one Western official.
``If we find blockage of the arteries, then everything will be
pretty straightforward. But of course if the arteries are clear,
then you have a whole new ball game.''
</P>
<P>
   Abiola's family, gathering here before his funeral, appealed for
calm. ``The greatest honor we can do him in death is to embrace
peace,'' Kola Abiola, the late politician's oldest son, said.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Abiola was the apparent winner of elections held in
1993, but annulled by the military government. The government said
last week that it would release all its political prisoners,
including Abiola, who had agreed to relinquish his claim to the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Deprived of its leading figure, the opposition here is in some
disarray, deeply concerned that further widespread rioting could
provide an excuse for a military clampdown or delay movement toward
democracy. Mobile police units fanned out across Lagos on Thursday
to quell unrest.
</P>
<P>
   There seems to be little threat of mass protests that could
bring down Nigeria's recently installed leader, Gen. Abdulsalam
Abubakar, because the opposition here is fragmented, Nigeria's
unity is fragile and there is no obvious successor to the military
ruler.
</P>
<P>
   Abubakar, who has impressed Western officials with his
reform-minded moderation since he took office last month, convened
the 27-member Provisional Ruling Council, the heart of the
country's military authority, Thursday for the second time in two
days. But the meeting adjourned with no announcement on how or when
a democratic system might be introduced. A working group is to
study possible timetables and is expected to report to the
government early next week.
</P>
<P>
   The council announced late Thursday that it would commute death
sentences handed down against Gen. Oladipo Diya and five other men
convicted of plotting to overthrow the country's dictator, Gen.
Sani Abacha. Diya and two co-conspirators now face 25 years in
prison, while the others face 20 years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While Abubakar's commitment to change appears clear _ and was
reiterated to South African Deputy President Thabo Mbeki, who
visited Thursday _ he faces a delicate choice between a gradual
process that could prove too slow to assuage an impatient nation
and a rapid shift that might precipitate chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Western officials said Thursday they doubt that an elected
president could take office before Jan. 1, 1999, if a credible vote
is to be organized.
</P>
<P>
   Tension was palpable in Lagos on Thursday, fanned by the
continuing uncertainty over Abiola's death. Members of Abiola's
family remained convinced that he was poisoned. Several opposition
leaders share this conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am personally convinced that Abiola was poisoned,'' said
Clement Nwankwo, a prominent human-rights lawyer and opposition
figure. ``The way his death has been described _ the cup of tea,
the gasping for breath, the protracted back and forth _ does not
sound like cardiac arrest to me. But the fact is that if the
autopsy shows foul play, that would really intensify a crisis that
now needs to be contained.''
</P>
<P>
   Nwankwo said his chief concern was that the country could
descend into what he called ``major ethnic conflict.'' Some of the
rioting and killing _ at least 19 people have been confirmed dead _
has involved clashes between the mainly Yoruba population of the
Lagos and Abeokuta areas and Hausa from the north.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are being attacked just because of where they are
from,'' the lawyer said. ``If this country becomes ungovernable, no
authority is going to hold elections, and that would be a terrible
outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Muslim Hausa and Fulani constitute a majority in the military
government and the armed forces, while a significant part of
Abiola's following came from the Yoruba tribe in southwestern
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions between the many ethnic and religious groups in this
country of 105 million people have been fanned by the domination of
northern military figures since independence in 1960 and the fact
that the oil that earns the country more than $10 billion a year is
concentrated in the southeast.
</P>
<P>
   The perceived exploitation of one part of the country by another
_ some officers, including Gen. Sani Abacha, the dictator who died
suddenly of a heart attack June 8, are widely reported to have
enriched themselves with oil money _ has inevitably made Nigeria
more volatile.
</P>
<P>
   In this context the Clinton administration is not putting any
pressure on the government to adhere to the timetable Abacha had
set for a democratic transition. A presidential election was to
have been held Aug. 1, and he had emerged as the sole candidate.
</P>
<P>
   With Abacha and Abiola dead, and the process of creating genuine
political parties not yet begun, the Aug. 1 election date is
regarded as entirely unrealistic, officials said. So, too, is the
Oct. 1 date that had been set for an inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The five government-created parties are largely meaningless in
the new context,'' one Western official said. ``Time is needed. New
parties have to be formed. A six-month transition looks all right
to us, although of course a period of years is entirely
unacceptable. The most important thing is to do this right.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. companies have about $7 billion invested in Nigeria, almost
exclusively in the oil industry, an increase of about $3 billion
over the last five years. With about 10 percent of U.S. oil imports
coming from Nigeria, there is clearly extreme concern in Washington
that any transition be handled prudently
</P>
<P>
   In addition, through its size and the strength of its armed
forces _ Nigerian troops are involved in military missions in
Liberia and Sierra Leone _ the country dominates the region, and
the United States is concerned that any chaos might rapidly spill
over Nigeria's borders.
</P>
</TEXT>
