<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-YANKEE-STADIUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: QUIT WHINING AND THEY WILL COME 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, July 10:
</P>
<P>
   Could George Steinbrenner's storied ambivalence about keeping
the New York Yankees in the Bronx after 2002 really be melting? His
team's winning streak this season and Bronx Borough President
Fernando Ferrer's prediction that fan attendance could break the 3
million barrier moved Steinbrenner to a tantalizing comment. ``Do
the 3 million, and then we'll talk about the Bronx after the
season,'' he said. ``That isn't getting me where I want to be, but
maybe it would be worth talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   This attitudinal shift, if genuine, is a welcome development.
</P>
<P>
   For several years now, the option of remaining in the Bronx has
been treated as though it were radioactive. Steinbrenner, the
club's principal owner, and some politicians have cast eager
glances toward Manhattan. Our hope, as we have noted, is to see
baseball's most important franchise stay planted on historic ground
in a renovated or new stadium that pays homage to the 75-year
tradition built by Ruth, Gehrig, Mantle, Jackson and others who
have worn the pinstripes.
</P>
<P>
   The tone of Steinbrenner's response to Ferrer's prediction,
however, could have been put less grudgingly. Then it would have
been heard and heeded by a wider audience of elected officials. He
challenged Ferrer to insure that attendance actually hits three
million. That would break the Yankees' 1988 record of 2.63 million
but fall well short of levels achieved in new stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   Reaching this milestone by October will require the Yankee
organization to move creatively. Steinbrenner should persuade Gov.
George Pataki, who controls the Metropolitan Transportation
Authority, to build a temporary Metro North railroad station at
Yankee Stadium now. This modest move alone could enable thousands
more from the suburbs to come and go by commuter rail. The club
should press the MTA and the mayor to promote the ease of hopping
on subway lines to reach the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, the club and the rest of Major League Baseball should
take some marketing courses from the NBA and the NFL Baseball must
learn how to market America's pastime to fans of all races and
backgrounds, especially given the prominence of black and Hispanic
players.
</P>
<P>
   With real effort, not sound bites, Ferrer's prediction and
Steinbrenner's challenge could be the beginning of a rapprochement
between the club and New Yorkers who want serious brainstorming to
make the Yankees successful in the place where they are most at
home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
