</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HASIDIM-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL DISTRICT FOR HASIDIC CHILDREN ONLY CALLED UNCONSTITUTIONAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The village of Kiryas Joel lost yet another decision Thursday
when a state appellate court ruled unanimously that the third and
latest effort by the governor and the state legislature to create a
public school district solely for Hasidic children violated the
Constitution's establishment-of-religion clause.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-0 decision by the Appellate Division in Albany essentially
upheld a lower-court ruling in April, but it was notable for its
strong recommendation that Kiryas Joel, a village of 12,000 Satmar
Hasidic Jews in Orange County, N.Y., invite public school teachers
from an adjoining district into its yeshivas to provide special
education for its disabled students. Sending public school teachers
into parochial schools was barred until June 1997, when the U.S.
Supreme Court, in Agostini vs. Felton, held it was indeed
constitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty broad judicial hint that they ought to give this
up and use Agostini for providing education in a way that's
acceptable,'' said Marc Stern, a lawyer for the American Jewish
Congress, which filed a friend-of-the-court brief opposing the
Kiryas Joel district.
</P>
<P>
   Except for handicapped students, all the children in Kiryas Joel
attend yeshivas. Establishing a school district is a means for the
village to tap tax dollars to help pay the cost of educating its
severely handicapped children. Kiryas Joel's leadership has always
maintained that it needed its own publicly financed district
because its students, distinguished by their garb, religious
practices and their language, Yiddish, felt ostracized in the
public schools of nearby Monroe-Woodbury.
</P>
<P>
   They succeeded in getting the Legislature and two governors to
pass three successive laws carving out a Kiryas Joel public school
district. Each effort was held unconstitutional by a succession of
courts because it applied only to Kiryas Joel and thus was seen as
favoring a particular sect.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the district, which instructs 40 disabled village
children and 150 other disabled Hasidic children from nearby
districts, has been allowed to continue operating until the legal
process is exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   The latest legislative effort contained provisions that
theoretically might have applied to at least one other school
district. But the appellate judges said that law also ``lacks the
neutrality toward religion mandated by the establishment clause of
the First Amendment.'' It does not cover a broad enough array of
eligible municipalities, the judges said, and its ``application to
other municipalities in the future is speculative.''
</P>
<P>
   Abraham Wieder, mayor of Kiryas Joel, said it was likely that
the village would appeal to the state's Court of Appeals. He said
the problem with permitting public school teachers from
Monroe-Woodbury to teach Hasidic children is that the
Monroe-Woodbury school board does not want the political
consequences or the expense of absorbing a populous district like
Kiryas Joel.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Waldman, leader of a group of dissidents within Kiryas
Joel, hailed Thursday's ruling because they oppose sending their
children into public schools, even if they are operated by the
village. ``It's a disgrace to the Constitution and a disgrace to
our religion that religious children should be forced to go to
public school,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
