<SLUG> BC-WELLPOINT-CERULEAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELLPOINT TO EXPAND REACH IN HEALTH-CARE FIELD WITH CERULEAN BUY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Managed-care specialist WellPoint Health Networks
Inc. said it will pay $500 million to buy the parent company of
Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   WellPoint will pay in stock and cash for Atlanta-based Cerulean
Co., which through its two Blue plans has 1.7 million members.
WellPoint, which operates the Blue Cross of California health plan,
already has about 100,000 members in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The suburban Woodland Hills-based company had targeted Georgia
three years ago as a place to expand because of its relatively
business-friendly regulatory environment and growing population,
said WellPoint Chief Executive Leonard Schaeffer. About two-thirds
of the company's current 6.7 million members are in California, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this deal we become No. 1 in market share in one of the
highest strategic geographic areas, plus inherit the Blue name and
trademark in Georgia. I'm very positive about it,'' Schaeffer said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors sent WellPoint shares up $1.437 1/2 Thursday to close
at $71.06 1/4, and analysts responded positively as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good deal,'' said analyst Ed Kroll at Cowen &AMP; Co. ``The
valuation is reasonable, and it's a good market where they're going
to be No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Cerulean is in the process of converting the nonprofit Georgia
Blue plans to for-profit status, Kroll said, a process WellPoint
itself went through in the early 1990s. Both Cerulean's Blue Cross
and Blue Shield unit and WellPoint's Blue Cross are licensed by the
Blue Cross and Blue Shield Association, a national group of health
plans with 68.7 million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know how a Blue Cross plan operates,'' Kroll said of
Schaeffer and his management team. ``They know what it took to
convert WellPoint from a nonprofit Blue Cross indemnity plan to
managed care ... and I'm confident the management team will
accelerate that process in Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   Schaeffer said he expects the deal to close in the fourth
quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   WellPoint also said Thursday it is increasing its stock buyback
program to as many as 8 million shares from 1 million shares. The
company said it will buy back the shares as it issues new ones to
pay for the Georgia purchase.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
