<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BEAT PADRES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARC J. SPEARS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With a 12{-game deficit still staring at them this
morning, the Dodgers have a long way to go if they expect to make
the San Diego Padres nervous.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, however, the Dodgers showed the National League West
Division leaders that they don't plan to go away quietly.
</P>
<P>
   In their first game after the All-Star break, the Dodgers played
arguably their most dominating game of the season by whipping the
Padres 12-3 in front 41,250 at Dodger Stadium. The Dodgers also
snapped the Padres' three-game winning streak and have won five of
their last seven games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like a ladder, we are at the first step,'' said Dodgers
manager Glenn Hoffman. ``Today was the first win and step in trying
to reach out and get back in the second half. I'll tell you, that
was a good sign today.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are still in need of one more starting pitcher, but
there isn't expected to a ``Big Unit' or any other well-known
pitcher coming to Chavez Ravine today.
</P>
<P>
   The chances for Seattle ace Randy Johnson or another front-line
starter joining the Dodgers now seem highly unlikely. Interim
general manager Tommy Lasorda and the Mariners have denied talking
about a deal for Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   However, a Dodgers deal for a fifth starting pitcher might be
made today. Cincinnati Reds left-hander Mike Remlinger (5-9, 4.50
ERA) is believed to be among the names of possible players
discussed, along with Kansas City's Tim Belcher and the Mets' Brian
Bohanan.
</P>
<P>
   Despite asking for a trade after the Dodgers acquired closer
Jeff Shaw last weekend, reliever Antonio Osuna was told by Lasorda
that he would not be traded. Afterward, Osuna asked Lasorda to tell
him the truth since he also reportedly told Paul Konerko the same
thing before shipping him to Cincinnati in the Shaw deal.
</P>
<P>
   Osuna, who was also promised more save opportunities, said
Lasorda told him: ``I am sincere. My word is in my heart. I'm not
going to trade you.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Lasorda: ``I never said I would trade Osuna, you guys
(reporters) said so.''
</P>
<P>
   With Osuna apparently off the market, the Dodgers may have
reliever Jim Bruske start or turn to their farm system if they
can't make a trade. Hoffman expects to name Sunday's starter today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to get that fifth starter, believe me when I tell
you that,'' Lasorda said.
</P>
<P>
   Former Angel Mark Langston (3-2) struggled in the loss for San
Diego, allowing six runs, eight hits and three walks in just 31/3
innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers scored four runs on five hits in the first inning,
two of them on Gary Sheffield's 15th home run. Eric Young, who
missed the previous five games with a strained right quadriceps,
got a leadoff single, stole his league-leading 33rd base and scored
in the first. Young (2 for 3), who came out in the fourth inning
for precautionary reasons, said he felt fine.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers batted around in the fourth inning for the fourth
time this season and scored six runs on six hits to go up 10-0.
During their hit parade, Raul Mondesi's infield single pushed his
hitting streak to nine games, Eric Karros (2 for 2) drove in two
with a single and Bobby Bonilla (2 for 4) had a two-run double.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are averaging 7.53 runs when Chan Ho Park (8-5)
pitches, the second-highest runs-per-outing behind a pitcher in the
league. The right-hander allowed one unearned run on three hits in
six innings to extend his home winning streak to 10 games, dating
to last July 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really wanted to show San Diego how much we wanted to
win,'' Park said.
</P>
<P>
   With the game in hand, the Dodgers' Trenidad Hubbard helped
liven it up after hitting a two-run home run in the seventh that
put the Dodgers up by nine. While Hubbard watched the ball fly
toward the left-field bleachers, Padres pitcher Brian Boehringer
yelled at him to stop showboating.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a guy that doesn't hit home runs every day hits a home
run, he gets a little numb,'' said Hubbard, who also had a
career-high three hits and insisted he didn't hear Boehringer. ``I
was not trying to rub his nose in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Boehringer didn't comment, teammate Tony Gwynn said:
``If you don't want a guy to hit a ball out the park, hey, don't
throw a bad pitch. Trenidad hit it right on.''
</P>
<P>
   And at least Thursday, so did the rest of the Dodgers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
