<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 00:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8618 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WENATCHEE-LEGAL-SPI &LR; A     07-10 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WENATCHEE-LEGAL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     EXPERTS TEAM UP TO GET NEW TRIALS IN WENATCHEE SEX CRIMES
CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   ANDREW SCHNEIDER (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW SCHNEIDER  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A skilled team of lawyers has formed to seek new trials for 16
people still in prison from the Wenatchee child sex-abuse cases.
</P>
<P>
   They're national experts in police misconduct, mental health
abuse, civil rights and DNA evidence.
</P>
<P>
   They've fought and won some of the state's hottest legal
battles.
</P>
<P>
   They've gotten convictions overturned for scores of people
wrongly convicted of murder, rape and other major crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Now they're teaming with law students and professors to
represent defendants in the Wenatchee cases.
</P>
<P>
   Called the Innocence Project Northwest, it may be the nation's
largest collection of free legal talent ever assembled for a single
effort: More than 40 lawyers who will meet Friday to take on
individual cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence and information that we've already collected
strongly indicate these people are innocent _ did not commit the
crimes they were imprisoned for,'' said Seattle lawyer Frederick
Leatherman, a project co-founder. ``It appears that none of these
people received justice as demanded by the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Leatherman and Jackie McMurtie, a University of Washington law
lecturer, modeled the project after an operation at New York's
Cardozo Law School. The National Association of Criminal Defense
Lawyers has offered to cover some costs.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40 lawyers have signed up to work on the Wenatchee
cases, and others have expressed interest in joining, Leatherman
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could we not become involved?'' asked Julie Spector, a
Seattle lawyer. ``It's a situation that calls for immediate
attention from defense lawyers because it is just so outrageous.
These people were wrongly accused, wrongly prosecuted and
wrongfully convicted.''
</P>
<P>
   Walter Palmer, another Seattle lawyer, added: ``There are
serious issues and I was uncomfortable not doing anything to help.
These convictions need to be looked at again.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the volunteers are seasoned professionals with 15 to 20
years of experience. At least 22 have worked as public defenders,
six as prosecutors. At least three have argued cases before the
U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   A few work for huge law firms, but most are private
practitioners. Two, Mark Prothero of Seattle and Jeffery Swan of
Yakima, are public defenders. All will work on the project on their
own time.
</P>
<P>
   Swan said he somewhat surprised himself by volunteering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not much of a joiner, nor much of an activist, but what
happened with these defendants in Wenatchee just infuriated me and
I have to do something,'' said the young public defender.
</P>
<P>
   They come from across the state _ lawyers such as Garth Dano of
Moses Lake, James Dixon of Olympia, Ron Ness of Port Orchard and
Mark Muenster of Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Their 16 clients are five women and 11 men, ages 26 to 66. Most
are serving 23-year sentences. They were among the 44 adults
arrested in Chelan and Douglas counties in the mid-'90s and charged
with 29,730 counts of rape and molestation of 60 children.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the lawyers joining the Innocence Project already were
working with Wenatchee defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Nielsen, who with New York lawyer Robert Rosenthal is
guiding the appeal of Mark and Carol Doggett, is also collecting
evidence for an appeal on the behalf of Jeannie Bendt.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle lawyer Robert Van Siclen is representing Harold and
Idella Everett in their bid to win a new trial. He and Rosenthal
also have filed an appeal on the behalf of Manuel Hidalgo
Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanna Lee Elliott of Seattle is developing an appeal for Doris
Green.
</P>
<P>
   Others will be assigned clients through the luck of the draw.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll do some sort of lottery or pick names out of a hat to
see which client each lawyer will get,'' Leatherman said..
</P>
<P>
   Their work crafting appeals in hopes of convincing courts to
order new trials will not be easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these 16 people are at the point where they have only
one chance left to present an argument to the court,'' Van Siclen
said. ``It becomes a massive challenge to pick the right issues,
with the right documentation, written in just the right words to
convince the court that a new trial is deserved.''
</P>
<P>
   The advantage of the joint effort is that many of the cases deal
with the same accusers _ two girls who, at the time, were foster
daughters of then-Wenatchee Detective Robert Perez _ who was the
investigator in most of the cases.
</P>
<P>
   The same police reports, medical evidence, mental health
records, social service agency documents and personnel link almost
all the cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working together, sharing information and resources, presents
a great benefit in allowing us to work these very similar cases
without everyone having to reinvent the wheel,'' explained
McMurtie.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal saw another advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this pool of experienced lawyers, the accused will
finally have power behind them that is nearly equal to the state.
The courtroom has been made into a level battle ground,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the lawyers joined because they fear what happened in
Wenatchee is happening elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``In cases involving children, more often then not, you are
facing the presumption of guilt, not the presumption of
innocence,'' said David Allen of Seattle. ``The rules are all
changed, and innocent people are sometimes convicted because of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lenell Nussbaum, another Seattle lawyer, added that she hopes
knowledge gained by the lawyers will help defendants in other cases
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe there are more innocent people in prison for child
sex-abuse than for any other charges,'' Nussbaum said. ``It's time
for our criminal justice system to find a way to correct the
injustices it has been creating.''
</P>
<P>
   Legal historians said it is extremely rare for so many
experienced lawyers to work simultaneously on a related case.
</P>
<P>
   Comparable efforts include defense of American Indians arrested
in the Wounded Knee protest in 1973 and the rush of young lawyers
to the South during the civil rights movement in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   At least four of those in the Wenatchee project cut their legal
teeth in one or both of those legal musters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is in the best tradition of our profession to help people
who need our services and can't afford to pay, and that is clearly
the case in Wenatchee,'' said Seattle lawyer David Marshall. ``It
is always more difficult to get the legal system to go back and fix
its mistakes. ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
