<SLUG> BC-NEWYORKER-SUCCESSION-1STLD-WRITETHRU-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORKER STAFF TAKES DEEP BREATH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to insert three new grafs starting in the middle of the 7th
graf,  
 and two new grafs near the end; no other changes)  (See also: MAGS-MOVIES) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wearing a black T-shirt to a meeting that was
anything but casual, S.I. Newhouse Jr. told uneasy staff members of
The New Yorker Thursday that the departure of his star editor, Tina
Brown, would not create precipitous changes at the magazine his
family owns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a slight editorial problem,'' he jokingly acknowledged
to about 75 employees, as Ms. Brown chuckled nearby, having stunned
Newhouse with her resignation exactly 26{ hours earlier. But just
before an awkward kiss and embrace of Ms. Brown, he vowed not to
use the occasion of her replacement to redefine the nature of the
magazine, to change its weekly publication schedule, or to begin
cutting its famously expansive budget.
</P>
<P>
   Newhouse gave no indication whom he is considering to succeed
Ms. Brown, according to several people who attended the meeting,
but said he planned to make the decision by next week. When he said
that no one in or out of the magazine had been ruled out, Susan
Orlean, a staff writer, brought down the house by raising her hand
and asking, ``Would you consider me?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Orlean said later that she would not really be submitting
her resume, but about 10 or 15 editors from around New York have
done so, several current and former employees said. Although Kurt
Andersen, the former editor of New York Magazine and currently a
New Yorker columnist, remains the front-runner in the rumor-driven
sweepstakes, Newhouse said only that he would make his selection
based on a gut instinct of who would make him both ``comfortable
and excited.''
</P>
<P>
   The 15-minute staff meeting came a day after Ms. Brown announced
that she was leaving the magazine to start a company affiliated
with Miramax Films that would produce a new monthly magazine, as
well as books, films and television programming. To dispel rumors
about a growing tension between her and Conde Nast Publications,
which is owned by Advance Publications, she thanked Newhouse, the
chairman and chief executive of Advance, for his ``unflagging
support,'' both financially and emotionally, although several
employees said the warmth appeared to be for display purposes.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was also attended by Steven T. Florio, chief
executive of Conde Nast, an appearance that was apparently designed
to downplay stories of hostility between him and Ms. Brown. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, Ms. Brown invited a large group of magazine
writers and editors to her home for champagne and dessert Thursday
night, in what was described by those who attended as a thank-you
and goodbye party.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown cried and hugged each of the writers and editors at
the party, which was attended by Hendrik Hertzberg, Joe Klein,
Roger Angell, Lillian Ross, Bill Buford and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New Yorker has been the love of my life, but love can
often be painful,'' Ms. Brown told the gathering. ``Sometimes in
the last six months, I have felt so vulnerable and exposed.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the tears and sadness of the farewell party, staff members
talked of the intense camaraderie of the magazine and how many of
them had been brought there by Ms. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown is expected to lure several writers to her new,
still-unnamed magazine over the next year, but employees said that
was not the explicit purpose of the gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Orlean's facetious self-nomination had its serious side: the
job is so coveted, and so closely watched, because of the
enormously broad opportunity it allows an editor to put his or her
stamp on an influential magazine. Other magazines are about news or
fashion or music; The New Yorker is largely about its editor's
interests, and as a result, staff members said they were deeply
concerned about life after such a prominent cultural fixture as Ms.
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``My deepest anxiety was that he would now bring in some kind of
efficiency expert or cost cutter,'' said Roger Angell, the longtime
writer and editor at the magazine, who asked for and received an
assurance from Newhouse that such a person would not be appointed.
``It was good to hear him say that that was the furthest thing from
his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Newhouse, of course, could hardly be expected to promise an
editorial shakeup. But employees are acutely aware that the
magazine has lost more than $100 million in the 13 years since it
was purchased by Conde Nast Publications, and that the choice of a
successor could be determined by whether Newhouse still wants to
spend such sums on the magazine's expensively acquired marketplace
verve.
</P>
<P>
   His remarks Thursday were interpreted by many employees as an
indication that he does not plan to turn off the faucet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not someone who believes in disinvesting from magazine
properties in a way that is likely to diminish their appeal,'' said
Henry Finder, editorial director of The New Yorker. ``It's a
fantasy that you can just put on a green eyeshade and go from red
to black, and I think the last thing he would want to do is to do
anything that would jeopardize the quality and cachet of the
magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Wickenden, the magazine's executive editor, agreed that
the meeting reassured anxious staff members.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a major turning point when there is a new editor
of an extremely important magazine,'' she said. ``But he was quite
clear that he intended to continue to publish an intelligent,
informed, serious magazine of culture and the arts.''
</P>
<P>
   It was less clear, however, whether a new editor would be
expected to share the particular interests Ms. Brown had brought to
the magazine since her arrival six years ago _ her fascination with
Hollywood and the celebrities of Washington, her enjoyment of
breaking news, her lavish use of graphics and photo spreads, all
but unheard of before her arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Though Finder said the magazine had a core identity, a
``genome'' that could not readily be changed, some people outside
the magazine questioned how much tradition could really be
preserved, noting that Ms. Brown's crusade to eliminate stodginess
from the magazine had already taken it far from its roots into
pop-cultural territory well-covered by other publications.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``People are looking at this with extra scrutiny because Tina
Brown raised the stakes, the eyebrows, the volume of that job, so
that any change will be considered dramatic,'' said Daniel Menaker,
a former senior editor of The New Yorker who left in 1994 after 20
years and is now senior literary editor of Random House, which
Newhouse recently sold. ``With a magazine like Refrigeration
Monthly, you know it will always be about refrigerators. With The
New Yorker, it's a more plastic situation, which will be shaped
much more by its editor.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown, however, in praising the talent and standards of the
magazine's writers and editors, said Thursday night that ``the
index of success is whether something survives beyond the person
who helps make it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Any new editor,'' she said, ``should be given the right to
make his own mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   The race to succeed Ms. Brown took on an almost comic aspect
Thursday, with people in and out of the magazine handicapping long
lists of candidates based on their perceived closeness to Newhouse.
Some people mentioned friends' names, as a favor; others tried
desperately to avoid being mentioned. Those leading the various
lists included Andersen; writer David Remnick; Peter Kaplan, editor
of The New York Observer; Michael Kinsley, editor of the online
magazine Slate; Katrina Heron, editor of Wired, which was recently
purchased by Conde Nast; and Dominique Browning, editor of Conde
Nast's House &AMP; Garden.
</P>
<P>
   But probably not Susan Orlean, as she is the first to admit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like everyone else in the world had been mentioned,
so I had to throw my name in, too,'' she said after the meeting
Thursday. ``With lists that long, it's just insulting if you don't
get mentioned.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
