<HEADLINE>
METS' FRANCO IS DISCIPLINED FOR CLASH WITH UMPIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John Franco already had three days off that he did
not really want during the All-Star Game break. Thursday, he was
informed that he will probably have to take three more days off
sometime next week.
</P>
<P>
   On the first day of the second half of the season, Franco, the
New York Mets' closer, was suspended for three games and fined
$1,500 for ``initiating contact with an umpire and personal
profanities directed towards an umpire,'' according to a statement
released by the National League.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension stemmed from Franco's reaction to Umpire Angel
Hernandez's controversial game-ending call at home plate in the
11th inning of last Sunday's 3-2 loss in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Franco announced that he would appeal the suspension. A hearing
is likely next week. Until then, Franco will be available to pitch
out of a Mets bullpen that would be considerably diminished by his
absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to comment on anything yet,'' said Franco, who
had expected only to be fined.
</P>
<P>
   Mets general manager Steve Phillips said he reviewed videotapes
of the argument showing Franco bumping Hernandez. But Phillips
sounded as if he felt that the suspension was a little harsh.
``It's tough,'' he said. ``Three games without your closer is not
insignificant. I think it's worthy of an appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   There was some speculation that Valentine would also be
suspended for his actions during the argument. But Phillips said
that the league president, Leonard Coleman, had told him
Valentine's ``efforts were to keep players away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
