<SLUG> BC-BRAWLEY-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY IN BRAWLEY DEFAMATION CASE ASKS TO BE SEQUESTERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (also see NY-COLUMN-BRAWLEY)  
 (bl)  
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ Showing concern about the scrutiny they are
under, the jurors in the Tawana Brawley defamation case asked
Thursday that they be sequestered.
</P>
<P>
   State Supreme Court Justice S. Barrett Hickman agreed, ordering
that they be sequestered after Thursday, their first full day of
deliberations. ``This is a trial and not a media event,'' he said,
without explaining whether jurors had been exposed to news
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors, who had previously resisted the suggestion of being
separated from their families, seemed to be settling into a
detailed examination of the evidence. But participants in the case
said it appeared that several of the jurors had been rattled by the
extensive attention to the case among their acquaintances when they
went home after the start of deliberations Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   In court, Hickman said a majority of the six jurors had agreed
Thursday that sequestration was now necessary. In addition, Hickman
said, one juror had requested that the courtroom sketch artists not
depict the jurors identifiably in the drawings that are used for
television coverage of the case.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors' new attention to the public focus on their
deliberations came as a growing throng of reporters paced the
sidewalk just under the second-floor window of their deliberation
room in the Dutchess County Courthouse. Television transmission
trucks, which have rarely been seen since the early days of the
trial, in the fall, parked down the block awaiting a verdict.
</P>
<P>
   During the nearly eight months of the trial, the attention has
usually been on the lawyers; the plaintiff, Steven Pagones, or the
defendants, the Rev. Al Sharpton, C. Vernon Mason and Alton Maddox.
</P>
<P>
   But as the focus shifted to the jurors, there were clear signs
that the panel was taking its responsibilities soberly, with a
touch of anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors, who began their deliberations Wednesday with several
requests for evidence in the case, Thursday sent 11 notes asking
for specific items or a rereading of certain testimony. When the
judge did not respond promptly, the jurors sent notes that
displayed irritation. ``Still waiting for Pagones testimony,'' said
one of the notes, after the jurors had asked a few hours earlier to
hear a portion of the plaintiff's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides in the case said the number of notes and the detail
of some of the requests showed that the jurors were digging in to a
thorough review of Pagones' assertion that the advisers defamed him
a decade ago. The advisers said he had raped and kidnapped Ms.
Brawley in 1987. He filed a lawsuit seeking millions of dollars in
damages after a grand jury exonerated him and discredited Ms.
Brawley's account in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Pagones has long maintained that it was obvious that the
advisers took part in a hoax, and some of his supporters had
predicted that a verdict would come quickly. Supporters of the
defendants have said they believe that they benefit from long
deliberations, which could signal that the jurors are questioning
some of the fundamental assumptions of Pagones' lawsuit, like the
conclusions of the grand jury report.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's voluminous requests for information provided grist
for both mills. The jurors asked for testimony that the defendants
said could only benefit them, like testimony that suggested Pagones
might have lived near Ms. Brawley for a time before she claimed she
had been assaulted.
</P>
<P>
   But the jurors also asked to have the closing statement of
Pagones' lawyer, William Stanton, read to them. In that statement,
he branded the defendants ``evil men,'' and supporters of Pagones
contended that this request could be a prelude to a denunciation of
the advisers by the jurors. Justice Hickman said he could not have
a closing statement read again.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors' request for sequestration also brought differing
interpretations. Some participants in the case said it appeared
that four of the jurors wanted to be kept in a hotel and separated
from acquaintances simply to focus on the case.
</P>
<P>
   But Mason, who has long suggested that Pagones is tied to a
Dutchess County establishment that is hostile to the defendants,
said, ``They're concerned about not receiving undue pressure in
Dutchess County.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
