A8632 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SCHOOLS-OFFICIAL-N     07-10 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOLS-OFFICIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BOARD MEMBER'S EDUCATIONAL ODYSSEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Terri Thomson's new constituents, the 1.1 million
students who attend New York City public schools, may be interested
to learn that she often spends her free moments as they do,
cramming for exams. Not in algebra or social studies, mind you, but
in courses like Protest Movements, Neighborhoods, and Urban
Planning.
</P>
<P>
   Besides being one of two new members of the New York City Board
of Education, and a longtime vice president of community affairs at
Citibank, Ms. Thomson, 49, is a college student six credits away
from a bachelor's degree at Queens College. Her dual major is
political science and urban studies, with a minor in sign language,
and she hopes to graduate in February.
</P>
<P>
   Her grade point average? 3.8.
</P>
<P>
   ``I blew it,'' she says, ``I was 4.0 for the longest time.''
</P>
<P>
   In embarking on a four-year term as a caretaker of and advocate
for the country's largest school system, Ms. Thomson possesses
little firsthand knowledge of life within public schools. She
attended parochial schools, including Bishop Riley High School in
Queens and the Thorpe Secretarial School, a now-defunct Roman
Catholic school in Manhattan, from which she graduated in 1966. Her
two daughters followed a similar route, in what she calls ``a
personal decision'' that was ``not a reflection at all on our
neighborhood schools'' in Flushing.
</P>
<P>
   But what does seem to qualify Ms. Thomson for the board, in
addition to two decades as a backstage player inside the city's
political theaters, is an empathy for those navigating the dead
ends and extended detours of the educational process.
</P>
<P>
   She contends that her own educational odyssey _ interrupted by
marriage, family and then work, but ultimately resumed at night and
on weekends a decade ago _ gives her unique standing to inspire a
system from which less than half of the students graduate in four
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going slowly, taking my time, fitting it into my
schedule,'' Ms. Thomson said of her college experience the other
night, in a telephone call from the weekend home in the Adirondacks
that she shares with her husband, Ed, an electrician.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look back,'' she added. ``I love going to school. I
think I will go to school the rest of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Thomson says that the mind-set that will light her way
through 110 Livingston Street, the board's labyrinthine
headquarters in Brooklyn, has been influenced by many passages in
her life. They include helping her daughters, 26 and 23, acquire
the skills to graduate from Williams College and Boston College;
stitching together a coalition of parents at the Electchester Co-op
in Flushing in the early 1970s to rebuild a rundown playground;
building on that experience to attend to constituent concerns in
the 1980s as the district administrator for Rep. Gary Ackerman, a
Democrat from northern Queens, and being the public face of
Citibank since the early 1990s in meetings with small-business
owners and politicians within the five boroughs.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the element of her background that has most tantalized
officials at City Hall, and most unnerved those within the inner
circle of Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew, is that she is the daughter
of a policeman, Albert Farrell, who retired in 1978 after 25 years.
The first major decision that Ms. Thomson will probably have to
make is to declare her stance on the mayor's bid to give the police
more responsibility for school safety.
</P>
<P>
   After being stymied for three years by Crew and an unwavering
four-member majority on the seven-member board, Giuliani is now
presented with a wild card in Ms. Thomson. She replaces Carol
Gresser, one of the most vocal opponents of expanding the police
role, and Ms. Thomson has said she has yet to decide on a position.
With no shortage of advocates seeking her vote, she says she still
needs to spend more time studying the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if growing up in a police officer's home would predispose
her, Ms. Thomson spoke cautiously.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there is a proposal on the table,'' she said, ``I'll look
at it and and see what questions I might have and make an informed
decision based on the outreach that I've done.''
</P>
<P>
   But anyone who takes her vote for granted would do well to
consider her position on publicly financed vouchers that would
benefit the same parochial schools she and her children attended.
She opposes them, saying that more investment, not less, is needed
for public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Thomson's evenhandedness and modesty are among the qualities
that prompted Queens Borough President Claire Shulman to tap her to
succeed Ms. Gresser.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman, a political ally of Ms. Shulman's, said of Ms.
Thomson: ``I think she probably gets embarrassed when her name is
in the paper. At least she used to.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She is a workhorse,'' he added, ``not a show horse.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Floyd Flake, who resigned from Congress last year after
11 years representing Jamaica, Queens, said he appreciated Ms.
Thomson's keen ear for people's concerns. He recalled Citibank's
decision not long ago to replace the tellers at its Rochdale branch
with bank machines. When Ms. Thomson learned that older people in
the neighborhood were terrified of entrusting their life savings to
such technology, she prevailed on the bank to install a customer
service representative to guide them through the first six months.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of flexibility,'' Flake said, ``will be very helpful
to her as a member of the board, which can be a place where people
dig deep into the cement and are sometimes intractable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
