<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-POLICE-BULLETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BULLETS DESIGNED TO MAIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, July 10:
</P>
<P>
   The New York Police Department's decision to switch from
conventional full-metal-jacketed bullets to more lethal
hollow-point bullets is regrettable. The hollow-point bullets,
which expand when they enter flesh, are banned as inhumane in
warfare by the Geneva Conventions because they cause great damage
to internal organs.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the Police Department can show that conventional bullets
are inadequate to protect public safety, there is no reason to
switch to a type of ammunition that can result in more severe
injuries for suspects, bystanders and police officers.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1997, Police Commissioner Howard Safir announced the
same change, but Mayor Rudolph Giuliani delayed the action. A
subcommittee of the Civilian Complaint Review Board, an independent
agency that monitors police conduct, has now recommended the use of
hollow-point bullets because they are somewhat less likely to
ricochet or pass through objects to hit bystanders.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever benefit these bullets offer in terms of ricochet
capacity is outweighed by the damage they would do to bystanders
who are hit directly. Former Police Commissioner Raymond Kelly
cautioned against the use of hollow-point bullets in 1994 because
one-fifth of the officers shot were wounded with their own guns or
by other officers.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, simply firing deadlier bullets will not bring down
suspects when accuracy is poor. About 80 percent of shots fired by
police in shootouts around the country miss their targets.
</P>
<P>
   A better way to increase safety is to insure that officers can
actually hit what they aim at. That takes target practice, not a
new brand of deadlier ammunition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
