<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-YONKERS-FINANCES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE OVERSIGHT PANEL DISBANDS AND LEAVES YONKERS ON ITS OWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   YONKERS, N.Y. _ Twenty-three years after a State Emergency
Financial Control Board first took over Yonkers' finances, the
board declared Thursday that the city could now take care of
itself.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-member board, in unanimously voting to disband itself,
cited the city's balanced budget during the last three years, its
healthy four-year fiscal projections and its commitment to pay back
debts to the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now is the opportunity to begin a new chapter in Yonkers'
history,'' said state Comptroller H. Carl McCall, who was a member
of the control board. The State Comptroller will continue as the
city's fiscal agent until 2018, monitoring Yonkers' finances and
insuring that its budget, now $253 million, continues to remain
balanced.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor John Spencer said, ``This is the best government meeting
I've ever attended.''
</P>
<P>
   The first control board in Yonkers was set up in 1975 in
response to the city's financial problems, which included improper
budget, finance and accounting practices that left it unable to
market its bonds. The board was disbanded in 1978, but brought back
in 1984, when the city was near bankruptcy and was so short of
money that it risked having to close its schools.
</P>
<P>
   Yonkers' finances were further strained by the battle over a
federal court order to desegregate the city's housing and its
schools. In 1988, after the City Council refused to comply with the
housing aspect of the case, the presiding judge, Leonard Sand of
U.S. District Court in Manhattan, imposed fines on Yonkers that
began at $100 a day and were to double each weekday.
</P>
<P>
   The control board imposed a hiring freeze and made plans for
drastic cuts as the fines mounted. The Council ultimately accepted
the housing plan and paid $819,000 in fines; the battle also cost
the city an estimated $15 million in legal fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today the shackles were removed,'' said Nicholas DeSantis, who
was city manager at the time of the desegregation battle. ``I saw
them when they came. It's nice to see them go.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, a state board was placed in control of the finances of
New York City, which was on the brink of bankruptcy. That board
concluded its oversight role 11 years later and now serves in an
advisory capacity, an arrangement that will stay in effect until
2008.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki said he would propose in next year's budget a
correction to the schedule of state aid payments that had
contributed to the Yonkers' cash flow problem for 20 years. Since
Pataki took office three years ago, state aid to Yonkers has almost
doubled, to $70.2 million this year from $37.2 million in fiscal
year 1995-96. Although a portion of its $16 million debt to Albany
was forgiven, the city has agreed to repay the state $11.1 million
as part of the agreement to disband the oversight board.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
