<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8640 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CONTRACTING-DECISI     07-10 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CONTRACTING-DECISION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT BARS NYC FROM AWARDING CONTRACTS TO BIDDERS OTHER THAN
LOWEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The state's highest court ruled Thursday that New
York City's more than century-old practice of awarding some
contracts to companies when they are not the lowest bidders was
illegal.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, which overturned the decisions of a trial court and
a lower appellate court, came in a complex case involving street
repair contracts, the area where the city most frequently
circumvents the low-bid requirement. The court threw out the
mechanism that the city uses for awarding some of those contracts,
under which the city and private utility companies like
Consolidated Edison and Bell Atlantic jointly seek bids for fixing
streets.
</P>
<P>
   State law requires that government contracts be awarded to ``the
lowest responsible bidder,'' but it gives New York City an
exemption. In a 5-2 decision Thursday, the state Court of Appeals
ruled that when voters adopted a new city charter in 1989, the city
lost its exemption and must adhere to the low-bid rule.
</P>
<P>
   The case involved four contracts worth about $100 million,
though the court ruling could affect hundreds of millions of
dollars a year in contracts. Most of the city's street repair
contracts would not be affected, however, because they do not
involve utility work.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling takes away from the mayor one of the broader powers
granted him under the new charter, albeit one that the city's
lawyers say Mayors David Dinkins and Rudolph Giuliani had used
sparingly. The charter allows the mayor to choose someone other
than the lowest bidder for a city contract if the mayor declares it
to be ``in the best interest of the city,'' placing no other
restrictions on that power.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Giuliani's office did not return repeated telephone calls
seeking comment on the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Finkelman, deputy chief of the commercial and real estate
litigation division in the city corporation counsel's office, said,
``One of the options we're exploring is state legislation to
remedy'' the loss of the city's exemption. He added that the city
``has had this authority to bypass the low bid since 1853, in one
form or another.''
</P>
<P>
   The city contended in court that the way it awarded
utility-related contracts made for faster, less troubled street
repairs, which the court acknowledged might be true.
</P>
<P>
   But the court concluded that the practice raised the cost of
street repair to taxpayers, because the city was not always taking
the lowest bidder. More importantly, the judges said, it raised the
specter of corruption, though they stressed that there was no
suggestion that the city had intentionally done any wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The competitive bidding statutes are intended to guard against
the opportunity for fraud,'' Judge Joseph Bellacosa wrote for the
court majority. That the city's practice ``opens the door to fraud
is plain to see,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Judges Vito Titone, George Bundy Smith, Howard A. Levine and
Carmen Beauchamp Ciparick concurred.
</P>
<P>
   The dissenting judges, Chief Judge Judith Kaye and Judge Richard
Wesley, ruled in the city's favor on different legal grounds, and
did not take up the issue of whether the mayor could legally bypass
the lowest bid.
</P>
<P>
   Milton Mollen, a former deputy mayor and former Appellate
Division judge, argued the appeal for Diamond Asphalt Corp., a
company that was denied contracts under the city's bid system. He
said the significance of the decision lay in the court's
invalidation of the mayor's power to bypass the low-bid
requirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very, very important,'' Mollen said, ``because it takes
away what was really too much power in the hands of an individual,
without any checks and balances.''
</P>
<P>
   Diamond Asphalt did not seek money damages in the case. Mollen
said he doubted that bidders who lost out under the now-banned
system had a valid claim for damages.
</P>
<P>
   Under the old city charter, a two-thirds vote of the city's
Board of Estimate could bypass the low bid requirement. The state
law requiring government to accept the low bid makes an exception
for longstanding local rules like the one in the old charter.
</P>
<P>
   The new charter did away with the Board of Estimate and gave the
mayor the power to bypass the lowest bid. The city asserted in
court that this was permitted because it was just a continuation of
the old rule.
</P>
<P>
   When a contractor repairs a street, it potentially endangers the
web of telephone, electric, natural gas and other lines under the
asphalt. So when the city hires a contractor to dig up a street, it
sometimes requires that the utilities hire a contractor, too, to
either safeguard their lines or move them until the work is done.
</P>
<P>
   The utilities have long found that the easiest and cheapest way
to do that was to hire the same contractor that the city did. The
utilities also contend that, knowing this, contractors, on winning
city contracts, would then charge the utilities inflated prices.
</P>
<P>
   City officials say that system often slowed the work, in part
because of frequent contract squabbles between utilities and
contractors.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the city and the utilities adopted a new system for
street repairs where utilities were involved. For each job, the
city would request a single bid _ the street work, plus the utility
work _ and have the utilities reimburse the city for their part of
the work.
</P>
<P>
   But contractors complained that often the lowest bidder for the
street work, the part the city would pay, was not the lowest bidder
over all and so was denied the contract. A group of companies that
lost out on street repair contracts that way filed suit.
</P>
<P>
   The city made two arguments in its defense. First, it said the
entire contract, including the part paid for by the utilities,
could be regarded as ``public work,'' and so joining them and
choosing the lowest overall bidder was acceptable. And second, it
said that even if the first argument were wrong, the mayor had the
power to bypass the lowest bid.
</P>
<P>
   The dissenting judges accepted the city's broad definition of
``public work.'' But the court majority rejected both of the city's
arguments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
