<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-JENKINS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
Brazil Makes Practice Of `Beautiful Game' 
 By BRUCE JENKINS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OZOIR-LA-FERRIERE, France _ I've probably spilled more drinks
and hors d'oeuvres than any six of my friends put together over the
years. And to think: If Dunga had been around, none of it would
have hit the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The World Cup magic of Brazilian feet was never more evident
than Thursday, at this remote countryside location some 40 miles
east of Paris. This is the Brazilians' training camp for the
tournament, and it is a place of many wonders.
</P>
<P>
   Watching these guys play among themselves, in relative privacy,
would be something like hanging around the 17-year-old Cassius Clay
as he worked the bag. Sitting in a corner of the North Carolina
gymnasium as Michael Jordan shot alone. Leaning against a tree in
some woodsy park as Joe Montana threw down-and-outs to Jerry Rice.
</P>
<P>
   I almost didn't find this precious slice of soccer heaven, but
as always, I had help.
</P>
<P>
   As the train whisked away, I was a solitary figure on the ramp;
nobody in either direction. The directions were a little blurry
from this point on. The weather was turning cool, a brisk wind
rustling through the trees under a heavy overcast. Rain seemed
imminent, and I didn't have a clue.
</P>
<P>
   Walking out of the station in any old direction, I suddenly
heard the single most important clue for any Brazilian soccer fan:
the pounding of drums. They were distant, like the high school
rat-a-tat on a football Friday night when you're several blocks
away. But it was all I needed. With the Brazilians come music,
fanaticism and a full-on bash. They will travel to Mars, as well,
if the World Cup ever goes there.
</P>
<P>
   After about a mile's walk, I arrived at a tiny, charming complex
with about 20 rows of bleacher seats. The place was packed with
Brazilians who had paid their way in. It's just an ordinary pitch,
home to a third-division team in normal times, but the grass was
deep green and immaculate, as it had to be. The best soccer team in
the world was here.
</P>
<P>
   At the top row of the ``press'' section, if you could call it
that, a number of Brazilian radio crews were fully set up.
Incredibly, they would be broadcasting the action back home. It was
just a scrimmage, a bunch of guys running around with nothing at
stake _ but in the soccer-mad towns of Brazil, it is paradise just
to hear the names: Ronaldo, Rivaldo, Cesar Sampaio, Dunga, Bebeto.
It is a language all its own.
</P>
<P>
   The fans wore jerseys of all these men, to say nothing of
Taffarel, Roberto Carlos and Denilson. This isn't like the
vicarious hoops thrill in Asia, Europe or Africa, where everyone in
a jersey is Jordan (OK, maybe the occasional Dennis Rodman, for
that kid who's just a little different). A good Brazilian team
always will spread the wealth. I even saw a Romario jersey, in
honor of the '94 World Cup star who was left off this year's team.
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldo is the youngest-looking sports deity I have ever seen.
Magic Johnson, Jean-Claude Killy, Greg LeMond and Rod Laver never
looked this young. Jim Brown was  &LR; never  &LR; young. The gap-toothed
Ronaldo looks like a kid who got a chance to run around with the
great ones for a day. That's all he did Thursday, by the way _ run
around. He did many laps in a slow jog around the perimeter, then
disappeared down a runway. He can do that, because he's Ronaldo,
and apologies to the kids. He's not taking BP today.
</P>
<P>
   As if it even mattered. I couldn't keep my eyes off Dunga, the
tough-guy midfielder and veteran of three World Cups. In this
playful scene he was a comedian, performing Globetrotter-like
miracles with his feet. He wouldn't just catch that fallen shrimp
or Heineken; he'd deliver it right back to your hand, with a little
wink in his eye.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of hands, one wonders: In a game where they might as
well be amputated, do they go stale on you? Could Rivaldo flip a
bottlecap or fancy-deal a deck of cards? Do these guys eat like the
ancient Vikings, hurling slabs of beef across the table?
</P>
<P>
   I got my answer from Sampaio, who picked up a ball, sent it
spinning on the tip of his middle finger, then watched it revolve
like a top, forever. I got it from Taffarel, the goalkeeper, making
artful catches with one hand. In the tense desperation of a game,
keepers perform time-it-or-die punches or two-armed wraparounds, as
if an infant child was heading their way. In the casual atmosphere
of practice, I saw many Fred Biletnikoffs.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, the Brazilians reminded me of children. They
had a dozen little games going, to the accompaniment of laughter
and playful roughhousing. One game sends a loose player into the
middle of an 11-man ring, all of them clasping hands. He only has
to make a touch, to stop the flow, but with these guys, he was like
a miniature man dropped into a pinball machine. The ball movement
was blinding.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer is often called ``the beautiful game,'' and in a
Brazilian practice, purity shines forth. Now free of the relentless
diving and tackling, the many fits and starts, it becomes an
uninhibited expression of freedom and personality. It's like a
dance floor out there, really, and we all know what that means. The
good dancers get the space, the respect and the girls. I'm one of
those guys who needs two or three kicks to get the Sunday paper
down the driveway, but if you've grown up with the game, like a
million kids in Brazil, the sight of these cavorting legends must
be magical.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil vs. France: Could Sunday's final get any better? The
Chicago Bulls of soccer against the host nation, all giddy and
fascinated with itself. I'll never forget the sight of the
jam-packed Champs-Elysees the other night, and what it meant for so
many thousands of French people to celebrate together. But I'll
take Thursday's memory along, too. The Brazilians truly make it a
beautiful game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
