A8644 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ATHLETICS-SFCHRON     07-10 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ATHLETICS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY STEVE KETTMANN 
</HEADLINE>
  
Curtain Rises, A's Fall  c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ That was far more than a ballgame Thursday at
the Coliseum. President Sandy Alderson raised the bar for his team
over the All-Star break, railing against local media for slighting
the A's impressive four-game winning streak to close out the first
half.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alderson was taking a calculated gamble with his talk of a
conspiracy against his team. If he demanded more attention, and his
team played well, he could expect more coverage _ and presumably
more fan interest.
</P>
<P>
   If he yelled at everyone to look at his team, and what they saw
was a team finding a way to lose, that wouldn't leave him any
better off.
</P>
<P>
   One game into a crucial, 11-game homestand that will determine
whether Alderson's outburst was smart, or just good for his blood
pressure, the verdict is: Maybe another day of obscurity wouldn't
have been such a bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   The A's wasted another beautiful outing from staff ace Kenny
Rogers, who left after eight innings with the score tied 1-1. Texas
rallied for three runs in the top of the ninth against closer Billy
Taylor, helped by catcher Mike Macfarlane's throwing error, and won
4-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pitches as well as he could pitch, and we come up dry,''
manager Art Howe said. ``It's a shame to waste that kind of
effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor has given up at least one run in four of his past five
outings, but it's hard to heap too much blame on him for Thursday's
ugly ninth. Pinch-hitter Tom Goodwin led off the inning with a slap
single to right, then stole second and took third on the play when
Macfarlane's throw bounced and skipped behind the bag.
</P>
<P>
   Will Clark earned a walk, but then Taylor struck out Juan
Gonzalez, the man with 101 RBIs, and got Ivan Rodriguez to smack a
hard-hit ball up the middle that looked like it would be an
inning-ending (and tie-preserving) double play. Instead, it caromed
off Taylor and into right field and the Rangers had the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got the groundball, it's just too bad it bounced off his
foot,'' Howe said. ``Luck wasn't in our corner today.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Giant John Burkett held the A's to one run on a Rickey
Henderson single to score Jack Voigt in the sixth. Rogers held his
old team to three hits over eight innings. Mike Simms' solo shot in
the third was the only damage and Rogers' ERA dropped to 3.05.
</P>
<P>
   The game proves nothing about how the A's (41-46) will fare over
the next three games against the Rangers (49-39), the team ahead of
them in the American League West, or against the first-place Angels
the next two games after that. The A's have bounced back well from
bad losses before, and besides, this was a noon start the first
game back from the three-day All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like we were all on a four-day holiday, instead of a
three-day holiday,'' Matt Stairs said. ``Both teams were
sluggish.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Howe: ``We don't have the luxury of letting it set in on
you. Tomorrow's another day.''
</P>
<P>
   But the A's have made it much harder to start the second half
strong and elbow their way into contention in the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Rangers have gotten past the A's ace, they get to
see how Tom Candiotti (5-10, 5.33) and Blake Stein (3-5, 6.52) fare
against the league's most explosive offense Friday night and
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   One year ago, the A's lost their first five games after the
break and did so by an average margin of more than four runs per
game.
</P>
<P>
   Either team could have pulled out Thursday's game in the ninth,
so there's no reason to think history will repeat itself.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
