<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAGING-BUS-DRIVER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SETTLEMENT EXPOSES BUS DRIVER'S LONG RECORD OF VIOLENCE TOWARD
PASSENGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BETH BARRETT  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Supervisors kept bus driver David Smith behind
the wheel for seven years despite his failing a drug test and
drawing 27 passenger complaints -- including that he shoved a
toddler and punched a rider.
</P>
<P>
   Now Smith has cost taxpayers $225,000 to settle a lawsuit
brought by 79-year-old Louis Ross, who claimed Smith hit and choked
him, causing injuries that cost him $10,000 in medical bills.
</P>
<P>
   An attorney for the Metropolitan Transportation Authority said
Thursday that he recommended a settlement in late May because the
agency was too vulnerable over its demonstrated failure to protect
the public in that case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The operator's history was the major concern,'' said Phil
Miller, deputy Los Angeles County counsel overseeing MTA operations
litigation. ``The agency has responsibility for the safety of
passengers on its buses.''
</P>
<P>
   The MTA board approved the payout June 25 in closed session.
Members did not call for an investigation of the case, nor were
they provided with a detailed explanation of what went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   However, board members were ``aghast and outraged,'' said Glenda
Wina, spokeswoman for Los Angeles County Supervisor Yvonne
Brathwaite Burke, who chairs the operations committee and was
briefed on the meeting. Burke was out of the office and unavailable
for comment.
</P>
<P>
   MTA board member and Glendale Councilman Larry Zarian, who did
not attend the session, said the facts in the case implicate MTA
supervisors who allowed what he termed ``a cancer'' to remain in
the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everything was in fact in his record, then someone was
neglectful,'' Zarian said. ``He continued to work and a supervisor
did not pay attention. That's not acceptable in my mind. The
reprimand should be of the person who kept him on the job.''
</P>
<P>
   The question, he added, is ``Why did they keep him?''
</P>
<P>
   MTA officials declined to respond, saying information about
Smith is confidential because it is a personnel matter. Such
confidentiality extends to all cases, whether or not the public's
welfare is at stake, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also declined to disclose whether any MTA supervisors
were disciplined.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly view what this operator did as an unfortunate
incident, but not typical of our bus drivers,'' said MTA spokesman
Ed Scannell. ``Our policy is not to discuss individual employment
histories.''
</P>
<P>
   The Daily News first described how the 79-year-old Ross was
beaten by Smith as part of a broader review of violent bus drivers
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   MTA records documented about 100 incidents during a five-year
span in which operators were implicated in passenger beatings,
assaults on motorists and other serious on-duty crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Former transit police officers provided anecdotal evidence that
the MTA's discipline was uneven, and that some complaints either
weren't thoroughly investigated or that the agency played favorites
with drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement documents in the Ross case show how the MTA
reacted to a driver with repeated allegations of misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the 27 passenger complaints beginning in February 1988,
Smith continued driving. In that span, he was accused of shoving a
2-year-old child, physically ejecting three minors from his bus and
punching a passenger.
</P>
<P>
   What ultimately slowed him down -- but didn't stop him -- was
failing a drug test ordered after he was suspended in September
1992 after a ``physical altercation'' with two women passengers,
the settlement states.
</P>
<P>
   He was discharged, but a successful appeal put him back behind
the wheel a year later, the records show.
</P>
<P>
   In his lawsuit, Ross contended that the MTA either was aware or
should have been aware of Smith's propensity to use physical force
on passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Ross said he had waited 15 minutes for a bus Nov. 18, 1995, at
Temple and Rampart streets when Smith pulled up but didn't open the
doors because he was talking with a passenger.
</P>
<P>
   Ross, who is hearing-impaired and of diminutive stature, began
to knock on the doors. When they opened, he asked -- Smith said he
shouted -- what had taken so long.
</P>
<P>
   It was then that Smith got out of his seat and hit Ross,
``causing him to fall backward into the handrail,'' the settlement
states. ``(Smith) then shook Mr. Ross and grabbed him by the
throat.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross, who could not be reached for comment, suffered cuts,
bruises and other injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who also could not be reached for comment, pleaded no
contest to a battery charge and served six months in jail.
</P>
<P>
   The County Counsel's Office said it never asked MTA officials
why they kept Smith on the payroll, but left no doubt that their
failure was critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe a court or jury would find the bus operator
assaulted Louis Ross on the bus,'' the settlement states. ``The MTA
will be strictly liable for such conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldy Norton, spokesman for the United Transportation Union,
said that while most bus drivers are professional, ``several may
not be the greatest people in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   It is up to the MTA to make sure the public is protected, he
said, citing rules that allow the agency to dismiss drivers for an
array of offenses, including ignoring directions to ``deal with
customers in a polite and professional manner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Discipline, that's their obligation,'' Norton said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
