   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BIRTHRATE-DECLINE (Stockholm, Sweden) _ Driven largely by
prosperity and freedom, millions of women _ here and throughout the
developed world _ are having fewer children than ever before.
Special report. By Michael Specter.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT8,9) have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-ROYALS (London) _ Prince William last month had his
first meeting with Camilla Parker Bowles, the woman his mother,
Diana, blamed for the failure of her marriage to Prince Charles.
The palace does not object to the publication of this news, fueling
speculation that there is a move afoot to win public acceptance of
Camilla as Charles's consort. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   AUSCHWITZ-LAND (Hadera, Israel) _ Last year, at the age of 62,
Zypora Frank learned a terrible truth: Her family had owned part of
the land on which the Auschwitz death camp stood, and where most of
her mother's family perished. In fact, she held the deed to that
land. By Serge Schmemann.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT11) has been sent to NYT photo clients)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SHIPYARD-LABOR (New Orleans) _ Five years ago, the workers at
Avondale shipyard voted to join a union, with hundreds of them
cheering wildly outside the company's headquarters along the
Mississippi when the vote count was announced. Today, there is
still no union at the shipyard. The 50,000 pages of documents
stacked in the offices of the National Labor Relations Board are
evidence of what happened instead, producing one of the longest,
most heavily litigated unionization fights in the board's history.
At a time when labor unions nationwide are stepping up efforts to
organize millions of workers, labor leaders point to the Avondale
battle as proof that the nation's labor laws are cumbersome and
replete with loopholes. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   NY-MISSING-MILLIONAIRE (New York) _ Over the last two years,
Sante and Kenneth Kimes, a mother-and-son team with long criminal
records, have traveled across the United States and beyond, always
remaining a step ahead of criminal investigators seeking to
question them about theft, arson and the disappearance _ or murders
_ of at least three people. Police finally tracked them down Sunday
in New York, arresting them at the New York Hilton on a Utah
warrant for writing a bogus check. But one last time, investigators
now fear, they were just hours too late. It was only after the
mother-and-son team were in jail that investigators suspected their
involvement in the disappearance earlier that day of a wealthy East
Side Manhattan socialite, Irene Silverman. By Christopher Drew.
</P>
<P>
   DAUGHTER-RECANT (Clarkstown, N.Y.) _ At her father's sentencing
last year, Stacey Hoehmann was a figure of tortured outrage,
providing her own pronouncement of doom for what she said was his
repeated sexual abuse of her as a teen-ager. ``Maybe nobody else
saw what he did, but God did and He's not going to forget,'' she
told the court and her father. ``So if you think it's over today,
it's not, because your day is still coming. You're burning in hell
for what you did.'' But on Wednesday, Stacey and her father, Joseph
Hoehmann, hugged jubilantly in a hallway of the same courthouse and
were joined in the embrace by Stacey's mother, Kelly Hoehmann. What
set off this dramatic reversal was a startling letter Ms. Hoehmann,
now 20, sent to Judge Vincent Alfieri Jr. of Clarkstown Justice
Court in March. Her accusation, she said, had all been lies. By
Joseph Berger.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT22) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   QUACKS-MUSEUM (Minneapolis) _ It is odd to find the Museum of
Questionable Medical Devices here in the capital of Midwestern
niceness. But just across the river from all the skyscrapers, in
the historic St. Anthony Main complex, is an array of bogus medical
devices spanning two centuries, a stunning testament to the myriad
ways people have tried to make money off the eternal ills of
humankind. By Tamar Lewin.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT16,17) have been sent to NYT photo clients)
