<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-EXPOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPOS DEFEAT METS, 9-8 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The day began with bad enough news, with the New York
Mets learning that their closer, John Franco, had been suspended
for three games because of his angry outburst at the umpires at the
end of last Sunday's disputed extra-inning loss to the Atlanta
Braves.
</P>
<P>
   And the day ended with Franco a double loser, as he took the
defeat in an unbelievably ugly 9-8 11-inning loss to the Montreal
Expos. If Franco had known how Thursday night's game would turn
out, he might have decided not to appeal his suspension after all.
</P>
<P>
   For Franco and the Mets it was a miserable way to begin the
second half of the season. The winning run came on Rondell White's
two-out single to left that skipped off Rey Ordonez's glove. Only
minutes before, Todd Pratt had led off the bottom of the 10th for
the Mets with a double. But after Edgardo Alfonzo failed to bunt
Pratt over, he hit a fly ball to right field on which Pratt tagged
up and went to third. The only trouble was that Pratt left the base
long before the ball was caught. The Expos appealed, and Pratt was
out.
</P>
<P>
   So it went for the Mets (44-40), who have now dropped eight of
their last 10 games and may need more than the return of Todd
Hundley on Sunday night to get them playing good baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Neither pitching staff seemed content with a lead on Thursday
night. The Expos blew three of them, the Mets coughed up two, all
while both teams were surrendering 34 hits. Over all, it was a
sloppy affair for both teams, who combined for four errors (two
apiece), not to mention a balk, a passed ball and another
base-running gaffe, by the Mets rookie Benny Agbayani, who fell
down on a botched hit-and-run play in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a month,'' said Mike Piazza, mindful that the Mets have
gone 13-20 since June 1. ``Every mistake we make is hurting us bad.
You hate to start the second half on a note like this. What can you
say? It's frustrating. It really is. You figure we scored enough
runs to win that game. We're just not getting it done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets rallied from deficits of 2-0, 5-3 and finally, 8-7.
They scored a run in the third, two in the fourth, three in the
fifth, one in the sixth and one more in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   And the two players who stand to lose the most playing time when
Hundley arrives in the outfield tomorrow evening _ Bernard Gilkey
and Butch Huskey _ each delivered important hits in the first three
rallies.
</P>
<P>
   Gilkey batted leadoff for the second time this season and
doubled in Ordonez, who tied his career high with four hits, for
the Mets' first run. The shot came within inches of clearing the
fence in left-center for a game-tying two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   Huskey and Ordonez singled in runs in the fourth to give Bobby
Jones a brief 3-2 lead. But Jones, who had allowed solo homers to
F.P. Santangelo leading off the game and Vladimir Guerrero with two
out in the third, contributed greatly to Montreal's three-run
fifth. He bobbled a potential double-play ball with runners on
first and second and one out and then nearly threw the ball away.
</P>
<P>
   Only a nice play by John Olerud to block Jones' throw stopped
Montreal from scoring right there. But with the bases loaded, Brad
Fullmer blooped a single to left for two runs, Mark Grudzielanek
hit a sacrifice fly to right and the Expos had a 5-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Shane Andrews muffed an Alfonzo grounder to open
the Mets' fifth. Olerud then tripled off White's glove in
right-center field to score Alfonzo and cut the deficit to 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   After Piazza popped out and Carlos Baerga took a called third
strike, it looked as if the Montreal right-hander Dustin Hermanson
might leave Olerud stranded on third with the tying run. But Huskey
drilled a 1-1 pitch some 430 feet over the center-field fence that
gave the Mets a 6-5 lead.
</P>
<P>
   They added a run in the sixth when Ordonez scored from second on
Chris Widger's passed ball and throwing error into left field. But
the Mets' rookie right-hander Jeff Tam, who had not allowed a run
in his first five major league innings over four appearances, gave
up three runs on four consecutive one-out hits in the top of the
seventh. Andrews's two-run double, which short-hopped Huskey in
right, capped the rally and put the Expos ahead by 8-7.
</P>
<P>
   Ordonez led off the bottom of the eighth against the
right-hander Anthony Telford with his fourth single and moved to
third on a pair of groundouts. Up stepped Alfonzo, who delivered a
single to left to score Ordonez and knot the game at 8-8. For the
Mets, the worst was yet to come.
</P>
</TEXT>
