</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-ORIOLES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIPKEN LIFTS ORIOLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ And now comes the hard part.
</P>
<P>
   As if they needed any reminder, the Red Sox, sights set on a
playoff berth and with Mo Vaughn back in the lineup, began the
second half of the schedule Thursday night with a 3-2 loss to the
Baltimore Orioles, preseason favorites who have fallen out of sight
in the American League East.
</P>
<P>
   While Vaughn walked and doubled in four plate appearances, the
Orioles prevailed on an eighth-inning single by
rusting-but-still-dangerous legend Cal Ripken.
</P>
<P>
   Iron Cal responded to an intentional walk to B.J. Surhoff by
clunking a broken-bat single into center field off reliever Jim
Corsi. That hit scored Eric Davis, who had opened the inning by
hustling his way to an opposite-field double and taking third on a
fly ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people figure they're being singled out (by an
intentional walk), but I saw it as a matter of strategy,'' Ripken
said. ``Corsi is tough on a lot of people, especially me.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just battle and try and do the best you can. I got a
little lucky today. I broke a bat and hit it in the right spot.
I'll take it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox' logic in passing Surhoff to get to Ripken seemed
unassailable. In eight career at-bats against Corsi, Ripken had
just one hit, and the Newton, Mass., native struck him out in
Boston last month. But Corsi, who had been unbeaten in 37 previous
appearances this season, reverted to Son of Steamer form as Ripken
reached down and dunked a javelin throw of a hit just over the Sox
infield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cal fouled off a couple of pitches then put the ball in
play,'' Corsi said. ``I made a good pitch. Sometimes you make a
lousy pitch, they hit a rocket right at somebody, and you look like
the hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have rather made a lousy pitch and have him hit a
rocket at Nomar. It's just aggravating, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   The aggravation was just beginning for Red Sox manager Jimy
Williams, who after a ninth-inning leadoff single by John Valentin,
was forced to use his pinch hitters out of sequence because plate
umpire Jim Evans said he saw Williams pointing at Jason Varitek in
the on-deck circle, when Williams in fact was pointing at Reggie
Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grabbed the pine-tar rag in the on-deck circle just in case
I had to hit,'' said Varitek, who was forced to bat and popped out.
``I was on the edge of the circle, handed the rag to Reggie, and
walked away. I never took a practice swing.''
</P>
<P>
   Orioles lefty Jesse Orosco had just given up Valentin's single
when Williams sent righthanded hitting Damon Buford to hit for
Scott Hatteberg. Orioles manager Ray Miller countered by summoning
his righthanded closer, Armando Benitez, when the confusion began.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who earlier this season experienced another umpiring
first when third-base umpire John Hirschbeck said he heard a pitch
hit Tampa Bay batter Quinton McCracken in a dome, said this was
another first.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I pointed, I pointed to Reggie,'' he said. ``I didn't
even see Varitek out there, myself. Reggie came up to hit and Evans
told me Varitek was already in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea. What was I supposed to do. Varitek's in the
game, Reggie's up to hit, and I don't have another catcher. I don't
understand. He says, `Varitek's got to hit or you don't have a
catcher.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, both Varitek and Jefferson came to the plate and
made outs, Varitek popping out, Jefferson whiffing, and the game
ended with DH Midre Cummings lining out to the track in
left-center.
</P>
<P>
   It's quite possible that had Jefferson been given the chance to
advance Valentin, Williams would have kept Varitek in reserve and
let Mike Benjamin hit in that situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea what was going on,'' said Jefferson, whose back
was still sore after taking a cortisone shot on Sunday. ``It caught
me totally off-guard. I was just thinking, `Get me in there, I
don't want to stretch my back too much.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles began the night losers of 11 of their last 12 and 26
1/2 games out of first place, the farthest they have been back at
the break in 43 years. The last time they were over .500 was May
14, when ace pitcher Mike Mussina was struck by a line drive hit by
Cleveland's Sandy Alomar, big brother of Orioles second baseman
Roberto Alomar.
</P>
<P>
   For the first seven innings, solo home runs were the order of
the night as two each by both sides _ Darren Bragg and Valentin for
the Sox off Mussina, Alomar and Mike Bordick for the hometown Birds
off Bret Saberhagen _ accounted for all the scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a lot of ways this is the toughest game of the season,''
said Saberhagen, who threw 102 pitches in five innings before
giving way to Derek Lowe, who went six up, six down. ``Everybody's
been relaxing, getting away from the game a little bit. The first
game back is tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were kind of dead out there, nobody's fault really, but it
was like we were a little laid-back. Hopefully, tomorrow we'll come
back out and play ball the way we've been playing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
