</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS LIFT BURDEN OFF STUNNED DAVIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Change is in the air. The Mariners refuse to go down
without a fight and Russ Davis did not start at third base Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Even he knows why.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, Lou (Piniella) can't keep throwing me at third if I'm
killing the team, you know? And I totally agree with it. I wouldn't
do it either,'' Davis said Thursday night, his Alabama drawl
telling an anguished tale of a season that needed its free-fall
stopped, for him and the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have a guy out there if you're trying to win a
championship and it's supposed to be a big banner year. I'm not
going to throw a guy out there who's booting balls and continues to
let runs come around. Try something different and if that don't
work ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Davis' voice trailed off, but he's facing facts. It's over for
him.
</P>
<P>
   At third base, that is. For now and probably the rest of the
season, which is a big relief for the snake-bit Davis and an
absolutely necessary move for the desperate Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday marked the start to the second half of 1998. Moving
Davis out of his own personal hell was the least the Mariners could
do, until, of course, they do something bigger and bolder, like
make some trades and start working toward really improving this
should-be contender.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, the M's electrified the Kingdome, beating the
Angels 8-6 and making it look like they could rise from the ashes,
although it will take two solid weeks to get the final read on the
team's EKG.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, smaller fires had to be put out. Immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, in another important American League West game
against the Angels, Davis is scheduled to start in left field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to let Russ play out there and maybe it will be
the right tonic for him,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to give him a chance to relax and help his
hitting, maybe offensively he can put up some good numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Which means Davis will become the 59th man to play that position
since Ken Griffey Jr. took over in center field 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The way Davis figures it, he can't be too great a liability in
his new position, which he has never once fielded, not even in the
minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   But considering that Glenallen Hill occupied that position for
much of the first half of '98, Davis understands no one is
expecting him to win a Gold Glove. Just make the routine plays.
Hit. Accept getting pulled for a better defensive player in the
late innings. Try not to wonder if he'll be part of a package when
the trades come.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is not out of the race. I don't know if this is the
answer or not. You never know. I might be able to go out and be an
All-Star left fielder,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, at this point in time, I need to do something
different just to get my mind off this whole thing at third base. I
need to flush all this stuff out of my head.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened to Davis in Texas right before All-Star Game break
was the final straw. It made his banishment from third base
inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it made it humane, since Davis' pain and suffering and
ham-handedness were so incredibly obvious and detrimental, to him
and his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five stinking errors in two days. That's the worst it's ever
been,'' said Davis, the 28-year-old Alabaman whose five fielding
gaffes against the Rangers pushed him to a major-league worst 25
errors.
</P>
<P>
   Davis never dreamed his major league career would have come to
this _ a nightmare that infield coach Steve Smith said left Davis
unable to sleep at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The team's) not living up to expectations and I feel like I'm
a real big part of that,'' Davis said, lifting up his cap and
running his hands through his hair, over and over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think over there it's just a case of not being able to get
negative thoughts out of my head. There's a lot of negativity
surrounding this whole ballclub, first of all. And I'm a big part
of that. It's something I've never really had to deal with. It's
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Drafted by the Yankees in 1988, Davis was one of their
well-regarded prospects, even if his mechanics at third base were
never natural or totally sound. But Davis worked at it. His bat was
dynamic and his former AAA-Columbus manager, Buck Showalter, would
have played him at Yankee Stadium if only a guy named Wade Boggs
had not signed there as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   But after two injury-shortened seasons with the M's, Davis'
first real chance to make his mark as an everyday third baseman
came this year. It was a disaster from the start _ although perhaps
it was not totally unpredictable that Davis would have trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like he's never had trouble before,'' said Smith, who
has worked extensively with Davis to improve his mechanics at
playing down on the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said he will look forward to the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seemed like I started out real bad and I dug myself a
big hole and it just keeps getting deeper and deeper. I'm trying to
claw my way out and I just haven't had any success doing it,''
Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   The M's have finally lifted the burden off Davis. It is what
many hope is only the first step toward inner-Mariner peace and
productivity.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
