<HEADLINE>
EX-BUSINESS PARTNER SUES GRIFFEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS and RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ An attorney for Ken Griffey Jr. has asked that the
Mariners' All-Star center fielder be dropped from a lawsuit in
which a former business partner accuses him of backing out of a
contract to open a chain of Griffey's Sports Bar and Grills.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Griffey signed an exclusive licensing agreement with
Thomas Brown and Endorsements Unlimited in 1992 to use his name and
likeness on restaurants, bars and nightclubs, Griffey later bought
out Brown of Bellevue and his partner, Hugh Stanton of Issaquah,
said David Lawyer, Griffey's attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Brown received $250,000 and Stanton got $400,000 from Griffey in
separate settlements approved by attorneys on both sides of the
business, which never took shape beyond the planning stages, Lawyer
said. Brown also names Griffey's parents, Ken Griffey Sr. and
Alberta Griffey, who also signed the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Brown claims Stanton conspired with the Griffeys to
oust him.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement was made after Griffey signed an agreement with
Planet Hollywood to develop the Official All Star Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   But in a lawsuit filed in King County Superior Court, Brown now
says he felt pressured to accept the settlement last March. He
claims Griffey's agent, Brian Goldberg, threatened his family and
that the ballplayer and his agent knew Brown needed money prior to
making a settlement offer, which originally was $125,000.
</P>
<P>
   Brown now wants up to $10 million, and says the contract could
have been worth $5 million to $7 million over five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can pay me my money and I'll walk away,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   But Lawyer claims the figure is ridiculous for a business
arrangement that never took form and was already settled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The corporation was a shell,'' Lawyer said. ``It had no
assets, it had no employees, it had nothing. They never opened a
restaurant, they never had a schedule by which they were going to
open a restaurant. They negotiated toward the execution of a lease,
but no lease was ever signed. . . . It never got off the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's attorney, Robert Brandt, said that while no business got
off the ground, the partners, including Griffey, did meet with
Seafirst bank officials and had plans to open a sports restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a business deal that's gone bad,'' Brandt said,
declining to comment about the specifics of the case.
</P>
<P>
   The next court date in the lawsuit is scheduled for July 24, in
which a judge will hear arguments on Lawyer's motion to dismiss the
case based on the signed settlement agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Among other issues, the lawsuit alleges that Griffey told
creditors about back taxes Brown owed and suggested they foreclose
on his stock in Endorsements Unlimited, and gave personal
information about Brown to other business associates to devalue his
stock.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyer said that Brown, a former motorcycle dealer, also claims
that Griffey had a hand in a criminal charge filed against Brown in
Kittitas County. According to the lawsuit, Brown claims Griffey
urged Ellensburg police to file criminal charges against Brown
after he took money for the sale of a motorcycle but never
delivered it to the Ellensburg buyer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
