<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIFFEY HITS 36TH HOMER IN M'S VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ For better or worse, here come the Mariners?
</P>
<P>
   If the M's have decided to marry into the notion of changing
their inept ways, it was evident Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The M's at least hope the wedlock to the second half of the
season is as eventful and fruitful as their 8-6 victory over the
American League West-leading Anaheim Angels at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing the Angels by 13 games after the All-Star break, the
Mariners know they need plenty of good karma to recover. Thursday
night did not erase three months of disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   However, it could be considered a step toward salvaging an
otherwise dissolution this season. Consider:
</P>
<P>
   -- The M's began an 11-game homestand and play three more
against Anaheim, the team they overtook for the division title in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   -- By the end of next week, the M's should know their fate after
facing second-place Texas following this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see where we're at by the middle of the month,'' M's
manager Lou Piniella said. ``If we get on the right foot and gain
some momentum, it'll give us a chance to get back in the race. . .
. All we have to do is play better. It doesn't matter how the front
team is playing. The only situation you can control is your own.''
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim had outscored the Mariners 32-12 and was unbeaten in
five meetings this season.
</P>
<P>
   However, M's starter Jeff Fassero (8-5) reversed that wave with
his third straight effective outing. The Mariners' offense
supported Fassero with a five-run fifth and three-run sixth.
</P>
<P>
   When Ken Griffey Jr. belted his AL-leading 36th home run in the
sixth, Fassero worked with an 8-1 cushion. Griffey's homer was the
330th of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to go out there and play,'' Griffey said. ``I'm
just trying to win as many ballgames as I can for the Mariners.
It's hard to do anything if you're not playing consistently.
Hopefully this is the start of it _ playing consistent ball for the
rest of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassero mostly dominated through 62/3 innings. He stayed in
front of the count, and kept batters off balance with his fastball
and a hard, inside slider.
</P>
<P>
   With a comfortable lead and two out in the seventh, Fassero
tried to finish the job. However, the Angels banged him around for
three hits and four runs in that inning. Fassero yielded to Bobby
Ayala, who allowed a base hit before he smothered Anaheim's rally.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella did not take any chances with an 8-5 lead. After Ayala
yielded a one-out double in the eighth, Piniella turned to Paul
Spoljaric. However, Spoljaric immediately gave up a towering double
to Darin Erstad, putting the tying run at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   When Spoljaric recorded an out, Greg McCarthy came on and ended
the inning when he got Jim Edmonds to fly out to left. Mike Timlin
pitched the ninth and recorded his second save.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always nice to win the first one. You just try to win the
series,'' Timlin said. ``If you do that, you come out on the
winning side.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Mariner Omar Olivares (5-5) took the loss for the Angels.
Olivares lost his third straight start.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners cracked Olivares in the fifth when Joey Cora began
a rally with a one-out double that was followed by Alex Rodriguez's
triple to right-center field.
</P>
<P>
   With one run in, Martinez and Segui both walked to load the
bases for Buhner, who promptly delivered a single to center. Dan
Wilson loaded the bases again after he chopped an infield hit to
third. That set up Shane Monahan's first major league hit.
</P>
<P>
   Monahan, called up from Class AAA Tacoma to start in left field,
struck out his first two times at the plate. However, his base hit
to center drove in two runs and capped the Mariners' game-breaking
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Cora added another run in the sixth when he sent an Olivares
fastball over the right-field wall for his third home run. Moments
later, Olivares hit Rodriguez on the left shoulder. That pitch
chased Olivares, who allowed seven earned runs.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim reliever Rich DeLucia entered the game and probably
wishes he had not. Griffey pounded DeLucia's first pitch to
straight-away center for a two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Fassero retired seven of the next eight batters he
faced after the third. He even pitched his way out of a
bases-loaded jam in the sixth. Fassero struck out Phil Nevin and
got Justin Baughman to fly out to right, which ended the Angels'
best scoring threat.
</P>
<P>
   How important was this game to Anaheim?
</P>
<P>
   Nevin was ejected for arguing a third strike. As part of his
tirade, Nevin threw his helmet and ripped off his jersey _
reminiscent of Hulk Hogan during his red and gold Hulkamania era.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the Mariners felt a sense of urgency, Timlin said:
``No. I was told this team was 13 games out in August (of 1995).
Everyone knows what we can do. We know what we can do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
