<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8866 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAACP-$ADV12-COX     07-10 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-$ADV12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NAACP OPENS NATIONAL CONVENTION WITH REVITALIZED SPIRIT
 &HT;    1000&AMP;add. For release Sunday, July 12
 &HT;    By MARK SHERMAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Californians voted to end affirmative action
programs two years ago, the nation's largest civil rights
organization was missing in action.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People
(NAACP) does not plan to repeat that mistake in November, when
voters in Washington state will have essentially the same question
before them.
</P>
<P>
   The association will spend $50,000 to try to defeat the
Washington ballot initiative. and it will work with a coalition of
labor and civic groups seeking to blunt the assault on affirmative
action programs.
</P>
<P>
   This effort is one sign of the renewed vitality of the
89-year-old organization, its supporters say, just a few years
after some people were wondering whether it would survive at all.
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP is expecting 6,000 people at its annual meeting, which
began Saturday in Atlanta. ``We're at a moment where the
organization is poised on a path of terrific opportunity,'' said
Roger Wilkins, the George Mason University professor who also is
board chairman of the NAACP magazine, Crisis.
</P>
<P>
   For Julian Bond, who returns to his home town for the convention
as the NAACP's new chairman, the trick is not necessarily doing
anything new, but doing ``the old things better.''
</P>
<P>
   The old things Bond spoke of include returning the organization
to its focus of fighting racial discrimination instead of its
members fighting each other. The NAACP is only now emerging from
several years of turmoil in its leadership positions. The resulting
financial crisis plunged it more than $4 million in debt and
prevented the organization from contributing to the campaign
against the anti-affirmative action issue in California.
</P>
<P>
   Bond claims the NAACP now has a $2 million surplus, a turnaround
that was achieved in part by mass layoffs of staff members at its
Baltimore headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   In Bond and the NAACP's president and CEO, former Rep. Kweisi
Mfume, D-Md., the civil rights group has two elegant public
spokesmen with vast political experience.
</P>
<P>
   The challenges facing the NAACP suggest they will need every
ounce of their skills.
</P>
<P>
   The association still is struggling to reach out to young
African-Americans, who have no memory of the seminal struggle for
voting rights, fair housing laws and desegregated schools. Some
young blacks still perceive the NAACP as a stodgy, slow-footed
group, a view Bond himself held when he was a young civil rights
worker in the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Walters, a University of Maryland political scientist,
said the NAACP's work with young people is directed primarily to
the middle class, a criticism he said holds for the organization in
general.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the vexing question. The young people I see taking part
are essentially middle class,'' Walters said. ``Eventually they are
going to have to deal with questions of urban policy, questions of
poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   With Hispanics about to become the nation's largest minority
group, NAACP leaders are increasingly talking in terms of working
with other ethnic and racial groups. ``Colored people come in all
colors,'' Bond has said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet of the NAACP's 64 directors, two are white and the rest are
African-American. Michael Meyers, president of the New York Civil
Rights Coalition, is a vocal critic of the NAACP, where he once
worked as a staff member.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is supposed to believe in racial harmony, but it is a very
segregated organization,'' Meyers said.
</P>
<P>
   To support his contention, he pointed to the NAACP's ambivalence
toward Nation of Islam leader Louis Farrakhan.
</P>
<P>
   There is no unanimity on the NAACP's board of directors about
the proper relationship with Farrakhan.
</P>
<P>
   Bond has unambiguously said Farrakhan preaches an exclusionary
message that has no place in the NAACP. But Mfume's history with
Farrakhan is more complex. He once spoke of a ``sacred covenant''
between Farrakhan and the Congressional Black Caucus, which he
headed at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Madison, a Washington talk radio host who was Bond's closest
competitor for the chairmanship, said African-American groups need
to work in concert because black congressmen would be chairmen of
three powerful committees in the House of Representatives if
Democrats can capture a majority in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should be open dialogue with Farrakhan. We stand at a
critical juncture that requires a major voter registration and
get-out-the-vote effort,'' Madison said. ``The Nation of Islam is a
major player.''
</P>
<P>
   Disagreement, if not outright dissension, among NAACP directors
is nothing new. Bond described the group as a firing squad standing
in a circle and facing inward. His job, he said, is to ``make them
turn around.''
</P>
<P>
   While money no longer is a source of controversy, Mfume and Bond
have acknowledged that a campaign to raise a $50 million endowment
is progressing more slowly than planned.
</P>
<P>
   The endowment drive is just one way Bond and Mfume have tried to
raise the NAACP's profile. Mfume has used an annual scorecard for
the hotel industry to shine a spotlight on hotel chains that the
NAACP says do not give African Americans sufficient employment,
management or ownership opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Two chains, Best Western and Omni, scored so low that the
organization will not do business with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one I didn't think would have political salience, but
it has made the hotel industry sensitive about the list and that's
good,'' Walters said. ``This is an example of the kind of civil
rights work they should be doing, instead of the social service
approach they seem to have taken too often recently.''
</P>
<P>
   Mfume also has tried to draw increased attention to the NAACP's
annual congressional report card of votes it deems critically
important, which this year includes three affirmative action
measures and a bill to provide vouchers for private schools to
low-income students in Washington. The NAACP opposed the bill,
which supporters said would provide mainly African-American
children their best way out of the city's troubled public schools.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Both sets of rankings are available on the NAACP's Internet site
(http://www.naacp.org), but Bond said the organization has yet to
modernize in terms of technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to bring us up to the 20th century,'' he said. ``Quite
often, the NAACP office in a town will be a telephone answering
machine in somebody's living room. ... I want there to be e-mail
and the same kind of communications network that almost every other
organization of our kind has. Nothing extraordinary, but enough to
more quickly mobilize our troops.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond tells audiences around the country that the NAACP today
``is not your father's NAACP.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics such as Meyers agree. But he laments the NAACP's demise.
``They're huffing and puffing and trying to blow people's houses
down,'' he said. ``The only house blowing down is their own
house.''
</P>
<P>
   Walters said Bond and Mfume have placed the NAACP in better
shape than it was a year ago. ``This is a solid team,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
