<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sign of the times: Pray for rain
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Just another dry spell, the men said at first. Ranchers
watched waterholes recede to brown puddles of mud that their
livestock would not touch. They watched the rank weeds shrivel as
the west wind relentlessly sought them out and smothered them with
its hot breath. They watched the grass slowly lose its green, then
curl and fire up like dying cornstalks.''
</P>
<P>
   _ From The Time It Never Rained, by Elmer Kelton
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL TEXAS _ Just off the shoulder of Hwy. 79, a few miles
north of Taylor, a sign sits in front of a parched cornfield,
sun-burned
</P>
<P>
   stalks rustling in the hot wind:
</P>
<P>
   Pray for rain.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the only entreaty to a higher authority for some
relief that I saw posted between here and Austin, but its setting
drove the point home
</P>
<P>
   harder. This country is drying up, the black land turning gray,
the corn well past saving, and most of the cotton crop in deep
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   I stopped on the way back from Austin to visit a friend who runs
the Taylor newspaper, which is conveniently located next to Ed's
Bar (Hours:
</P>
<P>
   Closed until open; open until closed), and around the corner
from Louie Mueller's Barbecue _ which serves the best beef brisket
in the free world.
</P>
<P>
   We went up the road to Frame Switch to eat lunch at the Texas
Cafe, which is graced by a giant statue of a bull that once made
Texas Highways magazine.
</P>
<P>
   If you've ever driven Hwy. 79 to Austin, you've seen the bull.
The food is pretty good too.
</P>
<P>
   My friend told me county farmers harvested less than 30 percent
of the usual corn crop, and predictions aren't any better for
cotton. He's an East
</P>
<P>
   Texas emigrant to the blacklands, and he loves it, though he had
the good sense to get out of the cow business when he moved out of
the Pine Curtain.
</P>
<P>
   He keeps seven head just to piddle with out at a small farm, and
he lives in town. The day before, he got two-tenths of an inch at
the house, and
</P>
<P>
   nine-tenths at the farm a couple of miles away.
</P>
<P>
   I watched that storm on my way into Austin the day before, as I
traveled through Elgin, the official, legislatively mandated
Sausage Capital of
</P>
<P>
   Texas. As I rounded the curve in that big-sky country, I could
see the storm off in the distance, toward Taylor, dropping rain
over a few miles at
</P>
<P>
   most _ including my friend's farm. To the north of the cloud was
blue sky. Same to the south. Such are the scattered showers that
offer what little
</P>
<P>
   relief we get these days.
</P>
<P>
   North of Taylor, farmers are already mowing down the fields of
drought-killed corn. Numerous ``for sale'' signs adorn fences along
the way.
</P>
<P>
   Cows stand sluggishly in stock ponds that barely reach their
ankles even when they're standing in the middle. I never once saw a
hay baler, or even
</P>
<P>
   someone working a tractor for that matter. There's nothing to
bale.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of Hearne, a fire along the railroad tracks claimed a
few miles of trees along the fence row and burned the grass along
the right-of-way. You
</P>
<P>
   see the remains of lots of grass fires these days when driving
through Texas. There's no rain to help the grass grow back.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Trinity River bottom, about 10 miles west of Crockett,
usually one of the prettiest spots in East Texas, is brown and
ugly, the grass
</P>
<P>
   chewed down to nearly nothing by the cattle. There's a ``for
sale'' sign on a chunk of that land too.
</P>
<P>
   Last time I remember it being this hot and dry in Central Texas,
and here too for that matter, was in 1980. I remember because I had
just moved to
</P>
<P>
   Austin, and I spent the first part of summer working for an
inventor who lived in what was then the country near Barton Creek.
I did a number of
</P>
<P>
   odd jobs, like driving a dump truck, breaking up rocks to help
build a garden, and other manual labor.
</P>
<P>
   It hardly rained that summer. Everything turned brown, including
my skin from hours under the sun. This summer is shaping up to be
at least that bad
</P>
<P>
   if something doesn't change pretty soon. It is bad here in East
Texas, but it's worse in the blackland country, where in some spots
less than seven
</P>
<P>
   inches of rain have fallen all year.
</P>
<P>
   In Franklin, a small town that sits on my imaginary border
between Central and East Texas, a church sign reads, ``Thanks for
the rain, Lord.'' I couldn't
</P>
<P>
   tell it had rained there, but I'll take their word for it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, please send us some more. Soon.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His
</P>
<P>
   e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
