<HEADER>
A8868 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-FIRESPEACH11-     07-10 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FIRESPEACH11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton sends message of sympathy to Florida fire victims
 &HT;    By Mary McLachlin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ President Clinton made a brief stop
recently in fire-weary Central Florida to thank firefighters,
sympathize with burned-out families and deliver three messages:
</P>
<P>
   _ Florida is ready to welcome tourists again and needs the
economic boost to recover.
</P>
<P>
   _ The world is facing further extremes of heat, drought and
severe weather and needs all the knowledge firefighters gained from
Florida's ordeal to be better prepared.
</P>
<P>
   _ It shouldn't take a disaster to remind us that we're all part
of a community and that ``we're at our best when we're giving.''
</P>
<P>
   With praise for ``the real American heroes,'' Clinton thanked
the firefighters who kept wildfires from consuming whole
communities.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke at the Daytona International Speedway in Volusia
County, which was hit hard by fires. But there was no trace of
smoke in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton squeezed in the visit between stops in Atlanta and
Miami, attracting a stage full of smiling state and local officials
and a tent full of awed firefighters, National Guardsmen, forest
rangers, Americorps volunteers and others.
</P>
<P>
   Before his speech, Clinton met privately with 10 families who
had lost homes Many of them were renting and had no insurance, and
are now living in hotels or with relatives. ``I'm very sorry for
what you're going through,'' Clinton told them.
</P>
<P>
   He also met with children who had donated money to fire relief
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton declared Florida's 34 counties disaster areas, and
announced new federal assistance for farmers and people who are out
of work because of the fires.
</P>
<P>
   The assistance includes a Labor Department grant of up to $1
million for hiring 200 temporary workers to help clean up charred
areas, restore roads and assist at shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton drew cheers when he alluded to the movie Armageddon and
said:
</P>
<P>
   ``This summer . . . the real American heroes are not up in space
fighting asteroids. They're in Florida fighting fires.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a few hundred of the 5,000 firefighters spread out through
Florida's fire zone got to attend the event, and they rushed to get
within handshaking and picture-taking distance as Clinton slowly
worked his way out through the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it!'' exulted Boca Raton firefighter and paramedic Joel
Narcowich, holding up ``the hand that shook the hand of the
president of the United States.'' And he got a picture with his
pocket camera.
</P>
<P>
   Narcowich and four others from Boca Raton arrived Tuesday, along
with seven from Palm Beach County Fire Rescue and a Broward County
contingent. They're manning fire stations so local firefighters who
have worked weeks without a break can get some rest.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
