<HEADER>
A8869 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIREFIGHTERS11-COX     07-10 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIREFIGHTERS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Firefighters made Florida homes safe for thousands
 &HT;    By Susannah A. Nesmith
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM COAST _ On the road to Greg Weston's neighborhood, a sheet
hangs between two trees with the message ``HOME OF THE BRAVE
(firefighters).''
</P>
<P>
   Weston, a sheriff's deputy, has been one of those firefighters
for the past month in Flagler County, where deputies, paramedics
and even regular citizens were pressed into service to try to save
this small county.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent night, just hours before the county was evacuated,
Weston's own house burned down while he fought a fire at the other
end of the county.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew, even if I was here, there was nothing I could have
done,'' Weston said, standing at his old address. ``There was an
identical house over there that had three firetrucks sitting on it.
The same thing. It's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   When he heard on the police radio that his house was going to
burn, he called his wife. She had about an hour to get their sons,
Alex, 2, and Paul, 6, and a few photos.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's great. Last night was the first time she cried,'' he
said. Last night they sent their sons to Pennsylvania with his
parents. ``You should have been there last night, trying to put
Paul in the van. He kept saying, `I want to go home.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Weston isn't going to let his children see what used to be their
home.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to start building a new one. But for now, he's back on
the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said `As long as my family's safe, I gotta keep working,'
'' said fellow deputy Chris Oh. ``I guess that's the Marine in
him.''
</P>
<P>
   He's one of hundreds of people in Flagler County who have gone
above and beyond the call of duty in the past month in this rural
county. Officials don't know how many of the 100 volunteer and 18
paid firefighters have been injured because none would leave the
fires _ paramedics went to the front lines where they bandaged them
up and sent them back to their hoses. Even the chiefs and captains
were fighting fires. The county's emergency operations director was
hospitalized Wednesday for exhaustion or heat-related problems.
</P>
<P>
   When it came to meals, citizens loaded up pickups full of what
they had cooked and collected at churches and in their
neighborhoods. Officials wouldn't take it at the emergency
operations center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd tell them where a fire was and ask them to take it to the
firefighters,'' Rich Weizer, Flagler's emergency spokesman, said.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Shinnick, 72, a volunteer firefighter, abandoned his sign
painting business to fight fires.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can just wait for the signs,'' Shinnick said. ``Something
like this is more important.''
</P>
<P>
   In front of the Palm Coast volunteer fire station, another sheet
hangs with a message on it, this one from the firefighters who
continued fighting after the county was evacuated and are still
fighting now that the residents have returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome home.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
