<SLUG> BC-MISSING-PAY-PHONES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE FIND 17 STOLEN PAY PHONES IN APARTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By MACARENA HERNANDEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If anyone has ever wondered what happened to the
telephones missing from phone booths in New York City, a partial
answer may have been found Thursday in a Manhattan apartment.
</P>
<P>
   The police said they found 17 public phones Thursday in an
apartment, and arrested two people, Phyllis Shepard, 30, and
Anthony Roper, 35. The two suspects were apparently so hungry for
quarters, police said, that they stole the phones, worth a total of
nearly $60,000, carried them back to the apartment, then broke open
the coin boxes for their paltry bounty.
</P>
<P>
   While vandalism to public phones is a problem commonly faced by
phone companies, it is unusual for entire phones to be stolen, said
Maureen F. Lanagan, a spokeswoman for Bell Atlantic, which has
about 9,000 phones on New York City sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   While Ms. Lanagan would not say how much money Bell Atlantic
phones can hold, officials at another phone company said that at
most the phones contain $150 worth of coins, but are emptied
regularly.
</P>
<P>
   The police said they caught onto the thefts after going to to
execute a warrant for a fugitive wanted in an unrelated case. While
they did not find the man they were looking for, they did find the
17 public phones.
</P>
<P>
   ``They see a man and woman in a the room with lots of pay
phones, most of them in plain sight,'' said an investigator who
spoke on the condition of anonymity. ``They were busted up pretty
bad: coin slots ripped open, backs ripped off, keys punched in.
There were no coins left and there were two crowbars in the room.''
</P>
<P>
   Roper and Ms. Shepard face felony charges of criminal possession
of stolen property and possession of burglary tools, the police
said.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the stolen phones were owned by Bell Atlantic,
other companies said they had had phones stolen, too. Wendy Macey,
a spokeswoman for AT&AMP;T, said her company had fewer problems with
theft because many of its units no longer require coins. In
addition to taking the money, she said, people who steal the phones
can sell the parts.
</P>
</TEXT>
