<SLUG> BC-NJ-PIZZA-SUICIDE-TRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT IN PIZZA MURDERS ATTEMPTS SUICIDE IN JAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ A man charged with murdering two pizza
deliverymen last year tried to commit suicide yesterday, only hours
before he was expected to plead guilty to avoid the death penalty
in the so-called thrill killing.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Thomas J. Koskovich, was found unconscious in his
prison cell after taking an overdose of sleeping pills, officials
said. He remained hospitalized in critical condition Thursday, his
breathing assisted by a ventilator.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued late Thursday afternoon, the Sussex County
Prosecutor, Dolores Blackburn, said that blood and urine tests at
Newtown Memorial Hospital, where Koskovich was in intensive care,
showed that he had taken sleeping pills known as tricyclic
antidepressants. A suicide note was found in his cell at the Walter
Keogh-Dwyer Correctional Facility in Newtown, Ms. Blackburn said.
</P>
<P>
   Koskovich, 20, the older of two defendants in the case, had
planned to plead guilty to murder Thursday afternoon for his role
in the slaying of Giorgio Gallara, a pizza shop owner, and
Gallara's employee, Jeremy Giordano, on April 17, 1997. Prosecutors
had accused Koskovich and the other defendant of killing the two
deliverymen after ordering pizza and luring them to an abandoned
house in Franklin, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The killings in April 1997 were a horrifying shock in Franklin,
a town of 5,000 residents in the northwestern corner of the state.
Even more stunning was the accusation by investigators that the
suspects, trying to relieve their small-town boredom, had killed
the pizza men just to find out what it felt like to commit murder.
</P>
<P>
   The guilty plea would have spared Koskovich execution but would
almost certainly have resulted in a sentence of life in prison. The
other defendant, Jayson Vreeland, was 17 at the time of the
killings and thus was not eligible for the death penalty. But he
faces first-degree murder charges, and if convicted, will face a
life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors and defense lawyers in the case declined to discuss
the plea bargain arrangement, which was first reported in The
Star-Ledger in Newark.
</P>
<P>
   The judge in the case, Reginald Stanton of Sussex County
Superior Court, postponed the hearing at which Koskovich was
expected to enter his plea, pending an improvement in his
condition.
</P>
<P>
   Koskovich's lawyer, Pamela Brause, said that she had met with
Koskovich on Wednesday and that he had appeared nervous _ much as
he had since he was arrested more than a year ago. ``We certainly
weren't expecting anything like this,'' she said. ``The whole
nature of these charges and the magnitude of these proceedings has
always been very difficult for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors at Newtown Memorial Hospital were unable to determine
immediately how many of the prescription pills Koskovich had taken,
according to the Prosecutor's statement. As a result, doctors could
not say whether they expected him to survive. Investigators said
that Koskovich had not been prescribed any medication while in
prison and that they believed he had obtained the pills from
another inmate to whom the pills had been prescribed.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, a prison drug test found heroin in Koskovich's
urine. Prison officials said the drugs had been smuggled into the
prison, and they arrested Koskovich and a second inmate who had
tested positive for heroin. After the arrests, prisoners were no
longer allowed to meet with visitors face to face but were required
to talk to them through a glass partition.
</P>
<P>
   Security at the hospital remained extraordinarily tight, with
sheriff's officers posted both outside Koskovich's room in the
intensive care unit and outside the main entrance to the unit. The
hospital also called in extra security personnel, Grace said. A
guard was positioned at the rear of the hospital, he said, and the
Newtown Police Department had stepped up patrols around the
hospital perimeter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
