u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COACH-DISCRIM-SUIT-NY     07-10 0438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COACH-DISCRIM-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER BROOKLYN COACH WINS DAMAGES IN SEX BIAS SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A U.S. District Court judge in Manhattan has upheld a
jury's verdict in a sex-discrimination suit that Brooklyn College
acted improperly against Molly Perdue, its former women's
basketball coach. The judge, Frederic Block, ordered the college on
June 17 to pay her $799,566 plus accumulated interest.
</P>
<P>
   The figure included legal fees and expenses totaling $356,381
over a five-year period, $134,829 in back pay and liquidated
damages for the same amount and compensatory damages of $85,000.
</P>
<P>
   From 1990 to 1992, Perdue was the college's women's basketball
coach and primary administrator of women's sports.
</P>
<P>
   She said that in 1991, when her coaching salary was $6,500, the
men's coach, Ron Kestenbaum, was paid $45,000. As the de facto
women's athletic director, she said, she was paid less than $38,000
while the men's athletic director, Mark Reiner, received more than
$72,000.
</P>
<P>
   Perdue testified that she had to clean the locker room and
gymnasium floor and launder her team's uniforms because there was
no one else to do it. In addition, she said, male members of the
athletic department subjected her to repeated sexual innuendos and
questions about her and her players' sexual activities.
</P>
<P>
   She sued the City University of New York, of which Brooklyn
College is a member, citing two pieces of Federal legislation: the
Equal Pay Act and Title VII of the 1964 Civil Rights Act. Last
August, a federal jury, citing ``willful'' and ``intentional''
discrimination by the college, ruled in her favor.
</P>
<P>
   On June 17, Block rejected CUNY's motion to overturn the jury
verdict and awarded damages. On Tuesday, CUNY filed an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the verdict is excessive,'' said Jay Hershenson,
CUNY's vice chancellor for university relations. ``As a matter of
law, there were significant errors. We are in the process of
reviewing all options.''
</P>
<P>
   Perdue now directs the boys' and girls' athletic programs at
Provincetown High School in Massachusetts. She said she was pleased
with the judge's decision and added, ``I hope this will help reduce
discrimination against women athletes at all levels.''
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Brake, a former senior counsel to the National Women's
Law Center, said: ``This case is very important for the cause of
equality for women in sports and everywhere else. It demonstrates
the increased ability individuals now have to fight large public
institutions because of changes in the civil rights laws in the
early 1990s.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
