<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANAGED-CARE-2TAKES-$ADV12-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANAGED CARE CONTROVERSY SIZZLES IN WASHINGTON SUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 12)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ This is the summer of forest fires in Florida and
the home run pyrotechnics of baseball stars Mark McGwire, Ken
Griffey Jr. and others. But here in the nation's capital and out on
the campaign trail, the hot topic this summer is managed care.
</P>
<P>
   A mad scramble is underway by both parties to tap voter
frustration over managed care, which now accounts for more than 80
percent of employer-sponsored health-care coverage in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show that more and more of the public is upset that the
health plans' cost-conscious method of providing health care too
frequently denies patients thorough medical attention.
</P>
<P>
   In a Time/CNN poll last week, 76 percent of respondents said
they supported federal regulation of managed care plans, which
monitor services provided to patients to ensure they are medically
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``This issue is incredibly potent,'' said Mark Mellman, a
Democratic pollster. ``I don't think there will be a congressional
race, a Senate race or a gubernatorial race in this country this
year where this will not be discussed and debated in some way. This
issue will be everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican pollster Bob Castro concurred. ``This is an issue
with legs in the public mind,'' he said. Even normally conservative
voters who oppose governmental solutions are ``willing to have the
government intervene because they can see no other way out,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Although the 1998 election is four months away, managed care
already has become a fixture in campaign advertising..MDRV/.MDNM/
In primary races, many Democratic candidates are promising voters
they'll do something about managed care horror stories, usually
involving instances of medical care being denied, with death or
injury resulting.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Health Benefits Coalition, an alliance of 35
employer and health insurance groups, is planning to spend $2
million this year trying to convince the public through advertising
that any effort to regulate managed care would mean big government,
higher-costing insurance premiums, and less employer coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Their ads feature a likeness of the cinematic Frankenstein
creature over the caption: ``Washington, be careful how you play
doctor. You might mandate a monster.''
</P>
<P>
   The coalition includes the American Association of Health Plans,
which represents over 1,000 managed care companies providing
coverage to 140 million people.
</P>
<P>
   ``This debate is being conducted as if mandates cost nothing and
hurt no one,'' said AAHP spokeswoman Susan Pisano. ``And that is
simply not true.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Democrats appear to have an edge in the battle over
the hearts and minds of voters concerned about managed care.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., and Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich.,
and others introduced legislation four months ago at a time when
GOP lawmakers were vacillating on what, if anything, to do about
managed care.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not something the Republicans have an advantage on,''
said Rick Reed, a Republican media consultant. ``Poll after poll
has shown the Democrats ... are perceived as more capable on all
health-care-related issues. That's a problem for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., denounced
managed care legislation as a sure way to drive up health care
costs. But now, in an effort to avoid getting stiffed on a
hot-button issue in an election year, Lott is pledging to bring up
a Republican version this year.
</P>
<P>
   A Senate task force headed by Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., is
drafting a GOP version that may parallel a House Republican bill
introduced last month, the product of a task force chaired by Rep.
Dennis Hastert, R-Ill. The GOP House bill, backed by Speaker Newt
Gingrich, shares several features of the Democratic proposal, which
was introduced in March.
</P>
<P>
   For example, both Republican and Democratic bills would allow a
patient unhappy with a coverage decision by a managed care plan to
appeal that decision to an independent body.
</P>
<P>
   Both bills also would assure easier access to emergency care and
would lift the ``gag rule'' in some plans that limit the freedom of
physicians to discuss treatment options not covered by the plan.
</P>
<P>
   There also are key differences. The Democratic proposal would
end the federal ban on lawsuits against health plan decisions
denying treatment when those decisions cause injury or death.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' bill includes a series of government-enforced
regulations for managed care plans. Among them: Plans must have a
``sufficient number, distribution and variety'' of doctors on hand,
must cover at least 48 hours in a hospital when a woman undergoes a
mastectomy, and must cover patients' costs for clinical trials of
new drugs that have been approved by the Food and Drug
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   None of these are in the House Republican proposal.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans have released only the outline of their
legislative proposal, not the details. However, the GOP plan
appears to permit court action only when a plan defies an outside
appeals body that concludes a patient merits a disputed kind of
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Republicans are hitting the Democratic proposal as a
``big government'' answer, a strategy that has produced victory on
other issues.
</P>
<P>
   From President Clinton's failed 1994 health care initiative to
torpedoed tobacco legislation last month, Republicans and their
various business allies have scored phenomenal victories by
targeting voters' fears that Washington-based solutions wind up
costing them big bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Republican pollster Bill McInturff said that at a minimum, the
GOP House leadership's proposal insulates its candidates this fall
against Democratic charges that Republicans are sitting on their
hands when it comes to managed care.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the House Republican measure are questioning the
sincerity of the GOP leadership say that despite a lack of details,
it appears to be loaded with ``poison pills,'' controversial
elements that Republicans know will never pass Congress. Among them
is a $250,000 cap on medical malpractice liability, an expansion of
controversial medical savings accounts, and permitting small
businesses to band together to purchase insurance in a way that
would negate state-level managed care regulatory law.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have opposed these features in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Speaker Gingrich package is really about protecting (GOP
members of) Congress at the ballot box, rather than protecting
patients,'' said Joan Alker, assistant government affairs director
for Families USA, an advocacy group lobbying for more controls on
managed care.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and their supporters say that the House GOP proposal
is a sincere attempt to forge marketplace solutions to complaints
about managed care rather than rely exclusively on government. And
besides, they say, it is the Democrats who are politically
motivated to stall legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many on the Democratic side are concerned the Republicans
could pass a bill and take the issue off the table in time for the
elections,'' said Dan Danner, a lobbyist with the National
Federation of Independent Business and chairman of the Health
Benefits Coalition. ``And they don't want that to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats agree that no bill at all would lend credibility
to Democratic campaign ads this fall charging Republicans with
indifference to the managed care issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically, I think it's better not to have a bill,'' said
Mellman, the Democratic pollster. ``But the bottom line is that we
have Democrats in the Congress and the Senate who think we should
have a bill for the good of the country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
