<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POSTAL SERVICE'S STAMP ACT COMES UNGLUED 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Postal Service has announced the 15 stamps
picked by the public to commemorate events, people and phenomena of
the 1960s. Sorry, you will not be licking an LSD stamp.
</P>
<P>
   Neither is there a birth control pill stamp, a stamp for John or
Robert Kennedy, a Motown stamp, a miniskirt stamp, a burning cities
stamp, nor a flammable draft card stamp.
</P>
<P>
   Instead you'll find a Barbie doll stamp, a first Super Bowl
stamp and a Ford Mustang stamp.
</P>
<P>
   It's like putting out a series of 1860s stamps and forgetting
Lincoln and Gettysburg, but including the invention of the
hand-crank eggbeater.
</P>
<P>
   The Postal Service offered 30 people and events of the '60s for
the public to vote on _ a list most certainly concocted by Cliff
the postman on ``Cheers.''
</P>
<P>
   No one else would have thought of including the invention of
televised golf as one of the great events of the '60s. Fortunately,
that one lost.
</P>
<P>
   From the 15 stamps selected for release a year from now (that's
Postal Service time), we can guess most of the 930,000 ballots were
from those who learned about the '60s from Time magazine
retrospectives.
</P>
<P>
   The public did vote for a peace symbol stamp, but that's
something that has made a big comeback. Martin Luther King's ``I
have a dream'' speech is honored on a stamp, but it's something
taught in every classroom today.
</P>
<P>
   The big question is: What's a Barbie doll doing on a '60s stamp?
Barbie was invented in 1959, and spurned in the '60s as a
capitalistic plot to subjugate women to false ideals of feminine
beauty and the millinery-industrial complex.
</P>
<P>
   The '60s stamps are divided into five categories: people and
events, arts and entertainment, sports, science and technology, and
lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the '60s weren't about categories, man.
Politics, music, sex and drugs melted together in one big brain
stew.
</P>
<P>
   So here are the winners.
</P>
<P>
   PEOPLE AND EVENTS: King's speech, the Vietnam War and the Peace
Corps.
</P>
<P>
   That's not too bad, except the Postal Service didn't give the
public the opportunity to vote on John F. Kennedy's assassination,
or any of the other assassinations that made the '60s more than a
toke in the park.
</P>
<P>
   Lyndon Johnson and Richard Nixon didn't get '60s stamps either,
even though their ugly mugs were all over that decade.
</P>
<P>
   At least the Postal Service got the Vietnam War on a stamp. I
just don't know how they get it all on a square inch of paper.
</P>
<P>
   ARTS AND ENTERTAINMENT: The Beatles, Woodstock and ``Star
Trek.''
</P>
<P>
   This is where things really go wrong. Motown lost in the voting
to some Brits, and what's with ``Star Trek''?
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Trek'' began in the '60s, but it didn't take off until
the invention of nerds in the '70s. No one who was really in the
'60s watched television. We went out and saw ``2001, a Space
Odyssey'' a couple of dozen times, and a lot of movies with
subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   Kids today can't believe that kids ever watched movies with
subtitles _ or movies with subtleties, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS: This is where the '60s stamp series starts to come
completely unglued.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Maris breaking Babe Ruth's home run record and the Green
Bay Packers perhaps deserve stamps, but how is it that the first
Super Bowl came in second in overall voting? (After the moon
landing.)
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't even called the Super Bowl, but the AFL-NFL World
Championship Game. It didn't even fill the Los Angeles Coliseum.
It's only famous in retrospect, as the beginning of a horrible
trend in American dietary history.
</P>
<P>
   Get with it, philately fans. The most important sports event of
the '60s, by far, was the invention of the Frisbee.
</P>
<P>
   I can't argue with the '60s science and technology stamps. The
moon landing, the computer chip, lasers _ those are fine. We
weren't paying much attention to any science besides brain
chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   The lifestyle category winners include the Barbie and peace
symbol stamps and a Ford Mustang stamp _ sorry, no VW. You know,
back then we didn't even use the word ``lifestyle,'' a '70s
platform shoe of a word.
</P>
<P>
   Balloting starts for the '70s stamp series on Sept. 1, so start
watching ``Brady Bunch'' reruns to see how the '70s weren't.
</P>
<P>
   It was a decade of amorality and bad mustaches, presidential
malfeasance, recession, oil shortages and great American films, but
you probably won't see stamps for any of those.
</P>
<P>
   You will see a platform shoes stamp, although I never met anyone
wearing them until the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Lord knows what Cliff the postman is dreaming up for us to vote
on as '90s stamps.
</P>
<P>
   The fall of the Soviet Union? If Ronald Reagan really caused it,
as claimed, it should be on an '80s stamp. An Internet stamp? It's
putting the Postal Service out of business.
</P>
<P>
   If Barbie and the first Super Bowl got on '60s stamps, this
decade is really in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Space aliens and Newt Gingrich (maybe on one stamp), cell phones
and beepers, the Teletubbies and the Spice Girls, and the Clinton
women series. Maybe a tattoo and piercing stamp, too.
</P>
<P>
   That's all I can think of, and the only drugs I've been taking
this decade are prescription.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 1229EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
