<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PRINCE AND PRINCESSES OF DYE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DIANA RATHBONE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ One way of ensuring the solvency of Social
Security would be to require at least one gray hair as a
prerequisite for benefits.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take much to realize that aging baby boomers are not
bringing about, as predicted, the graying of America, but rather,
thanks to sky-rocketing sales of hair dye, its fanciful coloring in
rich tones of black, blond, red and lustrous brown. As Jonathan
Swift remarked, ``Every man desires to live long, but no man would
be old.''
</P>
<P>
   I should confess at the outset that my own hair turned
prematurely gray when I was in my early 40s, starting with a big
streak across the bangs which gradually spread salt and pepper all
over my head.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't much fun when a ski lift operator offered me a senior
citizen discount, but at least it looked more striking than the
mousy brown hair that it had replaced. Anyway, there was no cause
for panic, having completed the process early; it could only be a
matter of time before my friends caught up.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, of course, in order to stay looking young for their
middle-aged mates and dates, they all started dyeing their hair.
Gail Sheehy, in her latest book, ``Understanding Men's Passages,''
hardly made news when she claimed that men approaching the
half-century mark are desperate to stave off the sexy young hunks
pursuing them up the generational ladder.
</P>
<P>
   And as one of their favorite tactics is to run off with girls
barely old enough to be their daughters, what else can women do but
try to emulate the appearance of those very same daughters?
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in the recent pictures of Carolina and Carolina Adriana
Herrara, hawking their new perfume, it was impossible to tell
parent from child, despite a 30-year age gap.
</P>
<P>
   Even my cousin, solidly cemented in a rock-solid marriage, told
me that her husband, in an effort to reassure himself of his
continued potency, suddenly made her wear a bunch of sexy nighties
right after his 50th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Lying in bed in her red and black lace, hair dyed, uncomfortable
and freezing cold, she could see how silly it was, but she worried
that if she refused, his young secretary might prove more willing.
</P>
<P>
   Then I found out that men were dyeing their hair, too. This, to
me, was the equivalent of them all suddenly wearing skirts.
</P>
<P>
   Not that I have anything against men wearing skirts (after all,
women wear trousers), but I never dreamed that fear of old age
would force even John Wayne types into such an overtly feminine
activity.
</P>
<P>
   There was something almost daunting about imagining dour war
hero Bob Dole sitting in a beauty salon, his hair covered in pasty
dye, his head under a heating lamp.
</P>
<P>
   And what did the poor man take us for? Did he really believe
that we would all vote for him just because his hair looked black,
even though we all knew he was over 70 and it really wasn't black
at all?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, apparently, is yes. In a recent survey of more than
100 leading image consultants, it was reported, quite seriously,
that men were rated ``less capable'' if they had gray hair.
</P>
<P>
   Even more ridiculous, after the gray-haired subjects had their
natural color restored (courtesy of hair dye, of course) the
``capable'' rating given by the same consultants to these same men
jumped 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If this is true, reality has been held hostage to perception,
and an entire generation will be forced to behave as if they are
middle-aged Peter Pans. In a few more years, everyone in America
(except President Clinton and me, of course) will look exactly the
same age.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes I think all this hair dyeing is a little like a
medieval morality play, where everyone tries to cheat Death,
parading around in painted finery, circling the shrouded figure
that hovers just inside the wings, ready to pounce if he catches a
straying gray hair.
</P>
<P>
   A counterattack seems indicated, something along the lines of a
``middle-aged is beautiful'' movement.
</P>
<P>
   Baby boomers, after all, have traditionally paid lip service to
the sanctity of life's processes; over the years we have refused to
shave beards, arm pits and legs; child birth with no pain killers
was a moral imperative; getting through menopause on nothing more
than Buddhist meditation is currently all the rage.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, with such a history behind us, a few gray hairs could be
seen as an ethical requirement.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diana Rathbone is a business analyst.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 1242EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
