<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 12:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9027 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MO-NIXON-BOS &LR;      07-10 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MO-NIXON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE CANDIDATE IN MISSOURI GETS A WAKE-UP CALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Jeremiah ``Jay'' Nixon has spent the day looking for
money and votes in rural Missouri towns, an Irish pub in this city,
and a suburban union hall. He's everywhere, it seems, but the most
likely destination for a Democratic candidate for the US Senate:
St. Louis's predominantly black north side.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon, Missouri's attorney general and a top Senate prospect for
the Democrats nationally, has so angered black leaders with his
proposal to end state aid for school desegregation that many are
actively working to defeat him. So it's prudent for him to keep his
distance when he can.
</P>
<P>
   The local NAACP has picketed Nixon's public events. Black civic
leaders are raising money for Republican incumbent Senator
Christopher ``Kit'' Bond. And the state's senior black politician,
US Representative William L. Clay Sr., has been trying to drum up
opposition to Nixon. Nixon and Bond are white.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon is expected to win his August primary and then challenge
Bond in a November contest that has become a lightning rod for
exploding black angst within the Democratic Party. Many black
voters say they are frustrated by being taken for granted and upset
that their issues _ from affirmative action to desegregation _ are
being ignored and sometimes even opposed by Democrats, who
typically get 80 to 90 percent of the black vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not unlike the Christian right's disagreement within
the Republican Party: We are saying we are one of the backbones of
your political strength, and you are dealing with us in an
unacceptable way,'' said Dr. Donald Suggs, a St. Louis oral
surgeon, newspaper publisher, and member of a group of black
leaders opposing Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts predict black frustration with the Democratic
Party here and elsewhere could lower voter turnout in the fall
congressional elections and perhaps beyond.
</P>
<P>
   In Maryland, for example, Baltimore's black mayor, Kurt L.
Schmoke, stunned Democratic officials by backing Harford County
Executive Eileen M. Rehrmann in the upcoming primary instead of
Democratic Governor Parris N. Glendening. Schmoke, who helped
deliver predominantly black Baltimore in 1994 to Glendening, says
the governor reneged on a promise to raise funds for public
education.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, black officials, including US Representative Alcee
L. Hastings, worked to defeat the Democratic candidate for speaker
of the House after a black man in line for the nomination was
ousted in favor of a white woman.
</P>
<P>
   But it's here that the complicated relationship between black
voters and white Democratic politicians seems most strained. The
rancor forced President Clinton to delay a visit to a Nixon
fund-raiser last fall until threats by blacks to picket it were
withdrawn. Eight days after the fund-raiser, Nixon asked the US
Supreme Court to end state funding for desegreation programs,
leaving blacks stunned and dismayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the folks in Boston know, when you mix race and politics
and money and schools and courts together, that is not a sanguine
situation,'' Nixon explained.
</P>
<P>
   As attorney general, Nixon has sought to end the court-ordered
busing of 13,000 black children from St. Louis city schools to
predominantly white suburban school districts. He has proposed
instead that the state pay $300 million to renovate schools and
build new ones to settle the city's 26-year-old desegregation case.
</P>
<P>
   Many black families believe Nixon's plan would rob their
children of access to high-quality education.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that we can push a lot of people toward Mr. Bond,
but we've done a fairly good job of pointing out that Nixon is
undeserving of Democratic support, and that I think will cut into
his margin in November,'' Suggs said. ``The Democratic Party has to
be concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond, a moderate Republican who is seeking a third term in the
Senate, is in some ways an unlikely choice for black voters. He has
never received more than token support from blacks in any campaign;
the national NAACP recently gave him a failing grade for his civil
rights record; and he, like Nixon, opposes funding for
desegregation.
</P>
<P>
   But many blacks here give Bond credit for appointing
African-Americans to high-profile jobs and judgeships during his
two terms as governor. They also say he has worked to restore
spending for federal housing programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have worked very hard to build a Republican base in the
African-American community from the time I was governor,'' Bond
said in an interview last week. ``It would change the entire
dynamics if we get a decent vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Mischeaux, president of the St. Louis NAACP, accuses
Nixon of dealing dishonestly with the black leaders and using
desegregation to woo voters in rural Missouri, where Democratic
candidates don't fare as well as Republicans and where residents
oppose the state spending of $1 billion so far on integrating
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would you choose this issue?'' asked Nixon, who recently
won an end to Kansas City's court-ordered busing with state
payments of $320 million over three years to the city schools. ``No
other politician in the state ... spoke as forthrightly and as
directly as I have, and there aren't that many rewards for speaking
your mind in politics, and this is one example of that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 1246EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 12:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9030 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-TANGLEWOOD-2ND &LR;  &UR;      07-10 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TANGLEWOOD-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... TMC faculty).''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ozawa did invite the jazz pianist Marcus Roberts to appear at a
Boston Symphony concert where Roberts's performance was deplorable;
Roberts came back the following season to participate in a short
fund-raising concert with the TMC orchestra that mingled serious
and popular repertory. There's no other evidence that Ozawa is
pursuing a jazz or ``outside influence'' agenda (Keith Jarrett's
appearance in a Mozart concerto, cited by Pincus, was not Ozawa's
idea, but the result of the pianist's longtime professional
assocation with the conductor Dennis Russell Davies, with whom he
had recorded the work in question).
</P>
<P>
   And Ozawa has never said or done anything to suggest that he
wanted the TMC or even the BSO's Shed concerts to be about solo
careers and superstar performers. Certainly the BSO's concerts in
the 5,000-seat shed depend on the stars of the music business, and
the performances of some of them deteriorated over the years. (How
are you going to tell the Tanglewood public that loves Itzhak
Perlman that they shouldn't enjoy him any more?)
</P>
<P>
   For a person in his position, Ozawa himself has always seemed
remarkably free of star-worship. Some of his proteges did become
superstars, like Jessye Norman and Kathleen Battle, but they were
promising young Americans when Ozawa started engaging them; they
remained loyal to him in their glory years, and he remained loyal
to them in their times of trouble. But he has also worked steadily
with musicians he admired who were not on that level of fame, or
even interested in it, like Peter Serkin, Maria Tipo, Benjamin
Luxon, Gidon Kremer and Vinson Cole; he has steered clear of some
dubious celebrities like Nadja Salerno-Sonenberg, and recently not
renewed his acquaintance with Evgeny Kissin or Midori.
</P>
<P>
   The revised TMC curriculum which went into place this summer,
and which Ozawa intends to keep evolving, was not ``devised in
large part by (the new director of the school, Ellen) Highstein,''
as Pincus says. It represented Highstein's organization,
consolidation and implementation of suggestions made during
meetings with Ozawa, last summer's faculty, students, and such
interested parties as Andre Previn, Bernard Haitink, John Williams,
members of the Juilliard Quartet, and others. Paradoxically there
does not seem to be anything in this summer's program that Kalish
and Fleisher could object to, at least on artistic grounds.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Pincus's new book is a sequel to his earlier book,
``Scenes from Tanglewood'' (1989), a distillation of his first
dozen years of reporting. Pincus is more ambitious and inevitably
less successful this time out because this is not just a book about
Tanglewood. He uses Tanglewood as a lens through which to examine
the issues facing America's entire musical culture.
</P>
<P>
   His eye and his ear remain as acute as ever, and his accounts of
such episodes as the planning, construction, and opening of Seiji
Ozawa Hall; the final residencies and last concert of Leonard
Bernstein; the 50th anniversary revival of Benjamin Britten's
``Peter Grimes'' are accurate, thoughtful and interesting. They
will prove informative even to people who were there. There are
lively portraits of, tributes to, and conversations with, such
diverse Tanglewood figures as Bernard Haitink, John Williams, Louis
Krasner, Lukas Foss, John Harbison, Alfred Brendel, and Keith
Lockhart. One need not agree with Pincus's conclusion about Ozawa
(``Ozawa seems to have overstayed his time; neither he nor the
orchestra is growing'') in order to recognize that he has provided
a complex characterization of a complex figure, which benefits from
the writer's travels to Japan to observe the conductor at work in
his own country.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably Pincus's intimate knowledge of Tanglewood overmatches
his knowledge of what is happening elsewhere. The book crucially
lacks a sense of context. It is odd to find American musical life
discussed only as it has been controversially codified in such
documents as the American Symphony Orchestra League's 1993 report
on ``Americanizing the American Orchestra'' (a study whose title
the book repeatedly gets wrong). Creeping commercialism at
Tanglewood, one of Pincus's major themes, needs to be discussed in
the context of what has been happening at such other summer
festivals as the Chicago Symphony's Ravinia, the Los Angeles
Philharmonic's Hollywood Bowl, and the Cleveland Orchestra's
Blossom, all of which have made different, and far more
commercially opportunistic, responses to the same pressures
Tanglewood faces.
</P>
<P>
   The book has been less meticulously edited than its predecessor.
The individual chapters seem to have been written for independent
publication, so there is a lot of repetition that becomes
irritating to someone who is reading all the way through. There is
also a light dusting of uncharacteristic error. Mezzos Frederica
von Stade and Mitsuko Shirai have been squeezed up into sopranos;
the conductor James DePreist's name is misspelled; Isaiah Jackson
did not conduct ``Gospel Night'' ``sometimes,'' but once, and
Charles Floyd went on to shape it into a beloved new tradition in
five subsequent seasons. ``Gospel Night'' is not the only BSO
activity tailored to ethnic or minority groups. Arthur Fiedler did
Irish, Italian, Celtic, Hispanic and Armenian nights beyond
counting (as well as ``Negro Nights''), and such programming
continued through John Williams' era into Keith Lockhart's Pops
today.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever personal interpretation he puts on events, whatever
reasoning and motives he imputes to people who have not stated
them, Pincus has certainly identified some of the principal issues
and dangers that face Tanglewood and, by extension, all of serious
cultural life in this country today. But he may have produced this
particular book prematurely: The restructuring and re-animation of
the TMC is one of the most ambitious and important projects of
Ozawa's career, and the time to evaluate it is not before it is
under &UR;  &LR; way, but after it has produced some results. Instead of
beginning in medias res, Pincus ends there. On the other hand, if
you're talking about Tanglewood, that may be only fitting;
Koussevitzky intended the place to be in medias res all the time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 1248EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
