<SLUG> BC-LEGAL-GUIDE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKLET GIVES CLIENTS TIPS ON DEALING WITH LAWYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Website is CQ)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CAHER  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In 16 years of administering a fund that
compensates victims of crooked lawyers, Fred Miller has seen enough
disgruntled law clients to write a book. So he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Avoiding Grief With a Lawyer: A Practical Guide,'' however, is
anything but a lawyer-bashing tome.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the consumer booklet published by the New York Lawyers'
Fund for Client Protection _ and freely available for the asking _
outlines the responsibilities of both attorneys and clients, with
the aim of diverting conflicts before they arise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most legal consumers will never need the Lawyers' Fund for
Client Protection, but there is a general consumer need for
education,'' Miller said. ``With every loss we prevent, it is less
money that we have to pay out, and more money we have available for
deserving clients.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lawyers' Fund is an unusual entity that uses attorney
registration funds to compensate people who are ripped off by their
counselor. Since the fund was established by the Legislature in
1981, the trustees have restored $70 million to clients of thieving
lawyers. In recent years, the fund has adopted a new approach in an
effort to not only resolve problems, but prevent them.
</P>
<P>
   Although only a tiny percentage of lawyers are ever accused _
let alone convicted _ of cheating clients, Miller urges a
buyer-beware attitude. He said consumers should scrutinize lawyers
the same way they do other people they hire to perform various
tasks. Miller said it is appropriate for a client to ask an
attorney where he or she went to law school and whether she or he
carries malpractice insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the power relationship, the consumer is afraid to
ask the lawyer questions,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   The booklet, written by Miller and illustrated by artist George
Thompson of New York City, can be viewed online at
www.nylawfund.org. It is also available from the Lawyers' Fund, and
Attorney General Dennis C. Vacco has ordered 10,000 copies to
distribute.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some tips from the booklet:
</P>
<P>
   _ A law client can fire a lawyer at any time for any reason and
is entitled to his or her file. However, the lawyer is entitled to
be paid for any work that was done, even if the job was not
completed.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lawyers are not allowed to charge ``unreasonable'' fees. In
divorce and other domestic relations cases, clients can use binding
arbitration to resolve disputes. Clients in other types of legal
matters may have to litigate fee disputes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Attorneys can be discilpined for neglecting client matters,
malpractice, fraud, misuse of funds and other transgressions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 1249EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
