<SLUG> BC-DISCOVERING-SPECIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LITTLE THINGS ADD UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH DALEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ant man was there, discovering two new six-legged species on
the forest floor. The lichen lady was there, too, surrounded by
green, flaky growth.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, two mussel men peered into glass-bottomed buckets
searching for pearly mollusks, while the grass guy plucked up long,
slender blades.
</P>
<P>
   By a 10 p.m deadline Saturday (July 4), they were well on their
way toward entry in the Guinness Book of World Records for
identifying the largest number of species in one day, with a
tentative count of 1,620.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, however, the marathon was held to spark a love of nature
and to help create annual species hunts and community nature clubs
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a marvelous thing; I hope it catches on,'' said Edward
O. Wilson, a naturalist, Harvard professor, and Pulitzer Prize
winner who is known as ``the ant man'' for his study of the
insects.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson and a fellow Harvard ant specialist, Stefan Cover,
discovered two ant species. ``And that ought to tell you something
about how little we know about things,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   But what the experts found in Concord and Lincoln will now be
widely known and available _ compiled for the first time in a
master bug, plant, animal, fungus, fish, and bird list.
</P>
<P>
   They used almost every tool imaginable to spot the species:
vials filled with formaldehyde, night-vision goggles, chest waders,
and binoculars. Friday night, small groups strung bedsheets between
trees in backyards. Bright mercury vapor lights illuminated the
cloth, and moments later, the expected guests arrived: moths.
</P>
<P>
   Amateur moth man John Himmelman's favorite so far? ``The
olive-shaded bird dropping moth,'' he said. The moth mimics the
look of droppings _ ``really beautiful'' ones, he said _ so it
doesn't get eaten.
</P>
<P>
   Himmelman only had to gaze onto a sheet to find his object of
fascination, but some specialists like Northeastern University
professor and biologist Gwilym Jones had to stay out all night to
find his prey: animals. The best sightings were a mink and an
ermine, although the latter was road kill.
</P>
<P>
   July Fourth was chosen for the census because it is the day
Henry David Thoreau chose to move into his cabin at Walden Woods,
the setting for his famous book ``Walden.'' It is also Biodiversity
Day. Concord and Lincoln were chosen because of Walden and because
the area has some of the oldest records of plant and animal
sightings, said naturalist Peter Alden, a census organizer.
</P>
<P>
   The idea wasn't simply to discover species but to catalog and
highlight the many species that have always existed in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``People go to the Serengeti to see all types of things, but we
don't look right where we are. The ultimate goal in doing something
crazy like this is to have nature clubs in schools like the
debating club or football team ... to have community nature
clubs,'' Alden said.
</P>
<P>
   For some, like bird watchers, finding species was as easy as
looking up. For others, like fish experts, it involved quite a bit
of diving.
</P>
<P>
   All herpetologist Tom Tyning had to do was walk along the
causeway at Great Meadows National Wildlife Refuge to find snakes,
turtles, salamanders, and frogs. His two best finds were a musk
turtle, a tiny 4-inch turtle that normally stays underwater, and an
emerald green leopard frog, so named for its black spots with
yellowish-orange halos.
</P>
<P>
   Mussel experts Brian Reid and Henry Barbour waded into water and
put their heads into glass-bottomed buckets. Their work paid off:
They found an eastern pond mussel, listed as a species of special
concern in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today is not a kindergarten nature walk. Most of these people
are experts,'' Alden said. ``But we want to get people interested
in what is around them ... There is so much.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 1250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 12:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9039 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV12     07-10 1451
