<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV12-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOND FUNDS REQUIRE SCRUTINY BEFORE JUMPING IN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 12 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 35 years old, and I have $55,000 in stock mutual funds
with Vanguard, Janus, and Legg Mason (of which $17,000 is an IRA
account), $10,000 in U.S. Savings Bonds, $6,000 in an annuity, and
$10,000 in cash. I also have a $32,000 IRA invested in a CD which
matures soon. I'd like to invest the CD money somewhere with good
returns but relatively low market risk. A friend suggested a bond
fund. What do you think of this advice? Any ideas about a good bond
fund?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  A.F., Braintree, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, there are a lot of good bond funds out there, but I
won't tell you any names until I deliver a little lecture about
time and risk. At age 35, you will probably have this money working
for you for between 20 and 30 years. That's a long time. It's
certainly true that if you put your money in a good bond fund for
about 25 years, you will see a few bumpy seasons, but the general
trend will be relatively smooth. In my computer I have a program
tracking our investments, and an 18-month chart showing net asset
value (but not total returns) for one of our funds, Vanguard GNMA,
is nearly as flat as a table. The same is true if you look at the
longer records in the Morningstar Mutual Funds pages -- the net
asset value was $10.05 at the end of 1986; it's $10.44 as this is
written. Its 10-year record shows 9.26 percent average annual total
returns. If such a pace were sustained for 25 years, that would
turn your $32,000 into $294,890.
</P>
<P>
   But it's also true that when you're talking about two or three
decades, the odds are almost overwhelming that stock funds will
outpace bond funds. If you were to select a stock fund instead, and
if you achieved just one percentage point better returns than we
cited for the GNMA fund, the difference in returns over 25 years
would be $75,409. I suspect you're about as spooked with the
current market as I am, so I suggest a cowardly approach. Begin my
moving $31,000 of your IRA to Vanguard Prime Money Market fund,
putting the final $1,000 in Vanguard Index Value fund. Then
instruct Vanguard to move $925 from the money market to Index Value
every month. This will spread your investment period out over about
36 months (presuming average 5 percent returns from the money
fund). This is an investment discipline called dollar cost
averaging. If the market takes a substantial dip during the
investment period, you will be buying subsequent shares at lower
prices, reducing your average cost per share.
</P>
<P>
   Okay, suppose you're still hell-bent for bonds. My suggestion
then is this: build a portfolio of three bond funds, running most
of the risk spectrum. You might, for example, put a third each into
Vanguard Short-Term Bond, Vanguard GNMA, and Vanguard High- Yield
Corporate Bond funds. From this, you might expect a portfolio
average yield of about 7.1 percent, nbased on current levels. But I
still think you'd be better off adding that IRA account to your
list of stock funds.
</P>
<P>
   Since we're talking about Vanguard, here's an incidental note
for H.S. of East Falmouth: You can reach Vanguard by calling
800-662-6273.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Shortly I expect to receive $400,000 from the sale of my
home. From this amount, I must be able to pay for my rental
obligation. I'll need returns of 6 percent to 7 percent --
preferably 7 percent. My other living expenses are covered by
Social Security and CDs. What do you suggest?
</P>
<P>
   H.S., Newton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, you might consider the bond portfolio I suggested for
A.F. in the question above, which would generate a 7.1 percent
yield at current rates.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem with that is that the most aggressive leg of
that portfolio -- the Vanguard High-Yield Corporate Bond fund -- is
a member of the fund class that's usually called ``junk bonds.''
You'll have to decide whether you are comfortable with the risks
these bring. Junk bond funds typically invest in portfolios of
bonds graded BBB, BB, B and lower. Because of their relatively low
credit quality, these funds can experience two kinds of volatility
-- the interest-rate volatility that affects all bond funds, and
credit volatility. The latter situation makes these funds subject
to market pressure when the economy weakens and investors worry
that some of these lower-rated companies might not be able to meet
their obligations.
</P>
<P>
   The good news, though, is that Vanguard's junk bond fund is a
very conservative entrant relative to its peers. According to
Morningstar Mutual Funds' last report, it held 5 percent of assets
in AAA-rated issues, 38 percent in BB-rated bonds, and the
remaining 57 percent in B-rated holdings. The average effective
maturity of the portfolio is 8.2 years, and the current yield is
8.4 percent. Morningstar reports a 10.25 percent average annual
total return over the last 10 years, and accords the fund a top,
five-star rating. (For the record, I own shares in this fund.) If
this makes you uncomfortable, you might decide to divide the
portfolio evenly between Vanguard Short-Term Bond and Vanguard
GNMA, a move which would bring the current portfolio yield to 6.5
percent, but which should give you a lower level of volatility.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, because bond markets can be quite volatile, it's always
nice to withdraw a little less than the total yield if you can
afford it. For example, if you were to invest in the portfolio that
includes the junk bond fund, but to take distributions that
represent only 6.5 percent of your initial investment, the effect
would be that you would be reinvesting a little money each month --
probably enough to insulate your principal from market shocks over
the long haul, and eventually even to allow a little growth in
principal. If you were to follow such a course, withdrawing
$2,166.66 a month, and if rates held steady, you might expect that
over the course of a decade (which would of course see market bumps
of various proportions) your principal might have grown to
$421,659.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have been out of college for about three years, and after
much soul-searching I've decided to enter the Peace Corps. After
paying all my debts, I have $7,500 in savings. My commitment will
be for 27 months service in a foreign country. Where would the best
place be to invest my savings over that period, providing little
risk and the ability to take out the money once I return?
</P>
<P>
   G.M., Stoneham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, if you are indeed looking for little risk, the menu of
options is pretty limited and boring. You might, for example, shop
around for the best two-year CD rate and then instruct the bank
that the funds should be automatically moved into a 90-day CD at
the prevailing rate when it matures. Thus your money would be
available to you precisely after 27 months, and you would know at
the outset what your earnings will be for the lion's share of the
time. Suppose you get 5.5 percent on the initial CD and that the
rate falls to 5 percent after the first 24 months; the result would
be that you'd have $8,570 upon your return.
</P>
<P>
   An alternative would be a fund money market fund from a mutual
fund company. Such funds provide an only minuscule level of risk
(but, unlike CDs, they are not insured by the government) and the
interest rate varies daily. As a general rule, if interest rates
tend to rise during those 27 months, you would be best off with a
money market fund; if rates tend to fall during the period, you'd
be best off if you locked in your interest rate through a CD.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to be more venturesome, you might look at
conservative bond funds. For example, just looking at offerings
within the Fidelity family, the 30-day yield on June 30 for
Fidelity Cash Reserves -- its largest money market fund -- was 5.25
percent. If you went with Fidelity Short-Term Bond, the yield would
step up to only 5.56 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Imagining that such returns were constant over 27 months, that
would translate to a difference of only $52 in total returns for
the period -- not, in my opinion, enough to warrant changing from
the ultra-low risk money fund to the riskier short-term fund. In
fact, the only bond funds that seem to me to offer a significant
difference in total returns, given the relatively short period of
time involved, would be the junk bond funds. But these cannot truly
be considered offerings with ``little risk,'' so they probably
don't fit the bill.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
