<HEADER>
A9040 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RADIO-SHACK-BOS &LR;      07-10 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADIO-SHACK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RADIO SHACK'S ELECTRONIC BUFFET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEABODY, Mass. _ In 1921, a young immigrant named Theodore
Deutschmann opened a downtown Boston store that sold leftover Army
gear to ham radio operators; he called his store RadioShack.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-seven years later _ and 35 years after a Texas
entrepreneur named Charles Tandy essentially bought it in 1963 _
RadioShack opened its 5,000th company-owned store here in the
Northshore Mall Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Franchisees own another nearly 2,000 stores. As a result,
RadioShack and its corporate parent, Fort Worth-based Tandy Corp.,
can claim they operate more stores than virtually any other
retailer, with the possible exception of McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   As Tandy president Leonard H. Roberts likes to say,
``Ninety-four percent of all Americans live or work within five
minutes of a RadioShack.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Few chains can claim greater longevity. Five-and-dime stores
have given way to Wal-Mart and Kmart. Mom-and-pop stores have been
decimated by category-killers in big-box superstores that focus on
one category of merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Yet RadioShack continues to thrive by selling many things in
small stores not much larger than fast-food restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Everybody knows that McDonald's is famous for hamburgers, but
if RadioShack were in the food business, it would be a dim sum
restaurant, a giant buffet line of accessories for the electronics
age.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of one dominant product line, it offers a little bit of
everything for customers whose houses are crammed with phones,
electric garage openers, boom boxes, timers to turn the lights on,
personal computers, and VCRs.
</P>
<P>
   Huge assortments are a holdover from the old days. In his first
store, founder Deutschmann sold vacuum tubes for radios _ and pots
and pans if he could get a good deal on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sold the first police radio scanner,'' said Jerry Colella,
who began a 30-year career with RadioShack in 1958. ``The
Patrolman, it was called. It sold for $19.95.''
</P>
<P>
   Deutschmann was shrewd when it came to knowing what ham
operators wanted. What he didn't understand was credit. When he
began offering customers credit in the 1960s, the chain, now nine
stores, ran into trouble, allowing Charles Tandy to essentially buy
it for the bargain-basement price of $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   Tandy's family was in the leather business, selling laces and
heels first to cobblers, and later expanding into wallet-and
belt-making kits as leisure time exploded after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   In Tandy's view, tinkering with TVs and hi-fis was a hobby for
the future, and he rapidly expanded RadioShack.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the chain's best customers are do-it-yourselfers, but
president Roberts, who will assume the title of chief executive
Jan. 1, sees a new breed of customer, people who are a &UR;  &LR; little
intimidated by technology and who are asking, ``Do it for me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These people want to be connected to technology, but they're
confused and they want help,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's where RadioShack comes in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our job to demystify technology for the masses,'' said
Roberts, who five years ago came up with the RadioShack slogan:
``You've got questions. We've got answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts' background isn't in surge protectors or batteries; it's
in roast beef sandwiches. He previously held the top jobs at
Shoney's Inc. and Arby's Inc., both fast-food restaurant chains.
</P>
<P>
   That experience was perfect training for RadioShack, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both restaurants and RadioShack are all about providing service
to customers, says Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   Small in square footage, RadioShack has consistently done well.
But Tandy ran into difficulties when it experimented with larger
formats that depended on low-margin, big-ticket items.
</P>
<P>
   Its Computer City stores, which it just sold to CompUSA Inc.,
are 25,000 square feet; its Incredible Universe stores, which it
exited from a few years ago, were nearly 200,000 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts by Roberts to refocus Tandy on RadioShack are reflected
in company numbers. In fiscal 1996, Tandy lost about $92 million on
sales of $6.3 billion. In 1997, Tandy reported a profit of $187
million on sales of about $5.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, RadioShack has had success with store-within-a-store
concepts. It offers products from Sprint Corp. in such a setting,
and telephone-related products account for nearly 30 percent of
revenues. It also has a special section for products made by Compaq
Computer Corp.
</P>
<P>
   These alliances strengthen RadioShack and give it more leverage
with its vendors, said George F. Sutton, an analyst with Dain
Rauscher Wessels in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``What RadioShack can say to a Compaq or a Sprint is, `We have
nearly 100 percent penetration (with our stores) in the United
States; if you want to reach a broad section of Americans, use us,
but we need something from you in return,''' said Sutton, who
thinks RadioShack can sustain monthly sales increases at its older
stores in the 5 to 8 percent range.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday RadioShack formally unveiled another
``store-within-a-store,'' this one called the PowerZone, which is
devoted to batteries, surge protectors, and similar accessories.
</P>
<P>
   An ad campaign will break soon starring James Doohan, the actor
who played Scotty in the original Star Trek series.
</P>
<P>
   Scotty, who powered up the Enterprise, will be joined in the ads
by power-hungry historical characters such as Cleopatra and
Napoleon. The ad's message: RadioShack can satisfy the power needs
of even the toughest of customers.
</P>
<P>
   Batteries, telephone cables, wires for the satellite TV dish _
all these little things are adding up in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're bread-and-butter business is really strong,'' said
analyst Lynn Detrick of Sanders Morris Mundy Inc. in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Because RadioShack sells so many things _ most stores carry
about 3,700 items, including 50 different batteries, it has no
direct competitors, Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Roberts thinks RadioShack's future is bright.
With the rapid changes in technology, people will need RadioShack
more than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to tell us, `We love technology, we can
afford technology, but please just come in to my house and tell us
what button to push,''' Roberts said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
