<HEADER>
A9041 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VT-GETTYSBURG-BOS &LR;      07-10 1439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VT-GETTYSBURG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR VERMONT, A NEW RECOGNITION OF ITS GETTYSBURG ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDITH GAINES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Nearly inconsolable'' after the failure of Union campaigns in
the spring of 1862, President Abraham Lincoln called for 300,000
more men to serve nine months in the Union army. Nearly 5,000
Vermonters answered the call.
</P>
<P>
   Green soldiers from Vermont's Green Hills, they would play a
pivotal role in the most storied battle of the war: the epic July
1-3, 1863, conflict at Gettysburg. After the battle, a New York
Times account concluded that a Vermont brigade ``did more than any
other body of men to gain the triumph which decided the fate of the
Union.''
</P>
<P>
   But somehow over time, the Vermonters' story got lost. Books,
films, even tour guides at the Gettysburg battlefield scarcely
mentioned their contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Now research by historian Howard Coffin of Montpelier is
re-awakening appreciation for the accomplishments of Vermont
soldiers led by Brigadier General G.J. Stannard. Coffin's
interpretation gets official sanction this weekend, when history
buffs, descendants of Civil War veterans, battlefield enthusiasts,
and others converge on Gettysburg to reenact the momentous battle
and Vermont's role in it.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 reenactments have been held since the 1920s at
Gettysburg. But this one, on the 135th anniversary of the battle,
is the largest ever, with 20,000 reenactors and more than 35,000
spectators expected daily. The 1863 battle involved 160,000 men
from both sides, with more than 50,000 dead and wounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first time that Stannard's part in the battle has
been recreated,'' said Steve Wakefield, one of the leaders of the
reenactment. He was referring to a wheeling maneuver by Stannard's
men that helped break the Confederate onslaught up Cemetery Ridge
known as Pickett's Charge.
</P>
<P>
   No one ever doubted that soldiers from Vermont fought at
Gettysburg. But exactly what they did, and how important it was, is
not well-known, Wakefield and others said.
</P>
<P>
   The 20th Maine regiment _ led by Colonel Joshua Chamberlain _ is
the New England unit perhaps most associated with the battle of
Gettysburg. But that hardy unit held the far left of the Union line
at a place called Little Round Top on the battle's second day _
rather than on the third day, when the Vermont brigade played its
role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been on battlefield tours at Gettysburg and never heard
the word `Vermont,''' said Brad Limoge, another reenactor and
amateur Civil War historian from Morrisville, Vt. ``Until Coffin's
book came out, I don't think anyone understood how Pickett's Charge
actually worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Mainers may still say their ancestors saved the Union Army. But
historians including James M. McPherson and D. Scott Hartwig have
praised Coffin's ``Nine Months to Gettysburg.'' He draws on old
diagrams of military maneuvers, eyewitness accounts in letters the
soldiers wrote home, and other reports to show conclusively, he
claims, that Vermonters played a decisive role.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_____ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 5,000 men who joined the Vermont Brigade in 1862 were a
well-educated bunch, many with political ambitions, most in their
early 20s, Coffin says.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran soldiers, who typically enlisted for two or three years,
derided the Vermonters as opportunists, ``nine-month boys'' trying
to get through their service as safely as possible. But other
Yankees supported them enthusiastically.
</P>
<P>
   Remembering the unit in October, just after it had formed,
private Ralph Sturtevant wrote: ``Our camp was thronged with
visitors from all parts of (Vermont) of high and low degree,
beautiful women and red-cheeked girls and their anxious faces ...
there to make farewell visit and say good-bye.''
</P>
<P>
   Clothing never was large enough or long enough for the Green
Mountain boys. Supplies were inadequate. ``The tents are so short
that those who sleep in them get wet either at one end or the
other,'' Lieutenant Colonel Roswell Farnham wrote home.
</P>
<P>
   When the men reached Gettysburg near the end of their term, they
had hardly fought at all, but disease and the privations of camp
life _ rain and chill or heat exhaustion, crowded conditions,
inconsistent food _ had taken a fierce toll, reducing their ranks
to about 2,500.
</P>
<P>
   The two armies collided just north of Gettysburg on July 1.
Union troops fled through the town but managed to hold onto the
high ground along Cemetery Ridge as darkness fell. Fighting resumed
and intensified on July 2 as the Vermonters helped plug a hole in
the Union line, recaptured four cannons, and took about 80
Confederate prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   The decisive moment, Coffin claims, came on July 3.
</P>
<P>
   On that day the Union line resembled a giant fish hook,
stretching three miles from Culp's Hill, along to Cemetery Ridge
south to the Round Tops; Confederate soldiers were massed to the
east along Seminary Ridge. Previously, Confederate General Robert
E. Lee had attacked both ends of the Union line; on July 3, he
decided to attack the middle.
</P>
<P>
   His main target was the portion of the Union line near a clump
of trees on Cemetery Ridge. Just to one side, crouching in a
ravine, the Vermonters in three regiments formed the most advanced
part of the line.
</P>
<P>
   About 3 p.m., after an earth-shaking, two-hour artillery duel,
an estimated 10,000 to 15,000 Confederates started across the mile
of farmland toward the Union line.
</P>
<P>
   Lieutenant Frank Haskell, from Tunbridge, Vt., described the
scene as the enemy advanced: ``Every eye could see his legions, an
overwhelmingly resistless tide of an ocean of armed men sweeping
upon us! Regiment after regiment ... the red flags wave, their
horsemen gallop up and down; the arms of (15,000) men gleam in the
sun, a sloping forest of flashing steel.''
</P>
<P>
   As the massed Confederates neared the portion of the Union line
where soliders in blue crouched behind a stone wall near the copse
of trees, the Vermonters rose up to fire. The Confederates veered
to one side, exposing their right flank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stannard saw the military opportunity of the century,'' Coffin
said in an interview. ``If he could move the men around 90 degrees,
he could fire into the side of the Confederate forces as they moved
forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like a great door, the Vermonters swung out wide and began
firing,'' Coffin continued. ``Every time they fired, they moved
closer, getting off 8,000 to 10,000 bullets in about 20 minutes.
One soldier said the sound was like `a vast mournful roar.'''
</P>
<P>
   Lieutenant George Benedict, in his report of the conflict,
recalled: ``Shells whizzed and popped and fluttered on every side;
spherical case shot exploded overhead, and rained showers of iron
bullets; solid shot tore the ground into furrows.''
</P>
<P>
   When the fighting was over, the high water mark of the
Confederacy had been reached, and the battle of Gettysburg had been
won for the Union. The Vermonters had lost 270 men killed, wounded,
and missing, Coffin writes.
</P>
<P>
   Sturtevant, surveying the area where General George Pickett's
charge had been broken, observed: ``If there was any spot on that
great field of battle that approximated more nearly than any other
the maelstrom of destruction, this was the place. They lay one upon
the other clutched in death, side by side. ... Some had on (Union)
blue, but nearly all wore the (Confederate) gray, and for on a few
square rods one could hardly step so thickly lay the dead.''
</P>
<P>
   On a rainy July 4, the Vermonters helped with the formidable
task of burial. Corporal Mark Day, from Essex, Vt., remembered:
``In the pouring rain, band after band of regimental musicians
gathered, the dead of both armies on every hand (as bands played)
the national airs and hymns, until a great volume of music and
thanksgiving rose from the field.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_____ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Civil war buffs who gather at Gettysburg this weekend will try
to recreate what the battle was like _ while substituting blanks
for ammunition. They will sleep in blankets on the ground, wadding
up jackets for pillows; eat from tin plates; fire antique weapons,
or reproductions of them; wear heavy wool uniforms made to Army
specifications of the 1860s _ including the long underwear that
kept the scratchy wool off their skins.
</P>
<P>
   But no reenactment can do the battle justice, Coffin says. ``One
man wrote about seeing a soldier shot near the clump of trees. His
lower jaw was torn away, his tongue was flapping in the breeze, he
was struggling just to breathe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There were hundreds of stories like that,'' Coffin went on.
``It was carnage, and we'll never really understand it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 1255EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9043 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-PARK-SYSTEM-2TAKES     07-10 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-PARK-SYSTEM-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDERFUNDED GEMS, MASSACHUSETTS PARKS SHOWING THE STRAIN 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Starting when she was just three weeks old in 1963, Maynard,
Mass. native Diane Lockhart's parents would pile her in the station
wagon with her five older brothers and sisters to head out Route 2
and spend ``all summer, every summer,'' at Otter River State Forest
in Baldwinville.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks on end, they would live in a surplus Army tent or a
pop-up camper, splashing in the pond and finding secret places in
the woods. ``That was all my family could afford to do, but we
loved it up there. It was so beautiful,'' Lockhart recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Today, she and her husband have a vacation home in Maine. But a
June weekend found them back at Otter River with their teenage
children trying to relive ``those wonderful family times,'' singing
songs, playing cards, and cooking pancakes on the campfire.
</P>
<P>
   Not many residents know it, but Massachusetts has the 10 biggest
state parks systems in the nation. Besides preserving some
remarkable physical wonders, many of the sites inspire loyalty from
families unable to afford a vacation home.
</P>
<P>
   But while the run-up to the park system's 100th birthday this
summer has brought substantial improvements, a broad range of park
visitors, advocates, and state officials agree it has barely
reached adolescence in living up to its potential.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular properties _ Walden Pond, Nickerson State Park
in Brewster on Cape Cod, and beaches in Salisbury and Westport _
attract hundreds of thousands of visitors every year. At parks like
Otter River, campsite reservations are snapped up months in advance
by families that feel a sense of ownership of their spot.
</P>
<P>
   But advocates fear that Massachusetts forests, parks, and
reservations _ which attract 18 million visitors a year _ are being
``loved to death,'' their trails rutted by mountain bikes and camp
sites denuded and worn to hardpan.
</P>
<P>
   Across the Department of Environmental Management system, many
state officials, park visitors, and environmental advocates see a
potentially first-class resource that sometimes falls far short of
what it could be.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a general competence, an acceptability of the state
forests, but what is so often lacking is a realization of a
creative vision,'' said Theodore Ames, a Berkshire County
environmentalist who heads DEM's oversight board. ``A lot of the
parks just seem tired.''
</P>
<P>
   State Senator Robert A. Durand, a Marlborough Democrat and an
avid outdoorsman who heads the legislative committee that oversees
the parks, agrees: ``There's no question that our state park system
has paled in the past in comparison with our neighbors to the
north. With a little more effort, we could really have first-class
parks.''
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of the $75 million DEM has invested in rebuilding the
parks system since 1991 can clearly be seen after a 20-year period
of neglect. During that time, park money was diverted first into
pools and skating rinks, then into Heritage Parks by Governor
Michael S. Dukakis in such urban settings as Lowell, Fall River,
and North Adams, with mixed success.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to major work on trails and visitor centers at
prized properties like Salisbury Beach, Walden Pond, and Purgatory
Chasm in Sutton, dozens of parks have received attractive
pine-ceiling restrooms to replace pungent pit toilets. General
sprucing-up was obvious at more than 40 sites the Globe visited.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got our wish _ they've got the nicest flushies over
there,'' said Frank Dowen, a Concord hairdresser who has been
bringing his family and grandchildren to Otter River for decades.
``It's a big improvement over six years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Wheelchair-accessible trails, beaches, and fishing facilities
are being added at a steady rate. Agency officials have also begun
installing about 16 cozy permanent tents called ``yurts,'' each
with beds, tables, and small decks. They will rent for $25 a night
at Nickerson State Park and several Berkshires parks, offering
winter camping for skiiers and hunters.
</P>
<P>
   Staff and funding increases made since the meat-cleaver cutbacks
of 1989-'91 have resulted in the reopening of dozens of parks and
beaches, including the pond at Harold Parker State Forest in North
Andover. Virtually all campgrounds again have a 24-hour,
seven-day-a-week official presence.
</P>
<P>
   But DEM has at least a $100 million backlog of maintenance work.
And parks advocates see all sorts of unmet opportunities to
constructively exploit some beautiful properties.
</P>
<P>
   Demand would clearly justify adding thousands of campsites to
the 3,500 already scattered around the state, widening dozens of
fresh-water beaches for peak weekends, and beefing up
interpretation of historic sites and natural wonders.
</P>
<P>
   In many areas, camping could be moved to more inviting spots: At
the state's biggest park, 16,200-acre October Mountain State Forest
in Lee, the 50-site campground sits not on one of the many
Berkshire overlooks but next to a humming electric transformer yard
and a former dump.
</P>
<P>
   Some natural resources seem clumsily handled, like Natural
Bridge State Forest in North Adams, where rusting chain-link-
fenced walkways sprawl over a marble chasm waterfall. Or Bash Bish
Falls in Mount Washington, where no-swimming warnings have been
sloppily spray-painted on the rocks.
</P>
<P>
   The entire system has only a dozen cabins for rent at two parks.
``They should build a whole lot more of these _ they're
wonderful,'' said Monroe Bethea, a state Department of Mental
Retardation worker visiting a new log cabin at Savoy Mountain State
Forest last month with clients for a fishing trip.
</P>
<P>
   Despite promises by former Governor William F. Weld and Acting
Governor Paul Cellucci to make state government ``think
entrepreneurially,'' DEM officials are moving only haltingly toward
bringing in new partners and promoting many of its holdings.
</P>
<P>
   DEM has done nothing to take advantage of a ``Second Century''
fund legislators approved two years ago reserving park-revenue
increases for DEM use, and barely tapped an eight-year-old
conservation trust made up of private donations.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 1256EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 12:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9044 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-STATE-PARKS-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     07-10 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-STATE-PARKS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... private donations.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eight years after its creation, the trust fund contains $920,000
that has mostly been stockpiled as an endowment. Last year, in its
first effort soliciting donations at the parks, DEM collected
$14,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been spending money for publicity, by any means,''
said Kelly Sinclair, director of the conservation trust.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has Cellucci's administration implemented recommendations
from a 1997 study completed at a cost of $225,000 that said
Massachusetts could have a parks system ``second to none'' simply
by better budget management.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts lags many states in forging partnerships between
both private ventures and resorts and environmentally-minded
nonprofit groups. One exception: Its association with the
Appalachian Mountain Club, which runs a popular and well-equipped
visitors center at Mount Greylock in Lanesborough.
</P>
<P>
   State Representative Steven Kulik, a Worthington Democrat, said
the state also should encourage more responsible logging, which
would generate revenue and improve the health of forests where
``good lumber is rotting in the woods.''
</P>
<P>
   DEM Commissioner Peter C. Webber, a former five-term Republican
state senator from Pittsfield, said it has been hard enough just to
dig out from decades of underfunding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to get to a place where I could be a little more
proactive'' about establishing more and stronger partnerships to
enhance park operations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The experience of Howard Fife, the manager for 20 years of Wells
State Park in Sturbridge and Brimfield State Forest, is typical of
DEM's successes and failures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little things are improving,'' Fife said, citing new restrooms
at Brimfield and $70,000 in buildings and grounds renovations at
Wells. But both parks badly need and could easily accommodate more
campsites and trails.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of potential out there... (but) we don't know
what we've got, we don't know where we're going, and we don't know
what we need,'' said Fife.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews suggest several obstacles to creating the ``second to
none'' parks system DEM officials want:
</P>
<P>
   _Geography: Most state parks are located west and north of
Worcester, but the majority of Bay State residents live within
Interstate 495 and tend to head two hours north or south to New
Hampshire, Maine, or Cape Cod instead of two hours west to a state
park.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't do a very good job of advertising within our own
state what we have,'' said Senator Durand. At least half of the
visitors to some parks are from Connecticut, New York, or New
Jersey _ not voters who can influence budget-writing legislators.
</P>
<P>
   _Private alternatives: The extensive, generally first-rate
sanctuaries and sites owned by the Trustees of Reservations and the
Massachusetts Audubon Society meet much demand for outdoor
recreation and thus reduce public pressure to improve state parks.
</P>
<P>
   _Lobbying: ``No group has had the parks as its single purpose,''
said James Gomes, head of the Environmental League of
Massachusetts, a group whose roots can be traced back 100 years to
the Massachusetts Forest and Park Association. ``If this had stayed
a single-purpose organization, there probably would be a different
picture for the parks system.''
</P>
<P>
   _Funding: Entrance and camping fees collected by DEM are
swallowed up by the state treasury, and legislators set DEM's
budget, creating little incentive for park workers to attract more
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing park advocates, state Representative Douglas W.
Petersen, a Marblehead Democrat who heads the Natural Resources
Committee, slammed as ``a horrendous decision'' Weld's
election-year gambit in 1994 to cut fees in half, reducing campsite
fees to $6 a night and day-use tickets to $2.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was not a soul complaining'' fees were too high,
Petersen said. Webber said camping fees could rise next year to $10
as a new telephone reservation system is finally installed, but
some advocates contend fees should be brought up to New Hampshire's
usual $12 level or to the $11-$17 charged in Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Along with many other states, New Hampshire and Vermont, which
often are credited with having more attractive state parks than
Massachusetts, operate their systems on a self-funding basis,
pushing managers to keep sites attractive.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we used to camp in New Hampshire state parks, you could
eat off the bathroom floor 24 hours a day,'' said Robert Guertin of
Springfield, visiting the Mohawk Trail State Forest in Charlemont.
</P>
<P>
   _Lingering bad reputation: ``I think a lot of Massachusetts
residents have had the experience of going to state parks, finding
they're not up to snuff, and not coming back,'' said Mark Primack,
a longtime open-space advocate who runs the Wildlands Trust of
Southeastern Massachusetts. ``Once people stop going to state
parks, they stop being advocates for state parks.''
</P>
<P>
   One widely praised change Webber made last year was banning
alcohol in all state parks, where drunken rowdies all too often
terrorized camping families and seniors.
</P>
<P>
   Webber acknowledged using ``soft enforcement. We're not evicting
people if they have alcohol automatically; we're not confiscating
alcohol if they bring it in.'' Beer cans and liquor bottles in many
of the parks' trash bins prove Webber's point.
</P>
<P>
   But interviews show the ban is extremely popular and campers
understand that it is not intended to keep well-behaved visitors
from enjoying a quiet drink.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good the way it's prohibited, but if it goes on, people
keep it under control,'' said Bob Parker, a retired Guilford,
Conn., printing technician visiting the D.A.R. State Forest in
Goshen with his grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   But while DEM gets credit for pulling the system back from the
depths of neglect and focusing on basic amenities like clean
bathrooms and curbing drunken misbehavior, many supporters contend
it has a long way to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have so much to build on,'' said Deb Cary, a Worcester
Audubon Society sanctuary manager. ``I don't want to be accused of
tearing it down, but it is badly undermaintained. We really need to
elevate the level of stewardship.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The parks are probably Massachusetts's most underutilized
natural resource,'' said state Representative Christopher J.
Hodgkins, a Lee Democrat who has spent several summer vacations
camping in Berkshire parks. ``They're like these secret treasures.
We ought to let opportunity happen on them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
