<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENE LETOURNEAU TURNED ORDINARY TALK INTO BACKWOODSY WISDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Maine -- This has been a tough week for icons. Roy
Rogers went to meet Trigger in that great corral up in the sky.Then
the conglomerate that owns the B&AMP;M Baked Beans plant here announced
that New England's quintessential baked bean factory is on the
block. And then Maine's favorite newspaperman, outdoor writer Gene
Letourneau, died at 90, ending a 65-year run as a journalist and
environmentalist.
</P>
<P>
   That's two good men no longer with us, and the fate of the baked
beans that are truly oven-baked hangs in the corporate balance.
Pillsbury Co. of Minneapolis says it hopes to find a buyer for the
waterfront factory that has been churning out the syruppy magical
fruit in cans or jars for 85 years at the same location. The 160
workers were informed Monday that the Pillsbury Doughboy is going
off baked beans, but because the plant runs two shifts and demand
for the B&AMP;M brand remains strong, Pillsbury expects to find a buyer
in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   For some reason, the B&AMP;M brand sells well in New England and in
Seattle, which makes me suspect that a lot of those high-tech types
who bailed out of the Land of the Bean and the Cod took their
fondness for baked beans with them when they went west to seek
their fortune.
</P>
<P>
   So you can still get your B&AMP;M beans, at least for a while, and
you can watch old Rogers flicks on video. But the words and wisdom
of Gene Letourneau are a finite commodity, and there won't be any
more of the columns he wrote virtually daily from 1946 on.
</P>
<P>
   In the way the late columnist Herb Caen came to embody the
spirit of the city of San Francisco, Letourneau wrote to and for
the folks who learned to hunt, fish, trap, and log before
``yuppies'' was a plural noun, or flatlanders found the forests.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Waterville in 1906, youngest of six kids, Letourneau was
city editor of the Waterville Sentinel when the boss, Guy Gannett,
asked him to write a daily outdoors column.
</P>
<P>
   Letourneau became a minor legend among New England newspapermen
for an accident that befell him in 1993, when he was alone in the
Allagash at a camp far from civilization. He'd taken a bad fall,
couldn't walk, and crawled for seven hours to reach his station
wagon.
</P>
<P>
   Then he hauled himself in, and drove 200 miles to his home in
Waterville _ with what turned out to be a fractured hip socket.
</P>
<P>
   His ``Sportsmen Say'' column ran in the Sentinel, the Press
Herald, the Maine Sunday Telegram,the Kennebec Journal and the
Central Maine Morning Sentinel. Anyone with interest in the
outdoors read him, and he built up a reputation for trustworthiness
and reliability that is rare in the journalism of this era.
</P>
<P>
   George Mitchell, the former senator, credited Gene and Ed Muskie
for spearheading the environmental movement in the Pine Tree State.
At his testimonal dinner, Roberta Scruggs of the Portland Press
Herald wrote that the old newspaperman said: ``I'm the luckiest man
in the world. Every day was a holiday. It was just a great life.''
</P>
<P>
   He had a remarkable way with people, and his sincerity and honor
won over even the most taciturn of Maine police, politicians, and
woodsmen. ``I'd get scooped once in a while,'' he said of his
earlier years as a police reporter and city editor, ``I'd hold
stuff in confidence and somebody would scoop me. But I'd win out in
the long run. I wouldn't break a confidence with anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   With that simple recipe for trust, he fashioned a remarkable
career. ``I realized right away that listening to people was the
best bet,'' he said of column-writing. ``Let them give me a story,
then I'd do the best I could with it.''
</P>
<P>
   He turned ordinary conversation into backwoodsy wisdom,
collected in the Press Herald Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
   _``You've got to be careful talking about dogs. It's worse than
talking about a man's woman.
</P>
<P>
   _``One thing I've noticed is when a man gets to be about 60 he's
not gung-ho about shooting things. He loses that desire.
</P>
<P>
   _``In the outdoors, you learn something new every day. A fellow
used to tell me you go down Main Street and it doesn't change very
much. But the outdoors changes every day.
</P>
<P>
   _``You can be president of the United States, but if the fish
don't want to strike, they won't. It's the greatest equalizer there
is.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Gannett chain's incoming president discovered
Letourneau's name and 60 years of active service on the employees
list in 1991, he thought it was a mistake, wrote Scruggs.
</P>
<P>
   The new executive asked Letourneau whom he reported to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I always reported to Guy P. Gannett,'' was the reply.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gene, Guy Gannett died in 1954,'' said the new boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' said Gene, ``That's been a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
