<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9051 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEABIRD-REFUGE-BOS &LR;      07-10 1587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEABIRD-REFUGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SEABIRD REFUGE IN MAINE TAKES FLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EASTERN EGG ROCK, Maine _ The sky is alive with scores of angry
terns, each screeching within inches of Terry Goodhue's ears as
they swoop past. Needle-sharp orange beaks peck the kneeling
researcher on the head, knocking his hat askew, while a few bomb
him with warm guano.
</P>
<P>
   Goodhue, who works for the National Audubon Society, pays no
mind to the attacks as he methodically attaches leg bands to the
fluffy, coffee-colored tern chicks on the ground. There's a
cardboard liner inside his hat for protection, and, not
surprisingly, it looks like a dart board from all the pecking.
</P>
<P>
   ``You only forget your hat once,'' jokes Sandra Ruggiero, a
Lexington, Mass., schoolteacher and mother of four who has
volunteered for a two-week stint working with Goodhue.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the kingdom of the birds, a rare place where
conservationists have restored a natural order that humans _ and
the gulls that eat their waste _ have wiped out elsewhere. Out
here, on a 7-acre pile of granite topped with grass and ragweed on
Muscongus Bay, more than 5,000 terns, laughing gulls, puffins, and
other seabirds run a cacophonous nursery that they zealously guard
against intruders.
</P>
<P>
   Eastern Egg Rock is the fruit of a 25-year effort by Audubon
biologist Stephen Kress that began when he brought his first
suitcase full of puffin chicks to the island. Capitalizing on
public affection for puffins, whose penguin-like bodies and parrot
beaks make them tourist darlings, Kress has made a home for
less-loved birds, too, such as the black guillemot, which looks
like a web-footed pigeon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable what's going on out there,'' said Kress, a
genial man whose trademark tam-o'-shanter hat gives him a jaunty
highlands look _ even though he's from Ohio. ``This is almost a
museum of what Maine seabird colonies used to be like'' before
European settlement.
</P>
<P>
   This unlikely museum, which has inspired imitators around the
world as well as five island spinoffs in Maine under Kress' Project
Puffin, remains a work in progress, however. Without human
intervention, aggressive herring and black-backed gulls _ which
thrive on waste from landfills and fishing boats _ would return to
drive out the other birds, including endangered roseate terns.
</P>
<P>
   So, Goodhue and the volunteers spend their summers in a uniquely
hostile world, an island so rocky that boats have difficulty
approaching, where the avian residents put up a ruckus every time
humans venture out of the one-room cabin affectionately known as
the ``Egg Rock Hilton.'' On wet days, the cloister of cabin life
has driven people to such boredom beaters as celebrating ``Black
Guillemot Appreciation Day.''
</P>
<P>
   With no electricity or water supply and soil too poor even to
grow tomatoes, the researchers are utterly dependent on the
mainland for supplies, yet largely cut off from civilization and
almost completely without privacy in this treeless place. In fact,
one of the few nods to human needs is the new outhouse; previously
the intertidal zone served as the restroom.
</P>
<P>
   Far from feeling imprisoned, however, the Egg Rockers feel
privileged, allowed to witness the daily drama of life in a bird
city against a backdrop of stunning ocean views of a lighthouse,
the artist colony on Monhegan Island, and the spruce-lined Maine
coast.
</P>
<P>
   Old journals of Project Puffin include paeans to island life
from such famous visitors as the late Marlin Perkins of ``Mutual of
Omaha's Wild Kingdom,'' and legendary bird guide author Roger Tory
Peterson. Journals also contain writings from hundreds of the
not-so-famous, such as Tom French, Massachusetts' top endangered
species official, who wrote fondly of his fried dogfish dinner on
the island in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call this the perfect antidote'' to everyday life, says
Ruggiero, the schoolteacher, who, like Montreal college student
Genevieve Smith and National Geographic photo editor Steven Walker,
is spending her vacation on the island.
</P>
<P>
   If life is hard on humans, of course, it is hardly less so for
the birds. The rocks outside the cabin window look like a barnyard
as dozens of downy tern chicks squeak for the attention of
fish-bearing parents. Often, only the first-hatched and biggest
terns survive, shoving aside the runts to starve, while chicks of
all species die from exposure to heat or rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just life out here, the way nature does its work. But
why do they have to be so cute?'' asks Walker, a bearish man in an
Australian bush hat.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the death, though, few places are more full of life.
In the tall grass, black-hooded laughing gulls throw back their
heads in hysterical cackles, while baby barn swallows with
comically oversized yellow bills peer out from a nest on the porch
of the cabin. The black guillemots carry blood-colored eels to
their young hiding among the granite slabs, as eider ducks in
formation rush by just above the water surface.
</P>
<P>
   The noise of this giant nursery never ceases as parents and
chicks call out to each other through the night, joined by a
strange nocturnal addition, Leach's storm-petrels. These black
robin-sized birds make almost eerie calls from nests beneath the
cabin, sometimes waking up whoever's inside.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the puffins are the unquestioned stars, attracting three
different tour boats that circle the island each day loaded with
tourists. Quiet and quirky, these so-called ``clowns of the sea''
stand apart from the hubbub, often lined up on the rocks at odd
angles, quizzically looking from side to side like idlers with
hands behind their backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public can't get enough of them,'' said Kress, who seems
to have lost none of his enthusiasm for the birds either. ``I think
it's because they're vertical as we are. We tend to enjoy animals
that are like us.''
</P>
<P>
   Some biologists resent the public preference for star animals
such as gorillas and eagles, when others, from scarab beetles to
kangaroo rats, are no less valuable. But Kress saw a chance in the
puffins to recreate a whole landscape that humans had largely
destroyed through careless disposal of waste that caused a gull
population explosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad we have one charismatic bird'' among the
seabirds, said Kress, a professor at Cornell University.
</P>
<P>
   By early in this century, hunters and hat makers had nearly
wiped out puffins from the coast of Maine, the only place in the
United States that Atlantic puffins nest. The birds had made a
modest comeback by 1969 when Kress arrived, but puffins had lost
all but one of at least six Maine nesting sites to the trash-eating
gulls. Today, puffins are listed as a threatened species in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   To reverse the decline, Kress and his team played nursemaid to
954 puffin chicks brought to Eastern Egg Rock from Newfoundland
from 1973 to 1986, digging artificial burrows for them to live in,
feeding them fish, and removing gull nests.
</P>
<P>
   The major scientific issue was whether or not puffin chicks
would return to raise their own young after their customary two to
three years at sea. To improve the odds, Kress' team put up dozens
of wooden puffin decoys in hopes of convincing the puffins that Egg
Rock was already a bona fide colony.
</P>
<P>
   Today, two decoys cemented to the rocks stand as reminders of
the landmark experiment, but the 18 pairs of puffins nesting on the
island feel right at home without them. Some have been returning
since the early 1980s to the same burrow and same mate. As a
tribute to Kress' success, wildlife managers from Quebec to the
Galapagos Islands now use decoys to draw seabirds.
</P>
<P>
   On Eastern Egg Rock, the puffins' return set the stage for the
broader goal of recreating a bird colony as it would have been
before European settlement. Driving off the herring and
black-backed gulls was enough for some species, such as the less
aggressive laughing gulls, while decoys and taped bird sounds
brought back the terns. In addition, Leach's storm-petrels moved in
to burrows that had been dug for the puffins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have everything on the island that was ever known to breed
here,'' said Kress, including the largest common tern colony in the
state and over half of the roseate terns in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   And the birds don't simply coexist: They provide for the common
defense. A walk across Egg Rock quickly demonstrates why Alfred
Hitchcock went to a tern colony to film his 1963 thriller ``The
Birds.'' In minutes, three species of terns as well as the laughing
gulls take angrily to the air to repel intruders.
</P>
<P>
   But Kress, who wears a tam-o'-shanter so the birds will peck the
pompom instead of his head, sympathizes. Pointing to an Arctic tern
egg as its parents swirled overhead, he says, ``Its parents came
all the way from Antarctica to lay that one egg on that rock, so
they've got a lot invested.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for Project Puffin now, Kress says, is to build
public support, which is why, after 25 years, he still answers
almost every student's inquiry about puffins. He and writer Pete
Salmansohn penned a book for elementary school children last year,
and educators for the project have talked to 2,000 students.
Recently, Kress hired a fund-raiser for the first time in hopes of
greatly increasing funding beyond the current modest
$400,000-a-year budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people don't care about these birds, it doesn't matter what
we do in the long run,'' Kress said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
