<HEADER>
A9053 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-TANGLEWOOD-2TAKE     07-10 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TANGLEWOOD-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN INSIDER'S SOLID LOOK AT TANGLEWOOD RANCOR 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
TANGLEWOOD 
The Clash Between Tradition and Change 
By Andrew L. Pincus 
Northeastern University Press, 210 pp., illustrated, $24.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The clash between tradition and change probably began in the
second minute of Creation and it will continue until the
Apocalypse.
</P>
<P>
   The particular circumstances of this clash as they unfolded at
Tanglewood over the last couple of years have brought the Boston
Symphony Orchestra its worst press since 1984, when actress Vanessa
Redgrave sued the orchestra for canceling her contract because of
her political views. This controversy is paradoxical, because
Tanglewood's founder, former BSO music director Serge Koussevitzky,
sought to sidestep the immemorial conflict by creating a tradition
that would be about change.
</P>
<P>
   There are many good reasons to read ``Tanglewood: The Clash
Between Tradition and Change,'' by Andrew Pincus, the music critic
of The Berkshire Eagle. It is a serious, thoughtful, and
thought-provoking book. Over the last 23 years, Pincus has
certainly spent more hours on the Tanglewood grounds than any other
journalist and probably more than any musician or administrator. He
knows the greensward as well as any individual can, and what is
encrypted on every blade of grass.
</P>
<P>
   Most of his readers, at least for now, will turn to his new book
to get the skivvy on the controversies swirling around the
Tanglewood Music Center, the BSO's summer institute for advanced
musical training, but they will not get to the bottom of the
matter. Pincus's account seems sketchy _ it has to be because too
much of what happened is unclear and key participants have chosen
not to talk publicly about it. But it also seems partial, which may
be why the BSO briefly contemplated forbidding the sale of the book
in the Tanglewood gift shop.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Pincus's treatment of the TMC controversies is more solid
than it was in his recent overheated article in Boston Magazine. &UR;  &LR; 
It has become routine for commentators &UR;  &LR; to discuss a 1994 Sony/PBS
educational video project involving Wynton Marsalis, Yo-Yo Ma,
Seiji Ozawa, and students of the Tanglewood Music Center as if it
were a schlocky and purely commercial venture, as if the TMC
orchestra had had been commandeered to back up the Spice Girls on
MTV.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Marsalis on Music'' video project was flawed in conception
and execution, but objections to it came to the fore only after the
taping was underway. By that time, it was too late to do anything
about scheduling conflicts, which certainly should have been
foreseen. At that point, Ozawa's only option was the one every
professional musician has to exercise repeatedly throughout his
career _ to soldier on, making the best of a bad situation. It
could be argued that instead of exploiting the TMC students, he was
offering them a lesson in professionalism.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over the Marsalis project crystalized a
longstanding conflict at Tanglewood between the ``ivory tower''
activities of the TMC and the populist requirements of a summer
festival that must attract an audience of thousands to every
concert. It also set in motion a chain of events that led to
Ozawa's dismissal of Richard Ortner as administrator of the TMC and
the high-profile resignations of the TMC's artistic director Leon
Fleisher and faculty chairman Gilbert Kalish. There is no evidence
that Ozawa either wanted or welcomed these resignations. In fact,
he repeatedly urged Fleisher, now 70, to remain in a reconfigured,
honorific and active position.
</P>
<P>
   Like most people who love Tanglewood and the Tanglewood Music
Center in particular, Pincus seems troubled and confused by these
events, events in which people on both sides of the controversy
sought to wrap themselves in the cape of Koussevitzky, who made a
natural ally to both sides because he was both firmly attached to
tradition and profoundly committed to advancing the cutting edge.
He believed that the ``eternal verities'' expressed in music could
be found in the work unknown young Americans hadn't composed yet as
well as in classics by Beethoven, Brahms, and Tchaikovsky.
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa has said little about his reasons for wanting change at
the TMC, but what he has said makes sense. He was not happy with
the parts of the operation he knows best, the conducting and the
orchestra program, and he wanted to restore a more direct
involvement by the BSO in its own school. Orchestra training is a
core element of the TMC's curriculum, and the school was not making
full or effective use of the very resource that makes it unique,
the sponsorship of a resident world-class symphony orchestra. In
noting this, quite belatedly, (more than 20 years into his music
directorship), Ozawa was measuring the TMC of recent years against
the very different Tanglewood of his first experience, when he
arrived as a student in 1960. The principal change he wanted was
the restoration of a tradition which withered away back in the
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question that the dismissal of Ortner was handled
badly, and that the subsequent year of transition, which unfolded
in the absence of a general manager, was troubled by numerous
administrative missteps and misunderstandings that led to hurt
feelings and bruised egos. The resignations of Kalish and Fleisher
were a public-relations disaster; more importantly, they
represented an artistic loss to Tanglewood.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless it is an enormous jump from these unpleasant facts
to the even more unpleasant implications of Pincus's assessment
that Ozawa ``was unhappy with the traditionalist stance of the
Music Center, which since its beginning under Koussevitzky had been
dedicated to ensemble performance and the art of music rather than
solo careers and glorification of the performer. Wanting to open
the festival and school to outside influences as jazz, Ozawa felt
blocked by `the club' (of Fleisher, Kalish and other ``entrenched''
members of the TMC faculty).''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
