<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV12-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINNED DOWN STAIN GIVES `WASHED' LOOK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 12 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My 48-year-old knotty pine summer house in Marshfield has a
lot of knotty pine that I think was stained with a Minwax stain;
the finish is dull. Can I put a white semitransparent stain on that
knotty pine? I don't mind the knots that will bleed through. I
don't want a painted look, but rather a sort of washed look.
</P>
<P>
   LISA COZZA, Medford, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If the paneling has not been varnished or waxed or treated in
any way other than the flat stain, then you can use a
semitransparent stain, but it won't be white, or at least white
white; off-white or light, light gray is the best you can do. While
that stain is designed for outdoor use, one thin coat on an inside
surface will be OK, although it would be a good idea to get out of
the house while the stain is drying.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to get a semitransprent stain look is to thin down a
white solid color stain or interior latex wall paint, and apply one
coat of that. Use water to thin down the stain or paint. How much
to use is up to you to get the desired look.
</P>
<P>
   The way to do that is to make a small mix of one part stain and
one part water, and apply that to a small area of the wall. Make a
different mix, and try that until you get what you like. Then make
a bigger batch with the proper formula and finish the job.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. A roofer redoing my roof proposes to put Ice &AMP; Water Shield
on my entire roof. Is this necessary? Also, there is a lot of snow
on the roof in winter; would the snow melt bring water into the
attic? I am having a ridge vent put in; how can I tell if the
roofer has cut a slot in the sheathing so the vent will actually
vent?
</P>
<P>
   A CALLER, from Needham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I think the Ice &AMP; Water Shield has to go up only six feet
from the eaves, but it wouldn't hurt to put it on the entire roof,
just somewhat more expensive. With six feet of Ice &AMP; Water Shield
and a proper roof installation, there should be no leaks into the
attic from snow melt or any other source. While the Ice &AMP; Water
Shield will not prevent ice dams, it will prevent water backed up
by the dam from getting under the shingles and causing a leak.
</P>
<P>
   It's the ridge vent and soffit vents (under the eaves) that
prevent ice dams.
</P>
<P>
   A certain amount of trust is required when you hire a pro to do
something. If you really don't trust the professional, find
another. But to determine if the sheathing were cut for a ridge
vent, go into the attic and inspect the under part of the ridge; if
the sheathing were cut, there should be a one- or two-inch-wide
strip open on each side of the ridge board. If you don't see these
open strips, or do not see daylight through them (you won't see a
lot of daylight, but there will be a little showing), then see the
roofer to make things right. Another way to check is to light a
match near the ridge; the movement of air from soffits to ridge
might be enough to blow the match out. Or, blow the match out and
see if the smoke goes up through the ridge.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I've been told that if you paint your siding blue or yellow,
it will prevent any nails holding the clapboards in place from
rusting. I find that hard to believe. Is it so?
</P>
<P>
   D.Z., Newton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Huh, wha? The handyman has heard a lot of wacky things, but
that one takes the cake. In three words, it ain't so. No paint, any
color, will prevent rusting, nor will it cover rusted nails; the
rust will bleed through, sooner than later. Painting the nails with
Kilz or any other primer-sealer/stain-killer-type finish also will
not work. Painting the rusty nails with Rust Reformer may work for
a while, but not permanently. Rust Reformer and other brand names
for the material contain phosphoric acid, which turns the rust
black and makes it paintable.
</P>
<P>
   Even countersinking the nails and filling them with putty may
not work for very long. Besides, the clapboards are only 1/4 inch
thick, not thick enough for effective countersinking.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to conquer rust is to remove it, and remove its
source. So, pull the old nails and replace them with stainless
steel siding nails. You might be able to drive the stainless steel
nails into the holes of the old nails; if not, drive the stainless
steel nails beside the old nail holes, and fill those old holes
with exterior wood filler.
</P>
<P>
   If you find pulling the old nails tedious and labor intensive,
you could instead countersink them clear through the clapboard and
fill the holes with wood filler. This is not as good as pulling the
old nails, because countersinking clear through the clapboards
could spilt them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The linoleum on the deck of a boat cabin looks like wood and
is still in pretty good shape, but the shine is gone. How can I get
it to shine again?
</P>
<P>
   REBECCA SCHULTES, Wilmington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Some linoleum are so old that not only have they lost their
shine but will not take a shine under any treatment. But it won't
hurt to try applying a coat of Future, and acrylic finish. If it
works, fine. If it doesn't, I don't think anything will.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107. The
Handyman chats on line Thursdays, 1-2 p.m, at
http://www.boston.com, keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
