<SLUG> BC-ONELIFE-SOAPS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLEZAK'S WILD RIDE ON `OLTL'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROL BIDWELL 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Amid the mayhem, murder, seduction and
double-dealing that for 30 years has characterized the fictional
town of Llanview, Pa. _ home of the ABC soap ``One Life to Live'' _
staid Victoria Lord Carpenter has always been the calm, reasonable
eye of the hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   Unless, that is, she's turned into one of her six alternate
personalities, shot a gangster, suffocated the father who sexually
abused her, or given birth while hypnotized, ``forgetting'' the
entire pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Viki's been a very busy girl over the years,'' mused Hollywood
born-and-bred Erika Slezak, who's played the character for 28
years. ``She's done some remarkable things. And I'm sure she'll do
some more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``OLTL,'' seen weekdays at 1 p.m., first aired on July 15, 1968.
Its creator, Agnes Nixon, initially focused story lines on the
blue-collar Polish Wolek family and the blue-blooded Lords, plus
their Irish, African-American and Jewish neighbors and friends.
</P>
<P>
   While the show has had a loyal following, the pinnacle of its
success so far was when it hit No. 2 in 1980-81, the year doctor's
wife Karen Wolek, played by actress Judith Light, was forced to
admit on the witness stand that she was turning tricks as a
prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the show and its cast has won 23 Emmys, one for
best actress for Light _ largely on the strength of those
confession scenes _ and five best-actress awards for Slezak.
</P>
<P>
   ``OLTL'' has also broken soap-opera ground with a number of
stories, including: having a light-skinned African-American woman
pass herself off as Caucasian (1969); filming inside a real-life
drug rehab center (1972); filming a soap opera within a soap opera
(``Fraternity Row,'' 1988) and even staging its own awards show;
exploring homophobia and reuniting the town's warring factions
through a moving display of the national AIDS Quilt (1992);
exploring the fallout from a brutal fraternity house gang rape
(1993); and delving into the world of Latino street gangs (1996).
</P>
<P>
   Today, with the show consistently hovering at No. 8 in the
11-soap field, executive producer Jill Ferren Phelps, who joined
the show six months ago, said she and head writer Pam Long are
aiming eventually for that elusive No. 1 spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know there are people who tune in once or twice a week,''
Phelps said. ``The trick to getting the ratings up ... is being
able to weave through enough suspense that the audience will have
to watch the next day to see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The show, which has undergone some cast changes and has more new
characters waiting in the wings, was hauled out of the doldrums
recently with the ``Who Killed Georgie?'' murder mystery, which
culminated with misfit newspaper publisher Todd Manning _ Viki's
brother _ holding the show's pivotal characters hostage until one
of them confessed to bashing in the head of the town's wacko
troublemaker/bad girl.
</P>
<P>
   That episode, which was bumped from daytime to prime time by
World Cup soccer matches, was a hit after head writer Pam Long and
her crew juggled the story line to take advantage of a new
nighttime audience they hoped might follow the show back to
daytime.
</P>
<P>
   ``OLTL's'' daytime episodes routinely draw about 3.2 million
viewers, but the June 25 prime-time episode _ in a slot filled
during the regular season by ``Nothing Sacred,'' which lost out
regularly in the ratings to blockbuster ``Seinfeld'' _ pulled in
more than 4.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   It's a trend Phelps hopes will continue.
</P>
<P>
   For a show that's reached the 30-year mark, there'll be
remarkably little fanfare to mark the milestone. All during this
month, the show's fans will be treated to daily 60-second interview
vignettes with Slezak and other cast members. And during the July
31 episode, many of the show's characters will meander down memory
lane, remembering the show's most intriguing story lines and most
complex and endearing characters through flashbacks.
</P>
<P>
   And if die-hard ``OLTL'' buffs want more, they can check out
major bookstores for a glossy, engrossing coffee table book, ``One
Life to Live: Thirty Years of Memories'' (Hyperion; $29.95) that
recounts the soap's entire history.
</P>
<P>
   Slezak's character accounts for a good deal of the show's
history. Viki's spent the past three decades publishing a
newspaper, battling mental illness and a paralyzing stroke, and
time-traveling to 1888 Arizona, to the underground futuristic world
of Eterna and even to heaven. All that, !ital!plus!off! being
elected mayor and finding love six times with five husbands (her
full name is Victoria Lord Gordon Riley Burke Riley Buchanan
Carpenter).
</P>
<P>
   One of her favorite story lines, Slezak says, was the 1997
scenario in which Viki warred with her six alternate personalities
_ wounded baby Princess, angry teen boy Tommy, truth-teller Tori,
seductive Niki, gatekeeper Jean and a manifestation of her own
dead, abusive father, Victor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard, but it was terrific fun,'' Slezak said. ``It was
such a challenge. I wanted to make them different enough so people
who tuned in in the middle of a scene would know which character
they were watching.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
