<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9059 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEET-SPICE-ART-BOS &LR;      07-10 1441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEET-SPICE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPICE-STRUCK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISA VALDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANSFIELD, Mass. _ This is a love story. As in Ann, Jennifer,
Jessica, and Tabitha love the Spice Girls. So when the four
Boston-area girls were chosen to meet the Spice Girls backstage,
before the group's Great Woods concert Wednesday night, you will
understand why they screamed and jumped and ran in circles. They
love the Spice Girls. More than anything, according to Ann LeBlanc,
who is 8. And a half.
</P>
<P>
   Think we're kidding? Witness the Herculean effort involved in
delivering the children from Ann's apartment in a Medford housing
development to the concert in Mansfield, 34 miles away. First, mom
Florence LeBlanc, 45, had to phone all of her friends who have
cars, because she can't afford one. Michael Stenson was willing to
drive, but his car was on the outs. Knowing how much the girls
loved the Spice Girls, he arranged to borrow his sister's rusty
gray Chevy. Everyone piled in, and Mike took off, so anxious to
make the kids' dream come true that he drove on the shoulder of
Interestate 93, weaving in and out of traffic like a daredevil.
Thirty miles later, he wrecked on the ramp from Interstate 495
South to Route 140, 1 mile shy of the destination.
</P>
<P>
   No one was hurt, but the girls began to cry. A dream deferred.
Then the police, including State Police Lt. Frederick Morse, who
was on paid police duty at the concert venue, arrived on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we saw them crying, we thought they were hurt,'' Morse
said in a phone interview from his Framingham post Thursday. ``But
when I realized it was because they weren't going to get to meet
the Spice Girls, I decided to take them down, blue lights and all.
It's traumatic enough being in an accident. I wanted to make it
better for them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have a ride home,'' said Florence LeBlanc, as she
crawled, dazed and stressed, out of the cruiser with her daughter,
sister, nieces, and daughter's best friend. ``But we couldn't pass
this up. We'll find a way home.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, before we get to the good part, where four squirming girls
come face to face with four very muscular, very rich British pop
stars, let's explain how LeBlanc and company could afford to attend
the show, which at $40 a pop would have cost them $240, which
Florence, the unemployed, single mother of four kids, says is
``more than a week's income'' for her household. Let's explain how
of the nearly 20,000 fans at the show, these kids were able to meet
the Girls.
</P>
<P>
   It was free, and arranged in the name of marketing, the magical
Spice Girls key word.
</P>
<P>
   Ann, who attends the Goodwill Fresh Air summer camp for
disadvantaged kids, was selected by counselors there for the free
tickets, which were donated by a board member with connections at
Aprilia, the Italian motorcycle company that sponsors the Spice
Girls tour. ``Ann was clearly the biggest Spice Girls fan at
camp,'' said Betsy Rosen, a Goodwill spokeswoman. ``She has the
necklace, the posters, the lollipops, the dolls. She's got it
all.'' Ann, in turn, chose to invite her best buddy, Jessica
Yanosky, age 9; and her cousins Jennifer and Tabitha Belbin, ages 9
and 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ann would never have even asked to go,'' said her mother.
``She knows I couldn't afford it. That's how much of a dream this
was for her.''
</P>
<P>
   This explains why the four girls, who spent painstaking hours
choosing their velvet outfits and platform shoes, ended up draped
in gigantic Aprilia T-shirts, which they were required to wear. ``I
wanted Sporty Spice to see my outfit,'' said Ann, who had finally
persuaded her mother to allow her to wear blue eye shadow. ``I've
never dressed up or gone anywhere like this before.''
</P>
<P>
   So there they were, half an hour before showtime, waiting at a
side gate, while everyone else watched the endless slew of
commercials on giant video screens. Sponsorship coordinator Ken
Smith, a Scot with short whitish hair and laughing eyes, tried to
soothe their nerves.
</P>
<P>
   ``How long? How much longer? Is it time yet?'' Tabitha
questioned, her face twisted in agony.
</P>
<P>
   ``One minute more,'' Smith said. So the girls started counting
the seconds, out loud. Florence, dressed in a black tank top and
tight jeans, puffed on her cigarette and eyed her anxious daughter.
A smile crept across mom's face as she recalled her first concert,
at 15 _ Seals and Crofts.
</P>
<P>
   ``57, 58, 59, 60!'' they cried in unison. Smith, true to his
word, turned, and opened the gate.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the gate were two round tables set up on the grass under
a canopy, where the girls were told to wait along with another
group. As they walked toward the tables, an entourage including
Aerosmith singer Steven Tyler passed. At that point, Florence and
her sister Janet Belbin (Tabitha and Jennifer's mom) suddenly
resembled their children. The moms turned on their heels and began
to follow Tyler into a room where VIPs sat eating things like tiny
meatballs on toothpicks. They didn't get very far.
</P>
<P>
   If waiting at the gate was bad, waiting at the tables was worse.
``I'm shaking,'' said Jennifer. Ann tried to remember all the
questions she had thought up back in Medford _ What is girl power?
Why did you name the band Spice Girls? But her mind was blank.
``Mom,'' she said, grasping her throat dramatically. ``I'm so
thirsty, Mom, I'm going to die.'' Jennifer jumped up and down, her
brown eyes bright and shiny. Jessica, nerves shot, stared at her
toenails, painted pink for the occasion. Then Jennifer spotted Baby
Spice through the window.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see her! I see Baby!'' The Medford girls began jumping and
climbing over one another, screaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see Scary!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I see Sporty!''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why they loved the Spice Girls so much, they answered,
variously, ``They're cool.'' ``They're sexy.'' ``They have girl
power.'' ``They dress cool.'' ``They don't let anyone push them
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Scary Spice (Melanie Brown), in velvet pants and halter top, was
the first to appear, ``You guys all right?'' she asked, signing
each of the girls' papers with a Magic Marker, moving along the row
of fans methodically. The girls, mouth agape, were speechless. And
then, as quickly as she had come, Scary was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Next came Posh Spice (Victoria Adams), with her new short,
slicked-back hair. Ann stared, her breathing shallow, and could
only manage a whisper, ``Victoria ...'' To which Posh replied:
``Hello there. Are you all OK? Yeah? Thanks for coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came Baby Spice (Emma Bunton), with her high blonde
ponytails. ``Everyone is OK?'' she asked, seeming rushed. Then she
was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it was Sporty Spice (Melanie Chisholm), Ann's personal
favorite. She watched the girls for a moment, a look of amusement
on her face. ``Hello everyone,'' she said. The girls gulped and
stared. ``You all OK? Look at you. I want to see you up dancing and
singing, OK? I'm glad you came. Have a jolly good time, OK?'' She
smiled, kind. And then she, too, disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Ann collapsed dramatically onto the grass. Upon being lifted up
by her mother, she said ``I fainted, Mom, I really fainted. I just
could not believe it. They talked to me. Sporty talked to me. This
is the best day of my life.'' Jennifer stared at her paper with the
four signatures, held it up to her mother, and asked, ``Isn't that
beautiful?''
</P>
<P>
   Tabitha held her paper to her chest and said, over and over, ``I
can't believe it. I can't believe it.'' Jessica, still overcome
with emotion, said nothing.
</P>
<P>
   As the girls walked hand in hand to their 12th row center seats
they talked about this, the biggest day of their lives, according
to Jennifer. It only got better, too, as the concert proceeded.
They danced and sang their way through, as Sporty had ordered.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the coolest costumes,'' said Tabitha, who had a
minor accident just when the show started. Her foot got jammed in
the seat and security had to take her to the first aid tent. After
an attendant wrapped the ankle, she returned to her seat and
resumed singing and dancing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God for the Spice Girls,'' Ann said, after it was all
over and she and her group waited for a cab, whose flat $80 fee was
paid for by Goodwill. ``If there were no Spice Girls, I don't know
what I'd do. I'd probably like KISS. That's why I'm glad there are
Spice Girls. Because they make you realize how stupid KISS really
is. When I grow up, I want to be a Spice Girl. I already have my
name. Junior Spice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 1307EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0068 </DOCNO>
