<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUN-TAN-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN AND TAN MAY NOT BE SO LOVELY AS TIME GOES BY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ There are times I wish I'd never sat in the sun.
Like the day a dermatologist removed a pre-cancerous growth from my
face and said: ``You were a sun bunny, weren't you? You'll be
back.''
</P>
<P>
   That was 15 years ago, and now I rarely put my face into direct
sunlight without at least a 30 block on and a big-brimmed hat. But
the skin doctor knew. He's probably seen it all, girls who dosed
baby oil with iodine, slathered it on like marinade, lay out by the
pool with an oven timer set to 15 minutes and then flipped like
shrimp for an even tan.
</P>
<P>
   Now, we're all paying the price.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Richard Glogau, chief of dermatology at the University of
California at San Francisco, calls it photo-aging. He has invented
a four-level scale. The pictures are very, very scary. If you're
not careful or, if with the enthusiasm of youth you think you're
impervious, consider this: You can look old, really old at 40.
</P>
<P>
   I also asked him what a woman would look like if she never let
the sun hit her: ``Denise Hale,'' he said. An Eastern European
whose mother told her never to go out in the sun, Denise, into her
60s, has skin like milk. Not a mark on her. So, it is possible to
protect yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Suntans were once a sign of the low-born, people who had to work
for a living. Fine ladies went to the beach covered up, sat under a
parasol or a beach umbrella and never let their sun and skin meet.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Duke and Duchess of Windsor and Coco Chanel showed
up in photographs brown as berries, suntans, particularly in the
dead of winter, became the status symbol of the idle rich, those
who could afford to luxuriate in Cap d'Antibes or Tahiti.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE AGING FACTOR
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine doesn't just burn you, it ages the skin and can produce
basal cell carcinoma, squamous cell carcinoma and melanoma. There
are three different kinds of ultraviolet sun rays: UVBs, UVAs and
UVCs.
</P>
<P>
   The rays that we are concerned with are the B's, which are short
rays and produce sunburn and eventually squamous cell carcinomas,
and the more insidious UVAs, which penetrate the dermal layer of
the skin, break down collagen, the superstructure that keeps skin
plump and non-wrinkled, and set loose those pesky free radicals,
rogue ions (think rust here) that mutate skin cells into melanomas.
</P>
<P>
   Think mnemonically: B's burn and A's age. UVAs are also present
on gloomy, cloudy days; they can go through nine feet of water and
penetrate the glass windows in cars. As for the UVCs, the
fast-depleting ozone layer has kept them away from skin thus far.
</P>
<P>
   Now, when you sit in the sun, a number of things can happen. Sun
rays raise the melanocytes, those tan-producing cells close to the
surface in the epidermal, or top layer, of the skin which are
designed to protect the skin of races whose natural habitat is
fairly close to the equator. Mediterranean types, Africans and
Semitic peoples all have more melanin in their skins than Nordic
types or the classic Irish/English rose who turns pink at the first
lick of a sunbeam.
</P>
<P>
   If you get a slight sunburn, the effects will show up
immediately with redness and discomfort. But over time, the more
treacherous damage shows up. It may take 20 years, but the payoff
for undisciplined sun exposure is photo-aging: loss of elasticity,
sun spots.
</P>
<P>
   You see them on women over 40 who have spent a lot of time in
the sun gardening, playing tennis, swimming and boating and have
forgotten to slather sunscreen on their hands.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DAMAGE CAN'T BE REVERSED
</P>
<P>
   All of this damage can be slowed or prevented, but not reversed
unless by surgical process, which is expensive, painful and not
always guaranteed. One of the new procedures for getting rid of
advanced sun damage is a TCA or Trichloracetic acid peel, which
burns off the top layers of the skin.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
<P>
   Says New York plastic surgeon Gerald Imber, ``With a TCA peel, a
28 percent solution is relatively effective. You just don't look
all that good. And you have to repeat it every couple of months.''
</P>
<P>
   Another radical procedure for getting rid of sun damage is a
computerized laser peel. ``It has to destroy the top layer of the
skin,'' Imber says. ``We can do the whole face, but it is not a
pleasant thought.''
</P>
<P>
   So, what to do if you don't want plastic surgery to tighten up
your drooping, collagen-reduced, dry, dull and lifeless skin or
laser resurfacing or even a chemical peel?
</P>
<P>
   Alphahydroxy (AHA) and Betahydroxy (BHA) acids, used over time,
can exfoliate the epidermis, or top layer of your skin, and produce
some clarity, lighten up some sun spots and generally resurface
your skin ... but don't expect too much. The change is gradual and
a lot more subtle than medical procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Your dermatologist can prescribe Retin-A or Renova which, again,
over time, resurfaces your skin. For the first few months, your
skin is dry, patchy, red and hypersensitive to sunshine. And once
you start on a prescribed regimen like this, you should never go
out in the sun again without sunblock on your face and a hat on
your head.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SCREENS VS. BLOCKS
</P>
<P>
   Be sure to note the difference between sunblock and sunscreen.
Sunscreens _ which carry a Sun Protection Factor (SPF) of 2 to 15 _
contain products such as Methoxycinnamate, Octyl Salicylate and
Benzophenone-3 which are sun screens. They filter out the burning
UVB rays but allow enough in to ensure tanning. The higher the SPF
number, the more protection you have.
</P>
<P>
   If a product contains titanium dioxide or Z-cote, transparent
micro-fine zinc oxide like the white stuff lifeguards slather on
their noses, it is a physical sun block, which prevents any UVB ray
from damaging your skin. These are indicated by products which have
SPFs of 20 and higher.
</P>
<P>
   Which is all well and good, if you remember to 1) use a lot of
product and 2) reapply every hour to account for perspiration and
swimming, which can wash it off.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two years, there is a new UBA blocker, Parsol 1789
(Avobenzone), which is in a limited amount of products. Parsol only
screens out UVAs and is known to cause sensitivity in some people,
as did the first sunscreen, PABA or Padimate-O, to which a number
of people have developed sensitivities.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to the sun, respect the power of nature and take
proper steps to protect yourself. Do not sun at high noon when the
sun's rays are the strongest. Use the appropriate sunscreen or
sunblock and reapply often. Wear a hat. Wear a tight-weave,
long-sleeved shirt. And don't pay any attention to some bronzed
supermodel.
</P>
<P>
   Just because they're rich and trendy doesn't mean they're right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
