<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-LAND-GIRLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LAND GIRLS' TILLS ROCKY SOIL IN WWII FARM DRAMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THE LAND GIRLS 
Directed by: David Leland 
Screenplay by: Leland, Peter Prince (novel: Angela Hurth) 
Starring: Catherine McCormack, Rachel Weisz, Anna Friel, Steven
Mackintosh, Tom Georgeson, Maureen O'Brien 
Running time: 110 minutes 
Rated: R (some sexuality) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``The Land Girls,'' writer-director David Leland gets the
hard part right. He richly invokes the wartime 1940s, specifically
life on a British farm where the hastily-recruited Women's Land
Army has been summoned to fill in for the men called to war and
keep the food coming. Skepticism and sexist wisecracks are quickly
silenced by the diligence and competence with which three young
women _ the so-called Land Girls of the title _ from different
backgrounds pitch in and get the job done, often ankle-deep in muck
and manure, and never with any complaining.
</P>
<P>
   From the turbans to the tweed jackets everyone wore to work,
``The Land Girls'' puts you on the farm managed by Tom Georgeson's
crusty patriarch, whose misgivings about the women's abilities
quickly give way to admiration as they keep the farm going,
although with more spirit and independence than he's used to
encountering in his docile wife. Leland, who made his mark as a
director sympathetic to strong women in ``Wish You Were Here,''
skillfully integrates a rather too obviously orchestrated trio of
characters _ Rachel Weisz's cerebral university grad, Anna Friel's
sassy hairdresser, and Catherine McCormack's introspective
romantic, waiting for the war to end so she can marry her naval
officer fiance.
</P>
<P>
   What they share is an attraction to the farmer's grown son,
Steven Mackintosh's Joe, who dreams of being a flier, but never is
called to service because of health problems and the high priority
assigned to keeping the farm running. They each take turns bedding
him, partly out of curiosity and a desire to get their respective
sexual initiations out of the way. Each goes on to other love, some
of it predictably tragic, although one remains emotionally attached
to him _ giving rise to a poignant epilogue. But the characters
seem fuller than the emotional trajectories they're assigned.
</P>
<P>
   In short, ``The Land Girls'' doesn't provide enough story to go
with its superb atmospherics. The harshness of the farm regimen _
and the integrity of that harshness _ is never matched by the
almost slickly mechanical channelings of the Land Girls's emotions.
Weisz, McCormack, and Friel certainly provide enough contour to
establish each of the three as distinct personalities, but the
hoped-for sense of heightened chanciness thrown at young hearts by
the imperatives and chaos of war never materializes. Nor does any
sense of romantic destiny. ``The Land Girls'' looks great and
convinces us it got where it wanted to go, but only geographically.
Emotionally, it's earthbound.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 1313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9073 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-PASSION-BOS &LR;      07-10 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-PASSION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LYRICAL `PASSION' BONDS MAN AND NATURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
PASSION IN THE DESERT 
Directed by: Lavinia Currier 
Screenplay by: Currier, Martin Edmunds (novella: Balzac) 
Starring: Ben Daniels, Michel Piccoli, Paul Meston, Kenneth
Collard, Nadi Odeh, Auda Mohammed Badoul 
Running time: 93 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (violence, including some depictions of barbarism, and
for nudity) 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Passion in the Desert'' is an oddly beautiful little nonesuch
that beats the odds and succeeds as a compelling contemplation of
the distance between man and nature as played out in the
relationship between a soldier and a leopard in the desert. The
story, adapted from a novella by Balzac, rides the fascination of
the French novelist and his age with the exotic,as an officer in
Napoleon's army, cut off from his regiment, finds the trappings of
the Age of Enlightenment stripped away with astonishing haste and
completeness as he's absorbed into the reality of the desert world.
</P>
<P>
   There are a dozen ways in which this film could have gone
ludicrously wrong, but the conviction of writer-director Lavinia
Currier sustains the delicate visual fabric, enhanced no end by the
cinematography of Alexei Rodionov. He takes full advantage of the
hallucinatory possibilities of the displacement experienced by the
strung-out officer, who staggers into a cave on the edge of a
ruined city, a place feared by pursuing bedouins. It's ruled by a
leopard whose presence is first revealed to the fugitive as a
Blakean pair of amber eyes glowing in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of eating the soldier, however, the leopard takes a
shine to him, leads him to water, and even shares its catch. What
follows is at times dreamlike, helped by the necessary absence of
dialogue. That which had gone before, in a prologue with Ben
Daniels's soldier leading a visionary painter played by Michel
Piccoli is not, to put it softly, credibility-enhancing. It helps
that Daniels is lithe enough to get with the crouching and body
language and feline moves he finds himself slipping into as he
enters the leopard's world, sometimes tensely, sometimes
wonderstruck at the animal's unexpected acceptance of him. The film
even succeeds in combining the lyrical and the sensual in a moment
when they touch pleasurably.
</P>
<P>
   It's a brave gamble, brought off. So is the moment when the
soldier can't shed his rational mindset fast enough as he cakes
himself with mud and dabs spots onto himself with a charred stick,
rendering himself leopardlike, recalling the painter's remark that
in the desert a man forgets he even has a name. The receding of
civilization and onset of otherworldly strangeness eclipse one's
marveling at the performance of the leopard (actually three cats
bred for the film) willing to allow the soldier to co-exist, then
cohabit, with it. Eventually, of course, the man must decide
between final immersion in nature or return to civilization. It's
to the film's credit that the ending is both dignified and
believable as Balzac's parable is brought full circle in this
steadily absorbing take on a kind of purity that has all but
vanished from films.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 1315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9075 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-YORKER-BOS &LR;      07-10 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-YORKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAFF FEARS NEW YORKER REVAMP IN WAKE OF BROWN DEPARTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One day after Tina Brown announced she was quitting
her job as editor of The New Yorker, her staffers started worrying
the magazine might soon be pushed into changes as deep and
unnerving as those that Brown herself fostered when she took over
the esteemed publication six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The ``big fear,'' said one longtime senior editor, who asked not
to be identified, is that Conde Nast, the magazine's owner, will
turn the weekly into a biweekly or even a monthly.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be the end of The New Yorker, as we know it,'' the
senior editor said Thursday. Articles would be less timely and
news-breaking _ and there would be far fewer articles, which would
discourage, and may prompt the departure of, its most prolific
writers.
</P>
<P>
   The New Yorker has been in dreadful financial shape for the past
several years _ a state of affairs which an article in this month's
Fortune magazine attributes more to the owners than to the editor.
Brown boosted circulation during her reign from 500,000 to 800,000
_ but, last year alone, the magazine lost $11 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``What worries many of us,'' the senior editor said, ``is that
the problem will be defined as 'too high editorial costs''' _ and
that those costs will then be slashed.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of turning it into a biweekly or monthly has ``been in
the wind for a long time, even before Tina got there,'' the senior
editor said. Brown, the editor said, ``always resisted'' the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Si Newhouse, the 70-year-old billionaire who owns Conde Nast,
paid a rare visit to The New Yorker's offices Thursday morning,
partly to relieve fears.
</P>
<P>
   One staff writer who attended the meeting said Newhouse was
asked whether Draconian cuts would be imposed on the editorial
budget and whether the magazine would go biweekly or monthly.
Newhouse said, ``No,'' to both.
</P>
<P>
   However, one skeptic noted that Newhouse also pledged to keep
then-editor William Shawn onboard when he bought The New Yorker in
1985 _ and then fired him two years later.
</P>
<P>
   Newhouse has not yet chosen a replacement for Brown. He told the
assembled staff members Thursday he would not rush into a decision
but hoped to make an announcement next week.
</P>
<P>
   One Conde Nast insider, who also asked for anonymity, said
Graydon Carter, the editor of Vanity Fair, was called to a meeting
with Newhouse Wednesday evening to discuss the job.
</P>
<P>
   According to the insider, Carter said he would rather stay at
Vanity Fair _ also owned by Conde Nast. Brown was Vanity Fair's
editor _ and transformed that magazine, commercially and otherwise
_ before she joined The New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   Many names have been bandied about as possible replacements, but
some of these named say they have not been contacted by anyone.
Even the rumor-mongers admit nobody really knows who the new editor
will be.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers Thursday noted that Newhouse's meeting with
Carter might suggest little interest in changing the basic
direction of the Brown-era New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, 44, has been hailed and reviled for taking the country's
most serious literary and political magazine and making it more
glitzy, commercial and occasionally sensational.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even some critics concede her magazine is more
consistently interesting than it was under her immediate
predecessor, Robert Gottlieb, and that she cultivated writers _
such as David Remnick, Jeffrey Toobin, Henry Louis Gates, and
Anthony Lane _ who are now considered among the nation's best.
</P>
<P>
   Brown announced Wednesday she will be joining Miramax, the
independent film production company owned by Disney, where she will
run a multi-media enterprise involving a magazine, movies, and
television shows.
</P>
<P>
   The New Yorker's spokeswoman, Maurie Perl, elaborated in an
interview Thursday that Brown's new magazine will be a monthly,
with its first issue slated for the Fall of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The new magazine will up the stakes on a growing ``synergy''
between Hollywood and the publishing world, in which film producers
more and more seek ideas from magazine articles.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there are certain properties from this magazine that will
lend themselves to future film or TV productions,'' Perl said,
``then, before they get optioned or sold to other studios, Miramax
will be in the position to make these deals happen for their own
company.''
</P>
<P>
   However, she emphasized, it ``will be a stand-alone magazine
first,'' just as her New Yorker and Vanity Fair were.
</P>
<P>
   One senior editor at The New Yorker said Thursday that Brown
quit of her own accord and was not about to be pushed out by Conde
Nast. The main factors were the recent death of her mother _ ``one
of those 'life-is-short' epiphanies'' _ and Fortune's recent
article, which ``may have solidified her impession'' that The New
Yorker's financial problems were ``systemic and insolvable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
