<HEADLINE>
TENNIS HALL READIES ROOM FOR THE TWO-FISTED BASHER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes Jimmy Connors' Records text table.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ He swaggered in like an old-time saloon fighter,
letting it be known he could beat any man in the house.
</P>
<P>
   And he did, eight out of every 10 times anyway, over a stretch
of two decades, a two-fisted belterweight whose constant striving
for knockout punches gave tennis the lusty flavor of prizefighting.
That was _ and is _ James Scott Connors, the 45-year-old Brash
Basher from Belleville, who tells you in no uncertain terms: ``I am
not retired.''
</P>
<P>
   Not when he can yet command attention, big bucks and the
respectful handshakes of his prey on the Nuveen geezers circuit,
generally known as the Connors Tour, which comes to Boston Aug. 5.
No, not while he's moonlighting for the Kansas City Explorers of
World Team Tennis.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Jimmy Connors, the icon, agreed to put the Newport Casino
on his dance card for Saturday afternoon. Flying in from Kansas
City after the Explorers' match tonight against Idaho, he'll stick
around long enough to be lionized and canonized at the
International Tennis Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   When recently he was elected to the Hall, there was some concern
that he'd give it a miss as an archrival, Bjorn Borg, did in 1987.
Ever a maverick, not overly fond of tradition or pomp, Connors had
skipped the assemblages of champions at the Wimbledon Centenary of
1977 and the unveiling of Arthur Ashe Stadium last August at the US
Open.
</P>
<P>
   But, jagged edges smoothed considerably, he'll show on
semifinals day of the Miller Hall of Fame tournament. ``Absolutely.
I've never been to Newport, and I'm anxious to see the Hall,'' he
said. ``I'm very honored to go in with the greats.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll be accompanied by wife, Patty, two kids and his determined
mother. Gloria Connors, a good amateur player herself, built a
court in their Belleville, Ill., backyard, and reared her ``Jimbo''
to be a champ of such enduring intensity and accomplishment that he
resided in the pros' planetary top 10 for 16 successive years, No.
1 five straight (1974-78), both records.
</P>
<P>
   In the early years, they were an insular trio _ Jimbo and Gloria
plus manager Bill Riordan _ against the world, usually winning,
relishing their anti-establishment success. Connors turned his back
on the men's union, ATP, and Davis Cup, while turning his withering
double-handed backhand loose to play and win more matches and
tournaments than any other guy ever.
</P>
<P>
   He was one-third of another '70s trio _ with first great love,
Chris Evert, and first great hate, Borg _ who changed the look of
the game. Until them, occasional two-handed backhanders were looked
on as freaks. Today their style is high church orthodoxy.
</P>
<P>
   Of Connors's Everestian 109 singles titles (Pete Sampras, with
55, doesn't even hallucinate about climbing that high), the first
of consequence was taken at Longwood a quarter-century ago. He
arrived, slight of build but ready to conquer. Socks and confidence
high, helmeted in Prince Valiant coiffure, he was twirling that
distinctive lightning rod: the Wilson T2000 steelie with its small
head and big control problems.
</P>
<P>
   No problem for Jimmy. He attacked boldly from the baseline with
it, and responded boldly, too, when he saw that he was not only
unfairly unseeded in the US Pro but scheduled to face world No. 1
Stan Smith in the opening round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have to beat him somewhere, and if I can't do it in the
first round, I don't deserve to win anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Magnetically flinging his wispy self at every ball as though it
were match point, Jimmy beat Smith and two other seeds, climaxing
in his national TV debut with a gritty five-set triumph over No. 5
Ashe. Said Ashe, ``I never played anybody who hit the ball so hard
for so long.''
</P>
<P>
   That seeding injustice and his barring from the French Open the
following year did nothing to improve Jimmy's regard for ``them''
in his them-against-me struggle. His towering 1974 is another
Connors summit unlikely to be scaled: US, Wimbledon, Australian
crowns among 15 titles on a 99-4 match record. Yet he was gallingly
deprived of a shot at a Grand Slam by officious French refusal to
accept his entry.
</P>
<P>
   As a player for the short-lived Baltimore Banners of World Team
Tennis, he was ruled off, victim of now forgotten political strife,
the brief French war against WTT. Though justifiably outraged, he
may have cost himself that major title by boycotting Paris until
1979.
</P>
<P>
   Small town kid, he took to New York like Sherman to Atlanta,
although the Apple adored being baked in his flames. For almost 20
years, Jimmy Connors was the US Open and the US Open was Jimmy
Connors. ``New Yorkers pushed me to my best,'' he says of the love
affair that brought forth five championships in seven finals as
well as seven other semifinal runs. ``I left my blood on that
court, and people knew it.''
</P>
<P>
   There, at Flushing Meadow, the transformation from prickly
upstart to icon began in 1978 as he roused crowds with animated
self-pumping, appealing for their help, literally baying at the
moon and sun. His Forest Hills triumphs at the starchy West Side
Tennis Club, on grass in 1974 and clay in 1976, rankled many
because he struttingly beat the estimable Ken Rosewall and Borg.
</P>
<P>
   But at Flushing he became the man of the people, never more so
than in his Indian Summer performance of 1991. As a lowly ranked
39-year-old wild card he staged a wild charge to the semis,
electrifying the country during a reborn fortnight.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, often put down as a personality-zero champ, concedes,
``No doubt Connors's era had more excitement. You had him, John
McEnroe, Bjorn Borg, Ivan Lendl with different personalities that
stood out _ and they all hated each other. People loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy's epic battles across the world with the other three made
it a rare period. Whether stunning Borg to win the 1977 Masters,
McEnroe in the 1982 Wimbledon finale or Lendl to seize the 1983
Open, he overflowed with an elixir that outweighed the titles,
money and tirades: an undying passion for tennis.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
JIMMY CONNORS' RECORDS &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Most years No. 1 on pro computer: 5 (1974-78), shares with Pete
Sampras &QL; 
Most years in Top Ten: 16 (1973-88) &QL; 
Singles titles: 109, between 1972 (Jacksonville) and 1989
(Israel). &QL; 
Singles tournaments played: 401 &QL; 
Singles matches played: 1,622 &QL; 
Singles matches won: 1,337 &QL; 
Singles matches won at US Open: 98 &QL; 
Singles matches won at Wimbledon: 84 &QL; 
Highest lifetime won-lost percentage: .824, 1,337-285.(1) &QL; 
 &QL; 
(1)Following Connors: Bjorn Borg (.814), Ivan Lendl (.805), John
McEnroe (.788), Sampras (.787). &QL; 
Source: Bud Collins &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
