<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-THURAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCORING NEVER REALLY HAS BEEN THURAM'S GOAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The craziest thing is that the man never scores.
(itals)Jamais.(unitals) ``Even during training, I don't score,''
says Lilian Thuram.
</P>
<P>
   Until Wednesday night, Thuram had played 37 soccer matches for
France and never produced a goal. He scored eight in six seasons
with Monaco, just one in three seasons with Parma. When coach Aime
Jacquet sent five men to the penalty spot for the quarterfinal
shootout with Italy, Thuram wasn't among them. ``Not my thing,'' he
shrugs.
</P>
<P>
   Thuram is a central defender, one of the best in the world. An
impeder, a disrupter, a preventer. Yet now, because he scored two
improbable and glorious goals to beat Croatia and put France into
Sunday's World Cup final for the first time, ``Thuthu'' has become
a demigod.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates hoisted Thuram on their shoulders on the floor of
the Stade de France. Along the boulevards and quais of the city, as
horns honked and firecrackers popped, celebrants chanted his name.
Le Monde and Le Figaro had his photo on their front pages. Even
Jacques Chirac singled him out for special tribute.
``Extraordinaire,'' the French president proclaimed,
(itals)``Vraiment formidable.''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens against the Brazilians in the final, Les
Bleus have already made history, have already brought le reve, the
dream, to life and touched off the most exuberant celebration in
the City of Light since the Liberation. And the 26-year-old Thuram,
who grew up playing the game on the black sand of Guadeloupe's
beaches in the Caribbean, is the unlikely architect of triumph.
``It's a wonderful thing,'' he said. ``I can't get over it. But
just because I scored two goals doesn't make me a hero.''
</P>
<P>
   For one terrible minute against the Croats, Thuram was the bobo,
who forgot to get back in time and watched from the wrong side of
the field as Davor Suker dashed in unbothered and scored 25 seconds
into the second half. And then, barely after the replay had been
shown, his gaffe in slow motion from five angles for the entire
world, Thuram produced a better one.
</P>
<P>
   Picking off a lateral pass from Zvonimir Boban 30 meters from
the Croatian goal, Thuram slipped the ball to Youri Djorkaeff, then
dashed behind the defense on a give-and-go and slammed home
Djorkaeff's return from the spot. Twenty-two minutes later, Thuram
came back for the coup de grace, stripping Robert Jarni of the ball
and firing it to the far corner before keeper Drazen Ladic could
react.
</P>
<P>
   It was the (itals)demi-heure,(unitals) the half hour, of a
lifetime and it left Thuram on his knees, stunned. ``In general,
when I'm in the attack zone, I'm not good,'' he admitted. ``I was
200 percent lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Thuram never scores because he's not supposed to. He's strictly
a rear-guard guy, a defender whom teammates, rivals and
connoisseurs appreciate more than the public does. ``He's the best
in the world at his position,'' says Croatian midfielder Mario
Stanic, who plays alongside Thuram in Parma.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Thuram is playing out of position for France, outside on the
right where he's actually been set free to explore space, to become
who he used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Thuram, whom the French consider the best athlete ever to play
for Les Bleus, was an attacker when he first began playing for
Portugais de Fontainebleau in the Paris suburbs, scoring four goals
in his first match. ``For me, to be a defender was unthinkable,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   When Nice put him there, Thuram told himself it wasn't possible.
When Monaco kept him there, Thuram committed errors on purpose. ``I
wanted to prove that I was a danger to them back there,'' he told
L'Equipe, the French sporting daily. ``But I quickly learned that I
didn't have the right to weaken the team to suit myself. In life,
you must be happy with what you have and not demand what people
don't want to give you.''
</P>
<P>
   So Thuram settled in at central defender for the Monegasques,
went to Parma in Italy's Serie A two years ago and quickly earned a
reputation as one of the league's top foreigners. He was Le
Parmesan now, living in an old and graceful city which made him
feel as if time had stopped.
</P>
<P>
   His roots, though, were still in Guadeloupe, where Thuram had
lived without a father with four siblings while his mother
Christiane worked as a maid in the 16th arrondissement here to earn
the plane fare to bring the children over. Thuthu had wanted to be
a priest. ``Because in the Antilles, the priest is a hero,'' he
once said. ``He represents strength and wisdom. He counsels the
good road.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the 10-year-old Thuram got to France, realized that priests
couldn't have children, and switched vocations. FIFA, which runs
soccer worldwide, requires players to keep their shirts tucked in,
but does not insist upon celibacy.
</P>
<P>
   So Thuram became a (itals)pur defenseur,(unitals) until French
national coach Aime Jacquet moved him to right back with freedom to
indulge his craving for open space. Nobody said anything about
scoring and for the first three matches, when France piled up nine
goals, nobody was asking the defenders to do anything more than
defend.
</P>
<P>
   But by halftime of Wednesday's semifinal, after Les Bleus had
managed just one goal in their last 313 minutes, they were
desperate for someone to step up, to do something (iteals)vraiment
formidable.(unitals) So Thuram came front and center, sticking out
his endless legs twice to filch balls and creating, in a
(itals)demi-heure(unitals) something France had been fantasizing
about for 68 years.
</P>
<P>
   When it was done, and he'd come back to earth from shoulder
height, France's improbable hero ran to the locker room, wiping
away tears. ``To play in the World Cup is a kid's dream,'' Lilian
Thuram said. ``And if it ends as you dream it, you never have to
wake up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
