<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYBODY'S IN ON THE FUN BUT THE UNITED STATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I don't know about you, but I have a fairly simple rating system
for a sporting event.
</P>
<P>
   Would I really, really, really want to be there, or would I
prefer to sit home with a good book and a preferred CD?
</P>
<P>
   I am not a soccer buff. I am neither a soccer lover nor a soccer
hater. In my mind, I could improve it, but I've always said the
same thing about hockey. (That's ice, as opposed to field, about
which I have no opinion). But even in its curiously flawed state,
there is a lot to be said for it. The World Cup is the ultimate
forum, and so, yes, dammit, I am very envious of my distinguished
colleagues John Powers and Frank Dell'Apa because they are there
and I am here.
</P>
<P>
   In vast overwhelming numbers, my fellow Americans just don't
care. Since it is not about us, or for us, or particularly friendly
to us, we US folks are not interested. The USA team flamed out in
three games, returning home amid a smidgen of controversy
concerning who played and who didn't, and whether or not the coach
could or should survive. The American public at large quickly got
over losing to Iran, and two weeks later not one American in 1,000
could tell you who Eric Wynalda or Steve Sampson is. It is almost
as if the 1994 World Cup never happened.
</P>
<P>
   Major American newspapers cover the World Cup, but we are
decades away from justifying a Sunday London Times-style 64-page
magazine preview that included, among other things, a
heavily-diagrammed four-page rating of the all-time Top Ten World
Cup goals. In case you are interested, Diego Maradona's 1986
astounding dash through practically the entire English team (as
opposed to the controversial ``Hand of God'' goal in the very same
game) was rated No. 1 by the 62-member panel of experts.
</P>
<P>
   We are quite happy pursuing our own parochial interests, and the
fact is we have more of them than any other country on this earth.
Most countries are lucky to have one decent football league, but
we've got highly organized and historically relevant leagues in
baseball, football, basketball and hockey, not to mention the
50-year-old NASCAR circuit and various other forms of automobile
racing, which are currently attracting more spectators than
anything, for reasons which will forever escape many of us.
</P>
<P>
   The above, of course, is just the beginning. We have the
largest, most diverse sports smorgasbord imaginable, so why does it
matter if we are not major players in the world of FIFA?
</P>
<P>
   Because we're missing out on all the fun, that's why.
</P>
<P>
   France is a reasonably reserved country. It spends a great
percentage of its time fending off the old ennui. The French are
difficult to please. Not unlike us, they like what they like and
are very happy to take a pass on everything else. What they really
like is cycling. The unquestioned No. 1 sporting event in France is
the Tour de France. To have the Tour pass through your village is
an unimaginable thrill. They have a first-rate soccer/football
league, but their passion for the sport in no way rivals that of
neighboring Spain or Italy, just to name two.
</P>
<P>
   But now there is no other topic in France but its football team,
which will play Brazil Sunday for the championship. The nation is
galvanized. Every cafe is Rick's, and everyone is getting misty
singing ``La Marseilleise'' while toasting the crafty Zinedine
Zidane (and we thought the only ol' Double Z we'd ever know would
be Zarley Zalapski) or the fearless goalkeeper Fabien Barthez. The
country is united in its passion for a team many of them were
ignoring a fortnight ago.
</P>
<P>
   It's harmless fun.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, people can take this stuff too seriously. Did
England's David Beckham deserve to be referred to in one London
tabloid headline as a ``Stupid Boy'' because he was sent off the
pitch with a red card during England's painful loss to Argentina?
Should the entire country of Croatia be plunged into mourning
because they were ousted from the competition by France two days
ago? We know the answers.
</P>
<P>
   But what is wrong with a little national caring? We in America
have no true bonding national interests, and when we actually had
one _ the original Dream Team _ it was dismissed by some as being
uninteresting because it was too good. Our No. 1 sport is football,
and no one else, aside from a few hearty Canadians, plays it. Not
enough people care about hockey to make that a point of true
national pride. We have never been able to make up our minds what
we want and expect from our various national basketball teams. A
true national baseball team might produce some talk if it had the
opportunity to play a seven-game series against a Latin American
counterpart, but the results wouldn't even make the agate in Paris,
Riyadh or Harare.
</P>
<P>
   There really is nothing to bring us together. The World Series
used to, but no longer. Back when the networks had a 90-95 percent
share, it seemed as if Everybody watched the World Series, ``The Ed
Sullivan Show,'' the Miss America Pageant, the Rose Bowl and ``I
Love Lucy.'' And we could always stand around together and curse
the Commies. Now you can watch the Food Channel or the X-Games. We
don't get together to celebrate anything. We don't even vote.
</P>
<P>
   There is only one sport that brings planet earth to the same
mental sporting arena, and that is soccer, er, football. The idea
that people staged protests in Bangladesh (which won't qualify for
the Cup in the next thousand years) because the power went off
during televised World Cup games is, well, charming. We know they
are watching in China. We know they are watching all over Africa,
South America and Asia. We also know not very many are watching in
America.
</P>
<P>
   There is only one sport that will ever enable us to take part in
the fun, and that sport is soccer. There is something very
intrinsically important about caring. It is why we are so haunted
by the 1918 business here. It's silly. It's stupid. It shouldn't
matter, but it does.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true in this World Cup business. America would
benefit from some communal caring. We could make do with a little
stranger-hugging over a Golden Goal.
</P>
<P>
   More than a billion people will be watching the game on Sunday.
Now that's a stage. I would dearly love to be either a Frenchman or
Brazilian for the next four days.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
