<SLUG> BC-ONADVERTISING-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REEBOK CAMPAIGN FINDS JUSTICE DOUGLAS A GOOD FIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reebok International Ltd. has a new copy writer for its sneaker
ads _ the late William O. Douglas, a former US Supreme Court
justice known for his defense of individual liberties.
</P>
<P>
   The voiceover for a new Reebok ad is taken from a speech Douglas
wrote for a 1976 bar association meeting.
</P>
<P>
   In it, Douglas warned young lawyers to remain vigilant against
totalitarian threats.
</P>
<P>
   In the ad, Douglas's words seem to allude to Reebok's footwear
rivals, which Stoughton-based Reebok portrays as fashion purveyors
of oppressive conformity in contrast to its emphasis on
individuality, empowerment, and performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``As nightfall does not come all at once, neither does
oppression,'' says the voiceover, slightly paraphrasing from a
speech that Douglas was too ill to deliver in person. ``It is in
such twilight that we all must be aware of change in the air,
however slight, lest we become victims of the darkness.''
</P>
<P>
   Berlin Cameron &AMP; Partners, the New York agency that created the
ad, had been writing another script for the ad's voiceover.
</P>
<P>
   But when someone at the agency found a copy of the Douglas
speech, Reebok said it decided to get permission from the Douglas
estate to use excerpts from it.
</P>
<P>
   The words of Douglas ``really multiplied the effectiveness'' of
Reebok's message, says Ewen Cameron, the ad agency's creative
director.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we heard it,'' says Reebok's Dave Fogelson, ``everyone
said, `Whoa! This is a perfect fit.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Reebok ad is likely to be first encountered on movie screens
rather than on TV screens.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer, the young consumers who buy the most sneakers are
more often found in theaters rather than in front of TV sets
watching reruns. So Reebok is going where its customers are.
</P>
<P>
   In the United Kingdom, ads in movie theaters have a long
tradition, says Cameron, a Scotsman.
</P>
<P>
   With fewer TV stations in the United Kingdom, there are fewer
opportunities to advertise in other countries. Now movie
advertising is becoming more prevalent in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   For a long time, though, many ads in US movie theaters were
``appalling, with very low production values,'' Cameron says.
</P>
<P>
   That's beginning to change, in part because of numbers.
</P>
<P>
   According to Sheila Wyle, director of advertising at Cineplex
Odeon Corp., 105 million Americans went to the movies last year.
</P>
<P>
   To weed out appalling ads, the chain imposes tough standards on
what it allows to be shown on its 856 movie screens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't accept anything that has already run on TV,'' Wyle
says. ``We want only work that is fresh and creative.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans go to theaters to get away from TV and TV
advertising,'' Cameron says.
</P>
<P>
   But if the ads are spectacular and on par with the special
effects used in most summer blockbusters, even an American movie
audience will be receptive to an ad's message, he says.
</P>
<P>
   In the hopes of not irritating paying customers, Cineplex Odeon
shows no more than three ads before a movie.
</P>
<P>
   Most TV ads tend to be 30 seconds long. At the movies, many ads
last 60 or 90 seconds. So long as an ad premieres in a theater, a
shorter version may later be shown on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the insistence on high quality, only the largest
companies, such as Levi's, AT&AMP;T, and Reebok, find it feasible to
advertise at the movies, Wyle says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A new ad from Dunkin' Donuts opens at a city construction site.
It's a hot summer day, and suddenly the workers start emitting
appreciative grunts and other macho noises.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not the hubba-hubba blonde strolling by the work site
that's got the lads in a lather _ it's the return of a worker from
a Dunkin' Donuts with a tray of Coffee Coolattas.
</P>
<P>
   The work is the first from Dunkin' Donuts' new ad agency, Hill
Holliday Connors Cosmopulos of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The first ads from Hill Holliday weren't supposed to appear
until the fall, but Dunkin' Donuts, based in Randolph, Mass., was
apparently so disappointed with the Coolatta ads from its previous
agency that Hill Holliday wound up coming to the rescue.
</P>
</TEXT>
