<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9105 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-BROTHERS-2TAKES-     07-10 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BROTHERS-2TAKES-$ADV12-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEB BUSH, LIKE HIS BROTHER, FINDS THE RIGHT TOUCH WITH DEMOCRATS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, July 12) 
(See optional ending) 
 
By KIM COBB 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Four years ago, speculating about two Bush
brothers winning their races for governor was just a political day
dream. Conventional wisdom gave Jeb Bush a shot at winning Florida,
but the pundits said George W. Bush was unlikely to unseat Ann
Richards in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Today, George W. is the popular governor of Texas and poised to
capture a second term. Polls show that brother Jeb, who lost his
first race, is so far ahead in the Florida governor's race that
people are joking about the start of a Bush political dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   But what makes the Bush brothers worth watching this time around
is less their family name than the new standard they are setting
for Republican candidates to court traditionally Democratic
minority voters.
</P>
<P>
   Jeb Bush, 45, joked about his attempts to woo Democrats at a
recent campaign appearance. He described a visit he paid to a
towering Broward County condominium enclave of mostly retired
Jewish Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may have been the first Republican allowed into that village
of 15,000,'' Jeb Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush does not expect to make serious inroads among what Florida
calls its ``condo Democrats.'' Bush lost Broward County by a huge
margin in 1994 despite a narrow loss statewide. He is determined
not to let it happen again.
</P>
<P>
   Jeb Bush also is capitalizing on a nasty schism between the
state Democratic Party's black and white leadership to court black
voters who may stay angry enough to vote Republican if he makes
himself accessible enough.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 20 percent of Florida's voters are black. Because Jeb
Bush only lost the 1994 governor's race by 64,000 votes, even a
small shift in the black vote could be important in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is campaigning in some of Florida's poorest black
neighborhoods as enthusiastically as he trolls for votes among the
moneyed, white country club set.
</P>
<P>
   This is the same Jeb Bush who, when asked in 1994 what he would
do for black voters, glibly answered, ``Probably nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people say Jeb has changed, most publicly by his conversion
to Catholicism, his wife's religion. Others say the narrow 1994
loss taught Bush how to win.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his associates says there's truth in both camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``And frankly, he's more prepared this time,'' says Houston
political consultant David Hill, who worked on Jeb Bush's campaign
four years ago. ``No matter how much you do, say, for Dad, that's
not the same as campaigning for yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he had to mature in that role as the candidate, not
just the (former president's) son. You see that in his speaking
style, even in the way he works the room,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that I think has changed in my ideological
framework ... is that in '94 I was focusing on how do we
institutionalize the limitations of government,'' &UR;  &LR; Bush said &UR; .
 &LR; ``I've been involved in a lot of different things between '94 and
'98 and it led me to believe the better approach is how do you
identify policies that lessen the demand on government.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a subtle, but pretty profoundly different approach,'' Jeb
Bush said, then paraphrased his father's campaign remark after
Republicans were criticized for veering too far to the right:
``Because of that it may sound kinder and gentler.''
</P>
<P>
   He also talks a lot about the lessons he has learned working
with a charter school he helped establish in Liberty City, a deeply
impoverished black neighborhood in Miami. The charter school was
funded by Bush's Foundation for Florida's Future, a public policy
organization funded by many political friends of his father and
Texas brother. The foundation also kept his name in the news
between elections.
</P>
<P>
   He now calls for ``putting aside party labels'' and building a
statewide education system strong enough to lessen the demand on
government by creating better, more self sufficient citizens. When
told he sounds like a conservative Democrat, Jeb Bush laughs and
says, ``Well, they're voting for me, too.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jeb Bush will also say, quite candidly, that circumstances
are allowing him to run a different campaign this time around. He
started the primary season in 1994 with five strong, extremely
conservative GOP opponents. To win that primary, he took as his
running mate an anti-abortion rights conservative and positioned
himself as far right as he could get.
</P>
<P>
   But his primary-season posture was unpalatable to moderate
Republicans and swing voters and cost him a November victory. And
when incumbent Gov. Lawton Chiles launched 11th-hour attacks on Jeb
Bush, people tended to believe them.
</P>
<P>
   This time, he is unopposed for the GOP nomination in the Sept. 1
primary.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the money.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was not underfunded in his last race, but he's
jet-propelled in 1998 after a huge infusion of Texas money, thanks
to the political connections of his father, former President George
Bush, and his brother George W.
</P>
<P>
   Texans had donated $372,000 to Jeb Bush's campaign and another
$455,000 to the Florida Republican Party by the end of the spring
campaign reporting period. The largest Texas donor, Hushang Ansary
of Houston, gave $100,000 to the GOP, and his company, IRI
International, donated another $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Under Florida law, candidates cannot accept donations of more
than $500 from any individual, but there is no cap on donations to
political parties.
</P>
<P>
   With those benefits, Jeb Bush says he can follow his instincts
this time, to take his message ``to places where Republicans don't
go.''
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, Gov. George W. Bush appears to be listening to the
same muse, if not reacting to exactly the same set of
circumstances, as he courts Texas' Hispanic vote with a strong
defense of bilingual education, opposition to military patrols of
the U.S. border with Mexico, and a pitch for improved education.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of Hispanics in our state who are learning the
power of voting,'' George W. Bush told reporters at the recent
League of United Latin American Citizens annual convention. ``And
you bet it's going to make a difference in campaigns in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to mean an enormous difference in the future, and I
think it's important for both parties to pay attention to the
Hispanic vote and Hispanic concerns,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Candidates such as myself must go out and go to the barrios
and knock on the doors and campaign, and that's exactly what I
intend to do,`` the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Texas brother, 52, had some advice for other Republicans
eager for support from historically Democratic Hispanic voters:
``First and foremost I think what Republicans should say is I want
your vote (and) I've got a plan that's optimistic and hopeful for
you.'' George W. Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing in Florida, Jeb Bush is selling himself to all voters as
a man with ``a hopeful, optimistic agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   But his pitch to black voters, who recent polls indicate are
giving him double-digit support, is putting Florida Democrats on
notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``To decide that is a constituency that not only Republicans
could win over, but he could win over, most people thought he was
crazy,'' said Jim Kane, pollster and editor of Florida Voter
magazine. ``It's turned out to be rather insightful, and perhaps
due to a certain amount of luck.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, Willie Logan, an African-American, was dumped as the
Democratic leader in the Florida House of Representatives, and
replaced by white legislator Ann MacKenzie. Party leaders claimed
Logan hadn't been doing his job, but black Democrats took it as a
racially motivated slap in the face.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Willie Logan situation was manna from heaven'' for Bush,
says U.S. Rep. Alcee Hastings. The Florida Democrat is threatening
to shift his support to Republican candidates and take other
disenchanted black voters with him if the state's Democratic
hierarchy does not apologize for its treatment of Logan.
</P>
<P>
   Hastings said Jeb Bush seized on the opportunity created by
Logan's ouster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typical of situations like that, he was in the right place at
the right time,'' Hastings said. &UR;  &LR; ``Added to that is the new
situation of blacks who don't have the history with the civil
rights movement. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Hastings says he is ``no defender of Jeb Bush,'' but he's
obviously intrigued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both the Bush brothers are seemingly mindful that they cannot
conduct business as their Dad did and expect to be national
leaders,'' Hastings said. ``What their Dad did was immoral,''
Hastings said, referring to Bush's decision not to denounce a
campaign ad made on his behalf that used a picture of black felon
Willie Horton as a scare tactic in his 1988 presidential campaign
against Michael Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're serious about the business of wanting to correct
those mistakes, they'll do what George W. is doing with Hispanics
and what Jeb is doing with black and Jewish voters,'' Hastings
said.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just the Florida governor's mansion at stake here.
State Democrats worry that if too many jump ship in this election,
they'll keep jumping when it comes time to vote in the 2000
presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of having Jeb Bush in a position to deliver Florida
votes to his brother should George W. decide to run for president,
makes Florida Democratic Party Chairman Mitch Caesar nervous. He
suspects many of the Texas donations to Jeb Bush's campaign and the
Florida GOP are really intended to help the older brother carry the
third most populous state in the United States in a bid for the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would anyone in Texas want to give money to Florida?
Obviously, it's his brother,'' Caesar said. ``They're playing
politics with Florida's future.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill says he doubts most donors are thinking strategically
enough to tie dollars for Jeb to the presidency for George W.
</P>
<P>
   ``While they're brothers, and both Republicans, I think they
operate in their own circles and worlds,'' Hill said. ``I know four
years ago people always suspected somehow the campaigns were
running in tandem. It's not true.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Florida Democrats also are complaining loudly about the Texas
donations, many of them from the oil industry, to play to
Floridians' concerns about the environment and their adamant
opposition to offshore drilling. ``Everyone is suspicious,`` Caesar
says.
</P>
<P>
   Kane said he thought Jeb Bush would eventually regret taking the
Texas money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeb has come out and said he's against drilling off the coast,
but saying it and taking the money _ people are skeptical of
politicians to begin with and they may not believe his campaign
rhetoric.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Democrats in Florida don't understand brotherly love
then they better reassess their emotions,'' responded the Texas
governor. ``I help my brother because he is my brother. If he asked
for help, I'm more than willing to help him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This business about how because of Texas he's going to somehow
change his position on offshore drilling in Florida just goes to
show they have no idea how he thinks,'' George W. Bush said,
``because Jeb is going to do what he says he is going to do, and
he's going to be a great governor.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeb Bush said he sought the Texas contributions, in part,
because he's not taking government money to fund his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Secondly, the amount of oil money, whatever amount that was,
was a small fraction of what was raised overall,'' Jeb Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the oil money is more than a ``small fraction.''
Ansary, the biggest Texas donor, heads a large, Houston-based
company that manufactures oil and gas rigs _ including offshore
rigs. The combined contribution of $150,000 to the Florida GOP from
Ansary and IRI adds up to nearly one-fifth of the Texas money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's completely idiosyncratic to the Bush brothers _
this is a very unusual situation,'' said Larry Makinson, executive
director for the Center for Responsive Politics in Washington. ``I
can tell you that (nearly) $850,000 traveling from Texas to Florida
is extraordinary _ there's no question, and it's clearly related to
the relationship between the two brothers and the potential for
higher office for George.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Donors flock,'' Makinson said. ``There's a certain logic for
contributors from Texas or anywhere, who want to make a good
impression on brother George to give to brother Jeb _ especially if
they knew Papa George.``
</P>
<P>
   The Bush family has a pretty golden touch with the donor
community, Makinson said, ``and they're taking full advantage of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
