<P>
   NAACP NATIONAL CONVENTION
</P>
<P>
   NAACP-MAIN _ ATLANTA _ Advance story on opening day of the
convention, including comments from Johnnie Cochran's Friday
speech. (RHill, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15-18.
</P>
<P>
   NAACP-FARMERS _ ATLANTA _ Advance on what USDA Secretary Dan
Glickman will tell the nation's oldest civil rights group what he
is doing to help save black farmers and farmland. He may be well
received by the NAACP delegates, but farmers will look at him with
a jaundiced eye. The challenges he faces are many, but his crivil
rights spokesman says that he can stand the test. (PScott, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 8.
</P>
<P>
   NBAF-CHOICE _ National Congress of Black Conservatives hold news
conference to challenge NAACP to reverse its position opposing
school choice. (Cumming, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY _ State Board of Education considers proposal to sell off
$43 million worth of Disney stock. Some board members are unhappy
with the company's not-for-the- kiddies movies. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-SHOOTINGS _ The body count is rising along the border is
immigrants trying to skirt the Border Patrol checkpoint south of
Corpus Christi end up dying from the heat. (Harmon, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   FIREFIGHTERS _ Greg Weston, a sheriff's deputy, has been one of
the President Clinton praised Thursday who has been fighting
wildfires for the past month in Flagler County, Florida. He's one
of hundreds of people in Flagler County who have gone above and
beyond the call of duty in the past month in this rural county.
(Nesmith, CoxNews Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   US-RUSSIA _ MOSCOW _ U.S. President Bill Clinton and Russian
President Boris Yeltsin had made no secret over the last several
months that they would like to have a summit in the fall. As
Clinton wound down his long trip to China, the word began spreading
that he was leaning toward just such a meeting. After confirming it
on Monday, the White House can expect a wave of criticism from
opponents near the level it received before the China trip. There's
plenty of ammunition: the sickly Russian economy; Kosovo upheaval;
India-Pakistan nuclear race; trade with Iran; NATO expansion; and
space cooperation. Clinton had been awaiting Russia's Parliament to
ratify the SALT II nuclear arms pact, but his decision to go seems
to be aimed at pressuring the Duma into such a ratification vote.
(Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With US-RUSSIA-BOX _ The issues facing a Clinton-Yeltsin summit.
(Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thursday, July 9.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-PEACE _ WASHINGTON _ Israel's U.N. ambassador Dore Gold
reaffirmed Thursday that Israel views this week's U.N. General
Assembly vote to grant the Palestinians' U.N. delegation nearly the
same rights as those given independent states as ``largely
symbolic.'' Speaking to a Democratic group here on a wide range of
Israeli issues, Gold said the U.N. vote -- which passed ov
overwhelmingly -- represents ``no effective change'' in the PLO
status at the United Nations. Gold's remarks came a day before
Palestinian negotiators were set to arrive in Washington on Friday
for talks with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
(Abulhassan, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   USCHINA _ The congressional investigation of satellite exports
to China is likely to expand outside Loral Space and Communications
and Hughes Electronics. At the urging of folks like Henry Sokolski,
head of monitoring nuclear proliferation at the Pentagon during the
Bush Administration, the select committee that Gingrich appointed
will look at defense and makers of other high-tech equipment such
as Lockheed Martin and Motorola to see if national security was put
at risk. Since Georgia is such a big defense state, what does the
delegation views on the investigations. What do the companies think
about the investigations? (Carr, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NIH _ WASHINGTON _ In the middle of fights over campaign
finances, tobacco legislation and other bones of contention,
President Clinton, House Speaker Newt Gingrich, the Senate
Republican leaders and congressional Democrats all agree on a
fairly major initiative: that the research budget of the National
Institutes of Health should be dramatically increased, even doubled
over the next decade. To officials at Emory University in Atlanta,
which hopes to propel itself into one of the ``top 10'' research
institutions in the country during that time, this is welcome news.
The University of Texas, Eastern Carolina University and other
universitities around the country are also thrilled at the prospect
of easier access to what is already the largest pool of research
money in the world, by a factor of 10. Why is this idea suddenly so
popular? There are several theories, including the fact that
politicians sense that meaningful medical breakthroughs lie just
ahead and the aging of the politically powerful Baby Boomers, who
are now reaching the stage in life where their own health has
replaced earlier concerns. (Nesmith, Cox News Service).
</P>
