<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATIONSBANK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINES DRAWN OVER MERGER OF NATIONSBANK, BANKAMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD IWATA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Federal Reserve Bank here was pelted with
testimony about the planned merger of San Francisco's venerable
BankAmerica Corp. and NationsBank Corp. of North Carolina, a deal
some consumer groups believe could threaten lending to minority and
lower-income neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   More than 300 people were scheduled to testify in hearings
Thursday and Friday in a plain conference room at the Federal
Reserve Bank. On the opening day, hand-painted banners lined the
walls, bearing messages such as, ``Keep my money in California,''
and ``Say no to the merger.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the $60 billion merger proposal, Charlotte-based
NationsBank would become BankAmerica, but the merged bank's
headquarters would move from San Francisco to North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Announced in April, the merger would create a bank with $570
billion in assets and 29 million customers.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony was a two-way street.
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank and its supporters flew in elderly folks, low-income
home buyers and small-business people to testify.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without NationsBank's help, I would have lost my home,'' said
Ginnie McNab, 70, a retired hospital employee who was approved for
a $75,000 mortgage at 6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents speaking Thursday were poised for a battle, but
acknoweleged the merger was destined for approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a street fight _ we'll close NationsBank down,'' said
Mario Obledo of the California Coalition of Hispanic Organizations.
</P>
<P>
   BankAmerica has been a corporate institution in San Francisco
for nearly a century, since it was founded in North Beach by
Italian immigrant A.P. Giannini.
</P>
<P>
   Some officials fear the merger will lead to thousands of lost
jobs, poorer service for consumers and a reduction in loans and
investment for low-income and minority neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the merger proposal, NationsBank and BankAmerica
announced a record $350 billion commitment over 10 years for
nationwide community lending. The plan includes $180 billion for
small businesses, $115 billion for affordable housing, $25 billion
for economic development and $30 billion for consumer loans.
</P>
<P>
   BankAmerica has enjoyed a reputation as its industry's pioneer
and leader in community lending over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: BankAmerica executives have placed a high priority
on serving women and minorities, small businesses and people in
low- to moderate-income areas.
</P>
<P>
   But politicians and community groups fear that NationsBank,
which will run the new bank, may neglect its community investments
in California _ despite NationsBank's strong lending record in
other parts of the country. Studies suggest local community lending
tails off when a bank moves its headquarters to another region.
</P>
<P>
   In weighing bank mergers, the Fed must look at the banks'
community lending records. Banks are required under the 1977
Community Reinvestment Act to provide loans and capital in all
neighborhoods in which they have branches.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators have never killed a major bank merger on these
grounds, although a handful of smaller deals have been stopped.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed, the Justice Department and the Treasury Department are
expected to sign off on the proposed BankAmerica-NationsBank merger
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Leading off the Fed hearing Thursday were NationsBank Chairman
Hugh McColl and the head of BankAmerica, Dave Coulter.
</P>
<P>
   ``My company has been through many mergers over the past 20
years,'' McColl said. ``We have found _ almost universally _ that
employment, lending, community development efforts and charitable
contributions actually increase. This has been our vision, and will
continue to be so with this merger.''
</P>
<P>
   Coulter added, ``I can assure you that BankAmerica has brought
unparalleled commitment to the communities we serve. The new
BankAmerica will continue in this manner, but on a much larger
scale than ever before.''
</P>
<P>
   Merger foes _ led by San Francisco Supervisor Mark Leno, the
Greenlining Institute and the California Reinvestment Committee _
urged that concrete financial promises to California be part of the
merger proposal before the Fed.
</P>
<P>
   Every major bank merger in California since 1992 has had
community lending agreements added to the Fed applications, said
Alan Fisher of the California Reinvestment Committee.
</P>
<P>
   If the new BankAmerica refuses to set firm lending goals in the
Golden State, the community groups threatened to steer consumers to
other banks.
</P>
<P>
   Merger opponents also said they could delay the merger for
several months, costing the banks millions of dollars. But they
conceded they don't have the legal or political firepower to derail
the merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know the merger is going to be approved,'' said Kevin
Williams of the San Francisco Human Rights Commission. ``This
merger was approved on the golf course. This deal has already been
cut, and we've been cut out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
