<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SOLDIERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SOLDIERS' CAPTURES SUMMER ACTION PRIZE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
SMALL SOLDIERS 
Directed by: Joe Dante 
Screenplay by: Gavin Scott, Adam Rifkin, Ted Elliott, Terry Rossio 
Starring: Kirsten Dunst, Gregory Smith, Jay Mohr, Phil Hartman,
Kevin Dunn, David Cross, Ann Magnuson, Denis Leary, Wendy Schaal,
with the voices of Tommy Lee Jones, Frank Langella, Ernest
Borgnine, Jim Brown, Bruce Dern, George Kennedy, Sarah Michelle
Gellar, Christina Ricci 
Running time: 109 minutes  
Rated: PG-13 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Small Soldiers'' is the summer's cleverest package of sizzle
yet. It's a toy story with attitude, a high-tech ``Gremlins''
driven by an army of attack toys that opens fire on human gamesters
after real battlefield technology is built into their microchips.
Bloodthirsty little cyberdevils, they explode from their boxes
dressed in commando gear, bulging with molded muscle, plastic faces
sculpted into macho sneers. It's up to a couple of kids _ Gregory
Smith and Kirsten Dunst _ to get these particular genies back into
the bottle, or, failing that, to destroy them before they vaporize
the storybook Ohio suburb where the mayhem unfolds.
</P>
<P>
   The film hits a hip note of tongue-in-cheek mock outrage as it
peddles crazed, soulless high-tech aggressiveness, while pretending
to send a message deploring it. As Denis Leary's cynical honcho of
the conglomerate that owns the toy company puts it, ``Don't call it
violence, call it action.'' In case anyone misses the point,
Leary's character is named Mars, as in the god of war. It won't be
giving away too much to reveal that a key computer password is
gizmo. Certainly the gizmos keep the pot boiling here, behaving
like evil clones of G.I. Joe. What's terrifying about them is their
resourcefulness. With nightmarish rapidity, they keep throwing
lethal transformations of household objects _ toasters, dish
antennas, nail guns _ at the humans and the good dolls.
</P>
<P>
   The latter, called Gorgons, are a noble race whose appearance is
grotesque, but whose souls are gentle. They're headed by a
lion-like leader voiced with sonorous dignity by Frank Langella. He
and the Gorgons personify a longing for the natural world of wood,
boats, forests, waterfalls, and bows and arrows as opposed to
high-tech zap. Evoking such previous antitechnology races as the
Hobbits and the ``Planet of the Apes'' denizens, they have their
human analog, especially Kevin Dunn as the back-to-the-simple-life
father of the kid played by Smith, whose Sorcerer's Apprentice ways
open the door to the mischief. Dunst puts a nice fearless edge on
her character and amusingly embraces her teen banality rather than
apologizing for it.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, played by the late Phil Hartman in his final movie
role, adds to the entertainment quotient as a caricature of a
boorish gadget freak. Her taste backfires amusingly when her
roomful of inhumanly slender Wendy (read Barbie) dolls is
transformed into a nasty girl gang who get turned on by the
soldiers and are inclined to tie people up by tying them down, as
the Lilliputians did to Gulliver. The computer graphics and effects
wizards certainly keep things popping. Joe Dante, who directed
``Gremlins,'' does a smooth job of meshing the live and
computerized components. Hollywood has been at this sort of thing
ever since Tod Browning directed Lionel Barrymore in ``The
Devil-Doll,'' but ``Small Soldiers'' rejiggers the formula in
smart, high-impact ways as it works both sides of the street on the
destruction-as-commodity issue. With summer far from over, ``Small
Soldiers'' will give teenage boys of all ages reason to go on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
