<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9212 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-KIDS-SPI &LR;      07-10 2000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-KIDS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREATE A STORIED VACATION WITH BOOKS FOR KIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CECELIA GOODNOW  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're traveling this summer, be sure to pack some books for
the kids. One if by land, two if by sea.
</P>
<P>
   If you're stuck at home, cheer up. That leaves more time to work
through a whole stack of the best new children's books, from
rhythmic read-alouds to hard-edged novels for young adults.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some contenders worthy of a ``golden hammock award.''
Enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Picture books
</P>
<P>
   ``If You Give a Pig a Pancake,'' by Laura Numeroff, illustrated
by Felicia Bond (HarperCollins, $14.95). Ages 3 to 6.
</P>
<P>
   We already know what happens ``If You Give a Mouse a Cookie'' or
``If You Give a Moose a Muffin.'' One thing leads zanily to another
until the story comes full circle. In this sequel, if you give a
pig a pancake, she'll want some syrup. Then she'll get sticky and
want a bath. The rubber duck will make her homesick for the farm
... and on and on, until the only logical thing is to have another
pancake! Warm-spirited fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beautiful Warrior: The Legend of the Nun's Kung Fu,'' by Emily
Arnold McCully (Levine/Scholastic, $16.95). Ages 4 to 8.
</P>
<P>
   In this original tale set in 17th-century China, young Mingyi
seeks help from a Buddhist nun with unusual prowess as a fighter
after a bandit demands her for a bride. Instead, the nun teaches
Mingyi to harness her own inner strength. Both elegant and warm,
this oversize book by Caldecott Medalist McCully has lively action
and expressive artwork that leaps off the page.
</P>
<P>
   (For slightly older readers, see ``Fa Mulan'' by Robert D. San
Souci, illustrated by Jean &AMP; Mou-Sien Tseng (Hyperion, $15.95).
Visually rich and sophisticated, it's based on the same legend that
inspired the Disney movie ``Mulan,'' about a Chinese woman who
becomes a great warrior.)
</P>
<P>
   ``A Home for Spooky,'' by Gloria Rand, illustrated by Ted Rand
(Holt, $15.95). Ages 4 to 8.
</P>
<P>
   A girl finds a starving, abandoned dog, Spooky, at the dump and,
against all odds, helps him recover and start a new life. The
Rands, who live on Mercer Island, have included notes and photos
(including a grim ``before'' photo) about the true events that
inspired this suspenseful, heartwarming tale. While Spooky finally
lands on his feet, there's a sobering message here about the
suffering faced by abandoned animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Bad Case of Stripes,'' by David Shannon (Blue Sky Press,
$15.95). Ages 5 to 9.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon takes the old saw, ``be yourself,'' to comic extremes.
Here, Camilla Cream is so shackled to public opinion, she refuses
to eat lima beans because her friends hate them. Her conformity
backfires when she breaks out in Technicolor stripes, then proceeds
to morph into whatever she encounters. The art is striking and the
book is selling well. But it gets off to a lurching start that begs
the question, ``Why stripes?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I Love You, Little One,'' by Nancy Tafuri (Scholastic,
$15.95). Ages 1 to 4.
</P>
<P>
   Next time your child asks, ``Do you love me?'' you can whip out
this book and reply with the poetry and firm assurance the question
demands. Here six baby animals and one child learn how they will be
loved ``forever and ever and always.'' The book is a lap full, with
wide pages filled with soft, full-frame pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hooray for Diffendoofer Day!'' by Dr. Seuss, with some help
from Jack Prelutsky and Lane Smith (Knopf, $17). All ages.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Seuss' rough, unfinished manuscript about a special teacher
and her lively school comes to life with help from two contemporary
icons. Prelutsky, a Seattle versemeister with great kid appeal,
captures the spirit of Dr. Seuss' rhyming tale. Smith's hip, visual
anarchy gives the mayhem a modern twist. Dr. Seuss fans will
especially enjoy the appendix, which explains the genesis of the
book and includes Dr. Seuss' rough draft and original sketches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tulip Sees America,'' by Cynthia Rylant and Lisa Desimi (Blue
Sky Press, $15.95). Ages 4 to 8.
</P>
<P>
   A young man who has never left home packs up his green
Volkswagen one day and journeys across the land, reveling in the
quiltlike farms of Iowa, the vast, dark skies of Nebraska, the
winds of Wyoming and the ocean of Oregon. The book, rooted in
Rylant's own 1993 cross-country trek, has a simple, poetic text and
good-natured, color-saturated artwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jungle ABC,'' by Michael Roberts, forward by Iman
(Callaway Hyperion, $19.95). All ages.
</P>
<P>
   This riveting collection of cut-paper collages will appeal to
visually sophisticated kids and adults. The images are bold and
abstract, printed on thick, oversize pages. Part of the fun is
trying to figure out what word each picture suggests. Check the
back for answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Snoops,'' by Miriam Moss, illustrated by Delphine Dorand
(Dutton, $14.99). Ages 6 to 9.
</P>
<P>
   With dry wit, this tale describes a neighborhood that plots
revenge on busybodies who tally their every misstep. The book
climaxes with a clever 3-D peek through the Snoops' own keyhole.
Original and droll.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Secret Knowledge of Grownups,'' by David Wisniewski
(Lothrop, Lee &AMP; Shepard/Morrow, $16). Ages 7 to 10.
</P>
<P>
   Behind this cover, which resembles a top-secret file folder,
lies the truth about parents' rules. Why do grownups really say to
eat your vegetables? To keep the wild things under control, of
course. Why comb your hair? To stop it from going back into those
little holes in your head! Clever fun, with fairly lengthy text.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Circle of Days, From Canticle of the Sun,'' by Reeve
Lindbergh (Candlewick, $15.99). All ages.
</P>
<P>
   This hymn of praise, written by St. Francis of Assisi in 1225,
makes a lovely read-aloud for the end of day. ``Lord, we offer
thanks and praise for the circle of our days. For sister moon, and
for the stars, brilliant, precious, always ours.'' The book is
beautifully designed, with a panel of inset illustrations below
each double spread. The pictures have the bold but cheerful look of
folk art.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little White Dog,'' by Laura Godwin, illustrated by Dan
Yaccarino (Hyperion, $14.95). Ages 2 to 5.
</P>
<P>
   This rhyming, cumulative story asks, ``Little white dog in the
snow, snow's so white, where did you go?'' In turn, a bluebird,
green bug, brown horse, yellow chick and black cat blend into their
backgrounds until the cat turns on a flashlight and sets each
animal searching for the next. Large type and stylized images lend
crisp simplicity to this fun read-aloud
</P>
<P>
   tale.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufsubhead &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHAPTER BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   ``Dancing on the Edge,'' by Han Nolan (Harcourt Brace, $16, 244
pages). Ages 12 and up.
</P>
<P>
   Pulled from the womb of a dead woman, Miracle McCloy is lucky to
be alive, as she's constantly reminded by her grandmother, a medium
with a knack for killing the spirit. After her father disappears,
Miracle descends into despair and nearly dies before a young
psychiatrist helps her build an identity based on hope. Depressing
as this sounds, it's a great read with some outrageously wacko
characters and flashes of humor.
</P>
<P>
   The novel, a release from last fall, won the 1997 National Book
Award in the Young People's Literature category. Nolan's previous
book ``Send Me Down a Miracle'' was a finalist in 1996, the first
year a young-adult category was recognized. Nolan is the only
author in any category to have books nominated two years in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mine Eyes Have Seen,'' by Ann Rinaldi (Scholastic, $16.95, 274
pages). Ages 12 and up.
</P>
<P>
   In 1859, abolitionist John Brown spent three furtive months at
the Kennedy Farm preparing for his suicidal raid on the U.S.
Arsenal at Harper's Ferry. His 15-year-old daughter, Annie, was
assigned to ward off strangers and oversee the 18 raiders hidden at
the farm. Viewed through her troubled eyes, this historical novel
is a spellbinding and nuanced character study of a man who embodied
both idealism and harsh zealotry. When the raiders bid Annie
farewell and march off to certain death, the scene is unbearably
sad and nothing short of haunting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Friends,'' by Kazumi Yumoto, translated by Cathy Hirano
(Yearling, $4.50 paper, 170 pages). Ages 10 and up.
</P>
<P>
   Winner of the 1997 Boston Globe-Horn Book Award, this widely
acclaimed coming-of-age novel tells of three Japanese boys who
begin spying on an old man to satisfy their curiosity about death.
Pressured by the demands of ``cram school'' and worried about their
futures, they are drawn instead into a life-affirming friendship
with the lonely castoff. Written in a breezy American style, this
book offers fascinating glimpses of contemporary Japanese life, as
well as an original, highly engaging story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freddy Goes to Florida,'' by Walter R. Brooks, illustrated by
Kurt Wiese (Overlook Press, $23.95, 196 pages). Ages 8 to 11.
</P>
<P>
   First published in 1927 as ``To and Again,'' this book launched
the classic Freddy the Pig series about a daydreaming,
poetry-writing pig who is by turns a cowboy, explorer, pilot and
all-round Renaissance Pig. The series grew to 26 titles by 1958
before disappearing from print and has never been available in its
entirety. Now Overlook is reissuing two titles a year in their
original format. Volume One is a little dated in spots, but our
7-year-old field tester not only ate it up, but begged to hear the
book a second time. Also out this year is the 1932 volume, ``Freddy
the Detective.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Smack,'' by Melvin Burgess (Henry Holt, $16.95, 327 pages).
Ages 14 and up.
</P>
<P>
   Be warned: This novel, winner of England's Carnegie Medal, is a
powerful and stark cautionary tale about two young runaways who
become mired in heroin addiction. It's a difficult book to read,
full of squalor and pathetically misguided characters. But the book
sticks with you and presents a far more compelling anti-drug
argument than ``Just Say No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For the Love of Venice,'' by Donna Jo Napoli (Delacorte,
$15.95, 245 pages). Ages 12 and up.
</P>
<P>
   Light enough for summer reading but meatier than the typical
teen romance, this novel explores the political issues behind
Venice's picturesque facade. Seventeen-year-old Percy feels lost
the summer his family visits the ``jewel of Italy.'' Then he meets
Graziella, a beautiful ice cream vendor who introduces him to
activists struggling over the city's domination by tourism, foreign
investment, floods and the weight of its own past. Against this
intriguing backdrop, Napoli keeps it light.
</P>
<P>
   NON-FICTION
</P>
<P>
   AND SUMMER FUN
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kids Summer Games Book,'' by Jane Drake and Ann Love,
illustrated by Heather Collins (Kids Can Press, $10.95, 175 pages).
Ages 7 to 11.
</P>
<P>
   This beat-the-blahs manual explains the rules of traditional
lawn games such as croquet and Capture the Flag, indoor games from
marbles to double solitaire and beach games for sand and sea. The
Disappearing Coin Trick suffers from a flopped illustration that
confuses the text's left-right directions, but otherwise the
instructions are simple and clear. For more specialized outdoor
activities, see ``The Kids Campfire Book'' by the same authors.
</P>
<P>
   ``National Audubon Society First Field Guild to Insects,'' by
Christina Wilsdon (Scholastic, $10.95 softcover, 160 pages). Ages 6
to adult.
</P>
<P>
   Useful both as a home reference and a child's field guide, this
book has more than 450 color photos and illustrations of 175
insects. It includes a waterproof identification card of 50 of the
most common North American insects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Reader's Digest Children's Atlas of the World'' (Reader's
Digest Young Families, $22.99, 128 pages). Ages 7 to 14.
</P>
<P>
   This oversize book is a feast for the eyes, with more than 3,000
illustrations of places, people and wildlife plus more than 50
full-color maps. It includes sections on ecology, weather, space
and basic map reading, plus fun facts and suggested projects. Use
it now to prepare for summer travel and later as a school reference
book.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
