<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVING-COLUMN-HAHN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUR VEHICLE MAY HAVE A MIND OF ITS OWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JON HAHN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you think the impending Year 2000 crisis in computer systems
is too big to grasp, how about something a little closer to home .
. . like the computer system that now runs your vehicle?
</P>
<P>
   There is a dark side to ``on-board diagnostics,'' now in the
so-called ``II'' or second stage, going into OBDIII. It's not a bad
thing. Quite the opposite, it will call attention to the slightest
malfunction of your vehicle and even identify what needs fixing.
</P>
<P>
   It could save a whole lot of money and even lives.
</P>
<P>
   And it could mean a whole lot more money to the big automakers,
especially if they continue to stonewall the independent and
after-market auto industry about sharing the new computer
information. ``Despite the strong language of the (Clean Air) Act,
the (federal and state) agencies are allowing vehicle manufacturers
to restrict the independent automotive parts and service industry's
access to all on-board diagnostics systems and OBD computers,''
reports a position paper by the Automotive Parts &AMP; Accessories
Association.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the big guys are sitting on the computer codes
that control the whole smear. No codes means no can do repair work.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, if your local independent mechanic is up to speed, he
can plug your vehicle into an expensive _ probably leased _
diagnostic testing machine and track your problem. And there's a
pro-rated charge for using the software put into the system by the
diagnostic machine folks, who, in turn, paid a bundle to get the
software from the automakers.
</P>
<P>
   But as we move to stage III, there appears to be a reluctance on
the part of automakers to share this information. That's
understandable, since greed is an integral part of marketing. You
want a larger share of the market, and what better way than to put
out a product that can only be serviced by your own dealers.
</P>
<P>
   The after-market, including your local independent mechanic,
says it's willing to pay a fair price for use of the diagnostic
software. That price no doubt will be passed along to us, but we
still have the option of dealing with an independent. So far, the
big automakers have been downright reluctant to share _ or sell, or
lease _ that software with the after-market. Does this all begin to
sound a little like an Eastside software firm wanting a larger
share of the market?
</P>
<P>
   I was first flagged on this by my trusty local mechanic, Kinnon
O. McKinnon, of K &AMP; M Automotive of Kirkland, Wash. I trust
McKinnon more than I trust my family doctor (but then, I take my
vehicles in more frequently and more regularly than I take this ol'
1940 body into the doc shop).
</P>
<P>
   Kinnon's initial warning had to do with the Big Brother aspect
of OBDII and III. And there is no doubt that the government, under
the Clean Air Act, might see and use the potential for monitoring
more than our tailpipe emissions.
</P>
<P>
   The government and industry are experimenting now with a system
that could monitor your vehicle emissions as you drive down the
road _ without your ever knowing it, according to Aaron Lowe, vice
president for governmental affairs for the Automotive Parts &AMP;
Accessories Association, a nationwide group of 1,400 companies and
auto parts dealers with retail service locations.
</P>
<P>
   ``California, which has the lead in this thing, wants to
eliminate its current (vehicle emission) testing system, and is
experimenting with linking the on-board computer with a
transponder, which could be monitored by roadside devices that take
the information off the car to see if there is an OBD `fault,'''
Lowe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The information would be relayed to a department of vehicles
and soon you'd get a notice that says your car needs such-and-such
repairs and that you have X number of days to make the repair and
prove that the work's been done.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the little dashboard light that warns, Get engine
serviced, is more than a gentle reminder. It has potential as a
tattletale, a snitch.
</P>
<P>
   When something causes your vehicle's warning light to flash, it
``throws a fault'' which registers in the computer. And almost
always, it's for a good reason. ``Any good technician should be
able to find and fix whatever's wrong; there's very little
guesswork,'' concedes McKinnon.
</P>
<P>
   ``But some systems will throw a fault if your gas cap isn't
tightly screwed on _ they monitor pressure in the fuel system _ or
if you've changed to a larger size tire or a performance muffler,''
McKinnon says. ``It used to be that you could `burn' a new code
into the computer to allow for variance in those situations, but
not any longer. And in the end, they have limited adaptability from
the after-market.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Bohanan, of the Specialty Equipment Market Association,
also warned that without automakers sharing software information,
it would be almost impossible to manufacture after-market parts and
equipment compatible with any vehicle's on-board tolerances. ``So,
if you drive to Home Depot and pick up a load of bricks, you're
going to swerve a bit as you drive home. And that is going to
register on board and throw a fault. And the fault code will stay
in the computer until it's checked out.''
</P>
<P>
   And where must you go to have it checked out? Why, the major
automaker dealership, of course.
</P>
<P>
   We'll hope to get their side of this on-board diagnostics thing
a bit down the road.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Hahn is a staff columnist for the P-I. He can be reached at
206-448-8317 or e-mail him at jonhahn(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 1420EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
