<SLUG> BC-MA-PARK-SYSTEM-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDERFUNDED GEMS, MASSACHUSETTS PARKS SHOWING THE STRAIN 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Starting when she was just three weeks old in 1963, Maynard,
Mass. native Diane Lockhart's parents would pile her in the station
wagon with her five older brothers and sisters to head out Route 2
and spend ``all summer, every summer,'' at Otter River State Forest
in Baldwinville.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks on end, they would live in a surplus Army tent or a
pop-up camper, splashing in the pond and finding secret places in
the woods. ``That was all my family could afford to do, but we
loved it up there. It was so beautiful,'' Lockhart recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Today, she and her husband have a vacation home in Maine. But a
June weekend found them back at Otter River with their teenage
children trying to relive ``those wonderful family times,'' singing
songs, playing cards, and cooking pancakes on the campfire.
</P>
<P>
   Not many residents know it, but Massachusetts has the 10 biggest
state parks systems in the nation. Besides preserving some
remarkable physical wonders, many of the sites inspire loyalty from
families unable to afford a vacation home.
</P>
<P>
   But while the run-up to the park system's 100th birthday this
summer has brought substantial improvements, a broad range of park
visitors, advocates, and state officials agree it has barely
reached adolescence in living up to its potential.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular properties _ Walden Pond, Nickerson State Park
in Brewster on Cape Cod, and beaches in Salisbury and Westport _
attract hundreds of thousands of visitors every year. At parks like
Otter River, campsite reservations are snapped up months in advance
by families that feel a sense of ownership of their spot.
</P>
<P>
   But advocates fear that Massachusetts forests, parks, and
reservations _ which attract 18 million visitors a year _ are being
``loved to death,'' their trails rutted by mountain bikes and camp
sites denuded and worn to hardpan.
</P>
<P>
   Across the Department of Environmental Management system, many
state officials, park visitors, and environmental advocates see a
potentially first-class resource that sometimes falls far short of
what it could be.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a general competence, an acceptability of the state
forests, but what is so often lacking is a realization of a
creative vision,'' said Theodore Ames, a Berkshire County
environmentalist who heads DEM's oversight board. ``A lot of the
parks just seem tired.''
</P>
<P>
   State Senator Robert A. Durand, a Marlborough Democrat and an
avid outdoorsman who heads the legislative committee that oversees
the parks, agrees: ``There's no question that our state park system
has paled in the past in comparison with our neighbors to the
north. With a little more effort, we could really have first-class
parks.''
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of the $75 million DEM has invested in rebuilding the
parks system since 1991 can clearly be seen after a 20-year period
of neglect. During that time, park money was diverted first into
pools and skating rinks, then into Heritage Parks by Governor
Michael S. Dukakis in such urban settings as Lowell, Fall River,
and North Adams, with mixed success.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to major work on trails and visitor centers at
prized properties like Salisbury Beach, Walden Pond, and Purgatory
Chasm in Sutton, dozens of parks have received attractive
pine-ceiling restrooms to replace pungent pit toilets. General
sprucing-up was obvious at more than 40 sites the Globe visited.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got our wish _ they've got the nicest flushies over
there,'' said Frank Dowen, a Concord hairdresser who has been
bringing his family and grandchildren to Otter River for decades.
``It's a big improvement over six years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Wheelchair-accessible trails, beaches, and fishing facilities
are being added at a steady rate. Agency officials have also begun
installing about 16 cozy permanent tents called ``yurts,'' each
with beds, tables, and small decks. They will rent for $25 a night
at Nickerson State Park and several Berkshires parks, offering
winter camping for skiiers and hunters.
</P>
<P>
   Staff and funding increases made since the meat-cleaver cutbacks
of 1989-'91 have resulted in the reopening of dozens of parks and
beaches, including the pond at Harold Parker State Forest in North
Andover. Virtually all campgrounds again have a 24-hour,
seven-day-a-week official presence.
</P>
<P>
   But DEM has at least a $100 million backlog of maintenance work.
And parks advocates see all sorts of unmet opportunities to
constructively exploit some beautiful properties.
</P>
<P>
   Demand would clearly justify adding thousands of campsites to
the 3,500 already scattered around the state, widening dozens of
fresh-water beaches for peak weekends, and beefing up
interpretation of historic sites and natural wonders.
</P>
<P>
   In many areas, camping could be moved to more inviting spots: At
the state's biggest park, 16,200-acre October Mountain State Forest
in Lee, the 50-site campground sits not on one of the many
Berkshire overlooks but next to a humming electric transformer yard
and a former dump.
</P>
<P>
   Some natural resources seem clumsily handled, like Natural
Bridge State Forest in North Adams, where rusting chain-link-
fenced walkways sprawl over a marble chasm waterfall. Or Bash Bish
Falls in Mount Washington, where no-swimming warnings have been
sloppily spray-painted on the rocks.
</P>
<P>
   The entire system has only a dozen cabins for rent at two parks.
``They should build a whole lot more of these _ they're
wonderful,'' said Monroe Bethea, a state Department of Mental
Retardation worker visiting a new log cabin at Savoy Mountain State
Forest last month with clients for a fishing trip.
</P>
<P>
   Despite promises by former Governor William F. Weld and Acting
Governor Paul Cellucci to make state government ``think
entrepreneurially,'' DEM officials are moving only haltingly toward
bringing in new partners and promoting many of its holdings.
</P>
<P>
   DEM has done nothing to take advantage of a ``Second Century''
fund legislators approved two years ago reserving park-revenue
increases for DEM use, and barely tapped an eight-year-old
conservation trust made up of private donations.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
