<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-LETHAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LETHAL' DEJA VU ALL OVER AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
LETHAL WEAPON 4 
Directed by: Richard Donner 
Screenplay by: Channing Gibson 
Starring: Mel Gibson, Danny Glover, Joe Pesci, Renee Russo, Chris
Rock, Jet Li 
Running time: 123 minutes 
Rated: R (violence and language) 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jokey carnage has no more dependable brand name than the
``Lethal Weapon'' franchise. One of the few things that makes
``Lethal Weapon 4'' watchable is the ease and familiarity with
which Mel Gibson, Danny Glover, Rene Russo, and Joe Pesci work
together. But that's also one of the things that makes it close to
unwatchable. The energetic extinguishings of human life are
insufferably glossed over with a series of genuflections to family
life on the most sentimentally manipulative level. Given the
insertion of kids and newborn babies into what passes for the plot
of this latest installment, the film turns into a game of gain a
life, lose a life, played for yuks.
</P>
<P>
   The plot barely bothers to go through the motions, stitching
together its set pieces aimed at the gonads and adrenals as LA cops
Gibson and Glover chase down a vicious Chinese triad. It's headed
by the film's only source of anything suggesting the presence of
fresh energy _ the deadly young ganglord played by Hong Kong
martial arts whiz Jet Li, making a dynamic US debut in an
uncharacteristic bad-guy role. After a fireball-filled prologue
that plays as if spliced in from a previous episode, Gibson and
Glover are nearly sent to the bottom of LA harbor by a Chinese
freighter while fishing with Pesci's snoop, incorporated into the
extended family. Also working her way into the group portrait is
Russo as the girlfriend whose pregnancy has Gibson's antsy cop,
Riggs, sweating over the M word.
</P>
<P>
   One of Glover's daughters is pregnant, too, which makes the bad
guys seem that much more killable when they go after the cops'
families in retaliation for the lawmen blowing the whistle on their
racket of smuggling illegal Chinese refugees into the States. The
lines are clearly drawn between the good guys and the bad. The
chases and shootouts unreel across rooftops, alleys, freeways, and
the inevitable waterfront warehouse. Speaking of inevitable, Glover
and especially Gibson are unable to avoid seeming a bit puffy with
the cops' physical exertions, so their advancing ages are written
into the script, especially when Jet Li's insolently unruffled
whirlwind almost Cuisinarts them both in combat.
</P>
<P>
   But despite all the wisecrack-flavored pandemonium, which revels
in its political incorrectness as it dances on the borders of
racism and homophobia in its humor, ``Lethal Weapon 4'' has the
spiritual energy of a dead battery. It's a bunch of high-paid
favorites going to the well yet again, trying to recycle the same
old stuff and disarm us with unearned we-are-family pieties as it
amps up the explosions. In short, it's a high-budget snuff film
posing as a two-hour-long Kodak moment. Cynical, meretricious,
unable to disguise the fact that it's getting awfully tired,
``Lethal Weapon 4'' is the best possible argument against ``Lethal
Weapon 5.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 1421EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9218 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-MADELINE-BOS &LR;      07-10 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-MADELINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CHARMING TRANSLATION FOR `MADELINE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
MADELINE 
Directed by: Daisy von Scherler Mayer 
Screenplay by: Mark Levin, Jennifer Flackett 
Starring: Frances McDormand, Nigel Hawthorne, Hatty Jones, Ben
Daniels, Kristian De La Osa, Arturo Venegas, Stephane Audran 
Running time: 90 minutes 
Rated: PG (momentary language) 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A lot of thought and care have gone into turning Ludwig
Bemelmans's beloved ``Madeline'' into a movie, and the result is a
quite charming translation from page to screen. Part of the appeal
of the Bemelmans books is the way their childlike drawings tap into
a sunny Paris of the mind, a Paris as everyone would like it to be.
Its proverbial 12 little girls in two straight lines bespeak a
world of privilege and gentility but _ as Bemelmans was aware in
1939, when he wrote the first Madeline book, and as we are reminded
whenever spunky little Madeline leads the others into trouble _ a
world barely able to sustain the illusion of serene order.
</P>
<P>
   The art direction and production design exquisitely capture the
book's old house in Paris, covered with vines, while gently moving
the story (an amalgam of four Madeline books) into the 1950s, out
from under the shadow of war and the grimness of postwar austerity.
Frances McDormand is a spot-on embodiment of Miss Clavel, the
clerical mother figure and beacon of safety. And Nigel Hawthorn
inscribes with a subtlety more than immediately apparent the role
of the English aristocrat, Lord Covington, who owns the boarding
school property and wants to sell it out from under Miss Clavel and
the girls.
</P>
<P>
   This brings home to the other girls the sense of life's
precariousness of which Madeline is already keenly aware, having
been orphaned. The film's one stretch involves giving Madeline a
British accent, presumably on the theory that one European country
is pretty much the same as another, and that an English-accented
Madeline poses less commercial risk than a French-accented one. The
important thing is that Hattie Jones captures Madeline's
fearlessness, whether giving Miss Clavel fits by balancing on a
bridge's stone railing or getting embroiled with kidnappers.
</P>
<P>
   The tonalities are seen to with sunny devotion to the original
on the part of director Daisy von Scherler Mayer. With Jones
leading the way, turning in the kind of confident performance that
only a 9-year-old actor (or an 89-year-old one) can, the screen is
filled with sweetly irrepressible energies that should satisfy all
but the most demanding Madeline fans (plus their parents), and more
than a few of the last category, too. If you've been wondering what
you can take your little girl to, in this summer of clunky comets
and clunkier lizards, look no further.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 1423EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 14:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9221 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MO-NIXON-BOS &LR;      07-10 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MO-NIXON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE CANDIDATE IN MISSOURI GETS A WAKE-UP CALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Jeremiah ``Jay'' Nixon has spent the day looking for
money and votes in rural Missouri towns, an Irish pub in this city,
and a suburban union hall. He's everywhere, it seems, but the most
likely destination for a Democratic candidate for the US Senate:
St. Louis's predominantly black north side.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon, Missouri's attorney general and a top Senate prospect for
the Democrats nationally, has so angered black leaders with his
proposal to end state aid for school desegregation that many are
actively working to defeat him. So it's prudent for him to keep his
distance when he can.
</P>
<P>
   The local NAACP has picketed Nixon's public events. Black civic
leaders are raising money for Republican incumbent Senator
Christopher ``Kit'' Bond. And the state's senior black politician,
US Representative William L. Clay Sr., has been trying to drum up
opposition to Nixon. Nixon and Bond are white.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon is expected to win his August primary and then challenge
Bond in a November contest that has become a lightning rod for
exploding black angst within the Democratic Party. Many black
voters say they are frustrated by being taken for granted and upset
that their issues _ from affirmative action to desegregation _ are
being ignored and sometimes even opposed by Democrats, who
typically get 80 to 90 percent of the black vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not unlike the Christian right's disagreement within
the Republican Party: We are saying we are one of the backbones of
your political strength, and you are dealing with us in an
unacceptable way,'' said Dr. Donald Suggs, a St. Louis oral
surgeon, newspaper publisher, and member of a group of black
leaders opposing Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts predict black frustration with the Democratic
Party here and elsewhere could lower voter turnout in the fall
congressional elections and perhaps beyond.
</P>
<P>
   In Maryland, for example, Baltimore's black mayor, Kurt L.
Schmoke, stunned Democratic officials by backing Harford County
Executive Eileen M. Rehrmann in the upcoming primary instead of
Democratic Governor Parris N. Glendening. Schmoke, who helped
deliver predominantly black Baltimore in 1994 to Glendening, says
the governor reneged on a promise to raise funds for public
education.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, black officials, including US Representative Alcee
L. Hastings, worked to defeat the Democratic candidate for speaker
of the House after a black man in line for the nomination was
ousted in favor of a white woman.
</P>
<P>
   But it's here that the complicated relationship between black
voters and white Democratic politicians seems most strained. The
rancor forced President Clinton to delay a visit to a Nixon
fund-raiser last fall until threats by blacks to picket it were
withdrawn. Eight days after the fund-raiser, Nixon asked the US
Supreme Court to end state funding for desegreation programs,
leaving blacks stunned and dismayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the folks in Boston know, when you mix race and politics
and money and schools and courts together, that is not a sanguine
situation,'' Nixon explained.
</P>
<P>
   As attorney general, Nixon has sought to end the court-ordered
busing of 13,000 black children from St. Louis city schools to
predominantly white suburban school districts. He has proposed
instead that the state pay $300 million to renovate schools and
build new ones to settle the city's 26-year-old desegregation case.
</P>
<P>
   Many black families believe Nixon's plan would rob their
children of access to high-quality education.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that we can push a lot of people toward Mr. Bond,
but we've done a fairly good job of pointing out that Nixon is
undeserving of Democratic support, and that I think will cut into
his margin in November,'' Suggs said. ``The Democratic Party has to
be concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond, a moderate Republican who is seeking a third term in the
Senate, is in some ways an unlikely choice for black voters. He has
never received more than token support from blacks in any campaign;
the national NAACP recently gave him a failing grade for his civil
rights record; and he, like Nixon, opposes funding for
desegregation.
</P>
<P>
   But many blacks here give Bond credit for appointing
African-Americans to high-profile jobs and judgeships during his
two terms as governor. They also say he has worked to restore
spending for federal housing programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have worked very hard to build a Republican base in the
African-American community from the time I was governor,'' Bond
said in an interview last week. ``It would change the entire
dynamics if we get a decent vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Mischeaux, president of the St. Louis NAACP, accuses
Nixon of dealing dishonestly with the black leaders and using
desegregation to woo voters in rural Missouri, where Democratic
candidates don't fare as well as Republicans and where residents
oppose the state spending of $1 billion so far on integrating
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would you choose this issue?'' asked Nixon, who recently
won an end to Kansas City's court-ordered busing with state
payments of $320 million over three years to the city schools. ``No
other politician in the state ... spoke as forthrightly and as
directly as I have, and there aren't that many rewards for speaking
your mind in politics, and this is one example of that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
