<SLUG> BC-CHIROPRACTORS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY CRITICIZES CHIROPRACTIC TREATMENT OF BACK PROBLEMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A new study could revive an old debate over
whether chiropractic treatment for lower back pain does any good.
</P>
<P>
   In the study by the Rand Corp., 29 percent of initial
chiropractic treatments for lower back pain were found to be
inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, 46 percent of the treatments were ruled
appropriate, says study author Dr. Paul G. Shekelle of the West Los
Angeles Veterans Affairs Medical Center. Twenty-five percent were
rated as being of uncertain value.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, a 29 percent inappropriateness rate is too high and
should be decreased,'' Shekelle said. The total number of
inappropriate treatments is probably higher, he said, because the
study examined only initial visits to a chiropractor.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he said, the 46 percent appropriateness rate
means that ``everybody needs to stop treating chiropractors as if
they are quacks,'' he said, adding that under certain
circumstances, he would refer a patient, even himself, to a
chiropractor.
</P>
<P>
   Shekelle's study appears in the June 30 issue of a prestigious
medical journal, Annals of Internal Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Chiropractors manipulate the human spine in the belief that this
treatment can relieve medical complaints. They disagree over how
widely the technique should be used.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, the American Medical Association and other orthodox
doctors' groups waged a fierce war on chiropractic, arguing that it
harmed many patients.
</P>
<P>
   One camp of chiropractors restricts itself to musculoskeletal
manipulations of backs and necks. Another camp claims that
chiropractic can benefit sufferers of conditions such as asthma,
ear infections and hypertension.
</P>
<P>
   And ``there is one group that believes chiropractors can be
primary care providers (like medical doctors) who can take care of
a whole gamut of symptoms,'' says Shekelle, an internist who
received his medical degree at the Duke University Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   Shekelle's study examined only one application of chiropractic _
treating lower back pain. He and colleagues examined the medical
records of 1,310 patients who sought treatment for lower back pain
at 131 randomly sampled chiropractic offices in the United States
and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The study was funded by three chiropractic organizations. Its
seven authors, led by Shekelle, include three chiropractors.
Shekelle said the funding groups had no control over Rand's
analysis and publication of its findings.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in the 1940s, the Santa Monica-based Rand Corp. is best
known as a private think tank heavily funded by the Defense
Department. Rand stands for ``Research and Development.''
</P>
<P>
   The study's 29 percent finding of inappropriateness upset some
chiropractors, Shekelle said. ``We've heard from some
chiropractors, `Why did you publish such a negative article about
us?'''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Wallace Sampson, a Stanford University Medical School
professor who edits the journal Scientific Review of Alternative
Medicine, expressed skepticism about the Rand findings.
</P>
<P>
   Sampson, an oncologist, insisted chiropractic manipulation can
harm patients by causing herniated discs or by delaying orthodox
treatment of a serious illness like cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Argyelan, president of the 4,000-member California
Chiropractic Association, said the Shekelle study was ``a good
report'' but expressed concern over the meaningfulness of the terms
``appropriate'' and ``inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Argyelan said he agreed with Shekelle's statement that a 29
percent rate of improper procedures is ``too high.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The chiropractic profession needs to support more research on
spinal manipulative therapy,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
