 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DAHMER-KLAN (Hattiesburg, Miss.) -- A courageous decision by a
Klan hanger-on to cooperate in an undercover FBI investigation led
to the arrest of Sam Bowers, now charged with murder in the
firebombing of Vernon Dahmer's home. By Curtis Wilkie. (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   MO-NIXON (Jackson, Miss.) -- Senate candidate Jay Nixon, seeking
the seat held by Republican Sen. Kit Bond, opposes court-ordered
desegregation, and many blacks are trying to end his political
career. By Ann Scales. 1200 words..
</P>
<P>
   DISCOVERING-SPECIES (Undated) -- One hundred superspecialists
fan across two towns on a 24-hour biodiversity marathon attempting
to identify 1,000 species of things that creep, craw, swim, wiggle
and fly. By Beth Daley. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   SEABIRD-REFUGE (Eastern Egg Rock, Maine) -- Twenty-five years
after Audubon biologist Stephen Kress set out on a quixotic mission
to restore a colony of endangered puffins, a 7-acre island has
become a living museum of New England's marine bird life before
Europeans. By Scott Allen. 1700 words.
</P>
<P>
   MA-PARK-SYSTEM (Undated) _ On the 100th anniversary of the
Massachusetts park system, the 10th largest in the nation, critics
say the state has made some improvements over the worst neglect
during the budget crisis at beginning of the 1990s, but the parks
are far from reaching their potential. By Peter Howe. (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   VT-GETTYSBURG (Undated) _ A new book and historical evidence
show that Vermonters in the Battle of Gettysburg did far more to
help win the battle than previously known. By Judith Gaines. 1400
words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NYHAN-COLUMN (Portland, Maine) -- Outdoor writer Gene Letourneau
turned ordinary talk into backwoodsy wisdom. By David Nyhan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIFESTYLE (l) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEET-SPICE (Mansfield, Mass.) -- Ann, Jennifer, Jessica, and
Tabitha love the Spice Girls. So when they were chosen to meet them
backstage, you will understand why they ran in circles. By Alisa
Valdes. 1500 words. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   BEAM-COLUMN (Undated) -- Alex Beam is writing on local topics
today; his column will not move.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-YORKER (New York) -- One day after Tina Brown announced
she was quitting her job as editor of The New Yorker, her staffers
started worrying about changes at the magazine. By Fred Kaplan. 900
words.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-SOLDIERS (Undated) _ ``Small Soldiers'' is a toy story
with attitude, a high-tech ``Gremlins'' driven by an army of attack
toys. By Jay Carr.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-JESSE (Undated) _ Tim Kirkman's autobiographgical memoir,
``Dear Jesse,'' reminds us that Jesse Helms is against lots of
things. By Jay Carr. (Attn.: N.C.)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-LAND-GIRLS (Undated) -- In ``The Land Girls,''
writer-director David Leland richly invokes the wartime 1940s. By
Jay Carr.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-PASSION (Undated) _ ``Passion in the Desert'' is an oddly
beautiful little nonesuch that beats the odds and succeeds as a
compelling contemplation of the distance between man and nature. By
Jay Carr.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-MADELINE (Undated) _ A lot of care has gone into turning
Ludwig Bemelmans's beloved ``Madeline'' into a movie, and the
result is a quite charming translation. By Jay Carr.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-LETHAL (Undated) _ Jokey carnage has no more dependable
brand name than the ``Lethal Weapon'' franchise. And that makes the
latest version close to unwatchable. By Jay Carr.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-ROCK (Undated) _ The Counting Crows will release a
double-CD of live performances, consisting of their gig on VH1's
``Storytellers'' and an electric show recorded for MTV's ``Live at
the 10 Spot.'' By Steve Morse.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-TANGLEWOOD (Undated) _ There are many good reasons to read
``Tanglewood: The Clash Between Tradition and Change,'' by Andrew
Pincus, the music critic of The Berkshire Eagle. By Richard Dyer.
(2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RADIO-SHACK (Peabody, Mass.) -- In 1921 a young immigrant opened
a Boston store that sold military surplus gear to ham radio
operators; he called it Radio Shack. Seventy-seven years later the
chain has nearly 7,000 stores. By Chris Reidy. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   ONADVERTISING-COLUMN (Undated) -- Reebok has a new star writing
advertising copy for its sneaker ads _ the late William O. Douglas,
former US Supreme Court Justice. By Chris Reidy. 750 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS &LR;   &UR; (s) &LR;
