<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9241 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-TANGLEWOOD-2TAKE     07-10 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TANGLEWOOD-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN INSIDER'S SOLID LOOK AT TANGLEWOOD RANCOR 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
TANGLEWOOD 
The Clash Between Tradition and Change 
By Andrew L. Pincus 
Northeastern University Press, 210 pp., illustrated, $24.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The clash between tradition and change probably began in the
second minute of Creation and it will continue until the
Apocalypse.
</P>
<P>
   The particular circumstances of this clash as they unfolded at
Tanglewood over the last couple of years have brought the Boston
Symphony Orchestra its worst press since 1984, when actress Vanessa
Redgrave sued the orchestra for canceling her contract because of
her political views. This controversy is paradoxical, because
Tanglewood's founder, former BSO music director Serge Koussevitzky,
sought to sidestep the immemorial conflict by creating a tradition
that would be about change.
</P>
<P>
   There are many good reasons to read ``Tanglewood: The Clash
Between Tradition and Change,'' by Andrew Pincus, the music critic
of The Berkshire Eagle. It is a serious, thoughtful, and
thought-provoking book. Over the last 23 years, Pincus has
certainly spent more hours on the Tanglewood grounds than any other
journalist and probably more than any musician or administrator. He
knows the greensward as well as any individual can, and what is
encrypted on every blade of grass.
</P>
<P>
   Most of his readers, at least for now, will turn to his new book
to get the skivvy on the controversies swirling around the
Tanglewood Music Center, the BSO's summer institute for advanced
musical training, but they will not get to the bottom of the
matter. Pincus's account seems sketchy _ it has to be because too
much of what happened is unclear and key participants have chosen
not to talk publicly about it. But it also seems partial, which may
be why the BSO briefly contemplated forbidding the sale of the book
in the Tanglewood gift shop.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Pincus's treatment of the TMC controversies is more solid
than it was in his recent overheated article in Boston Magazine. &UR;  &LR; 
It has become routine for commentators &UR;  &LR; to discuss a 1994 Sony/PBS
educational video project involving Wynton Marsalis, Yo-Yo Ma,
Seiji Ozawa, and students of the Tanglewood Music Center as if it
were a schlocky and purely commercial venture, as if the TMC
orchestra had had been commandeered to back up the Spice Girls on
MTV.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Marsalis on Music'' video project was flawed in conception
and execution, but objections to it came to the fore only after the
taping was underway. By that time, it was too late to do anything
about scheduling conflicts, which certainly should have been
foreseen. At that point, Ozawa's only option was the one every
professional musician has to exercise repeatedly throughout his
career _ to soldier on, making the best of a bad situation. It
could be argued that instead of exploiting the TMC students, he was
offering them a lesson in professionalism.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over the Marsalis project crystalized a
longstanding conflict at Tanglewood between the ``ivory tower''
activities of the TMC and the populist requirements of a summer
festival that must attract an audience of thousands to every
concert. It also set in motion a chain of events that led to
Ozawa's dismissal of Richard Ortner as administrator of the TMC and
the high-profile resignations of the TMC's artistic director Leon
Fleisher and faculty chairman Gilbert Kalish. There is no evidence
that Ozawa either wanted or welcomed these resignations. In fact,
he repeatedly urged Fleisher, now 70, to remain in a reconfigured,
honorific and active position.
</P>
<P>
   Like most people who love Tanglewood and the Tanglewood Music
Center in particular, Pincus seems troubled and confused by these
events, events in which people on both sides of the controversy
sought to wrap themselves in the cape of Koussevitzky, who made a
natural ally to both sides because he was both firmly attached to
tradition and profoundly committed to advancing the cutting edge.
He believed that the ``eternal verities'' expressed in music could
be found in the work unknown young Americans hadn't composed yet as
well as in classics by Beethoven, Brahms, and Tchaikovsky.
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa has said little about his reasons for wanting change at
the TMC, but what he has said makes sense. He was not happy with
the parts of the operation he knows best, the conducting and the
orchestra program, and he wanted to restore a more direct
involvement by the BSO in its own school. Orchestra training is a
core element of the TMC's curriculum, and the school was not making
full or effective use of the very resource that makes it unique,
the sponsorship of a resident world-class symphony orchestra. In
noting this, quite belatedly, (more than 20 years into his music
directorship), Ozawa was measuring the TMC of recent years against
the very different Tanglewood of his first experience, when he
arrived as a student in 1960. The principal change he wanted was
the restoration of a tradition which withered away back in the
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question that the dismissal of Ortner was handled
badly, and that the subsequent year of transition, which unfolded
in the absence of a general manager, was troubled by numerous
administrative missteps and misunderstandings that led to hurt
feelings and bruised egos. The resignations of Kalish and Fleisher
were a public-relations disaster; more importantly, they
represented an artistic loss to Tanglewood.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless it is an enormous jump from these unpleasant facts
to the even more unpleasant implications of Pincus's assessment
that Ozawa ``was unhappy with the traditionalist stance of the
Music Center, which since its beginning under Koussevitzky had been
dedicated to ensemble performance and the art of music rather than
solo careers and glorification of the performer. Wanting to open
the festival and school to outside influences as jazz, Ozawa felt
blocked by `the club' (of Fleisher, Kalish and other ``entrenched''
members of the TMC faculty).''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 1435EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9243 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-TANGLEWOOD-2ND &LR;  &UR;      07-10 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TANGLEWOOD-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... TMC faculty).''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ozawa did invite the jazz pianist Marcus Roberts to appear at a
Boston Symphony concert where Roberts's performance was deplorable;
Roberts came back the following season to participate in a short
fund-raising concert with the TMC orchestra that mingled serious
and popular repertory. There's no other evidence that Ozawa is
pursuing a jazz or ``outside influence'' agenda (Keith Jarrett's
appearance in a Mozart concerto, cited by Pincus, was not Ozawa's
idea, but the result of the pianist's longtime professional
assocation with the conductor Dennis Russell Davies, with whom he
had recorded the work in question).
</P>
<P>
   And Ozawa has never said or done anything to suggest that he
wanted the TMC or even the BSO's Shed concerts to be about solo
careers and superstar performers. Certainly the BSO's concerts in
the 5,000-seat shed depend on the stars of the music business, and
the performances of some of them deteriorated over the years. (How
are you going to tell the Tanglewood public that loves Itzhak
Perlman that they shouldn't enjoy him any more?)
</P>
<P>
   For a person in his position, Ozawa himself has always seemed
remarkably free of star-worship. Some of his proteges did become
superstars, like Jessye Norman and Kathleen Battle, but they were
promising young Americans when Ozawa started engaging them; they
remained loyal to him in their glory years, and he remained loyal
to them in their times of trouble. But he has also worked steadily
with musicians he admired who were not on that level of fame, or
even interested in it, like Peter Serkin, Maria Tipo, Benjamin
Luxon, Gidon Kremer and Vinson Cole; he has steered clear of some
dubious celebrities like Nadja Salerno-Sonenberg, and recently not
renewed his acquaintance with Evgeny Kissin or Midori.
</P>
<P>
   The revised TMC curriculum which went into place this summer,
and which Ozawa intends to keep evolving, was not ``devised in
large part by (the new director of the school, Ellen) Highstein,''
as Pincus says. It represented Highstein's organization,
consolidation and implementation of suggestions made during
meetings with Ozawa, last summer's faculty, students, and such
interested parties as Andre Previn, Bernard Haitink, John Williams,
members of the Juilliard Quartet, and others. Paradoxically there
does not seem to be anything in this summer's program that Kalish
and Fleisher could object to, at least on artistic grounds.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Pincus's new book is a sequel to his earlier book,
``Scenes from Tanglewood'' (1989), a distillation of his first
dozen years of reporting. Pincus is more ambitious and inevitably
less successful this time out because this is not just a book about
Tanglewood. He uses Tanglewood as a lens through which to examine
the issues facing America's entire musical culture.
</P>
<P>
   His eye and his ear remain as acute as ever, and his accounts of
such episodes as the planning, construction, and opening of Seiji
Ozawa Hall; the final residencies and last concert of Leonard
Bernstein; the 50th anniversary revival of Benjamin Britten's
``Peter Grimes'' are accurate, thoughtful and interesting. They
will prove informative even to people who were there. There are
lively portraits of, tributes to, and conversations with, such
diverse Tanglewood figures as Bernard Haitink, John Williams, Louis
Krasner, Lukas Foss, John Harbison, Alfred Brendel, and Keith
Lockhart. One need not agree with Pincus's conclusion about Ozawa
(``Ozawa seems to have overstayed his time; neither he nor the
orchestra is growing'') in order to recognize that he has provided
a complex characterization of a complex figure, which benefits from
the writer's travels to Japan to observe the conductor at work in
his own country.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably Pincus's intimate knowledge of Tanglewood overmatches
his knowledge of what is happening elsewhere. The book crucially
lacks a sense of context. It is odd to find American musical life
discussed only as it has been controversially codified in such
documents as the American Symphony Orchestra League's 1993 report
on ``Americanizing the American Orchestra'' (a study whose title
the book repeatedly gets wrong). Creeping commercialism at
Tanglewood, one of Pincus's major themes, needs to be discussed in
the context of what has been happening at such other summer
festivals as the Chicago Symphony's Ravinia, the Los Angeles
Philharmonic's Hollywood Bowl, and the Cleveland Orchestra's
Blossom, all of which have made different, and far more
commercially opportunistic, responses to the same pressures
Tanglewood faces.
</P>
<P>
   The book has been less meticulously edited than its predecessor.
The individual chapters seem to have been written for independent
publication, so there is a lot of repetition that becomes
irritating to someone who is reading all the way through. There is
also a light dusting of uncharacteristic error. Mezzos Frederica
von Stade and Mitsuko Shirai have been squeezed up into sopranos;
the conductor James DePreist's name is misspelled; Isaiah Jackson
did not conduct ``Gospel Night'' ``sometimes,'' but once, and
Charles Floyd went on to shape it into a beloved new tradition in
five subsequent seasons. ``Gospel Night'' is not the only BSO
activity tailored to ethnic or minority groups. Arthur Fiedler did
Irish, Italian, Celtic, Hispanic and Armenian nights beyond
counting (as well as ``Negro Nights''), and such programming
continued through John Williams' era into Keith Lockhart's Pops
today.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever personal interpretation he puts on events, whatever
reasoning and motives he imputes to people who have not stated
them, Pincus has certainly identified some of the principal issues
and dangers that face Tanglewood and, by extension, all of serious
cultural life in this country today. But he may have produced this
particular book prematurely: The restructuring and re-animation of
the TMC is one of the most ambitious and important projects of
Ozawa's career, and the time to evaluate it is not before it is
under &UR;  &LR; way, but after it has produced some results. Instead of
beginning in medias res, Pincus ends there. On the other hand, if
you're talking about Tanglewood, that may be only fitting;
Koussevitzky intended the place to be in medias res all the time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
