<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9270 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GE-ENVIRONMENT-HNS &LR;      07-10 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GE-ENVIRONMENT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 EPA CHIEF BLASTS GENERAL ELECTRIC OVER PCBs IN HUDSON RIVER  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In the Clinton administration's harshest
criticism of the General Electric Co., the head of the U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency accused GE of conducting a ``public
disinformation'' campaign about the dangers of PCBs in the Hudson
River.
</P>
<P>
   EPA Administrator Carol M. Browner, testifying at a state
Assembly hearing on her agency's progress in assessing the dangers
of the river's PCBs, also accused the corporation of promoting
``politics at its most cynical'' by deploying legions of
Washington-based lobbyists to water down federal Superfund
legislation to clean up toxic wastes.
</P>
<P>
   GE is currently listed as a responsible party at 75 Superfund
sites in the nation, including 200 miles of the Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   ``GE would have the people believe that _ and I quote _ living
in a PCB-laden area is not dangerous,'' Browner said in a 65-minute
hearing Thursday before five Democratic assemblymen and attended by
more than 100 people at the state Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell people that PCBs are not dangerous is simply wrong,''
she said. ``Clearly, the science has spoken. PCBs are a serious
threat. They are a threat to our health, our environment and our
future.''
</P>
<P>
   The EPA is engaged in a contentious years-long reassessment of
its decision not to dredge the Hudson River to remove PCBs, an
industrial chemical banned in 1976 and known to cause cancer in
animals. Earlier this year, the agency postponed its final
recommendation on the matter until December 2000, largely due to
erroneous data supplied by GE, Browner said.
</P>
<P>
   GE said its officials did not attend Thursday's hearing because
the company was not given enough advance notice, but it disputed
Browner's comments on the danger PCBs pose to humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``PCBs do not cause cancer in humans,'' nor have the chemicals
been shown to cause any other adverse health effects in humans, GE
spokesman David Warshaw said in a telephone interview from the
company's headquarters in Fairfield, Conn. ``The risk scenarious
(of the danger of PCBs to humans) overstate the risk and don't
reflect real-world conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   The hearing was the first in a series to address the health and
environmental risks along the Hudson, said Assemblyman Richard
Brodsky, a Democrat who chairs the Environmental Conservation
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   PCBs were legally discharged into the Hudson for about 30 years,
beginning in the mid-1940s, by factories along the river. GE plants
at Hudson Falls and Fort Edward were the largest contributors,
dumping an estimated 500,000 pounds of the chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   During her remarks, Browner repeated the agency's scientific
findings that PCB, or polychorinated biphenyl, has been linked to
birth defects and non-Hodgkins lymphoma in humans.
</P>
<P>
   Browner is the second Clinton Cabinet member in the past year to
blast GE's treatment of the Hudson. In October, Interior Secretary
Bruce Babbitt stood at a historic site near Hudson and blamed GE
for ``the sickness'' of the river.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA has come under fire by environmentalists for continually
pushing back its deadline to decide whether to dredge the Hudson.
But on Thursday, Browner pledged to stick to the December 2000
deadline and vowed to force GE to pay for the cost of any cleanup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
