<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9277 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV12-BO     07-10 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV12-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG NEW FORD F250 SUPER IN A LOT OF WAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)  
 (For release Sunday, July 12 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R.WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No sooner had I departed for Colorado in a large red Dodge Ram
cum 24-valve Cummins diesel, obviously the largest, best-suited
vehicle available for the task of hauling a heavily laden 22-foot
trailer up into the Rockies, than did Ford's version of a Big Red
Truck arrive on my doorstep. I come home from 4,600 miles in the
cab of a truck to find ... a (itals)bigger(unitals) truck.
</P>
<P>
   It is Ford's F250 4 x 4 Supercab XLT, a heavy-duty giant that
stands a shade more than 77 inches tall on a 158-inch wheelbase,
its bright red clearcoat paint job gleaming in the sun. Standard
powertrain for this truck is a 5.4-liter, V-8 engine with 5-speed,
manual transmission _ but this is the heavy heavy duty. This Big
Red Truck has a 4-speed electronically controlled transmission
attached to a 275 horsepower _ 410 ft/lb of torque _ 6.8-liter,
V-10 gas engine.
</P>
<P>
   Dodge has a big V-10 gas engine, had it before Ford did. But the
Dodge engine, good as it is, is a bit rough-sounding, an audio
arrhythmiadue to the design process _ the stretching of an existing
V-8 by cobbling together an extra couple of cylinders with an
asymmetrical crankshaft. The Ford V-10 is one of a series of
modular engines, a family of motors designed with components in
common; it was conceived as a V-10 from the get-go with a
symmetrical crankshaft. The end Ford product is whisper quiet,
silky smooth.
</P>
<P>
   So here I am with this humongous truck designed for stump
pulling, barge hauling, and other such beastly employment, and
nothing of any consequence to pull, haul, carry, or drag. If it
were winter now, I would fill the truck's cavernous plastic-lined
bed with ice and snow, stuff that weighs plenty, doesn't scratch
the paint, and is easy to unload _ just wait for a warm spell. But
this is summer; snow is hard to come by (except in the Rockies, but
I'm not there now) and I have no prospect for hauling anuything
more than a couple of sticks of lumber and some pegboard from which
I hope to fashion a pot rack. To this end, I head for Maine in the
Big Red Truck and the barn where the ancient Toolcraft radial arm
saw and the jointer/planer are stored.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the F250 has running boards, otherwise it might be
necessary to drag along a ladder for entry and exit. The bumper as
step facilitates the mounting/dismounting. The seat is a
three-section bench; the back of the middle section folds down to
reveal a large storage bin with coin holder _ something I think
Ford copied from Dodge.
</P>
<P>
   Gauges are clear, the controls pretty straightforward _ this is
a work truck. But I wish the fashion clowns who design radios would
get that message; working stiffs on the job don't have time to be
bothering with little rockers and cute tuning bars _ a couple of
knobs will suffice, guys. The preset buttons at least are large
enough for a human hand, even a hand swathed in a glove, but
controls fashioned for audio dilettantes are not welcome, out of
place, in a work vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The route north takes me over that mix of rough pavement, short
stretch of dirt, and scenic back roads. I note with sadness that
the church with the peculiar four-gabled steeple, so long a
landmark for a route change, was a wreck, its steeple on the
ground, roof timbers laid bare _ either in the process of
demolition or reconstruction _ the latter, one hopes. It is sad to
lose structures of unique character in a world full of
cookie-cutter plastic architecture.
</P>
<P>
   The F250 is sprung for a load _ it needs a ton or two to smooth
it out. Still, it is far from harsh. A little hoppy at times on the
uneven pavement, but it never loses its footing, is stable in the
corners, exhibits very nice handling characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the driver/passengers up front is a bench seat wide
enough for three more, and while the front-to-back space is a bit
scant for adult thighs, knees, and feet, three kids will be OK. I
pile it with stuff. This is, by the way, a four-door 4(MUL)4. The
rear doors cannot be opened until the front doors are open, a
safety thing, but four doors make this a very convenient vehicle.
Better yet, the seat flips out, folds down, and forms a hard
surface on which to pile heavy stuff _ toolboxes and the like. Or a
place for the dog, right under the gun rack (your option).
</P>
<P>
   I run the Ford out to Glenn By-ron's place, he who prepped the
Dodge and trailer for Colorado; he goes over it admiringly. ``You
know this is a heavy-duty truck soon as you see those eight-lug
wheels,'' he says. ``Love to have this to pull the trailer.'' Love
to have this, period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got an engine or two you need delivered?'' I ask jokingly.
Byron is serious in his well-considered answer in the negative.
</P>
<P>
   The mirrors are big, set way out to see around trailers; the
mirrors are segmented, too, with a small wide-angle bottom portion
designed to show you the rear wheels as you back up, a safety plus.
</P>
<P>
   Empty _ or virtually so _ this truck wants to gallop; all that
power and nothing to pull, like a sled dog too long confined to the
yard. I spend a day cutting wood, dadoing, shaping _ measure twice,
cut once, I remember. Still, when I get home, the pieces of this
complicated contraption that look perfect assembled on the barn
floor will prove to be a quarter-inch off on two sides _ and 150
miles distant from the machine that can fix that in jiffy. Thus
cut, the pieces of the prefab pot rack are even lighter going home.
I am tempted to go rock-picking and maybe build a wall, anything to
try this truck with a proper load.
</P>
<P>
   The bed has a liner, and the usual four tie-downs are hidden
behind waterproof plugs, two friction type in the rear, two screwed
in place up front. In the box are three slots for 2 x 6s to lie
athwart the cargo area to support flat loads such as sheet rock or
plywood and six slots for 2 x 6s or 8s to divide the box into
compartments. If you need the 4WD, by the way, there is a switch on
the dash to engage the front axle and hubs in either high or low
range at the touch of a finger and thumb.
</P>
<P>
   Price? This is not a toy. Basic sticker is $25,055 plus $640
destination for 5.4-liter V-8 and manual, fairly well equipped. The
V-10, automatic, trailer package, 4-wheel antilock brakes and a
host of other options bring the final tally to $32,110 delivered.
Fuel mileage is tough, too; this is not a mini suitable for the
dump on weekends and commuting weekdays. This is a serious truck
with a serious fuel appetite as evidenced by its 38-gallon fuel
tank, just a wee bit smaller than a DC-3's. For just over 900
miles, the Ford averages 11.59 miles to the gallon _ that's empty;
figure a lot less as the load increases.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, though, I found myself wishing for a real job that
needed a real truck ... well, for a few seconds anyway. This gig
beats real work most days.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For the on-line browsers, I'll be available to chat on line
about cars Tuesdays, 2 p.m. to 3 p.m. Just point your Internet
browser to http://www.boston.com and enter the keyword chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
