<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRING OFF SOME NOT QUITE RANDOM THOUGHTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's just too hot for my mind to hold one thought for long, so
what follows are miscellaneous musings with a common thread.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton made an emotional appeal during a White House
ceremony this week for stiffer penalties against gun owners who
fail to keep firearms out of the reach of children.
</P>
<P>
   My husband and I, legal gun owners both, share our house with a
90-pound German shepherd and a slightly odd cat. No children living
at home. But should a situation occur like the one in Arkansas, in
which a twisted little juvenile illegally enters our secured home,
steals our property and uses it in a heinous act, under Clinton's
proposal we would be held responsible because we didn't keep the
guns locked up _ which would defeat one of the purposes why we own
them in the first place: easy access in the event that our safety
is threatened.
</P>
<P>
   Is this not the craziest logic ever posed as justification for
more controls on law-abiding gun owners? Gun owners with children
living in the house have a moral responsibility to keep firearms
secured. But to hold gun owners legally responsible if a juvenile
steals a gun from their secured home is lunacy.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The volume of response to my column on the Second Amendment was
awesome. I'd like to share some of the thoughts that came in from
across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``What many politicians who favor more restrictive gun laws
don't get is that crime is all about behavior,'' wrote Capt. James
D. Eisel of the Department of Public Safety at Michigan's Wayne
State University. ``It's simple, really. A lot of people are
misbehaving, sometimes violently, and sometimes they use firearms.
Removing firearms won't change their behavior, only the weapon they
will use. Changing behavior takes time and legislation can't do it.
Parents and society must effect this change, but this solution is
unacceptable to those who want immediate results. And so the real
problem and solution are invisible to those who earnestly, but
mistakenly, strive to control violent crime by controlling guns.''
</P>
<P>
   C.D. Blair of Charleston, W.V., wrote: ``Regarding the recent
spate of youthful violence, I fear that we have neglected for some
years to instill in our children the values necessary for them to
restrain their violent (and natural) impulses, and I'd rather see a
serious public health/education movement to correct this than a
blanket banning of the tools they have used to express their
discontent.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard L. Sellers, a native Texan who is in his second term as
sheriff of Aiken County, S.C., wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``In a free society, the idea of government protecting us from
ourselves by vesting authority and power only in that government is
an invitation to a loss of that freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a career member of the law enforcement establishment, first
on the federal level, now locally elected, I am constantly
frustrated that we cannot legally act to intercept a known criminal
on the basis of what he or she might do, but at the same time we
consider denial of weapons to responsible citizens on the premise
that they might misuse them.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The central Queensland coast of Australia has a problem with
roaming packs of hungry dingoes that are terrorizing its human
inhabitants. The wild dogs have taken to stalking people in their
hunt for food.
</P>
<P>
   Here in the good ol' U.S. of A., the answer to that problem
would be easy: Wild dog bites man; man shoots dog. But our friends
Down Under don't have that option. Australia has some of the
toughest gun laws on the books; individual gun ownership is nigh on
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Seems every dog will have its day Down Under.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is a senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Her e-mail address is
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com, and her phone number is (817)
390-7599. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
