<HEADER>
A9324 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LETHALWEAPON-SEQUELS-     07-10 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LETHALWEAPON-SEQUELS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR DEGREES OF `LETHAL WEAPON'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the ``Lethal Weapon'' series started 11 years ago, it was
fairly simple: two mismatched detectives vs. virtually
indestructible bad guys.
</P>
<P>
   As the sequels came, two good guys just weren't enough. Each new
entry has added a good guy, to the point where ``Lethal Weapon 4''
(which opened Friday) has five actors sharing poster space.
</P>
<P>
   The bad guys have been used more economically, usually one
super-villain leading an army of goons. Here's a look at the
series' evolution:
</P>
<P>
   ``Lethal Weapon'' (1987)
</P>
<P>
   The good guys: Mel Gibson and Danny Glover are unlikely partners
Martin Riggs and Roger Murtaugh. Riggs, near-suicidal after the
death of his wife, will do just about anything to save the day;
Murtaugh is a family man who prefers that his life stay calm.
</P>
<P>
   The bad guys: Gary Busey, with a peroxide 'do, is Joshua, a
killer even more psychotic than Riggs; he's a sidekick to the
General (veteran heavy Mitchell Ryan), leader of a drug ring.
</P>
<P>
   Memorable scene: Riggs stops a suicide by handcuffing himself to
the guy and jumping off a building with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lethal Weapon 2'' (1989)
</P>
<P>
   The good guys: Joe Pesci joins Riggs and Murtaugh as Leo Getz,
an annoying, noisy, motor-mouthed and did we mention annoying
two-bit hustler who ``helps'' the cops in their fight against South
African gold smugglers.
</P>
<P>
   The bad guy: Joss Ackland is easily the series' best villain as
Arjen Rudd, who uses diplomatic immunity to get away with murder.
</P>
<P>
   Memorable scene: Riggs uses a truck to tear the bad guys'
elevated mansion off its foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lethal Weapon 3'' (1992)
</P>
<P>
   The good guys: Rene Russo joins Riggs, Murtaugh and Getz as
Lorna Cole, an Internal Affairs cop so tough that her idea of
foreplay is comparing scars with Riggs.
</P>
<P>
   The bad guy: Stuart Wilson is the series' weakest villain as
Jack Travis, an ex-cop turned weapons dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Memorable scene: The series' lamest entry starts off with a long
bomb-defusing gag in a parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lethal Weapon 4'' (1998)
</P>
<P>
   The good guys: Chris Rock joins Riggs, Murtaugh, Getz and Cole
as Lee Butters, a young, gung-ho detective with an unusual fondness
for Murtaugh _ but not for the reasons Murtaugh thinks. They go
after Chinese smugglers/slave traders/counterfeiters.
</P>
<P>
   The bad guy: Asian actor star Jet Li brings back delicious
villainy as Wah Sing Ku, whose martial-arts moves are too much for
Riggs and Murtaugh. Well, almost too much.
</P>
<P>
   Memorable scene: In one of the best chase scenes in years, Riggs
water-skis down a freeway on the underside of a dining-room table.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
