<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 15:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9327 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHARKS-$ADV13-COX     07-10 0403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARKS-$ADV13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REPORT SAYS SHARK PROTECTION EFFORTS LAG
 &HT;    For release Monday, July 13
 &HT;    By DANIELLE SHOOK
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal efforts to protect endangered sharks in the
Atlantic Ocean and Gulf of Mexico are being hampered by a lack of
state regulation, an environmental coalition reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two decades, shark populations in the Atlantic and
Gulf regions have declined by as much as 85 percent. To counter
this trend, the National Marine Fisheries Service five years ago
created a plan to prevent overfishing of sharks in federally
controlled waters.
</P>
<P>
   However, the report, ``Sharks on the Line,'' noted that sharks'
seasonal migration brings them inside the federal three-mile limit,
where they often fall prey to fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juvenile mortality must be reduced to speed the recovery of
large coastal sharks,'' said the report's author, Dr. Merry Camhi,
a staff scientist at the Audubon Society. ``The best way to do this
is to reduce fishing in nursery grounds, which primarily occur in
state waters.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ellen Pikitch, director of fisheries programs for the
Wildlife Conservation Society, said that ``even if all fishing of
large coastal sharks were to cease, recovery could take decades.''
</P>
<P>
   The report by the Ocean Wildlife Campaign ranked Florida, which
has by far the most active commercial shark fishery in the region,
first among 18 states for responsible management of the shark
catch.
</P>
<P>
   But it recommended that most states in the region take one or
more of the following steps:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Closing of state waters to shark fishing during federal
closure periods.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Imposing limits on the number and size of sharks allowed to be
caught.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Prohibiting the catching or possession of species protected in
federal waters.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Banning finning, the process of cutting the fins off live
sharks and dumping the wounded shark back into the water, where it
dies. The fin is then used in the popular shark fin soup.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Ocean Wildlife Campaign are the National Audubon
Society, the National Coalition for Marine Conservation, the
Natural Resources Defense Council, the Wildlife Conservation
Society and the World Wildlife Fund. The group is supported
financially by the Pew Charitable Trusts.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
