A9338 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLU     07-10 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING ATTACHED TO E-MAIL PHOTOS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: My husband cannot send photos (not dirty ones)
from America Online 4.0 to people with older versions of AOL.
What's up with that?
</P>
<P>
   _ Perfectly Innocent
</P>
<P>
   DEAR INNOCENT: Hey, it's not up to me to judge what's dirty and
what isn't _ as long as I get a copy, purely in the interest of
scholarly research, you understand.
</P>
<P>
   The new AOL software gives you two ways to send pictures. You
can embed photos in the body of your letter or you can attach them
to the E-mail, which is the way most of the world already operates.
If hubby mailed somebody an embedded picture of you dusting the
crystal chandelier, the recipient can only see it if he has AOL 4.0
or a really good imagination.
</P>
<P>
   If the photos are attached as separate files, just about anybody
should be able to see what a great housekeeper you are.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: We have Win95 on our PC. We just purchased a
notebook with Win98 installed. Some games will not load in Win98.
Is this the Evil Empire's way of ensuring we are going to retire
broke and have to eat dog food because we must keep buying new
software?
</P>
<P>
   _ Alpo Gourmet
</P>
<P>
   DEAR GOURMET: It's so easy to sit back and blame Big Bill for
every little thing that goes wrong in your pathetic little life,
isn't it? Bill isn't evil. He's a guy just like you or me who
happened to be in the right place at the right time. Do you think
he can't still feel your pain?
</P>
<P>
   Geez, of course not. What were you possibly thinking? This guy
is worth $51 billion, and you're about as important to him as a
gnat is to an elephant. He could buy you, sell you and forget you
in a heartbeat, and the only thing about our lonely existence he
confirms is that a good haircut must cost $52 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But, just this once, it's probably not his fault. Windows 98
shouldn't make that big a difference when it comes to games. It is,
after all, just a spiffed-up version of Win95. My guess is that
your games have some particular hardware requirements _ most likely
video or memory _ that the notebook just isn't up to.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I just bought a refurbished laptop from
somebody for $700. It has Word Perfect and ProComm already loaded.
If this guy can provide software that cheaply, why can't the big
manufacturers do the same and lower prices?
</P>
<P>
   _ Bargain Hunter
</P>
<P>
   DEAR BARGAIN: And I suppose you got certificates of authenticity
and original documentation with all that cheap software? No? I'm so
surprised. Congratulations on your bootlegs. You'll be happy to
know I forwarded your mail to the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Just kidding! They already had your name and address anyway. As
for the guy you bought the stuff from, sleazebuckets like that
ought to be locked up. You don't steal books from the library or
tapes from Blockbuster. Don't steal from software publishers
either.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: My clock keeps perfect time when the PC is on,
but not when it's off. A technician suspects the motherboard is
about to go. Am I being snowed?
</P>
<P>
   _ Complete Novice
</P>
<P>
   DEAR NOVICE: Like Aspen in December. Most PC clocks keep time
about as well as what you get at Free Watch Night at the ballgame.
When you turn on the PC, Windows gets the time from the clock, then
takes over timekeeping and does a much better job. You should get a
time synchronization program from someplace like www.tucows.com to
reset your clock any time you're on the Net. You should also go to
Free Bat Night, then have a serious talk with your technician.
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay offers occasionally
accurate advice about most things electronic. He can be reached on
Internet at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com; via snail-mail at Fort
Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth 76101; or fax: (817)
390-7257. His real name is Michael Gerst, editorial systems manager
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
