<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9340 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONEGIN-BALLET-REVIEW-     07-10 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONEGIN-BALLET-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TOUCHES FOR STUTTGART'S `ONEGIN' 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
(js) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lincoln Center Festival '98 has brought the Stuttgart
Ballet back to New York City with the tried and true. After John
Cranko's ``Romeo and Juliet,'' his ``Onegin,'' the company's
signature piece, introduced new dancers in familiar roles at
Lincoln Center's New York State Theater on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   In this first of three casts, the Korean dancer Sue Jin Kang as
Tatyana, the heroine in love with Onegin, one of Romantic
literature's well-heeled misfits, proved outstanding in her dancing
and acting.
</P>
<P>
   Cranko's three-act treatment of ``Eugene Onegin,'' the great
Russian narrative poem by Aleksandr Pushkin, took New York by storm
in 1969. The opera-house scale of the ballet, its sumptuous decor
by Jurgen Rose, pretty in its pastels and clever in its oversize
lace curtains, tantalized further with its score. Cranko's 1965
ballet did not turn to music from Tchaikovsky's opera about Onegin
but used a persuasive patchwork of other Tchaikovsky music
effectively arranged and orchestrated by Kurt-Heinz Stolze.
</P>
<P>
   To a public yearning for full-evening dramatic ballets,
``Onegin'' was so seductive that company after company throughout
the world snapped up the work for their own repertory. Oddly, the
Joffrey Ballet, which performed Cranko's ``Romeo'' and ``The Taming
of the Shrew'' did not. ``Onegin'' was last seen in New York in
1993, when the Bavarian National Ballet from Munich offered Kirill
Melnikov's sensational and revealing performance in the title role.
</P>
<P>
   This was a performance imbued with Stanislavskian esthetics,
charting the hero's emotional progression from world-weary snob
full of coldness and formality to an Onegin, physically spent and
disheveled in his powerfully projected passion. Perhaps it took a
Russian (Melnikov was once in the Kirov Ballet) to open up the
role's deeper dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of profundity was missing on Wednesday, although the
cast on view did its visible best to fill in the outlines of
clearly sketched roles. One of the problems after Cranko's death in
1973 was that his ballets were so meticulously accurate in their
details that they began to look preserved in amber.
</P>
<P>
   The current production has new touches. Perhaps in an attempt to
revitalize the action, there are broader flourishes. Certainly
Robert Tewsley, a British dancer most recently seen in the National
Ballet of Canada, gives Lensky, Onegin's friend, an unexpectedly
violent edge. Enraged when Onegin flirts with his fiancee, Olga,
this Lensky is anything but Pushkin's (or Tchaikovsky's) gentle
victim. A stylish dancer who keeps to a clean line in the signature
arabesques of Lensky's solos, Tewsley challenges Onegin to a duel
in a rage that goes over the top. One expected Onegin to be killed,
but of course it is Lensky who is shot by Onegin. In that duel
scene, Cranko offers some of his silliest choreography: Lensky is
caught in a tug of war between Olga and Tatyana or is sandwiched
between the two women.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all such lapses when Cranko misfired in his search for
an expressive use of the academic idiom, he was essentially a
classical choreographer with a firm theatrical touch. One can
quarrel with dramatic details: Would the mature Tatyana at the end
really show Onegin the door by pointing her finger after he
realizes his mistake in rejecting her years ago?
</P>
<P>
   This ``Onegin'' is more Cranko than Pushkin, and Ms. Kang's
concentrated performance showed how well she understood her role.
Trained in South Korea and Monte Carlo after winning a top prize at
the Prix de Lausanne competition in 1985, she joined the Stuttgart
the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Her toe work is strong and she was fearless in the tosses and
lifts of the duets that Cranko employs to develop Tatyana's
relationship with Onegin. In his most brilliant theatrical device,
Cranko gives physical shape to the famous love letter that the
young Tatyana writes to Onegin. A mirror dance with a double leads
to a fantasy love scene where rapture soars through the
choreography's twists and arching shapes.
</P>
<P>
   The counterpoint of this pas de deux is the farewell when
Tatyana, remaining faithful to an elderly husband (Ivan Cavallari),
rejects Onegin in turn. Roland Vogel as Onegin was more than
impressive as a partner and less than persuasive as Onegin.
Cranko's distilled gestures (hand to brow) encouraged him to go
through the motions rather than the emotions of his role.
</P>
<P>
   If he was too refined, Elena Tentschikova's Olga lacked nuance.
But Ms. Kang, progressing from intimidated adolescent to a complex
character, knew how to shade her performance. It was her show.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart Kershaw, now with the Pacific Northwest Ballet in
Seattle, was the guest conductor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
