<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUMPROPE-CHAMPIONS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZIPPIN' ZEBRA SKIPPERS TAKE MEDALS IN NATIONAL JUMP ROPE
COMPETITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL BOURGEOIS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRANDVIEW, Texass _ The ZZ's are tops.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas has the Cowboys, Stars and Mavericks. Arlington has the
Rangers. Grandview has the Zippin' Zebra Skippers. But unlike those
other teams, the ZZ Skippers, as they are more commonly known, can
boast of some national titles this year in the rarefied world of
jump rope.
</P>
<P>
   Four Zebras walked away with national titles last week at the
National Jump Rope Championship at Walt Disney World in Orlando,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Brandy McDonald, 13, competing in the 12- to 14-year-old
category, was tops in the single-rope speed jumping competition.
She jumped 302 times in one minute, or about five times a second.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no trick,'' this no-nonsense champ said. ``I just do it,
but it takes a lot of practice.''
</P>
<P>
   In the double-dutch (two ropes going in opposite directions)
speed relay, the 11-year-old team of Kalyn Gaston, Brittany
Richardson and Melissa Baird also took the gold. They jumped 590
times in two minutes. They said it has taken four years of practice
and teamwork.
</P>
<P>
   Why do they do it?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun,'' they said, almost in unison.
</P>
<P>
   The team of Jena Rhine, Kyla Johnson, Molly Buker and Brandy
McDonald, all 13, took the silver in the double-dutch pairs speed
competition and the bronze medal in the double-dutch pairs
freestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Harvey (one of five boys on the team), Natalie Deloach and
Brandy McDonald, all 13, won the silver medal in the double-dutch
single freestyle.
</P>
<P>
   This was the team's third trip to the nationals, but it was the
first time any Zebra brought home a medal.
</P>
<P>
   The team started about seven years ago when Trina Griffith, a
rookie physical education teacher at Grandview Elementary School,
had a brainstorm.
</P>
<P>
   Her kids were doing Jump Rope for Heart, an annual event
sponsored in most schools by the American Heart Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw that the kids could learn the tricks,'' Griffith said.
It was also a sport in which everyone can participate. And so a
team was formed.
</P>
<P>
   From 15 the first year, it has grown to about 70 this year, but
only 21 traveled to Orlando for the national championships, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   How the ZZ Skippers helped raise money for the trip is as
unusual as the sport itself.
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raiser involved 40 life-size pink plastic flamingos and
a scheme that bordered on extortion.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, many of the 1,200 people in this quiet
southern Johnson County community awoke to find a herd of 10 pink
plastic flamingos grazing in their front yards.
</P>
<P>
   For any cash donation to the team, the flamingos were removed.
For $25 you could buy ``insurance'' that they wouldn't come back
and the right to send the flamingos to a friend or neighbor of your
choice.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith said some people actually felt left out if the
flamingos didn't show up in their yard.
</P>
<P>
   The flamingos raised $3,600.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith said jump rope has a camaraderie sometimes lacking in
other events.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not cutthroat. Everybody shares tricks,'' she said. It
provides an extensive aerobic workout and the equipment isn't
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   One jump-rope mom, Karen Richardson, said the kids also don't
have to be as tall or strong or fast as they might have to be to
play football or basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that the elementary kids can do. They don't
have to wait for middle school to participate in a sport and it
gets them in great shape,'' Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just have a good time,'' said Kay Gaston, another
jump-rope mom. ``They travel all over, make new friends. As a
parent, this is one of the best organizations I've ever had my kids
involved in.''
</P>
<P>
   The kids said the travel is one of the best things about it.
</P>
<P>
   They've attended tournaments all over Texas and traveled to New
Orleans and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith said they are also ]one of seven All Star Demonstration
Teams in Texas for the American Heart Association's Jump Rope for
Heart.
</P>
<P>
   They average about 40 performances a year at schools, churches,
civic clubs, parades and festivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We even do family reunions,'' Griffith said.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, they plan to go back to the nationals, providing they
can raise the money.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith said she has a garage full of pink plastic flamingos
that might be some help.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
