<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Managing editors, weekend editors)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service calls your attention to the
following religion features.
</P>
<P>
   Photos, where indicated, have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphics, where indicated, have been sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   For retransmission of these stories, call 212-556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEWS AND FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-ST.NICHOLAS-NYT (Demre, Turkey) _ In the 1950s local
businessmen guessed that the legend of Santa Claus might be Demre's
ticket back to prosperity. Since then the Turkish government has
claimed St. Nicholas, a 4th century bishop here _ and by extension
Santa _ as its own, issuing a stamp in his honor and sponsoring
conferences here to honor his memory. In 1981 a statue of him,
looking remarkably like the popular image of Santa minus the
potbelly, was built here. By Stephen Kinzer. Moved 7-8. WITH
GRAPHIC and PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENTOLOGY-MINTON-BOS (Undated) _ Robert Minton, a Boston
multimillionaire who retired in 1992 at age 46, is engaged in a
crusade against the Church of Scientology instead of sitting back
and enjoying his financial success. He says he believes in the
First Amendment; has the money to fight the church and what he
calls its harassment of critics and former church members; and
because he cannot forget being locked up at age 16 in a mental
institution against his will. By Patti Doten. Moved 7-9. WITH
GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   HINDU-HUGGING-NYT (New York) _ The line of people seated
crosslegged on the floor snaked the length of the Universalist
Church, as young and old, healthy and infirm waited their turn for
a hug from a sari-clad woman with a diamond in her nose. But it was
no ordinary hug of affection that drew admirers worldwide to Mata
Amritandandamayi, an Indian guru whose name means ``mother of
immortal bliss.'' By Nadine Brozan. Moved 7-7.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-CHURCH-ATTENDANCE-NYT (Rome) _ Hoping to shake his flock
loose from the grip of secular pastimes and preoccupations, Pope
John Paul II reminded Catholics on Tuesday of their obligation to
attend Sunday Mass. By Alessandra Stanley. Moved 7-7.
</P>
<P>
   AFGHANISTAN-NYT (United Nations) _ The Islamic Taliban movement,
which rules most of Afghanistan, has given the people 15 days to
get rid of their TV sets or see them smashed by the religious
police. VCRs, videotapes and satellite dishes were also ordered to
disappear by Afghanistan's minister for the prevention of vice and
the promotion of virtue, who reports to the Ministry of Religion.
By Barbara Crossette. Moved 7-9.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-CHURCHES-NYT (Jerusalem) _ Another dimension of the
ancient and complex struggle for the Holy City: the first public
manifestation of an ancient dispute between Arab members of the
Orthodox Church, one of the largest Christian communities in the
region, and the Greek church officials who for centuries have
controlled the Jerusalem Orthodox Patriarchate. The Orthodox Church
is majr landowner, and Arab Christians are protesting its sale of
some of that land to Jews. By Serge Schmemann. Moved 7-4.
</P>
<P>
   NY-CLERGYMAN-COCAINE-NYT (New York) _ The director of an
important pre-seminary program to help college students interested
in the priesthood, Msgr. James White was emerging as a role model,
one of the few prominent black priests in an archdiocese concerned
about expanding its reach within the black community. Yet that
stellar background has only deepened the sense of tragedy felt by
White's friends and fellow priests after his arrest on cocaine
charges. By James Risen. Moved 7-8.
</P>
<P>
   CATHOLICS-DEBATE-NYT (Undated) _ In issuing an apostolic letter
this week deeming some of the most controversial issues within the
Roman Catholic Church beyond debate _ including euthanasia, the
ordination of women and sexual relations outside marriage _ Pope
John Paul II ignited new debate among Roman Catholics in the U.S.
By Nadine Brozan. Moved 7-3.
</P>
<P>
   ROME-RELIGIOUSSITES-TEX (Rome) _ Rome's religious sites make for
a spellbinding pilgrimage A look at some of the Eternal City's
locations associated with Peter, Paul and other figures in
Christianity. By Jim Jones. Moved 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS (Undated) _ Catholic educators finally see a
small crack in the door between public and private schools that has
been firmly shut for decades. But Thomas Groome, a theologian and
expert on Catholic education, thinks the country still does not
fully understand why Catholic education is so appealing to
Catholics and non-Catholics: teaching with values. By Diego
Ribadeneira. Moved 7-8.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT (New York) _ Brooklyn's Plymouth Church,
whose pulpit was once occupied by Henry Ward Beecher, recently
discovered an 1849 time capsule. The idea of creating a new time
capsule, to give a broad range of information about the current
church and its members, has offered the congregation an unusual
opportunity to think about its identity and its hopes for the
future. By Gustav Niebuhr. Moved 7-3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
