   TURKEY-ST.NICHOLAS-NYT (Demre, Turkey) _ In the 1950s local
businessmen guessed that the legend of Santa Claus might be Demre's
ticket back to prosperity. Since then the Turkish government has
claimed St. Nicholas, a 4th century bishop here _ and by extension
Santa _ as its own, issuing a stamp in his honor and sponsoring
conferences here to honor his memory. In 1981 a statue of him,
looking remarkably like the popular image of Santa minus the
potbelly, was built here. By Stephen Kinzer. Moved 7-8. WITH
GRAPHIC and PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENTOLOGY-MINTON-BOS (Undated) _ Robert Minton, a Boston
multimillionaire who retired in 1992 at age 46, is engaged in a
crusade against the Church of Scientology instead of sitting back
and enjoying his financial success. He says he believes in the
First Amendment; has the money to fight the church and what he
calls its harassment of critics and former church members; and
because he cannot forget being locked up at age 16 in a mental
institution against his will. By Patti Doten. Moved 7-9. WITH
GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   HINDU-HUGGING-NYT (New York) _ The line of people seated
crosslegged on the floor snaked the length of the Universalist
Church, as young and old, healthy and infirm waited their turn for
a hug from a sari-clad woman with a diamond in her nose. But it was
no ordinary hug of affection that drew admirers worldwide to Mata
Amritandandamayi, an Indian guru whose name means ``mother of
immortal bliss.'' By Nadine Brozan. Moved 7-7.
</P>
