<P>
   For Saturday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-U.S.-EUROPE (Washington) _ Barry McCaffrey, who heads the
White House war on narcotics, goes to Europe Saturday to boost
international cooperation in the anti-drug effort and to learn what
other nations are doing to prevent substance abuse. By NICOLE
TSONG.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-DISNEY (Austin, Texas) _ The State Board of Education
votes 8-4 to sell off its estimated $43 million in Walt Disney Co.
stock because of the company's adult-oriented movies. The vote fell
strictly along party lines, with Democrats opposing the sales or
abstaining from taking a stand. By KATHY WALT.
</P>
<P>
   AGENTS-GUNS (Harlingen, Texas) _ The assault rifle used to kill
two U.S. Border Patrol officers and wound a deputy sheriff is owned
by the Harlingen Police Department and was issued to police
detective R.D. Moore, the father of the suspect in Tuesday's
homicides, a source involved in the investigation says. By JAMES
PINKERTON.
</P>
<P>
   AGENTS-FUNERALS (Harlingen, Texas) _ Services are held for the
two U.S. Border Patrol agents killed while assisting local law
enforcement officers pursue a suspect. Attorney General Janet Reno
attended separate services for Susan Lynn Rodriguez, 28, and rookie
agent Ricardo Guillermo Salinas, 24. By NATHALIE TREPANIER and JOHN
MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ECUADOR-ELECTION (Quito, Ecuador) _ Desperate for a dynamic
leader, Ecuadoreans will head to the polls Sunday for a
presidential runoff election. The winner will begin a four-year
term Aug. 10 and attempt to restore a measure of stability to this
battered nation of 12 million people. By JOHN OTIS.
</P>
<P>
   ECUADOR-CUP (Quito, Ecuador) _ When asked who will win on
Sunday, the day of this nation's presidential runoff, some
Ecuadoreans say it's no contest: Brazil in a blowout. Brazil? Yes,
Sunday is also the day of the World Cup final and that could affect
voter turnout. By JOHN OTIS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SOC-WORLD-CUP (Paris) _ As the World Cup nears its conclusion
with Sunday's championship game, we take a look back at the highs
and lows, the best and worst of the monthlong soccer festival. By
JOHN P. LOPEZ.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (St. Louis) _ The Houston Astros try to make it two
in a row over the St. Louis Cardinals as they send pitcher Mike
Hampton to the mound in the second game of a four-game series. By
CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   With: BBN-MICKEY
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-IMF (Washington) _ As the House returns Monday, Speaker
Newt Gingrich appears set to rekindle a bitter debate over U.S.
funding for the International Monetary Fund that could pit him
against his own leadership team. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   MANAGED-CARE (Washington) _ This is the summer of managed care
in the nation's capital and on the campaign trail. Both parties are
scrambling to tap voter frustration over the system that now
accounts for more than 80 percent of employer-sponsored health-care
coverage in the United States. By DAN FREEDMAN. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ For Americans, President
Clinton's trip to China was little more than a blip on the radar
screen of history. But for millions of Chinese, especially the
young, his message that democracy and freedom are an inevitable
part of their country's future will resonate for generations. By
ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Filed Thursday)
</P>
