<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9369 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FALLTELEVISION-TEX     07-10 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALLTELEVISION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HITS AND MYTHS: WHAT GETS ON TV _ AND STAYS THERE _ IS ANYBODY'S
GUESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hits and flops come and go with such regularity in the
television industry that they are mostly taken for granted. To
better understand why is to know that only 27 of the 128 new
prime-time programs ordered by the major networks over the past
four seasons were welcomed back. And seven of those switched
networks.
</P>
<P>
   Call this the throw-mud-against-the-wall-and-see-what-sticks way
of doing business _ which I'm sure punches holes in your theory
that sane reasoning was behind, say, UPN's decision to unearth
``Love Boat: The Next Generation'' from its watery depths.
</P>
<P>
   Even with millions of dollars at stake in the production,
promotion and airing of series programming, snagging a hit these
days appears to be about that simple and _ let's be candid _
senseless.
</P>
<P>
   The network executives know it, the show producers sense it, the
actors deny it and, unfortunately, viewers experience it. When one
series fails, another like it merely emerges to happily take its
place, continuing a cycle that hinges on a viewer's short-term
memory.
</P>
<P>
   This appears to be the sentiment as the networks showcase their
rookie stock for the 1998-'99 season to the nation's TV press over
the next three hype-filled weeks. Before us: 37 new series, many
cloned and clunky, carrying unwanted buzz or having little or no
buzz to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, sure, a giddy WB will arrive with ``Felicity,'' a promising
drama about an introspective coed (Keri Russell) who'll remind you
of a collegiate Ally McBeal. And the 38-minute tape provided on the
WB drama ``Hyperion'' (with a surprisingly effective Mark-Paul
Gosselaar of ``Saved by the Bell'') caught my interest, believe it
or not.
</P>
<P>
   But after that, the pickings I've viewed are so thin it's
troubling. NBC, the No. 1 network in terms of viewership, offers
Nathan Lane and his ``Encore! Encore!,'' a sitcom from the
``Frasier'' creators, who have pretty much ripped off themselves.
High-brow humor will fly as Lane plays a snobby opera singer
returning home to live with his low-brow family.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Olin, back for more abuse after ``EZ Streets,'' will pitch
hard for ``L.A. Docs'' on CBS, which is an ``L.A. Law'' with
stethoscopes, while in ``The Kings of Queens,'' Kevin James
(''Everybody Loves Raymond'') plays yet another pudgy working-class
stiff having to deal with a live-in interruption of his
testosterone activities. (The networks continue to look for the
next ``Roseanne.)''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from ABC's decision to remake ``Fantasy Island'' (this one
with Malcolm McDowell as Mr. Roarke) nothing is more bothersome
than CBS' green light to clone another ``60 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   More than any other, the ``60 Minutes'' move represents the
nervousness among programmers these days as they try to figure out
how to lure viewers back into the fold. CBS basically was forced to
keep pace with NBC, which now has ``Dateline NBC'' stretched over
five nights; ABC, which has combined ``PrimeTime Live'' with
``20/20''; and even CNN, which has just launched three newsmags.
</P>
<P>
   With profits high and ratings better than sitcoms or dramas
appearing in the same time period, the seven-night-a-week
newsmagazine might not be far behind.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? Hit series are becoming harder to find as audiences
continue to give more time to nontraditional channels like Comedy
Central (''South Park'') and even mininetworks like The WB, whose
savvy, aggressive style in creating shows like ``Buffy the Vampire
Slayer'' and ``Dawson's Creek'' has made it a serious contender to
knock off Fox as the hip programmer of choice for the highly
coveted young viewer.
</P>
<P>
   (Talk among the critics is that it has already replaced Fox as
the network of choice when it comes to attending its evening
entertainment events; stars AND poolside dancing!)
</P>
<P>
   How bad is it? According to Nielsen numbers, the network share
of prime-time audience since 1994 has fallen from 68 percent to a
projected 58 percent. This is significant because it's the first
time the networks have controlled less than 60 percent of the
available audience.
</P>
<P>
   And cable smells blood. Having already made TV movies look
laughably amateurish by comparison (except for the consistently
stellar ``Hallmark Hall of Fame'' or ``Oprah Winfrey Presents ...''
franchises), HBO and Showtime are now attacking with some half-hour
and hour series high in quality and risk-taking subject matter. On
Aug. 1, Showtime will offer ``Lincs,'' a black-cast comedy starring
Pam Grier, and ``Rude Awakenings,'' with Sherilyn Fenn.
</P>
<P>
   Since USA silenced skeptics with its thoughtful version of the
feature film ``La Femme Nikita,'' talk is increasing on how it will
handle ``The Net,'' a takeoff of the Sandra Bullock film about a
woman fighting to win back the identity stolen from her via
technology. It begins July 19. Even Lifetime leaps into the mix
with three original series in August.
</P>
<P>
   During the next few weeks, the networks will trot out a range of
stars. Some are spinning off from longtime shows (''Murphy
Brown's'' Faith Ford as a new single in CBS' ``Maggie Winters'').
Some are returning to television (Shannen Doherty as a modern-day
witch in The WB's ``Charmed''). Others show up after coming up
empty on the big screen (Moira Kelly of the romantic comedy drama
``To Have and to Hold'' on CBS).
</P>
<P>
   That audiences have traditionally been unfazed by big names (Ted
Danson's sitcom crashed and burned, as did shows headed by Gregory
Hines and Danny Aiello), perhaps the key is the material
surrounding them.
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on a talent pool sucked dry. Not only are casts being
stocked with second-rate performers, but second-rate writers are
doling out the lines. No wonder we're witnessing more newsmagazines
and reality shows like ``World's Scariest Police Chases.'' They
attract ratings and make money.
</P>
<P>
   And the cost of programming continues to rise. ``ER'' set a new
standard for the cost of a regular series at $13 million an
episode. This season, Helen Hunt (who probably won't appear at the
press tour; she doesn't need the ink) and co-star Paul Reiser (who
probably will make an appearance; he needs the ink) will pocket $1
million for each episode of NBC's ``Mad About You.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it supply and demand, not to mention being in the right
place at the right time. Needing to secure the veteran show after
losing ``Seinfeld,'' NBC negotiated with Hunt shortly before her
Oscar win for ``As Good as It Gets.'' Not a bad deal for stars of a
series that failed to crack the Nielsen top 30, finishing behind
``Hiller and Diller'' and ``Soul Man,'' both ABC casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, it's the simple, senseless world of network television. Pay
first and think second. Who knows? Something might stick.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is television critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Contact him at (817) 390-7862. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
