<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9379 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-10 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOM'S AND DAD'S EASY-PC ADVENTURE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Personal computers are a lot easier to set up and use than they
used to be, according to the monolithic industry that builds and
sells them. But as anyone without a degree in computer science will
tell you, they're not easy enough.
</P>
<P>
   In order to use a PC so it becomes a pleasure rather than a
hassle, users still need to know the basics of how it works. For
example, they must understand the concepts of where files are
stored in order to be able to retrieve something downloaded from
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Computer makers say their current crop of machines, combined
with Microsoft's new Windows 98 operating system, is easier to use
than ever. I decided to put that to the test, but I needed some
help. I've set up and tested so many PCs that it's hard for me to
really know what novices will think. I needed a newbie's
perspective; so I called upon two people who have helped me out
time and again throughout my life: dear old mom and dad.
</P>
<P>
   My parents are not completely computer illiterate, but they're
close. They've had a hand-me-down PC that uses an older 80486 chip
for about 18 months. They know how to turn it on, get onto the
Internet via America Online, send e-mail to family members, play a
few simple games and browse through CD-ROM-based encyclopedias.
</P>
<P>
   But, like many novice users, they don't understand the plumbing
of the Windows 95 file system. They don't snap to the difference
between America Online's content and that of the Internet. When I
tell them to launch the AOL browser, they say, ``What's that?''
</P>
<P>
   They aren't dumb. It's just that the vagaries of the personal
computer are not second nature to them, which is the case with many
who have not grown up with PCs omnipresent in the home and
workplace. They don't want to know how the damn thing works _ they
just want it to work, period, and be easy to use.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq Computer Corp. agreed to be the technology guinea pig in
a little experiment with my parents. The Houston company just
launched a new line of consumer PCs, which the company claims is
its friendliest yet, with pushbuttons on the keyboard for launching
Internet services and favorite programs. The Presarios come with
software that makes it easy to download updated drivers and other
software for keeping the PC in top shape.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq is loaning them one of these machines for about a month.
They are trying out a Presario 2254, the lowest-end system, and a
14-inch MV400 monitor. I took the system to their home in Corpus
Christi over the Fourth of July weekend and watched as they set it
up.
</P>
<P>
   Well, actually, not ``they,'' but he. My mother had no interest
in assembling the thing. Now, my father, who is in his late 60s, is
as mechanically inclined as they come. I remember watching him
restore a Triumph TR3 sports car when I was a child, and the week
before I drove down there he designed and built an all-wood patio
cover over his back porch.
</P>
<P>
   But he admitted being intimidated about setting up a new PC,
just because it was a computer. ``I'm always intimidated by
something I'm not in complete control of,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The 2254, which sells for just $899, is aimed at novice users
who don't want to spend a lot of money on a system, but don't want
to be stuck with a slow, out-of-date machine. It is not fancy, but
it's more than adequate, with a 233-megahertz Advanced Micro
Devices K6 processor; 32 megabytes of memory; a four-gigabyte hard
drive; a 56K fax modem; and a 64-bit 3-D graphics card. It comes in
a desktop, rather than a mini-tower case.
</P>
<P>
   As with most consumer PCs, it comes with a poster that uses
pictures to show how the PC should be assembled. Also, most of the
connections that need to be made are color-coded _ for example, the
green keyboard plug goes into a socket on the back of the unit
that's rimmed in green. Both of these features were a great help to
my father.
</P>
<P>
   But there were three points at which his progress came to a dead
halt. If I had not been there, he would have given up and called
technical support.
</P>
<P>
   The first involved hardware. The speakers that come with the
monitor must be joined together, and then connected to the back of
the PC. The poster just showed the cable from one speaker linking
with the other, but didn't show the connections, which are standard
RCA male-female stereo jacks. My father's not into stereo systems,
so he didn't recognize the plugs, and relying on the poster left
him baffled.
</P>
<P>
   The second snag came when he installed the drivers for his
printer. Windows 95's setup routine wanted to look in a particular
folder on the hard drive where other drivers are kept. My father
kept clicking on the OK button, only to be told the driver couldn't
be found.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't realize that you had to tell Windows to look in a
different place _ the floppy drive, which is A: _ to find the disk
he'd just inserted. Although he's used that 80486 machine for some
time, he's seldom had to use the floppy, and it didn't occur to him
from what he saw on the screen that he needed to direct Windows'
attention to it. He also didn't know that it's drive A:. I suspect
a lot of novices get stuck at this point.
</P>
<P>
   The final problem involved America Online's software, which came
with an old list of modems that did not include the high-speed, new
Presario model. We could not get the modem to connect to the
high-speed dialup number in Corpus Christi for AOL, and had to fall
back to a lowly 14.4K line just to connect. Once we signed on, AOL
downloaded a set of updated modem information and the software then
worked as it should. But again, if I had not been there, my parents
would have had to suffer with AOL's tech support line before
figuring out to fall back to the slower dialup number.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the real test, with the machine in place. My parents
will live with this system for a month, and I'll report back on how
they did. I figure letting them use a system designed for novices
is the ultimate test of any PC's user-friendliness.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dwight Silverman can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and questions to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000 and enter
access code 1001. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
