<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9383 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZWEEK-ART-$ADV12-NY     07-10 1290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZWEEK-ART-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WEEK IN BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 12) 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (jt)  
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; TAXING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Charm School for the IRS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A bill to rework the IRS cleared Congress by an overwhelming
vote. It aims to reduce the fear that the agency strikes in the
hearts of taxpayers and to increase the help it gives to citizens
on the complex tax code. The bill, which President Clinton said he
would speedily sign, also strengthens the role of a taxpayer
advocate. The small number of people who get into serious disputes
with the agency receive new rights and protections, and the burden
of proof will fall on the agency, instead of on the taxpayer. And
the bill has something even for those people already on good terms
with the IRS: It reduces to 12 months, from 18 months, the time
that investors must hold stocks, bonds and other assets to qualify
for the lowest capital gains tax rate, which is 20 percent for most
people.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SAVING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Einstein Bond &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The government is bringing out savings bonds linked to the
inflation rate. The bonds have denominations ranging from $50 to
$10,000, and bear the likenesses of heroes including Helen Keller,
Martin Luther King Jr. and Albert Einstein. The Clinton
administration hopes that the 30-year bonds, the first of which go
on sale in September, will appeal to small investors saving for
college costs or retirement. Like other saving bonds, they offer
special tax benefits. As long as investors hold the bonds, they may
defer paying taxes on their earnings, which are reinvested and
added to the principal. If the bond is redeemed to pay for college
tuition, investors may exclude part or all of the interest in
calculating their income taxes. About one in three households own
savings bonds.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE MEDIA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New Era at New Yorker &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Tina Brown, the editor who transformed The New Yorker, for
better or worse, is leaving to work at a new venture owned by
Disney's Miramax films unit. The new venture puts her in
collaboration with Harvey Weinstein, right, a co-chairman of
Miramax, and Ron Galotti, center, who quit as publisher of
Vogue.The idea is to invent a magazine from scratch to dig up the
kind of articles that might be turned into movies and television
specials. An editor with a flair for show business, Ms. Brown
transformed The New Yorker from a venerated icon that some said was
verging on irrelevance into a kind of news magazine of the power
elite. It won awards and new readers during her six years at the
helm, but lost money for the publisher, Conde Nast. But S.I.
Newhouse Jr., the owner, ruled out major changes, and said he would
pick an editor who would make him both ``comfortable and excited.''
Whomever that may be, the days when The New Yorker was famous for
high-quality literary journalism and humor, mixed with sometimes
seemingly endless articles on obscure topics, may be long gone.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ACCESSORIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Southern Style &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Saks Fifth Avenue, another New York landmark, is getting a
Southern owner, Proffitt's Inc., which is paying a hefty $2.1
billion for the 96-store chain. Proffitt's itself runs 234 stores
that serve middle-income shoppers in the South and Midwest, at the
Proffitt's, Younkers, Carson Pirie Scott and Herberger's chains.
The company will change its name to Saks Inc., to win some of the
glamour and air of fashion savvy of the acquired chain, which
carries goods by Gucci, de la Renta and Saint Laurent. Through
acquisition, Proffitt's has built itself into the fourth-largest
department store company in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIABILITY I &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Accord on Breast Implants &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Dow Corning agreed to pay $3.2 billion to settle tens of
thousands of claims of injury from silicone breast implants. The
tentative agreement would end a legal battle of nearly a decade and
let the plaintiffs receive money as early as next year. It would
also enable Dow Corning to emerge from bankruptcy proceedings. But
the agreement leaves unresolved the dispute over the extent of harm
from silicone implants. Dow Corning, supported by a growing body of
research, has denied throughout the battle that implants cause
systemic illness like autoimmune disorders. One of the plaintiffs,
Peggy Pardo, said Dow Corning would get on with business, and the
women would get on with their lives, but ``a lot of them have been
destroyed.'' Upwards of a million American women received implants
in the 1970s and 1980s. The manufacturers, besieged by lawsuits,
had agreed in 1993 to settle all litigation with a payout of $4
billion, but that deal fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIABILITY II &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; No Lid on Damages &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A move in Congress to limit big jury awards for injuries caused
by faulty products suffered defeat, leaving the issue stuck again
in the legislative wilderness, perhaps for years. Republicans
backed the measure but failed to win the 60 votes needed in the
Senate to end a filibuster. The bill would have provided nationwide
standards including broad immunity for retailers and wholesalers
and would have limited punitive damages for small companies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SNEAKERS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `Shaq Attack' Falls Short &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Reebok and its rivals are beginning to back away from costly
dependence on stars to deliver the buzz to lift sales. Reebok and
Nike have reported quarterly losses, and Reebok canceled its $3
million-a-year marketing deal with 7-foot-1 Shaquille O'Neal, whose
Shaq Attack sneaker failed to deliver what Reebok counted on.
``Even Dennis Rodman didn't work for Converse,'' said Bob Williams,
whose company, Burns Sports, matches athletes and advertisers. Many
teen-agers have turned to casual footwear by the likes of Doc
Martens and Timberland.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE INTERNET &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Stratospheric Stocks &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most Internet companies, Yahoo actually makes a small
profit, and that has sent its stock to stratospheric levels. The
tiny company runs the most popular sites on the World Wide Web, and
after reporting higher earnings last week, its market value shot up
to nearly $9 billion _ yes, that's billion. And Amazon.com, the
money-losing online bookstore, is valued at $5.3 billion, more than
Barnes &AMP; Noble and Borders Group combined.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ECONOMIC MEDICINE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Russia Wants Another Dose &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Internet can rescue Russia if the IMF cannot.
Russia's economy is plenty sick, and the patient and doctor are
bickering. The Russians say they need $10 billion to $15 billion
from the lenders, and some investment bankers say it really needs
$20 billion. But the IMF is short of cash after gigantic bailouts
of Asian countries. The fund is indicating that it may come up with
only $5.6 billion and is putting pressure on Russia to straighten
out the mess on its own. President Boris Yeltsin has urged
Parliament to adopt an ambitious plan to cut the budget deficit,
but the fund wants much more. It also insists that Russia pass a
new tax code, tighten bank rules and end a system in which wages go
unpaid, tax debts accumulate and companies do business in barter.
In another distressing note, Russia was again unable to find a
buyer for the state oil company, Rosneft.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE EURO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Slowpokes Zoom Ahead &LR;
</P>
<P>
   As Europe races to adopt a single currency, Spain, Portugal and
Ireland are growing much faster than bigger and wealthier countries
like France and Germany. The smaller economies have become magnets
for foreign money, and jobs are being created. Ireland's economy is
booming, with growth of more than 8 percent this year. It is even
experiencing labor shortages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 1612EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
