<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9391 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KEEVE-FILMS-$ADV12-87     07-10 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEEVE-FILMS-$ADV12-875(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUTH-TELLER: FROM `UNZIPPED' TO `NAOMI' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 12)  
(lh) 
 By RUTH LA FERLA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Sweet'' might not be the first word that comes to mind to
describe Naomi Campbell, the famously petulant celebrity model and
the star of Douglas Keeve's new fashion documentary, ``Naomi
Conquers South Africa,'' to be broadcast on VH-1 next Saturday. But
sweet she is, at least at the instant she is glimpsed in the movie
in her limousine en route to a meeting with President Nelson
Mandela. The meeting is clearly a high point of her trip, which is
a cash-raising mission for Mandela's Children's Fund.
</P>
<P>
   In those few seconds in the car, Ms. Campbell sheds her
customary hauteur. ``We're going to see Granddaddy; I hope
Granddaddy is happy to see me,'' she says blithely of Mandela, who
had named her his honorary granddaughter. But the quaver in her
voice and her restless puffing on a cigarette betray a serious case
of jitters.
</P>
<P>
   Keeve, the director of the 1995 documentary ``Unzipped,'' about
designer Isaac Mizrahi, is enough of a professional to know when
he's mined cinematic gold. ``I love that moment with Naomi,'' he
said. ``She is very nervous and sort of regal at the same time.
There is a little girl in her that kind of squeals, and on top of
that, there is always the classy diva. The way she smokes drives me
crazy. She's like a cat with no self-consciousness at all _ it's
beautiful to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   In his four years as a filmmaker, Keeve, a former fashion
photographer, has turned his director's penchant for voyeurism into
a flair for comedic truth-telling. ``Douglas has a way of peering
beneath fashion's skirts _ and that can be very enticing stuff,''
said Gabe Doppelt, the VH-1 producer who commissioned Keeve's
latest project, framed as a romp with distinctly melancholy
undertones.
</P>
<P>
   His films do display a brute honesty that is rare in a business
propped on illusion. And his rogue's gift for glorifying fashion
and simultaneously sending it up has a way of discomfiting even his
staunchest supporters. ``To be quite frank,'' Ms. Doppelt said,
only half in jest, ``I'd never let Douglas near me with a camera.''
</P>
<P>
   Chances are that Keeve would be just as loath to turn that
camera on himself. Moody, slow-talking and a shade suspicious, the
director, who is 40, is his own most stringent censor. He is
typically tight-lipped, whether he's talking about movies (``I
hated `Boogie Nights' _ do we have to say that?'' he said), or the
four-year hiatus between ``Unzipped'' and his current project.
After the Mizrahi film, which shared the award for the best
documentary at the 1995 Sundance Film Festival, Hollywood came
courting. In no time at all, Keeve said, he found himself working
on a romantic comedy, ``Inconvenient,'' a venture by Trimark Films
that was to star Rob Schneider, Janeane Garofalo and Lisa Kudrow.
It collapsed after Keeve resigned, he said, over creative
differences. A series of subsequent features also faltered or
simply failed to materialize.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were pigeonholing him a little too soon,'' said Michael
Kostigan, the senior vice president of production at Columbia
Pictures. ``They were offering him the obvious kinds of scripts
about the modeling world, but the kinds of things he wanted to do
he wasn't getting.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeve chalked up his misfortunes to his lack of experience as a
commercial filmmaker. ``I was new to Hollywood and very eager, and
I think I got attached to the wrong projects,'' he said. ``When you
move from one world to another, there are bound to be a few
bumps.''
</P>
<P>
   Lured back by Ms. Doppelt to more familiar turf, Keeve leaped at
the chance to follow Ms. Campbell last February to Cape Town, where
she was scheduled to organize a benefit fashion-show tribute to
Gianni Versace. The film is part of a documentary series on VH-1
called ``Fashion Kingdom.'' He brought a renewed zest to the
project, relentlessly tracking his subjects: Ms. Campbell; her
co-stars, Christy Turlington, Kate Moss and Amber Valetta, and an
entourage of some 30 other models, on and off the runway.
</P>
<P>
   During the filming, Keeve thought nothing of invading the
models' privacy, poking his lens around corners, down corridors,
into bedrooms and baths, sometimes encountering a thorny hostility
that was more than he had bargained for.
</P>
<P>
   On one such explosive occasion while filming additional footage
recently in Los Angeles, Keeve pointed his camera at Ms. Campbell
as she came bounding backstage just in time to appear as a guest on
the Magic Johnson television talk show. ``She was extremely late,
and when she saw that I had started shooting, she came rushing up
and smacked the camera,'' Keeve recalled. ``I was shocked, but I
wasn't offended. When Naomi is angry, it pops out. I think that's
how she stays healthy. Most of her feelings are right on the
surface.''
</P>
<P>
   Bent on penetrating that surface, Keeve hung in, meeting his
subjects' initial resistance with a steely tenacity of his own.
``He's a provocateur,'' said Nina Santisi, Mizrahi's right hand and
a co-producer of ``Unzipped.'' ``He will probe until people reveal
something. And he'll keep the camera going day and night, over the
models' protests.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeve said: ``I'm the director, so when people tell me to do
things, I don't listen. There was a lot of door-slamming on this
project. Sometimes I'd put my foot in the door, and sometimes I
wouldn't be quick enough.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He was swift, however, to pry his way into the hotel spa in Cape
Town, catching Ms. Campbell in the midst of a therapeutic salt
scrub. Stretched flat on her back, clad in nothing but a towel and
a shower cap, she looked utterly vulnerable, submitting to a brisk
massage while she rehearsed the next day's program. ```I have a
dream' _ that's the introduction,'' she was explaining languidly,
when a jet of ice water cut her short, causing her to squeal like a
baby.
</P>
<P>
   He also succeeded in capturing Ms. Campbell's lofty air of
entitlement mixed with incredulity, when Simon, a rich young South
African who had befriended the troupe, presented her in a jewelry
store with an outrageously expensive diamond necklace. Keeve kept
close watch as the otherwise worldly Ms. Campbell wandered dazedly
out of the shop, pleading: ``Let's get an ice cream. I need
something _ I'm in shock.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeve brings to such moments a curious mix of affection and
censoriousness. ``I'm always judgmental, every second,'' he said.
``When you make a documentary, you are never a fly on the wall as
much as you are a hideous predator.'' He was enough of a cynic to
let Ms. Campbell wax on about Mandela's bravery (he subsisted in
prison on a diet of insects) and then to pan to her tapering
fingers as she reached for a large box of chocolates.
</P>
<P>
   But more often than not he is an unabashed fan, letting his
camera limn his subject's curves or rest on her face to register
the smallest flicker of emotion. In perhaps the film's most
touching scene, Keeve homed in as Ms. Campbell picked up a hankie
and mopped Mandela's brow. A few seconds later, in front of the
crowd that had gathered at the president's mansion, she embraced
her idol as tears ran unchecked down her cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   Such scenes of haunting intimacy contrast sharply with the
moment in ``Unzipped'' when the director hovers a little too close
to Cindy Crawford, prompting the model to chide, ``Hellooo, my
pores are not that small.'' These days even his balkiest subjects
eventually submit to his scrutiny. ``People learn to trust him,''
said William DeVizia, who headed the film's production team. ``I'm
amazed that in this genre he has that kind of access.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeve claimed it is his bumbling technique that puts his
subjects at ease. ``I'm an amateur,'' he said. ``I keep things very
folksy and low-tech. I'm not steady with the camera. I'm too busy
making sure that I don't trip over something.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was quick to concede that he is also a canny manipulator,
well versed in the fine art of flattery. ``I told Naomi that if she
did this movie, it would make her a legend,'' he said with a laugh.
``Did she believe it? Not for a minute. But I think she liked
hearing it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, I think at a certain point people just get tired of
lying,'' he continued. ``Naomi is a member of a world whose only
constant is change. And I think she recognized that here was a
chance to do something that transcends all of fashion's ephemeral
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeve hopes his future projects will combine his taste for the
racy and the ridiculous. He describes the feature-length film he
has been writing for the last three years as ``a cautionary tale
about male models, sort of a `Valley of the Dolls' meets `Leaving
Las Vegas.''' Recently, Keeve, said he agreed to work on a
documentary about the pornography industry. ``I'm well suited to
that,'' he said. ``There are similarities between the world of
fashion and the world of porn. Both are small subcultures. Both
have interesting, dynamic kinds of people in them. And both are a
little bit taboo _ I love that.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeve, who thinks of himself first and foremost as an
entertainer, maintained that exploring forbidden worlds sometimes
goes against his grain. ``It's not my nature to follow people round
with a camera and invade their lives, but at the same time, it's so
fascinating,'' he said. ``I'm curious. I don't understand the way
people operate. I'm always baffled by the way they act. But I'm
hoping at some point maybe the camera will figure it out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 1616EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
