<HEADLINE>
CHRYSLER STILL HAS LOCK ON MINIVAN MARKET
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by CARS-CARAVAN-GLANCE) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If that toy-store chain hadn't already claimed all variations of
the ``'R' Us'' name, Chrysler Corp. could advertise itself as
``Minivans 'R' Us.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years after reviving the minivan concept begun in the
1950s by the Volkswagen bus Chrysler still owns a virtual lock on
the market.
</P>
<P>
   And for good reason, too. The company's bread-and-butter
vehicles, which singlehandedly have kept Chrysler in financial
black ink since the mid-80s, come in such a wide variety and price
range that it's hard for any one competitor to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say there aren't other good minivans on the
market, and that there aren't some better vans. There are. But no
other manufacturer provides such a choice for consumers, from the
most basic and least-expensive models to the luxurious ones like
this week's test drive _ the 1998 Dodge Grand Caravan ES.
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Caravan is a stretch version of the basic Chrysler
minivans (Dodge Caravan and Plymouth Voyager), 13.3 inches longer
than the short ones. Most of that extra length is in the cargo
compartment, which gives families a bit more luggage space for
vacations and hauling the kids' soccer-team gear around town.
</P>
<P>
   Our Grand Caravan ES was about as luxurious as a minivan can get
without leather seats (those are available on the fancier Chrysler
Town &AMP; Country models). New for 1998 were such features as a
pumped-up 3.8-liter V-6 engine ($335 extra) rated at 180 horsepower
and 240 foot-pounds of torque and the optional automatic headlights
and self-dimming driver's side mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler was the first minivan builder to offer dual rear
sliding doors, a great convenience that allows loading and
unloading the kids from the driver's side. This was such a novel
idea that we kept forgetting our test vehicle had the left-side
door, so we mostly used the traditional curbside door for rear
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   The ES model is basically the top-of-the-line LE model with a
special package of extras ($1,155) that included body-color
exterior trim, a heavy-load/firm-ride suspension, fog lights and
gold-colored forged-aluminum wheels. Base price is $26,605 plus
$580 transportation, but with all the options ours maxed out at
$29,325, about $10,000 higher than the average sales price for a
Dodge or Plymouth minivan. The price included a built-in $1,190
options discount, which more than paid for the ES package.
</P>
<P>
   The automatic headlights and self-dimming outside mirror were
part of a separate $1,765 package that also included self-dimming
inside mirror, dual front and rear air-conditioning, eight-way
power driver's seat, leather-wrapped steering wheel, and a
windshield-wiper de-icing system.
</P>
<P>
   Although our test car came with the heavy-duty suspension _
designed for a whole vanload of people and cargo _ the ride was
still very sedanlike. The interior is much more quiet than one
would expect in a minivan (the kids provide most of the noise) and
the seats are very comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Ours came with seating for seven passengers, with two buckets up
front, a two-person center bench with two integrated child-safety
seats ($225), and a three-person rear bench. Because of storage
areas on each side of the third seat, there is not as much room as
in the rear seat of some competitors such as the Ford Windstar, so
the seat is better suited to three kids than three adults.
</P>
<P>
   Thoughtfulness abounds throughout the Grand Caravan. It's easy
to tell that Chrysler has listened to its customers and designed
these vehicles with the users in mind. Cupholders are the
self-adjusting, ratcheting type that adjust to small juice boxes or
large coffee mugs and there are enough for everybody. They are
mounted so that they remain in place when the middle seats are
lifted to allow passengers into the rear, another thoughtful
feature.
</P>
<P>
   One of my favorite amenities in the Caravan is the hooks for
plastic grocery bags built into the back of the third seat. This is
a great idea that helps keep groceries from spilling all over the
cargo compartment.
</P>
<P>
   Visibility is outstanding from every seating position thanks to
all the glass. And, even though the interior is as roomy as a big
box, the Caravan's exterior has a smooth, sleek style that carries
a remarkable 0.35 coefficient of drag _ which means it glides
through the air with a minimum of wind resistance. That's quite a
feat for a minivan and it helps keep the fuel economy manageable at
17 miles per gallon in the city and 24 mpg on the highway.
</P>
<P>
   Although minivans are a long way from sports cars, the
180-horsepower engine moves the Grand Caravan along at speeds high
enough to attract speed cops and there is more than enough power
for routine passing and freeway merges. This is the most powerful
engine available in a Chrysler minivan; the others are four- and
six-cylinder models ranging from 150 to 158 horsepower (which still
is adequate for most situations).
</P>
<P>
   Trailer-towing is limited to 2,000 pounds without a special
upgrade, which raises the weight limit to 3,500 pounds. These
weight limits apply to all engines but the base four-cylinder,
which can handle only up to a 1,000-pound trailer. But I would
recommend the 3.8-liter engine if you need to pull trailers.
</P>
<P>
   Standard amenities included power windows, power door locks with
remote control, power rack-and-pinion steering, antilock brakes,
rear wiper and washer, air-conditioning stainless-steel exhaust
system, overhead console with trip computer, tilt steering wheel,
cruise control, tachometer, illuminated visor vanity mirrors, and
side-window defoggers.
</P>
<P>
   Other options on our test vehicle included an in-dash 200-watt
AM/FM/cassette/compact-disc stereo, candy-apple-red metallic paint
($200), alarm system ($150), and a roof luggage rack ($175).
</P>
<P>
   The fuel tank holds 20 gallons of gasoline, enough for more than
400 miles between gasoline stops on highway cruises. The kids'
bladders usually won't go that long, though.
</P>
<P>
   SUBURBAN UPDATE: Readers are asking about the pending redesign
of the full-size General Motors sport-utilities, which are due out
next year as 2000 models.
</P>
<P>
   For an idea of how they'll look, just check out the new
full-size Chevrolet and GMC pickups that will go on sale this fall.
As in the past, the Chevy/GMC Suburban and the Chevy Tahoe/GMC
Yukon basically will be identical to the full-size pickups from the
front seat forward.
</P>
<P>
   That means there won't be any radical changes because there is
nothing radical about the new pickups. But,like the pickups, these
vehicles will be more powerful and roomier, and will have better
brakes than the current models or their competitors. Expect to see
them on the market in late August or September 1999.
</P>
<P>
   (G. Chambers Williams III writes on transportation issues for
the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. His mailing address is
Star-Telegram/Northeast, 3201 Airport Freeway, Suite 108, Bedford,
Texas 76021; his E-mail address is chambers(at)star-telegram.com.
Fax: (817) 685-3883. Check out his Wheelin' new-car review column
weekly on the Internet at
ww.netarrant.net/today/news/opinions/necol.htm. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
