<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RETURN FRED HARRIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA FE, N.M. -- In 1976, he proclaimed with a firm conviction
and an Oklahoma twang that ``The issue is privilege.'' Fred Harris,
the last unabashed populist to run for president, was elected to
the US Senate at 33, then served with folksy energy and enthusiasm
as chairman of the Democratic National Committee. His '76 campaign
was the last one powered by peanut-butter-and-jelly sandwiches and
sincerity.
</P>
<P>
   But, as he joked, ``the little people'' lacked stools and
stepladders to reach his name on the ballot. He finished fourth in
the New Hampshire primary, fifth in Massachusetts, and his populist
crusade faded away.
</P>
<P>
   At 67, Fred Harris is back in active politics as the new
chairman of the Democratic State Committee of New Mexico, where
he's lived for 20 years. ``I'm still a populist and a
progressive,'' he says. ``I've been working in campaigns but in the
background. I've written a bunch of books, and I've been teaching
and lecturing.''
</P>
<P>
   A professor of political science at the University of New Mexico
in Albuquerque, Harris is resuming a public role because a major
fan, Democratic gubernatorial nominee Martin Chavez, asked him to.
``It's a real coup for the Democratic Party,'' Chavez said. ``When
I'm asked who my heroes are, he's in the top five.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have controlled the governor's office in The
Roundhouse, as the circular state capitol here is known, since
1994, when Governor Gary Johnson benefited from a 10 percent vote
for a Green Party candidate. Democrats suffered defections of 17
and 15 percent to Green Party candidates in special congressional
elections in 1997 and last month. The GOP won both, prompting
Chavez to ask Harris to provide liberal and populist bona fides.
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats regard the resurrection of Harris with keen
interest because of the Green Party's threat as a plausible
alternative. ``If that Green Party virus ever catches in
California, I'd be terrified,'' says Bill Carrick, who runs
Democratic campaigns in the nation's largest state. ``We've managed
to keep the minor party candidates from hurting Democrats. The
Libertarian, Reform, and American Independent parties hurt the
Republicans more than the Greens and the Peace and Freedom party
hurt us.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrick thinks Harris will find it hard to harness working-class
populism with upper-class environmentalism ``because people who
want jobs are always skeptical of people who favor trees over
jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, if ``the issue is privilege,'' don't most
environmentalists live in a privileged class? ``That's absolutely
true,'' Harris replies, but adds that populists and
environmentalists ``ought to have the same goals. First, cleaning
up the environment makes jobs, as President Clinton and Vice
President Gore have shown. Secondly, it's really working-class and
poor neighborhoods that are the most polluted. I see this as a
progressive issue, although there is a special appeal on
environmental issues to people with higher levels of education.''
</P>
<P>
   Education is the major issue of privilege today, Harris argues.
``It means support for schools, rather than vouchers that take away
money from public schools,'' he says. ``The present governor has
been a Mr. No, vetoing things like computers in the classroom and
all sorts of social programs. Marty Chavez is a person who will say
yes to education.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris describes Chavez, a former mayor of Albuquerque, as
``smart and right on the issues. I think he's going to win.
Republicans who succeed must carry Albuquerque, and we've got a man
who can prevent that.'' Chavez gushes: ``It's like we were playing
a good game and all of a sudden Michael Jordan walks up and was
available. Fred Harris is Michael Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   That's hoop hyperbole, but Harris and Jordan do share some
traits: a big-league work ethic, a sly sense of humor, a few flashy
moves, and an apparent inability to contemplate retirement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
