<HEADLINE>
`ZOOM' RETURNS TO ENTERTAIN A NEW GENERATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURA YUEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just as bellbottoms, mood rings, and the Village People are once
again cool, the children's TV show ``Zoom'' returns from the disco
days to entertain a new generation.
</P>
<P>
   The 1970s children's television series has been revived _ and
revamped _ for a second life. Come January, old ``Zoom'' fans, now
in their 30s, can watch a new generation once again sing the show's
opening theme song (``Come on and Zoom Zoom Zoom-a Zoom ...''),
speak the secret Ubbi Dubbi language, and mail letters to ``Box
three-five-oh, Boston, Mass., oh-two-one-three-four!''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great thing to be a cultural icon,'' said senior
producer Jonathan Meath. ```Zoom' is a cherished part of kids'
lives who grew up in the '70s. We want it to be a cherished part of
kids who grow up in the '90s.''
</P>
<P>
   WGBH-TV in Boston has resurrected the show for PBS, this time
catering to children whose parents were part of the original
``Zoom'' generation. Thanks to the Internet, ``Zoomworld'' can only
get bigger. Thanks to the deep-sixing of the cast's rugby uniform
shirts, the Zoom kids can only get hipper. But in general, the show
will keep the same content _ a hodgepodge of crafts, science
experiments, games, and skits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judging from the pilot we showed, people feel glad we haven't
taken the heart out of the old `Zoom,''' said executive producer
Kate Taylor, who worked as an editor and segment producer for the
original series. ``We're making the show very un-'90s, in the sense
that it still uses real kids, not Hollywood actor-types.''
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, ``Zoom'' was and will continue to be television of
the children, by the children, and for the children. Kids write and
host the show, while others across the country send in recipes,
sketches, brain teasers, and game ideas to Box 350 _ or now, to
Zoom(at)wgbh.org. Targeting the 5-11 age group, the program tries
to promote critical thinking, reading, writing, and creativity.
</P>
<P>
   At the show's zenith in the '70s, ``Zoom'' fans mailed 10,000
letters a week to WGBH's ZIP code, 02134. The program ran on
weekday afternoons on PBS from 1972-79, with repeats until 1981,
becoming the first series written and performed by kids. Back then,
the mama's boys and your little brother watched Mr. Rogers. The
cool kids watched ``Zoom.''
</P>
<P>
   The creators of ``Zoom,'' part 2, hope to expand the show into
an interactive multimedia affair. They want children to use the Web
site at www.pbs.org/zoom to pitch ideas, chat with other
``Zoomers'' around the country, and retrieve instructions for games
and experiments. Outreach after-school programs in the 4-H and Boys
and Girls Clubs, where kids can make crafts and play games in
``Zoom'' fashion, will make ``Zoom'' seem nothing short of a kid's
empire. ``We have the chance of creating a much bigger universe
than we did in the past,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   The show will have some changes: No more red and blue rugby
shirts that scream '70s; today's cast wears funky plaids, comfy
denims, and bright T-shirts. Forget the staged song-and-dance
sequences to ``Michael, Row Your Boat Ashore.'' Old-school Zoomers
will notice small variations in the theme song; a one-sentence rap,
for instance, has been inserted into the familiar jingle.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 800 children tried out for the cast at the November open
auditions in Boston. Producers scoped out fun, energetic, and
interesting personalities, often shying away from youngsters with
acting experience, Taylor said. ``We're looking for the kids'
natural selves,'' she said. ``Some of the kid actors don't always
know how to show that because they're always being directed.''
</P>
<P>
   The exuberant cast of Alisa, David, Jared, Keiko, Lynese, Pablo,
and Zoe are 8- to 13-year-olds who come from various ethnic
backgrounds and neighborhoods in Massachusetts and New Hampshire.
Their presence on TV seems to tell kids it's OK to wear braces,
have baby fat, or look like anything other than a Brady kid.
``Zoom'' policy does not disclose the last names of cast members.
``Our kids represent every person,'' Meath said. ``We want kids at
home to feel like they're on a first name basis'' with the cast.
</P>
<P>
   But camera shy, the ``Zoom'' cast are not. Shooting 40 episodes
Monday through Friday this summer, they transform the black WGBH
studio set to a lively summer camp. When MC'ing a relay race, Jared
uses a commanding voice akin to a pro-wrestling announcer. Lynese,
Alisa, and Zoe can do a striking impression of the Spice Girls
between cuts. They all complain about each others' smelly feet when
the directors ask them to shoot a scene barefoot.
</P>
<P>
   When director Bob Comiskey tells them to do a fourth take of the
same segment, the blond and bespectacled Zoe cries, ``Oh, for the
love of Bob!''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always cool to see kids from different backgrounds coming
together, emerging as this wonderful community,'' said drama coach
Shea Schatell. ``They celebrate each other's creativity.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, ``Zoom'' became less of a TV presence and more
of a nostalgic pop-culture reference. On TV's ``Friends,'' Joey
lied on his resume, claiming to be a ``Zoom'' kid. Rosie O'Donnell
has mentioned the hit on her show. On a ``Saturday Night Live,''
skit, a Senator Edward Kennedy impersonator conversed in Ubbi Dubbi
with the moderator. Since the mid-'80s, curious grown-up fans wrote
to Box 350, asking, ``Whatever happened to `Zoom'?''
</P>
<P>
   That's partly why the creators are releasing a ``Zoom''
nostalgia video and book that compiles snippets of old shows and
``Where are they now?'' profiles on former cast members. While some
of them have gone onto show business, others have become train
engineers, child psychologists, and writers.
</P>
<P>
   Former ``Zoom'' fan Chris Whitbeck, 32, said he was thrilled
when producers called to ask if he would be interested in working
for the show. Whitbeck, science coordinator for Brookline Public
Schools, explains science concepts and experiments to the cast
before showtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so shocked when they called me,'' he said. ``I sang them
that song, `Oh-two-one-three-four!' I said, `Oh, It's `Zoom!' I
know you!'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
