A9405 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-10 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMPLOYERS LEARN TO DEAL WITH DEATH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Nearly 30 years ago when Tom Gentry was working at a
local refinery, a co-worker dropped dead on the job.
</P>
<P>
   After his body was removed, the company's attitude was: ``OK,
fellas, get back to work,'' and no one in the company said a word
about what felled the poor guy, said Gentry, president of the Oil,
Chemical and Atomic Workers Union Local 4-227.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of insensitivity is still common at many companies
when an employee dies, either on the job or at home. Many times,
employers don't know what to say or do, so they just ignore the
death.
</P>
<P>
   But employeesimagine the most gruesome details _ especially if
the death is violent, like a suicide _ and don't have a chance to
grieve, said the Rev. Diana Dale, president of the Worklife
Institute in Houston. When that happens, employees feel alienated
and direct their anger toward the company.
</P>
<P>
   A few employers have rethought the way they handle death and are
bringing in counselors.
</P>
<P>
   After a suicide, for example, a big counseling session with the
deceased employee's co-workers lets them talk about the guilt they
feel by not recognizing the employee's pain or, if they saw it, not
interceding, said Dale, who is a corporate chaplain and is hired by
companies to counsel employees after a death.
</P>
<P>
   They also typically talk about the anger they feel toward their
deceased co-worker for taking his life and their anger with God for
letting it happen, Dale said. It's good to let people explode in a
supportive atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Some employees feel guilt over the way they react to an
employee's death, she said. At one company, a geologist was killed
in an accident and the manager's first reaction was annoyance about
having to find a new geologist, Dale said, and the manager felt
guilty for thinking of his own concerns first.
</P>
<P>
   In another instance, Dale was brought in to talk to employees
about the pain they felt about losing a co-worker who died at his
desk of cancer. Employees were angry that they had to watch him go
downhill day by day and that he increasingly couldn't carry his
weight in the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Dale said she encourages employees to express themselves and
tells each group that the conversation is confidential. She
typically meets with groups of managers separately because they
want to save face and appear to be in control.
</P>
<P>
   Employees also want to know the details of the death, which
makes it important for the company to explain what happened, Dale
said. That way, people aren't brooding over the specifics, and it
keeps the rumor mill quiet.
</P>
<P>
   When a company has a death at work, employees need a ritual to
mark the passing and let employees grieve, said Terrence Deal,
professor of education at Vanderbilt University in Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Deal remembers the time when he was a ninth-grade U.S. history
teacher and his 5-year-old son died suddenly. When he returned to
work, Deal said his students sat him down for a ceremony. The
students sang some songs they wrote, spoke about how sorry they
were, presented some food and lined up so each could give him a big
hug.
</P>
<P>
   Deal said the ceremony helped him and the students, who had also
attended the funeral, commemorate the death in their own special
way and get back to work.
</P>
<P>
   Deal, who specializes in the study of rituals and ceremony,
suggests to companies they host a lunch or call a special meeting
to reminisce about a deceased employee.
</P>
<P>
   In every company there's always someone employees turn to for
spiritual advice, he said. That person is easily identified _
sometimes it's the receptionist, other times the custodian _ and
Deal suggests the employer let the on-site spiritual leader devise
a ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   When that ritual doesn't take place, there can be real troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Deal said he was doing some consulting work at one company in
which everyone was complaining about an employee who had made
several mistakes _ installing urinals in the women's restrooms and
putting the company logo upside down on company cars.
</P>
<P>
   Deal said that when he found out the employee had been dead for
five years, he told the chief executive that the company should
have some kind of ceremony to put him to rest. Maybe an exorcism,
Deal suggested with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Dale recommended that companies develop a plan to handle an
employee death and have a counselor ready to come at a moment's
notice to talk to employees. It's really important to catch
employees the day the death occurs or otherwise they'll begin to
feel alienated, she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
L.M. Sixel can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to lm.sixel(at)chron.com, or call (713)
220-2000 and enter access code 1002. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
