<HEADLINE>
DRUG CZAR TO PURSUE INTERNATIONAL ANTI-DRUG DIALOGUE IN EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE TSONG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Barry R. McCaffrey, who heads the White House war
on drugs, takes off Saturday for Europe to see how other officials
are trying to curb narcotics abuse and to promote greater
cooperation in fighting traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   The trip comes two days after President Clinton launched a $195
million national anti-drug ad campaign aimed at teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey, a retired Army general, said Friday he realizes that
he and his European counterparts do not share ``precisely the same
culture or historical context or legal context, but I want to
listen to what they are doing and saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``The common thread running throughout this visit is that the
problem is the same ... drug consumption and the terrible damage to
humans, to their families, to their (country's) economy.''
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey, who begins his trip in Stockholm, Sweden, said he
wants to learn how its treatment system works and whether it might
be adapted to help the 4 million chronic addicts in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've not yet built the infrastructure required to handle that
problem in a more rational way,'' he said. ``It's one of the major
shortcomings in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   He complained that international efforts to combat illegal drugs
are hampered because no worldwide standard exists for monitoring
drug use and prevention. His trip, he said, will allow him to have
``serious and continuing dialogue on data collection.''
</P>
<P>
   The eight-day tour includes visits to Amsterdam, The Hague and
Rotterdam in the Netherlands as well as Vienna, Austria; Zurich,
Switzerland, and Lisbon, Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   In Vienna he will visit the United Nations Drug Control Center,
where he will meet with Pino Arlacchi, executive director of the
U.N. drug control program, and discuss ways to improve global
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey will also visit the European Monitoring Center for
Drugs and Drug Addiction in Lisbon, where, he said, ``17 of my
colleagues in Europe with the same title of `drug czar' have agreed
to come (to) consult with one another.''
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey said he plans to outline drug prevention tactics that
the United States is funding.
</P>
<P>
   European officials, he said, were ``shocked'' to learn that
American drug campaigns stress prevention and asked him to tell
more about them.
</P>
<P>
   He said that when he tells foreign drug officials that ``85
percent of all the drug research on the face of the Earth is done
by the U.S. ... it surprises them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
