<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YES, PCI GRAPHICS CARD WORKS IN A COMPUTER WITH AN AGP SLOT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I just bought a new computer, and it came with a graphics
card in the AGP slot. I don't really like the card that's built in,
so I'm thinking about putting the card from my old computer into
this one. I really liked the older card, but it goes into a PCI
slot. Can I still use it in this computer, which uses AGP graphics?
</P>
<P>
   A: AGP stands for Accelerated Graphics Port, and it's yet
another standard for connecting video cards to computer system
boards. There have been several, starting with the original ISA
(Industry Standard Architecture), VLB (VESA Local Bus) and then PCI
(Peripheral Component Interconnect).
</P>
<P>
   Each new type of connection comes along with a new generation of
Intel Corp. processors, it seems. VLB first was used with the 80486
chip. PCI came along with the original Pentium. And AGP was
introduced along with the Pentium II.
</P>
<P>
   While VLB now is defunct, both ISA and PCI slots live on in
modern computers. The industry is trying to phase out ISA slots,
though, because they are not fast and don't work very well with the
plug-and-play standard. It's not been easy, though, because there
are lots of cards that still use the ISA standard out there _
ranging from modems to sound cards to network cards.
</P>
<P>
   Most modern video cards are available in PCI format, though some
manufacturers are starting to balk at introducing their newest
cards in anything but AGP. For example, Matrox Graphics has
announced a new card called the Millennium G200 that, initially at
least, will be made only as an AGP card. Company officials aren't
ruling out a PCI model, but one is not promised.
</P>
<P>
   Since most new PCs have both kinds of slots, you can indeed use
a PCI graphics card in a computer with an AGP slot. Just be sure
you remove the AGP card so there are no conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   You also might check with the maker of your favorite graphics
card to see if an AGP version is available.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am planning to upgrade my Pentium 166 to a Pentium II 400.
I also am planning to upgrade to Windows 98. Should I change out
the motherboard first, or upgrade to Win 98 and then change the
motherboard? I rather suspect many of your readers will be
considering making the same kinds of changes.
</P>
<P>
   A: This really is a chicken-or-the-egg question, isn't it? Do
you do the major hardware surgery or the major software surgery
first?
</P>
<P>
   Given that replacing the most crucial part of your system _ the
motherboard _ is a more challenging task, I'd start with that
first. Get the new motherboard in place and let the established
operating system handle the task of recognizing everything when you
turn it on for the first time. Once everything settles down,
install the new operating system.
</P>
<P>
   However, you may end up having to do a fresh install of the
operating system if things go horribly wrong. After all, the setup
in the Windows 95 Registry is going to be expecting one kind of
motherboard, hard drive controller, etc., and it will get a
different one once you turn the upgraded PC on. If it craters, that
might be a good time to load Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   Just make sure you've got a working boot disk that includes your
CD-ROM drivers in case you need to do an installation from scratch.
And, of course, make a full backup of your system before you do
anything.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I just bought my first computer, a Macintosh! Yes, I bought a
Mac, can you believe it? Anyway, I'd like to find some places to
get shareware and freeware. Can you help?
</P>
<P>
   A: You've made Steve Jobs very happy. You're just what he's
after _ computer novices to expand the Mac's market share.
</P>
<P>
   You can make yourself very happy at Info-Mac, which is
considered the best source for Macintosh shareware. It's at
www.pht.com/info-mac/.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about your computer? Dwight Silverman can receive
electronic mail via the Internet. Address your comments and
questions to dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000
and enter access code 1001. &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
