<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9459 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AF-TERRORISM-HNS &LR;      07-10 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AF-TERRORISM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS OBJECT TO PLAN TO MOVE AIR FORCE ANTI-TERRORIST SQUAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SIG CHRISTENSON  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ An Air Force plan to move an anti-terrorist unit
from Lackland Air Force Base to Georgia has drawn a sharp rebuke
from a bipartisan coalition of Texas lawmakers who say the troops'
welfare is being sacrificed to Pentagon politics.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison wrote a letter Thursday
protesting a Pentagon decision to relocate the 820th Security
Forces Group, pegged to move from Lackland to Moody Air Force Base
in Valdosta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   The letter touts the advantages of keeping the unit at the San
Antonio base, and asks Acting Air Force Secretary F. Whitten Peters
to discuss the issue with the lawmakers before the move occurs.
</P>
<P>
   It also questions moving the group when the Air Force is looking
to save money by consolidating operations.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ciro D. Rodriguez, a Democrat, said Thursday the move
frustrates Texas lawmakers because San Antonio took a big hit when
the Base Closure and Realignment Commission ordered Kelly Air Force
Base, a longtime economic generator, to close by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kelly is the largest base ever to be closed, so there is no
doubt we have paid our dues,'' said Rodriguez, a member of the
House National Security Committee. ``Enough is enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The Security Forces Group, established last year in a Lackland
ceremony that featured then-Air Force Chief of Staff Ronald
Fogleman, now has about 60 people, but in time will grow to 600.
</P>
<P>
   It is part of a worldwide anti-terrorist operation based at
Lackland in the wake of the 1996 bombing of the Khobar Towers
complex in Saudi Arabia that killed 19 Americans and wounded
hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, delivered to Peters' office Thursday, was described
by one Senate staffer as the ``opening volley'' in a battle to keep
the 820th at Lackland.
</P>
<P>
   The other lawmakers from Texas who signed Hutchison's letter
were Republican Sen. Phil Gramm; Rodriguez and fellow Democratic
Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez; and Republican Reps. Henry Bonilla and
Lamar Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a time when the military is moving to consolidate its
forces for greater efficiency, moving the 820th from Lackland ...
makes little sense,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said Peters had told him that housing and other
facilities available for the 820th ``were a little cramped'' at
Lackland, so moving the unit made sense.
</P>
<P>
   Peters could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Those opposed to the move say Lackland and San Antonio offer
more amenities and are better suited to serve the needs of the
820th, a combat-ready rapid deployment force created to protect Air
Force installations worldwide against terrorist attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Moody is located in Valdosta, a South Georgia city of 47,000.
Moody has been marked for shutdown by the Base Closure and
Realignment Commission three times this decade, but survived.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
