<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9475 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMEN-PLASTIC-SURGERY     07-10 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-PLASTIC-SURGERY-$ADV12-ART-850(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN WHO ARE PLASTIC SURGEONS ARE HARD TO FIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 12)  
(lh) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Stephanie Hallberg was 16, she decided she
wanted to reduce the size of her breasts. Ten years later and after
visits with doctors _ all men, all of whom recommended she keep her
breasts the way they were _ she found a doctor who sympathized with
her predicament and agreed to perform the surgery, Dr. Michelle
Copeland, who works out of a Fifth Avenue office complete with its
own operating room and all-female staff, down to the
anesthesiologist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't even imagine going to a man for any plastic
surgery,'' Ms. Hallberg, 26, said. ``A man can study the woman's
body forever, but I believe he can never really understand how a
woman is put together, mentally, emotionally, physically.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hallberg is lucky to have found a plastic surgeon who is a
woman, since they are indeed a rarity _ only about 4 percent of all
the board-certified plastic surgeons in the United States,
according to the American Society for Aesthetic Plastic Surgery. In
New York, the disparity is even greater: Of approximately 500
board-certified plastic surgeons, only 12 are women, and only about
half of those spend the bulk of their time practicing cosmetic
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The women's health movement has brought steadily increasing
numbers of women into medicine: women now make up 46 percent of the
classes admitted to medical schools. But it has scarcely touched
the field of cosmetic surgery, which remains overwhelmingly
dominated by men, even though its patient population is
overwhelmingly female _ 89 percent of cosmetic surgery patients are
women, according to the American Society of Plastic and
Reconstructive Surgeons.
</P>
<P>
   It is men who are lifting the eyebrows, enlarging the breasts
and suctioning away the fat to remake women's faces and bodies.
</P>
<P>
   The almost exclusively one-way relationship suggests to some the
myth of Pygmalion, the king who in Greek legend sculptured a statue
of his ideal woman, which then came gratifyingly to life and became
his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jane Petro, a professor of plastic surgery at New York
Medical College in Valhalla, N.Y., is one who thinks ``the
Pygmalion angle'' helps explain why many more men than women are
drawn to the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' she said. ``Just look at the number of male
plastic surgeons whose second wife was once their patient. It's
unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Cosmetic surgery is booming in the United States, driven by the
aging of the baby-boom population and the gradual erosion of a
cultural stigma against surgical self-improvement. Plastic surgeons
performed 686,201 cosmetic procedures in 1996, a 69 percent
increase over the 1992 figure of 406,156, according to the American
Society of Plastic and Reconstructive Surgeons.
</P>
<P>
   This boom has lofted the average salary of plastic surgeons to
$350,000, one of the highest in medicine, an income largely
unfettered by managed care and other insurance, since the elective
procedures are paid for directly by well-heeled patients.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite these enticements, women are not streaming into
cosmetic surgery, as they are into other medical fields, like
pediatrics, general medicine and obstetrics and gynecology. What
would explain this paradox?
</P>
<P>
   Doctors, medical authorities and cultural observers suggest a
variety of reasons, from the hard-core practical to the
philosophical. Whatever the explanation, however, the imbalance
would seem to have ramifications for the ever-shifting concept of
American feminine beauty. The pervasiveness of the mostly male
surgical elite helps perpetuate ``the svelte, sculpted, Baywatch
woman,'' said Leslie Laurence, the co-author of ``Outrageous
Practices: How Gender Bias Threaten's Women's Health'' (Ballantine
Books, 1994).
</P>
<P>
   ``We measure ourselves against these cultural icons and feel we
fall short,'' she said. ``I believe that women surgeons bring a
different sensibility, just by virtue of understanding what it's
like to be a woman. When you're talking about things like breasts
and hips and bags under the eyes, they know what these things mean
to us and they understand our insecurities and desires a bit
better. A woman surgeon can separate away the cultural ideal from
reality.''
</P>
<P>
   One explanation for the lack of plastic surgeons who are women
that rolled off the tip of nearly every doctor's tongue _ both male
and female _ is that the rigors of plastic surgery training are too
intense, that a woman cannot balance the demands of surgical
training and a family or husband. Plastic surgeons must graduate
from a four-year medical school, then complete a five-year
residency in general surgery, followed by two years of plastic
surgery residency, capped off in most cases with a one-year
fellowship.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time you get out, you're 35,'' said Dr. Samantha Kwon,
who has just finished her plastic surgery training eight years
after graduating from medical school and will begin practicing in
Manhattan this fall. ``And a lot of times, a woman has other
priorities; getting married, raising a family,'' she said. ``You
cannot balance a general surgery residency and a family.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In medical _ not surgical _ practice, women currently make up 21
percent of the nation's doctors, according to figures supplied by
the American Medical Association. They comprise 33 percent of
family practice and internal physicians, and around 85 percent of
pediatric doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors confirm that surgery has long been a boys' club with a
remarkably hostile environment for women. Dr. Kwon said that her
surgical training was ``military in its hierarchy. Some women feel
it's too stressful. And some programs take only men and one token
woman, although they won't admit that. That makes an uncomfortable
environment for women.''
</P>
<P>
   That macho attitude may drive some women away from surgery in
general. ``No matter how much we can legislate equality, surgery is
still something that women are counseled away from,'' said Dr.
Deborah T. Gold, a medical sociologist at the Duke University
Medical Center. ``It's subtle, and not everyone may realize it, but
it happens.''
</P>
<P>
   But the fact is, plenty of women do become surgeons _ just not
plastic surgeons. In 1994, according to the Association of Women
Surgeons, there were 10,004 obstetric-gynecologic surgeons who are
women, 3,031 general surgeons and 2,026 practicing ophthalmologic
surgery. The number of women populating surgery's ranks has risen
dramatically in the last 30 years: from 2,129 in 1970 to 17,107 in
1994. All the surgical subspecialties have to complete similarly
rigorous surgical training periods. Grueling training alone does
not explain the paucity of women in plastic surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Anne Carlon, a surgical obstetrician-gynecologist in
Manhattan, said she never thought about plastic surgery in medical
school, and chose her field because, as a woman, she sympathized
with the needs of female patients. She surmised that women chose
careers in medicine motived more by altruism than by monetary
concerns. ``Plastic surgery is something of a money maker,'' she
said, ``and I think that a lot fewer women than men have that as a
major factor in deciding what field they want to go into.''
</P>
<P>
   Some patients say that there are fewer women practicing plastic
surgery because patients tend to _ as backward and sexist as it
sounds _ trust men more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I've always gone to male doctors, and I always will,''
said one woman in her '60s who spoke on condition of anonymity and
who has visited Dr. Daniel Baker, a celebrated Manhattan surgeon,
for procedures. ``How long have women been doing this, anyway?''
</P>
<P>
   Building a plastic surgery practice _ unlike, for example, one
in cardiac surgery or gastroenterology _ requires a fair bit of
socializing, and in this regard some women physicians say they're
at a disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   Baker and Dr. Sherrell Aston, two of Manhattan's most eminent
sculptors of famous faces, may benefit by having beautiful wives
who circulate with them through the charity-ball circuit and help
to gather wealthy clients with time on their hands and furrows on
their brows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't go out to parties and get our picture in Avenue
magazine,'' said Dr. Helen S. Colen, a plastic surgeon who shares a
Manhattan practice with her husband, referring to a New York
magazine known for publishing photographs of socialites at play.
``As a woman you just can't be as famous as Dr. Aston and Dr.
Baker, in your tuxedo with your famous wife. How? They go for three
months and sit in the Hamptons and get their pictures in the
papers.'' She added: ``If I had a wife, well, who knows what I
could do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Plastic surgeons' reputations are made on their results, not
based on their spouse,'' Aston said, when reached between surgical
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Some cultural critics think the reason for the scarcity of women
plastic surgeons is based on atavistic fears. Nancy Friday, the
author of ``The Power of Beauty'' (HarperCollins, 1996), believes
that women do not have an interest in making other women more
beautiful or youthful-looking. The upshot, she argues, is that
fewer women go into plastic surgery, and fewer women choose to have
women operate on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at all those fairy tales about the wicked stepmother, the
older woman who wants to destroy the beauty of the younger one,''
Ms. Friday said. ``I can't think of a woman who would want to give
me youthful, sexual beauty power. We know in our gut that another
woman really doesn't wish us an extended youthful beautiful period
in our lives. It's all because of the unspoken competition between
women.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis J. Lynch, the president of the American Society of
Reconstructive and Plastic Surgeons, disagreed. ``That statement is
way off base and doesn't reflect the reality of the women who are
practicing plastic surgery,'' he said. ``Women have long been an
important and trusted part of our society.''
</P>
<P>
   And feminine instinct may have played a trusted, beneficial role
in at least one aspect of plastic surgery: a number of women
cosmetic surgeons said they refused to use silicone breast implants
even before they were removed from the market in 1992, following
lawsuits claiming injuries. (Last week the Dow Corning Corp. agreed
to pay $3.2 billion to settle some of the lawsuits.)
</P>
<P>
   The patients who seek out women for their procedures are for the
most part grateful for the womanly attention. Most said that at its
best it felt like the relationship with a close girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Another woman, who spoke only on condition that her name not be
used because her husband is a public figure, said that after having
had six children, she visited a male plastic surgeon to discuss a
breast tuck and augmentation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took one look at me and _ well, after six kids, you know,
it's deflate, deflate, deflate _ and said, `What's the point?
You're this age now, and just learn to live with it.' I was 39
years old. I thought, `Gee, I guess it's about time to go pick out
my cemetery plot.'''
</P>
<P>
   A friend referred her to Dr. Susan Craig Scott, who practices on
the Upper East Side and who she said treated her with kid gloves,
``like a newborn baby, like a best friend.''
</P>
<P>
   And if she hadn't found Dr. Scott, the absolute worst might have
happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would still be deflated, deflated, deflated,'' she said with
a laugh. ``Now, everything's back where it ought to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
