<SLUG> BC-TEEN-OFFENDER-CEXP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN OFFENDER SHARES HER STORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDITORS: Children's Express is an independent, non-profit news
service reported by children whose tape-recorded interviews,
roundtables and commentary are edited by teens and adults. The
features are transmitted by The New York Times Service and are
available to New York Times News Service clients at no extra
charge.) 
 (JT)  
 By Children's Express/Upper Peninsula, Michigan Bureau. Editors:
Luke Sanders, 15; Will Sullivan, 15 and Marie Reff, 14.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is a story about Christy, a 16-year-old from Marquette
County, Mich., who has been in trouble with the law since she was
12. She told us that she had been through counseling from a young
age and it has helped her to understand her situation and see what
she wants to do with her life.
</P>
<P>
   Although she has had a tough home life, which seems to be the
root of a lot of problems among teens, she doesn't blame her
actions on anyone but herself, saying that everyone makes their own
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Christy also says that ``court sucks'' but that if you make bad
decisions, it's your fault that you're there. She is a wise person
who has learned a lot the hard way. Here is her story in her words:
</P>
<P>
   Christy: I don't think I'm a bad kid. I don't think that
anybody's bad kids. I just think that we make bad decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The crimes I've committed are one B&AMP;E (breaking and entering),
an obstruction of justice, domestic violence and a few assorted
misdemeanors.
</P>
<P>
   At the time I was committing those crimes, getting into trouble,
I was dating one of the head honchos of the gang. Technically I was
not involved in the gang, but the people I hung out with were.
</P>
<P>
   My home life pretty much sucked and still does. My dad's not
around. He lives at the bar. They're divorced, but my mom _ she is
a pretty big alcoholic and she gets really physical when she
drinks. I've gotten misdemeanors because I always run away.
Wouldn't you run away if your mom started beating on you? That's
why I ran away _ with no shoes.
</P>
<P>
   When I get physically abused by my mom when she's drunk, that's
being a victim. But nothing ever happened to her! I'm not blaming
my mom for my problems, 'cause she didn't make the decisions. I
did. But you know, it just kind of drove me to make the bad
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   I've never had money problems at home. I mostly get what I want
and if I don't get what I want I'll go out and get it myself. But I
think that if some kid has less money than another kid, he'll be
kind of envious and jealous and say, ``Well, since he has that and
I don't, then I can go kick his ...''
</P>
<P>
   I have this T-shirt that says ``People are not for hitting.'' No
matter what a person does, they're not meant to be hit or pushed
around. When that's happening I just feel kind of powerless. I want
to help them, or just go in there and say, ``Just back off, because
he didn't do anything.'' That happened today at lunch.
</P>
<P>
   I guess you gotta think about what you're doing before you go
hit somebody. If more people actually thought about what they were
doing instead of just doing it, I think that would control a lot of
the violence.
</P>
<P>
   When I got involved with the court system, I think I was about
12. The first few times you do something, they'll just slap you on
the wrist and say, ``Don't do it again.'' But if you are a habitual
criminal or a repeat offender, then they get a little bit harsh on
you.
</P>
<P>
   Now I'm on intensive probation, which means my probation officer
comes up and sees me a couple times a week during school; and right
now if I mess up, if I do something bad, I could get sent away to
lockup for a year.
</P>
<P>
   It does suck, but you know, if we weren't such
bad-decision-making kids we wouldn't be involved in the justice
system.
</P>
<P>
   Some day I'm pretty sure we'll realize that life's not one big
party. We've gotta wake up and get a job.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think community service is a punishment. It all depends
on what you're assigned to do. Sometimes they have kids out digging
holes in dirt and stuff. My program was great. I've done Bridges.
It's a program where you work with handicapped senior citizens and
you just become their friend for a while. It was pretty cool. It
made me wake up and realize that the senior citizens are not there
to just bug us and say that we're a bunch of nobodies.
</P>
<P>
   If you just try to be good and stay away from the bad influences
and hang tough, then you can get through it. And if you have good
support from friends, family, boyfriend, girlfriend, anybody _ it
really helps.
</P>
<P>
   I'm pretty much focusing on school right now _ it's about time _
and on getting my family life back together. I haven't had that for
about four years.
</P>
<P>
   I wish for the world to be a better place _ no more pollution
and all that. Another wish would be to have everybody be happy and
love one another so there's no fighting. And the third wish would
be for everybody to have a home and food to eat so there wouldn't
be anymore homeless people or hungry people I'd have to worry
about.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
