<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACING CIRCUIT VS. THE SALES CIRCUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R. WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Sunday the NASCAR faithful will have gathered in great
numbers to worship the idols of the Winston Cup at the shrine in
Loudon, N.H. The chief service of the day is the NASCAR Winston Cup
Jiffy Lube 300, as the name suggests, a 300-lap race named for its
sponsors, a cigarette manufacturer, and a franchiser of quick
oil-change facilities. This is not a gathering of Lutherans or
Episcopalians.
</P>
<P>
   While the races are named for, and the cars bear the logos of,
any person or enterprise willing to put up some bucks, it is the
auto manufacturers who have the most to win or lose _ or so they
would seem to believe. ``Win on Sunday, sell on Monday'' goes the
shibboleth that justifies this expensive pursuit of bragging
rights, and the likes of Ford and General Motors go head-to-head to
prove to prospective buyers the value of their products.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, for example, is pitting its Taurus against the General's
Monte Carlo (Chevy) and Grand Prix (Pontiac) on the NASCAR circuit
with pretty fair results _ Taurus has been very successful in the
'98 NASCAR campaign, with seven wins in the first 16 races and 50
top-five finishes out of a potential 80. Taurus? A racer?
</P>
<P>
   Well, not exactly _ but then neither is Monte Carlo nor Grand
Prix. These are all front-drive cars in the showrooms, and NASCAR
doesn't race front-drive cars, only front-drive marques. Those
racers are all rear-drive vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   So, it's a Taurus body with a rear-drive race car underneath?
Well, not exactly.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR has strict rules on body measurements _ fender height,
deck height, etc. And there are the aero enhancements, the skirts
and air dams and stuff that help move the air around a car and move
the car through the air efficiently. So, the Taurus racer standing
next to the showroom Taurus sedan doesn't look much like its
namesake _ not to mention the patchwork paint job with all the
sponsors' logos. A mouse doesn't resemble a camel much, either,
even though they are both mammals.
</P>
<P>
   Your showroom Taurus is an inch and a half shorter in the
wheelbase and about seven pounds lighter than the racer, powered by
a 200-horsepower, 3.0-liter Duratec V-6 with dual overhead
camshafts in tandem with a 5-speed, automatic transaxle. The
rear-drive racing Taurus has a 4-speed manual gearbox attached to a
700-horsepower (more or less), 5.8-liter V-8.
</P>
<P>
   But why is it necessary to race Taurus, the Ford flagship, to
sell it? It's been a winner from the beginning, with four million
on the road. Perhaps it isn't necessary, but Ford says it's
working, and, with the demise of Thunderbird, the Ford NASCAR barn
had been suddenly empty. Remember, too, that Taurus, the sales
leader from 1992 through 1996, had slipped to third behind Toyota
Camry and Honda Accord in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Taurus sales, Ford says, have gone up with the racing program,
increasing to 154,698 in the first five months of May from the like
'97 period total of 145,963. But is it the racing or is it
something else? Taurus is the only NASCAR label with increased
sales over 1997; Monte Carlo is off a smidgen, and Grand Prix is
down 13,600, according to Ford's figures.
</P>
<P>
   And what of Thunderbird? The 'Bird is the most successful single
marque in NASCAR history, with 284 victories and five championships
_ a rear-drive car on the street that more nearly resembled its
racetrack counterpart _ and yet its lackluster sales led Ford to
discontinue it.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe that's not exactly the whole story, either. Thunderbird
sales probably wouldn't have declined any more, might have gained a
little, with some marketing effort. It was a ``lateral'' seller
with a faithful following.
</P>
<P>
   And it's coming back. Maybe Ford just shelved it for a bit to
add some drama to its reincarnation as the Ford ``millennium'' car,
a roadster once more _ or maybe as a family of cars. Or maybe not.
I do know that Thunderbird is returning, and I suspect that the
racing program is a self-fulfilling sales prophecy: If you think it
works, it is working.
</P>
<P>
   And I'll bet that the Taurus dip in popularity in '97 was a
result of radical styling, not a lack of a racing pedigree.
</P>
<P>
   But I hope the manufacturers never discover that racing isn't
the sales tool it's hyped to be; there's a lot of technology under
the hoods of those street cars that was born in racing programs.
Racing may not do as much for the manufacturers as they think, but
it does plenty for the rest of us who cherish reliable,
fun-to-drive cars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For the on-line browsers, I'll be available to chat on line
about cars Tuesdays, 2 p.m. to 3 p.m. Just point your Internet
browser to http://www.boston.com and enter the keyword chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
