<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE NEWS IS BAD, ANALYSTS FEEL THE HEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV:Graphic has been sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (JT)  
 By RICK GLADSTONE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wall Street securities analysts occasionally deliver bad news on
a stock. But it's unusual when they unequivocally call their past
advice to buy it a blunder.
</P>
<P>
   That is what David Snyder, an analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette, did with regard to the shares of the Agco Corp., a
leading maker of farm equipment, whose stock has fallen by a third
since March and is languishing in the $19 to $20 range. Snyder
removed Agco from the firm's ``recommended list'' on May 30, saying
the company had often fallen short of earnings expectations since
1996, when it began an enormous expansion overseas. Given that
history, he wrote in a summary of Donaldson, Lufkin's stock picks,
``investors are not likely to be very patient with any
disappointments.''
</P>
<P>
   But Snyder went further. He wrote that Agco's stock valuation
would likely remain depressed, and that ``we have been terribly
wrong on Agco's stock over the past two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder subsequently left Donaldson, Lufkin, co-manager of the
underwriting of Agco securities in 1996 and 1997, for Dawson
Samberg Capital Management, a money management firm. Leslie
Thompson, a spokeswoman for Donaldson, Lufkin, called Snyder's
departure and the Agco downgrade coincidental. ``A good analyst is
an honest analyst,'' she said. `` Snyder is a very well respected
person. We have the highest regard for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder did not return several telephone calls for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Czelusniak, vice president of corporate relations at
Agco, said the company, based in Duluth, Ga., had only recently
learned that Snyder had moved on, but she declined to comment on
his departure.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Snyder's downgrade of Agco to ``market performance'' _
considered a euphemism for ``sell'' _ was conspicuous because of
its blunt, self-critical assessment of a perceived mistake. Against
the backdrop of the voracious appetite for stocks in a
seven-year-old bull market, a sell signal like that tends to stand
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He committed the unforgivable,'' said Marvin Roffman, a
securities analyst at Roffman Miller Associates in Philadelphia. In
the ``sell side'' world of stocks, Roffman said, ``even using the
word `sell' is anathema.'' Snyder was not the first to lower his
opinion of Agco. Eric Hunter, an analyst at S&AMP;P Equity Group, said
he downgraded the stock from ``accumulate'' to ``hold'' in January,
largely because the company was trying to maintain prices in Latin
America, one of its most promising markets, while rivals were
cutting theirs. ``How long can you maintain that strategy until you
lose customers?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Others say the stock remains attractive. John Mackin, who
follows Agco for Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, said the decline in
the share price reflected economic pressures in developing
countries that have affected all companies trying to sell costly
machinery abroad. His rating on the stock has been a ``strong buy''
for two years.
</P>
<P>
   Downgrades of stocks have become unusual in the last several
years, in part because of a marked change in the role analysts play
in a stock's prospects.
</P>
<P>
   These researchers once worked in relative obscurity to help
determine which stocks clients should buy and sell. Now, firms
compete more aggressively for the lucrative investment banking
business of publicly traded companies, so it is in their interest
to promote the stocks of those companies.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, critics say, many stock analysts who work for Wall
Street firms have grown too cozy with the companies they cover and
have lost credibility _ effectively becoming cheerleaders instead.
</P>
<P>
   That may help explain why recommendations to buy stocks vastly
outnumber recommendations to hold or sell. The First Call Corp., a
Boston research firm that tracks analysts' opinions on 6,000
stocks, says more than a third are rated ``strong buys,'' slightly
less than a third are ``buys,'' and most of the rest are ``holds.''
Only 1 percent are ``sells.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Hill, research director for First Call and a former
securities analyst himself, said there was more fear now among
analysts that they would offend their firm's investment banking
departments or the companies they cover.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some reluctance to put a sell on a stock,'' Hill
said. ``It's tougher now to be independent.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are far more indignant about what they regard as a high
level of excessively optimistic analysis, which they say hurts
investors' ability to gauge a stock's prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unequivocally, what you'll see is that today, analysts are
like the front guys,'' said Roffman, a former analyst at Janney
Montgomery Scott, a Philadelphia investment firm. ``They can't tell
it like it really is.''
</P>
<P>
   Roffman speaks from experience: He was dismissed by Janney
Montgomery in 1990 after he refused to retract a negative report
about the financial stability of Donald Trump's Taj Mahal casino
after Trump had complained and pushed for Roffman's dismissal.
Roffman then started his own research firm, unfettered by possible
conflicts that might arise if he were also trying to generate
investment banking fees. Roffman also sued Trump, contending
defamation, settled the case for an undisclosed sum and was awarded
$750,000 from Janney Montgomery in a New York Stock Exchange
arbitration claim.
</P>
<P>
   Roffman's case was well-known in the industry, but there have
been other, less publicized examples. Wall Street firms sometimes
lose a client company's investment banking business because of a
downgrade, and analysts have been ostracized by a company in
retaliation for a downgrade. Sometimes, a company sharply curtails
analyst access to management if it deems that a rating on its stock
is too low.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Michael L. Mayo, a banking analyst at Credit Suisse
First Boston, was excluded from a Mellon Bank analysts meeting.
When he asked why, he said Mellon executives told him it was
``because of your rating on the stock.'' Mayo rates Mellon as a
``hold.'' Mellon declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Even analysts who do not work for Wall Street firms can find it
difficult to appraise a company's stock critically. Like others,
they try to maintain cordial relations with a company's management
to gain access to information that will help them evaluate growth
potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot more leeway than these guys on the Street.
There's not much a company can do if we downgrade its stock,'' said
Hunter of S&AMP;P Equity Group. Still, he said, issuing a downgrade
``is never a comfortable situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, however, a sell signal can make an analyst a hero.
Andrew Shore, an analyst at Paine Webber, downgraded the shares of
the Sunbeam Corp. in early April before the appliance company _
formerly a Wall Street darling _ began a plunge from the mid-$40s
to the $10 level last month. Shore was also the first analyst to
publicly question the capability of Albert Dunlap, Sunbeam's chief
executive, who was dismissed on June 13 amid growing questions
about the company's accounting practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I had made a major sell call like this in my
whole life,'' Shore recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after he downgraded the stock, Shore said, he
received some ``extremely nasty phone messages.'' Weeks later, he
said, some of those same callers phoned to apologize and to thank
him.
</P>
<P>
   Shore said that he felt vindicated but that any analyst who
issued a sell recommendation had better be right.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot more pressure when you say sell,'' he said.
``Everyone who owns it at least listens when you say sell.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 1704EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
