<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9544 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      07-10 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVE LAWMAKER CREDIT FOR WHAT TAX RELIEF KANSANS HAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Phill Kline and his fellow tax-relief crusaders
continue to have their view of the world validated by Kansas'
explosive revenue growth.
</P>
<P>
   The Shawnee Republican has made a fair shake for taxpayers the
centerpiece of his political career, but all he's gotten for his
trouble from GOP moderates is a jaundiced eye and a maverick label.
Meantime, many Kansans who have benefited most from Kline's
tax-relief quest probably are unaware of the good he's done them.
</P>
<P>
   It's safe to say, though, that considerably less tax relief
would have emanated from Topeka in recent years without the House
Taxation Committee chairman's dogged crusade. He was vindicated yet
again last week when the final accounting for fiscal year 1998
showed tax receipts much higher than anyone expected.
</P>
<P>
   Although revenue estimates for fiscal '98 were revised upward by
$70 million in April, the final tax take topped even those high
expectations by $52 million when the fiscal year ended June 30. All
told, tax collections were up 10.5 percent and individual income
tax receipts rose a whopping 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   This probably didn't surprise Kline, who continually insists the
state can afford more tax relief than many want to give. Moderates
usually counsel caution, warning that good economic times can't be
counted on to continue forever. Kline says that's no excuse for the
state not to share more of its bounty with its taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout this clash of wills, the argument has focused on
whether state government should make out better than the taxpayers
who provide the revenue. Kline says Topeka gets too much of the
best of things, and the latest revenue figures seem to bear him out
convincingly. How many average Kansas taxpayers, for instance,
enjoyed the same 10-percent-plus income boost that state government
experienced during the past year?
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, substantial tax relief was enacted during this
year's session of the Legislature, but tax relief Topeka-style
doesn't do justice to the average taxpayer. It's a scatter-gun
approach that may or may not get the money back into the pockets of
those who make the state's continuing windfalls possible.
</P>
<P>
   What Kansas needs, and what Kline and his allies should pursue,
is a mechanism such as Missouri's Hancock Amendment that mandates
rebates directly to taxpayers when the state's income growth
outpaces that of its taxpaying benefactors.
</P>
<P>
   The nationwide tax revolt launched 20 years ago last month by
voter approval of California's Proposition 13 has done much to ease
the burden of taxpayers throughout the land. As Policy Review
recently noted, within two years of the initiative's passage, 43
states had moved to provide some form of property tax relief, 15
had lowered income tax rates and 10 indexed income taxes to
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayers in some states have fared better than others, and
while Kansas has had its moments, it hasn't exactly been in the
tax-relief vanguard. It still taxes food, for example, and until
recently had one of the most onerous property taxes on cars in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, as the economic expansion of the '90s has proceeded
apace, many in Topeka have resisted sharing the state's good
fortune fully with its taxpayers. Given the embarrassment of riches
of fiscal '98, it's obvious that Kansas taxpayers need the same
protection the Hancock Amendment provides for Missourians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 1714EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
