r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HALLMARK-PURCHASE-KAN     07-10 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HALLMARK-PURCHASE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALLMARK CARDS TO SPEND $310 MILLION TO BUY CREATIVE PUBLISHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Hallmark Cards Inc. said Thursday it is
spending $310 million to buy Creative Publishing plc in the United
Kingdom, the latest move in an international market share slugfest
with rival American Greetings Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland-based American Greetings bought two United Kingdom
competitors earlier this year, which boosted its market share to
nearly 20 percent and over Hallmark's 14.5 percent share.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday's move by Kansas City-based Hallmark would once
again put it back on top in the United Kingdom, home to the most
active card-buying population on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fitting claim because the first known commericially made
card was created in England in 1819. Per capita purchases of
greeting cards in the United Kingdom are 50 to 55 cards a year,
compared with 28 to 30 in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our interest has always been to be the market share leader in
the United Kingdom...because it is such an important market,'' said
Hallmark spokesman Steve Doyal.
</P>
<P>
   When Hallmark completes its buyout of Creative Publishing, it
will own just under 30 percent of the greeting card market in the
United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Doyal said Creative Publishing is a perfect fit with Hallmark
because there is little overlap between the two. Hallmark is the
United Kingdom leader in everday cards, while Creative Publishing's
strength is in boxed cards. Plus, Doyal said, the two distribute
their products differently.
</P>
<P>
   As a result no layoffs are planned, and Hallmark will be able to
use a production facility owned by Creative Publishing. Hallmark
currently outsources its production in the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Hallmark had worldwide sales of $3.66 billion last year,
compared with $2.2 billion for American Greetings, whose fiscal
year ended Feb. 28.
</P>
<P>
   Greeting card analyst E. Gray Glass III said the three biggest
greeting card markets in the world are the United States, the
United Kingdom and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Until Thursday's move, American Greetings was No. 1 in the
United Kingdom and Canada, where it has more than 40 percent of the
market and Hallmark has 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Hallmark is the leader with an estimated
44 percent of the market, compared with about 30 percent for
American Greetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This puts Hallmark back on top in two of the three most
important markets,'' Glass said.
</P>
<P>
   That is, if the deal gets done.
</P>
<P>
   There was some supposition Thursday that American Greetings
would make a rival bid for Creative Publishing. American Greetings
spokesman Jim King said the company doesn't comment on speculation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will say we've made two acquisitions in the U.K. this year,
one in March and one in May, that nearly doubled our market
position...and we're quite pleased with the way those have worked
out,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about American Greetings making a rival bid, Doyal said,
``It's hard to tell what they might do.''
</P>
<P>
   Doyal said Hallmark and Creative Publishing will make a formal
filing with the Office of Fair Trade, which will be followed by a
20-day comment period. It is possible, Doyal said, that if American
Greetings were going to make a rival bid, it would do so during
that period.
</P>
<P>
   Just how important is it to be No. 1 in any given market?
</P>
<P>
   In a American Greetings press release dated May 11, when it
acquired the second of two United Kingdom competitors this year, it
boasted of its strengthened market share in the United Kingdom, and
that it is No. 1 in Australia, New Zealand, Canada and South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday, King of American Greetings downplayed being No.
1 in a market just for the sake of being No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think us or Hallmark is going to get into a market
share game that doesn't make sense,'' King said. ``We're more
focused on does an acquisition make sense...than we're size X and
they're size Y.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
