<HEADER>
A9553 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCINERNEY-FASHION-NOV     07-10 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCINERNEY-FASHION-NOVEL-525&AMP;ADD-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'80S VOICES ON PARALLEL FASHION TRACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday July 12)  
(lh) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ From the moment that the hapless hero of Jay
McInerney's coming novel, ``Model Behavior,'' slaloms through a
crowd of air-kissing New York fashionistas at the ``party you have
been to 600 times already,'' you are prepared for 176 pages of
haute-runway literature.
</P>
<P>
   The book traces the unraveling relationship of a
fashion-magazine journalist and his size 6 girlfriend, who is
employed as a model in the New York hothouse of fashion, where
appearance is destiny.
</P>
<P>
   The book is one of two titles with themes of fashion and
celebrity that Alfred A. Knopf is preparing to publish in the next
six months. The second, ``Glamorama,'' is by Bret Easton Ellis, the
author of ``Less Than Zero'' and ``American Psycho.''
</P>
<P>
   These two are not just any authors, of course. A decade or so
ago, at the outset of their careers, McInerney and Ellis were
regarded as chroniclers in touch with the tenor of the times, their
youthful characters experiencing dissipation against the background
rush of 1980s urban materialism.
</P>
<P>
   A decade later, fashion, modeling and personal appearance have
assumed a focal place in popular culture, and McInerney and Ellis,
with uncanny timing, have popped up again as authors attuned to the
Zeitgeist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fashion has become so all pervasive _ it reminds me of back in
the '80s when people asked why are you writing about drugs,''
McInerney said, referring to his first novel, ``Bright Lights, Big
City.'' ``To which I answer, How can you not?''
</P>
<P>
   McInerney, whose first wife was a model and who later lived with
another model, Marla Hanson, for four years, insisted that fashion
was only one strand in his novel _ although it is a thick one. In
the book, which is scheduled for publication in September, he makes
some rather stinging observations about the ``howling
mindlessness'' of the profession of modeling. And that state is
precisely what appeals to McInerney.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's interesting about models is precisely nothing except
what we choose to invest in them,'' he said. ``They are empty
vessels, and by definition, they're pure surface. The model's job
used to be to sell clothes. And oddly enough it's become more and
more about selling a notion of glamor and celebrity. What appeals
to me about writing about a model is what it tells us about us.''
</P>
<P>
   McInerney shares a close friendship with Ellis, along with a
common editor and agent. They also write about literary characters
with a similar penchant for dating models.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, they don't share fashion tips, but McInerney does
include a passing reference in ``Model Behavior'' to Ellis, whose
blurb of praise for a short-story collection by one of the literary
characters is greeted with barbed enthusiasm: ``Oh, yeah, terrific.
All the homicidal slackers will skateboard straight to Barnes &AMP;
Noble for a copy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Fisketjon, the editor for both authors, described the
titles as ``very, very different books. Jay's book is a highly
comic novel, and Bret's book _ certainly while extraordinarily
funny in the first half or third _ is a much darker, darker book''
(i.e. _ imploding hotels and plunging planes).
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Fisketjon said that Ellis has been working on his novel for more
than eight years, while McInerney's novel grew out of a short story
called ``Philomena'' that he wrote four years ago for The New
Yorker. McInerney's book also includes a collection of seven short
stories that span his career.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis was traveling in London this week to promote a BBC
documentary about himself, and he did not respond to messages. A
paragraph in the publisher's fall catalogue refers to his new novel
of ``a young man in what is recognizably the fashion and celebrity
obsessed New York'' who is drawn into a shadowy mirror of that
society.
</P>
<P>
   But a friend of Ellis', Julie Grau, sketched out the broader
outlines of the novel, which is scheduled for publication in
January. The plot revolves around a sometime model and would-be
actor named Victor, who necessarily dates models and operates a
nightclub with a shadowy impresario. Real celebrities mingle with
Ellis' imaginary characters, and the plot shifts among the fashion
worlds of New York, London and Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Grau, who is an editorial director at Riverhead Books, said
Ellis had conducted a considerable amount of personal research for
his novel, including cruising to Europe aboard the QE2 _ which
figures in his book _ and haunting the fashion shows of Paris. She
said that it was happenstance that two friends and contemporaries
like Ellis and McInerney were both fascinated by fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, both of them travel in this sophisticated New York
world in which the fashion industry winds its way through it,'' she
said. ``And I think it's just a coincidence of these two writers
emerging from this time, and traveling in the same circles and
finding something fascinating, lampoonable and emblematic of our
fixation, as a society, with beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   But when the writers meet at these glittering parties, do they
exchange literary updates? Divvy up the searing anecdotes for their
novels?
</P>
<P>
   McInerney said that he and Ellis avoid the topic of their work.
</P>
<P>
   But, he joked, ``every once in a while he'll ask who made my
suit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
