<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-SATELLITE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER SATELLITE GETS EMERGENCY CALL TO ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT CAMPBELL  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Less than a month after completing tests on a
spare weather satellite parked in space high above the Midwest,
forecasters already are calling it to the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration activated
the backup bird Thursday when one of the two older satellites that
gives a complete view of North America and surrounding oceans
threatened to go wobbly.
</P>
<P>
   The timing was perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We applaud our superior planning,'' quipped Gerald Dittberner,
satellite program manager for the agency in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Also applauding are forecasters on the 17th floor of the Bolling
Federal Building in Kansas City, where the Aviation Weather Center
provides crucial information for aircraft from the Philippines to
the Azores.
</P>
<P>
   The satellites also give earthbound folks advance notice of
hurricanes approaching in the Atlantic as well as storm systems
coming in from the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Antennae on the federal building receive information from the
satellites that is just 7 minutes old. Losing a satellite would be
serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our forecasters sitting in downtown Kansas City would suffer
greatly trying to look at a real-time picture and see what's
happening out there,'' said Jim Henderson, deputy director of the
Aviation Weather Center.
</P>
<P>
   The weather center can warn a passenger jet from Japan to avoid
a storm near the International Date Line. It also can see into
valleys of the Sierra Nevada to caution a twin-engine plane about
fog.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for us to have a view from space,'' said Peter
Browning of the National Weather Service in Pleasant Hill, Mo. ``We
can see visible imagery during the day, and 24 hours a day we get
the various infrared channels.''
</P>
<P>
   With that information, forecasters can determine the temperature
of the cloud tops to judge the severity of a storm front sweeping
down the plains toward Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The space eyes are called GOES, which stands for geostationary
operational environmental satellite. They are parked 22,300 miles
above the equator where they rotate with the Earth, providing a
constant view below.
</P>
<P>
   One is parked on a longitude roughly in line with Philadephia
and the other on a line roughly with Juneau, Alaska. It is the west
one, GOES-9, that is dying. One of two gyroscopes that keep it
steady failed in June. Now the other one is acting up.
</P>
<P>
   So GOES-10, which was launched by NASA in April 1997 but
certified ``all system go'' only last month, is being pressed into
service. There will be little or no disruption in weather data or
in the familiar video loops seen on television newscasts.
</P>
<P>
   GOES-10 is now parked on a longitude roughly in line with
Denver. It will be moved west to the position of GOES-9, which will
be shoved a few hundred miles farther into space.
</P>
<P>
   This series of four GOES satellites, built by Loral Corp., cost
about $2 billion. Each was supposed to last at least five years.
GOES-9 lasted a little more than three years.
</P>
<P>
   The eastern one, GOES-8, has been operating more than four
years. The question now is whether it will keep working until the
next GOES is launched in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have gone through a single-satellite scenario before and we
didn't enjoy that a lot,'' Browning said. ``There was a lot of
finger-crossing hoping (GOES-9) wouldn't fail before we got a new
one up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Dittberner added: ``So far, so good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
