<HEADER>
A9560 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTIBIOTICS-ANIMALS-K     07-10 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIBIOTICS-ANIMALS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY RAISES CONCERNS ABOUT ANTIBIOTICS FOR ANIMALS CONSUMED BY
HUMANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MANSUR  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: To keep them healthy and speed their growth, the
nation's cattle, hogs, poultry and other food animals are fed 19
million pounds of antibiotics each year.
</P>
<P>
   But a new national study raised troubling health concerns
Thursday about the widespread practice.
</P>
<P>
   The routine use of antibiotics on farms has created strains of
disease-causing bacteria that are resistant to the antibiotics and
infect more humans every year, according to the National Research
Council's study.
</P>
<P>
   ``The National Research Council report is a landmark because it
is the first authoritative U.S. report that explicitly acknowledges
that agricultural uses of antibiotics pose a risk to the public
health,'' said Michael Jacobson, executive director of the Center
for Science in the Public Interest, a health advocacy group in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The National Research Council committee that wrote the report
was led by James Coffman, Kansas State University provost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Using antibiotics to control and treat diseases in animals
improves the safety of our food supply by providing healthier
sources of meat, cheese, milk and eggs,'' Coffman said in a
statement released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there have been a few cases in which resistant bacteria
have been passed to people.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the committee found that ``there is no doubt'' that
drug-resistant bacteria are passed from animals to humans. It can
occur through direct contact with animals or their manure, through
exposure to food contaminated by the bacteria or person-to-person
contact.
</P>
<P>
   The study said it's uncertain, though, how much the use of
antibiotics in animals has contributed to the recent increase in
resistant strains of bacteria that infect humans.
</P>
<P>
   Public and animal health advocates have debated for years
whether the widespread use of low levels of antibiotics in food
animals might harm humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been some debate, especially in agribusiness, that
says the use of antibiotics on animals is a separate pool (from the
human pool) and the animal usage can't affect the resistance
problem that people have,'' said Jean Halloran, director of the
Consumer Policy Institute for the Consumer's Union of United States
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``The committee concluded this was not a debate,'' said
Halloran, who also served on the National Research Council
committee. ``It said, `This is not true. The pools overlap.' ''
</P>
<P>
   This is the study's key finding, she said, and it should give
consumers another reason to make sure to cook meat thoroughly and
take other precautions, such as washing cutting boards and knives
after chopping chicken.
</P>
<P>
   ``One would have to say there is not yet a massive problem of
antibiotic resistant infections, for if it were we would know
that,'' Halloran continued. ``But the problem could get worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at a point now where we can do something. We shouldn't
let this problem get out of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Animal Health Institute, a trade
association of animal drug makers, said Thursday that the group has
yet to review the new study but believes questions remain about the
scientific certainty of the link between resistant strains in
animals and humans.
</P>
<P>
   Those questions should be resolved before any regulatory actions
occur, said Lisa Dry, the institute's spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The group recently proposed its own plan to address the issue of
antibiotic use in animals. It includes new guidelines for the
prudent use of the drugs in farm animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We share the concerns of the human medial community that
overuse of these important medicines can lead to resistance,'' said
Alexander Mathews, president and CEO of the Animal Health
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some public health advocates, such as the Center for
Science in the Public Interest, have called for a government ban on
routine antibiotic use in food animals.
</P>
<P>
   But the National Research Council committee didn't go that far,
saying more research and data collection should be done first. The
committee's recommendations included:
</P>
<P>
   Create a national database on antibiotic use and resistance
trends that would be accessible to farmers, veterinarians, doctors
and other interest groups.
</P>
<P>
   Establish a national oversight panel that includes regulators,
animal and human health experts, agriculture and consumer groups to
monitor the new data and to recommend how antibiotics should be
used in humans and animals.
</P>
<P>
   Improve the research budgets for developing new classes of
antibiotics. That would ensure a future alternative to the current
drugs in use.
</P>
<P>
   Educate the public on the proper use of antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, antibiotic-resistant strains of salmonella and
other disease-causing bacteria have grown, raising new concerns
among public health officials.
</P>
<P>
   Cases of human infection related to one type of salmonella, for
example, have remained relatively flat in the United States,
according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. But 34
percent of those salmonella cases in 1996 involved a strain
resistant to five types of antibiotics. In 1980, less than one
percent involved antibiotic-resistant strains.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study in the New England Journal of Medicine estimated
that this type of drug-resistant salmonella, known as DT104, may
now account for up to 340,0000 cases in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   This same strain has posed even more concern in Britain, where
some public health officials estimate it may account for more
sickness and death than any other type of salmonella. Britain has
banned the use of human antibiotics at low or ``subtherapeutic''
levels.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the World Health Organization proposed phasing out the
use of antibiotics, particularly those used to treat humans, at
subtherapeutic levels.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 years ago, scientists reported that using low
levels of antibiotics could increase the growth rate of farm
animals. Today, 88 percent of the antibiotic drugs used in
livestock and poultry are given at subtherapeutic levels, the
National Research Council study found.
</P>
<P>
   The drugs keep the animals healthier, especially when many are
confined tightly inside barns. The drugs are fed to the animals in
their feed or water.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 1718EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
