<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9564 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-NEA-COMMENT-KAN &LR;      07-10 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NEA-COMMENT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALL IT THE ART OF KILLING DEMOCRACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALICE THORSON  
 c. 1998 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: The Supreme Court's recent ruling that the National
Endowment for the Arts can apply decency standards in choosing what
art it will fund ostensibly is an attempt to curb the means of
artistic expression. But its real target is the end of much
avant-garde art, namely its liberal social agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The defunding of some art on grounds of indecency and obscenity
is ironic, considering the government-funded obscenities we read
about every day. Think of the behavior of people whose five- and
six-figure salaries taxpayers pay annually. Where to begin? The
Lewinsky scandal? Trent Lott's misinformation campaign against
gays?
</P>
<P>
   What does it say about our society that we have less trouble
giving lots of money to scoundrels and bigots than a measly
one-time grant to a lone artist who chose to smear herself with
chocolate and bean sprouts as a means of self-expression and
feminist social comment?
</P>
<P>
   Karen Finley is not unique among contemporary artists in
devoting a lot of her time to thinking about where this society is
falling short and where it's headed.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is she unique in stridently expressing her criticisms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Post-sixties agit-prop'' is how The Wall Street Journal, in a
recent editorial, referred to art funded by the NEA.
</P>
<P>
   Agit-prop. With or without the artist's consent, art has always
been used as propaganda for something _ from the Christian faith to
Stalinism. And as anyone who has taken the time to experience it
knows, at the heart of most of this so-called ``post-sixties
agit-prop'' art is advocacy of the values most important to
democracy: tolerance for difference, intolerance of discrimination,
the free and open exchange of ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Now what could be more worthy of funding than that?
</P>
<P>
   One concern expressed by The Wall Street Journal editorialist
was that ``endowment grants were being used to jump the social
queue, to in a single funding cycle establish as normal ideas and
lifestyles that otherwise might take a generation to enter the
mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, indeed. Women and people of color, lesbians and homosexuals
all have reaped the benefits of this agitprop art's leadership role
in making the mainstream respond to their complaints and concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy, for instance, over Robert Mapplethorpe's
photographs, which helped to spawn this long-running funding debate
and the so-called ``culture wars,'' did more to focus public
attention on the gay presence in the population and their issues
than any talk show could ever achieve. But if there hadn't been
public funding involved, it might well have taken a generation to
get these issues on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   A not unimportant dimension of these public-funded art
controversies is their role as lightning rod for the country's
philistinism, Puritanism, religion-based intolerance and
stultifying ignorance about art's role in shaping culture.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the way contemporary artists go about it is not very
pretty, or downright offensive to some. But the aims of their art
are quite different from those of the great art of the past
commissioned by the church, the monarchy and the nobility, which is
the art that contemporary art-bashers invariably hold up as a
standard.
</P>
<P>
   The fact remains that much recent art funded by the NEA has been
about holding democracy to its promise. Apparently, a lot of
powerful people have a problem with that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
