<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-HANGING-REVIEW-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HANGING GARDEN' HAS SOME BLOOMING WEIRDNESS IN IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 1998 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Hanging Garden,'' a romantic drama, is rated R for
language, sexuality and drug use. Running time is 1 hour 31
minutes. Two out of four stars.
</P>
<P>
   Most movies fail because they don't try to be anything. ``The
Hanging Garden,'' at least, fails because it tries to be too much.
</P>
<P>
   This surreal Canadian comedy//drama practically defies
categorization. That it's a homecoming movie and a
dysfunctional-family movie is obvious from the first scene, when
our gay central character returns after a 10-year absence to attend
his sister's wedding.
</P>
<P>
   It's an event to forget. Alcohol-sodden Dad snores through the
ceremony, Granny is in a full-throttle Alzheimer's episode, the
sullen bride is a vision of venom in white, and Mom quietly seethes
at the indignity of it all. To top it off, the new arrival
discovers he has a 10-year-old tomboy sister he never knew existed
and has to endure an amorous pass from the groom.
</P>
<P>
   Then things get weirder.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Fitzgerald's writing//directing debut takes its title from
the family's huge garden. The clan is so horticulturally obsessed
that Dad (Peter MacNeill) is known as ``Poppy,'' Mom (Seana
McKenna) is named Iris, Sis (Kerry Fox) is Rosemary, the
unsuspected little sibling (Christine Dunsworth) is Violet. Our
visiting hero is Sweet William (Chris Leavins).
</P>
<P>
   Other characters are called Black-Eyed Susan, Laurel, Basil and
Dusty Miller. There's a dog named Peat.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the wedding, the family falls apart. Dad throws
his weight around and threatens to get violent. After years of
putting up with the garbage, Mom vanishes one night.
</P>
<P>
   Weirder still, Sweet William is haunted by earlier versions of
himself. He keeps stumbling across himself as an abused little boy
(Ian Parsons) and as an obese, miserable gay teen (Troy Veinotte)
who halfway through the film hangs himself from a tree (thus ``The
Hanging Garden'').
</P>
<P>
   Even though much of ``The Hanging Garden'' doesn't work, one can
only admire the efforts of a large and remarkably talented cast who
make these characters seem painfully real and who somehow make
palatable the script's more outlandish notions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 1720EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
