</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OVERPOPULATION-CEXP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNCIL TRIES TO SLOW EARTH'S POPULATION GROWTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDITORS: Children's Express is an independent, non-profit news
service reported by children whose tape-recorded interviews,
roundtables and commentary are edited by teens and adults. The
features are transmitted by The New York Times Service and are
available to New York Times News Service clients at no extra
charge.) 
(JT) 
 By Children's Express/New York Bureau. Editor: Monique Bishop, 15.
Reporters: Olivia Ryan, 9 and Joel Solow, 10    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Humans won't have to go to subterranean settlements or colonize
another planet to solve it, but overpopulation is a really big
thing. It is mosly caused by lack of birth control and education,
and young marriage, according to Christina Horpeza, the public
information specialist for the Population Council.
</P>
<P>
   The council was founded 30 years ago to address the problem of
overpopulation, to understand the factors that affect it. Horpeza's
group believes education is the key, because they found that the
more educated people are, the fewer children they have.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's kind of an over-simplification of this situation, but
basically when people are educated, they tend to have fewer
children and they have them spaced apart,'' said Horpeza. ``It
makes for healthier children and it's better for the family.''
</P>
<P>
   She said overpopulation was a very complex situation that you
can't attribute to one cause or another, but Horpeza thinks there
should be a worldwide effort to fund programs to teach people about
birth control.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for the women, and it's good for the society. In
many countries, the custom is for children to get married when
they're still teenagers. They start having babies right away. If
you get married when you're 15, you can have 10 children by the
time you're 30. If you get married when you're 20, you have fewer
children,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there could be laws that say you can't get married
before age 16, 18, whatever. But to have people actually respect
the laws and obey the laws, you need education to tell them why
this is important.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at a point where throughout the world, the largest
number of youth are entering their reproductive ages, 16 through
44.''
</P>
<P>
   The council does a lot of studies and found that it's not
necessarily ``developed versus developing'' countries when looking
at what poses the greatest risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're finding that more and more people are moving into cities
and putting a lot of stress on the environment,'' said Horpeza.
``This happens in developed countries as well as in developing
countries, but a lot of times in developing countries, they don't
have the infrastructure to provide services for the people.
</P>
<P>
   ``A key component is actually the distribution of food, getting
food from the area where it's grown to where the people are who
need it. You could be a producer of zillions of acres of meat. If
you can't get it to the people, what good is it? That's probably
the bigger problem right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Horpeza said that there are a certain number of births per
couple that the earth needs to replace itself, and that is 2.1,
which would mean that if every couple in the world were to have two
children it would keep the population at the same level.
</P>
<P>
   ``The .1 is to allow for people that die young,'' she said.
``(And) some people will be having three (children), some will have
one.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked how she felt about the law in China that says how
many children a couple should have, Horpeza said that she didn't
feel it was working.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should have laws. It should be voluntary.
That policy is coercive. People try to get around that and they end
up hurting themselves or other people. They have done research and
found that the girl babies are less cared for and sometimes they're
not reported to officials because the Chinese prefer boy babies.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one should be told how many children you're going to have,
but people should be aware of the health implications and knowing
how to have the resources to take care of the children.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if some of the countries that are overpopulated
should shift some of their people to underpopulated countries to
balance things out, Horpeza said that it was already happening and
not working.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexicans are trying desperately to come here to make a living.
When they come here, they find conditions aren't fair,'' she said.
``Then we have a whole debate in Congress about whether we should
support them with our welfare system or educate their children. In
Indonesia where their economy is going down, they're trying to
immigrate to Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never that simple. There's always one country with a good
economy that everybody wants to go to. All the pressure is on that
country. Hopefully, the more we go along, we educate more people
and we work out equitable economies.''
</P>
<P>
   The best approach, she said again, is for ``children to be in
school. Go to school for as long as possible and learn. Don't start
quitting school to work and have babies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
