<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV12-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PROPOSAL THAT MAKES SENSE FOR TEACHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 12 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Tom Birmingham knew he'd struck a chord when he stopped
in his Chelsea Dunkin' Donuts for the coffee he gulps before
heading to his State House office.
</P>
<P>
   The morning paper had splashed the Massachusetts Senate
president's bold suggestion that the state offer a $20,000 signup
bonus for outstanding candidates to become public school teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arthur Orloff wants to be one of those teachers,'' declared a
grinning Birmingham of one of the Dunkin' regulars. Later in the
day, the Chicago Tribune, Washington Post and Time Magazine would
ring up seeking details. But Birmingham knew that once you've
cracked the Dunkin' Donuts kaffee klatsch krowd with a
conversation-provoking notion, events take on a life of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Not for the first time has Birmingham, the most liberal of the
commonwealth's top state-level officeholders, taken an idea and
twisted it into a legislative proposal that challenges
conservatives to put up or shut up.
</P>
<P>
   You want better school teachers? Then put up or shut up.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get what you pay for,'' said the Senate president, a labor
lawyer by trade with strong union sympathies. If the best and
brightest college grads want no part of the chore of improving the
public schools, then give them enough of an incentive to make them
swerve out of their other career choices into the educational
trenches.
</P>
<P>
   His idea was spawned in the dismay over the teacher
certification test scores, when more than half the applicants
failed. ``First we had the teacher test results, which were
apalling,'' said Birmingham Thursday. ``Then we had two weeks of
gnashing-of-teeth, recriminations, the predictable blame-tossing,
and so forth. Plus, we had the news of the big increase in the
state (tax yield) surplus. So I saw the convergence, and married
the two.''
</P>
<P>
   His bold scheme caught the ususal bemoaners of public education
flat-footed. Many of our leading lights of the capitalist system
believe fervently in the merits of financial incentives for
corporate bosses, tort lawyers, first basemen and point guards. But
try and implement any such scheme for public servants, and there's
hell to pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a whole slew of reasons why bright college graduates
do not want to become school teachers, but one of them is
financial.''
</P>
<P>
   So he will ask the state Senate to approve, in its financial
definciency budget of the year, which will pass before July 31,
enough money to start a system of $20,000 bonus incentives for the
best and brightest of the college crop.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is roughly parallel to the deal the US military struck
with medical students in past years, when the services had
difficulty retaining doctors. Uncle Sam paid for medical school
tuition, in exchange for a certain number of years' commitment to
serve as a military doc. The Pentagon has launched different
incentive programs to retain highly-trained personnel such as
pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Teaching has taken a nosedive in status in recent years, said
Birmingham. ``We used to rely on gender discrimination, when all
those bright professional women who could not look forward to a
career in medicine or the law became school teachers instead.
</P>
<P>
   With only seven GOP senators in the 40-member Senate, Birmingham
is confident he can deliver the votes to put the Senate on record
for his bonus plan. He mocked conservatives who say ``they are
'shocked, shocked,' that we have to pay people more than we do to
be teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonuses in other states, in the $1,500 range, are nowhere near
high enough to affect the recruitment stream, he reasoned.
``Nobody's going to make a career decision for 1,500 bucks.''
</P>
<P>
   If this is a capitalist system, he argues, and if money is the
huge incentive for mutual fund traders and stock brokers and big
league ballplayers, why don't the same rules apply to essential
professionals like teachers?
</P>
<P>
   But the teacher bonus may come to an abrupt demise in the
Massachusetts House, where Speaker Tom Finneran (D-Dorchester),
elected in the first place by the votes of Republican House
members, has stalled a number of Senate-approved initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's plan to spend $72 million on improvements to or
near Foxboro Stadium for the benefit of New England Patriots ownber
Robert Kraft is going nowhere in the House. And the Senate-approved
hike in the state's minimum wage, to $6.75 in stages, and thence to
be indexed to inflation, is similarly stalled, as are various
measures like a domestic partners' bill.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these Senate-passed bills are being held hostage to
Finneran's conservative philosophic constructs. A pattern has
developed where Birmingham, a product of the Chelsea public
schools, a Catholic high school (Austin Prep), and Harvard and
Oxford, pushes progressive ideas, which come to naught in the
House. That pattern seems not to disturb Acting Gov. Cellucci,
whose re-election strategy seems to consist of trying not to rock
any boat, no matter how small a dinghy, in the scheme of things.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this session, Birmingham had challenged the business
community, which has been bemoaning the lack of skilled workers in
this Golden Age of an economy.
</P>
<P>
   The business lobby had been agitating for two causes: a
reduction in the unemployment compensation tax, because the flush
times had built up a considerable surplus in the fund that pays
unemployment benefits; and some state financial help to retrain
workers whose skills need upgrading.
</P>
<P>
   Birmingham offered them a deal: he'd ask the Legislature to
reduce the employer-paid comp tax by $98 million, while at the same
time setting aside $18 million for the state to underwrite the
re-training of existing workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you and I _ the taxpayers _ were going to be asked to pay
for retraining, that was the No. 1 priority for Associated
Industries of Massachusetts (the prime business lobby). But when
AIM saw my offer, their reply was `no deal.' They only want
retraining if someone else pays for it.''
</P>
<P>
   With the legislative session due to end July 31, and with little
more than passage of the required $19.4 billion state budget due to
be accomplished, Birmingham seems to be setting out some bold
positions in hopes that next year more might be achieved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
