<P>
   GM-STRIKE _ It's been nearly three decades since the General
Motors Corp. has faced more pressure to settle labor disputes with
a workforce that has crippled its production and caused
billion-dollar losses. Heading into this weekend, anticpiation is
high that GM and the United Auto Workers can settle two strikes at
plants in Flint, Mich. that started in early June and has idled
162,000 workers. But if Flint accords can't be reached this
weekend, GM losses will start climbing towards $2 billion and the
automaker could suffer permanent losses to its market share. The
automaker also must keep making progress in talks with Local UAW
leaders in Dayton and Indianapolis or risk having a repeat of the
Flint labor unrest later this summer. Everyone from the striking
workers to GM dealers and suppliers continue to feel the economic
crunch of the strike. (Wagner, Dayton Daily News) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   APPLE _ There was a lot of excitement and optimism at Apple
Computer's Macworld Expo this week in New York. How long that lasts
depends on the success of the iMac, due out in mid-August. After
hoping for a big boost from its New York sojourn, the company has
already said it would move the expo back to Boston. An assessment
of Macworld. (Mahoney, Austin American-Statesman) ETA: 7 p.m. ET
</P>
<P>
   UPS-JOBS _ Neither side expects another strike, but the
Teamsters and United Parcel Service are at it again. This time, the
union is accusing the UPS of trying to sidestep a promise to create
2,000 full-time jobs this year. UPS spokesman Norman Black
confirmed Thursday that the company notified the union that it
won't add the jobs this year. Black said it was because package
volume had not rebounded completely from last summer's 15-day
strike. (Mitchell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m ET
</P>
<P>
   APPLE-IMAC _ NEW YORK _ The iMac, Apple Computer Inc.'s
ballyhooed economy computer, represents a big step toward the
mainstream of personal computing for the company that prides itself
on making computers for an elite minority, industry experts said
recently at the Macworld Expo. (Mahoney, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED.
</P>
