<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9595 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEACH-STUDIES-NYT &LR;      07-10 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEACH-STUDIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN LIFE IS A DAY AT THE BEACH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., N.C., Va., Fla., Hawaii, Mass.)   (bl)  
 By PETER APPLEBOME   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   His full-color business card shows him on the white sands of
Lanakai Beach in Oahu, wearing white shorts and matching knit
shirt, his shadow knifing out into the blue-green waters.
</P>
<P>
   Shimmering above the water in print the color of the sand is the
simple identification ``Dr. Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything about Stephen Leatherman sounds like something from a
Carl Hiassen novel, from his ``Dr. Beach'' moniker to his place of
employment (fictitious-sounding but mushrooming Florida
International University in Miami), to his role as an academic who
regularly turns up in magazines like Conde Nast Traveler or on
shows like ``Regis and Kathie Lee'' rating the world's beaches.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Beach's nice-work-if-you-can-get-it life style seems like an
inspiration, sort of Jimmy Buffett meets Carl Sagan. But rather
than fiction, Leatherman is an example of the way a few media-savvy
academics manage to transform themselves from mere toilers in
arcane academic groves to mini-celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   Leatherman is a respected scientist in the field of
environmental coastal science, with 13 books and 147 academic
papers to his credit. But he does more than write on the details of
littoral drift, inlet dynamics, overwash processes and dune
migration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I became so well-known at the University of Maryland that one
of the vice presidents said, `With you out here, Leatherman, we
don't need other professors for publicity,''' he said of his
previous posting. ``Frankly, it became a problem at my department.
Here I was publishing like crazy, bringing in a million dollars in
research grants, but, boy, were they jealous. They just went
bananas. They tried to put a basket over me, hide my light. They're
glad I left, and I'm glad too, but I can't ask for a better
situation than I have here.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Beach's rise from beach-obsessed youngster to
beach-and-publicity-obsessed professor began in Charlotte, N.C.,
where his father turned most of his backyard into a sandbox and the
young scholar to be spent hours preparing for his life's work by
building elaborate sand castles.
</P>
<P>
   He attended North Carolina State, where he took part in a
work-study program on beach erosion, spending frigid winter months
driving between Raleigh and the Outer Banks. He got his doctorate
at the University of Virginia, then settled into a life at the
University of Maryland that he figured would amount to a lot of
papers with titles like ``Barrier Island Dynamics: Overwash
Processes and Aeolian Transport'' or ``Lamination Sampling
Techniques for Unconsolidated Sediments.''
</P>
<P>
   His life changed in 1989 when a reporter for Conde Nast Traveler
called looking for a list of his favorite beaches. He came up with
10 off the top of his head, which turned to an instant publicity
bonanza when published in the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing if not an astute marketer, Leatherman decided to make
the list an annual event, with each year's winner retired from
competition and the others judged on things like beach width, sand
quality, water color, amount and quality beach development,
frequency of rip currents and presence of seaweed, jellyfish and
mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   The latest Top 10 and all seven of the retired ``National
Winners'' are in Florida and Hawaii. But East Hampton Beach and
Westhampton Beach on New York's Long Island cracked the Top 20 this
year, as did Coast Guard Beach, Mass., the only other East Coast
beach north of North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Released each Memorial Day, the ranking has become the coastal
version of Blackwell's list of the world's worst-dressed women and
turned Dr. Leatherman into enough of a media creature that his
publicity material lists 63 television appearances, from the
``Today'' show to Globo television in Brazil. Last summer he moved
to Florida International, which has grown in its 26 years into a
school with 30,000 students, for which he is director of the
Laboratory of Coastal Research and International Hurricane Center.
</P>
<P>
   He is a critic of much seaside development. But unlike his
fellow high-profile beach expert, Dr. Orrin Pilkey of Duke
University, who is viewed as an unabashedly fierce opponent of
beach development, Leatherman positions himself as an environmental
centrist. He sees a role for beach nourishment programs, rebuilding
eroded beaches with tons of imported sand. But he says the U.S.
Corps of Engineers has turned beach nourishment into a bloated
industry and that the federal government is supporting it by
directing millions of dollars to projects better financed with
local hotel and restaurant taxes.
</P>
<P>
   With water levels rising, beaches eroding and coastal property
potentially at risk in the trillions of dollars, Leatherman can
persuasively argue that his work, as cushy as it may sound, is
important and of the moment as well as fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got 100 cities on barrier islands that are on a
collision course with nature,'' he said. ``You can say those
environments are dynamic and shifting and not very suitable for
development, but what are you going to do? Let Atlantic City or
Miami Beach wash away? It's not realistic. In 1979, when Miami's
beach was wasting away, you were looking at the development of a
waterfront slum. Now the beach is back, and it's paid for itself
100 times over.''
</P>
<P>
   It's rough work, but someone has to do it. His most recent opus
is a slick, colorful guidebook called ``America's Best Beaches.''
It shows him, pencil and checklist in hand, hard at work on the
beach, with a written description above, ``Dr. Beach at work.'' He
said he spends about 20-25 percent of his time on the road,
examining the nation's beaches from the ground or the air. Over the
last 10 years he has been to all 650 of them at one time or
another.
</P>
<P>
   And how does he spend vacation with his wife and children,
Stephen Beach and Sandra?
</P>
<P>
   ``We usually go to the beach,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
