<SLUG> BC-HANDKERCHIEF-CHIC-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANDKERCHIEFS FOR HANDLING THE HEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 12)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID COLMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As anyone who has been in these Yankee parts lately
knows well, the South has no monopoly on stifling heat and
humidity. The question is: Why should Southern gentlemen have a
monopoly on that wonderful summertime accessory, the pocket
handkerchief?
</P>
<P>
   A white linen handkerchief can do more for a man's personal
style and comfort during the summer heat than the lightest-weight
tropical wool suit. It is odd that what was once a simple
utilitarian item has acquired a reputation as a stuffy, antebellum
accessory.
</P>
<P>
   That's a shame, said Mimmo Spano, the custom tailor at Bergdorf
Goodman. ``When you're wearing a suit in the summer, and it's hot,
and you have a little sweat, you take out the handkerchief and mop
your brow with it.''
</P>
<P>
   A pocket handkerchief also lends a note of elegance to a jacket
worn without a tie. Since summer is normally a season of casual
dress, the handkerchief becomes something of a wardrobe hero.
``It's a casual look; that's the idea,'' Spano said.
</P>
<P>
   A handkerchief looks best folded square and placed in the
pocket, or stuffed casually in with the forefinger, the points
sticking out. A multi-pointed wonder folded with the thoroughness
of an origami swan defeats the purpose. ``To me that's too
contrived,'' Spano said. ``It looks good when it looks natural.''
</P>
<P>
   The same principle should be followed when buying handkerchiefs.
White linen without a monogram is the simplest and most versatile.
For more adventurous types, there are linen squares made in pastel
colors. Beyond that, one is entering the territory of the pocket
square, which is made of colored silk and often gaudily patterned.
Pocket squares are a bit of a tease, being too expensive, fragile
and unabsorbent for brow-wiping. ``They are more for show,'' Spano
said. Or at least, more for fall.
</P>
<P>
   At Saks Fifth Avenue, a box of three Irish linen handkerchiefs
is $38. Bergdorf's sells linen handkerchiefs for $25 each. At Polo
Ralph Lauren they are $18.75 each. They can sometimes be found even
more cheaply in your father's dresser.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from linen handkerchiefs, plain white cotton handkerchiefs
are also widely available. And for heat-wave emergencies, there is,
of course, the cotton bandanna, which can be bought from any number
of sidewalk vendors all over the city for about $2, in colors from
the traditional red, white and blue to green, orange and azure. If
one is dressed simply enough _ say, in a blue blazer, white shirt
and khakis _ a bandanna makes a colorful, summery flourish.
</P>
<P>
   But if the heat is still too much, the best retreat is somewhere
with good air-conditioning where a tie is optional.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
