<HEADER>
A9609 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-LMAY11-COX     07-10 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-LMAY11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Survival lessons learned in a land of extremes
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   McCaysville, Ga.--Call it extreme gardening. I knew from the
first pick-clashing-with-rock that gardening in the mountains would
be a whole different experience from what I was used to in Atlanta.
I'm still learning how different.
</P>
<P>
   The hard, red soil that newcomers to Atlanta complain about is a
piece of clay compared to the stony McCaysville hillside that my
young garden calls home. Dig a hole, or rather, hack one out, and
you always get as much rock as dirt. Well, I've hacked out quite a
few in the last several months, and put in a good number of plants,
many brought up from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   I rejoiced at the heavy, frequent downpours in this high rain
forest, as they made watering unnecessary for weeks and weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the ex-Atlanta plants go through a second spring
because of cooler temperatures up here, I figured summer would be
comfortable, that they would continue adapting with ease. After
all, it never broils in the cool, cool mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Ha, ha, as Patsy Cline would sing, ain't that a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   In my open space near the cabin, my new baby garden panted and
fainted as a merciless June bore down on it from sunup to sundown
and the rain forest morphed into desert. Longtime residents shook
their heads and allowed as how this was unusual, and I watered
furiously, watching the liquid get sucked into the ground, leaving
no trace of dampness after a minute or so _ a disappearance swifter
than the beautiful lizards in skins of intriguing colors and
textures.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing what survives is an education. A cutting from the Atlanta
corkscrew willow remains unfazed, while one from an anise fried and
died. Japanese painted ferns take a baking and keep on stepping.
Alas, several tomatoes did not; one plant did fine until the heat
scorched its stem black. Amazingly, one tomato was hanging on, even
as the stem leaned on a nearby stump to die.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, thistle, a natural mountain lover, always
stands tall. As do several volunteers, including a happy-faced
sunflower. The Japanese maples, tough as any tree, teeter on the
edge of brownout but grow more determined by the week. One
coreopsis thrives, one doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, I'm gardening Darwinian, with more sun and less
watering than even cacti could love. But in some ways, all
gardening is experimental. I just want plants to hold on, knowing
help is on the way; some year soon, the new trees _ pines,
hemlocks, magnolia _ will provide some shade.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, what lives will owe a lot to the nights. They're
much cooler than I expected after such hot days, and extremely
dewy. Every daybreak, the garden looks as if it's been watered.
</P>
<P>
   Dew. Mist. Stars bright. What nights: Extreme is their name.
Darker than any nights I've ever known. And so still that lightning
bugs seem to make a sound as they flash big lights that I still
mistake for airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of mistakes, I brought one to the mountains: a
container dogwood that got damaged when I foolishly allowed water
to stand on the soil's surface rain after rain. I unpotted it and
planted it here, hoping the dry, rocky ground would dry it out.
</P>
<P>
   Now, much of it already water-killed, the tree stands under the
broiling sun and wet nights. And I wait to discover if, in this
place of extremes, it will become a supreme miracle _ or a graphic
reminder against making your move too late.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: leemay(at)bellsouth.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
