<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-MODERATOR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Presbyterian aims to reach minorities
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA--As students at Columbia Theological Seminary return to
classes this fall, the seminary's president will be on the road or
in the air as the top representative of the 2.6 million-member
Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.).
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Douglas W. Oldenburg, 63, was elected moderator of the
denomination's General Assembly at its annual meeting last month in
Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   He takes the helm of a denomination that has steadily lost
members over the past quarter-century, but whose losses seem to be
slowing.
</P>
<P>
   Oldenburg has high hopes for a denominational plan to establish
new congregations, especially among African-American, Hispanic,
Asian and other ethnic groups. The assembly heard a report on the
effort, with preliminary projections of starting more than 500
churches by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very strongly that our church has to come to terms with
the increasing ethnic diversity in the United States,'' Oldenburg
said. ``I think that concern is shared by the church leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he also sees a growing enthusiasm for evangelism in the
denomination. ``It used to be when people moved into a community,
almost all of them visited churches,'' he said. ``That's no longer
the case. We have to be much more intentional than in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Oldenburg has a four-point agenda for his year as moderator:
``Lift up'' the denomination and focus on what Presbyterians have
in common; emphasize education; focus on children; and encourage
Presbyterians to examine what they believe about the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   He said he will ask each congregation to get involved in a new
ministry to children _ such as a tutoring program, a shelter, a day
care center or parenting classes _ and urge each church to study
how to interpret scripture.
</P>
<P>
   Many divisive denominational debates over the years have been a
result of different ways of using the Bible, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Oldenburg, known as a theological liberal who grew up in a
conservative family, said he first decided to attend a seminary to
explore scripture in depth.
</P>
<P>
   He said he does not expect Bible study to be ``a panacea that
will solve all our problems, but we need to discuss the issues with
each other.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Oldenburg said, he is doing what he can to
recognize the theological diversity in his denomination. He
appointed the Rev. James Mead of Tacoma, Wash., as his vice
moderator. Mead, more theologically conservative than Oldenburg,
finished second in the balloting for moderator.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
