<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9614 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-SLAVEGRAVE-C     07-10 2105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-SLAVEGRAVE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Long hidden in a tangle of greenery, a slave cemetery speaks to
a church's history _ and its present.
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTEVILLE, Ga.--Eddie Hawkins likes cutting grass and doing
yardwork. So, when he and his wife and five children joined little
Antioch Baptist Church in Fayette County(Ga.) about four years ago,
it seemed natural that Hawkins would keep up the church cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins, 50, had no way of knowing that his volunteer job would
change the church.
</P>
<P>
   Looking up a wooded slope from the neatly laid-out plots of
graves one day, Hawkins noticed what appeared to be a tombstone on
the edge of an overgrown wooded area nearby. With his hedge
clippers and his weed trimmer, he freed the stone of the brambles
and briers that nearly covered it, brushed it off and told the
occupant of the grave below, ``Welcome back.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins had exposed the edge of a divide that runs through the
history of the South, splitting people into owner and property,
slave and free, black and white.
</P>
<P>
   Recently on a sunny summer Saturday, about two dozen members of
Antioch and Fayetteville's New Hope Baptist Church gathered to
continue Hawkins' work. From the vines and bushes and trees, they
have reclaimed more than 100 graves.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Antioch and New Hope congregations are mainly white.
Most of the people buried in the graves are believed to be slaves
and their descendants.
</P>
<P>
   In the cemetery near the church, the mortal remains of revered
church members lie under carefully maintained marble and granite.
``Asleep in Jesus, Blessed Sleep,'' says the stone of Charity
Whitaker, a mother who died at 60. ``Darling, We Miss Thee,'' the
brokenhearted parents of 13-year-old Clifford Watkins Tombs wrote
in 1911. ``A Beloved Wife,'' V.W. Mills put on the grave of his
Viola when she died at 21.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, most of the newly uncovered graves are merely
sunken rectangles in the rich brown dirt with plain flat broken
rocks at each end. Two are mounds carefully covered in seashells. A
handful have engraved stones.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, 150 years after the Southern Baptist Convention was
founded in Augusta, in part to defend the right of its members to
own slaves, the country's largest Protestant denomination issued a
formal apology. ``Whereas, many of our Southern Baptist forebears
defended the `right' to own slaves, and either participated in,
supported or acquiesced in the particularly inhumane nature of
American slavery,'' the resolution says in part, ``be it therefore
resolved, that we ... lament and repudiate historic acts of evil
such as slavery, from which we continue to reap a bitter harvest.
...''
</P>
<P>
   The official statement of Antioch's denomination, passed
overwhelmingly in the air-conditioned hall of the Georgia World
Congress Center, seems remote and institutional from the side of
the graves of the anonymous slaves in the Antioch churchyard.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Elton Johnson, Antioch's pastor, said the church is not
cleaning up the slave graves because of any denominational
position. ``We're doing it for one reason,'' he said, ``we're
righting a wrong.'' Johnson, 64, is a former missionary to Brazil
and college dean who sells home security systems during the week.
He came to metro Atlanta about five years ago after taking a job in
a firm that went bankrupt. Most Sundays, his congregation numbers
in the 20s.
</P>
<P>
   The metaphors are impossible to miss as Johnson speaks about
``clearing away'' and ``letting the light in.'' When he says, ``I
figure if something is being hidden, it should be uncovered,'' he
seems to be talking about the past as much as the graves
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   `All in gospel order'
</P>
<P>
   The Antioch slaves were not always anonymous. They are listed
alongside their owners as founding members of the church. On March
5, 1829, when 19 people ``all in gospel order'' gathered in a log
schoolhouse to form a congregation that would be part of the Flint
River Baptist Association, 14 were recorded with last names _ Gay,
Powell, Crittendon, Pate, Reeves, Whitaker, Howell and Lee. The
other five were listed by first name only, identified as ``servant
of ...''
</P>
<P>
   Ester belonged to a man named William King, who was not on the
church roll. Milley, Paul, Peter and Jack belonged to the Gays, a
clan that traces its American roots to Henry Gay, who first
appeared in then Nansemond County, Va., in 1663. Fayette County
records show that in the mid-19th century, Thomas B. Gay declared
that he held 35 slaves, worth $13,500, and 2,766 acres of land
valued at $14,000.
</P>
<P>
   The congregation gave Brother Davy, a black man who belonged to
Thomas Gay's father, Gilbert, the freedom to be an evangelist to
``his people.'' Brother Davy needed the church's credentials to
pass freely between farms and plantations, avoiding capture by the
patrols that roamed the county looking for escaped slaves. Church
minutes show that the congregation prayed for his work from time to
time in 1830 and 1831.
</P>
<P>
   By 1850, the little band of Baptists was ready to construct a
building. Church records show that it was to be 60 feet by 40 feet,
with a balcony on the west end for ``colored members'' who also
would be allowed to sit on the back row of the lower level. The
pulpit would be on the north side, with the preacher facing south.
</P>
<P>
   The little Antioch congregation added members by letter or
baptism and subtracted them by death or denunciation, black as well
as white, listing their milestones and misdeeds side by side in the
church minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1851, just as the first building was being finished, minutes
of the congregation recorded the deaths of ``our beloved Sister
Sara Stubbs,'' a white woman, and ``Our Sister Mary ... a colored
woman'' who belonged to Gilbert Gay.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, the church heard charges against two members,
one of them John, a ``colored man'' and ``servant'' who took a
second wife after his first wife left him. ``On motion the church
believed there is no disorder in the colored brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Jones, a white member, did not fare as well. According to
the minutes, she was expelled from the church for marrying a man
when her former husband was still alive.
</P>
<P>
   The white families intermarried. Thomas Gay's daughter Lavicy
married John I. Whitaker, the son of Antioch's original clerk,
Simon Whitaker. In the 1850s, the younger Whitaker, who lived
across the road from the church, deeded property to the
congregation for as long as it remains a Baptist church in good
standing. Some current Antioch members believe the property may
have included the graves of some Whitaker family members and their
slaves.
</P>
<P>
   And so the church plugged along until the Civil War. The Flint
River Baptist Association officially expressed approval of
secession in September 1861. At the time, 25 percent of the members
of churches in the association were black.
</P>
<P>
   In historical documents of the church, the first mention of the
war was a reference to the death of Brother Capt. Jesse Mercer
Spratlin, who died in Richmond in November 1861 ``while in the
service of the Confederate States of America.''
</P>
<P>
   While the country warred, church services at Antioch went on.
The church held its annual revival as usual in August 1862,
baptizing 43 people and receiving five by transfer of membership.
Eleven new black members were among them, bringing the church's
total membership to 106 white, 31 ``colored.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1863, the church released its pastor to preach whenever he
could ``to the Confederate soldiers'' and collected $58 to send The
Christian Index, the Georgia Baptist newspaper, to Confederate
troops.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the war, the church held weeknight meetings to pray
``for our country'' _ the Confederate States of America.
</P>
<P>
   The church canceled services in early September 1864, according
to minutes, ``owing to the Yankee army (a portion of it) being in
the neighborhood committing depredations.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, black and white members of Antioch met together. Church
logs show slaves continuing to join the church as late as 1865. But
the divisions were clear. Along with cases against members who used
profanity or failed to come to church, the Antioch congregation
charged three of its black members in 1865 with ``absconding from
their owners.''
</P>
<P>
   After the war, according to records, white members of Antioch
asked the black members whether they wanted to continue as part of
the same church or start their own congregation. The former slaves
opted to start their own church, and were given the use of a
schoolhouse on the Antioch property. Records show that white
deacons preached to them ``until one of their own could take
over.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1892, when the church bought more land, part of it was set
aside for burying ``colored people.''
</P>
<P>
   Antioch continued as a white church, holding annual homecomings,
all-day ``singings'' and ``protracted meetings,'' as their revivals
were called, eating homemade Brunswick stew stirred with a limb in
an old iron pot. They planted cotton on the church grounds to help
support the church, chopped wood at home and hauled it to heat the
building, and swept the churchyard with straw brooms.
</P>
<P>
   There were arguments and splits and changes_ in 1888, a group
led by the Rev. Isaac G. Woolsey left to form Harmony Grove Baptist
Church after deciding it was sinful to sing hymns with the
accompaniment of an organ. The new church, now named Woolsey, is
right up the road from Antioch. And Antioch itself now worships in
a red-brick building constructed in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the church's historical material has been gathered by
Carol Heath, 63, who moved to Fayette County from Florida more than
two decades ago and joined Antioch. She has supplemented official
church minutes with oral histories from older members, some now
dead.
</P>
<P>
   Although her name is still on the church roll, Heath no longer
attends Antioch. Her family and some other longtime members left in
what some characterize as a ``power struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The little church just sort of goes up and down, like most
little old country churches do,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Heath had heard there was a ``colored cemetery'' on the grounds
of Antioch, she said. ``I couldn't believe the church hadn't
cleaned it up. This goes back to prejudice _ blacks do black stuff
and whites do white stuff. Some of the older members thought blacks
should take care of black things.''
</P>
<P>
   Heath said she approves wholeheartedly of the effort to reclaim
all of the cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the doors to God's house should be open to all his
children,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   `A sobering thought'
</P>
<P>
   On the first work day to clear the old cemetery, members of
Antioch and New Hope gathered outside Antioch to hear a few words
from the preacher. Johnson told them a little of the background,
and suggested that before they began work, each find a sunken spot
and kneel to pray, to ask God to forgive the country for the sin of
slavery and forgive the church for its neglect.
</P>
<P>
   Rubye Maxwell, 69, was there. Her 37-year-old son was buried
nearby when he died of a seizure in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about the difference in how my son was buried and
how these people had been buried,'' she said. ``You couldn't help
but wonder about the circumstances _ who it was, how they were
treated, the life they might have led. It's a sobering thought that
they could be buried there and nobody knows who they are.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most of us are starting to feel a burden is being
lifted from us,'' said Emmett Sanders, 72, a retired Ford worker.
Sanders joined Antioch five years ago because he wanted to be part
of a congregation where ``if one of us is out, we are missed.''
</P>
<P>
   As they clean the cemetery, workers are leaving dogwoods and ivy
vines. They have visions of a park with benches and beautiful
blooming trees where people can sit in the shade and reflect on the
graves, each one marked, they plan, by a cross.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a lingering shadow,'' said Johnson, looking out over
workers chopping trees, digging up weeds and feeding tree limbs
into a wood chipper as graves become more apparent. ``God could not
bless this church as long as what was here was being willfully
perpetuated. We cannot back up 100 years and correct the sins of
the past ... but for today and tomorrow, we can say this will not
be the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Hawkins, who started the whole thing, says the progress is
``like a miracle to me. It's almost like these people didn't exist.
It's kind of like getting them reborn.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
