<HEADER>
A9615 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-VOLUNTEER-CO     07-10 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-VOLUNTEER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A doctor, a dean and a volunteer
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Haverty's family built its reputation in the furniture
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Haverty built his on blood.
</P>
<P>
   The American Red Cross recently picked Haverty as its top
volunteer in the United States. The 72-year-old Atlanta native and
resident was awarded the Charles Drew Award, an annual honor named
after the man who initiated the first successful effort to
separate, store and ship plasma.
</P>
<P>
   Haverty, an affable conversationalist with a broad Georgia
twang, said he was shocked by the honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had nominated someone else,'' he said. ``I had no idea I was
going to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Haverty was picked for his role as a Red Cross advocate in the
medical community. A retired doctor, Haverty has worked with the
Red Cross for 28 years.
</P>
<P>
   When AIDS became a national concern, Haverty used his medical
background to help develop a protocol that ensures the safety of
blood products provided by the Red Cross. ``Blood is very important
and it's not easy to get,'' Haverty said. ``It's absolutely
essential for people's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Haverty comes from a family of achievers.
</P>
<P>
   His grandfather, James Haverty, started Haverty Furniture Cos.
Inc., now one of the leading furniture retailers in the South. His
great-grandfather built railroads. He fled Ireland during the
potato famine and became a railroad laborer.
</P>
<P>
   Haverty, married with a son and two daughters, said his family
taught him that service comes with success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Service is the price you pay for the space you occupy,''
Haverty said. ``If I am going to be as fortunate as I am, I ought
to make the lives of others easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Haverty became involved in the Red Cross after leaving his
practice as a pediatrician in 1968. He became the founding dean of
the College of Health and Human Sciences at Georgia State
University, and joined the American Red Cross because he thought
his students should learn about health services firsthand and would
benefit if he had an official relationship with the agency.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, Haverty learned how much he enjoyed working with
the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good bunch of people,'' Haverty said. ``It's big and it
offers almost anything anyone would want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues invariably describe Haverty as a Southern gentleman
who gets along with people. The nomination letter for the Drew
Award noted that Haverty ``has a knack for listening and then
articulating problems in such a fashion that the solutions proposed
make listeners think, `Of course, why didn't I think of that?'''
</P>
<P>
   Haverty hesitates when asked to talk about himself. ``It's
wonderful when someone tells me how great I am,'' he said. ``It's
not great for me to tell someone how great I am. I don't think it's
proper to toot your horn.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry. The Red Cross will handle his ``tooting'' in the
future. After all, he's one of the organization's top volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
