<HEADER>
A9652 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKSON-MUSIC-REVIEW-     07-10 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-MUSIC-REVIEW-ART-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JANET JACKSON: AT THE MERCY OF LUST, YET IN TOTAL CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
(lb) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's a mistake to underestimate Janet Jackson.
True, she's not the strongest singer around, or the most original
songwriter; she works slowly, with four-year gaps between albums
and tours, and keeps quiet between projects. Yet long after the
other masters of the 1980s pop spectacle have withdrawn _ Madonna
to motherhood, Michael Jackson to fatherhood _ Ms. Jackson has not
just persevered but thrived.
</P>
<P>
   Her current U.S. tour, built around her 1997 album, ``The Velvet
Rope'' (Virgin), began on Thursday night at the MCI Center, and
with her performance, she made clear that she and her collaborators
since the mid-1980s, Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis, have been one of
the most consistent songwriting teams in pop.
</P>
<P>
   Onstage, Ms. Jackson also found ways to keep the arena
startling. Between cooing come-ons and aerobic dance routines, she
faced down trauma and healed herself.
</P>
<P>
   The current tour, which arrives in New York's Madison Square
Garden on Oct. 10 and 11 (when it will be televised live by HBO),
reflects an era in which music video, Las Vegas revues and Broadway
have converged.
</P>
<P>
   Every moment is choreographed for Ms. Jackson, nine dancers and
her band. In the more athletic songs, she appears to be
lip-synching, although she does sing live in ballads and parts of
the uptempo songs.
</P>
<P>
   Like most multimillion-selling songwriters, Ms. Jackson has
something for nearly every pop radio format, from lush ballads to
funk to hard-rock riffing to electronic dance music to hip-hop.
Each kind of beat arrives with its own costume. While most of the
show is outfitted in stark black and white, one stretch of cheerful
songs bursts into color, with harlequin costumes like a Disney
production of Cirque de Soleil.
</P>
<P>
   Pop spectacles are about razzle-dazzle, the sight and sound of
someone going all out to entertain. They're about reassurance, too,
invariably winding up with a big optimistic song, preferably a
communal sing-along. But spectacles are also about power: the
ability to deploy large forces, onstage and backstage, to realize a
star's whims.
</P>
<P>
   Onstage, Ms. Jackson presents herself as the leader of a posse,
sometimes wearing quasi-military uniforms. While most of her songs
are about what goes on between lovers in private, she travels with
reinforcements.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Rope Burn,'' a song about bondage fantasies that begins
``Tie me up, tie me down,'' Ms. Jackson brought a man up from the
audience and sat him in a chair while she and two female dancers
caressed him and teased him. Although Ms. Jackson sang about
submission as she writhed against a pole, she definitely had the
upper hand. In other songs, the male dancers ended up as
supplicants before attractive women.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with ``Control'' in 1986, Ms. Jackson's songs have
wrestled with the question of who's in charge and whether love also
means surrender. With her small, sweet voice, she often portrays
herself as a woman at the mercy of lust, finding satisfaction by
fulfilling male desires. But in another cluster of her songs, she
refuses to be subservient.
</P>
<P>
   While the music often follows the lead of Michael Jackson,
Prince and Diana Ross, Ms. Jackson and her collaborators enhance
every borrowed idea, so that even when the sources are
recognizable, the songs are convincing. They can be sultry and
lovelorn; they can be fiercely cathartic.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One song, ``What About,'' starts out as a marriage proposal,
with gentle acoustic guitar, but suddenly gives way to hard-rock
guitar and furious accusations of abuse. Ms. Jackson staged it
unsparingly, with dancers acting out assault and rape; the
stylization didn't soften the violent emotions.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution came with ``Rhythm Nation,'' a call for unity and
good intentions, and ``Special,'' an anthem that declares, ``We
have to deal with our past.'' For an encore, she brought on Colin
Powell _ the tour is contributing to America's Promise, his
organization to promote mentors for children _ and finished with
``Together Again,'' an elegy disguised as an arm-waving, feel-good
song. She honored the pop conventions, but she had made them follow
her commands.
</P>
<P>
   Usher was torn between spectacle and song as he opened the show.
He can draw squeals simply by taking off his shirt, and he did,
repeatedly. He also moonwalked and went through nearly half a dozen
costume changes and dance routines before he showed up in white
pajamas and began crooning, with his best Stevie Wonder melismas,
about undying love, punctuated by hip twitches and slow push-ups.
The squeals only redoubled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
