<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEENS-DRINKING-CEXP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEENAGERS AND ALCOHOL: A SADD SITUATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDITORS: Children's Express is an independent, non-profit news
service reported by children whose tape-recorded interviews,
roundtables and commentary are edited by teens and adults. The
features are transmitted by The New York Times Service and are
available to New York Times News Service clients at no extra
charge.) 
(JT) 
 By Children's Express/Indianapolis Bureau. Editor: Jacob Pactor,
15. Reporter: Laura Bohnert, 13   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whether it be drinking late with friends or attending the
funeral of a classmate killed by a drunken driver, alcohol plays a
big role in the lives of teenagers. And although most teens know
the dangers of drinking and then driving, many continue to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers 21-24 years old had the highest intoxication rate for
fatal crashes in 1996, according to the National Highway Traffic
Safety Administration.
</P>
<P>
   About 4.4 million Americans between 12-20 were binge drinkers,
meaning they consume five or more drinks in a row on a single
occasion, according to the National Institute on Drug Abuse's 1996
National Household Survey on Drug Abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a totally preventable problem where people, once they
have consumed beverages that makes them unable to function
properly, decide to perform dangerous activities,'' said Meggan(cq)
Ways, a senior at Indianapolis' Brebeuf Jesuit Preparatory School
and president of the school's Students Against Drunk Driving (SADD)
chapter. The national organization recently changed its name to
Students Against Destructive Decisions to encompass more of the
problems facing teens.
</P>
<P>
   A team from the Indianapolis bureau of Children's Express spoke
with two others seniors, from Park Tudor High School in
Indianapolis, to ascertain what young people are doing in the
battle against drunken driving.
</P>
<P>
   Although the names are different, chapters at Brebeuf and Park
Tudor are anti-substance abuse organizations that participate in
events such as ``Prom Promise,'' in which teens are asked to take a
vow during prom weekend not to drink or use drugs, and ``Red Ribbon
Week,'' a national anti-drug week.
</P>
<P>
   SADD also promotes a ``Contract for Life,'' in which youth and
parents agree to contact each other if one has been drinking and
cannot responsibly drive home.
</P>
<P>
   Why do teens drink?
</P>
<P>
   Nan Ruby: To have fun. I mean, that's what everybody thinks it
is.
</P>
<P>
   Meggan: If you're in a situation where everybody else is
drinking, it's hard to say, ``Oh no, I'll just have a soda.''
</P>
<P>
   Katy Hebert: It's rebellious. It's something that your parents
wouldn't approve of, and sometimes teenagers like stuff that their
parents don't approve of.
</P>
<P>
   Meggan: If you see someone in a movie get into a car and drive
home drunk and everything is fine, it's going to send an impression
that this is something good and fun to do.
</P>
<P>
   Katy: Drinking isn't a major problem at Park Tudor, because more
people are aware of the other options besides drinking.
</P>
<P>
   Nan: It's not that big of a problem, because kids are usually
spending the night or parents take keys away (when they suspect
there might be drinking).
</P>
<P>
   Meggan: I hear about people drinking and driving, but what I her
is through gossip. People don't seem to take this problem
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Nan: I've taken the keys away from friends before and told them
that they can't drive because I thought that they were too drunk to
drive.
</P>
<P>
   They're obviously not caring for other people, so why should I
be caring for them? Why should I comfort them? I just say, `You're
stupid. Don't do it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Katy: Your friend's life is more important than making it home
by your curfew or getting in trouble for leaving the party.
</P>
<P>
   Meggan: If it's a difference between saving someone's life and
saving his or her feelings, you obviously have to go for the life.
</P>
<P>
   The Contract for Life
</P>
<P>
   Katy: It's like a trust contract, that your parents put enough
trust in you to give you the freedom to go out and have fun, but
yet they expect you to be safe and come home safely.
</P>
<P>
   I think it's good that it also says for the parent to agree to
come home safe and sober. If the parent's in danger, they should
have to do exactly what the child has to do. It's not hypocritical.
</P>
<P>
   Meggan: I think one main reason that kids drive themselves when
they're drunk is because they're afraid of what their parents will
say if they call them.
</P>
<P>
   Nan: I think parents should have a talk with their kid when
he/she gets the license and say, ``Be responsible. If you're going
to be in this situation, call me and I will understand. You won't
get in trouble at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Katy: Sometimes it's hard to remember that your parents love
you. If you come home drunk, they will be angry with you, but it is
so much more important for a parent to have their child be safe.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
