<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9674 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GIRLPOWER-CEXP-NYT &LR;      07-10 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIRLPOWER-CEXP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT GIRL POWER REALLY MEANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDITORS: Children's Express is an independent, non-profit news
service reported by children whose tape-recorded interviews,
roundtables and commentary are edited by teens and adults. The
features are transmitted by The New York Times Service and are
available to New York Times News Service clients at no extra
charge.) 
 (JT)  
 By Children's Express/Washington, DC Bureau. Editor: Jennifer
McVeigh, 16. Reporters: Kenyan Churchwell, 13; Alana Mayo, 10;
Lexie Kruvaent, 12 and Brittany Martin, 13    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Ms. Foundation talks about girls changing the world,
they don't even call it girl power. They talk about powerful girls.
``At the Ms. Foundation for Women, we'd be talking about the power
that girls feel, particularly before adolescence,'' said Marie
Wilson, president of the foundation. ``The power that they see in
their mothers, a power that girls naturally have and adults can
help sustain.''
</P>
<P>
   Her definition of `girl power' just doesn't fit with the Spice
Girls and Madonna, who exert their sexuality. It's about using your
mind as well as your body in positive ways. Girl power is the power
that girls possess to change the world.
</P>
<P>
   She said that there are other definitions of girl power, like
the Spice Girls use, but it's not real power. It's very different
and it's not the kind most girls need to hear about.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a kind of wonderful uninhibited thing, but it's also
exposing girls to risk in ways that are not always responsible,
acting as if the world is already changed for girls so that you can
flaunt certain things that you really can't right now. Sex is
power, but it's not real.
</P>
<P>
   ``Power isn't money. It's isn't control. It's influence.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said real girl power comes from girls' minds and what
they can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we think of the fact that girls are now looked at as being
more powerful in the world and looked at more for their potential
than for their victimhood,'' she said, ``I think it's (the
popularity of the phrase a) great success. As long as we talk about
girl power in the best sense, it has mothers like (professor) Carol
Gilligan at Harvard and Donna Shalala who's the secretary (of
Health and Human Services) and Oprah Winfrey.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I object to is using it in a product that is really
exploitative of girls. I do believe that advertising and marketing
are exploiting the girls' market right now. If companies are gonna
use girl power to sell products that are kind of neutral, like
T-shirts, I'd rather it be 'girl power' than 'girl sadness.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson mentioned Nike's `If you let me play' campaign, however,
as an example of `exploitation for good' because there are kids
getting more attention.
</P>
<P>
   But I don't always like Nike's business practices when they
exploit workers,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Girl power can also mean girls who are using their power as
consumers and to control the media, said Wilson. Go to companies
and say, ``I don't like the way you have just white women. You want
girls like me when you advertise.'' She mentioned new magazines
that girls are writing themselves to express their viewpoints.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's changed some things. I think what's important is the new
publications, like Teen Voices and New Moon. Some of the
publications are starting to have influence on magazines like
Seventeen,'' said Wilson. ``Seventeen had a feature not too long
ago, real girls model real clothes, that to me is a more important
use of girl power.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we can't sit here and be hypocritical and act as if girls
aren't interested in reading about boys, clothes or whatever.
Seventeen and these other magazines wouldn't be in business if
girls weren't interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson repeated that girl power is about influence in lots of
ways. It's also about freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about, can a boy be a nurse and a girl be a doctor? Can
you control your life? Can you have the amount of children you can
support? Do you have the power to influence the world around you?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
