<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9677 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FARAH-VENATOR-PROFILE     07-10 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARAH-VENATOR-PROFILE-$ADV12-ART-1,000(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETAILING WIZ STRUGGLES FOR RESPECT WITH VENATOR GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 12)  
(ART ADV: A graphic and a photo are being sent to NYT
graphics/photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204, 1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roger Farah spends 40 minutes with a guest at lunch before he
even mentions the company he runs, which happens to be one of the
country's oldest retailers. He talks with profound affection about
his children. He comments about his salad. He spins cheerful yarns
about life in Atlanta, where he once lived.
</P>
<P>
   All of this good nature and thoughtful banter are a bit
perplexing, because Farah has the right to be an angry man.
</P>
<P>
   When Farah became chief executive of Woolworth Corp. in 1994,
the company was nearly insolvent. Its inventory systems were so
antiquated that Halloween candy sat melting in a storeroom in the
middle of July. Its stores were not equipped to tally daily sales,
unheard of in modern retailing. Its namesake dime stores were
bleeding cash, as were many of its other divisions.
</P>
<P>
   He was certainly aware of some of this when he signed on. But
the sheer breadth of what needed fixing was not exactly what he had
bargained for.
</P>
<P>
   In a few short years, however, he has reduced the company's
overall debt to $440 million, from $1.2 billion; winnowed its 41
widely disparate divisions down to 21 store formats by unloading
most of the underperforming mall specialty stores; sold its elegant
headquarters building in Manhattan, and, in perhaps his most
dramatic move, closed its fabled dime stores.
</P>
<P>
   Just into his fourth year, he has changed not only the company's
name, to Venator Group, but also its century-old strategy; for all
intents and purposes, Farah is now running a sporting goods holding
company.
</P>
<P>
   Its crown jewels _ Foot Locker, Lady Foot Locker and Kid's Foot
Locker _ are undergoing badly needed renovations. Three smallish
acquisitions _ a pair of sporting goods chains and an athletic
goods catalog _ underscore the new direction. And a proposed big
addition _ the 206-store Sports Authority chain _ is in his sights.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all that, the new Woolworth _ er, Venator _ cannot
command the recognition that would seem appropriate for one of the
largest restructuring attempts in recent corporate history. And
Farah, 45, widely recognized as one of the most savvy and
accomplished retailers in the country for his work at Saks Fifth
Avenue, Neiman Marcus and Federated Department Stores, is now
struggling for a measure of respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, Farah has done things that badly needed to be done,''
said John Horan, publisher of Sporting Goods Intelligence, a trade
publication that closely follows Venator. ``But the jury is still
out. He hasn't shown results to date.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, insult has followed injury with depressing regularity
lately.
</P>
<P>
   Venator's stock has fallen 14 percent so far this year, even as
the Standard &AMP; Poor's retail index soared nearly 55 percent. Last
year, the stock was dropped as a component of the Dow Jones
industrial average, and Fidelity Investments has cast off a large
stake, according to the most recent filings. And despite its $6.6
billion in annual revenues, Venator is covered regularly by just a
handful of analysts, two of whom have been relentless in issuing
unusually negative reports.
</P>
<P>
   There is more.
</P>
<P>
   A large shareholder, Greenway Partners, has taken to regularly
complaining that Farah is not moving fast enough, demanding that he
unload more divisions. The proposed acquisition of the Sports
Authority was roundly panned by investors who responded with a
mini-selloff. Even worse, an upstart sporting goods company in
Denver, Gart Sports Co., made its own offer for Sports Authority, a
surprise that has Farah's investment bankers at Morgan Stanley
scrambling for a response.
</P>
<P>
   If all of this sets Farah's hair on fire (an expression he is
fond of using), there is no public face for his rage. ``I don't
think the Street understood how broken this company was, and I
didn't think it was my job to report that to them,'' he said in an
interview in his office in the Woolworth Building, where Venator is
still based. ``The progress here has been dramatically
undervalued.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Farah's challenge remains daunting. He is pushing ahead with
a company focused on athletic wear when that business, largely
because of depressed sales of sneakers, is in the dumps. His key
supplier, Nike, has yet to show signs of improving its own battered
fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   He is remodeling, expanding and adding fresh goods to his
2,848-store Foot Locker division, but is still playing catch-up
with competitors like Finish Line and Just for Feet.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Venator's sales continue to sag, and its profit margins
remain weak. On Tuesday, the company announced that it expected to
lose 5 cents to 10 cents a share for the quarter ending Aug. 1, and
its stock hit a 52-week closing low, at $18.25. It continued to
slip throughout the week, closing at a new 52-week low of $17.4375
on Friday. That wasn't just bad news for investors; it knocked
roughly 18 percent off the value of the company's $570 million
offer for Sports Authority.
</P>
<P>
   All of which means Farah is in danger of getting some permanent
bruises unless profits resume growing at Venator, which is Latin
for ``hunter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have played Woolworth my whole 16-year career,'' said
Michael Petersen, a portfolio manager with Security Distributors, a
mutual fund family based in Topeka, Kan. He recently sold his
fund's Venator shares in the face of weakened earnings and margins,
as well as queasiness about the company's commitment to sporting
goods. ``I am a big believer that the numbers tell me everything I
need to know about management,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   These hard knocks present a big change for Farah, who has been
used to much more glamour _ and success _ in business. Starting out
at Saks, he went on to executive positions at Neiman Marcus and
Federated, where he became, at 35, the youngest president ever of
Rich's, a Southern department store chain.
</P>
<P>
   Farah's department store career ended in 1993, when Macy's tried
to lure him away from Federated's merchandise services unit, where
he was chief executive. But Allen Questrom, then Federated's chief
executive, stopped that cold, saying it would violate Farah's
contract. Farah was served legal papers as he boarded a ferry to
Nantucket and, as a result, ended up spending only a few months as
Macy's president.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   After all that, few in the industry expected him to roll up his
sleeves and dig into Woolworth, a sclerotic retailer whose most
famous unit was a dusty purveyor of hard candy and Dippity-Do.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Farah came in, people were very surprised,'' said Kirk
Palmer, who runs an executive search firm in New York. ``Woolworth
was one of those companies that none of us in the search industry
ever looked at because, frankly, they were viewed as being really
mediocre managers and retailers. But here came this Wunderkind that
everyone loved, and they wondered what in God's name was he doing
going over to Woolworth.''
</P>
<P>
   Farah may be wondering the same thing, but he says he is
optimistic. ``I thought it was a challenge to be taken,'' he said.
``I thought there was value to be created.''
</P>
<P>
   In that spirit, comparisons to Arthur Martinez are inevitable.
Martinez left Saks Fifth Avenue as chief executive to try a
turnaround at the beleaguered, unglamorous Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. in
1992. He, too, shut down a vaunted but ultimately unprofitable
business, the Sears catalog.
</P>
<P>
   But even Martinez, who is otherwise impressed with Farah, was
surprised when Woolworth stopped being Woolworth to become an
athletic goods business. ``We had a $4 billion catalog business and
a $16 billion store business,'' he said. ``It was central to the
history of the company but smaller to the economic picture. The
Woolworth dime stores may have been too far gone, but those
locations were magic. I think they have punched out the hole of the
doughnut by closing them.''
</P>
<P>
   Farah acknowledges that he was not quite ready for how hard it
would be to turn around Venator's fortunes. ``In my wildest dreams,
I was not prepared to hear that I could not get daily sales''
reports, he said. ``I have made more tough decisions in the last
three years than in my entire career.''
</P>
<P>
   Many shoppers probably have no idea of Venator's components.
Besides its Foot Locker division, the company owns Champs, a chain
of large athletic shops, and Colorado, which sells outdoor gear
like Patagonia jackets.
</P>
<P>
   The company also runs the giant Kinney footwear chain and the
smaller Footquarter. Then there are 860 stores in the Northern
Reflections group _ mall stores that sell a casual look that favors
items like lavender T-shirts with vine prints and cotton walking
shorts. There are two other mall chains as well: Afterthoughts,
which sells accessories for teen-agers, and San Francisco Music Box
Co. Venator does 37 percent of its business overseas, an unusually
high level for an American retailer.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the problem? In a word: sneakers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that Woolworth was run like a 19th century
family business until Farah came on board, sneakers had
traditionally been good to the company. For years, Foot Locker had
few worries because of its paramount position at the mall,
dominating the market with the latest Nike products.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last two years, the appetite for Nike basketball
shoes has waned considerably. In their stead have come other
sneaker brands and products, including New Balance, skateboard
shoes and hiking boots, none of which Foot Locker was quick to get
in stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``During 1996, there was unprecedented momentum in the footwear
business because Nike could do no wrong,'' said Faye Landes, a
retail analyst at Salomon Smith Barney. ``But what was not really
apparent then was that other concepts coming along would catch on.
And in a mature business, there are competitors who are doing
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Those competitors began opening stores across the mall from Foot
Locker shops _ and typically in bigger spaces. Finish Line, for
example, has 5,400-square-foot stores, compared with a
3,000-square-foot average for Foot Locker.
</P>
<P>
   A larger store means two things: more room for suppliers other
than Nike, and shelf space for marked-down goods, which Foot Locker
was also short on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Close-outs are important to moms who are buying shoes for
growing kids,'' said Horan, the newsletter publisher.
</P>
<P>
   There are other problems. For years, Woolworth let Foot Locker
more or less run itself and invested little in the upkeep of the
stores, using its cash flow to support other chains.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the tricky issue of the supplier's upper hand. In
90 percent of retailing, the merchants call the shots. They choose
what and how much to buy and put pressure on vendors to pay for
advertising, give special deals for large purchases and buy back
unsold merchandise. The sporting goods business is an exception.
For years, Nike pushed the merchants around, telling them how much
merchandise they would receive and when they would get it, often
even commanding how it would be displayed.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Venator's plan to buy Sports Authority is intended
to change that calculus because it would help consolidate the
fragmented sector. Venator already owns 16 percent of the sporting
goods business in the United States. Add Sports Authority _ the
combined company's sales would be about $5 billion _ and it would
have a bigger opportunity to dictate terms to suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   ``As it stands now,'' Horan said, ``Nike can live without Foot
Locker far more than Foot Locker can live without Nike.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of how difficult the business is, at least a
half-dozen sporting goods merchants have been shuttered or taken
over by larger companies in the last two years, and many more may
be on that path.
</P>
<P>
   Farah sees trends in athletic shoes as cyclical and says sales
can turn upward on a dime with a few hot new products.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business we had to build around was athletic,'' Farah
said. ``Would I have preferred to be in an up cycle when we were
trying to grow our business? Absolutely. We will primarily rise and
fall on that. But on the flip side, we think it is an opportunity
to consolidate the business.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Farah is trying hard to focus on areas of the
business that are not worn on the feet. So far, 130 Woolworth
locations are scheduled for conversion to Champs or Foot Locker,
and the new Foot Lockers have the bells and whistles expected of a
modern sneaker emporium. They are larger and brighter, with giant
displays and huge video screens to lure customers. The new Kid's
Foot Locker stores, including one in Nyack, N.Y., look like giant
cartoonlands, with huge skateboards jetting from the ceilings.
</P>
<P>
   But Farah's background is in apparel, and that is what he is
trying to emphasize. Foot Locker has mostly dabbled in the licensed
apparel business _ team jerseys and the like _ but will add
private-label lines to its mix.
</P>
<P>
   All these changes have not been easy. Large stores with
complicated fixtures and features take much time and money to
build, and they have opened more slowly than the company had hoped.
Venator wanted to have well over 100 big stores by now in the Foot
Locker family; there are just a dozen so far. And some company
executives are upset that footwear may take a back seat to clothes.
</P>
<P>
   So can Farah make this company turn the corner? His fans say
that if anyone can, he's the one.
</P>
<P>
   Most people who know Roger Farah agree on two things: His
merchandising smarts and the almost obsessive way he studies a
problem to find a solution. Call up some of the most respected
names in the business, the kind of people who do not generally
comment publicly about their peers, and be prepared to hear them
bubble over about Farah.
</P>
<P>
   James Zimmerman, chief executive of Federated, calls him ``the
complete deal.'' Myron Ullman III, the no-nonsense chairman of DFS
Group, said that when he was chief executive of Macy's, Farah was
the only man he wanted to hire. Matthew Serra, the chief executive
of Stern's, who oversaw Farah at Saks, still recalls fondly how the
younger man had the foresight to sell knock-offs of Gucci loafers
in 1977, when few stores were willing to try that approach. Farah's
loafers, which sold at half the price of the real thing, flew off
the shelves.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a brilliant 22-year-old,'' Serra said. ``He had
tremendous capacity to assimilate knowledge and information. I
couldn't promote him fast enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Most great merchants are known for their intuitive skills, not
their financial acumen. Farah is said to have both, poring over the
smallest details until he feels he understands a business situation
completely.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Shull, who worked with Farah at Federated and is now
president of Barneys New York, remembered him taking a special trip
to Asia to personally oversee some factories. His subordinates at
Venator say he will tinker with store displays until he thinks they
are right.
</P>
<P>
   But there are downsides to all of this micro-managing. ``Roger
loves to ask questions, to probe, to get into people's heads,''
said a former Venator executive, speaking on condition of
anonymity. ``But then it takes a long time to get answers.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to communicating with those merchants and managing
and motivating them, Farah employs some special touches.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Beauchamp, a buyer at Saks under Farah early in her
career, recalled their first meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been looking at Saks as being very traditional, very
classic,'' she said. ``So Roger calls and asks me to meet him on
the main floor. He walked me through Saint Laurent, Escada, Chanel
and everything out there, giving me an awareness of who the Saks
customer was, instead of asking me, `Where are you going with all
this traditional cashmere?' Here he was showing me feathered
sweaters and sequined bags. It was a nice introduction to Roger's
style.''
</P>
<P>
   There is tougher part to that style, she added. ``Roger ruled
with an iron fist in a velvet glove,'' added Ms. Beauchamp, until
recently the president of men's wear at Donna Karan International.
``Some people can tell you to go to hell, and you'll enjoy the
trip. Roger had that ability.''
</P>
<P>
   But that ability, and all the others he may possess, will add up
to little if sneaker sales don't turn around. ``At the end of the
day,'' said Ms. Landes, the analyst, ``it comes down to the whims
of a 14-year-old boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Farah obviously has a personal interest in the company's
performance. In addition to his $1.5 million in base pay last year
and $780,000 bonus, he received 800,000 stock options and 200,000
shares in restricted stock.
</P>
<P>
   But if Farah is worried, there are no outward signs. After an
interview, he went to meet the car that would take him to the
airport. He was on his way to Oregon to meet with Nike executives.
</P>
<P>
   He looked over the memo his office had given him for the trip:
Portland, often rainy, would be sunny for his visit. With that
news, he went smiling down the hall _ he might even have been
whistling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
