<SLUG> BC-POP-CDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POP CDS: MATCHING THE MUSIC TO THE BEACH 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ANN POWERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In summer, myriad pop-culture offerings surface to suit the free
and overheated mood. There are literary page turners for beach
reading and blockbusters augmenting the allure of movie-house air
conditioning. Pop's hot-weather genres include surf music and Miami
bass, and the hit songs that seem to have been born inside car
radios.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely, though, are whole albums singled out for the season. The
qualities that make CDs ideal for summer lazing _ an easygoing mood
that can drift into hothouse torpor, a focus that fades in and out
like a daydream _ aren't usually applauded by critics, who prefer a
certain clarity. That leaves listeners to find their favorites on
their own.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few suggestions, keyed to particular summer scenes.
Consider these albums beach reading for the ears.
</P>
<P>
   For a New York City Beach
</P>
<P>
   Hipsters heading to Coney Island will want to equip themselves
with the Beastie Boys' ``Hello Nasty'' (Grand Royal/Capitol), the
latest from this eminent trio of cool hunters. Mixing old-school
hip-hop bragfests with nearly New Age meditations about living
mindfully in a busy world, ``Hello Nasty'' ranges widely enough to
please everybody on the boardwalk.
</P>
<P>
   The Buddhist-inspired philosophizing is paired with vintage
Europop, ambient electronics and sweet, wide-eyed neo-psychedelia
like that of the Beasties' pal, Sean Lennon. The beat-heavy rants,
accelerated by the frenetic record-scratcher DJ Mixmaster Mike,
feature enough dazzling wordplay to make for many surfside games of
Guess the Reference.
</P>
<P>
   Attentive listeners will notice an unresolved split between the
group's attempts at egoless expression and the consummately
ego-driven boasts essential to its raps. But barbecuing party
people will just enjoy the flow.
</P>
<P>
   For a Tar Beach
</P>
<P>
   The third album from the English collective Massive Attack,
``Mezzanine'' (Virgin Records America), raises the kind of humidity
that can drive apartment dwellers to sleep on the roof. Its songs
hang together like a soundtrack for a midnight movie about one such
night. As their creeping, erotic dub rhythms build and their
synthesized chords swoon, each seems to carry another insomniac
upward, toward the smoggy sky.
</P>
<P>
   As always, guest vocalists flesh out the characters occupying
Massive Attack's mise en scene. Elizabeth Fraser of the Cocteau
Twins is an angel (or a ghost) floating through the heavy mix. The
reggae legend Horace Andy plays Ms. Fraser's mystical counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Del Naja and Grant Marshall rap in a sneaky, sing-song
style that tips them as the heavies. Sara Jay makes a cameo as a
mysterious seductress. ``Mezzanine'' sets up these characters'
fateful encounters; it's up to the listener to travel up its steps
and fill in the details of the plot.
</P>
<P>
   For a Nude Beach
</P>
<P>
   Like those brave enough to take it all off near the sea, the
second album by the rhythm-and-blues love man Maxwell, ``Embrya''
(Columbia), wears its sensuality proudly. Its rhythms coalesce into
a mellow groove that rarely shifts, causing each song to crash into
the next in a great oceanic wash.
</P>
<P>
   A little bit jazzy, a little bit Caribbean and a little bit
1970s soul, the sound is mostly soothing, the work of an expert
seducer who knows it never pays to push. It's the aural equivalent
of lotion rubbed on one's back by someone interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell, the man behind the massage, never lets his croon get
too urgent as he mouths coy phrases like ``Maybe you're more than
just a one-night lady,'' and cosmic ones like ``You are me and we
are you.'' It's all very relaxing, but like so many idealized
bodies, the one Maxwell presents doesn't have a lot going on
inside. That doesn't mean he's not fun to spend an afternoon
sharing a towel with.
</P>
<P>
   For a Rocky Maine Beach
</P>
<P>
   Dana and Karen Kletter included a song about the seaside on
``Dear Enemy'' (Rykodisc), their debut album, and undoubtedly they
were imagining one of their native Southern beaches. But this
delicate collection just as easily evokes a stony coast, where
surprises lurk in the tide pools. The sisters are twins, and their
vocals twine together in that eerie way open only to siblings as
they share intimate, sometimes surreal tales of domesticity and
solitude.
</P>
<P>
   Alternating homespun piano parts, accompanied by friends from
the underground rock scenes around Richmond, Va., the Kletters hit
upon a folkwise sound that would be traditional if it weren't so
quietly quirky.
</P>
<P>
   Their unusual style prompted Joe Boyd, the producer who worked
with the legendary folk rocker Nick Drake, to come out of
retirement and produce ``Dear Enemy.'' Meticulous and strange, with
flashes of mordant humor, it is a rustic journey for the mind.
</P>
<P>
   For a Lakefront Beach
</P>
<P>
   Straying from the minimalist country of the Scud Mountain Boys,
that group's singer and guitarist, Joe Pernice, enlisted his
brother, the guitarist Bob, and several friends for a lush journey
into orchestral pop with the Pernice Brothers' ``Overcome by
Happiness'' (Sub Pop).
</P>
<P>
   Reminiscent of Big Star's classic third album, ``Overcome'' taps
an all-American yearning that recalls neon-lighted fairgrounds and
lovers' cars parked at the edge of a Great Lake.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the beauty, each song is haunted by bitterness, but its
fatalism is characteristic, too, of a land _ and a season _ in
which dreams can be won or dashed at a sideshow roulette wheel. Joe
Pernice exhibits a tendency to say one thing and sound like its
opposite, which also suits summer, when life's hard edges seem to
melt like the sad verses of his songs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
