<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING TRACK OF FILES ON DISK 
</HEADLINE>
   By LONNIE BROWN   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time was when a home computer user had a few floppy disks with
several files on them. To find something, users stuck a disk in the
drive, looked through the directory, and if the file wasn't there,
repeated the process with another disk.
</P>
<P>
   Times change. Today's floppy disks hold several times the files
that the old five-and-a-quarter-inch disks did. Moreover,
removable, high-density drives can hold the same amount of
information contained on 70 or more floppy disks.
</P>
<P>
   Where did that ``Letter to Auntie Pearl'' file go?
</P>
<P>
   DiskCataloger keeps track of such things. The program (Windows
95; about $40) from Sheridan Software Systems Inc. sets up a
DiskDataloger folder under Windows' Explorer. There, it stores
information on all the disks inserted into the computer (provided
the user clicks on a ``register the disk'' button) whether the disk
is a floppy or one of the newer high-capacity Zip, Jaz, Sparq or
other name-brand removable disks.
</P>
<P>
   It also indexes both commercial CD-ROMs and rewritable CDs.
Indexing a commercial CD, on which the files cannot be changed, may
not seem helpful, but it comes in handy when looking for a piece of
clip art, sound or other small item frequently found on CDs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now users do not have to constantly print hard-to-use indexes
of each disk or endlessly play disk/CD shuffle to see the contents
of each disk or CD,'' said Sheridan President Bob Wolf.
</P>
<P>
   Disks are quickly cataloged by the program. After that process
is finished, the user gives the disk a name or number, then places
the same name or number on the disk so it can be retrieved when
needed by the program.
</P>
<P>
   Users can search for files by using wild cards (typing ``day''
with bring up a list of all files ending in ``day,'' for instance).
It can also be used to find files modified between two dates.
</P>
<P>
   If the disk containing the sought-after file isn't in the drive,
DiskCataloger will prompt the user to insert the disk in the proper
drive.
</P>
<P>
   Frequently used files can be dropped on the desktop where
DiskCataloger will create a shortcut for them. Clicking on the
shortcut will call up the file. A prompt will appear telling the
user to insert the appropriate disk in the drive if the file is not
found.
</P>
<P>
   The program also handles files that have been compressed. The
``zipped'' files are stored in a separate folder, and the zipped
file can be quickly expanded to see what other files it contains.
</P>
<P>
   When displaying the disk tree, disk icons show what type of disk
has been cataloged. In addition, users can assign different colors
to the disk icons so that they match the color of the disk being
cataloged or match the color of the label on the disk. It's a small
feature that makes indexing and locating disks easier.
</P>
<P>
   Once a disk is ``registered'' - the program's term for indexing
- the program automatically keeps track of files on the disk that
have been renamed, deleted or added.
</P>
<P>
   When a disk is initially inserted, DiskCataloger will ask if the
disk is to be used on one computer or more than one. The answer
depends on how the program will track the disk. But even if the
disk finds its way into another computer, it can easily be
re-indexed in a future session. The designation can also be changed
so DiskCataloger will automatically re-index a disk used in more
than one computer.
</P>
<P>
   The indexed disks can also be stored under separate category
headings, so several users of the same computer can have the disks
they use indexed under one heading.
</P>
<P>
   A trial copy of the software can be downloaded from the
company's Web site (www.shersoft.com). It will operate for 15 days.
After that time period, users can restore its operation by buying
the product from the company. For information, contact Sheridan
Software toll-free: (800) 823-4732.
</P>
<P>
   (Lonnie Brown is associate editor of The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla. He can be reached by e-mail at LonnieB001(AT)aol.com. An
archive of his recent computer columns is on the Internet at
http://www.theledger.com/data.htm.)
</P>
</TEXT>
