<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, July 11, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stalled low pressure will circulate cool, moist air over
northern New England. Abundant clouds and scattered showers are
expected, mainly away from the coast with brisk winds from the
northwest. It will turn drier and brighter Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   A cool morning will yield to a pleasant afternoon with very low
humidity from the Great Lakes to the middle Atlantic coast as high
pressure maintains control. Puffy clouds will mix with intervals of
sunshine in the Appalachians. It will be cool again Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Strong to severe thunderstorms will ignite from the central
Plains to the western Tennessee valley as a jet-stream disturbance
interacts with a front stalled across the Deep South. Some storms
will produce damaging wind gusts and hail. Farther east, weaker
thunderstorms will erupt near the Atlantic coast. Thundershowers
with downpours will affect parts of Florida, mainly near the west
coast.
</P>
<P>
   A vigorous disturbance 18,000 feet over the northern Rockies
will cause potent thunderstorms to erupt near a cold front pressing
east through Montana and Wyoming toward the western High Plains.
Some of these storms will have large hailstones and winds over 58
mph. Elsewhere, the monsoon circulation will sponsor afternoon
thundershowers in the southern Rockies, while a weak disturbance
will prompt a few storms over eastern Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and a few showers will plague the Northwest coast.
Tranquil weather will embrace the rest of the Pacific states while
portions of the Southwest experience blistering heat.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Hot Southern Night
</P>
<P>
   Early Thursday morning, the mercury only fell to 83 degrees in
Texarkana, Ark., after reaching an afternoon high of 102 degrees
the day before. Never before since records began in 1930 did the
city have such a warm night. Typically, record warmth at night is a
byproduct of very high humidity and a persistent wind. During the
night, the ground cools by radiating energy into space. When the
air is in motion, the amount of time it is in contact with the
chilling ground is reduced, resulting in warm nocturnal conditions.
Winds at Texarkana averaged between 5 and 15 mph Wednesday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
