<SLUG> BC-CHILDREN'S-EXPRESS-ADVISORY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS: THE FOLLOWING FEATURES FROM CHILDREN'S EXPRESS MOVED
TODAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Children's Express is an independent, non-profit news service
reported by children whose tape-recorded interviews, roundtables
and commentary are edited by teens and adults. The features are
transmitted by The New York Times Service and are available to New
York Times News Service clients at no extra charge.) 
 (JT)  
 c. 1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIRLPOWER-CEXP (Undated) _ When the Ms. Foundation talks about
girls changing the world, they don't even call it girl power. They
talk about powerful girls. ``At the Ms. Foundation for Women, we'd
be talking about the power that girls feel, particularly before
adolescence,'' said Marie Wilson, president of the foundation.
``The power that they see in their mothers, a power that girls
naturally have and adults can help sustain.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OVERPOPULATION-CEXP &LR;  (Undated) _ Humans won't have to go to
subterranean settlements or colonize another planet to solve it,
but overpopulation is a serious problem. It is primarily the result
of a lack of birth control and education, and young marriage,
according to Christina Horpeza, the public information specialist
for the Population Council. The council was founded 30 years ago to
address the problem of overpopulation and to understand the factors
that affect it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TEENS-DRINKING-CEXP &LR;  (Undated) _ Whether it be drinking late
with friends or attending the funeral of a classmate killed by a
drunken driver, alcohol plays a big role in the lives of teenagers.
``It's a totally preventable problem where people, once they have
consumed beverages that makes them unable to function properly,
decide to perform dangerous activities,'' said Meggan(cq) Ways, a
senior at Indianapolis' Brebeuf Jesuit Preparatory School and
president of the school's Students Against Drunk Driving (SADD)
chapter. The national organization recently changed its name to
Students Against Destructive Decisions to encompass more of the
problems facing teens.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TEEN-OFFENDER-CEXP &LR;  (Undated) _ This is a story about Christy,
a 16-year-old from Marquette County, Mich., who has been in trouble
with the law since she was 12. Although she has had a tough home
life, which seems to be the root of a lot of problems among teens,
she doesn't blame her actions on anyone but herself, saying that
everyone makes their own decisions. Here is her story.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
