<HEADER>
A9720 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APRIL-TRANSCRIPT-$ADV     07-10 1648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APRIL-TRANSCRIPT-$ADV12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TRANSCRIPT DETAILS TURMOIL WITHIN CNN OVER CONTROVERSIAL REPORT
 &HT;    With APRIL-OLIVER. Moving in (w) Washington and (e)
entertainment categories for release Sunday, July 12.
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Following are excerpts from a July 2 conference
call in which CNN reporters and producers learned of an internal
network investigation that concluded there was insufficient
evidence to support its June 7 story alleging that U.S. forces
dropped sarin nerve gas on American defectors in Laos.
</P>
<P>
   Various participants in the conference call confirmed the
accuracy of the transcript, which was obtained by Cox Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The conference call included CNN officials and employees in
Atlanta, Washington and elsewhere. A purpose of the conference call
was to inform reporters and producers about the findings of the
internal CNN investigation, which was prepared by noted attorney
Floyd Abrams and David Kohler, general counsel of CNN News Group.
</P>
<P>
   Among the participants were:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jim Connor, who is now acting executive producer of the
program called ``NewsStand,'' a collaborative effort between CNN
and Time magazine, which are owned by Time Warner. Connor declined
to discuss the transcript.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Producer April Oliver and senior producer Jack Smith, who
played key roles in preparing the broadcast. Neither provided the
transcript to Cox, but both confirmed the accuracy of their
comments.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pamela Hill, who resigned as executive producer of the
program. She could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The transcript offers a glimpse of the internal agony and
conflict over the story, which CNN has publicly retracted and
apologized for airing.
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _
</P>
<P>
   Connor: ... ``Washington, here's the deal. There is a fifty-page
report prepared by Floyd Abrams and David Kohler. Fifty-four page
report. That will be released shortly. I'll make sure you get
copies. There is a statement by (Tom Johnson, CNN Chairman and CEO
and president of CNN News Group) which I will fax to you shortly as
soon as I'm allowed to release that. (NewsStand executive producer
Pamela Hill) has resigned and her resignation has been accepted.
...
</P>
<P>
   ``The central findings of the report are that, while a lot of
material was gathered in support of the broadcast, there was
insufficient evidence to support the broadcast, there was
insufficient evidence to support the conclusions, that there were
problems with the two key on-air sources ... (and that another
interviewee was) used in an inappropriate way and that (two others)
who. . .said it was not sarin, were ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Kohler and Floyd Abrams spent a lot of time and a lot of
money trying to find somebody who could back us, and they couldn't.
...Rick Kaplan (president of CNN-U.S.) believes in this program, he
believes in all of us. And we're going to go on. We're going to try
and kill this thing, drive a stake through its heart and bury it
(once the internal report and retraction are issued) so it's gone,
and go forward with our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _
</P>
<P>
   Connor, asked if anyone else had been requested to resign, names
senior producer Jack Smith and producer April Oliver.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver: ``I'm sitting here and no one has contacted me and I'm
not _ as far as I'm concerned I'm not resigning, they will have to
fire me.''
</P>
<P>
   Connor: ``All right April, let's deal with this separately. I
thought you had been contacted. I had been given the information
that you had been.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver: ``I have not.''
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _
</P>
<P>
   Oliver then takes issue with the conclusions in the Abrams
report and complains that the internal CNN investigation did not
offer her an adequate opportunity to defend her reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver: ``We were not given feedback on that report even though
we were promised feedback on that report. Jack and I both feel that
there were substantial flaws in that report. For instance, to knock
down (retired Navy Adm. Thomas Moorer, now 86, who at the time of
the alleged gassing was chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff) as a
source they used my very first get-to-know you conversation where
he says 'I'm not confirming anything,' instead of my last
conversation with him where he confirms everything. They just
completely neglected to go to the hardest evidence and I'm not sure
why.
</P>
<P>
   ``This contention that (mission commander Eugene) McCarley was
ignored is inaccurate. He was in there multiple times defending his
point of view. McCarley said clearly, ``'Whatever was dropped from
the sky, I don't know what it was.' He said, 'it was an accident we
went into that village.' He got the opportunity to present his
point of view multiple times. He was one of the lead figures in the
broadcast. I think it was quite unfair for us to have been promised
an opportunity to comment on the report and then not have that
opportunity at all. In addition, this notion that I have resigned
is false. ...I have not even been contacted.''
</P>
<P>
   Connor: ``April, I will withdraw what I said and I will make
sure that you are contacted ASAP. ...I want people to understand
one thing here. Jack (Smith) defended this with fire, emotion,
logic and reason for an hour last night. Should you have gotten
more time _ yes. But he was stalwart in his defense of the
reporting, in his defense of the story. I mean, it was the most
honorable act I have ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _
</P>
<P>
   Oliver later asks to make another point about the report from
the internal investigation:
</P>
<P>
   Oliver: ``The producers requested an hour to do this story in
January. We wrote a proposal outlining an hour, knowing full well
that it was a controversial story and that it needed full vetting.
Every time that they hit on us in that report, it's for something
we excluded. When you came to us this past spring, you told us to
do a 14-minute piece.''
</P>
<P>
   Connor: ``That's right.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver: ``So, how come we're being fired for not including all
these things that we couldn't possibly fit into a 14-minute
piece?''
</P>
<P>
   Connor: ``April, you're asking the unanswerable.''
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Smith joins the conference call in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Smith: ``I hate to be late, as they say, to your own hanging,
but tell me the latest.''
</P>
<P>
   Connor: ``Well, the latest is that Pam's resignation has been
accepted. Pamela's got some things that she wants to say to us.
...Will you go get her ask her to come in?''
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Hill, who has just resigned as executive producer of the
program, addresses the group:
</P>
<P>
   Hill: ``I just want to say to you all that this has been as
traumatic for all of you as it has been for those of us most
immediately involved. I believe that the company did the right
thing. I absolutely believe that they did the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a mistake. (CNN reporter and commentator) Jeff
Greenfield asked me early on, 'did we add two an two and get five?'
And at the time I did not believe that. I believed that we had
added two and two and had four. The documentary evidence. The
evidence, the briefing book was very persuasive. We were all moving
too fast to get to air and everybody moving very, very, very fast,
but I think that in the end as questions came up here. ...I wanted
Floyd to come in, I was the person who first called Floyd Abrams, I
have a huge regard for him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good faith on the part of everybody involved. We _ I
think in the end we didn't have all of _ the report takes the view
that we didn't have enough information to go to air and I think
that is fair. Floyd and David Kohler read everything. They spent
two very intense weeks on this and when _ if you don't have it,
then the very best thing is to do what the company did. That is to
take a look at this and say 'OK, we weren't ready. We didn't have
it and we retract.'''
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _
</P>
<P>
   Smith then provides his account of his meeting earlier in the
day with CNN Chairman and CEO Tom Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Smith: ``Let me tell you so that everybody hears this. Tom
Johnson called me about 10:15 this morning and after we discussed
the report. ...I told him that I strenuously objected to its
conclusion and a great many of its particulars. A great many of its
particulars. Tom Johnson then said, 'I'm here to ask you either to
resign or I'm going to terminate you. If you don't resign, I'll
terminate you.' I said to Johnson that there had been an agreement
with David Kohler last night at one in the morning that April and I
would have an opportunity to comment and criticize the draft report
and that no action would be taken until that was accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom Johnson then said he would hold in abeyance what he said
to me with respect to resignation or termination until that noon
meeting, that noon call with Kohler and whoever else was supposed
to be on that call, took place. That's my last conversation with
Johnson. I also told him at the time that April and I had not been
interviewed as part this investigation in spite of Mr. Abrams and
Mr. Kohler indicating that would be done. It was not done. We were
misled and we were deceived.
</P>
<P>
   A participant in Atlanta said, ``it raises the question about
the whole credibility of the. (Abrams) report.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith: ``And they should hold off the release of anything until
we have that conversation. Fairness is not being accomplished here.
They should not go forward with any public release until we, the
principals of this story, who've been gagged for the last two
weeks, have an opportunity to speak about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have gagged us. They have deceived us and they have
misled us and every reporter in this room should know that. This is
a corporate whitewash. This is a cave to the military
establishment, to the secret army which is one step away from the
secret police. ``
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
