<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this
transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100, ext. 224.
WASHINGTON, July 10 -- The following chart shows how senators and
house representatives voted on key bills and amendments within the
last week. A ``Y'' means the member voted for the measure; an ``N''
means the member voted against the measure; a ``?'' means the
member did not vote; and a ``P'' means the member voted
``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: IRS
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted Thursday, 96-2, to revamp the IRS and expand
the rights of taxpayers. When Clinton signs the measure, it will be
the most significant change in the agency since 1952. Supporters
said the bill will make the IRS more accountable to private
citizens and more customer service oriented. It will also place the
burden of proof on the agency in certain disputes before tax court.
No one rose in opposition. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: SANCTIONS
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted Thursday, 98-0, to lift sanctions on
agricultural exports and medicine to India and Pakistan. Under this
legislation, those countries could buy American farm products.
Supporters said cutting off agricultural sales to countries
involved in nuclear proliferation hurts only American farmers and
ranchers and does not deter nuclear build-up. A ``yes'' vote favors
the bill.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: EDUCATION
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted Thursday, 96-1, to pass a higher education bill
that would allow college students to borrow money at lower interest
rates and would increase the maximum federal grant for needy
students by $2,000. Lawmakers will have to resolve differences
between this bill, which they say would make a college education
available to more Americans, and the administration's stance, which
opposes giving lenders subsidies to keep interest rates low. No one
rose in opposition. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3
</P>
<P>
   --- --- ---
</P>
<P>
   SANTORUM (R-PA) Y Y Y
</P>
<P>
   SPECTER (R-PA) Y Y Y
</P>
<P>
   THERE ARE NO HOUSE VOTES THIS WEEK.
</P>
