<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-CROCKETT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUGLAS S. CROCKET, 70; REPORTER, DIRECTOR OF GLOBE SANTA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Douglas S. Crocket of Yarmouth, Mass., a lifelong newspaperman
and longtime director of Globe Santa whose heart-rending stories
led thousands to dig deep each Christmas and provide presents for
needy youngsters, died of colon cancer Friday in Cape Cod Hospital
in Hyannis. He was 70.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Crocket wasn't a journalist. He was a reporter. A reporter
of the old school: a tough-talking sweetheart who could converse
cynically about current affairs, then crank out a human interest
story that would make you cry over your cup of coffee the next
morning.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Somerville, Mass., he got bitten by the newspaper
bug while still a student at the Cambridge High and Latin School,
when he got his first story published in the old Boston Record
American. He became a copy boy at the Record.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from high school he served in the Navy, where
he got further training as a reporter for the Jacksonville (Fla.)
Navy Base newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   He graduated from Boston University in 1952 and was editor of
the Arlington Advocate for about a year before joining the Globe
staff.
</P>
<P>
   During his long career at the Globe, Mr. Crocket wrote about
everything from local politics to lion trainers. He had a fine eye
for detail: the young defendant who sat in court clutching rosary
beads and religious pictures as her one-year sentence was read, the
cabdriver with the rat-a-tat rap of the pitchman. And he saw it all
with an unblinking eye. ``Agony '' he once wrote, ``is not physical
pain. It is the collapse of a man who has lost his youngest son.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Crocket took a hands-on approach to his profession. At
various times he performed as a circus clown, pumped gas, and drove
a garbage truck for feature stories published in the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   He also taught journalism at Boston University for many years,
but he is perhaps best remembered for his many years as director of
Globe Santa. He began writing stories and raising funds for the
annual project shortly after the Globe took over the drive from the
Boston Post when it folded in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   Though he retired in 1987, he returned to the Globe every
Thanksgiving for the next 10 years to write stories and raise funds
for the monthlong Globe Santa drive. His byline and his craggy
visage looked out from newspaper photos as he accepted checks for
the fund.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew V. Storin, editor of the Globe, said: ``Doug was right
out of the `The Front Page.' He was the ultimate street reporter
who could talk to anyone and get anyone to talk to him. When his
reporter's legs gave out, he applied those same skills to making
Globe Santa the great charity it is.''
</P>
<P>
   When informed of his death, William O. Taylor, chairman of the
board of directors of the Globe, said: ``Doug was one of the true
`Globies','' _ as we used to call Globe staffers who made a unique
contribution to the paper. Doug was No. 1 Globe Santa
representative to the community. He developed a loyal following,
year after year, building on friendships for the benefit of young
kids. We will all miss his enthusiasm and dedication.''
</P>
<P>
   He leaves a sister, Joan, of Charlestown, Mass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 1825EDT &QL; 
