<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-DISPUTE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE SUMMONS PARTIES IN TEXAS TOBACCO DISPUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE FOY  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Hoping to kick-start stalled negotiations
between feuding sides in the state's multibillion-dollar tobacco
settlement, U.S. District Judge David Folsom has told all parties
in the dispute to appear at the federal courthouse in Texarkana on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The $15.3 billion settlement was reached earlier this year, but
has been bogged down over objections to fees the Texas attorney
general agreed to pay the private lawyers hired to fight the case.
Leading lawmakers say the $2.3 billion in fees for lawyers is too
much for a case that never went to trial.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, counties and hospital districts fear that the
landmark settlement will prevent them from getting their share of
the settlement or from suing the tobacco industry to recover costs
of treating smoking-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Dan Morales, the private attorneys he hired in
the case and representatives from Gov. George W. Bush's office will
attend the closed hearing in the judge's chambers.
</P>
<P>
   Also included will be attorneys for the lawmakers who are
challenging the lawyers' fees and the consortium of counties and
hospital districts angered over the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge is very interested in seeing this settlement
finalized,'' said Sonya Sanchez, a spokeswoman for Morales.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez said Folsom is expected to act as a ``catalyst'' to help
wrap up negotiations in the dispute so the settlement with the
tobacco industry can become final.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has insisted that he, too, wants an end to the ordeal. He
believes that is possible if Morales will agree to sever the
contentious attorneys' fees issue from the main settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Banning, a spokesman for the group of private attorneys
hired by Morales, said Folsom could insist on assuming a position
of mediator in the complex disputes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, if he gets them all in a room together, they can
hammer something out,'' Banning said.
</P>
<P>
   A top priority in the hearing will be to address the legal claim
by the group of counties and hospital districts, Sanchez said. The
challenge has the ability to scuttle the entire deal.
</P>
<P>
   The counties and hospital districts have complained that the
deal Morales reached with the tobacco industry cuts them out of any
financial settlement. It also unfairly limits their ability to
recover damages from tobacco companies, the group contends.
</P>
<P>
   Folsom was scheduled to hear the Texas lawsuit against the
tobacco industry in Texarkana, but the parties settled out of court
before the trial began.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
