<HEADER>
A9778 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-INFLATION-BOS &LR;      07-10 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-INFLATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHOLESALE PRICES EASE AFTER THREE-MONTH RISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Asia's shrinking economies have taken some of the steam out of
US wholesale prices.
</P>
<P>
   Prices charged by producers of the nation's goods eased in June
for the first time in three months. The government reported Friday
the Producer Price Index declined by 0.1 percent last month as
falling demand for oil by struggling Asian countries pulled down
oil prices, a big component in the index.
</P>
<P>
   Another damper on inflation has been a sharp decline in Asian
currencies, starting with the Thai bhat last year and spreading
recently to the Japanese yen. As the dollar's value has risen
against these currencies, US consumers are paying less for Asian
goods. Lower import prices in turn have forced American companies
to lower their prices to compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inflation is simply not a problem,'' said Nicholas Perna,
chief economist for Fleet Financial Group Inc. ``Right now what is
more of a problem is ... how much damage is the Asia situation
doing to the US economy. We simply don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   But a reversal in producer prices _ following an 0.2 percent
rise in each of the two prior months, April and May _ may not be
enough to ease concerns that inflation may flare in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Federal Reserve Board, which can raise rates to
crube inflation, are concerned that the the overheated US economy
and low unemployment are pushing up wages, a force driving
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Fed members voted in a May 19 meeting to keep the federal funds
rate steady at 5.5 percent. Some Fed members said that their vote
was a close call and that they may vote to raise rates at the next
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The producer price report by the Labor Department contained some
evidence of increasing inflation pressures.
</P>
<P>
   The ``core'' PPI in June, which excludes the volatile prices of
food and energy, rose a moderate 0.2 percent last month, matching
increases in two prior month. Economists blamed the June rate on an
unexpected jump in prices of prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tiny little red flag but it's still a red flag,'' said
William Dudley, senior US economist for Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co. in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   A more precise measure of inflation, the Consumer Price Index,
is scheduled to be released next week.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the long-running economic boom in this country,
inflation has remained calm for years.
</P>
<P>
   The Producer Price Index for the year-ending with June rose a
slight 0.8 percent, according to Fleet's Perna. But the PPI for the
first six months of 1998, when annualized, increased 1.5 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 1828EDT &QL; 
