<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-IMF-$ADV12-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMF FUNDING DEBATE PUTS STRESS ON HOUSE GOP LEADERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 12)   (EDS: Filed in the ``w'' and ``f'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Speaker Newt Gingrich's support for new U.S.
funding for the International Monetary Fund appears likely to
rekindle a bitter debate over the role of the 182-member
organization that could pit him against other Republican leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The funding debate comes as Russia and the IMF work out the
final details of a bailout loan that is expected to total between
$10 billion and $15 billion.
</P>
<P>
   If the Russian deal goes through, the IMF _ which already has
committed $35 billion in the past year to rescue crisis-stricken
Asian nations _ would be close to going broke.
</P>
<P>
   IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus says the Russian bailout
would leave the lending institution ``unable to quickly intervene
in any future financial crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Pushing Congress to help the IMF by approving $18 billion in new
U.S. contributions, Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin warned recently
that a deepening of the Asian crisis or the eruption of a new
currency crisis elsewhere could have a ``very substantial impact on
the U.S. economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration's request for $18 billion won Senate
approval in March but has run into stiff opposition in the House
where IMF critics complain that the institution is too secretive
and that many of the conditions the IMF imposes on borrowing
countries end up hurting their economies rather than helping.
</P>
<P>
   Critics also argue that the IMF encourages banks and investors
to make risky loans because they know the IMF would step in and
protect them if their investments went bad.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich had opposed the $18 billion plan until last month. But
under pressure from corporate lobbying groups and agricultural
advocates that have been hurt badly by plummeting Asian economies,
the speaker has become a supporter of more U.S. help.
</P>
<P>
   Just before Congress recessed for the July 4th holiday, he
announced his support and said the House would take up IMF funding
legislation by September.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the kind of changes you have in Indonesia, in Russia and
in South Korea, and the potential challenges in Japan, we have an
obligation to work with the International Monetary Fund,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker's sudden support for the IMF was countered by ardent
opposition from Majority Leader Richard Armey, R-Texas, Majority
Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, and other conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Giving the IMF more money is not a panacea for all the
troubles that bedevil the Asian economy,'' DeLay said after hearing
of Gingrich's new stance. ``In fact, in many instances, the IMF is
the problem, not the solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Armey continues to argue that the IMF causes more harm than good
by not allowing corrupt and incompetent banking systems to fail
under a free-market system.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay and Armey insist that any more U.S. help for the IMF
should be conditioned on the IMF's commitment to adopt new policies
of openness. If the reform measures are not included in the bill or
Gingrich asks for too much money, sources say DeLay and Armey may
work against the speaker on a final floor vote.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich has not said how much money he will try to secure for
the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF funding issue also has become snarled in a campaign by
conservative House Republicans to link anti-abortion provisions to
foreign-policy initiatives, including IMF funding.
</P>
<P>
   These conservatives oppose any legislation approving money for
the United Nations or the IMF unless the measures include separate
provisions barring American aid to overseas family-planning groups
that advocate abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, an anti-abortion provision introduced by Rep.
Chris Smith, R-N.J., effectively killed a bill to make overdue
payments to the United Nations and to provide additional IMF
funding.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Gingrich, R-Ga., supported the Smith measure.
</P>
<P>
   So even if the speaker is able to placate DeLay and Armey, he
still faces the threat of Smith attaching an anti-abortion measure
to the IMF funding measure, which Clinton has threatened to veto in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress approves IMF funding but attaches the anti-abortion
provisions to the bill, Clinton would be caught in a tight corner
because he is eager to help the IMF, on the one hand, but is
nervous about offending abortion rights groups, on the other.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Wolfe, a spokesman for Smith, said the congressman has not
decided whether to add an anti-abortion provision to any new IMF
funding bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still waiting to see if an IMF funding bill makes it to
the floor, but if it does, we would certainly consider attaching an
abortion measure to it,'' Wolfe said.
</P>
<P>
   IMF officials say the fund has only about $10 billion to $15
billion in its coffers that can be used to help member countries
through financial crises. Established in 1945, the IMF primary role
today is to stabilize faltering financial markets around the world.
The fund often accomplishes this by buying large amounts of a
currency that's falling and by providing money to banks that are
near collapse because of bad loans.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF could tap into an emergency fund of about $24 billion,
but any use of that money requires the approval of the United
States and other rich countries, which IMF officials say would
waste valuable time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY COULD END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To help garner support for the IMF, Gingrich has attempted to
draw attention to falling American exports to Asian countries,
particularly in agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
   ``Farmers and ranchers must have the confidence that they will
be able to sell their products on the world market without
restriction in the years ahead,'' Gingrich said in a letter to Rep.
Robert F. Smith, R-Ore., chairman of the House Agriculture
Committee before the recess.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James Leach, R-Iowa, who introduced an IMF funding bill
last month, said in an interview that many Americans fail to
understand how important exports are to Iowa and other agricultural
states.
</P>
<P>
   ``My state's whole economy is dependent on agriculture, and
agriculture is now an international industry that needs strong
economies in Asia to buy its goods,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Forty percent of Iowa's farm income comes from foreign sales,
which have plummeted as many Asian economies continue to
disintegrate. In the past two years, Indonesia's economy has shrunk
by 80 percent, Thailand's by 50 percent, South Korea's by 45
percent, Malaysia's by 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   By looking out for agricultural interests, Gingrich also may be
keeping his options open for a possible presidential bid in 2000,
when Iowa would be a key battleground for Republican nominating
delegates.
</P>
