<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9810 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEY-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      07-10 0350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEY-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDY BEY: TALENT FOR A GROWING AUDIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Andy Bey isn't your typically ingratiating jazz
singer-pianist; in performance, his extraordinary talent can seem
protected in a glass museum case, resting on a pillow. And his
sense of pacing asks that you travel at least halfway toward him.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing in a trio (Peter Washington on bass and Vito Lesczak
on drums) at Iridium on Tuesday night, he warmed up with a long
instrumental version of ``Just Friends,'' playing a wealth of dryly
articulated scales over the chords, making the music constantly
change colors while his rhythm section chugged along at midtempo.
It wasn't the kind of opening shot that ropes in the attention of a
late-night audience.
</P>
<P>
   But when he started singing the next song, Jerome Kern's
``Yesterday,'' his bass-baritone voice made his piano playing seem
cold excercises by comparison. On the song's short phrases _ ``Sad
am I/Glad am I'' _ he shot up into a falsetto, wringing the
microtones of the blues from them, and he expelled each line with
the power of a snare-drum being socked. He is more forcefully
rhythmic than most jazz singers and, indeed, many jazz musicians.
</P>
<P>
   Bey, who is in his mid-50s and has long been a special taste for
aficionados, is slowly entering that inevitable process for
promising jazz players in the 1990s: reaching new audiences. His
repertory based in standards is changing; on Tuesday he introduced
two songs from a forthcoming album that departs from jazz entirely.
</P>
<P>
   One was Nick Drake's ``River Man,'' a magisterially sad and
mysterious song that he performed away from the piano, sitting on a
stool, with Paul Meyers accompanying him on acoustic guitar. The
other was a lullaby in Spanish, ``Drume Negrita,'' a brighter and
harmonically simpler song that let Bey explore the muddy bottoms
and exotic highs of voice. At times the song approached the sort of
music Milton Nascimento made in the early '70s, kaleidoscopic in
mood and breaking free of all genres.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
