<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9819 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KAYE-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT     07-10 0381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KAYE-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUMP RHYTHM JAZZ PROJECT: MISMATCHED SONG AND DANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Billy Siegenfeld is an Al Pacino look-alike with a
rough purr of a singing voice. He and his collaborator, Jeannie
Hill, move with a speed and expansiveness that suggest that their
feet disdain mere human dance steps. But with one exception, the
program of five pieces that Siegenfeld, Ms. Hill and their Jump
Rhythm Jazz Project presented on Tuesday night at Kaye Playhouse
was a disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   That was not the fault of the company's engaging, immensely
skilled dancers, and, with the exception of a few too-cerebral
riffs, the frequent use of music performed live by the Jump Rhythm
Jazz Trio was a plus. The problem was that Siegenfeld and Ms. Hill
are not the bright, sophisticated song-and-dance duo they attempt
to be. Neither performer is a strong enough singer for the extended
revue suites they presented, and Siegenfeld's New York grittiness
does not mix well with the sweet wholesomeness that Ms. Hill
projects.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight of the evening was ``Released in Their Own Custody
(Trading Romance for a Good Piece of Fruit),'' choreographed by
Siegenfeld, a professor of dance and music theater at Northwestern
University and a guest teacher at the Broadway Dance Center in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The new dance, which never quite delivers on the subtitle, is a
celebration of the music of Christian McBride, the jazz bassist,
heard here on tape in pop standards and a composition of his own.
Most of all, it suggests that Siegenfeld is on to something with
the Jump Rhythm style, a matter of taut, precise, fast and
far-moving jazz dancing.
</P>
<P>
   The first of the three sections, ``Too Close For Comfort,'' is a
particular pleasure. The dancers (Annie Arnoult, Becky Cooper, Kari
Knudson, Kelly Malone, Matthew Metro and Birgitta Victorson) are
like hard little projectiles hurtling through space.
</P>
<P>
   But each step and gesture is clear, and soon the hurtling
becomes a kind of ground-skimming flight that captures the
exuberant physicality of good dancers when moments of extreme
control and abandon are seamlessly combined.
</P>
<P>
   The fine cast was completed by Justin Jones and Anna Marie
Paulilio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 1845EDT &QL; 
