<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9821 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-USCHINA-$ADV12-COX     07-10 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USCHINA-$ADV12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WIDENING PROBE OF SATELLITE SALES WORRIES INDUSTRY
 &HT;    With USCHINA-DATA. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories for release Sunday, July 12.
 &HT;    By REBECCA CARR
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The congressional investigations into whether
sensitive satellite technology was given to China are expanding to
examine the track record of other satellite manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   And the nation's satellite makers are less than pleased at the
prospect of being brought into an inquiry involving two of their
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   With nine congressional committees looking into various aspects
of the nation's export policy, there is a growing concern among
U.S. satellite manufacturers that they are being unfairly dragged
into a election-year partisan showdown on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of concern among the companies that Congress is
rushing headlong into this,'' said Clayton Mowry, director of the
Virginia-based Satellite Industry Association, which represents 16
American satellite companies. ``By being overly aggressive, we are
concerned that they will start to legislate before the facts are
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Mowry said the congressional focus should remain on whether
Loral Space and Communications and Hughes Electronics helped the
Chinese figure out why a satellite launch failed in February 1996
in southern China, and if that action posed a national security
threat.
</P>
<P>
   But investigators, defense experts and members of Congress are
seeking to pry information from other satellite manufacturers such
as Lockheed Martin and Motorola, as well as companies that produce
satellite components, to see if technology intended for commercial
use was used for military purposes by the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   ``The layer of the onion is just now being pulled away,'' said
Rep. Dana Rohrabacher, R-Calif., who chairs the House Science
Committee's space and aeronautics subcommittee, which is looking
into the issue. ``In pulling away that layer, we will find other
companies that may be involved at putting American military
personnel at great risk.''
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high for the satellite industry. An economic
analysis by the Maryland-based Futron Corp. estimates that revenues
from the U.S. commercial satellite market, now valued $5.7 billion,
could climb to six times that amount by 2003. Total sales have
skyrocketed from $3.2 billion in 1991 to a projected $60 billion by
the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Aerospace analysts say that if Congress goes too far in
restricting the satellite launches, it could undermine an industry
on the cusp of a boom. Chiefly, the companies say they are worried
about a push to reverse the 1996 decision by the Clinton
administration to shift the authority to approve foreign launches
of U.S. satellites from the the State Department to the Commerce
Department.
</P>
<P>
   The business community strongly backed that move, with some
comparing the State Department application process to a ``roach
motel,'' the type of place where you check in, but never check out.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a real sexy issue for Congress,'' said Marco Caceres,
senior space analyst at the Teal Group, an aerospace consulting
firm in Fairfax, Va. ``Whenever you put the question of national
security out there, congressmen and senators love to get on the
bandwagon.''
</P>
<P>
   But full-scale examination of the practices of the entire
industry risks losing control of the satellite market to the
European satellite makers, Caceres said. American companies have
built 72 percent of the 185 commercial satellites launched over the
last decade. ``The Europeans are probably sitting back grinning,
saying 'here comes Congress,' `` he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin is equally concerned about the outcome of the
congressional investigations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potential international market for commercial satellites
is enormous, and we don't want to give it away to the Europeans,''
said James Fetig, director of national media relations.
</P>
<P>
   Some may believe that restricting U.S. satellites from being
launched in China will lead to more being launched in the United
States, he said. ``Instead, in the global marketplace, it is
possible that the U.S. will actually lose that satellite business
because our international customers can buy satellites in Europe
that can be launched on foreign launchers, so as a result we may
lose both satellite and launch business.''
</P>
<P>
   But to some, congressional scrutiny has been long in coming.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Sokolski, the top Pentagon expert monitoring nuclear
proliferation during the Bush administration, has told several
congressional panels that he believes that American technology has
helped the Chinese military.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we keep playing footsie with these guys on these
(satellite) transfers, we're going to get burned,'' said Sokolski,
who now runs the Nonproliferation Policy Education Center in
Virginia. Congress should address how the American satellite
manufacturers became so dependent on the Chinese launchers in the
first place, he said, and it should delve back to the Bush
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Contrasting that view is Jeffrey Record, a visiting professor at
the Sam Nunn School of International Affairs at Georgia Tech. The
difference between technology that can be used solely for military
purposes and technology that can be used for commercial purposes is
narrowing. For example cell phones, computers and satellites can
all be used for military purposes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to prevent China from getting the
information they want,'' Record said. ``There is a crowd out there
that wants to make China public enemy number one to take the place
of the Soviet Union. But one has to watch that because of the
enormous amount of potential in China.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., has been one of the most vocal on the
congressional investigation. He is concerned that there is an
attempt by the Democrats to broaden the investigation to ``muddy
the waters and distract attention from the core issues of the
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We must remain focused: Did Loral and Hughes violate U.S. law
by transferring sensitive missile technology to China? Did the
White House grant waivers for exportation of sensitive military
technology?'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 1845EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0256 </DOCNO>
