Virginia. Congress should address how the American satellite
manufacturers became so dependent on the Chinese launchers in the
first place, he said, and it should delve back to the Bush
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Contrasting that view is Jeffrey Record, a visiting professor at
the Sam Nunn School of International Affairs at Georgia Tech. The
difference between technology that can be used solely for military
purposes and technology that can be used for commercial purposes is
narrowing. For example cell phones, computers and satellites can
all be used for military purposes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to prevent China from getting the
information they want,'' Record said. ``There is a crowd out there
that wants to make China public enemy number one to take the place
of the Soviet Union. But one has to watch that because of the
enormous amount of potential in China.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., has been one of the most vocal on the
congressional investigation. He is concerned that there is an
attempt by the Democrats to broaden the investigation to ``muddy
the waters and distract attention from the core issues of the
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We must remain focused: Did Loral and Hughes violate U.S. law
by transferring sensitive missile technology to China? Did the
White House grant waivers for exportation of sensitive military
technology?'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
