<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAVEHILL-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANCES FOR WAVE HILL: A DUET UP CLOSE, WITH ECHOES ACROSS THE
LAWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dances for Wave Hill began its eighth year on
Wednesday afternoon with a new resident mentor, the performance
artist Ann Carlson. But the point of the three-week summer series
seems not to have changed. Dances by two choreographers spilled out
over Wave Hill, the sprawling environmental center in the Bronx,
with two of the three pieces clear responses to the demands of the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Creach's ``Par Terre,'' danced to delicately atmospheric
string music composed by Andy Teirstein and performed live,
occurred on a long sweep of lawn. Creach played imaginatively with
space and shapes in the piece, an extended duet that suddenly
emerged from under a faraway tree and traveled closer to the
audience. Four dancers served as counterpoint, tiny figures
cavorting around the tree.
</P>
<P>
   Creach seemed intent on exploring how a pair and a larger group
of dancers can split, merge and echo each other at varying
distances. The distant performers might have been children in a
leafy playground. Ornamental poses and edgy, complex action and
response blended with play for the compelling lead dancers, Paul
Matteson and Richard Patten.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the 10 musicians, solemn teen-age violinists dressed in
black, framed the duo and spread out like splashes of black paint
on the green vista. ``Par Terre'' had its aimless moments, but
Creach provided material for the contemplation of performing in
general and dance outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   Aimlessness was a greater problem in two pieces by Fausto Matias
that completed the evening's program. ``(En)Counter Gravity'' was
the more substantial of the two, with a few witty points to make
about gravity. Four dancers ran, rolled down and scrambled back up
a steep hill and tackled one another in sometimes
audience-scattering scrimmages.
</P>
<P>
   But the points were made early on and left largely undeveloped
in the piece, a structured improvisation full of once-fashionable
ingredients that was performed to sometimes arch comments about
gravity and an electronic score manipulated by the disc jockey
Steven Nardi.
</P>
<P>
   Matias took a coy look at Portuguese-style bullfighting in
``Tourada.'' Esteban Cardenas and Michael Dalby stood out as the
sweetly dopey bull and an impassive waiter in a cast completed by
David Figueroa and Yoko Yamanaka. The program will be repeated at 5
p.m. Sunday at West 249th Street and Independence Avenue in
Riverdale, the Bronx. Ms. Carlson takes over at 6:30 on Wednesday
and at 5 p.m. on July 19.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
