<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-BRIBERY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-ARMY GENERAL SENTENCED IN BRIBERY CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHILIP TRUE  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A Mexican army general convicted of trying to
bribe a top Baja California drug enforcement agent last year has
been sentenced to 20 years in prison, the attorney general's office
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Alfredo Navarro Lara was convicted of inviting Jose Luis Chavez
Garcia, then a delegate to the attorney general's office, to a posh
hotel and offering him $1 million per month to protect the
smuggling operation of the Arrellano Felix cartel, the agency said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have said that Navarro told Chavez that he and his
entire family would be killed if he refused the bribe.
</P>
<P>
   Navarro was arrested in March 1997, about a month after the
arrest of Gen. Jesus Gutierrez Rebollo on charges that he took
millions of dollars to protect the cartel from rivals in the
northern Mexican state of Chihuahua.
</P>
<P>
   Gutierrez was the country's drug czar at the time, and his
arrest rocked Mexico and nearly derailed the U.S. certification of
Mexican drug-fighting efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Gutierrez was sentenced to 13 years in prison on weapons
charges. His trial on drug and abuse-of-authority charges
continues.
</P>
<P>
   Navarro and Gutierrez are being held at a top-security prison
outside Toluca. Navarro has been cleared of conspiracy charges, but
the attorney general's office plans to appeal that acquittal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 1848EDT &QL; 
