</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-CARGOPLANE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN SAYS IT MAY BUY FOUR BOEING C-17 CARGO PLANES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL D. TOWLE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As part of a major shift in its defense strategy,
Britain has announced it will spend an estimated $900 million for
four Boeing C-17s in what would be the first international order
for the new Air Force cargo jet.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase, which still must clear hurdles in the British
government, could open the door to more C-17 sales to Britain and
to other NATO allies in Europe, aerospace industry analysts said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Northrop Grumman's plant in Grand Prairie, Texas, is a major
subcontractor to Boeing for the C-17. About 1,500 employees at the
plant in far west Dallas make the tail wings and engine housings
for the giant cargo jet.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force is expected to buy 120 C-17s, called the
Globemaster. Boeing, the prime contractor, assembles the plane at
its plant in Long Beach, Calif. More than 40 planes have been
delivered to date.
</P>
<P>
   British Defense Secretary George Robertson on Wednesday laid out
a plan for Parliament that explained how Britain would reshape its
military forces to be better able to conduct quick-strike
operations. When he made the plan public, he announced Britain's
desire to buy the Globemaster.
</P>
<P>
   The C-17 was developed for the Air Force to fly troops and
oversized equipment long distances. It also can land on and take
off from short runways, allowing the plane to fly to places that
previously could be reached only by smaller aircraft or by land.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force has flown the C-17 into several hot spots,
including Bosnia and the Persian Gulf during the recent Iraqi
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the post-Cold War world we must be prepared to go to the
crisis rather than have the crisis come to us,'' Robertson said.
``We will declare as potentially available to the United Nations a
much larger proportion of our readily available forces.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Engle, a spokeswoman for Northrop Grumman, said the
British plans were ``good news'' for the plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very hopeful that this will mean the sale of some
additional C-17s above the 120 the Air Force plans to buy,'' she
said. ``This is some great news for a great airplane.''
</P>
<P>
   British officials have not said when they will complete plans
for the C-17 purchase, but industry insiders say a contract could
be signed before the end of the year. Robertson said an
``equivalent'' to the C-17 could still be considered, but analysts
say no such aircraft exists and that an equivalent plane would be
too costly to develop.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you figure in the tremendous research and development
cost to produce something new and the time needed, it is worth
their while to go with the C-17,'' said William Dane, an aerospace
industry analyst with Forecast International, a Newtown, Conn.,
company that analyzes the defense industry.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing spokesman Rick Fuller said the company could deliver the
first of the four aircraft two years after the British place an
order.
</P>
<P>
   He said the company is confident that an order will be placed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been talking to the Brits for several years, providing
them with information,'' Fuller said. ``They have seen the airplane
perform at air shows and have had the opportunity to observe it in
Bosnia and in other operations where they have been involved with
the Air Force. They are well aware of its capabilities. The C-17
fulfills their requirements for the rapid reaction force.''
</P>
<P>
   Dane, who estimates the cost of a single C-17 at $225 million,
predicts that the Royal Air Force ultimately will buy 10 to 12
C-17s and that other European countries could buy at least that
many.
</P>
<P>
   ``This order is a foot in the door,'' Dane said. ``The logical
thing is for the other NATO allies in Europe to go in and buy a
dozen C-17s and have them at their disposal.''
</P>
<P>
   Germany, France, Belgium, the Netherlands and Japan all have
expressed varying degrees of interest in the C-17.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson's plan spelled out an effort to make British military
forces more capable of responding with the United States to any
crisis worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Britain was the only member of the NATO alliance that committed
troops, ships and planes alongside U.S. forces in the crisis with
Iraq. British officials also said they were prepared to join U.S.
forces in air operations in the crisis with Yugoslavia over Kosovo,
had it been warranted.
</P>
<P>
   The cargo compartment of the C-17 can accommodate Army wheeled
vehicles in two side-by-side rows. Three Bradley infantry fighting
vehicles comprise one deployment load. Similarly, the Army's newest
main battle tank, the M-1, can be carried along with other
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
