<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9851 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN     07-10 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGLICAN BISHOPS HOPE FOR UNITY DESPITE DIFFERENCES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Archbishop of Canterbury George Carey won't like it much. But
gay and lesbian issues likely will command great attention at the
upcoming worldwide Lambeth Conference in Canterbury, England.
</P>
<P>
   Carey is the symbolic leader of the 70-million-member Anglican
Communion, which encompasses 32 self-governing provinces, including
the Episcopal Church in the United States. And Carey has said he
hopes the global gathering he will host July 18-Aug. 9 will focus
on prayer, spirituality and unity amid diversity.
</P>
<P>
   The diversity certainly will be at Lambeth, a conference held
once every 10 years and named for Lambeth Palace in London, the
archbishop's official residence. But achieving unity among the 800
bishops attending will take some doing.
</P>
<P>
   Anglicans, like members of some other church families, are
radically divided over the practice of ordaining gays and lesbians
and conducting church ceremonies to bless the unions of same-sex
couples.
</P>
<P>
   Many American bishops have been ordaining gay and lesbian
priests and conducting same-sex-union ceremonies for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Other Episcopal bishops _ including Bishop Jack Iker of Fort
Worth, Bishop James Stanton of Dallas and several bishops from
Africa, Asia and South America _ see that as deplorable. Such
practices, they contend, violate biblical and church laws.
</P>
<P>
   Those bishops opposing gay ordinations and same-sex blessings
will be lobbying for the Lambeth Conference to support a ``Kuala
Lumpur Statement'' issued by some 80 bishops from the Southern
Hemisphere at a meeting in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, in February
1997.
</P>
<P>
   The statement called on Anglicans to adopt a clear statement
declaring unacceptable ``the endorsement of the ordination of
non-celibate homosexuals and the blessing of same-sex unions.''
Stanton and Iker helped lead a conference of more than 40 bishops
from around the world in Dallas last September that supported a
similar statement.
</P>
<P>
   No clear pronouncement on homosexuality and the church is likely
to come out of Lambeth this year. But the subject will be
discussed. And some bishops are leaning toward appointing a
commission to study the volatile issues surrounding gays and
lesbians in the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very characteristic of Anglicans to avoid an issue by
studying it to death,'' said the Rev. Sam Edwards, executive
director of a Fort Worth-based conservative group, the Episcopal
Synod of America. Edwards will be in England during Lambeth and
will have regular sessions in Canterbury with other traditionalists
from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Anglicans do have a history of moderating conflicts through
study. It happened to some degree at the Lambeth 10 years ago, when
the dispute over ordaining women _ particularly female bishops _
was raging throughout the church.
</P>
<P>
   Then-Fort Worth Bishop Clarence Pope, now retired, took a lead
role internationally in the dispute and was the founding president
of the conservative Episcopal Synod of America. He argues that
ordaining women violates biblical and church teachings.
</P>
<P>
   During the Lambeth 10 years ago, the bishops appointed the Eames
Commission, named for its chairman, Bishop Robin Eames of Ireland,
which studied ways in which bishops with differing points of view
on women's ordination could continue to work together.
</P>
<P>
   The study helped quiet the controversy but didn't solve it. Many
opposed to ordaining female priests and bishops now have left the
church.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue of female bishops has faded to the back burner,
despite the fact that some bishops _ including Fort Worth's Iker _
still object to female priests and bishops.
</P>
<P>
   Some bishops, including Bishop Noel Jones of the Church of
England, have announced they will boycott some parts of the Lambeth
Conference because for the first time, 11 female bishops _ eight
from the United States _ will attend. Some female bishops will lead
Bible studies and other gatherings. Also, Jones says he won't stand
for the Lambeth's official photograph if female bishops are posing
with him.
</P>
<P>
   Iker, the staunchly conservative Fort Worth bishop, isn't going
that far. He won't boycott any events at Lambeth _ except if he is
asked to take Communion from a woman bishop. He also won't shy away
from having his photo taken with bishops of the opposite sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have my picture taken with anybody,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
