<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9856 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECUADOR-CUP-HNS &LR;      07-10 0473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECUADOR-CUP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD CUP FINAL MAY AFFECT VOTER TURNOUT IN ECUADOR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN OTIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador _ When asked who will win Sunday, the day of this
nation's presidential runoff election, many Ecuadoreans say it's no
contest: Brazil in a blowout.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil?
</P>
<P>
   For those unfamiliar with the planet's most popular sport, it
should be explained that Sunday is also the day of the most
important game in soccer: the World Cup final.
</P>
<P>
   So many Ecuadoreans will be glued to their televisions for the
live broadcast of the match between Brazil and France that it could
affect voter turnout. According to a recent survey by the Quito
polling firm CEDATOS, 58 percent knew the date of the game being
played in the Paris suburb of Saint-Denis. But just 32 percent knew
the date of the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest soccer fans are going to stay home,'' said Cesar
Parraga, a waiter at a bar in downtown Quito.
</P>
<P>
   Shaking her head in wonder, bookseller Leonor Monge said
Ecuador's election officials ``made a big mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They should have moved the election forward a week,'' Monge
said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though their national team didn't qualify for the World
Cup, Ecuadoreans have followed every kick of the monthlong
tournament. For dyed-in-the-wool aficionados, the face-off between
presidential candidates Jamil Mahuad and Alvaro Noboa lacks the
drama of epic showdowns like Argentina vs. England or Italy vs.
France.
</P>
<P>
   Quito stores have reported a run on TV sets. Newspapers that
normally have no foreign correspondents have dispatched staffers to
France. Readers are so hungry for gossip about top players that
Vistazo, Ecuador's largest news magazine, published a cover story
about the girlfriend of Ronaldo, Brazil's superstar striker.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are much more concerned about who wins the World Cup
than who wins the presidency,'' said Nancy Cordova, director of
projects for CEDATOS.
</P>
<P>
   Voting is mandatory in Ecuador. Those who don't possess the
small card handed out on election day signifying that they voted
can be fined when they try to cash government checks or use other
state services.
</P>
<P>
   Still, about 35 percent of Ecuadoreans stayed home during the
May 31 first-round presidential vote. One possible explanation:
There were two World Cup qualifying matches played that day.
</P>
<P>
   Such apathy is partly due to a democratic overdose. The World
Cup comes along just once every four years. But due to a wave of
political instability and the ouster of Ecuador's president, the
country has had five nationwide elections in the past 26 months.
</P>
<P>
   Voters will do it all over again Sunday _ if they're not
watching the game. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
John Otis is a free-lance writer who wrote this for the Houston
Chronicle. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
