<HEADER>
A9876 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-BLUECHIPS-ART     07-10 1319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-BLUECHIPS-ART-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING WITH: LARRY PUGLIA, T. ROWE PRICE BLUE CHIP GROWTH FUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 12)  
(ART ADV: Graphics are being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By WILLIAM R. LONG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, blue-chip growth stocks have led the market ever
higher, often leaving smaller and cheaper stocks far behind. Does
that worry Larry Puglia, lead manager of the T. Rowe Price Blue
Chip Growth fund?
</P>
<P>
   Not much. ``There's always the risk that all stocks are pretty
fully valued, and we could see a pause or even a correction in the
market,'' Puglia said. ``But we take encouragement from the fact
that we think you can find reasonably valued companies in the
market today.''
</P>
<P>
   The fund does own some stocks with high valuations, including
Microsoft, which has a price-to-earnings ratio of 64.4. But, Puglia
said, ``We think that they're reasonably priced, relative to the
growth that we think they'll be generating.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the $3.1 billion portfolio, which usually has about 150
positions, maintains an average P/E ratio roughly equivalent to the
24.2 forward P/E of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index.
</P>
<P>
   ``So our view is that we've got a portfolio of companies that we
hope will perform better than the market, but we're buying it at
roughly the same price as the market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since Puglia helped start the fund in 1993, it has had an
average annual return of 25.1 percent, through July 3, according to
Morningstar Inc., the financial publisher in Chicago. That is
better than the 23.3 percent annualized return of the S&AMP;P 500 and
the 19.7 percent of the average large-capitalization blend fund,
which buys big-company stocks but is neither growth- nor
value-oriented in its investing style.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, the fund's returns have lagged modestly behind
the S&AMP;P but they are still ahead of those of its peers. This year,
Blue Chip Growth has returned 18.6 percent, through July 3, versus
19 percent for the index and 16.1 percent for the peer group.
</P>
<P>
   Puglia, 37, has been with T. Rowe Price since 1990, but his
penchant for blue chips started at a much earlier age. During his
youth in Waynesburg, Pa., he learned his first investing lessons
from his father, who owned a Buick dealership. ``He would buy good
companies and literally hold them for 15 or 20 years,'' Puglia
said.
</P>
<P>
   What makes true blue chips? He defines them as stocks that
provide ``durable, sustainable earnings-per-share growth.'' A
company that meets the standard, he said, is likely to have a
leading position in its market and seasoned, first-rate management,
and is more likely to stand up well in times of market stress.
</P>
<P>
   Identifying potential winners takes some doing. At T. Rowe
Price, the fund uses proprietary software to screen data bases for
about 15 technical characteristics, like steady earnings growth and
return on equity over one, three and five years.
</P>
<P>
   But quantitative screens are not the only source of Puglia's
ideas. ``We'll look under every stone,'' he said. He scrounges
through news reports and economic data, and meets with companies'
suppliers and competitors. Sometimes he even culls through rivals'
portfolios. ``There are plenty of other managers out there with
excellent track records,'' he said, ``and we're willing to learn
from others where possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Puglia said he calculates what he calls a company's
``self-sustaining growth rate'' with a formula: return on equity,
multiplied by one minus the payout ratio, which is the percentage
of earnings paid out in dividends. If a company has a 25 percent
return on equity and is paying out 20 percent of earnings in
dividends, for example, it has a self-sustaining growth rate of 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
   If that rate is sustainable over three to five years, it makes
for an attractive stock, Puglia said. ``And if we have good
management that we can trust, shareholder-oriented management that
is essentially a good steward of that capital, we can count on them
to either invest that capital in their highest-returning businesses
or make value-added acquisitions.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite some market skepticism, Puglia's fund is bullish on the
companies involved in recent mega-mergers, like Travelers Group,
which is merging with Citicorp. Travelers, in fact, is the top
stock in the portfolio, at 1.5 percent of its holdings. ``It is a
company with, above all, very strong management that has shown over
a period of time that they can compound earnings at above industry
average rate,'' Puglia said. ``They've generated compound annual
growth of over 20 percent for the past five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Combined, Citicorp and Travelers will be ``arguably the premier
financial services company in the world,'' he said, with access to
100 million customers in 100 countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some Travelers subsidiaries are already selling Citicorp
credit cards,'' he said. ``And that's just an example of how
they're going to aggressively cross-sell one another's products to
this big customer base that they have.''
</P>
<P>
   Blue Chip Growth bought Travelers for about $12 a share at the
fund's start in 1993, and the stock is now at $69. He predicted
that the combined entity, to be called Citigroup, will hit $90
within 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Another major position is Bristol-Myers Squibb. None of the
company's key drug patents will expire over the next few years, he
said, and the company has sold off noncore businesses facing
litigation and other problems.
</P>
<P>
   Bristol-Myers' most promising products include Pravachol, a
widely used cholesterol-lowering agent, and Avapro, a new product
for treating high blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The company has ``a very powerful position in the cardiovascular
area, which of course is a very good area because you tend to have
very high margins on the products,'' Puglia said. ``Bristol-Myers
also has the No. 1 or No. 2 anti-cancer franchise in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's main anti-cancer drug is Taxol, derived from the
Pacific yew tree. ``Taxol continues to receive new indications for
treating various forms of cancer,'' Puglia said.
</P>
<P>
   He first bought Bristol-Myers in July 1997 at about $85 a share,
then bought a lot more in August at between $73 and $77. The stock,
now at $119.5625, is valued at 28 times projected 1999 earnings of
$4.20 a share, Puglia said. ``While the stock's not cheap, it's
still valued very attractively relative to the other drug group
names.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he expects Bristol-Myers to hit at least $145 within 18
months. ``If they sell some operations and do some different
things,'' he said, ``we think it could actually be a lot bigger
upside than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Consolidation helps make USA Waste Services another of Puglia's
favorites. The company is buying Waste Management Inc., the No. 1
garbage-disposal company in the country. After the merger, USA
Waste will have more than 20 percent of the waste market
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   And before long, Puglia predicted, the market will take notice.
``People will realize trash disposal is a good business,'' he said.
``It's not affected by what happens in Asia, it's not particularly
discretionary _ people have to have their garbage picked up _ and
this company has got a proprietary position in terms of landfills
and customer base.''
</P>
<P>
   The merger will bring economies of scale and allow the company
to consolidate landfills and shut down unprofitable ones, Puglia
said. ``The management of USA Waste has shown an excellent ability
to control costs and to generate consistent earnings growth and
consistent cash flow growth,'' he said. Moreover, earnings will
probably grow at 18 to 20 percent over the next three years, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Puglia bought the stock at less than $35 a share in May 1997.
The stock is now at $52.1875, and he thinks it could hit $65 within
18 months.
</P>
</TEXT>
