<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-AURORA-FOOD-$ADV12-ART-760&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPETITE FOR NEW ISSUES MAY BE WANING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 12)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(lb) 
 By SANA SIWOLOP   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Judging from all the newly issued stocks of computer, software
and Internet-related companies, the current market for initial
public offerings looks hotter than a summer beach party.
</P>
<P>
   There are signs, however, that the overall initial-offering
market may be cooling down. To take its pulse, investors might look
at the experiences of two brand-name heavyweights _ Aurora Foods
and Seagram Co. Aurora plunged into the IPO market last month and
has seen its stock almost stand still, while Seagram evidently
decided to pull back.
</P>
<P>
   Aurora's credentials certainly looked strong. The company was
formed less than two years ago, aiming to build itself into a
grocery company with top-brand products; it has already reduced
costs at its acquired businesses by about $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Aurora has also restored some sizzle to well-known brands.
Consider Celeste frozen pizzas and Aunt Jemima's frozen breakfasts:
In the year before Aurora acquired them, Celeste's sales dropped
16.8 percent and Aunt Jemima's dropped 8.9 percent. Since then,
Celeste's annual sales have grown 8.6 percent and Aunt Jemima's by
10.5 percent, according to the prospectus.
</P>
<P>
   And more good news may be coming. Even though the food industry
is mature and most products now register only single-digit annual
sales growth, Aurora has been extremely selective about what it has
bought, said Linda Killian, an analyst at Renaissance Capital, an
IPO research firm in Greenwich, Conn. As a result, Ms. Killian said
she thought sales for the company's products were far from peaking.
</P>
<P>
   Still, investors so far seem to have shoved Aurora's stock into
the icebox. Since the company went public at $21 a share, its
shares have remained in the $21-$22.50 range and closed on Friday
at $22.
</P>
<P>
   Experts in initial offerings said two things might be
suppressing the stock. First, like those of other recent
food-company offerings, shares of Aurora have been sideswiped by
industry speculation that Seagram has grown discouraged with the
IPO market for packaged-food companies, and, as a result, is
seeking private buyers for its Tropicana juice business.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, concern has grown that Aurora's offering may have
been a bit too richly priced, given the company's heavy debt load,
a result of six acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Basham, editor of Emerging and Special Situations, a
newsletter published by Standard &AMP; Poor's, said Aurora was typical
of food companies that had sold shares to the public. The stocks
have suffered, he said, on concerns about debt.
</P>
<P>
   Reducing debt was the main reason for Aurora's public offering
in the first place. Basham, however, said Aurora's long-term debt,
even after its offering, still equaled 54 percent of the company's
capital. He said that was far above the debt level of 35 percent to
40 percent that most food companies were carrying.
</P>
<P>
   Debt is also a concern at Seagram. In order to finance its
recent purchase of Polygram NV, the Dutch music giant, Seagram had
planned to sell its Tropicana fruit-juice business to the public in
an offering of $3.5 billion to $4 billion, which would have made it
the largest domestic initial offering ever.
</P>
<P>
   Given the current market weakness for food-company offerings,
however, industry experts said it might make more sense for Seagram
to pursue a private deal, possibly with a company that already has
a strong beverage-distribution network in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seagram isn't getting the value it wants,'' Basham said.
</P>
<P>
   That may be a problem across the overall initial-offering
market. John Fitzgibbon Jr., editor of IPO Aftermarket, an industry
newsletter, said data emerged in June that suggested IPO prices
were weakening.
</P>
<P>
   Although June was still a good month for initial offerings
overall, with 57 issues raising $6.82 billion _ the highest monthly
figure so far this year _ Fitzgibbon said that only seven of those
issues were priced above their initial filing ranges. Some 24 were
reduced in size or price, or both.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Fitzgibbon said, of the 200 initial offerings
priced from January to May, 75 were priced above their filing
ranges and only 37 were priced below.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gotten to be commonplace that deals are being slashed in
price in order to get done,'' Fitzgibbon said. ``And we've also
started to see filings trickle, rather than gush in, from perhaps
15 or 20 a week to now just a handful.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said a weak market has potential for good deals.``Even
though the IPO pipeline is very large, we see people pulling back
from the table,'' he said, ``and when supply gets cut, the market
gets stronger.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   This summer, technology offerings are still scoring highest with
investors, following earlier 1998 stars like Broadcom, Micromuse,
Exodus Communications, Visual Networks and Doubleclick.
</P>
<P>
   June had its share of technology high-fliers. Inktomi Corp., a
company in San Mateo, Calif., that designs and makes software to
ease congestion on the Internet, went public on June 10 at $36 a
share. Its shares have more than doubled in price, to $76.
</P>
<P>
   Two other June standouts were Microstrategy Inc., a software
company, up 135 percent from its $12 offering price; and
Software.net Corp., an online reseller of commercial off-the-shelf
software, up 50 percent from $13.25.
</P>
<P>
   According to Fitzgibbon, of the 13 offerings this year that have
started trading at levels more than double their initial offering
prices, seven are Internet related.
</P>
<P>
   So far, most of the new Internet stocks are holding up well, but
Ms. Killian offers a note of caution. She points out that compared
with last year's offerings, more Internet-related companies in the
current IPO market have limited operating histories.
</P>
<P>
   Do investors care? Maybe not. Ms. Killian said Internet-related
offerings were raising more money, on average, than they did last
year, perhaps in the range of $10 million to $15 million more for
each.
</P>
<P>
   But Internet offerings may be in danger of getting slammed, as
they were a year ago. A study by Morgan Stanley Dean Witter at the
time found that stocks of Internet-service companies that had gone
public since August 1995 were trading at nearly 75 percent below
their offering prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a fear-and-greed cycle within the IPO market,'' Ms.
Killian said. ``A year ago we were in a fear cycle, and now we're
in a greed cycle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
