<HEADER>
A9890 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-RONALDO-     07-10 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-RONALDO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'98 THE YEAR OF RONALDO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OZOIR LA FERRIERE, France _ The Brazilians bid adieu to Stade de
Tres Sapins Friday. The 3,000-seat stadium had been filled with
blue-and-gold-attired spectators and hundreds of journalists every
afternoon since the Brazilian national team arrived 43 days ago for
the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Jacques Loyer, mayor of Ozoir La Ferriere, said he hopes to
rename the site Stade Claudio Taffarel after the goalkeeper whose
performance clinched Brazil's penalty-kicks win over the
Netherlands in the semifinals. Whether or not Loyer's proposal is
approved, this community, carved out of the fir forest of the
Parisian banlieus, will not soon forget the time the Brazilian
circus came to town.
</P>
<P>
   With Brazil on the verge of a fifth World Cup title, there was a
mad scramble among journalists, lined up along the running track
surrounding the field, for comments concerning Sunday's game
against France. Though there are enormous expectations for this
team, the Selecao seems able to hold itself outside the side-show
atmosphere, exuding calmness and confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been counting down the games,'' coach Mario Zagallo
said. ``Four games left, three, two, one. The reason I have done
this is because I have confidence in this team, in the Brazilian
heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``France is a very good team; its defense is strong. The fact
that they have gotten to the final tells you this, because it is
very difficult to get to the final of the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is not in hand for us. It is incredibly hard to win
the World Cup in Europe. But if we don't win it now, when will we
be able to?''
</P>
<P>
   Brazil is the only team to win the World Cup four times, and the
only team to win outside its hemisphere. Zagallo certainly would
like to succeed this time, since it is doubtless his last chance.
But even if the Brazilians do not win this one, it would be hard to
imagine them failing to win future World Cups, whether the site is
another continent or another planet. The inexhaustible wealth of
talent, the commitment of the country, and the incredible support
all suggest that Brazil will continue to be a major factor in World
Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, this tournament will be remembered for the
performance of Ronaldinho, the 21-year-old who has come the nearest
to matching the charisma of Pele. Zagallo, the coach who began his
World Cup career playing with Pele in 1958, will move on. Dunga,
the 34-year-old captain whose fighting spirit has lifted Brazil,
will play his last international game.
</P>
<P>
   And Ronaldo Luiz Nazario de Lima will take control, as he did in
carrying the offense against Holland. He scored in the first minute
of the second half, and nearly clinched the victory with a strong
solo effort midway through the half. He has been billed as a sort
of soccer savior, the first to be thrust blatantly onto the global
scene by modern saturation media methods, which attempt to separate
the individual from the team context.
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldinho mostly has been well-received, though he drew
criticism from the Vatican after an Italian tire company
superimposed his image on the Cristo Redentor statue overlooking
Rio de Janeiro. Savior, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Pele and Argentina's Diego Maradona, whose images evolved
more subtly, through an appreciation of their talents, Ronaldinho's
popularity has been generated by the mass marketing machinations of
multinationals.
</P>
<P>
   But even without that campaign, Ronaldinho's phenomenal bursts
of speed and ability to deliver in key situations would be
capturing imaginations of even the world's most destitute spots.
After the game against the Dutch, an Albanian village reported that
15 children born that day were baptized ``Ronaldo.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it is impossible to separate the down-home, almost naive
nature of Ronaldinho from the enormous money-spinning operation
that surrounds him. He spent Friday's training session mostly
jogging slowly, separated from the scrimmage, resting his legs,
which have been insured for $52 million for this tournament alone.
</P>
<P>
   The previous day, Ronaldinho had been allowed to leave Brazil's
castle-hotel in Lesigny, where the Confederacao Brasileira de
Futbol is paying $1 million for the team to stay. He went to nearby
Pontault Combault, where his mother, Sonia, prepared a home-cooked
meal of fejoada. Sonia has brought the flavor of Rio to France,
along with the family _ Nelio Jr., who is attending school in the
United States; nephews and nieces; Susana ``Ronaldinha'' Werner;
and their dog, Sharon.
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldinho has been rejuvenated at this home-away-from-home when
the team returned from trips to Marseille and Nantes. He plays his
lucky drums, one autographed by a samba group, the other by James
Brown, which ``give rhythm to the game and life.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, he receives the sustenance that fame and sponsorship money
cannot provide.
</P>
<P>
   The Nazario de Limas' youngest son was born in 1976, two years
after Brazil last failed to repeat as World Cup champions. By then,
Brazilians fully expected their team to succeed every time, an
unrealistic ambition that concluded with a bad-tempered defeat to
the Dutch at Germany '74.
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldinho was just another (itals)menino do rua,(unitals) a
street urchin, who might or might not survive the turbulence of the
big city. He demonstrated enough talent to try out for Flamengo,
but not enough for the country's biggest club to pay for his bus
fare.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Ronaldo was 17, though, he had found success as a
prolific scorer at Cruzeiro in Minas Gerais. European clubs became
interested, and PSV Eindhoven bought him for $5 million. Ronaldinho
was being regarded as the new Pele, but at USA '94 he remained on
the bench as Brazil won the World Cup for the first time since
1970.
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldinho was a young, gap-toothed striker whose personality
was submerged by that veteran, high-profile Brazilian team.
</P>
<P>
   Things have changed greatly since. Ronaldinho moved on to
Barcelona in Spain, scored dozens of exciting goals, somewhat
devalued since he has joined Italy's Serie A with Internazionale.
In Italy, he has been revered by everyone except opposing
defenders, who have hacked and double-teamed him to distraction. He
has not had as much of a highlight show career in Serie A, but the
rough tests have helped forge Ronaldinho's character.
</P>
<P>
   He has been subjected to similar attention in the World Cup,
expending abnormal amounts of energy to function on a Brazil team
that is still developing. But when Brazil has needed Ronaldinho, he
has been its most resourceful and threatening offensive weapon.
</P>
<P>
   And, should Brazil win this tournament, there will be no end to
what might be named after Ronaldo Luiz Nazario de Lima.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
