The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News service for Saturday, July 11. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
BULLS _ Former Phoenix fireman Ron Beier still vividly remembers
the big red bull charging and hooking his thigh with a horn when he
was running with the bulls in Pomplona, Spain. But Beier and many
of his friends will be getting their adrenaline rush for the first
time in the United States on Saturday in the Running of the Bulls
in Mesquite, Nev. Between 400 and 600 people have coughed up $50
apiece to run a quarter mile route with a dozen bulls from a Utah
ranch. The run will be held on an Arizona ranch on the Nevada
border because the Nevada Department of Transportation wouldn't
give permission to have it on Mesquite's main street. This event
finally found a home after running into problems with the city
councils from Phoenix and Long Beach. By MARK SHAFFER. Story will
move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
HMO APPEAL _ New appeal rights for HMO clients go into effect this
month. With HMO. By JODIE SNYDER. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
HMO _ Citizens groups join for regulation of HMO's but complain
that the health and insurance industry's $1 million in campaign
contributions to lawmakers and the governor have closed the door to
them. Includes top money recipients and rebuttal from lawmakers and
HMO spokeswoman. By MIKE MCCLOY. Story will move int he ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
INCOMEGAP (Undated) - The gap between rich and poor Arizonans is
widening, says a new study that gives the state generally low marks
for economic success. By RUSS WILES. Story will move in the ``F''
category.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
LEIBOWITZ-COLUMN _ Now comes the Whiny Killer, Arizona's newest
criminal celebrity. Wednesday, he makes the ``Republic's'' front
page. Later that day, Douglas Alan Smith calls a press conference
from jail and makes the airwaves anew. Three years ago, the Whiny
Killer took the life of a father of four. Now Smith needs some
help. He has developed this burning desire to die. He wants a judge
to order the state to lend a hand with his suicide. By DAVID
LEIBOWITZ. Story will move in the ``K'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
WALKER-COLUMN (Phoenix) - Preview of PBS special about the Berlin
airlift, featuring interviews with Arizonans who served in it. By
DAVE WALKER. Story will move in ``E'` category. EMBARGOED FOR
SUNDAY JULY 12. &QL; 
 &QL; 
AUTO-REVIEW (Undated) - The two stretch-cab Toyota Tacoma pickup
trucks looked pretty much identical: jacked up, huge tires on
modular wheels and the initials TRD written large on the sides of
their pickup boxes. TRD stands for Toyota Racing Development. Upon
closer inspection, the difference between the two trucks is
glaring. One has a rugged four-wheel-drive system for serious
off-road work, complete with low-range gearing, that gives it the
capabilities of a mountain goat. The other truck doesn't. Called
the PreRunner, it's just a two-wheel-drive, despite its rugged
off-road styling and attitude. But before you write it off as a
mere poser, the two-wheel-drive model does have distinct
attributes. By BOB GOLFEN. Story will move in the ``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
