<HEADLINE>
DOCUMENTARY EXPLORES ALLIES' BERLIN AIRLIFT  
 (EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY JULY 12) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVE WALKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - The first battle of the Cold War was a humanitarian
mission, an air bridge into Berlin from Allied-controlled sectors
of a subdivided Germany.
</P>
<P>
   During the Berlin Airlift, which ran from June 1948 to May 1949,
2.5 million tons of lifesaving supplies were flown into the
devastated German capitol by American and British transport planes.
A total of 277,000 flights were made under always difficult and
often dangerous conditions. Ground crews changed 60,000 sparkplugs
a month to keep the airborne conveyor belt operating.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday evening, PBS celebrates the 50th anniversary of the
airlift with a one-hour documentary, ``The Berlin Airlift.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to get an airplane in every three minutes,'' said
Earl Kielgass, then an airlift pilot, now a Tempe, Ariz., resident.
``We would've liked to get one in every minute, but couldn't do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Stalin sparked the airlift by blockading all ground
routes into Berlin, which was surrounded by Russia's piece of
Germany. For nearly a year, all of the food and fuel to sustain the
city's more than 2 million residents came in via air corridors.
</P>
<P>
   Berlin had largely been reduced to rubble during World War II,
and was beginning its agonizing recovery from being ``a city of the
dead,'' as it's described by one observer in the PBS special.
</P>
<P>
   Stalin's attempt to starve Berlin was his way of turning its
residents into communists. The airlift foiled his plans, as planes
often flew three round-trip missions a day, stopping only long
enough at each end to load supplies on and off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really strenuous flying,'' said Kenneth Herman, now a
Goodyear, Ariz., resident, then a pilot. ``You had to maintain a
precise air speed, a precise altitude and stay in the corridors so
the Russians wouldn't shoot you down.'' While Stalin allowed the
Allied air-relief effort, he didn't want it to be easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the problems was navigating up there,'' Kielgass said.
``The Russians could jam your radio beacon, and you'd get
off-course. The Russian aircraft were flying around you, and they
could harass you. In the clouds, you really couldn't see their
airplanes, but their locations were called in to us by radio. All
you could do was grit your teeth and keep going. They were just an
annoyance.''
</P>
<P>
   The cargo had to get through. It doesn't sound very dashing or
romantic a half-century removed from the event, but coal was the
chief cargo carried by Herman and Kielgass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally our squadrons carried coal,'' Kielgass said. ``Coal
and flour, mostly. Berliners didn't have any electricity. They had
to have coal to generate power and heat during the winter months.
It was very critical.''
</P>
<P>
   Herman, who eventually flew 190 airlift missions, was a
transport pilot and training specialist during the war, but many of
the airlift pilots had directly contributed to Germany's
devastation. Kielgass, who flew a fighter bomber over Germany in
the war, said few of his fellow pilots saw any contradiction in the
mission.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most moving elements of the PBS special is the story
of Gail Halvorsen, who dropped candy to German kids using
handkerchiefs as parachutes. (The ``Candy Bomber,'' as he came to
be known, also toted along a home-movie camera for many of his
flights. His silent color footage _ as well as the can-do spirit it
captures _ warms the otherwise chilly special, which is built from
black-and-white newsreel and military footage.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of Berlin were decimated during World War II,''
Herman said. ``There was very little food. They were literally
starving.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't trying to kill people during the war. We were
trying to stop the oppressive Nazi government. Many, many German
people were against the Nazi government. I was a little prejudiced.
My grandparents had come from Germany, and here I was back in the
land of my forefathers, flying into Berlin several times a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Herman, president of the Berlin Airlift Veterans Association,
has returned to Berlin several times. Particularly since the fall
of Communism, he said, the rebuilt city has proved that the airlift
was well worth the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Berlin is a beautiful city, with open spaces and parks,'' he
said. ``It's fast becoming the cultural and economic and political
center of Europe, if not the entire world.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were to live anywhere else in the world, rather than Rome
or Paris, I'd pick Berlin.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
