<HEADLINE>
CABLE OFFERS IT ALL, FROM PETS TO VETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The ability to run the gamut from profound to
absurd, often in a heartbeat, is TV's blessing.
</P>
<P>
   And its curse.
</P>
<P>
   This was plainly evident Friday in Pasadena, as The Learning
Channel gave TV critics a taste of ``Vietnam: The Soldiers'
Story,'' a six-hour, first-person documentary, while Animal Planet
announced a new fall series called ``Judge Wapner's Animal Court,''
featuring people and their pets in real disagreements over
``grooming disasters'' and ``paternity disputes.''
</P>
<P>
   I haven't seen a clip of ``Judge Wapner's Animal Court,'' so I
can only judge the idea itself as absurd. But having seen a
five-minute sampling of ``Vietnam: The Soldier's Story,'' I can't
wait to view the remaining five hours and 55 minutes Oct. 11-13.
</P>
<P>
   The special is hosted and narrated by Vietnam veteran Jack
Smith, an ABC News correspondent and the son of TV news pioneer
Howard K. Smith. As a young soldier, Smith was wounded during the
battle of the Ia Drang Valley in 1965. Covered in blood, he was
used as a human sandbag by a North Vietnamese machine gunner who
presumed him dead.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Smith was at the Berlin Wall for the fall of
communism in 1989, an event that he says brought his Vietnam
experience ``full circle.'' But he has no doubt that the United
States waged a futile war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't put your sons in harm's way,'' he said, ``unless you
intend to win the war.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX) Former ``Melrose Place''-holder Brooke Langton stars in
USA Network's serialization of the Sandra Bullock movie, ``The
Net,'' which premieres next Sunday at 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Playing a computer expert whose life has been turned upside down
by cyber-terrorists, Langton said she's reasonably comfortable on
the Internet, but far from expert.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've searched (the Web) for things when my animals have gotten
sick,'' she said, ``or for something really bizarre that no one's
awake at 2 a.m. to talk to you about.''
</P>
<P>
   After its Sunday premiere, ``The Net'' will team with ``Sins of
the City,'' a new detective show set in Miami, as part of USA's
Saturday lineup.
</P>
<P>
   _ So you think Rupert Murdoch has shaken up the L.A. Dodgers?
Just wait till Aug. 15, when Murdoch's Fox empire puts its stamp on
the Family Channel. Only Pat Robertson's ``700 Club'' will survive
from the old lineup when the new Fox Family Channel debuts.
(Robertson, who sold the channel to Fox and Saban Entertainment for
$1.9 billion last year, insisted that his ``700 Club'' stay.)
</P>
<P>
   But no more ``Hawaii Five-O,'' no more ``Home &AMP; Family.''
Instead, look for a lot of recycled children's programming in the
daytime, including ``Pee-wee's Playhouse'' and ``Shining Time
Station,'' along with Fox Kids shows like ``Goosebumps'' and
``Bobby's World.'' In the evening, expect reality shows, more
adult-targeted comedies and movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most TV is not safe for family viewing,'' said president Rich
Cronin, new president of the Fox Family Channel. ``We have an
opportunity to expand on the current audience by creating a network
that the whole family will watch together, a network that
entertains contemporary families with a Fox attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Wonder if the Dodgers will be watching.
</P>
<P>
   John Levesque is the P-I's television critic. Call him at
206-448-8330 or send e-mail to: tvguy(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
