<HEADLINE>
MOTORISTS IN THE DRIVER'S SEAT IN GUBERNATORIAL RACES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When it comes to campaign issues, Massachusetts
motorists are suddenly in the driver's seat.
</P>
<P>
   First state Treasurer Joseph D. Malone, a Republican
gubernatorial candidate, proposed doing away with the 2.5 percent
excise tax that automobile owners pay each year.
</P>
<P>
   Then US Representative Brian Donnelly weighed in with a plan to
shake up the state's insurance system to give good drivers lower
rates.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, former state Senator Patricia McGovern offered a
plan to eliminate the dreaded Registry of Motor Vehicles, and
instead let car owners register at local town halls.
</P>
<P>
   Acting Governor Paul Cellucci quickly hitchhiked a ride on that
proposal, endorsing it as a topnotch idea. Indeed, Cellucci was so
worried about political road rage that for weeks he refused to take
a position on a (now defunct) ballot question to eliminate turnpike
tolls _ even though his own Turnpike Authority needs that revenue
for its Big Dig contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the days when, say, Frank Sargent, a Republican
governor, nixed plans for an inner belt around Boston. Or when
Michael Dukakis, a Democratic governor, set a civic example by
taking the Green Line to work and campaigned against a third harbor
tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   With gasoline barely a buck a gallon, sports-utility vehicles a
second home for Yuppies, and road trips a form of recreation, auto
issues seem to be where the rubber meets the road.
</P>
<P>
   One reason, suggests Democratic political consultant Mary Anne
Marsh, is the prominence those issues played last year in
gubernatorial races in New Jersey and Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, where drivers pay the nation's highest insurance
rates, Governor Christine Todd Whitman almost lost the election to
an obscure state senator who campaigned principally on insurance
costs.
</P>
<P>
   In the Virginia election, Republican James S. Gilmore 3rd's
campaign-trail proposal to slash the state's car tax is credited
with helping the GOP sweep the state's three statewide offices.
</P>
<P>
   This year, those successes have spawned similar efforts across
the country. In California, for example, Governor Wilson has
proposed cutting the car license fee; in Georgia, Republican
gubernatorial candidate Guy Millner wants to do away with the car
tax; in New York, Democratic gubernatorial hopeful Betsy McCaughey
Ross has put forth a plan to slash insurance rates.
</P>
<P>
   Those campaigns have demonstrated that auto issues are the
pocketbook matters of the late 1990s, says Marsh.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you take tolls and auto insurance rates and excise taxes,
it all adds up to more money out of people's pockets than is
returned by the tax cuts they are talking about,'' said Marsh.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that a widespread loathing of Registry lines, and it
helps explain why automobile issues have taken a front seat this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Of the various plans, Malone's is the most dramatic fiscally;
his auto excise tax cut would save car owners a total of $380
million when fully phased-in after three years. (Under Malone's
plan, the state would replace the revenues lost by cities and town,
who currently get the tax revenue.)
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a deep-seated anger about that tax,'' says Malone
spokesman Eric Fehrnstrom. ``You pay a sales tax when you buy the
car, you pay a fuel tax when you gas it up, you pay tolls when you
drive the car, and then on top of that, the government charges you
an excise tax just because the car is sitting in your driveway.
People understand the inherent unfairness of that.''
</P>
<P>
   McGovern is just as surely banking on the simmering frustration
most every driver has experienced while negotiating Registry lines.
Announcing her plan, she asked: ``How many times have we stood in
line at the Registry and said to ourselves, `There has to be a
better way?' ''
</P>
<P>
   But over at the Conservation Law Foundation, transportation
expert Stephen Burrington looks longingly to Portland, Ore., where
voters in 1996 elected Earl Blumenauer to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   A former city and county official, Blumenauer pushed many of the
policies -- light rail, ride-sharing, bike paths, bike racks on
buses -- that have given Portland its reputation as a distinctly
livable and different city.
</P>
<P>
   Burrington argues that political candidates elsewhere have
overlooked the power of those quality-of-life issues as they have
courted car owners. Matters like traffic calming and improved mass
transit could find receptive audiences, if only they had candidates
to champion them, Burrington claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a swelling of public interest in the livability
issues,'' Burrington said. ``There are some real sleeper issues
that people running for office would do well to seize on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
