A9912 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECUADOR-ELECTION-HNS &LR;      07-10 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECUADOR-ELECTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTERS `OPTIMISTIC' PRESIDENTIAL WINNER WILL RESTORE STABILITY TO
ECUADOR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN OTIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador _ Few tears will be shed when Ecuador's president
steps down next month. Fabian Alarcon is so despised that a recent
newspaper cartoon depicted hecklers pelting the interim head of
state with garbage.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate for a dynamic leader after two years of political,
economic and natural disasters, Ecuadoreans will head to the polls
Sunday for a presidential runoff election.
</P>
<P>
   They will choose between Quito Mayor Jamil Mahuad, a
Harvard-trained technocrat, and business magnate Alvaro Noboa,
often described as the richest man in Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   Mahuad topped Noboa in a May 31 first-round vote but failed to
receive more than 50 percent of the ballots, forcing Sunday's
runoff. Mahuad had a double-digit lead over Noboa in several recent
polls.
</P>
<P>
   The winner will begin a four-year term Aug. 10 and attempt to
restore a measure of stability to this battered South American
nation of 12 million people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very optimistic,'' said Faisel Baki, an investment banker
in Quito, the capital city. ``The new government is going to change
things. Either Mahuad or Noboa will bring new projects forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Any semblance of progress has been stalled during the past two
years due, in part, to the revolving door at the presidential
palace.
</P>
<P>
   Abdala Bucaram, an eccentric populist elected in 1996, was
ousted after six months by the Ecuadorean Congress for ``mental
incapacity.'' After a brief power struggle _ at one point, three
politicians claimed to be president _ Bucaram was replaced by
Alarcon.
</P>
<P>
   High hopes for the interim government quickly turned to disgust,
when Alarcon became ensnared in a series of corruption scandals.
</P>
<P>
   He has been accused of authorizing at least 1,000 no-show jobs
while he was president of the Congress. He also has been linked to
a scam involving the resale of clothes donated to victims of
Pacific coast flooding caused by the El Nino weather pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the country's economy has gone into a tailspin.
Falling prices for oil _ the pillar of Ecuador's economy _ $1.5
billion in flood damage and capital flight by nervous investors
have led to a fiscal deficit that could reach 5 percent of the
gross domestic product by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   An infusion of foreign cash could have offset some of the
problems, but the erratic policies have discouraged foreign
investment. For example, when the government tried to privatize 35
percent of EMETEL, the state telephone company, it received two
rounds of bids, then scrapped the process with no explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Ecuador could also be earning more petro-dollars. The
300-mile-long SOTE pipeline is too small to transport daily output
from oil wells in the Amazon jungle to the Pacific coast. Foreign
firms made several offers to upgrade the pipeline, but Alarcon
balked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has simply been incompetent,'' Baki said.
``There is no other word for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some say a more accurate word is ``corrupt.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. firms such as Proctor &AMP; Gamble, United Parcel Service and
Colgate-Palmolive have been brought to court in what many say were
frivolous lawsuits. Other companies say they have been pressured to
pay bribes. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Foreign executives complain that contracts in Ecuador are about
as reliable as ``wet paper,'' said U.S. Ambassador Leslie
Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is Ecuador's biggest trading partner. But when
American executives stop by the U.S. Embassy, they often receive
blunt advice: Stay out until the next president is sworn in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be open and honest about the risks of operating in
one of the most difficult investment climates in Latin America,''
said a U.S. official.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, trade between the two nations has dropped by
50 percent, according to Robert Moss, president of the
Ecuadorean-American Chamber of Commerce. One breakthrough, however,
was Ecuador's approval of a bilateral intellectual property rights
treaty designed to protect U.S. firms and trademarks.
</P>
<P>
   The next government is expected to negotiate an agreement with
the International Monetary Fund on a reform program. Analysts say
that under either a Mahuad or Noboa government, Ecuadoreans can
expect austerity measures, such as the elimination of subsidies for
cooking gas and a sales tax increase, to help resolve the fiscal
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   If responsible measures are adopted, some observers predict, the
economic outlook could improve dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   Mahuad, 48, received a master's degree in public administration
from Harvard University and has been a successful, two-term mayor
of Quito. He has a respected team of economic advisers and is
well-regarded by the nation's business community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mahuad would be ideal,'' said Fabian Corral, a corporate
lawyer who represents foreign firms.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Noboa, 47, is a political neophyte. He has been
hurt by his close ties to the disgraced Bucaram, who lives in
self-imposed exile in Panama and has been accused by Ecuador's
Supreme Court of stealing $88 million during his six months in
office.
</P>
<P>
   Noboa was endorsed by Bucaram's Roldosista Party. From Panama,
the former president has played a high-profile role in the
campaign. Mahuad once claimed that Noboa had ``sold his soul to
Bucaram.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Noboa, who is from the port city of Guayaquil, has wide
support along the Pacific coast, where voters often complain that
they are neglected by Quito-based politicians such as Mahuad.
</P>
<P>
   And as one of the heirs to his late father's banana empire,
Noboa has impressed voters with his corporate connections. He
promises to create 1 million jobs, build 200,000 homes and attract
billions of dollars in investment through his ties to Wall Street
bankers and business people.
</P>
<P>
   ``His basic strength is the image that he can bring foreign
investment to the country,'' Baki said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
John Otis is a free-lance journalist who wrote this for the Houston
Chronicle. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
