u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOLS-DISNEY-HNS &LR;      07-10 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-DISNEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS SCHOOL BOARD OBJECTS TO DISNEY MOVIES, DUMPS $43M IN STOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA TOLLEY  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Walt Disney Co. may be home to beloved
children's characters such as Mickey Mouse, Goofy and Donald Duck,
but the Texas Board of Education decided Friday it isn't a suitable
place to invest money because a subsidiary produces films
containing sex and violence.
</P>
<P>
   With eight Republicans voting to divest and four Democrats
voting against, the board ordered $43 million in Disney stock sold
from the $17.7 billion Permanent School Fund. Interest from the
fund helps defray the cost of public education in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The American Family Association of Texas, which is involved in a
national boycott against Disney because the company offers benefits
to domestic partners of employees, praised the move.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents, noting that the school fund also has investments
in companies involved in alcohol, gambling and defense contracting,
denounced the vote as hypocritical.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great news,'' said Wyatt Roberts, chairman of the Texas
AFA. ``In my view, I think that Disney is the corporate equivalent
of Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde. They do some good things but they also
do some very, very bad things. I think it's time someone held them
accountable, and I think that's what the vote today represents.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas AFA sent a videotape to board members that contained
excerpts from such movies as ``Pulp Fiction'' and ``Chasing Amy,''
all films made by Miramax, a Disney subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Wyatt said state taxpayers shouldn't have to subsidize films
that ``corrupt and damaged our children.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barbara Rush of the Texas Freedom Network, a nonpartisan
group formed to counter social conservatives on such issues, said
elected officials in Texas shouldn't be bowing ``to the political
pressures of a right-wing special interest group.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The board has chosen to put politics in front of our
children's interests in its divestiture of Disney stock,'' Rush
said.
</P>
<P>
   Claudia Peters, a Disney spokeswoman in Orlando, Fla., said the
company did not comment on ``individual investment strategies.''
But she also said the vote would change the film-making decisions
at Miramax.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Walt Disney Company produces more family entertainment
than any other entertainment company in the world, and any products
are marked with the Disney brand name are suitable for all ages,''
she said, adding that Disney subsidiaries that produce films for
``mature'' audiences are set up under other names and adhere to
ratings system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Furthermore, Miramax is a highly acclaimed film label that has
received 110 nominations and 30 Academy Awards over the last 10
years,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Several board members, supporters and opponents, talked about
the issue before the vote was taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of issues that people could get uptight
about,'' said board member Will Davis, a Democrat from Austin.
``We're going down a very slippery slope.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis and others said the Disney stock had been a good
investment. The school fund's internal portfolio has realized a 108
percent return on the Disney stock that was purchased two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   But David Bradley of Beaumont and Richard Neill of Fort Worth,
both Republicans, cited concerns about recent losses in the stock
as a reason for divestiture.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Offutt, a Republican board member from San Antonio who
spearheaded the effort to divest, said he had concerns about the
future profitability of Disney stock. But he added he was
responding to complaints about Miramax films.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an elected official, when I hear substantial numbers of my
constituents have concerns, I need to be responsive to those
concerns,'' Offutt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have concerns that we have state money invested in things
that citizens of this state object to. If Miramax wants to make
`Pulp Fiction II,' I have no problem with that, they can go for it
and try and make some money. But I don't have to invest taxpayer
dollars in a corporation that may be producing movies that many
citizens find objectionable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But member Alma Allen, a Democrat from Houston, called the vote
to divest ``political hypocrisy'' because the school fund also has
investments in companies involved in alcohol and gambling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not be voting to divest,'' Allen said. ``And in fact,
two weeks from today, I will be at Disneyland where my
grandchildren want to go, and I'm going to take all five of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney stock closed up $1.12 on in trading Friday, to $38.12.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
