<SLUG> BC-ANDREA-DORIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDREA DORIA DANGEROUS LURE TO ADVENTURESOME DIVERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Mich.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOODS HOLE, Mass. _ Even as his rescuers carried him from the
crippled and dying ship 42 years ago, Vincenzno Torre saw a
terrible truth in the elegant vessel just before it slipped beneath
the waves and into its 235-foot deep grave.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Andrea Doria,'' said Torre, 65, his voice still fully
flavored with the accent of his native Italy, ``she's beautiful,
but dangerous.'' &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   That appellation is as apt today as it was when the the Italian
ocean liner collided with the Swedish-American Stockholm off
Nantucket in July 1956. The tragedy killed 52 people then, and the
majestic liner's wreck is still claiming lives today.
</P>
<P>
   Two have been killed in the past three weeks in accidents that
diving specialists predict will hardly diminish the attraction of
what scuba enthusiasts consider the water world's most alluring
inverted pinnacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't call it the Mount Everest of diving for nothing,''
said Douglas J. Costa, 27, of Plymouth, who made four dives on the
Andrea Doria last summer. ``It's a beautiful wreck if you know what
you're doing. The depth is pretty much twice the recreational
limit. The currents can be so strong that you feel like a flag on a
flagpole. But it's so well preserved and so big that you could
drive a truck through some of its rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's all sorts of things that could go wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   For Richard Roost, 46, of Ann Arbor, Mich., the pull of the
Andrea Doria was irresistible. Friends said Roost had wanted to
descend to the wreck site for some time. He was among a group of
divers who last week chartered The Seeker, a 60-foot commercial
diving boat out of Montauk, Long Island. He jumped into the seas
above the wreck site about noon last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, his diving associates found him dead in the
first-class bar lounge of what four decades ago was a $30 million,
697-foot, 11 story luxury liner that was en route from Genoa to New
York City with more than 1,600 people aboard. It was struck by the
smaller Stockholm 45 miles south of Nantucket.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard called Roost's accident ``another tragic example
of the dangers'' of recreational deep-water diving. ``It's not in
our territorial waters, and people are going to take whatever risks
they're going to take,'' said Coast Guard Petty Officer Steve
Carleton. ``This is a popular wreck.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it's increasingly popular said diving authorities, who
call it one of the deepest, murkiest, most risky goals of the sport
diver on the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   In an era of improved training and equipment and a rekindled
fascination with the sinking of the Titanic _ far out of reach for
SCUBA divers _ the Andrea Doria has become a must-see stop for
those who consider themselves expert guides along the Atlantic
Ocean's adventuresome underwater tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``The allure of shipwrecks has been there over the millennia,''
said Doug Maier, 47, a high school health teacher, who plans to
make his first dive on the Andrea Doria late this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have a huge fascination for these things,'' said Maier,
who has been diving for about 10 years. ``It's like walking back
through a portal of history. It's going to seem huge. It's going to
seem like a sunken city, and it'll extend much further than I'll be
able to see. The enormity of it is going to take my breath away.''
</P>
<P>
   The trip from the docks in Plymouth to the Andrea Doria wreck
site takes 10 hours in good seas, but for careful, experienced
divers, the voyage is at least a five-year journey in which skills
are polished in scores of incrementally more difficult dives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I discourage people who don't have at least six years of
experience from doing this,'' said Paul Adler, owner of East Coast
Divers, a retail dive store in Framingham and a member of the
Quincy Underwater Recovery Dive Team. ``They should have between
150 and 200 dives under their belt before they attempt something
like diving on the Andrea Doria, and that's a lot of dives.''
</P>
<P>
   The margin for error is critically slender.
</P>
<P>
   Divers use gallows humor in joking about the number of times
``death'' appears on the release forms charter companies make them
sign before they descend to the wreck _ having paid an average $700
to $1,000 in charter fees. Between the end of June and the middle
of August, as many as 20 to 30 divers at a time may be found swim
ming in the sunken ship and around its debris field that is a
magnet to artifact collectors.
</P>
<P>
   Once in the water, some divers proceed along a nylon rope line
that guides them in and out of the wreck, which lies on its side
and has been described as resembling a husked-out watermelon. The
current can be strong. The water is cold. And the visibility varies
greatly.
</P>
<P>
   At 200 feet, divers have only about 20 minutes before they must
start a time-consuming series of stops as they return to the
surface so they can prevent the bends, the formation of lethal gas
bubbles in their blood. Divers commonly descend and ascend along
the anchor line of the charter boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you run into a difficult situation, it's harder to get out
of it because your judgment and physical coordination may be
impaired,'' said Adler. ``If you get entangled in something, it
would be simple to untangle yourself in 30 or 40 feet, but it might
be very difficult at 200 feet because the oxygen can become toxic
at 217 feet. It's almost like playing Russian Roulette at that
depth.''
</P>
<P>
   Even experienced divers like Roost can get into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   R. Todd Smith, 37, of Middleborough, a 17-year diving veteran,
said he attended an instructor training program with Roost in Santa
Ana, Calif., in 1988, and considered him a skilled diver.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may have been diving alone, which in my mind is a really
bad idea,'' Smith said. ``Like climbing Mount Everest, you do this
with other people. No matter how good you are, you can't plan for
every contingency.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Divers Alert Network (DAN), a non-profit divers
support organization at Duke University, the number of diving
accidents and fatalities generally has declined in the past few
years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the most recent year for which statistics are
available, there were 483 diving injuries and 85 diving-related
deaths among recreational divers and technical divers in the US and
Canada. In 1995, there were 590 injuries and 104 deaths, according
to the DAN annual report. Preliminary numbers for 1997, a DAN
spokeswoman said, are down again.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most famous explorer of the Andrea Doria wreckage
was Peter Gimbel, the department store heir whose underwater
pictures, taken the day after the ship sank, were published in Life
magazine, and then in publications around the world. Over the next
three decades, Gimbel made hundreds of dives to the wreckage while
producing two acclaimed documentary films about it.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, after investing more than $2 million in his searches,
he brought up a Bank of Italy safe from the wreckage. Gimbel almost
died of oxygen poisoning during his first 1981 dive _ he was
brought up unconscious, but recovered _ and claimed the wreckage
had ``a malevolent spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   But that forboding spirit is no discouragement to divers like
Greg Dawe, 38, of Beverly, an advanced scuba diving instructor who
was scheduled to depart for the Andrea Doria wreck site Friday
night and to be diving on it Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of my friends are divers,'' he said. ``This is one of the
things that we do every summer. Some people go to Maine for a
camping trip, we go to the Andrea Doria. It's a social experience.
It's a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel like a gnat on the back of an elephant when you're
down there. It's so big. It's like diving on the inside of
somebody's mansion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 1925EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
