<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9919 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NANCY-DREW-895(2TAKES     07-10 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NANCY-DREW-895(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECRET OF THE ETERNALLY YOUNG SLEUTHS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Iowa)   (Ideas)  
(lb) 
 By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After nearly seventy years, Nancy Drew is still going out with
Ned Nickerson, and Joe Hardy is still dating his friend Chet's
sister, Iola. There are certain things about the Nancy Drew and
Hardy Boys series that never change. Yet these wildly popular
teen-age detective novels _ since they began in 1927, about 200
million volumes have been sold _ have nonetheless been seen to
reflect historical changes.
</P>
<P>
   The figure of the eternally competent Nancy has been a magnet
for scholars who read into the Nancy Drew books the trajectory of
American womanhood throughout the course of the century.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, there was a scholarly conference on her, followed by a
book, ``Rediscovering Nancy Drew,'' edited by Carolyn Stewart Dyer
and Nancy Tillman Romalov (University of Iowa Press, 1995). She was
even the subject of a book by novelist Bobbie Ann Mason, ``The Girl
Sleuth'' (University of Georgia Press, 1995).
</P>
<P>
   The latest addition to this scholarly obsession is ``The
Mysterious Case of Nancy Drew and the Hardy Boys,'' due out in
October. Based partly on newly available papers of the Stratemeyer
Syndicate, the books' original publishers, at the New York Public
Library, Carol Kismaric and Marvin Heiferman have traced the
evolution of both series from the '30s to the present.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have tried to understand why these icons of popular culture
have had such an emotional pull on people,'' said Ms. Kismaric.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, Frank and Joe Hardy have attracted less scholarly
notice than Nancy Drew, though they have received avid attention
from collectors.
</P>
<P>
   One California collector, Tony Carpentieri, has scanned every
Hardy Boy book up to the late '70s into a computer. He has counted
the words, and the number of times each character is mentioned. He
has tabulated how often Joe is hit on the head and how many times
the boys' mother says, ``I'm worried about you.''
</P>
<P>
   Carpentieri published the results of his research in ``Hardy &AMP;
Hardy, Investigations.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nancy Drew and Hardy Boys books were begun in 1927 by Edward
Stratemeyer, the son of German immigrants who loved the Oliver
Optic boy adventure series. Adolescents had only recently begun to
emerge as a distinct group occupying a place somewhere between
childhood and adulthood. The transcontinental railroad facilitated
the distribution of books, and a new market had emerged for series
books, shipped weekly to teen-agers hungry for adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Stratemeyer conceived of a series based on the adventures of two
intrepid boy detectives, Frank and Joe Hardy. The books were
written under Stratemeyer's direction by Leslie McFarlane, who used
the pseudonym Franklin W. Dixon. Other authors also wrote the
books, but they were always under the Dixon name.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, Stratemeyer established rules. No serious
violence: A character could be knocked unconscious only once in
every book. Each chapter must end with a cliffhanger. There were
girls, but no ``mushy stuff,'' as the contemporary editor of the
series at Simon &AMP; Schuster, Anne Greenberg, put it.
</P>
<P>
   The boys grew up in the mythical city of Bayport, drove cars,
flew planes. They embodied ``the ideals of masculinity,'' Heiferman
and Ms. Kismaric write. ``They always solve problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Their friend Phil Cohen was a ``diminutive, black-haired Jewish
boy.'' Phil was nerdy and never had a girlfriend. Blacks were
usually characterized as slow-witted or were servants. And the boys
had a ``pale, nervous, tight-lipped'' mother who hovered in the
background.
</P>
<P>
   Three years after the Hardy Boys came the Nancy Drew books,
originally written by Mildred Wirt Benson under the pseudonym
Carolyn Keene. Nancy was more upper-class than the Hardys, spent
less time outdoors, and encountered less bad weather. She had fewer
ethnic friends.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy's color was blue. She had blue eyes, drove a blue
roadster, dressed in blue. The color blue, in the eyes of Heiferman
and Ms. Kismaric, is a coded reference to class, Nancy's
blue-bloodedness.
</P>
<P>
   She too had a condescending attitude toward other ethnic groups.
Like most fairy-tale heroines, she lived in a dream world with no
mother to nag her, no homework, no chores. She had her tall, dark,
handsome father, Carson Drew, all to herself. Ms. Kismaric and
Heiferman note that they had a somewhat erotically charged
relationship, with Nancy running her fingers lovingly through her
father's hair.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning, Nancy broke stereotypes. She was a reflection
of the women of the modern era, who had got the vote, drank in
public and were beginning to drive. ``The crucial thing was that
she was mobile,'' said Ms. Kismaric. Though Nancy liked Ned
Nickerson, she was always in control. She has a friend George _ a
short-haired tomboy with tailored clothes _ taken by some critics
to have been gay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plots of Nancy Drew mysteries are like sonnets, endless
variations on an inflexible form,'' Bobbie Anne Mason wrote in
``The Girl Sleuth.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the Hardy Boys and Nancy Drew lived in Edenic paradises,
surrounded by a body of water, ``ever-changing, yet familiar,'' Ms.
Kismaric and Heiferman write, ``as the plots in each mystery.''
There was no pollution, no racial strife. There was evil, but it
could always be resolved by the virginal Nancy or two boys
unencumbered by sexual longings.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Edward Stratemeyer died in 1930, the year Nancy Drew began, and
Edna and Harriet, his daughters, took over the company.
</P>
<P>
   In 1942, Harriet Stratemayer Adams (she had married Russell
Vroom Adams in 1915) assumed full control of the series. She
revised and updated the books, wrote and commissioned new ones,
making Nancy a more ``feminine'' and compliant figure. Gradually,
Adams transformed Nancy, and many readers never forgave her for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had to get women out of the jobs they'd had in World War
II and make them consumers again; they had to make her less bossy
and less independent,'' said Carolyn Heilbrun, a retired professor
of English at Columbia University, who has written on Nancy Drew.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy became less assertive, and began to ask permission to do
things. She needed Ned Nickerson's help now when she solved a
crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``She doesn't sass cops,'' said Ms. Kismaric of Nancy under
Harriet Adams. ``She is behaving the way society would rather women
behave.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the earlier books, when Nancy and the police would do
something together, Nancy would drive her car,'' said Carolyn
Stewart Dyer, a professor of journalism at the University of Iowa
and an editor of ``Rediscovering Nancy Drew.'' ``But in the later
books, she would wait for the police to get her in their car.
Before, she would break and enter to search the house. After 1959,
she wouldn't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ms. Adams is credited with ridding the books of their
ethnic stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   The original publishers of Nancy Drew and the Hardy Boys was
Grosset &AMP; Dunlap. In 1980, after a lawsuit over rights, Simon &AMP;
Schuster became the publisher of new books in the series. Simon &AMP;
Schuster is also publisher of ``The Mysterious Case of Nancy Drew
and the Hardy Boys.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon &AMP; Schuster began a series for older girls, the ``Nancy
Drew Files.'' ``Simon &AMP; Schuster tarts her up and makes her
sexier,'' said Ms. Kismaric. ``Her romantic life starts heating up.
These were marketing ploys.'' In the ``Files'' books, Nancy began
to moon over Ned and other boys. As feminism advanced, Nancy's own
feminism retreated even more.
</P>
<P>
   Today Nancy drives a van rather than a jalopy. But it is still
blue.
</P>
<P>
   The character of the Hardy Boys has remained much the same, Ms.
Kismaric and Heiferman write, ``locked into a state of eternal,
excitable boyhood,'' except for their toys. Over the years, the old
books have been revised, and new ones have been written. The boys
have gone from jalopies to convertibles to jet travel. They have
traveled on a yacht owned by a supermodel. Their ages were raised
so that it is legal for them to fly a plane.
</P>
<P>
   And the ethnic slurs have ended. Now Phil Cohen, their Jewish
friend, has become an electronics whiz and helps the boys solve
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``But mostly it is the nature of evil that changes,'' said
Heiferman. ``In the beginning, the evil is confined to the little
town of Bayport, which is fraught with criminals, people who steal
things. As the books go on, they begin working with the CIA and
Scotland Yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is the sense that evil in the books is more nefarious
and more pervasive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
