<HEADLINE>
HOLY CROSS PRESIDENT STEPS DOWN DUE TO BAD HEALTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The president of the College of the Holy Cross, the Rev. Gerard
Reedy, credited with boosting the academic standing of the
Jesuit-run school in Worcester, has resigned because of poor
health, college officials announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply put, the physical challenges of the office have become
too burdensome for me and have affected me physically and
emotionally,'' Reedy wrote in a letter to the chairman of the
college's board of trustees.
</P>
<P>
   Reedy, 58, who was appointed president of New England's oldest
Catholic college three years ago, has had a long-time heart
problem, school officials said.
</P>
<P>
   During his tenure, Reedy was hailed for improving the college's
academic reputation, increasing the number and quality of student
applications and presiding over a major jump in Holy Cross's
endowment.
</P>
<P>
   He endeared himself to students at the liberal arts school when
shortly after his inauguration he moved into a student dormitory.
Reedy, who spent most of his academic career at Fordham College in
New York before coming to Holy Cross, said he wanted students to
have more access to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your tenure as president has seen a continued improvement in
the reputation of the college,'' H.E. Lentz, chairman of the
college's board of trustees said in a letter accepting Reedy's
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate news release, Lentz said Reedy's ``countless
friends and supporters can only wish him Godspeed and thank him for
his dedication and sacrifice for Holy Cross.''
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1843, Holy Cross enrolls about 2,700 undergraduate
students.
</P>
<P>
   Replacing Reedy on an interim basis for the next academic year
will be the school's provost, Frank Vellaccio. Holy Cross has
already launched a search for a new Jesuit president.
</P>
<P>
   Reedy will spend the next year living at the Jesuit residence on
campus while he decides what to do next, school officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board understands that your ceaseless efforts for the
college have taken their toll, and the rigors of the
position...have been at substantial cost to your health,'' Lentz
said in his letter. ``We are saddened by this turn of events and
will miss your wisdom and wit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
