A9922 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RACE-HEALTHCARE-BOS &LR;      07-10 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-HEALTHCARE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACE, HEALTH CARE DEFICITS LINKED IN PANEL TESTIMONY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Tearful stories of getting second-class health care
because of race and angry demands for more minority health funding
_ those were among the raw emotions evident as more than 300 people
engaged in President Clinton's initiative on race.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in its year-long existence, the board
advising Clinton on the initiative heard testimony Friday on how
health care is affected by the nation's difficulty in dealing with
race.
</P>
<P>
   In historic Faneuil Hall, where abolitionists once met, and in
the city where Paul Revere began the nation's first local health
board, blacks, Latinos, Asian Americans and Native Americans spoke
about what health care means to them, and how it has been affected
by race in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Thomas, a Pueblo Laguna Indian from New Mexico, cried
as she related her family's ills, ranging from asthma to hearing
loss, and recalled the recent lingering death of her aunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past 18 years, my children, my aunt and I have often
had to travel great distances to find health care,'' she said, as
some members of the audience wept along. And while Medicaid,
Medicare, private insurance and the Indian Health Service
theoretically make care available, ``they don't provide my family
with the consistent, quality, accessible and culturally competent
care they need and deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Also bringing tears to the audience members' eyes were personal
stories of race and health told by Gay Head Wampanoag Tribal
Council chairwoman Beverly Wright and US Surgeon General David
Satcher.
</P>
<P>
   Satcher, who grew up in the segregated South, said that when he
developed whooping cough at the age of two, his parents could not
bring him to the white-run hospital. Instead, they persuaded the
town's only black physician to come to their house. While the
physician didn't expect Satcher to live beyond the week, Satcher's
mother nursed her son back to health.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never take for granted one breath I take, or the
responsibility I have in the Department of Health and Human
Services as surgeon general,'' said Satcher. As part of his
responsibility, Satcher said he is committed to reducing racial
disparities in such key health indicators as infant mortality,
vaccination rates, heart disease, diabetes, cancer and AIDS. He
received the only standing ovation of the three-hour meeting.
</P>
<P>
   A panel of local health officials from a range of ethnic and
racial backgrounds also told the presidential advisory board about
models that work in caring for diverse populations, and about
systemwide barriers that block their ability to provide services.
</P>
<P>
   Elmer Freeman, executive director of the Center for Community
Health, Education, Research and Service at Northeastern University,
highlighted his program's training of health care professionals to
meet the special needs of a diverse, urban population.
</P>
<P>
   But when asked by an advisory board member about how the system
helps or hurts his work, Freeman called a ``significant
impediment'' the way the US government pays for graduate medical
education _ by inadequately supporting the community-based training
of social workers, nurses and other health professionals while
reimbursing hospitals for training doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Another exchange over government funding between advisory board
members and a member of the audience was more heated.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Clark, program manager for youth services at Dimock
Community Health Center, demanded the advisory board recommend to
Clinton that cuts in spending for at-risk youths be restored as one
way to improve health in minority communities, but felt
dissatisfied when one board member said he believed local
governments made the cuts, not the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a joke, a farce,'' Clark said in an interview. He was
accompanied by 16-year-old Theresa Clark, no relation, a Dimock
peer leader who helps educate youth about avoiding risky behavior.
Theresa Clark agreed that she didn't like the advisory board's
answer, adding, ``I don't think they had an answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Other meeting participants called for Clinton to support clean
needle exchange to prevent the transmission of the AIDS virus,
drug-abuse treatment on demand, Medicare and Medicaid reimbursement
for translator services and community health workers and similar
measures to improve access and reduce racial disparity.
</P>
<P>
   The advisory board, as part of its effort to come up with
answers to the difficult question of race, has already recommended
stepped-up civil rights enforcement, increased educational programs
and other social measures. It expects to make its health care
recommendations within the next few weeks, and complete its final
report by the end of September.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who has already incorporated funding for some
of the recommendations in his fiscal 1999 budget, plans to take the
advisory board's report and create a plan to be announced to the
American people by next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
