<SLUG> BC-AGENTS-GUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIFLE USED TO KILL BORDER AGENTS OWNED BY POLICE, OFFICIAL SAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARLINGEN, Texas _ The assault rifle used to kill two U.S.
Border Patrol agents and wound a deputy sheriff Tuesday is owned by
the Harlingen Police Department and was issued to the killer's
police detective father, authorities confirmed Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one of those tragic things,'' a source involved in
the investigation said. ``You can't get any worse than two Border
Patrol agents killed by the son of a police officer.''
</P>
<P>
   The source also said Friday that Ernest L. Moore, a 25-year-old
heavy equipment operator for a San Benito construction company, was
under the influence of alcohol, cocaine and marijuana when he went
on a rampage, killing four people and wounding two others. Moore,
who was fatally wounded by law officers, was buried Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of the killings, Cameron County Sheriff Omar Lucio
insisted that the two assault rifles Moore used came from the Moore
family's private collection and were not police department
property. But on Friday he corrected himself, saying he had since
learned that one of the weapons was owned by the Harlingen Police
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Moore was carrying a semiautomatic MAK-90, a
Chinese version of an AK-47 assault rifle, when he walked into a
Rio Hondo home before dawn Tuesday to abduct his ex-girlfriend. She
escaped unharmed, but he killed two other women who lived there and
critically wounded a man.
</P>
<P>
   The weapon used was the personal property of Moore's father,
Harlingen Police Detective R.D. Moore. That type of gun has been
banned from importation into this country since 1994, but weapons
already in the United States can legally be bought and sold.
Authorities said they believe Detective Moore bought his gun
legally.
</P>
<P>
   After killing Margarita Flores, 53, and her daughter, Delia
Morin, 31, and wounding Flores' 22-year-old son, Dan Morin, in Rio
Hondo, Ernest Moore sped to his father's home in San Benito. He
took an AR-15 semiautomatic assault rifle _ a civilian version of
the military's fully automatic M-16 _ from his father's gun safe
and hid in a nearby cornfield.
</P>
<P>
   That gun had been issued to Detective Moore by the Harlingen
Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   Moore sprang from the field and ambushed Border Patrol agents
Susan Rodriguez and Ricardo Salinas, shooting before they could
draw their side arms. He also wounded Cameron County sheriff's
deputy Raul Rodriguez, before other deputies shot Moore four times.
</P>
<P>
   A source involved in the investigation said Friday that
Detective Moore was unaware that his son had taken the weapons from
his home. He cooperated with police who came looking for his son,
the source said.
</P>
<P>
   The source, who asked not to be identified, also confirmed that
preliminary autopsy reports indicate Ernest Moore had alcohol,
cocaine and marijuana in his system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know he was at a friend's house the night before. They were
drinking, and he left the house at 2:30 or 3 in the morning,'' said
the source. ``We know he was consuming drugs. They admit to him
using drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Tuesday, Ernest Moore had a spotless police record.
</P>
<P>
   Friends of the family described the elder Moore, a senior
detective with more than 25 years of experience, as an honest,
by-the-book officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known him for years. He's straight and honest,'' said one
Harlingen merchant. ``He'll give you a break if you deserve it, but
if you don't, he'll run you in.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
