A9925 &Cx1f; var-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      07-10 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, July 12, will move Saturday in the `a' category.
</P>
<P>
   BOLIVIA-REVIEW (La Paz, Bolovia) _ All around Latin America,
book stores are well stocked with new texts about free markets and
global free trade. Such books brim with hope for the future, and
they are beginning to appear even in this backwater capital high in
the Andes. But here, they still have to share shelf space with a
rather depressing best-seller that carries a very different
message. The book, first published in 1937, is Alcides Arguedas'
``A Sick People,'' and it seems at times that every literate
Bolivian has read it. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   CZAR-BURIAL-REVIEW (Undated) _ In writing, ``Uneasy lies the
head that wears a crown,'' Shakespeare couldn't have imagined the
likes of Nicholas II, Russia's last czar, whose remains will be
interred on Friday in St. Petersburg, Russia, along with those of
his family. Nicholas was considered a lightweight, a weak,
unengaged but brutal ruler who preferred family life to affairs of
state, even as the 300-year-old Romanov empire was collapsing
around him. His burial, however, is a potent political symbol for
post-Communist Russia. By Judith Dobrzynski.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-REVIEW (Lagos) _ What the man in the Nigerian street
thinks about recent events. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   NUCLEAR-DETERRENCE-REVIEW (Washington) _ The potential nuclear
arms race between India and Pakistan is an uneasy and unwelcome
test of how to get along in a world where non-proliferation appears
to have failed. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   SOCCER-U.S.-REVIEW (Undated) _ As soccer reaches its apogee in
Paris with the World Cup final between France and Brazil, the game
remains as mysterious to vast numbers of Americans as it was when
all they saw of it was grainy photographs of Pele leaping in
triumph about something or other. By Kirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   JOURNALISM-REVIEW (Undated) _ There's a curious new genre that
seems to be emerging in American journalism: the media obituary. In
the hushed, somber tones used for that most solemn of news
accounts, reporters have been busy churning out virtual death
notices for the careers of disgraced colleagues. By Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   CRIME-REWARDS-REVIEW (Undated) _ The offering of rewards has
increased in recent years, in part because of successes like the
Ennis Cosby case. But there is little evidence that they do much to
solve most crimes. By Kit R. Roane.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-YORKER-REVIEW (New York) _ Resign? From The New Yorker? In
the past, editors either died or were forced to walk the plank,
their pockets weighted down with bullion. The restless Tina Brown
simply left. By William Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   ABUSIVE-JUDGES-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Megalomania is an
occupational hazard for judges,'' said Professor Paul Carrington of
the Duke University Law School. He added that a trial judge
inevitably has a great deal of power over everyone in the
courtroom. ``Judges can get awfully full of themselves,'' he said.
``Put it this way: everybody laughs at the judge's jokes.'' By Neil
A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-RELIGION-REVIEW (Undated) _ As the century began,
optimists could easily have convinced themselves that by the time
2000 rolled around there would be nothing left for scientists and
theologians to argue about. Each would have long since agreed on
how to divvy up the intellectual terrain. Science would continue
its inevitable march toward a grand explanation of how the material
world works, leaving to religion the endless arguments over why the
universe came to be and how people ought to behave in it. It hasn't
happened that way. By George Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   LABOR-REVIEW (Undated) _ The United States may not yet resemble
France, which is paralyzed every year or two by a strike, but
suddenly American labor unions have taken to the streets in a way
not seen in decades. Some labor stalwarts who grew up singing
``Solidarity Forever'' are hailing recent developments as signaling
that union militancy, squelched in the Reagan years, is making a
comeback. But other analysts suggest that this month's three-ring
labor circus is a coincidental confluence of events that should be
viewed as exceptions to the long, steady decline of militancy. By
Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
