<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9928 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEIBOWITZ-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      07-10 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEIBOWITZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAST WORDS? WE HOPE SO, BUT NOT SOON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID LEIBOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - Now comes the Whiny Killer, Arizona's newest
criminal celebrity. On Wednesday, he makes ``The Arizona
Republic's'' front page. Later that day, Douglas Alan Smith calls a
press conference from jail and makes the airwaves anew.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, the Whiny Killer took the life of a father of
four. Now he takes what else he can _ our valuable time.
</P>
<P>
   All of a sudden, Smith needs some help. He has developed this
burning desire to die. He wants a judge to order the state to lend
a hand with his suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the poor Whiny Killer. Pity him, please. Think of him in
prison, only 34 years old, life a neverending stretch to serve,
with epilepsy and painful seizures to boot. A jury found Smith
guilty of beating a 68-year-old man to death, but prosecutors
didn't seek the death penalty. Unlucky murderer. The irony's
practically killing him.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life has absolutely no meaning,'' he went on for the
cameras. ``I can add this tiny bit of purpose to it by going ahead
with the death penalty rather than slowly deteriorating in
prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Two words. A rhetorical question.
</P>
<P>
   Who cares?
</P>
<P>
   Let the Whiny Killer plead, let his lawyers grandstand and make
motions galore. Let Smith beg for an IV full of poison, whatever he
wants.
</P>
<P>
   He should live, regardless.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, this will cost more than 30 grand a year for a cell on
Death Row. Yes, this will deny us the symmetry of a life for a
life. But Douglas Alan Smith's whims ceased to matter the moment
Samuel Ambrose's heart stopped beating.
</P>
<P>
   Which was the same moment the dead man's family began to matter
most.
</P>
<P>
   They are the ones we should listen to now, the only ones who
deserve our time and the justice system's ear. The old teacher,
Sam, left behind two sons and two daughters, and a wife of 40-some
years. Alice Ambrose is her name.
</P>
<P>
   We owe her and her children. Them, and only them.
</P>
<P>
   The widow answers the question reluctantly. She is not big on
press, not one for the public eye. Not one to whine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted life without parole,'' Alice explains. ``The family,
we did not ask for or push for the death penalty. No one in the
family did that. We went along with the (county) attorney's office,
what they decided was appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Those few sentences end any debate. Gag the Whiny Killer, and
fast. But leave space for him to breathe. For a good long time.
</P>
<P>
   I say this not to encourage suffering _ his _ but to prevent
more anguish _ theirs. What started three years ago with 60-odd
blows to the skull hasn't come close to ending for Samuel Ambrose's
family. Their troubles deepen with each new request, each court
date, each presumptuous quote like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost feel like I know them,'' says Smith of the Ambroses.
``I sit in bed at night and think about them.''
</P>
<P>
   Alice Ambrose can only laugh at the gall. ``I don't know him. I
never talked to him or anything like that. He's just the person who
killed my husband.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing more, nothing less. No one worth heeding.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the Whiny Killer has been given enough consideration,
in court and out, by the survivors of the late Navy veteran. The
family has thought of Smith often, says Renee Infantolino,
Ambrose's daughter. Every minute spent considering the killer was a
minute they couldn't spend thinking about Samuel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten to the point where we feel it's never going to
end,'' the daughter says. ``That's part of why we never asked for
the death penalty. We didn't want to deal with this 10, 15 years
down the line. All we want to do is get it done, make sure he can't
do it again. That way we've done what our duty is, to make sure the
world is a little safer.''
</P>
<P>
   Theirs is a practical decision, and just. In the end, it is all
that matters. Think about it.
</P>
<P>
   Who deserves our time more? The family who was robbed, or the
killer who robbed them? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
