<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-PENSIONS-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURFING THE WEB AND SNARING AN OWED PENSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 12)  
(lb) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly 1,400 Americans are collecting pension benefits because
they found their names on an Internet site created by the Pension
Benefit Guaranty Corp., the federal agency that insures pensions.
</P>
<P>
   The agency posted the names of about 8,600 people who have not
applied for benefits due to them from plans the agency now
administers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority of the people entitled to pensions receive
their full pension, but sometimes people move or forget to inform
past employers of their new address,'' said David Strauss,
executive director of the agency. ``The pension search helps us
find workers owed benefits who couldn't be located when their
pension plans are closed.''
</P>
<P>
   A total of more than $4 million in benefits has been paid to
nearly 1,400 people since the agency started its Pension Search
Directory on the Internet 18 months ago, he said. The remaining
7,200 or so are owed nearly $13 million in benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The pension beneficiaries who have been located through the
directory live in 40 states; 113 of them are from New York and 309
are from California.
</P>
<P>
   The average value of those recovered benefits, if paid
immediately in a lump sum, was $4,100, though most people will get
monthly annuity checks. Benefits range from a few dollars to more
than $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the accounts were for closed pension plans in which the
former workers could not be found, Strauss said.
</P>
<P>
   Others were participants in pension plans that the agency took
over because they did not have enough assets to pay all promised
benefits. The agency guarantees pensions up to about $34,000
annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are continuously striving to ensure that workers receive
every dollar of their hard-earned pensions,'' said Labor Secretary
Alexis Herman, who is chairwoman of the Pension Benefit Guaranty
board.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet directory lists workers who have pension money
coming to them from terminated defined-benefit pension plans. The
directory address is http://search.pbgc.gov. As of Friday
afternoon, 98,358 name searches had been made, said Judy Welles,
the agency's senior spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The directory contains nearly 1,000 companies owing pension
benefits. They are concentrated in the transportation, machinery,
retail trade, apparel and financial-services industries.
</P>
<P>
   Individuals who find their names on the Internet list must
supply additional information to verify their identity, a process
that typically takes four to six weeks, officials said. Monthly
checks start coming about two months later, they added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
