<SLUG> BC-WOODWARD-FUND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODWARD DEFENSE FUND DEPLETED, SUPPORTERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM F. DOHERTY   AND ESTHER LEACH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Louise Woodward defense fund, which once was flush
with more than $450,000, is almost empty and cannot pay for her
defense in the wrongful-death suit pending against her, supporters
say.
</P>
<P>
   Without money for a lawyer, Woodward has not responded to the
suit brought by the parents of 8-month-old Matthew Eappen, the
infant who was fatally injured while in her care. Her decision not
to challenge the suit within 20 days of its filing means that,
under court rules, she has waived her right to a trial.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Quinn, a partner in the Liverpool firm of solicitors Quinn
and Melville, said Friday: ``We have been quoted six-figure sums to
defend the civil case, and the Woodwards are in no position to go
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no significant sums of money left in the trust fund,
and we have asked people to stop donating. The purpose of the trust
fund was not to defend a civil case.''
</P>
<P>
   Although EF Au Pair, the agency that brought Woodward to the
United States, paid for her defense in the criminal trial, Woodward
agreed to use the money from the fund to help pay for her appeal.
The fund has also been used to pay expenses the former au pair's
parents incurred flying back and forth from England while she was
in jail here before and during her trial.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward returned to England last month after the state Supreme
Judicial Court upheld her manslaughter conviction sentence of the
279 days she had already served.
</P>
<P>
   The Eappens' lawyer, Fredric L. Ellis, said that he will ask US
District Judge William G. Young to determine how much Woodward
should pay the Eappens in damages. Ellis said he wants to prevent
Woodward from profiting from Matthew's death by selling her story
in a book or movie deal. But he has admitted it may be difficult to
enforce an award from a US court in England.
</P>
<P>
   The Eappens have said they will donate any money they receive to
a charitable trust they set up to fight child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Woodwards' closest friends and staunchest supporters,
Sandra McCabe, also said the family does not have the money to
fight another legal battle. ``People think the family have lots of
money, but it has all gone (to America) in legal fees,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family are not making any statements,'' she added. ``Their
solicitors have said it all. I have faith that one day the truth
will come out and Louise will be seen to be innocent.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Woodward is considering which university she will
attend and hopes it will be in the London area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 1935EDT &QL; 
