A9936 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRELAND-PARADE-BOS &LR;      07-10 1392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-PARADE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABSENCE OF PARAMILITY GROUPS MINIMIZES PARADE PROTEST VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTADOWN, Northern Ireland _ After six days of standoff, a
familiar pattern has developed in the pasture opposite Drumcree
Church here. By day, it is a quiet, bucolic scene. Children run
through the fields and old men tell war stories in tents that dot
the hillside.
</P>
<P>
   By nightfall, however, the old men and the children have
departed. The field unleashes the anger of young men who hurl
insults, rocks, and even bombs across the barbed wire at the police
and British soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   But as bad as it is, the violence spawned by the confrontation
between Protestants who want to march through a Catholic
neighborhood in Portadown and the security forces on duty to stop
them is not as bad as it was during a similar situation here two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The primary reason for that difference is the refusal of the two
main Protestant loyalist paramilitary groups to get involved, which
means that violence is sporadic and poorly organized.
</P>
<P>
   There have been nightly rioting, carjackings, and firebombings,
to be sure. Isolated roadblocks have sprung up, but only
temporarily. And despite expectations of mayhem this weekend, when
the marching nears its peak, the disruption is not on the scale of
1996, when Northern Ireland was paralyzed by violence orchestrated
by the loyalist paramilitary groups.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with that prospect two years ago, the Royal Ulster
Constabulary lifted its blockade and let the Orangemen march after
beating Catholic protesters off the Garvaghy Road. That
capitulation touched off the worst rioting in years. Today,
however, the police chief, Ronnie Flanagan, is convinced that his
force can hold the line, and British Prime Minister Tony Blair has
lent more soldiers to that effort.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities are more confident this year because the two
main loyalist paramilitary groups, the Ulster Defense Association
and the Ulster Volunteer Force, support the Good Friday agreement,
which stipulates that their members will be released from prison
within the next two years. The two groups are wary of wrecking the
release of their prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Still, individual members of the Ulster Defense Association and
Ulster Volunteer Force are suspected of involvement in the
accompanying violence around Drumcree. While acknowledging that
individuals have been involved in violence, David Ervine, leader of
the Progressive Unionist Party, the political wing of the Ulster
Volunteer Force, said the violence would be ``far worse'' if the
organizations joined in.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Shankill Road in West Belfast, a loyalist
hotbed, has been quiet because of the control exercised by loyalist
leaders, Ervine said. East Belfast, another area under the control
of loyalist paramilitary, has seen violence, but not nearly as much
as in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But this is little consolation to the people who live in places
like Collingwood, a middle-class subdivision just a few miles up
the road from Drumcree. About 30 armed men, some with hoods on
their heads, invaded the quiet cul-de-sac at about 1 a.m.
Wednesday, sneaking in through a hole in a fence that had been
erected to ward off such attacks. One of them repeatedly fired a
shotgun into the air and, as happened two years ago, the homes were
pelted with Molotov cocktails.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Dowds ran out of his house in his pajamas and picked up a
garden hose to douse flames pouring from the living room of a
neighbor, Michael Lavery. It was only after he and other neighbors
helped the Laverys and their 2-year-old daughter escape the flames
that Dowds looked back and saw his own house was on fire. Dowds
collapsed with chest pains, while neighbors helped his elderly
disabled wife, Joan, out of the house.
</P>
<P>
   Being English and Protestant did not save the Dowds from the
wrath of a mob that professes to be loyal to the English monarch
and the Protestant faith.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, the Orange Order began its siege here after the
British government refused to let it march down the Catholic
Garvaghy Road. Since then, the terror inflicted on the people in
Collingwood has been repeated dozens of times across Northern
Ireland. It is a form of intimidation to force people from their
homes that occurs around this time each year, when Protestant
groups parade to commemorate Protestant King William of Orange's
1690 victory over Catholic King James II.
</P>
<P>
   While overall violence has declined, the bitter standoff at
Drumcree has exacerbated this annual ritual of hatred, according to
Glyn Roberts, spokesman for Families Against Intimidation and
Terror. Roberts said that while exact figures are not yet
available, more than 100 people had been intimidated out of their
homes in the past week.
</P>
<P>
   The homes in Collingwood were targeted because the owners are
Catholic, as have been most victims of intimidation, said Roberts.
But Protestant police officers and their families have also been
singled out in retaliation for police keeping the peace at Drumcree
and standing up to loyalist thugs elsewhere. An off-duty police
officer and his 11-year-old son were beaten by a loyalist mob in
Londonderry. A Protestant family in Dungannon was burned out
because vigilantes deemed them too friendly with too many
Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   Brid Rodgers, the newly elected assembly member for the area,
visited the Collingwood residents to promise them 24-hour
protection and fix the hole in the fence where the intruders
entered.
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers says thugs who attack innocents under the cover of
darkness are operating with a political agenda. ``These tactics of
intimidation and terror are being used in an orchestrated way by a
small minority to accomplish what they couldn't at the ballot
box,'' she said. ``They are trying to destroy the Good Friday
agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people thought that the 71 percent of those who endorsed
the agreement in May voted for a new era of accommodation between
Protestant unionists who want to remain in the United Kingdom and
Catholic nationalists who aspire to unity with the Irish Republic.
But ancient tribal hatreds have cast a dark shadow over what had
been a promising few months.
</P>
<P>
   Orange Order leaders insist their protest is peaceful and that
they cannot be held responsible for the violence carried out by
sympathizers. But Sean Dowds counters that the Orange Order cannot
wash its hands of the terror visited on him and his neighbors. Four
police officers were seriously wounded Friday by a nail bomb thrown
from the Orangemen's camp at Drumcree.
</P>
<P>
   While Orange Order leaders agreed to indirect talks Friday in an
effort to avert the crisis, they have refused to have direct
negotiations with the Garvaghy Road residents because a leader of
the residents, Breandan MacCionnaith, is a former member of the
Irish Republican Army who was convicted of taking part in the
bombing of a British army veterans hall here.
</P>
<P>
   But earlier this week, the local Orange Order leader, Denis
Watson, was seen having an extended conversation with Kenny
McClinton, who as a loyalist assassin killed two men and served 16
years in prison before having what he calls a spiritual conversion.
Also seen chatting with Orangemen outside Drumcree Church was Mark
``Swinger'' Fulton, the reputed leader of the Loyalist Volunteer
Force, which murdered a Catholic man here in April and has carried
out some of the most notorious murders in Northern Ireland over the
last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Watson was defensive when asked if he was being hypocritical in
refusing to talk to MacCionnaith, who was convicted of taking part
in a bombing in which no one was hurt, while having no qualms about
talking to McClinton, a double murderer.
</P>
<P>
   Watson said McClinton ``is a repentant terrorist. There is a
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The violence and disruption is expected to peak this weekend, as
thousands of Orangemen and sympathizers converge here and the
marching season climaxes Monday with dozens of parades all over
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   In Collingwood, meanwhile, the ``For Sale'' signs have sprung
up. The local councillor, Kieran McGeown, visited Friday, trying to
reassure residents. ``These are professional people, good people,''
McGeown said. ``If people like that go, we're in trouble.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
