u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONN-MURDER-BOS &LR;      07-10 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONN-MURDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEW LEADS IN STABBING OF BOY, POLICE SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN O'BRIEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDSOR, Conn. _ Police said Friday they had few leads in the
savage stabbing death of a 7-year-old boy in his mother's home
Thursday and appealed to the public for help in apprehending two
masked intruders blamed for the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators distributed pictures of a man's black, digital
Casio watch, which a family member said was ripped off one of the
men while he struggled with the boy's mother.
</P>
<P>
   Windsor Police Captain Peter McDermott Friday said that three
people had already called investigators to say they recognized the
watch. It did not appear that those calls would develop into any
significant leads.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators also said neighbors observed a dark-colored sport
utility vehicle in the area at the time of the early morning
attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, (the murder) is not going to be solved if it is
just up to the police,'' said McDermott. ``We are going to need the
public and the media. We have come up with a very vague description
of two men based on the mother's account. We have no facial
features. They were wearing masks. I am praying, but I am not
anticipating an arrest soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Police said they didn't believe the attack was random, but added
they didn't yet have a motive for the murder.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's mother, 30-year-old Tammi Cuyler, dialed 911 at 2:30
a.m. Thursday and reported a violent attack in her Lovell Avenue
Home. Jarrell Cuyler, 7, was pronounced dead at the scene. His
throat was slashed.
</P>
<P>
   His 3-year-old sister, Lindsey, received injuries to her neck
and wrists and was taken to a local hospital, where she was in
stable condition. A third child, an 18-month-old nephew, was also
in the room, but was unharmed, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Tammi Cuyler told relatives she heard a noise in the house and
went to investigate. Two men burst into the home and one pinned
Cuyler to the floor while the other attacked the children, she told
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Cuyler struggled with the men while hearing her son ask, ``What
are you doing?'' and her daughter scream. During the struggle she
tore off a watch and glove worn by one of the attackers.
</P>
<P>
   Cuyler is a supervisor at the state Department of Children and
Families. Her husband, Arnold Cuyler, lives in nearby Bristol and
works for Fleet Bank. The couple is separated.
</P>
<P>
   Both parents were interviewed for several hours by police, who
described them as ``cooperative.''
</P>
<P>
   A team of 30 investigators from the Windsor and state police
departments followed leads and searched the area in and around the
home Friday. Dr. Henry Lee, the noted forensic specialist who works
out of the state crime lab, was also called in to help with the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Windsor is ordinarily a quiet suburb of Hartford, which is five
miles to the south on Interstate 91. Cuyler and her children had
lived in the neighborhood of neat, middle-class homes since last
year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Armstrong of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
