<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9944 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPLE-iMAC-COX     07-10 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-iMAC-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Apple ventures into real world after Macworld
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Apple Computer Inc. has enjoyed three days of near
euphoria with the Macintosh community at the MacWorld Expo this
week, and now re-enters the real world where market-share size
matters.
</P>
<P>
   The months ahead will reveal how far the momentum created by
fast, new computers and a mold-breaking new product for consumers
will carry the company, Apple watchers agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to give Steve Jobs a lot of credit for creating a
lot of buzz and raising the banner of Apple,'' said Steve Dube of
Wasserstein &AMP; Pirella of New York. ``He's slowing the erosion of
Mac customers to Windows and that's very critical. But whether he
can reverse it is another question.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple stock set a 52-week high this week after Jobs, Apple's
co-founder and interim chief executive, told a Macworld audience of
about 3,000 that Apple would report its third profitable quarter in
a row. Shares closed Friday at $32.06 1/4, up 37 1/2 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Following strong sales of powerful new computers based on the G3
PowerPC chip, Apple will release the iMac next month.
</P>
<P>
   Apple's fortunes are of interest to Austin's strong Macintosh
community, which ranges from thousands at the University of Texas
to home users to graphics designers to companies that sell products
for the Mac.
</P>
<P>
   Through weeks of adept marketing and controlled access to the
iMac computer, Jobs and Apple have sparked considerable buzz based
on the $1,299 consumer PC.
</P>
<P>
   For example, when Austinite George Cole tried to touch an iMac
that Apple demonstrated in Dallas last month, employees blocked
him, he said.
</P>
<P>
   `` `No, no, no','' Cole quoted them as saying. `` `That's the
iMac Steve Jobs used when he demonstrated it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``They're thinking: Smithsonian,'' Cole said in a recent
interview.
</P>
<P>
   First, Apple must get in it the Smith's home and the Jones's
home and millions of other homes.
</P>
<P>
   At least one observer says that is possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be the most successful product launch in
the history of the industry,'' said David Moser, vice president of
MacCentral, a World Wide Web-based site that closely follows Apple.
</P>
<P>
   While it is several hundred dollars more expensive than entry
level machines from other companies, Mac supporters note iMac
features that competitors' machines don't have.
</P>
<P>
   The monitor and system unit are in one box. Jobs claims, and
cites Byte magazine tests as evidence, that the computer's 233
megahertz PowerPC processor is faster than Intel Corp.'s Pentium II
chips.
</P>
<P>
   Designed for Internet use, the iMac has an ethernet connection
for high-speed data transmission that far surpasses the capacity of
conventional modems and telephone lines. Until buyers have access
to cable modems or special telephone lines, the iMac will be able
to connect at 56.6 klbs. Besides the home, Jobs and Apple hope the
iMac will appeal to schools,as well as families, which would help
slow erosion of Apple's share of the education market to products
made by Dell Computer Corp., Compaq Computer Corp. and other PC
companies.
</P>
<P>
   At MacWorld Friday, Heather Hurley came out of a sparsely
attended work session for educators with a renewed sense of
excitement about the Mac.
</P>
<P>
   The 29-year-old third-grade teacher in Concord, Mass., has three
Macs in her classroom and just got a PowerMac with one of the new
G3 processors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love them,'' said Hurley, one of 15 people who sat through a
presentation on using Macs in the classroom. ``They're just really
easy to use.''
</P>
<P>
   Like school districts around the country, the Concord district
has debated whether to stay with Macintosh, Hurley said. Concord's
decision was to stand by the Mac.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have several parents who don't necessarily agree with the
decision the school district made to go all Macs,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and Apple executives agree that Apple's fate hinges to
a large extent on the availability of software for the Mac. Jobs,
in his keynote Wednesday, said more than 170 software titles had
been introduced or planned since he unveiled the iMac in May.
</P>
<P>
   It is a symbol of the how dramatically Apple's world has changed
in the past year that the biggest complaint vendors had was the
show's location.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to move it to New York after 13 years in Boston did
not sit well with several businesses who spent thousands of dollars
_ tens of thousands in some cases _ for floor space in the huge
Jacob Javits Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did us no favor moving here,'' said Dudley Baker, who was
on duty at a small booth rented by National Instruments of Austin.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which recently introduced new data-acquisition
boards for scientists and engineers, said the company has many more
customers along Route 128 near Boston than it does in the New York
area.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in a large square booth in front of shelves of unsold
software and other Mac products, John Chouinard, manager of
Computer Town, which is a large store in Nashua, N.H., estimated
that his sales fell 20 percent from last summer's show in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really kind of sad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Show organizers declined to disclose the attendance, although
one official told the Boston Globe only that attendance was ``north
of 30,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year's show in Boston drew between 45,000 and 48,000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
