<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0298 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9946 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MATH-TEACHERS-ART-     07-10 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The blue fliers began appearing in the middle of last
month, on university campuses and in hiring halls from Vienna to
Salzburg to Innsbruck. ``If you can read this,'' the brochures
beckoned in English, ``have we got a deal for you!!!''
</P>
<P>
   The advertiser is the New York City Board of Education, and the
``unique chance'' it is offering to Austrians is full-time
employment, for at least a year, as mathematics and science
teachers in high schools in all five boroughs. The starting salary
is $30,000, airfare not included.
</P>
<P>
   In less a month, nearly 300 Austrians have called the Ministry
of Education in Vienna requesting applications, and, with
interviews starting in two weeks, administrators predict that as
many as 50 could end up standing in front of city classrooms when
schools reopen in September.
</P>
<P>
   States with growing student populations, like California and
Texas, routinely recruit in states graduating too many teachers,
like Indiana and Minnesota, but New York's is among the first
large-scale international recruiting missions.
</P>
<P>
   New York City, the nation's largest district, with 1.1 million
students and 65,000 teachers, has struggled in recent years to find
thousands of candidates qualified to teach math and science.
Austria has long fretted over what to do with its surplus of
hundreds of teachers trained in those very subjects who cannot find
work. The disparity exists, in part, because Austrian schools do
not compete with a thriving computer industry that has
cherry-picked so many American students who might otherwise have
considered teaching, and in part because American education majors
rarely specialize in math and science.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Dr. Alfred Posamentier, a professor of mathematics
education at the City College of New York, who taught education
courses in Austria on a Fulbright Scholarship in 1990. Earlier this
year, he had the brainstorm that Austria and New York City could
help relieve each other's staffing quandaries. By last month, plans
for a pilot program were in place.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Elke Rogl, 26, who studied mathematics and physics at the
University of Vienna but has been frustrated in her bid to find a
full-time teaching job, says her best chance lies in New York, of
all places.
</P>
<P>
   Once the New York City Board of Education accepts her
credentials, which administrators consider likely, she will need
only to persuade an interviewer at board headquarters in downtown
Brooklyn that she is fluent in English. She will have her
opportunity during a 15-minute video teleconference from Vienna
during the last week in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think math is a universal language,'' said Ms. Rogl, who
like many Austrian children began learning English soon after she
began speaking German. ``They will understand me.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she felt daunted by the hardscrabble reputation and
daunting diversity of New York City schools, whose total population
is equal to that of the entire Austrian school system, Ms. Rogl
betrayed no qualms. After all, she said, Austria's schools have
been flooded in recent years by immigrants from the former
Yugoslavia and the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   In seizing on Posamentier's idea, the city school system is
expanding on a nascent trend. While visiting Berlin in the spring,
for example, Posamentier was surprised to encounter teachers from
Houston recruiting German math and science teachers. Houston has
also been scouring Mexico for bilingual teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this works,'' said Gary Barton, the deputy director of
human resources for the New York City board, ``I see no reason we
can't expand to other countries.''
</P>
<P>
   To Dr. Kurt Scholz, the president of the Vienna Board of
Education, who asked that he be described to American readers as
``the Rudy Crew of Austria,'' the exchange is about a lot more than
the law of supply and demand.
</P>
<P>
   Scholz says that in helping shepherd the recruiting effort, he
feels he is returning a favor to New York for taking in so many
Austrian refugees during World War II. They included the parents of
a not-yet-conceived Alfred Posamentier, who lost all four of his
grandparents to the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York preserved the best of Viennese culture and history
during the war,'' said Scholz, who recently visited Crew in
Brooklyn. ``We're paying back the debt on the one hand. We're also
saying that these two countries got in touch during a dark period
in this century, and thank God.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a project would seem to pose a logistical nightmare,
particularly given the few short weeks that officials have to bring
it together. Board officials, working with the Austrian consul
general in New York, are confident they can secure visas for all
the airlifted teachers, who would be permitted to work under a
special classification as ``research scholars,'' allowing them to
stay up to three years. They will not, therefore, need green cards.
</P>
<P>
   As for the teachers' qualifications, Barton, the board hiring
official, said that the education and training for aspiring
teachers in Austria often outstrips that many of the teachers
already working in New York. Anyone studying to be a teacher in
Austria, for example, must major in two related subjects _ say,
mathematics and biology _ and then spend a full year as an
apprentice teacher.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
