<HEADER>
A9947 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISNEY-COX     07-10 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    State Board of Education to sell Disney stock
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Score one for the folks who believe the
marketing wizards who gave America the Mouseketeers have become
conscienceless profiteers.
</P>
<P>
   In a battle over money and morals, the State Board of Education
voted Friday to sell its $43 million stake in the Walt Disney Co.
The entertainment conglomerate, critics said, has become a purveyor
of cinematic sex and violence.
</P>
<P>
   The 8-4 vote was the end result of an effort initiated by the
American Family Association of Texas, which sent board members
highlights of the films ``Pulp Fiction'' and ``Chasing Amy,''
not-for-kid films produced by Disney subsidiary Miramax.
</P>
<P>
   Board members who voted for divestiture said it was the right
thing to do for money and moral reasons. Richard Neill, R-Fort
Worth, noted that Disney stock value has dropped 17 percent in the
past two months
</P>
<P>
   ``I wished we would have gotten out two months ago,'' said
Neill, a board member honored last month by the Texas Christian
Coalition. ``We would have saved millions of dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney's stock could become less attractive if more people
become concerned about the company's adult-oriented movies, Neill
has said.
</P>
<P>
   During the debate that began Thursday in a committee, board
Chairman Jack Christie, R-Houston, also made it clear that the
decision was aimed at driving home ``a message to Miramax . . .
that the public in general has had enough of exposing children to
the violence and explicitness in these movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many more school shootings do you want before we have to
do something to reverse that trend?''
</P>
<P>
   Disney officials took a hands-off approach to the board's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't comment on the stock market or individual investment
strategies,'' said Claudia Peters, the company's director of
corporate communications.
</P>
<P>
   Disney does comment, however, when critics assail the reputation
the company has cultivated for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Walt Disney Company produces more family entertainment
than any other company in the world,'' said Peters. ``And any
products marked with the Disney brand name are suitable for all
ages.''
</P>
<P>
   Products from subsidiaries such as Miramax, she acknowledged,
can be more adult-oriented. They are always so labelled, Peters
said.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Mary Helen Berlanga, D-Corpus Christi, said it is
parents' responsibility _ not the board's _ to take action to keep
kids away from unsuitable entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not let our children view movies like those where
Arnold Schwarzenegger appears where there is so much violence,''
she said, adding, however, that the board should not mix social
policy with investment decisions. The vote also drew criticism from
the Texas Freedom Network, which said, in effect, that the board
showed it had a small mind, after all. The Austin-based group works
to counter the political efforts of social conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're disappointed that the board has put these narrow
political considerations ahead of the education of the children of
Texas,'' said Richard Levy of Austin, a network board member who
said the board will be hard-pressed to replace the Disney stock
with investments of equal potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not taking a moral position, but a political position
advanced by a right-wing organization and imposing it on the
taxpayers of Texas,'' Levy added.
</P>
<P>
   Board members who opposed the proposal said investment decisions
should be bottom-line oriented.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do not make investment decisions on any criteria other
than financial merit,'' said Will Davis, D-Austin. ``If you do, you
are going to make serious mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Disney stock has performed well for the state's Permanent
School Fund, Davis added, noting it had produced a 108 percent
return over two years.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Constitution, Davis reminded colleagues, requires
state officials to base investment decisions solely on financial
considerations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of issues people can get uptight about,'' he
said, ``but when you start trying to draw parameters under other
terms . . . then you start making moral judgments, social judgments
and other types of judgments that some of us will support and some
of us will criticize.''
</P>
<P>
   But board member David Bradley, R-Beaumont, said the 15-member
panel has the ultimate authority to decide how to invest the
Permanent School Fund, which now tops $17 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are elected representatives, representing districts and
constituents. They have empowered us to make decisions. That's a
responsibility each of us weighs pretty heavily. The buck does stop
here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Alma Allen, D-Houston, voted against divestiture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe a vote to divest is political hypocrisy for this
board,'' she said, noting the holdings in alcoholic beverage and
casino companies. Allen also said her vote was driven by a desire
to avoid personal hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not be voting to divest. Two weeks from today I will be
at Disneyland,'' she said. ``That's where my grandchildren want to
go, and I'm going to take all five. Last year we went to Disney
World. And we have been there twice. And I just spent $4,000 to go
next week,'' she said. ``So it is hypocrisy for me to cast a vote
to divest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are going to be pure and clean and void of sins let's
totally divest and get out of the investment business all
together,'' she added. ``If we are in the business of investing,
let's be in the business of investing.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
