<SLUG> BC-LUCENT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lucent workers reject union contract
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Workers in Norcross have voted overwhelmingly to
reject their union's tentative contract with Lucent Technologies,
increasing the chances of another confrontation at the bargaining
table and a possible strike.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the contract is rejected depends on whether a majority
of Lucent workers in the nation vote no, but indications are of
grass-roots resentment _ especially among older workers _ of what
is seen as an anemic pension package.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Communications Workers of America, which
negotiated the agreement, have predicted the contract's
ratification.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am certainly surprised,'' said Drew Clark, international
staff representative for the CWA's District 3, which covers the
Southeast. ``A lot of people had given me the impression that they
were dissatisfied, but I didn't talk to anybody who said they would
definitely vote against it.''
</P>
<P>
   CWA's national leadership has expressed satisfaction with the
five-year deal, which includes an 18.75 percent increase in wages,
as well as a freeze in worker costs for prescription drugs and
doctor visits. The agreement also calls for higher pension payments
_ but the increase was insufficient, according to Norcross workers.
</P>
<P>
   An average worker with 30 years of service who retired this year
would be paid $1,042 a month, said Leon Gussick, president of CWA
local 3263, which represents workers in Norcross. The contract
called for an average worker with 30 years of service to be paid
$1,185 per month on retiring in 2003. He said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Folks feel that as well as the company is doing, they should
have given more at the bargaining table. These are the people who
produce the product and satisfy the customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucent last year had net income of $541 million on $26 billion
in revenue. The New Jersey-based company, spun off from AT&AMP;T two
years ago, has about 7,300 employees in metro Atlanta. About 3,620
of those workers are represented by the CWA.
</P>
<P>
   The union and the company forged the contract in the early hours
of May 31, about 90 minutes after the start of a strike. If this
deal is tossed out, union and company would head back to the
bargaining table _ confronting the possibility of another, more
serious strike. Gussick said he is discouraged but will wait to see
how the rest of Lucent workers vote. If the national contract is
rejected, the CWA would seek a better agreement, he said. ``I think
the company would sit down and bargain with us. But how far they'd
go with additional demands is another story.''
</P>
<P>
   The CWA represents 25,000 Lucent workers. About 21,000 Lucent
employees are represented by the International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
