<SLUG> BC-MANHUNT-REWARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN'S TIP EARNS $34,000 REWARD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing; attn.: Kansas)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AMY GRAVES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Her tip made possible the successful end of a
months-long manhunt for a killer. But Mary King isn't talking now.
</P>
<P>
   King, of Boston, was awarded $34,062 this week for tipping off
investigators looking for the man responsible for the murders of
three people in Salina, Kans., in July 1996.
</P>
<P>
   King, then living in Quincy, a Boston suburb, called ``America's
Most Wanted'' in November 1996 after seeing a familiar face on the
television show. The man they wanted, she said, was at the St.
Francis homeless shelter in Boston, where she worked as a
counselor.
</P>
<P>
   Her call led to the capture of Alan Eugene White, now serving a
life sentence for the beating deaths of Dolores McKim, 80, her
daughter, Carol Abercrombie, 56, and Abercrombie's grandson,
Christopher, 5. They were killed in McKim's home.
</P>
<P>
   The slayings so shocked residents of the city of 50,000 that
they started raising money as a reward for anyone who could lead to
the killer's capture.
</P>
<P>
   Except for $5,000 from a state fund, all the money came from
private sources, Salina Police Chief Jim Hill said Thursday. ``It
ranged from children bringing in change to larger donations from
local corporations'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   Several people attempted to claim the reward, including White's
parents, who cooperated with police by providing blood so that DNA
collected at the crime scene could be tested to determine if it
matched. Their claim was rejected.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Salina city commissioners voted to give King all but
$10,000 of the $44,062 raised. The rest went to White's prison
cellmate, who aided in the investigation, Hill said. Kansas prison
officials are not releasing the cellmate's name, but Hill said his
reward will be used to pay restitution to victims of the property
crime for which he was convicted.
</P>
<P>
   King was given the money because she was first with the
information, Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She called immediately, and actually told (investigators) what
bed he was sleeping in,'' he said. Before the show was over that
night, Boston police had White, 28, under arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly owe a lot to Mary King for leading us to Alan
White,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   But an end to her role in the case is something King would
probably call a reward in itself, according to her lawyer, Ann
Palmieri of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Palmieri, who learned of the reward Tuesday when called by a
Kansas reporter, said her client has not told her how she plans to
spend the money.
</P>
<P>
   King, 40, has shied away from speaking publicly since the arrest
and no longer works at the shelter.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's always said that she's very afraid for herself and any
repercussions from him,'' Palmieri said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 1948EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
