<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0302 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9954 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYC-TOUR-BOS &LR;      07-10 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD CUP BOOTS TOUR DE FRANCE INTO IRELAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The people of France are not fools; they realize they can handle
only so much hoopla at one time.
</P>
<P>
   So, to make way for the soccer frenzy that's going on as France
gets ready to face Brazil in Sunday's World Cup final, the Tour de
France is stepping aside. Way aside. In fact, all the way off the
mainland and into Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The 189 riders _ 21 teams of nine cyclists each _ kick off the
three-week race Saturday with a short time trial in downtown
Dublin. Then it's a 112-mile circuit race in Dublin Sunday, and a
125-mile race from Enniscorthy to Cork Monday before the riders
pack their bikes onto an airplane and head to France to continue
the Tour there.
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's race, called a prologue, riders will set off
individually at one-minute intervals on the 3.5-mile course to race
against the clock. And even though it's not considered one of the
race's 21 stages, it sets up the almost-2,400-mile race; the
winning rider will wear the yellow jersey at the start of Sunday's
stage.
</P>
<P>
   The question, though, is whether he can hang on to it. That's
doubtful, since there is no clear-cut heir apparent to the leader's
jersey that German rider Jan Ullrich took last year.
</P>
<P>
   So over the next three weeks, as the Tour winds its way on a
counterclockwise circuit of France, traveling through the Pyrenees,
Alps, and wine country, it's a safe bet that several riders will
wear the yellow jersey before the race finishes in Paris Aug. 2.
</P>
<P>
   One advantage Ullrich has is that he's just 24; another is that
one of his teammates is Bjarne Riis, the Dane who won the Tour in
1996, when Ullrich finished second. The year before that, five-time
champ Miguel Indurain won the race, but no one since has been such
a dominant force.
</P>
<P>
   Ullrich's fitness is in question, though. He gained weight and
was out of shape over the winter, and only recently seemed to be
back in racing form. Team director Walter Goldfroot stood up for
the defending champ, saying critics should compare Ullrich with
former Tour champions Indurain or Greg LeMond, both of whom were
said to battle weight problems.
</P>
<P>
   Others to watch include France's Richard Virenque, who finished
second last year; Italy's Marco Pantani, who won the Tour of Italy
this spring and finished third in the Tour last year; France's
Laurent Jalabert, who won the world title in the time trial last
year; and Spaniard Abraham Olano, who is on Indurain's former team.
</P>
<P>
   While no one on the American-based US Postal Service team is apt
to break the top 10, it was one of only three teams to finish last
year's race with its nine-man roster intact.
</P>
<P>
   This year's team features four Americans, including George
Hincapie, who won the national championship in Philadelphia last
month. His teammates are Tyler Hamilton of Brookline, Mass.;
Frankie Andreu of Deerborn, Mich., a new team member but a Tour
veteran; Marty Jemison of Salt Lake City; Dariusz Baranowski of
Poland; Viatcheslav Ekimov of Russia; Peter Meinert of Denmark; and
Pascal Derame and Jean-Cyril Robin, both from France. Robin
finished 15th overall in the Tour last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
