<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MD-CUSTODY-DISPUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADOPTION RULING ANGERS CHILDREN'S RIGHTS ADVOCATES
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Md., Pa) (js) 
By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a ruling that has angered advocates for
children's rights in adoptions, an appeals court in Montgomery
County, Md., has upheld a decision that allows a young boy to be
returned to his mother even though she was previously convicted of
murdering another one of her children.
</P>
<P>
   The Maryland Court of Special Appeals said on Thursday that the
trial judge ruled properly in denying another woman's efforts to
adopt the boy, Cornilous, who is now 2, concluding that the
circumstances that caused the mother to kill _ _ postpartum
depression _ no longer posed a threat to the boy.
</P>
<P>
   The mother, Latrena Pixley of Washington, who is now 26, pleaded
guilty to second-degree murder after suffocating her 6-week-old
daughter, Nakya, and dumping the infant's body in a trash bin. Her
sentence, five to 15 years in prison, was suspended on the
condition that she serve three years of weekends in a halfway
house, followed by probation.
</P>
<P>
   During her probation, Ms. Pixley used stolen Social Security
numbers to obtain credit cards, which she used. She pleaded uilty
to fraud charges and was sentenced to two months in jail and
another month in the halfway house.
</P>
<P>
   Four months after the birth of Cornilous, her fourth child by
four different fathers, Ms. Pixley asked a Montgomery County police
officer, Laura Blankman, to care for him. A year later, Ms.
Blankman tried to adopt the child, arguing that Ms. Pixley was an
unfit mother.
</P>
<P>
   But that effort was blocked last year by a state court, which
ruled that the child's reunion with his mother was ``in his best
interest on a longer-term basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Hall Jr., a lawyer for Ms. Pixley, said on Friday that Ms.
Pixley was ``very pleased'' by the court's ruling, calling it ``one
of the final pieces for getting full-time care and custody of her
son.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pixley, who must live at least another year in the halfway
house, has two other young sons. One lives with his paternal
grandparents, and the other with a foster family in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Poster, a lawyer for Ms. Blankman, did not return a
telephone call, seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   William Pierce, president of the National Council for Adoption,
a nonprofit group based in Washington that assumed some of Ms.
Blankman's legal costs, called the ruling a concession to the
``misguided panacea of family preservation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like a child who has a safe and good home with an
employed police officer will be torn away and turned over to a
convicted child murderer,'' Pierce said. ``This is quite a
commentary on the state of America's judicial system, and sends a
chilling message to anyone in the country who considers stepping
forward to help a child in danger.''
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Hochman, a spokesman for the National Adoption Center, a
Philadelphia organization that helps children in minority groups
and those with special needs find adoption, said that any case in
which a child is returned to a biological parent ``would give
pause'' to people seeking adoption.
</P>
<P>
   Adoptive parents should know, she added, that until biological
parents give up a child for adoption or a court rules against them,
a child is always eligible to be removed from foster care.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the three-judge appeals panel, Judge Joseph Murphy
concluded that Judge Michael Mason of the Montgomery County Circuit
Court was correct in calling Ms. Pixley ``a selfish con artist
whose parental rights should have been terminated.''
</P>
<P>
   But Murphy also ruled that he was more persuaded by Ms. Pixley's
demonstrating that ``she is now free of the mental illness she was
suffering from when she murdered her daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he wrote, Ms. Blankman's objections to the decision
to return Cornilous to Ms. Pixley were correctly overcome by the
judge's determination that the boy did not risk abuse or neglect by
his mother _ the only conditions that the law recognizes to prevent
their reunification.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
