A9962 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-U.S.-SAUDI-BOMBPROBE-     07-10 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-SAUDI-BOMBPROBE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMBING INVESTIGATION CONTINUES, SAUDIS INSIST
</HEADLINE>
 (js) 
By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Saudi government insisted on Friday that the
investigation of a 1996 terrorist bombing that killed 19 U.S.
airmen in Saudi Arabia had not collapsed, and that Saudi law
enforcement officers were cooperating with their U.S. counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   The assertions made here by Prince Abdul Aziz bin Fahd, the
youngest son of King Fahd of Saudi Arabia and a member of the royal
cabinet, contradicted the account of U.S. officials, who have said
in recent weeks that the investigation has broken down because of
disputes with the Saudis.
</P>
<P>
   Out of frustration, the FBI has quietly pulled out the dozens of
investigators who were initially sent to the scene of the bombing,
at the Khobar Towers apartment complex in eastern Saudi Arabia,
leaving behind only a single agent as a liaison to the Saudis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cooperation in this regard between the two governments is
ongoing and continuing because it is of the utmost importance for
both countries,'' Abdul Aziz said at a news conference called after
he met earlier on Friday with President Clinton in the White House.
``Investigations of this nature tend to be complex and require a
lot of time.''
</P>
<P>
   While he said he knew of ``no misunderstanding'' between the two
countries over the investigation, the prince's remarks did seem to
suggest that jurisdictional disputes between the FBI and Saudi law
enforcement officials might be responsible for reports of ill
feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to emphasize that the event occurred in Saudi Arabia,
and the investigation is the responsibility of Saudi Arabian law
enforcement,'' he said. ``The Kingdom of Saudi Arabia has spared no
effort to apprehend the perpetrators of this crime.''
</P>
<P>
   As the case has languished, families of the U.S. victims of the
bombing have begun to complain openly about the slow pace of the
inquiry. They have asserted that the case is not being pursued
aggressively because of U.S. fears of offending Saudi Arabia, an
important oil supplier.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said that the Khobar Towers investigation was not
on the agenda for Friday's 35-minute meeting between the prince and
Clinton, and that the conversation in the White House dealt instead
with the need for continued close ties between the United States
and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   The later news conference was unusual if only because the Saudi
Embassy in Washington rarely sponsors gatherings for U.S. news
organizations. Saudi officials rarely comment publicly on delicate
topics like the Khobar Towers investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But the Saudi government seemed eager to provide a public
showcase for Abdul Aziz, who is only 24 years old and is making his
first official visit to Washington as a member of the Saudi
Cabinet. He is described as a favorite among King Fahd's many
children.
</P>
<P>
   The prince denied reports that the king, who is in his mid-70s,
is seriously ill. The king suffered a stroke in 1995 and was
hospitalized earlier this year after tests and treatment for what
was reported to be an inflamed gall bladder.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father's health, thank God, is good,'' the prince said.
``In fact, it's excellent. He performs normal duties, although he
has some pain in his knees. He continues his government
responsibilities in a normal manner, everyday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
