<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TENORS-WORLD-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE SOCCER FANS, TEAMS GONE, SING ANYWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (js) 
By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ No doubt the Three Tenors would have been even happier
if their teams _ Italy for Luciano Pavarotti, Spain for Placido
Domingo and Jose Carreras _ had not been eliminated from this
year's world soccer championship here. Still, for their third
successive open-air concert before a World Cup final, on Friday
night the three avid soccer fans drew a crowd far larger than the
80,000 people who will watch France play Brazil in the Stade de
France on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Performing beneath a specially constructed covered stage on the
Champs de Mars, with a lighted Eiffel Tower as a magnificent
backdrop, they had a paying audience of some 8,000 people seated
before them but also, in the park beyond, a couple of hundred
thousand more people for whom the two-and-a-half-hour concert,
relayed by loudspeakers and giant screens, was entirely free.
</P>
<P>
   The television audience was even larger. Tubor Rudas, the
Hungarian-born impresario who first brought the three singers
together in Rome in 1990 and organized their 1994 concert in Dodger
Stadium before the 1994 World Cup final in Los Angeles, said he
expected a television audience in excess of 1.3 billion. In the
United States, the concert was broadcast by PBS, live on Friday
afternoon and repeated on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Yet while the concert of operatic arias and popular songs has
become a feature of the soccer championship, its purpose evidently
goes beyond entertaining those who heard it on Friday. With sales
of the albums for the 1990 and 1994 concerts exceeding 23 million
copies, Atlantic Records and Decca Records have invested heavily in
the latest show, confident of strong television, CD and video
sales. As Rudas put it, he was presenting ``a free concert for a
live recording.''
</P>
<P>
   The Three Tenors, who had promised an entirely new program,
spent several months preparing with James Levine, who conducted the
Orchestre de Paris. The composer Lalo Schifrin in turn arranged the
lively crowd-pleasing medleys that brought the three men together
on stage before intermission and again before the final curtain.
These mixed the solemn and the simple, Schubert's ``Serenade'' and
the Mexican bolero ``Solamente Una Vez.'' The inclusion in the
final medley of ``You'll Never Walk Alone,'' from the Rodgers and
Hammerstein musical ``Carousel,'' offered a preview of the concert
single chosen by the tenors to be issued after the concert.
</P>
<P>
   For all the promised novelties, there were also other well-oiled
favorites, although Pavarotti could spots, Domingo and Carreras were more original.
Domingo remembered his parents _ professional zarzuela singers _ by
singing an excerpt from the Spanish zarzuela ``La del Soto del
Parral,'' and he included ``Memoires de Danton,'' a lushly romantic
aria written by his son, also named Placido. From classical operas,
Domingo sang ``Amor ti vieta'' from Giordano's ``Fedora'' and
``Rachel, quand du seigneur'' from Halevy's opera ``La Juive.''
</P>
<P>
   Carreras, in turn, began the evening with ``Io conosco un
giardino'' from Pietri's ``Maristella'' and included Grieg's song
``T'Estimo.'' For much of the audience on Friday, though, the
performance was as important as the program. And as ever, the three
belted out their songs with good humor and panache, Pavarotti
waving his trademark handkerchief, Domingo singing as if addressing
the most distant listener, Carreras trying not to be upstaged by
his better-known partners.
</P>
<P>
   The response was enthusiastic. With each final note, the seated
audience _ paying no less than $1,100 for the best seats _ roared
with delight. This crowd included prosperous Latin Americans in
town for the World Cup final and that well-known U.S. soccer fan
Henry Kissinger. A couple of hundred yards away in the darkened
park, the applause was equally warm. Here the large crowd could see
the tenors only on projection screens, the sound of their voices
slightly out of sync with their lips, but at least they were
compensated by easy access to popcorn, soda and ice cream. When the
show ended, everyone watched fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   The tenors seemed as relaxed as might be expected of a trio that
has performed together before huge crowds on 13 occasions: apart
from their three World Cup shows, they performed in 10 concerts
around the world in 1996 and 1997. And with Pavarotti just 62,
Domingo 57, and Carreras 51, they are not about to retire after
this gig. Not before the year 2002, at least. That is when soccer's
next World Cup will be held in South Korea and Japan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
