u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARINE-FLIERS-NYT &LR;      07-10 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARINE-FLIERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIALS ORDERED FOR 2 MARINE FLIERS IN ITALIAN GONDOLA ACCIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Calif., N.Y.)  (mk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A senior Marine Corps general ordered a court-martial on Friday
on the most serious possible charges for the pilot and the
navigator of an electronic warfare jet that hit a ski lift cable in
Italy in February, killing 20 people.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gen. Peter Pace, commander of the Marines in the Atlantic
fleet, also said that he wanted to conduct a hearing personally to
discipline the commander of the squadron, along with the executive
officer, the director of safety and the operations officer, for
dereliction of duty. They could face loss of pay, confinement to
base and official reprimand.
</P>
<P>
   The case, which has already been the subject of three reports
and seven days of public hearings, has already raised difficult
questions about not only the conduct of the crew but the soundness
of management in the Marine Corps, the U.S. Air Force and the
Defense Mapping Agency and its successor, the National Imagery and
Mapping Agency. Those questions will now be argued in detail at a
court-martial at Camp Lejeune, N.C., probably beginning sometime
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know this is going to be a a knock-down drag-out,'' said
Frank Spinner, the civilian lawyer for the jet's pilot, Capt.
Richard Ashby, 31, of Mission Viejo, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The plane, an EA-6B Prowler based temporarily at an air base in
Aviano, Italy, for duty over Bosnia, was on a training flight
through the Italian Alps when it hit the cable near Cavalese. The
incident has strained American relations with Italy, and a Marine
officer who was a member of a Marine Investigation Board that first
looked into the incident hinted that there had been political
pressure from above to come down hard on the crew.
</P>
<P>
   But administration officials insisted that the White House and
State Department had not brought pressure on the Marines to seek
tougher penalties against the crewmen as a means of appeasing the
Italian government. ``This call was made by the Marines,'' an
official said.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby was sitting in the front cockpit of the jet, at the single
set of flight controls. Next to him in the cockpit, functioning as
mission planner and navigator, was Capt. Joseph Schweitzer, 30, of
Westbury, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A hearing officer who conducted seven days of testimony on the
flight recommended earlier this month that only Ashby should face
the most serious charge, involuntary manslaughter, a crime that
involves ``culpable negligence'' and carries a sentence of up to 10
years for each of the 20 counts. He said the navigator, Schweitzer,
should face the lesser charge of negligent homicide, which carries
a maximum penalty of three years for all counts together.
</P>
<P>
   But Gen. Pace ruled that both should face the more serious
charge. He agreed with the hearing officer that they should also
face charges of damage to military property, damage to private
property and dereliction of duty.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing officer, Lt. Col. Ronald Rodgers, who is a military
judge, said that two officers in the rear cockpit, who did not have
a view out the front and had limited information about the plane's
altitude, should not be court-martialed, and Pace accepted that
recommendation on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But Rodgers also said in his report, released July 2, that he
had ``substantial doubt'' that any of the men could be convicted
because of systematic errors by others, a position stressed by the
defendants' lawyers on Friday. Spinner, in a telephone interview,
said, ``by initiating disciplinary action against these
individuals, that suggests that Pace agrees there was systemic
error, which takes the spotlight off Ashby and the crew and says,
`Hey, there are other problems here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   David Beck, a civilian lawyer representing Schweitzer, said:
``We're not applauding that these four individuals face
punishment.'' But he said of his client: ``Joe is encouraged that
they are looking at other factors.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
