<SLUG> BC-SOC-CUP-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PELE SEES BRAZILIAN WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Pele predicted Friday that his home country, Brazil,
would win the World Cup for the fifth time when it meets France in
the championship game Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brazil has the best attack; France has the best defense,''
Pele said at a news conference to announce a MasterCard-sponsored
All-Star team. ``Both teams will play for the win, but I am sure
France will not play the way they have been playing. They will be
careful. It's normal to be that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brazil will win, of course. Only Brazil has won the World Cup
in Europe, in 1958 against the home team, Sweden. Brazil is playing
against the home team in the final again. Everything is going
normally, then.''
</P>
<P>
   Pele, who has been commentating for a Brazilian television
station, criticized conservative tactics and refereeing. Asked
about Italy's performance, Pele said: ``I am from the school of
football where you play forward. Italy was playing not to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   He said refereeing ``was the low point of the tournament, the
negative, the weak point. Maybe it is because they tried to change
the laws during the tournament and they got mixed up. There were a
lot of bad calls, but the criteria was very confusing.''
</P>
<P>
   Pele provided advice for African teams, which finished with a
combined 3-7-8 record. ``I never said that an African team would
win the World Cup by the year 2000,'' Pele said. ``The African
teams were very good. The problem is that people see something in a
team and they come to find that winning the World Cup is not like
they think. One game can spoil everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very tough tournament, one month long. African
people must do two things if they want to fulfill expectations at
that level: have an organized league inside their country, and the
national team must play abroad, get outside the country, to get
experience, and not just put a team together a few weeks before the
World Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Last chance
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Croatia's Davor Suker has a last chance to challenge for the
World Cup scoring title in Saturday's third-place match between
Croatia and the Netherlands at Parc des Princes. Suker is tied with
Ronaldo (Brazil), Luis Hernandez (Mexico), and Marcelo Salas
(Chile) with four goals, one behind Gabriel Batistuta (Argentina)
and Christian Vieri (Italy).
</P>
<P>
   If Croatia wins, it will be the best finish by a first-time
World Cup finals qualifier since Portugal in 1966, when Eusebio led
the event with nine goals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Stars of show
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The All-Star team included goalkeepers Fabian Barthez (France)
and Jose Luis Chilavert (Paraguay); defenders Roberto Carlos
(Brazil), Frank De Boer (Netherlands), Marcel Desailly (France),
Lilian Thuram (France), and Carlos Gamarra (Paraguay); midfielders
Edgar Davids (Netherlands), Dunga (Brazil), Michael Laudrup
(Denmark), Rivaldo (Brazil), and Zinedine Zidane (France); and
forwards Dennis Bergkamp (Netherlands), Brian Laudrup (Denmark),
Ronaldo (Brazil), and Suker (Croatia).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 2009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0313 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9976 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-NYT &LR;      07-10 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRENGTH AGAINST STRENGTH: BRAZIL'S OFFENSE VS. FRANCE'S DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLAIREFONTAINE, France _ For anyone who has followed the career
paths of the defenders on the French World Cup team, it is no
surprise that they have been the finest in the world for the past
month. What is a surprise is that between them, they have managed
to outscore Ronaldo: 5 goals to 4.
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldo, the Brazilian striker with the muscular thighs and
wicked first step, has no intention of being overshadowed in
Sunday's World Cup final against France, but even at age 21, he has
seen enough tactical systems and hard tackles to know excellence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true that they are very, very solid defensively,'' he
said. ``They have hardly shown any weaknesses.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be strength against strength in the Stade de France:
Ronaldo, Rivaldo, Bebeto and Brazil's two offensive-minded outside
fullbacks, Cafu and Roberto Carlos, against the French back line
and defensive midfielders.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever wins that struggle probably wins the game, and according
to the French, they do not intend to win it by sticking a single,
bold defender on Ronaldo. They will share the responsibility:
switching, adjusting, double-teaming when necessary and pushing
forward when possible.
</P>
<P>
   Since the knockout round of this World Cup began, all three of
France's goals have been scored by players whose customary role is
to make it difficult for opposing strikers. Central defender
Laurent Blanc scored the first golden goal in World Cup history to
break a scoreless tie against Paraguay in the second round. Right
back Lilian Thuram scored twice against Croatia in the semifinals
after having never scored before in 37 previous international
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Blanc won't play on Sunday _ a major loss _ because he received
a questionable red card against Croatia. But there are plenty of
world-class defenders left in the French half of the field. Seven
men will try to keep Brazil from having a fifth title to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   FABIEN BARTHEZ
</P>
<P>
   POSITION: Goalkeeper. AGE: 27. INTERNATIONAL MATCHES: 19. CLUB:
Monaco.
</P>
<P>
   Barthez won his spot over the veteran goalkeeper Bernard Lama,
who like Barthez, served a several-month suspension after testing
positive for marijuana. Barthez is an imposing presence: excellent
in the air but less adept at distribution. In 1993, he was the
goalkeeper on the Olympique Marseilles team that won France's first
European Champions Cup title. In this tournament, Barthez has given
up only two goals in six games (one on a penalty kick), and his
shaved head has become a French talisman. Blanc has kissed it on
the field before every game, and despite his suspension, Blanc
plans to kiss it again on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   BIXENTE LIZARAZU
</P>
<P>
   POSITION: Left back. AGE: 28. INTERNATIONAL MATCHES: 38. CLUB:
Bayern Munich (Germany).
</P>
<P>
   A Basque who played for the quintessential Basque club, Athletic
Bilbao, in Spain before moving to Munich last season, Lizarazu is
short, extremely fast and the most consistently offensive of the
French defenders. The player called Liza was in danger of losing
his spot on the team after missing the early season with an injury,
but Coach Aime Jacquet kept the faith and Lizarazu has done nothing
to make him lose it this summer.
</P>
<P>
   MARCEL DESAILLY
</P>
<P>
   POSITION: Central defender. AGE: 29. INTERNATIONAL MATCHES: 48.
CLUB: AC Milan (Italy).
</P>
<P>
   Desailly has been arguably France's finest player in this World
Cup. He has not lost a duel yet, and though he has yet to score a
goal, he hopes to rectify that against Brazil. He is sensitive,
occasionally abrasive and powerful on land and in the air. Desailly
was born in Ghana and moved to the French mainland at the age of 6
after his mother, a Ghanan, married a Frenchman. Like Barthez, he
was part of the Marseilles club that won France's first European
Champions Cup title in 1993. Desailly won a Champion's League title
with Milan in 1994 playing in midfield. He will be leaving AC Milan
for Chelsea in England next season. Lucky Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   FRANK LEBOEUF
</P>
<P>
   POSITION: central defender. AGE: 30. INTERNATIONAL MATCHES: 15.
CLUB: Chelsea (England).
</P>
<P>
   Desailly's future teammate was relatively unknown when he left
for England two years ago. On the other side of the channel,
Leboeuf has become a star and occasional newspaper columnist. Adept
in the air and at man marking, he also has a way with a free kick,
but he does not have the presence, speed or international
experience of Blanc. Expect the Brazilians to test him often.
</P>
<P>
   LILIAN THURAM
</P>
<P>
   POSITION: right back. AGE: 26. INTERNATIONAL MATCHES: 26. CLUB:
Parma (Italy).
</P>
<P>
   Even before he became a national savior against Croatia, Thuram
was considered France's finest defender. A central defender with
his club, his effectiveness and confidence have increased
substantially since he left Monaco for Italy two years ago. Fast,
agile and likable, he is now giving the three-time Olympic gold
medalist Marie-Jose Perec a run for the title of most popular
athlete from the French island of Guadeloupe. Raised by his mother,
he moved to the Paris suburbs at 9.
</P>
<P>
   DIDIER DESCHAMPS
</P>
<P>
   POSITION: defensive midfielder. AGE: 29. INTERNATIONAL MATCHES:
75. CLUB: Juventus of Turin (Italy).
</P>
<P>
   He is the captain and one of the few links to the French team
that failed to qualify for the last World Cup. Deschamps, a Basque
like Lizarazu, plays with the French playmaker Zinedine Zidane at
Juventus, the club owned by the Agnelli family, which owns Fiat.
Small and smart, Deschamps covers enormous ground and is a fine
tackler and clogger of passing lanes. He quit soccer for six months
as a teen-ager after his older brother died in an airplane crash.
Deschamps is a close friend of Desailly _ he is the godfather of
one of his children _ and a distant cousin of the Wimbledon women's
finalist, Nathalie Tauziat.
</P>
<P>
   EMMANUEL PETIT
</P>
<P>
   POSITION: defensive midfielder. AGE: 27. INTERNATIONAL MATCHES:
25. CLUB: Arsenal (England)
</P>
<P>
   As recently as last spring, the swashbuckling Petit was
considered unlikely to make the 22-man French team, but his fine
season at Arsenal under the French Coach Arsene Wenger earned him a
spot in the starting lineup. A phenom as a teen-ager, he later lost
his way after a divorce and, like Deschamps, the death of a
brother, but Petit has learned to think and play positively again. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
