<HEADLINE>
STRONG ASKS FOR MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 12.)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.)  
 (JT)  
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Strong Capital Management, which recently announced a shake-up
of several funds, is seeking approval from its board to merge the
Strong Small Cap fund into the Strong Growth fund.
</P>
<P>
   For investors in the Small-Cap fund, the move is the second big
change in two months. At the end of May, Strong announced that
Scott Sindelar, a portfolio manager from Mid-Continent Capital in
Chicago, would succeed Mary Lisanti as manager of the fund, which
had lagged behind its peers. Ms. Lisanti left Strong to become
chief of equity investing at Northstar Investment Management in
Stamford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first interest was to appoint a manager to continue to run
the fund for shareholders after Mary's departure,'' said Jody Lowe,
a spokeswoman for Strong. ``After that, we looked carefully at the
fund. Assets have dropped from $230 million to $136 million, and
its relevant track record is such that we believe it would be
difficult to turn the cash flows around.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors in Strong Small Cap should be aware that although
Strong Growth has an enviable record, it holds stocks of a variety
of market capitalizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not what you bought,'' warned Susan Belden, editor of the
No-Load Fund Analyst in Orinda, Calif., referring to the stocks in
the Small Cap fund. ``If you want small-cap exposure, bail out.''
She added, however, that investors should consider the tax
consequences of selling.
</P>
<P>
   Strong also announced three new offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Sindelar will run Strong Strategic Growth, a U.S. stock fund
that invests in inexpensive medium- and large-cap growth stocks.
</P>
<P>
   David Lui, who took over Strong International Stock from Anthony
Cragg at the end of May, will run Strong Overseas, which will
invest in at least 10 countries outside the United States at all
times. Lui joined Strong from Phoenix Duff &AMP; Phelps.
</P>
<P>
   Strong Foreign Major Markets will use a quantitative,
value-oriented approach to investing in each of the countries in
the Morgan Stanley Capital International Europe Australasia and Far
East index. It will be managed by Shirish Malekar, who runs
Strong's International Bond, Short-Term Global Bond and Global High
Yield Bond funds.
</P>
<P>
   The new funds will have a $2,500 minimum.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New Funds &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Invesco Funds has started Invesco Growth and Income. The lead
manager of the fund is Trent May, also the lead manager of Invesco
Growth and co-manager of Invesco Small Company Growth. Co-manager
of the new fund will be Fritz Meyer, who manages separate accounts.
The minimum investment is $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Transamerica Premier Funds has started a junk bond fund,
Transamerica Premier High Yield Bond, to be managed by Heather
Creeden, who has managed a separate junk bond account since 1991.
The fund's minimum investment is $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
