</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INFLATION-BOND-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME INFLATION PROTECTION FOR U.S. SAVINGS BONDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 12.)  
 (JT)  
 By EDWARD WYATT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Uncles everywhere will sleep better.
</P>
<P>
   The government savings bond, that favorite gift of unimaginative
relatives _ appropriate for birthdays and graduations, for a
confirmation or a bar mitzvah _has been embellished to keep up with
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Treasury Department announced that beginning on
Sept. 1 it will sell Series I savings bonds, which will provide
protection against a general rise in consumer prices. The interest
paid will be pegged partly to changes in the Consumer Price Index.
As with the current Series EE savings bonds, holders can defer tax
payments on their earnings until a bond is redeemed. Based on
current interest rates and inflation prospects, the bonds are
expected to earn a real return of about 3 percent after inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The bonds will supplement, rather than replace, the Treasury's
offerings of Series EE savings bonds, much as the inflation-indexed
Treasury bonds introduced last year gave investors a new option to
invest in government securities. Both offer a way to hedge against
the erosion of principal from inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the inflation-indexed bonds, which were at best a
moderate success with individual investors, the new securities may
help to revive sales of savings bonds, which in recent years have
been losing popularity to stocks and mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   Savings bonds have a reputation as a sleepy investment, but they
are one of the country's most widely held securities. Roughly one
in three American households, and 55 million individuals, own
government savings bonds, with most of those investors buying the
bonds through payroll deduction plans, said Daniel Pederson,
president of the Savings Bond Investor, a Detroit-based information
service for investors.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the ubiquity of savings bonds, Americans' holdings have
remained about $185 billion since 1995, according to the Flow of
Funds report from the Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Now, investors have a more compelling option for the
conservative end of the portfolio, even if they don't believe that
higher inflation looms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody will say that they'll give mutual funds
a run for their money,'' Pederson said. ``But they can earn two to
three points better than inflation.''
</P>
<P>
   High-income individuals close to retirement are likely to be
drawn to the new bonds. They are likely to want to protect their
portfolios from inflation without generating more income, which
would require payment of federal income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings rate of the new savings bond is a combination of a
fixed interest rate, specified at the time of purchase, and an
inflation rate, adjusted semiannually.
</P>
<P>
   The Series I bonds will be sold at face value _ rather than at
50 percent of face, as Series EE bonds are _ in denominations of
$50, $75, $100, $500, $1,000 and $5,000. Beginning in May 1999,
denominations of $200 and $10,000 will be added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 2013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
