<HEADER>
A9987 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-10 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: OVER AND OVER AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If someone were to make a movie about the Mideast peace process,
there could be only one appropriate title: ``Groundhog Day'' _
where the same day, the same discussions, just get repeated over
and over. But even Groundhog Day eventually came to an end. And so
will the peace process version. It closes May 4, 1999 _ the day the
Oslo agreement runs out.
</P>
<P>
   Circle May 4 on your calendar, Middle East fans, and think what
it could portend. If Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and the
Palestinian chief Yasser Arafat quickly can conclude this
long-delayed second redeployment in the West Bank, learn to work
together and begin serious talks about a final status agreement,
then May 4 will be no problem. Even though Oslo will have run out,
the two sides will have a framework of understandings and a pathway
of negotiations that can sustain the peace beyond the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   But if Groundhog Day continues until May 4, 1999 _ with
Netanyahu dragging out the negotiations on issues that are not
fundamental to Israel's security, with Arafat hoping that the
longer things are dragged out the more pressure Bibi will be unrafat, who is not a healthy man, may well
choose to declare a Palestinian state in the West Bank and Gaza to
complete his life's work before he dies.
</P>
<P>
   That Palestinian mini-state could engage in trade, treaties and
other actions without regard to Israel. Netanyahu would then have
only terrible choices: annex those areas that the Palestinians
don't control in the West Bank, set up a blockade of the new
Palestinian state (which would cost Israeli businesses $3 billion
in exports a year) or send Israeli boys to recapture the West Bank
from the self-declared Palestinian state. There is no way that
Egypt or Jordan could continue relations as usual with Israel in
the wake of any of the above.
</P>
<P>
   Khalil Shikaki, who heads up polling at the Center for Palestine
Research in Nablus, told me: ``Last year only a small percentage of
Palestinians were in favor of declaring a Palestinian state, no
matter what. Now the number is 57 percent, and it will get to 90
percent by May 1999 if there is no agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of a war between Israeli troops and Palestinian
police would be very high. Look what happened last week. Israeli
troops and Palestinian police got into a standoff at a Gaza
intersection over an issue of free passage.
</P>
<P>
   Because communication between Netanyahu and Arafat is
nonexistent, they had to call the U.S. envoy, Dennis Ross, at his
home in Bethesda, Md., to sort it out. That is pathetic. After May
4, every other intersection in the West Bank and Gaza will be a
potential flashpoint. What if Ross' kids are on the phone?
</P>
<P>
   When Israeli President Ezer Weizman took the highly unusual step
of denouncing Netanyahu as a liar who is undermining Oslo, what he
was essentially saying was that Netanyahu seems incapable of
playing the historic role that many, including myself, have hoped
he would: that is to advance the peace process, albeit in his own
more cautious fashion, so as to bring along as much of the Israeli
right as possible but still, at the end of the day, make the tough,
necessary compromises.
</P>
<P>
   Weizman was right to raise that question. Shimon Peres believed
Oslo was a moral imperative. Yitzhak Rabin believed it was a
strategic imperative. Bibi seems to believe neither. He views Oslo
as a political issue that needs to be managed up or down _
whichever way boosts his political fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   Notes the Middle East expert Stephen Cohen: ``If people thought
Bibi was truly committed to the logic of Oslo _ that the only way
forward is through mutual recognition between the two peoples and
mutual cooperation between the two political leaderships _ they
would believe he is sincere in looking for alternative ways to
achieve its objectives. But what Weizman was saying was that Bibi
has left too many people in doubt. And the hour is getting late.''
</P>
<P>
   It's still not too late, but the breakthrough has to happen now.
If Groundhog Day plays until May 4, the next movie will be
Titanic. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 2014EDT &QL; 
