<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   US-RUSSIA _ MOSCOW _ U.S. President Bill Clinton and Russian
President Boris Yeltsin had made no secret over the last several
months that they would like to have a summit in the fall. As
Clinton wound down his long trip to China, the word began spreading
that he was leaning toward just such a meeting. After confirming it
on Monday, the White House can expect a wave of criticism from
opponents near the level it received before the China trip. There's
plenty of ammunition: the sickly Russian economy; Kosovo upheaval;
India-Pakistan nuclear race; trade with Iran; NATO expansion; and
space cooperation. Clinton had been awaiting Russia's Parliament to
ratify the SALT II nuclear arms pact, but his decision to go seems
to be aimed at pressuring the Duma into such a ratification vote.
(Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With US-RUSSIA-BOX _ The issues facing a Clinton-Yeltsin summit.
(Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move Thursday, July 9.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-BACKLASH _ TEHRAN, Iran _ Iran's conservatives are fighting
back. A year after the election of the moderate but not powerful
President Mohammed Khatami, concerned fundamentalists have arrested
and impeached key supporters. The political climate seems to swing
daily between reform and backlash. The clash between Iran's two
cultures is as clear as the difference between two of its
provacative publications _ one preserving the past, the other
looking forward. At Shalamche magazine's storefront office, the
walls are covered in burlap, one corner is ringed with sandbags and
artilery shells are used for decoration. The young staff won't meet
with foreign journalists, but their magazine outlines their view
that Islamic values are under attack. Though the Iran-Iraq war is
over, Shalamche has a new target across town: The Jamaeh daily.
Jameah has become a symbol of Iran in transition. The daily, one of
more than 300 new publications since Khatami's election, pokes fun
at political leaders and prints long interviews with dissidents.
Its office is also staffed with young idealists, but it's in a
California-style villa. The wall in Jameah carries a
tongue-in-cheek staff petition asking editors why the swimming pool
is empty. But, Jamaeh has bigger problems than an empty pool.
Attacked in court by three conservative groups, the paper has been
ordered to close. We are moving from traditionalism to modernism,''
says the paper's editor Mashallah hamsolivin. Don't let this
newborn baby, the election, die now.'' (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   JOURNAL-IRAN _ TEHRAN, Iran _ These are nervous times in Tehran.
I could sense the difference from my last trip in December, when
reformers were gleeful about the prospects for changing their
fundamentalist nation under newly-elected President Mohammed
Khatami. Now, reformers are channel surfing between World Cup
soccer games and the trial of a popular mayor, accused of
corruption by a justice system run by religious hardliners. Though
Tehran is full of articulate, informed people with a lot to say,
slightly fewer wanted to be quoted this time. The day after
watching a World Cup match with a group of young Iranians, one
called and asked that I not tell anyone I was with them. These
days, hanging out with foreign journalists can be controversial,
especially if the evening in question included cassettes of Western
dance music. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move Thursday, July 9.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   NIH _ WASHINGTON _ In the middle of fights over campaign
finances, tobacco legislation and other bones of contention,
President Clinton, House Speaker Newt Gingrich, the Senate
Republican leaders and congressional Democrats all agree on a
fairly major initiative: that the research budget of the National
Institutes of Health should be dramatically increased, even doubled
over the next decade. To officials at Emory University in Atlanta,
which hopes to propel itself into one of the top 10 research
institutions in the country during that time, this is welcome news.
The University of Texas, Eastern Carolina University and other
universitities around the country are also thrilled at the prospect
of easier access to what is already the largest pool of research
money in the world, by a factor of 10. Why is this idea suddenly so
popular? There are several theories, including the fact that
politicians sense that meaningful medical breakthroughs lie just
ahead and the aging of the politically powerful Baby Boomers, who
are now reaching the stage in life where their own health has
replaced earlier concerns. (Nesmith, Cox News Service 1250)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY-MAIN _ Not since the '50s have things been this good
this long. Not only are most people living better, a DDN poll shows
a majority believe the best is yet to come. With things going so
well, cities throughout the country are looking for ways to sustain
the good times. Seattle is one of the leaders in the sustainability
movement, which seeks to identify the strengths and weaknesses in a
community and target problem areas for future growth. (Dempsey,
Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY-RICH _ Used to be, you were a millionaire if you
earned that much during your lifetime. Now, the definition is
changing as even ordinary people are making millions off the stock
market in a single year. (Shepard, Cox News Service)
</P>
