<HEADER>
A9993 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-AGING-ADVICE-A     07-10 1256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-AGING-ADVICE-ART-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOULD OCTOGENARIANS WALK ON THE WILD SIDE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 12.)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.)  
 (JT)  
 By LAURA PEDERSEN-PIETERSEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 87 years old and looking for investment advice _ not tax
avoidance schemes _ specifically for my age group.
</P>
<P>
   _MARTIN FIELD, Laguna Hills, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. Hang on while I turn down the gramophone, fill up my fountain
pen and grab a grape Nehi out of the icebox. If you think financial
planners have passed you by in favor of those 60-something
whippersnappers down the block, don't fret. Brokers may soon make
cold calls based on black-market lists of videophiles who've rented
Walter Matthau movies.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? The number of Americans who are 85 or older is
rising rapidly: The total jumped 51 percent from 1980 to 1996, and
it is expected to climb an additional 32 percent by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Gerontologists, not to mention marketers, already call this age
group the ``oldest old'' _ an unfortunate moniker that sounds only
slightly better than ``prime of geezerdom.'' Likewise, people in
the 75-to-84 age group have been classified as the ``young old''
(though you'll find that many women still prefer ``of a certain
age,'' especially if you don't want a hatbox in the face).
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, many brokers have guided Generation A away from
owning stocks _ and toward bonds, fixed-income securities and
certificates of deposit. And if we're talking about the money you
need to live on, that is probably sound advice.
</P>
<P>
   Take it from Edward Polisher, a 96-year-old estate planning
lawyer at Cozen &AMP; O'Connor in Philadelphia. ``I wouldn't invest
money in equities at my age,'' Polisher said. ``First of all, my
blood pressure can't take the gyrations of this market and second,
if stocks go down, there's no time to make it back.''
</P>
<P>
   Polisher knows about plunging prices _ he was married on Oct.
29, 1929. Nearly 70 years later, he says, he puts his money in
government bonds or tax-free securities and ``invests in people'' _
in worthy causes like underwriting a lecture series at his alma
mater.
</P>
<P>
   A case can also be made, however, for taking some financial
risks as you head toward the big double-zero. ``The idea of putting
money you don't need to live on in bonds and fixed-income
securities is ludicrous,'' declared Venita VanCaspelcq, a former
Houston stockbroker, in a feisty, Ann Richards-sounding, ``I love
you but cut the cards'' Texas drawl.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. VanCaspel, the author of six books on investing, argued that
``for one, the bond market, like the stock market, fluctuates, and,
two, you'll never keep pace with inflation.''
</P>
<P>
   What to do? ``If you want access to a certain amount of your
cash then use a money market account,'' she said. For the rest, she
advises sticking with stocks. Ms. VanCaspel, herself of a certain
age, said: ``Pick a mutual fund with a lot of large-cap and
blue-chip stocks. Most older people have other interests than the
stock market'' and thus don't have time to track individual stocks.
</P>
<P>
   She recommended three funds for the older investor: Investment
Company of America and Washington Mutual Investors, both part of
the American Funds, and Janus Worldwide. If you need monthly
income, she suggests setting up a check-a-month withdrawal program.
</P>
<P>
   She approves of buying individual stocks, as long as you have
the time, training, temperament and money to diversify. ``As we
mature emotionally, we tend to clutch our money a little harder,''
she said, mindful of Jackie Mason's remark: ``I've got enough money
to last the rest of my life, unless I buy something.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. VanCaspel advised steering clear of options and commodities
and anything else with a prospectus that weighs more than the last
issue of Modern Maturity magazine. For many people, she says, that
means sticking ``with companies such as Coca-Cola, GE and Wal-Mart
_ makers or providers of things that people use all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Owning high-technology stocks can be OK, too, despite their
volatility, she said. But if you want to trade them, she warned,
``your timing has to be excellent.'' She suggests buying through a
technology mutual fund like Seligman Communications and Information
class A or T. Rowe Price Science and Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Pierre Schoenheimer, a New York money manager, has an
89-year-old client who has used a simple, buy-and-hold approach to
market success without reaching for his beta blocker pills. The
client's portfolio consists of one corporate bond and 13 stocks _
mostly in phone, real estate and banking sectors. All 13 had
returns above the market average last year.
</P>
<P>
   James O'Shaughnessy, chairman of O'Shaughnessy Funds in
Greenwich, Conn., and author of ``How to Retire Rich'' (Broadway
Books, $25) offers a different conservative strategy: Go to the
top-ranked stocks in the Value Line Investment Survey and buy the
10 that pay the highest dividends. This will net you mostly utility
companies like Ameren, Allegheny Energy, Laclede Gas and New
England Electric.
</P>
<P>
   And Ms. VanCaspel is adamant that when it comes to Europe over
the next two years, no one _ octogenarian or otherwise _ should sit
on the sidelines. ``They're doing all the things we did 10 years
ago _ downsizing, restructuring, and getting more competitive,''
she said of the Europeans. ``The common currency will be
fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   Yale Hirsch, editor of the Stock Trader's Almanac, also thinks
it's folly to let dormant dollars gather prune-juice rings. But he
suggests pushing the envelope further, into a hedge fund. Such
funds can take long and short positions, use leverage and invest in
derivatives, thus increasing potential risks and rewards. Hirsch,
who is so coy about his age that I suspect he may know all of
Franklin D. Roosevelt's campaign song, ``Happy Days Are Here
Again,'' asks, ``Why not increase your net worth as much as
possible in order to pass it on to your heirs?''
</P>
<P>
   For information, you may want to pick up ``Fundamentals of Hedge
Fund Investing,'' by William J. Crerend (McGraw-Hill, $55), or
subscribe to MAR-Hedge, a monthly newsletter that ranks and tracks
1,300 hedge funds. (800 638-2525, $495 a year).
</P>
<P>
   But before you set your sundial by all this information,
consider a man who has decided to invest in his old age by
investing in old age itself _ by trying to abolish it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nine years ago I decided that I felt great and was happy and
wanted to live much longer,'' said Miller Quarles, 83. In the
American do-it-yourself tradition, Quarles, a Houston geophysicist,
started the Geron Corporation, a biopharmaceutical company in Menlo
Park, Calif., whose mission is to develop products for treating
cancer and other age-related diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ``There must be a longevity gene in every living thing that
determines the time of death for each species,'' Quarles said. ``Or
how else would you have butterflies which last only two days and
down in the Galapagos Islands, turtles living for 200 years?''
</P>
<P>
   Quarles is clearly aligning himself with the turtles. He has
founded the Curing Old Age Disease Society (713-654-0194) in
addition to offering a $100,000 prize to anyone who finds a cure
for aging by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   While the reward waits at Nationsbank, Quarles receives many
letters asking him to first send the prize money and promising the
cure later. No dice. ``I wasn't born yesterday,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
