<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9998 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-DISNEY-HNS &LR;      07-10 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DISNEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS EDUCATION BOARD VOTES 8-4 TO SELL DISNEY STOCK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The State Board of Education voted 8-4 Friday to
stake out a moral high ground and sell off $43 million of Walt
Disney Co. stock in protest over violent and sexually explicit
movies and recordings made by Disney subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   The vote followed more than a year of pressure from the
conservative American Family Association to get the board to divest
its Disney stock, initially on the basis of obscene lyrics on
record albums produced by Disney subsidiaries. Later, complaints
were raised over the violence, sex and drug use depicted in some
films produced by Disney-owned Miramax Films.
</P>
<P>
   But the AFA also has been involved in a national boycott of
Disney over its internal policies to grant health benefits to
domestic partners of gay and lesbian employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally believe that a vote to divest is political
hypocrisy,'' said board member Alma Allen of Houston, a public
schools administrator and one of four Democrats voting against the
measure. ``We have other (morally questionable) stocks that we've
invested in.
</P>
<P>
   ``So if we're going to be pure and clean and devoid of sin,''
she added, ``then let's totally divest and get out of the
investment business all together and just go with (certificates of
deposit).''
</P>
<P>
   Other holdings by the $17.6 billion Permanent School Fund are
Harrah's Entertainment Inc., a casino operator, Anheuser-Busch
Companies Inc. and Asahi Breweries Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   Education Commissioner Mike Moses, out of town on vacation,
directed investment managers for the school fund to sell the Disney
stock ``as expeditiously as possible,'' said Debbie Graves
Ratcliffe, spokeswoman for the Texas Education Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Disney spokeswoman Claudia Peters noted that Texas is the first
state fund to divest its stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our company has been achieving 20 percent compound annual
growth in earnings per share over the past several years,'' she
said. ``The Walt Disney Company produces more family entertainment
than any other company in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that movies for mature audiences are produced by
subsidiaries that do not carry the Disney name and adhere to the
Motion Picture Association of America rating system.
</P>
<P>
   Grace Shore of Longview, who was appointed to the board last
November by Bush, was one of eight Republicans to vote for dumping
Disney. She said it makes financial sense to sell the stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been taught to buy low and sell high,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we're going to take the money we make from
selling Disney and throw it in a hole. Maybe it's time to take the
profit and run.''
</P>
<P>
   Voting against the measure were Allen and fellow Democrats Joe
Bernal of San Antonio, Will Davis of Austin and Rosie Sorrells of
Dallas. Two other Democrats abstained; Rene Nunez of El Paso and
Mary Helen Berlanga of Corpus Christi both are locked in tough
re-election battles with social conservatives. Republican member
Monte Hasie of Lubbock was absent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of issues that people could get uptight about,
but when you start trying to draw parameters ... then you start
making moral judgments, social judgments, other judgments that some
of us will support and some of us will criticize,'' said Davis, who
had tried to stall the issue in committee earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   Sorrells said she was ``totally against singling out Disney''
and that if the board did not want to invest in companies doing
``inappropriate things,'' the board needed to re-examine all its
investments.
</P>
<P>
   Berlanga said that while she thinks parents need to take a stand
against allowing children to view ``movies like those where Arnold
Schwarzenegger appears, where there's so much violence,'' it would
be inappropriate to make investment decisions based on moral
viewpoints. She added that her decision to abstain from voting
would give managers the flexibility to make such decisions at the
appropriate time.
</P>
<P>
   Even some of the Republicans who voted in favor of divestiture
had concerns about the impact of their decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the future will there be any policies or something written
as a guide over issues like this?'' asked GOP member Geraldine
``Tincy'' Miller of Dallas. ``Or are we just going to react as we
go down the road?
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand the concern and I'm very sympathetic, but I'm
also listening and hearing a lot of other people say we have a lot
of other companies that are in the entertainment business that do
things that maybe we don't approve of.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that ``in the future I'm concerned this could be a
domino effect on our investments and what impact that would have on
the return on our investments for the children.''
</P>
<P>
   Board Chairman Jack Christie of Houston said he expects the
Texas Legislature next session to provide guidelines on appropriate
investments of tax dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Others voting in favor of divesting included David Bradley of
Beaumont, Richard Neill of Fort Worth, Robert Offutt of San
Antonio, Randy Stevenson of Bullard and Richard Watson of Gorman.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush, also a Republican, has said that investment
decisions should be made on the basis of financial return on
investments. On Friday, spokeswoman Linda Edwards said the governor
stands by his earlier statements that, ``The board members are
independently elected, and it's their decision to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's vote represents the first time the board has ordered
investment managers of the public school trust fund to make a
specific sale or buy, said Ratcliffe of the TEA.
</P>
<P>
   In years past, however, the Permanent School Fund has taken its
cue from state leaders who encouraged divestiture of other stocks
for moral reasons. For example, last year a fund manager sold $3.5
million in stock in Seagram Co. one day after Republican state Sen.
Bill Ratliff, chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, protested
the ``filth'' on Seagram's MCA record albums.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, investment managers sold off all holdings in tobacco
companies at the urging of Christie and Attorney General Dan
Morales. At issue then was Morales' decision to file suit against
tobacco companies in an effort to recoup money spent by Texas on
tobacco-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
