u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABORTION-CONTRACEPTIV     07-10 1302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-CONTRACEPTIVES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE GROUPS MOUNT CAMPAIGN AGAINST PRESCRIBED BIRTH CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Right-to-life groups and the Roman Catholic Church
have mounted an assault on legislation that would require health
plans to pay for prescription contraceptives, an issue that was
gaining some momentum in the wake of insurers' initial embrace of
Viagra, the impotence drug.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the effort oppose any government funding of
abortions, and believe that some forms of contraception amount to
abortion in fact if not in name.
</P>
<P>
   But family-planning advocates say they are alarmed by what
appears to be a new front in the war over a woman's right to
prevent pregnancy: an attack on paying for drugs such as
birth-control pills and Norplant implants, and intrauterine
devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time we have seen social conservatives in
Congress come out directly against contraceptives and take up the
line of the Catholic Church,'' says Wendy Turnbull, a lobbyist for
the Alan Guttmacher Institute, which studies reproductive issues.
``They are showing their true colors, which is to oppose not just
abortion but any family planning methods.''
</P>
<P>
   Up to now, the abortion debate has been largely over procedures
and drugs that end a pregnancy. Now, abortion opponents in Congress
are attacking forms of contraception, such as the Pill and IUDs.
And the arguments don't always distinguish between pregnancy
prevention and termination.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Christopher Smith, a New Jersey Republican and
one of Congress's most ardent abortion foes, is leading the House
opposition to contraceptive coverage. ``His position is that
chemicals that produce abortions should not be covered by taxpayer
dollars,'' said spokesman Ken Wolfe.
</P>
<P>
   Activists for women's health admit they have taken advantage of
the huge hype around Viagra _ and the initial rush by insurers to
cover prescriptions for it _ to push to end what they consider an
inequity in reproductive rights. For years, groups like Planned
Parenthood have complained that women are shortchanged because half
of all private insurers don't pay for the Pill or other
prescription contraceptives.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put a product that enables men to be sexually active and
is covered by health insurance next to products that enable women
to be sexually active without getting pregnant and are not
covered,'' said Carol Weisman, a professor at the University of
Michigan School of Public Health. ``Suddenly people start paying
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Nita Lowey, a Democrat from New York, had the
first success. The House Appropriations Committee approved the
fiscal 1999 Treasury-Postal spending bill with Lowey's amendment
requiring the government to provide more than 2 million federal
workers with insurance coverage for contraceptives.
</P>
<P>
   But when the bill came to the House floor late last month, Smith
and Representative David McIntosh, Republican of Indiana,
circulated a memo urging colleagues to vote down the rule for
debating the spending bill because the Lowey amendment would
encourage abortions. The rule was defeated.
</P>
<P>
   The National Right to Life Committee lobbied lawmakers to oppose
Lowey's amendment, as did the National Conference of Catholic
Bishops, which asserted in a letter that ``drugs such as Norplant,
Depo-Provera, and the low-estrogen Pill sometimes act not by
preventing ovulation or fertilization, but by preventing the embryo
from implanting in the womb.'' The so-called ``morning after pill''
approved by the Food and Drug Administration as an emergency
contraceptive falls in the same category, the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Alvare, a spokesman for the Catholic Conference, says the
issue is ``new, different...and tricky'' because it requires people
to understand that the church defines IUDs and Norplant, which
prevent implantation of a fertilized egg in the womb, as
abortion-inducing drugs, not as contraceptives.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the Lowey measure _ which expressly prohibits
insurance coverage for abortions _ say they were blindsided by the
antiabortion opposition. Lowey says her amendment had strong
bipartisan support, the blessing of the House GOP leadership, and
was aimed at finding some rare common ground in Congress on a
family planning issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of Americans support contraception. I would
venture that the majority of Americans use contraception,
regardless of their religion,'' Lowey said. ``I don't think
Congress has any business debating whether women should have access
to it, and the fact that we are just shows that the extreme right
wing has taken over the Republican agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowey says she hasn't given up on her measure, but lobbyists for
family- planning groups say the debate has soured the climate and
made lawmakers who fear the abortion issue reluctant to touch her
amendment in an election year.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible victim of the abortion fight could be a Senate
bill, co-authored by Republican Olympia Snowe of Maine and Democrat
Harry Reid of Nevada, that would require health insurance plans
that cover prescriptions to also provide benefits for
contraceptives. A hearing on the measure is scheduled for later
this month.
</P>
<P>
   Reid, an abortion opponent, said he is sponsoring the bill
because making contraceptive drugs and services more available
would reduce both the number of unintended pregnancies and
abortions. The average annual cost of adding health insurance
coverage for contraceptives would be $21 a year, according to the
Guttmacher Institute, a New York-based nonprofit group.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland recently became the first state to mandate that private
insurers offering prescription coverage pay for all contraceptives,
while six other states require some level of coverage. In
Massachusetts, Senator Dianne Wilkerson has proposed a bill to make
contraceptive coverage mandatory. A spokesman said the senator
expects the measure to pass muster with both the right-to-life and
church groups and emerge soon from committee.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent survey by the Kaiser Family Foundation, 75
percent of Americans favor such legislation, and 73 percent say
they would support it even if it meant their insurance premiums
would rise. Women spend an estimated 68 percent more than men for
health care each year, a gap explained in part by out-of-pocket
costs for contraceptives, the Guttmacher Institute reported.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance industry has vowed to fight the
contraceptive-coverage bills in Congress ``regardless of the
merits,'' because mandated benefits drive up costs and hurt
consumers, said Richard Coorsh, a spokesman for the Health
Insurance Association of America, a private group.
</P>
<P>
   ``These providers pay for abortions, vasectomies, and tubal
ligations, so for heaven's sake, why won't they cover
contraceptives?'' Senator Reid asked. ``I say it's wrong to deny
women the choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Some insurers are also paying for Viagra, though concerns about
its safety and cost _ 2.9 million prescriptions for the $10 pill
since it was introduced in April _ are causing some of the biggest
providers to rethink and even retract their initial decision to
underwrite it. And some states have balked at federal rules
requiring Medicaid, the health-insurance program for low-income
people, to pay for Viagra. Under Medicaid, states must pay for
family-planning services, including contraceptives but excluding
fertility drugs and procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Coorsh says the justification for private insurers to cover
Viagra is it can be a ``medical necessity'' to treat impotency
resulting from an illness such as diabetes, while contraceptives
are considered elective, and pregnancy is not regarded as an
illness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 2021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
