u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-STRIKE-500&AMP;ADD-NYT     07-10 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-STRIKE-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM'S DEMANDS FOR LABOR PEACE ELSEWHERE SLOW STRIKE TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. _ Negotiations to settle a 36-day strike at two
General Motors auto parts factories here slowed to a crawl Friday
as GM stiffened its demand for a guarantee that workers at several
factories elsewhere would not go on strike later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Knechtel, GM's vice president for North American
personnel, said the company could not conclude a deal here without
being sure of labor peace at a truck parts factory in Indianapolis,
a car assembly plant here and two brake factories in Dayton, Ohio.
``We want the risk removed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Shoemaker, vice president for GM issues at the United
Automobile Workers union, said that seeking accords in long-running
disputes at the other factories would only delay a settlement in
the strikes here, which have forced GM to close 26 of its 29 North
American assembly plants and temporarily lay off 161,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
   Even when a deal is reached here, it will take at least two days
for workers to vote on its ratification and return to their jobs.
So the impasse Friday means the end of GM's hope to reopen the
factories here on Monday, when the company's annual two-week summer
shutdown was originally scheduled to end.
</P>
<P>
   Once the parts factories resume production, it will take several
more days for GM to make and ship enough parts to start reopening
its assembly plants. It is losing about $75 million for every
workday that its factories remain closed. With little prospect that
any assembly plants will reopen before the end of next week, GM
faces at least $300 million in losses in addition to the $1.18
billion in strike-related losses before the summer shutdown began.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street, fed up with annual factory-level labor disputes
that have cost GM about $1 billion a year in lost after-tax
profits, has been demanding that any agreement assure labor peace
in the coming months. But at the annual UAW convention in Las Vegas
two weeks ago, Shoemaker mentioned that there could be further
strikes in Dayton and Indianapolis if GM did not improve its labor
relations practices.
</P>
<P>
   The factories in both cities supply many GM assembly plants, so
Shoemaker's widely reported remarks alarmed auto analysts and GM
investors, who have put pressure on the company to seek a solution.
A 17-day strike at the Dayton brake factories in 1996 also shut
down 26 of GM's assembly plants, with an after-tax cost of $900
million.
</P>
<P>
   Shoemaker said that it was a mistake for GM to pay so much
attention to the Dayton and Indianapolis disputes and contended
that GM had many factories with labor problems. Settling grievances
in Dayton and Indianapolis will not eliminate the risk of future
work stoppages elsewhere, he said, adding that the UAW would never
issue a blanket guarantee of labor peace at every factory.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't remove the threat of further potential strikes, and
they can't get a no-strike guarantee,'' Shoemaker said. ``All they
can really do, unless they step up and settle Dayton and
Indianapolis very quickly, is assure that there's a good chance
that this strike will be of a longer duration than would be
otherwise necessary.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Shoemaker said that it had not been a mistake for him to mention
Dayton and Indianapolis in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Both Knechtel and Shoemaker were grim about the likelihood of a
quick deal to settle the strikes here. ``Progress is being made,
it's not as fast as we'd like it to be,'' Knechtel said.
</P>
<P>
   Several people close to the UAW said that rough compromises had
been reached on many issues at the two Flint factories and that
last-minute talks were focusing on whether workers here would be
paid for some vacation days that they missed while picketing. Local
union officials were quietly reserving auditoriums Friday for
ratification votes by members, possibly as soon as this weekend.
Even workers on the picket lines were told by the union not to talk
to reporters as both sides went out of their way to prevent any
disclosures or public criticisms that might slow an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But Shoemaker denied that much had been accomplished, even in
talks at the two factories. ``The progress is very, very, very,
very slow and very disappointing,'' he said. ``There is hardly
anything resolved at either place.''
</P>
<P>
   People close to the UAW said the union was trying to drive a
hard bargain with GM, particularly in demanding vacation pay. GM
stock price has been closely tracking the progress of negotiations,
rising several dollars on reports that a deal was near and dropping
when the two sides seemed unable to settle their differences. By
repeatedly issuing gloomy pronouncements on the talks, Shoemaker
has put pressure on GM to settle while also preventing workers from
raising their hopes, these people said.
</P>
<P>
   Though the details of the bargaining here are not clear, the
negotiators have focused on solving local disputes over work rules,
worker safety and investments in the two struck factories here
rather than a national agreement that would address GM's broader
problems, like a work force larger than needed for its shrinking
market share.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators have also not addressed the broader question of what
GM will do about Delphi Automotive Systems, its auto parts
subsidiary. GM told the UAW more than a year ago that it would keep
at least 80 percent of Delphi even if it did a partial initial
public offering. Shoemaker said that the UAW had not taken a
position on even a partial offering. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
