<SLUG> BC-FALCONS-NOTE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Upbeat Reeves itching for July 23 to arrive
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The Atlanta Falcons finished their pre-training camp
work Friday with a voluntary passing workout in Suwanee. The next
time the team comes together, it will be for real.
</P>
<P>
   Training camp starts on July 23, and coach Dan Reeves can hardly
wait for players to put on pads and start hitting. It's difficult
to make evaluations when players are in cleats, shorts, jerseys and
helmets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The closer you get (to training camp), the more excited you
get,'' he said. ``You start getting butterflies in your stomach.
(Third-year cornerback) Juran Bolden has great skills and has
improved, (second-year safety) Chris Bayne has made great progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``(First-round draft choice) Keith Brooking brings an energy
level that I think affects everyone. But I've been at this long
enough to know there are some guys who look good in these kinds of
things who will disappoint you when the pads are on, so we'll wait
and see.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Reeves took some positives from the 14 days of on-field
work. ``It's more teaching than anything ... where we work on
getting timing down, especially between quarterbacks and
receivers,'' he said. ``We work on a few things so that they're
fresher in the players' minds once training camp starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been excited by the program with (speed coach Loren
Seagrave). That was a great idea. I can see improvement, for
example, in (wide receiver) Terance Mathis. This has all been good
for the quarterbacks to see which receivers have an extra gear, and
how they get in and out of cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach has some concerns, too. There is no guarantee that
backup quarterback Steve DeBerg, 44, will make the team, and the
squad is thin on the defensive line, particularly at tackle.
Currently listed as backups are Nathan Davis, who was inactive for
14 of 16 games as a rookie last year, and Mark Campbell, a free
agent who was inactive for every game in Denver in 1995-96, and
played just a handful of games last year for Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The team is about $1.6 million under the salary cap, so Falcons
officials will be on the lookout for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our depth on the defensive line is probably my biggest
concern,'' Reeves said. ``We're going to look at everybody, but
teams just don't let many of those guys go (in training camp).''
</P>
<P>
   Two-minute drill
</P>
<P>
   It was obvious Friday's workout was voluntary; about 35 of 80
players were present for the 45-minute practice. About half were
rookies or members of last year's practice squad. There were at
least four starters present, including Mathis, running back Jamal
Anderson, strongside linebacker Henri Crockett and fullback Bob
Christian. ... The only lingering injuries have been tendinitis in
Christian's knee and defensive end Chuck Smith's back strain.
Trainer Ron Medlin expects both players to be fine for the start of
training camp. ... Don't be fooled if you've seen the old black
Falcons logo with a big, red ``A'' covering part of it. The team is
not changing its logo. The new one is a secondary logo, used
chiefly for marketing purposes and NFL Properties. The all-black
bird with white trim is still No. 1. ... There has been no
significant progress on where training camp will be next year if
there is construction in Suwanee. Furman University officials will
soon present to the Falcons a preliminary plan to host camp. ...
Single-game tickets go on sale July 18 at the Georgia Dome and
Ticketmaster.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
