A0019 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAACP-FARMERS11-COX     07-10 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-FARMERS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    USDA leader to present his case on Wednesday
 &HT;    By Peter Scott
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Secretary of Agriculture Dan Glickman, who has
acknowledged that his agency has discriminated against black
farmers, will tell his story on Wednesday to the nation's oldest
civil rights organization _ the NAACP.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of America's 18,000 black farmers also are expected on
the same day to address the national convention, but the lead
plaintiff in a $2.5 billion discrimination suit filed against the
United States Department of Agriculture says he will not attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the NAACP is being used by Democrats trying to
convince blacks they are doing all they can to settle the suit we
filed, when all Glickman has to do to resolve it is write a check
and sign it,'' said North Carolina farmer Tim Pigford, the lead
plaintiff in the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the convention is expected to help give black farmers new
allies in their fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black farmers have appealed to us for help, and it is a just
cause,'' said the Rev. R. L. White, president of the Atlanta branch
of the NAACP. ``That is what the NAACP is all about. We try to call
attention to inequities wherever they are found.''
</P>
<P>
   At the convention, Glickman is expected to discuss ``Civil
Rights at the USDA _ the Progress We Have Made and the Challenges
We Face,'' according to spokeswoman Laura Trivers.
</P>
<P>
   The number of challenges facing Glickman and the USDA are piling
up:
</P>
<P>
   Black farmers who are suing the USDA are considering a sit-in
strike in Washington to demand Glickman's removal for what they see
as a failure to act on their complaints, lead attorney Alexander
Pires said.
</P>
<P>
   Court-ordered negotiations to settle the $2.5 billion suit
crumbled two weeks ago with no signs of the farmers or the USDA
moving closer to a settlement. At the same time, several black
farmers who have reached partial settlements still have not
received any checks.
</P>
<P>
   A companion lawsuit has been filed by another group of black
farmers from 14 states and the Virgin Islands month. The $500
million discrimination suit, filed on July 7, was on behalf of 129
black farmers whose complaints were made after Feb. 21, 1997, a
period not covered in the existing $2.5 billion discrimination
suit. The House of Representatives on June 24 waived the two-year
statute of limitation barring new complaints in old cases.
</P>
<P>
   D.J. Miller &AMP; Associates, an Atlanta-based consulting firm, also
is suing the USDA. The firm, which was hired by the USDA to
investigate complaints of discrimination by the nation's county
committees, says the USDA owes the firm some $400,000 for a report
it produced on disparity and racial discrimination within the
100,000-employee agency.
</P>
<P>
   John Boyd, president of the National Black Farmers Association,
filed a formal complaint charging a USDA official allegedly used a
racial epithet in reference to him. John Sparks, special assistant
to Glickman for civil rights, said the Boyd complaint is hard to
resolve, since the only evidence is Boyd's word against the senior
official at the USDA, who denies making the remark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Secretary Glickman has done more to right wrongs than anyone
before him,'' said Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have almost 100,000 folks working here who have a long
history of doing business one way, and it is going to take a while
to turn it around. We're talking about 30 years of problems allowed
to fester here and it's a tall order to require in a year they be
solved. All we can do is keep at it and take advantage of the
window of opportunity we have here with Glickman and the support of
President Bill Clinton,'' said Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
