<SLUG> BC-NAACP-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cochran urges NAACP to keep its dreams alive
 &HT;    By Raven Hill
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The big names are already in town as the NAACP kicks
off its annual convention this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Johnnie Cochran Jr. gave the keynote address Friday during the
Clarence M. Mitchell Jr. Memorial Lecture Luncheon, where he was
honored for his work as a civil rights activist.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles lawyer addressed shortcomings of the justice
system and urged the audience to take a more active role in
changing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never been a people to give up,'' Cochran said. ``We
always come back.'' Quoting New York University law professor
Derrick Bell, Cochran said, ``Ours is a struggle that doesn't have
room to give up.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 10,000 delegates are expected to arrive this weekend
for the 89th annual convention of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People. The focus Friday was on the ACT-SO
competition, now in its 20th year. The 850 youth participants
arrived at the Georgia World Convention Center for orientation and
final rehearsals for ACT-SO, which stand for Afro-Academic
Cultural, Technological and Scientific Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   A showcase of high school students' talents in academics and the
performing arts, the ACT-SO competition's final judging is Monday.
Participants come from NAACP branches across the country, including
Atlanta's, which sponsored 13 students.
</P>
<P>
   While 72 students will walk away with college scholarships,
participant Kevin Richmond, a high school senior from Phoenix, said
the competition offers all young blacks a unique opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``You often see athletes are glorified in the media. This is our
chance to show we can do something,'' Richmond said.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting in the registration line, Emmitt Carlton, president of
the Virginia NAACP, said he expects to be ``recharged'' when the
convention ends Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the best part about coming to the convention,'' Carlton
said. ``You have the chance to hear something you can take back and
use.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
