<SLUG> BC-REFS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NBA referees plead guilty to tax fraud
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Two NBA referees, one active and one retired, pleaded
guilty Friday in federal court in Atlanta to tax fraud charges
involving their failure to report income pocketed from downgrading
first-class airline tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Madden, 60, who lives in Roswell, and Joe Forte, 54, of
Smyrna, face maximum sentences of three years in prison and
$250,000 fines. They will be sentenced Sept. 25.
</P>
<P>
   The two officials stood before U.S. District Judge J. Owen
Forrester while entering their guilty pleas. Madden and Forte are
well-known names to NBA fans. Madden, recognized as one of the best
referees in NBA history, retired in 1994 after having officiated
more than 35 NBA Finals games.
</P>
<P>
   According to a federal criminal complaint, Madden and Forte
downgraded their first-class tickets given to them by the league
for coach seats and pocketed the difference and failed to report it
as income.
</P>
<P>
   ``You understood it was income, didn't you?'' Forrester asked
both referees, who admitted that they did. ``It felt like income.
It spent like income. The bottom line is you were getting more
money than it cost you, and you were enjoying the proceeds.''
</P>
<P>
   Madden and Forte are part of a federal crackdown on tax fraud
abuses by NBA refs. They were charged in Atlanta because they filed
their tax forms here. They bring to nine the number of current or
former referees to be charged nationwide. All but one have pleaded
guilty.
</P>
<P>
   The two men were charged with underreporting income on their
1993 returns. Forte reported income of $111,059 but failed to
report $30,019 in excess airfare reimbursements. Madden reported
income of $214,214 for 1993 and failed to report $31,611.
</P>
<P>
   According to their plea agreements, Forte failed to pay at least
$17,738 in taxes owed from 1991-93. Madden failed to pay $22,176 in
taxes over the same period. The two referees agreed to pay the
taxes plus penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Of the referees who have pleaded guilty and been sentenced, all
have received sentences of either probation or some sort of home
detention.
</P>
<P>
   But Forrester is an independent-minded jurist with a reputation
of being one of the toughest sentencing judges on the Atlanta
bench. And he reminded the two men that they should take nothing
for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your lawyer might have expressed the hope you might get
probation, some short sentence, some favorable treatment,''
Forrester told the two men. ``But you should have no assurance
that's the way it will turn out.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
