<HEADLINE>
INS CHIEF, RENO HONOR FALLEN BORDER PATROL AGENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NATHALIE TREPANIER,   JOHN MacCORMACK and REGINA MONTAGUE  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARLINGEN, Texas _ The brotherhood of green became a sisterhood
as well Friday as U.S. Border Patrol agents from around the nation
honored the agent who died wearing badge number 7097.
</P>
<P>
   In a service attended by nearly 1,000 people at the Queen of
Peace Roman Catholic Church here, Susan Lynn Rodriguez was
remembered as a mother, wife, sister and daughter _ and a model
agent.
</P>
<P>
   And as Doris Meissner, the commissioner of the Immigration and
Naturalization Service, noted in a tearful eulogy, Rodriguez will
be remembered by history for something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am deeply sorry that Agent Rodriguez is the first woman in
the 77-year history of the Border Patrol to make the ultimate
sacrifice for her country,'' said Meissner, whose agency oversees
the Border Patrol and its green-uniformed officers. ``It makes it
all so ever more difficult to bear.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, 28, and rookie agent Ricardo Guillermo Salinas, 24,
were gunned down Tuesday helping local law enforcement agents
investigate a double homicide in nearby San Benito. The suspected
gunman, Ernest Moore, 25, was mortally wounded in a gunfight with
the police and was buried Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno praised Rodriguez as a servant of
the nation and as a woman who led the way for others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she would say to all women in the Border Patrol,
`Never stop dreaming,''' Reno said. ``She would ask us to leave
here today with dignity, although she would forgive us a few
tears,'' the attorney general said.
</P>
<P>
   At the close of the service, Rodriguez's body, in a cherry
coffin draped with an American flag, was carried from the church
between two long lines of green to the waiting hearse.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband Gilbert, an immigration officer, accepted the folded
flag and then an embrace, and the hearse left for the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Friday in San Antonio, Reno praised those who risk their
lives for their country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricardo Salinas was a great example of the men and women who
serve,'' she told told a packed San Fernando Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his name let us go forth from here today. To rededicate
ourselves to this nation he served and loved and died for. To what
this nation stands for. And let us strive, as Agent Salinas
strived, to do our best.''
</P>
<P>
   Archbishop Patrick Flores presided over the hour-long ceremony,
offering words of hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``A great monument that could be built in the memory and honor
of Ricardo would be to say that we are not going to do to others
what was done to him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement agents from Texas and other states attended the
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a brotherhood _ a sisterhood, too, now _ and even if you
don't know them, you come to the funerals,'' said Larry Arthurs, a
Border Patrol agent in Laredo.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a certain risk you take when you carry a gun and a
badge, and this is the ultimate price you have to pay. Any agent
will tell you the same thing,'' said Agent Mark Lazarski, also of
Laredo.
</P>
<P>
   ``But she left a 2-year-old daughter and a husband,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's father, Steve Williams, is a retired Border Patrol
deputy sector chief.
</P>
<P>
   Rodgriguez was the training officer for Salinas, who had joined
the border force only a few months earlier and was still on
probation at the time of his death.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas was buried at the Fort Sam Houston National Cemetery in
San Antonio. Rodriguez will be buried Sunday at the Painted Rock
Cemetery in Philadelphia, Tenn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
