<SLUG> BC-GM-UAW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM, UNION WORK TO END STRIKE BY MONDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   General Motors and United Auto Workers officials have begun
negotiating virtually around the clock in hopes of ending by Monday
the bitter six-week-old strike that has so far cost the company
$1.2 billion and idled 161,000 workers across the country. But
observers say such huge differences remain on the table that a
weekend settlement is practically impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become a manic process,'' said Greg Gardner, senior
editor of the trade publication Ward's Auto World. ``They talk
until they're exhausted, they crash for awhile and then they go
back at it. But the big issues are still unresolved. They say they
want something before the weekend is over, but I don't see any way
that can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Observers said GM is pressing for union concessions such as a
guarantee that UAW won't strike any of the company's U.S. plants
for the remainder of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it very hard to imagine they're going to relinquish the
right to strike,'' Gardner said.
</P>
<P>
   The union likewise has given little ground on company demands
that workers at assembly plants in Flint, Mich., be forced to
produce more and at faster rates.
</P>
<P>
   The strike began June 5, when workers at GM's Flint Metal Center
walked out citing the company's refusal to hire more staff and
replace broken-down equipment. A week later, in keeping with a
union strategy to disrupt the release of a new line of pickups,
employees at a parts factory across town joined the strike. Without
parts to work with, 26 of GM's 29 assembly plants nationwide were
idled.
</P>
<P>
   So far, GM has had to cancel prduction on 227,000 cars and
trucks in the United States, Canada and Mexico. Recovering from the
loss in sales will take months, observers said.
</P>
<P>
   While GM earlier said it intended to hold out for big
concessions, the strike has taken an unusually heavy toll. Analysts
earlier had said the company was willing to lose at least $2
billion to wait out the union. Having already lost $1.2 billion, GM
may not want to wait much longer, observers said. The company has
already taken drastic cash-saving measures like shutting off all
power at plants affected by the strike _ something it has never had
to do before.
</P>
<P>
   Another element of time pressure on GM is the strike's
disruption of a planned new line of pickup trucks, slated for
release in the fall. The line is viewed by the company a key
element in a plan to revamp its public image. The trucks are
expected to be among GM's biggest money makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``As they start trying to gear up for the new model year is when
they're really going to get hurt,'' said John Stamm, a professor at
Babson College who has followed GM's labor relations.
</P>
<P>
   Observers also said GM may be anxious to settle the strike
before second-quarter earnings are released Tuesday. Analysts say
profits will be strong in the period, a fact that could fuel
anti-company sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   The union is also feeling the heat, observers said.
Increasingly, striking workers _ paid a fraction of their salary
from the union's $800 million strike fund _ have put pressure on
UAW leaders to resolve the strike before their own money runs out.
</P>
<P>
   Racheting up pressure earlier this week, GM officials said they
have prepared a detailed cost-cutting plan that includes the
unprecedented move of cutting off medical benefits to striking
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is serious posturing,'' Gardner said. ``Whether or not
they actually do that, it puts a lot of pressure on union leaders,
who are already hearing from the rank and file that people are
starting to miss mortgage payments or that they've got to come up
with tuition for the fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Though a quick solution appears unlikely, observers said there
are signs of conciliation. In a taped telephone message, GM vice
president Donald Hackworth said Friday that ``settling the strike
is a top priority, and nothing is more important than getting our
employees back to work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
