</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MISSING-MILLIONAIRE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM DANCING GIRL TO WEALTHY WIDOW TO POSSIBLE MURDER VICTIM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., La.)  (bl) 
 By SUSAN SACHS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Her nickname was Zambi. That's what her fellow
dancers at Radio City called the petite 17-year-old from New
Orleans with big dreams and bigger ambitions. She was tough, she
was flirtatious and she married well enough to leave the arduous
seven-show-a-week life of a music hall ballerina far behind.
</P>
<P>
   But Irene Zambelli Silverman, the wealthy 82-year-old widow who
disappeared last Sunday from her East 65th Street mansion and is
now feared dead, never quite shook off the glitter of her stage
days.
</P>
<P>
   Well into her 70s, she swept into an awards dinner for a friend
accompanied by an escort of 10 well-built young men. On her cue,
they all dutifully applauded and cheered the surprised recipient,
who recalls her mischievously explaining at the time, ``I rented
them for the night.''
</P>
<P>
   She also took up academics at a relatively late age _ and with
the same idiosyncratic approach. After signing up for a few history
courses in the mid-1970s at Columbia University, Mrs. Silverman
delighted classmates by arriving with a wheel of aged Brie cheese
or ordering in catered lunches and afternoon tea for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``She decided to write a life and did it by living it _ and she
more or less lived it to the hilt,'' said James Shenton, a Columbia
University history professor. Like others, he has begun to talk of
his friend of 25 years in the past tense since police announced
they are holding Kenneth and Sante Kines, a former tenant and his
mother, who were found with Mrs. Silverman's passport and other
documents.
</P>
<P>
   To hear her friends tell it, the life that Mrs. Silverman
improvised for herself turned out to be as colorful as any young
showgirl's fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of an immigrant Greek seamstress and an
Italian-American father whom she once described as ``living on the
edge of respectability'' before he left the family, Mrs. Silverman
told friends that her mother brought her to New York City at the
age of 16.
</P>
<P>
   A veteran of years of ballet classes in her native New Orleans,
she soon got a job in the ``corps de ballet'' at Radio City Music
Hall. It was a matter of enduring irritation to her that many
people assumed she had been a Rockette and not a ballerina.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wanted to make it clear it was more than chorus line; it
had more of a patina of cultivation,'' said Ronald Grele, head of
the oral history research office at Columbia, who was befriended by
Mrs. Silverman about 16 years ago when she became interested in
tape-recording her mother's memories of the millinery trade.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the ballet corps traded time on the Radio City
stage with the Rockettes, performing both excerpts from the
classics and some original numbers. ``Some of it was for the masses
and was a little bit corny, but some of it was magnificent,'' said
Janice Herbert, another Radio City ballet alumnus who joined the
troupe 10 years after Mrs. Silverman had retired. ``It was probably
the hardest job in New York _ every day, 365 days a year, with
rehearsals between shows. Plus, the stage is cement.''
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1940s, young Zambi apparently had had enough. And
she was being pursued by a persistent young real estate man named
Samuel Silverman who apparently picked her out from the group of
young dancers and fell head over heels.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the old stage-door Johnny,'' said Stuart Ho, president
of Capital Investment of Hawaii Inc., who first met Mr. Silverman
in 1963 and remained close friends with the couple for many years.
``Irene was one of these Auntie Mame types. She was a little bubbly
and ebullient and yet could be very serious. He was a brilliant
man, with connections at the very highest levels.''
</P>
<P>
   In retelling the story many years later, Mrs. Silverman would
claim that she at first resisted Samuel's entreaties. ``Then,
whatever reservations I had were overcome by the realization he was
going to make me rich,'' she told Shenton.
</P>
<P>
   In 1941 the two were married in a synagogue around the corner
from Radio City. Mrs. Silverman, a Roman Catholic, once joked to a
friend that, with a Greek mother and an Italian father, ``I decided
I'd better do something about it _ so I anglicized myself by
marrying a Jew.''
</P>
<P>
   After World War II, the couple traveled extensively in Europe on
business. According to Ho, Mr. Silverman worked for Empire Trust
Co. of New York, then one of the city's biggest banks, before
striking out on his own as a mortgage broker. He developed
properties in France and later Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the days just after statehood in 1959, when financial
institutions on the mainland weren't familiar with Hawaii as an
investment area, it was Sam Silverman who provided the connections
and advice in New York City,'' recalled Ho, whose company is one of
the largest real estate developers in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Silverman also worked with a number of other big developers,
including Los Angeles theater chain owner William Forman, and
worked particularly closely with Columbia University in building
its real-estate portfolio in the 1960s and 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   But Mr. Silverman, apparently about 10 years older than his
wife, remains something of a mystery to her friends. Shenton, for
instance, is convinced that Mr. Silverman grew up on the Lower East
Side and was essentially self-taught. Other friends said they had
the impression Mr. Silverman was from the Midwest. Ho said he was
told by Mr. Silverman that he graduated from Columbia University
Law School, although a spokesman for the school could find no
record of his attendance.
</P>
<P>
   While he was alive, the Silvermans were always on the move. They
had an apartment in Honolulu, which Mrs. Silverman donated to
Columbia University after her husband died. They also had a large
apartment on the Place de l'Opera in central Paris that backed up
onto the Comedie Francaise theater. Whenever there was a
performance, the voices of the actors and the audience's applause
could be heard clearly _ and loudly _ in the Silvermans' living
room, friends said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The combined elegance and eccentricity of the place seemed to
suit Mrs. Silverman. ``She always dreamed of living in 18th century
Paris and holding `soirees,''' said Shenton.
</P>
<P>
   In 1957, the Silvermans had purchased the limestone mansion at
20 E. 65th St. Mr. Silverman had resisted at first, but the posh
address, he later admitted, was good for his business. For Mrs.
Silverman, it was the beginning of an enduring love affair and she
began collecting what she called ``scraps of ephemeria'' about the
history of the house.
</P>
<P>
   Her research led her to a descendant of the Sherrill family that
had built the house at the turn of the century. As she recounted
the experience to Christopher Gray, an architectural historian who
wrote about the home for The New York Times, George Gibbs Sherrill
acted as though ``he hated the idea Jews bought the house.''
</P>
<P>
   But in her distinctively peppery fashion, Mrs. Silverman found a
way to avenge the perceived slight to her husband. Some years
later, she wrote in a letter to Gray, she found a locked safe in
the house. She had workmen open it. Inside was a cache of old
military medals, apparently left behind by the Sherrills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a little charm bracelet of all the medals. That was my
way of getting back at them,'' she wrote in her characteristically
bold handwriting. ``I did it and I'm not afraid to admit it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Silverman did not deny herself much. Champagne flowed
freely in her house, recalled Robert Jakoubek, a publishing
industry executive who met her when they attended history classes
at Columbia together. A dinner at her house might well be fine
French food or, just as likely, rice and beans or bacon, lettuce
and tomato sandwiches. She sometimes also served up merciless
imitations of acquaintances and strangers alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had one of the most observant eyes, especially when it
comes to human anatomy. I remember a long digression on the
unfortunate chin of Kenneth Starr,'' said Jakoubek, recalling a
recent conversation with Mrs. Silverman about the special
prosecutor. ``And her observations were never politically
correct.''
</P>
<P>
   After her husband died, Mrs. Silverman consolidated a lifetime's
worth of artwork, antiques, shoes, clothing and memorabilia into a
top floor duplex of her mansion and subdivided the rest into
individual apartments, each one with a different layout and
character. She never gave her friends a clear answer when they
asked why she bothered.
</P>
<P>
   But it must have fulfilled her dream of that Parisian-style
salon, with her at the epicenter of social activity, as she rented
out to strangers and celebrities like conductor Peter Duchin,
singer Chaka Khan and author Andrew Murray.
</P>
<P>
   Renters learned to live with their landlady's restless
redecorating and somewhat eclectic tastes. She hung a painting said
to be a Renoir in a bathroom. The furniture changed on a regular
basis, although not always for aesthetic reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was always a work-in-progress,'' said Henry Sinkel, a
former tenant. ``Something was always being puffed, fluffed,
renovated and changed. You never knew when you walked in if
something wasn't being fine-tuned.'' When she realized Sinkel was
seeing a lot of a particular woman, she surprised him one day by
removing the bed in his apartment and replacing it with a bigger
one.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Mrs. Silverman had begun an autobiography,
friends said. She filled sheet after sheet of paper with her large
scrolling writing, often dashing off some of the more amusing
recollections in letters to her friends.
</P>
<P>
   But she was slowing down. She had begun to tire more easily,
complained of aches and pains and had surgery on the tear ducts of
her eyes. Dinner guests would be shooed out of the house before 9
p.m., so she could go upstairs and watch television before dropping
off to sleep. She began to collect the clothes her mother had sewn
for donation to the Metropolitan Museum of Art and set up a
foundation, named the Coby Foundation for her mother, to promote
research into the millinery trade.
</P>
<P>
   Her friends cannot imagine that she simply disappeared. A quiet
exit didn't fit her temperament. ``She had a temper,'' said
Shenton, who believes she must have fought fiercely with any
attacker. ``She once said to me, `Never forget, I grew up in New
Orleans and I know what a fishmonger's wife is.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 2034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
