<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-ONLINE-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINKING RATIONALLY AS THE WEB GOES WILD 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., July 12) 
(jt) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a wild week on Wall Street for Internet stocks. But
because many of these fledgling companies may be years away from
actually making money, the sight of their stocks skyrocketing one
day and plummeting the next is enough to make investors wonder if
the Internet is paved with gold or just a high-technology version
of the tulip craze.
</P>
<P>
   There is not much doubt that people who have been riding the
wave this year have done well. The Interactive Week Internet Index,
a group of 50 companies, has risen 46 percent this year. After
hitting a record last Monday, the index retreated but still ended
the week up 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Internet stocks have been good for managers like Paul Cook, a
former director of information technology at Munder Capital
Management in Birmingham, Mich., who now runs the Munder NetNet
fund, which invests in companies engaged in research, design,
development and manufacturing related to the Internet. specific
holdings described below
</P>
<P>
   Since it began in August 1996, this fund, with a maximum 5.5
percent load, or initial sales charge, and $33 million in assets,
is up more than 57 percent on average per year. So far this year,
it has risen more than 37 percent, excluding the load.
</P>
<P>
   During a business trip last week to the Research Triangle of
North Carolina, Cook took some time to talk about the current
mania.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What has been driving the big moves in these stocks? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I think a lot of it is driven by speculation about who will
be the next company to get snapped up by a much bigger company from
another medium as a way of buying their way on to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Also, I think there has been a bit of a short squeeze on some of
these stocks. And there are momentum players who are involved. I
hear that this is a retail phenomenon, but I don't believe it. If
it is, there are some awfully big retail players out there.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Those sorts of conditions have pushed prices for a number of
these stocks to very high levels. What do you say to an investor
who either owns or is contemplating a purchase of a stock like
Yahoo, for instance?
</P>
<P>
   A. I think Yahoo is overvalued and has been overvalued for a
while. But I would not short it. Anyone who did that in the last
couple of months has gotten creamed.
</P>
<P>
   Q. You own 50 stocks out of what you see as a universe of 600
companies. Are there really 600 Internet companies out there? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I would guess there are only about 25 pure Internet stocks,
companies like Onsale, Inktomi, Doubleclick and Gravity.
</P>
<P>
   But the fund is not a pure Internet fund. What we are looking
for are beneficiaries of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is your biggest holding currently?
</P>
<P>
   A. Microsoft. And we also own companies in areas like finance,
where companies like Charles Schwab, E-Trade and Ameritrade are
giving their customers the opportunity to buy and sell stocks over
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What other groups do you see as beneficiaries of the
Internet?
</P>
<P>
   A. Security firms who ward off hackers or insure that a
transaction works. Hardware companies like Sun Microsystems, as
well as anyone else making servers, like Cisco Systems. Content
providers like Cnet. And consulting companies like Forrester
Research, Medigroup and the Gartner Group. Those companies will be
important in helping others construct their best Internet strategy.
</P>
<P>
   We also like so-called portal stocks like America Online, a
stock that has done extremely well. But we also like Worldcom and
MCI. These stocks are pretty frothy, but I don't think they are
fully valued yet.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Your opinion on Amazon.com?
</P>
<P>
   A. I own Amazon. I used to be overweight in the stock. Now I am
underweight. But I think they have a real opportunity to leverage
their brand to sell not only books and CD's but cigars and wine, to
become the supermarket of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Q. There are an awful lot of companies that are putting an awful
lot of what they sell in other ways onto the Internet for free.
When they start to charge customers for the information, isn't
there a risk that customers won't pay the freight? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. There is the risk that people will not buy what Internet
companies are selling. But I think that over the long term, as more
and more companies start building their own Internet presence, you
will get a critical mass of customers.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Much of the growth in the Internet has occurred during
extremely good economic times. What happens when the United States
economy turns down?
</P>
<P>
   A. I think the digital economy is decoupling from the regular
economy. The price of entry to get on the Internet is coming down.
In my view, the forces for the digital economy will survive better
than other sectors of the economy in a recession, because it is in
the process of ramping up, with its own evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What sorts of things do bother you?
</P>
<P>
   A. The biggest issue I have with these stocks is that next year
there will be 300,000 positions for information technology
professionals, and colleges and universities will generate only
34,000 who are qualified to fill the jobs. That means it will be
hard for the companies to add people as needed, and they will have
to spend money as needed to get good people. That, in turn, will
drive up the price of the product.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What advice would you give investors who are interested in
sinking money into some of these stocks?
</P>
<P>
   A. A lot of information about these companies is flying around
out there, and a lot of it is rumor. I would stay clear of rumors.
Try to make informed decisions. At the moment, I don't know how
many investors are doing that. I think a lot of investors are just
chasing these stocks up, and that scares me.
</P>
<P>
   But at this stage it is too hard to pick winners and losers,
which makes it difficult to pick one or two names. You should
either create your own basket of stocks or buy a fund. That is why
we created ours. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
