<P>
   DRUGS-U.S.-EUROPE (Washington) _ Barry McCaffrey, who heads the
White House war on narcotics, goes to Europe Saturday to boost
international cooperation in the anti-drug effort and to learn what
other nations are doing to prevent substance abuse. By NICOLE
TSONG. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-DISNEY (Austin, Texas) _ The State Board of Education
votes 8-4 to sell off its estimated $43 million in Walt Disney Co.
stock because of the company's adult-oriented movies. The vote fell
strictly along party lines, with Democrats opposing the sales or
abstaining from taking a stand. By KATHY WALT.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-DISPUTE (Austin, Texas) _ A federal judge has told all
parties in lingering dispute over Texas' record tobacco settlement
to appear in court Monday. The $15.3 billion settlement has been
bogged down over objections to fees the Texas attorney general
agreed to pay the private lawyers hired to fight the case. By
NICOLE FOY.
</P>
<P>
   AGENTS-GUNS (Harlingen, Texas) _ The assault rifle used to kill
two U.S. Border Patrol officers and wound a deputy sheriff is owned
by the Harlingen Police Department and was issued to police
detective R.D. Moore, the father of the suspect in Tuesday's
homicides, a source involved in the investigation says. By JAMES
PINKERTON. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   AGENTS-FUNERALS (Harlingen, Texas) _ Services are held for the
two U.S. Border Patrol agents killed while assisting local law
enforcement officers pursue a suspect. Attorney General Janet Reno
attended separate services for Susan Lynn Rodriguez, 28, and rookie
agent Ricardo Guillermo Salinas, 24. By NATHALIE TREPANIER, JOHN
MacCORMACK and REGINA MONTAGUE. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   CONCEALED-GUNS (Austin, Texas) _ More than 1,600 Texans with
permits to carry concealed handguns have been arrested for state
crimes since the ``right-to-carry'' law went into effect in 1996,
the Department of Public Safety says. Nearly 200,000 Texans are
licensed to carry concealed handguns. Licensees have been arrested
a total of 2,203 times. By JOHN W. GONZALEZ. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-NAPALM (Houston) _ GNI Group has been awarded a contract
to process and recycle millions of gallons of Vietnam-era napalm.
The first shipment of napalm, which has been stored by the Navy in
Fallbrook, Calif., will be moving to Deer Park, an industrial city
of 8,000 west of downtown Houston. By RUTH RENDON.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ECUADOR-ELECTION (Quito, Ecuador) _ Desperate for a dynamic
leader, Ecuadoreans will head to the polls Sunday for a
presidential runoff election. The winner will begin a four-year
term Aug. 10 and attempt to restore a measure of stability to this
battered nation of 12 million people. By JOHN OTIS. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   ECUADOR-CUP (Quito, Ecuador) _ When asked who will win on
Sunday, the day of this nation's presidential runoff, some
Ecuadoreans say it's no contest: Brazil in a blowout. Brazil? Yes,
Sunday is also the day of the World Cup final and that could affect
voter turnout. By JOHN OTIS. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-BRIBERY (Mexico City) _ A Mexican army general convicted
of trying to bribe a top Baja California drug enforcement agent
last year has been sentenced to 20 years in prison, the attorney
general's office reports. By PHILIP TRUE.
</P>
