<HEADER>
A0035 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-IMF-750&AMP;ADD-NY     07-10 1312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-IMF-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN URGES WESTERN LEADERS TO SUPPORT FINANCIAL ASSISTANCE
PACKAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (hlw) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Boris Yeltsin went over the head of the
International Monetary Fund on Friday and urged Western leaders to
support a multi-billion-dollar package of financial assistance to
defend the Russian currency.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials say they were now seeking assistance of $20
billion or more, at least $10 billion of which it hopes would come
from the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   The total is $5 billion to $10 billion more than the government
previously said it needed, and the request to the IMF is about
twice what the fund has spoken of providing.
</P>
<P>
   The expanded request reflects Moscow's anxiety about a rapidly
deteriorating economic situation, which is not only threatening the
stability of the ruble but threatening to shake the foundations of
Russia's political establishment.
</P>
<P>
   In an extraordinary series of appeals, Yeltsin telephoned
President Clinton, President Jacques Chirac of France, Prime
Minister Tony Blair of Britain and Chancellor Helmut Kohl of
Germany. The Russian president also called Michel Camdessus, the
head of the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   Afterwards, the Clinton administration expressed support for the
beleaguered Yeltsin government, which has been locked in difficult
negotiations with a tight-fisted IMF.
</P>
<P>
   Washington said that Russia needs to take firm measures to deal
with its financial crisis. But it also indicated that the IMF needs
to provide substantial loans to calm the financial markets and
should make realistic demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States government certainly agrees that Russia
needs an IMF program that works, one that the Russian government is
both capable of implementing and that addresses the country's most
pressing financial and structural problems,'' the White House
spokesman, Mike McCurry, said.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``It's time for these negotiations to come to
closure.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yeltsin government and the IMF are in some agreement about
the overall direction of economic reform but not the pace. The
Russians feel that their financial markets are so shaky right now
that they face an emergency and cannot afford dragged-out
negotiations. Earlier on Friday, the Yeltsin government painted a
bleak picture of the pressures that have forced it to go hat in
hand to the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation on financial markets has gotten worse,'' Prime
Minister Sergei Kiriyenko told the upper house of parliament.
``Treasury bill yields are rising. Social tension is also growing.
We are ready to consider any proposal, but we simply cannot fail to
repay treasury bills.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin spoke in even starker terms of social tensions. He
warned against any ``extremist'' plans to exploit the financial
crisis to dislodge him from power.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, there have been repeated calls for Yeltsin's
resignation, including from coal miners protesting wage arrears. So
far, however, there have not been any dramatic challenges to
Yeltsin's hold on power.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have enough force to cut short any extremist plans to seize
power,'' Yeltsin said in an address to senior military officers.
``They will fail.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's focus, however, was not so much on challenges to
Yeltsin's authority as on the economic assistance the Kremlin says
is needed to maintain stability.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The loans that Yeltsin is seeking would be used for two
purposes. The main one is to shore up the reserves of the Central
Bank and prop up the ruble. Another aim is to restructure its
short-term debt, which Russia has been forced to issue at enormous
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, the Yeltsin government said it needed $10 billion to
$15 billion in new loans. But on Friday, two senior Russian
officials said the financial markets were in such distress that $20
billion or more was now required. A major debate concerns how much
money the IMF should contribute to the overall package. The IMF
recently discussed providing only $5.8 billion in new loans.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians are negotiating to assemble a financial package
from several sources. According to the Russian plan, about $10
billion to $12 billion would come from the IMF. They are wrapping
up negotiations to borrow about a billion dollars from the World
Bank and some $800 million from the Japanese. The Russians also are
in negotiations to to borrow $10 billion from Western commercial
banks.
</P>
<P>
   But putting together that package has proved to be very
difficult. For one thing, the IMF has made clear that it would not
disburse new loans unless Russia took bold steps to cut its federal
deficit and win support for tax reform and revenue raising measures
in the Communist-dominated parliament. The parliament has scheduled
a decisive session on Yeltsin's plan last next week.
</P>
<P>
   In his talk with Clinton, Yeltsin sought American pressure on
the fund to speedily complete negotiations so that the Kremlin
could obtain desperately needed funds. The U.S. and the other
countries that Yeltsin called on Friday are the principal backers
and contributors to the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   Emphasizing his plight, Yeltsin spoke of the difficulties he
faced in winning support for his deficit-cutting measures and tax
reforms in the Communist-dominated parliament. He also underscored
the steps he was taking to deal with the problem, including trying
to collect taxes from Gazprom, the nation's biggest corporation.
</P>
<P>
   While the United States is supportive, American officials said
Clinton also told the Russian president that he needed to get his
economic program through the parliament or impose new fiscal
measures by decree.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin did not ask for direct American assistance or try to
negotiate over the amount.
</P>
<P>
   But Yeltsin aides have also been looking to the United States
Treasury Department for help. ``The U.S. Treasury Department is
pushing the IMF to get a swift but firm agreement in order to avoid
devaluing the ruble,'' said Anders Aslund, an expert on the Russian
economy at the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace. ``The
Treasury Department understands how dangerous an economic meltdown
in Russia would be.''
</P>
<P>
   John Odling-Smee, a senior IMF official, arrived here for talks
on Friday, stirring expectations that a preliminary deal might be
struck this weekend for the expanded program of assistance Moscow
has been seeking.
</P>
<P>
   But the initial round of discussions between Odling-Smee and
Anatoly Chubais, the chief Russian representative in the talks, did
not go entirely smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   Odling-Smee reportedly argued that the Yeltsin government's
revenue projections were off by $5 billion, Russian officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the difficulties have been with the fund. There have
been problems with commercial banks as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians would like to be able to use the funds they borrow
without restriction. But some Western banks are insisting that the
funds be used to buy back Russian treasury bills the banks are
holding.
</P>
<P>
   The visit this month by Vice President Al Gore and the September
summit meeting here between Clinton and Yeltsin have helped focus
American attention on Russia and its economic travails.
</P>
<P>
   But while Yeltsin was seeking help, his prime minister was
striving to build parliamentary support for the government's
measures to cut the deficit and restructure the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing before the upper house of parliament, Kiriyenko
painted a disturbing portrait of the nation's economic ills and
warned that the failure to act would plunge the country into
economic chaos.
</P>
<P>
   The upper house, which has always been more pliant than the
Communist-dominated lower chamber, gave its broad support.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must pool our efforts,'' Kiriyenko said. ``Failing that, we
will be responsible for ruining the country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
