<SLUG> BC-SOC-CUP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESAILLY IS LAST LINE OF FRENCH DEFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The brilliance that can come from striker-cum-god
Ronaldo has won admirers the world over, but if the Brazilian star
thinks he's going to make his mark on this World Cup in Sunday's
final, the French suggest he should think again.
</P>
<P>
   There's only one rationale for their confidence, but it's a good
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have our anti-Ronaldo plan in place,'' brags Didier
Deschamps, France's captain. ``It's called Marcel Desailly.''
</P>
<P>
   If anyone can stop the unstoppable, it might be the imposing
defender from Ghana, whose performance at the heart of the French
defense this Cup has been so spectacular, so flawless, that there's
a movement afoot to deny the tournament's MVP award to an attacker,
an unheard-of prospect.
</P>
<P>
   Argues Deschamps, with one man in mind: ``The player of this
World Cup is not necessarily a forward; it can be a defender.''
</P>
<P>
   If any defender warrants such praise, it's Desailly, who has
been among the world's finest defensive players since helping
Olympique Marseille to that tainted European Champions Cup title in
1993. He moved onto AC Milan the following year, won another
Champions Cup there, and has coupled his play as a defensive
midfielder at Milan his preferred position with stirring
exhibitions in the middle of the French defense.
</P>
<P>
   Desailly, 29, who moved to France when he was 4, has been at his
best the past month, as France has surrendered only two goals just
one of them in open play in six matches en route to the title-game
showdown with Brazil at the Stade de France. He can expect to play
the pivotal role on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   He'll do so without his usual partner in the back, sweeper
Laurent Blanc, who is suspended for the final. In Blanc's place
will be Franck Leboeuf, a superb passer whose game has been marred
by occasional lapses of judgment. Leboeuf is no Blanc, but
Desailly's experience and presence is expected to raise his
teammate's game considerably.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how to play with Franck Leboeuf,'' says Desailly, who
will join Leboeuf at Chelsea following the World Cup. ``I'm happy
for him, but I'm sorry for Laurent Blanc. I like the way Franck
Leboeuf tackles. Tactically, he's very intelligent and that will
help us against Ronaldo and Bebeto.''
</P>
<P>
   A quiet, unassuming man with an incisive sense of humor,
Desailly demonstrated early the power and speed that define his
game. He joined Nantes when he was 12, made his first-team debut a
few years later, and climbed the pinnacle of world soccer by his
mid-twenties. The only thing missing from his resume is a World Cup
title.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people mention the Platini generation (which won the 1984
European title, France's greatest soccer accomplishment), they
immediately name three players Michel Platini, Alain Giresse and
Jean Tigana,'' Desailly says. ``We want that to happen to us as
well. We want people to remember our names. We want to make
history.''
</P>
<P>
   The opportunity arrives Sunday, but it comes with the most
difficult of challenges: stopping Ronaldo, universally considered
the greatest player in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played against Ronaldo four times for Milan,'' Desailly
says. ``When I marked him, I think I played a nice game. This is a
different team, a different situation, but big competitions bring
out the best in me. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to stop (Ronaldo) from turning with the ball and
accelerating away. Otherwise, you can only stop him by fouling him.
But it's wrong to sum up Brazil as Ronaldo. The danger could come
from anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   France has demonstrated that this tournament, with four of its
11 goals and all three in the knockout phase coming from defenders.
Blanc and Bixente Lizarazu have one each, and Lilian Thuram has
two, both in the 2-1 semifinal win over Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   And so the real challenge has been issued. Desailly is expected
to be perfect on defense, but can he carry France to the title with
a goal?
</P>
<P>
   ``All our defense except me has scored,'' he says, a smile
opening on his face. ``So I know what I have to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
