<HEADER>
A0043 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FALCONS-FEAT-COX     07-10 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALCONS-FEAT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A bigger Graziani fighting for a job
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- For all the fuss in recent days about Falcons
quarterbacks, it seems like Tony Graziani has been forgotten. But
the second-year player is still in Suwanee, bigger and potentially
better than before.
</P>
<P>
   Graziani gained 15 pounds during the offseason after having a
rough rookie year. He became the first rookie quarterback to start
a game for Atlanta since 1993, but when he took over for injured
Chris Chandler last season in the eighth game at Carolina, things
got ugly.
</P>
<P>
   After completing 4-of-18 passes for 24 yards and two
interceptions in the first half, Graziani, a seventh-round pick
from Oregon, took a seat. Billy Joe Tolliver took over. The Falcons
lost 21-12 and dropped to 1-7 for the season. Graziani took just a
few more meaningless snaps all season.
</P>
<P>
   Graziani's youth and slight build and Chandler's tendency to get
hurt _ he missed all or parts of six games _ caused the Falcons to
make backup quarterback a top offseason priority. The team was 7-3
in games Chandler started and finished, and 0-6 in others.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Falcons gave Graziani a choice. ``We left it up
to Tony whether to go to the World League and play, or stay here
and work on getting stronger,'' coach Dan Reeves said. ``He decided
to stay, and I think it's been good.''
</P>
<P>
   Graziani, 24, thinks so too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided to work out,'' he said. ``I needed to get bigger to
be able to take more punishment. I wanted to add strength to my
legs.''
</P>
<P>
   He also needed a stronger arm after struggling to throw certain
passes. The 6-foot-2 Graziani has grown from 195 to about 210
pounds, and thinks he has met both goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``My arm feels stronger, and some receivers and a couple coaches
have said it looks stronger,'' said Graziani.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves has never said Graziani is the team's quarterback of the
future, and it's uncertain whether he's ready to be the backup of
the present. He's an excellent athlete, but lacks experience. And
more conclusive evidence is needed on his arm strength.
</P>
<P>
   So the team signed 44-year-old Steve DeBerg on Monday after
failing in offseason attempts to get unrestricted free agent Ty
Detmer, who ended up in San Francisco, or restricted free agent
Eric Zeier of Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   The team did sign free agent Mark Rypien. But when family issues
put Rypien's career on hold last month, the Falcons opted for
DeBerg, who last played in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Graziani said he's not offended.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to compete with whoever is there,'' he said. ``I
think Steve can help both Chris and I, and (rookie free agent)
Brian (Brennan of Idaho) too.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
