<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-NOTEBOOK11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Park back in action after recovering from injuries
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ The crutches are gone and only a slight limp
remains. Steve Park is ready to go racing again after spending 13
weeks rehabilitating injuries suffered in the March Primestar 500
at Atlanta Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're leaving here Sunday and flying straight to Indianapolis
to test Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday,'' Park said of beginning
preparations for the Brickyard 400 Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got three cars going out there, and five or six motors.
We're taking it pretty seriously. We want to make that comeback
race one that's memorable to all of us, especially myself.''
</P>
<P>
   During his rehabiliation, Park figures he was on crutches the
longest, a month and a half; four weeks off his feet; and three or
four weeks with a cane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't walk like an IndyCar driver for the rest of my life, I
hope,'' Park said. ``The majority of the limp I have is because I
work out three days a week with the leg. If I take it easy, from
Thursday to Monday, the limp pretty much diminishes.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as the accident goes, Park says he's forgotten it and
placed more emphasis into trying to run the race here. But, there
was neither enough time nor a way to get it done.
</P>
<P>
   Green at Indy
</P>
<P>
   David Green, released by Buz McCall last month, has a one-race
deal with team owner Larry Hedrick to test a second car in
preparation for the Brickyard 400 at Indianapolis Motor Speedway.
Green's involvement will in no way affect regular driver Steve
Grissom. Green, last year's runnerup for Winston Cup Rookie of the
Year, currently drives full time on the Busch Grand National
circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Non-performer
</P>
<P>
   When Todd Bodine was released earlier this week by team owner
Bob Hancher, the reason given was poor performance, not pressure
from the sponsor, Tabasco/McIlhenny Co. ``It's my obligation to
make changes to perform,'' Hancher said. ``And recent changes at
the Mcllhenny company really didn't have to do anything about it.''
Hancher expects to name a permanent driver next week. Ted Musgrave
is a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Dallenbach hopeful
</P>
<P>
   Wally Dallenbach has his fingers crossed that he'll be a member
of Hendrick Motorsports in 1999. And John Hendrick, acting head of
Hendrick Motorsports, acknowledges if a fourth team is formed he'd
like to have a driver like Dallenbach.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
