<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-CUP-THIRD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIRD ISN'T A BAD PLACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ It's a meaningless game the participants would just as
soon skip, but they can't, and so the two most disappointed sides
in France the Netherlands and Croatia are searching for something
to spark them in tonight's World Cup third-place game at Parc des
Princes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a secret that it is difficult to feel 100 percent for
a match like this one,'' said Dutch coach Guus Hiddink, whose squad
missed its chance to play in Sunday's final by losing on penalty
kicks to Brazil. ``You play as a matter of honor.''
</P>
<P>
   The tickets and television rights have been sold, so the game
must go on, although one would be hard-pressed to term it a
``battle.'' Past affairs have been more like friendlies than
competitive matches, and neither Holland nor Croatia can be
expected to give a full effort after suffering shattering semifinal
losses.
</P>
<P>
   They claim otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We owe it to ourselves and the fans to play well,'' Dutchman
Aron Winter said. ``We want to show everyone we deserved better.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We really wanted to play in the final, but now we have to
concentrate and try to be third,'' said Croatian forward Davor
Suker, who netted his fifth goal of the tournament in the 2-1 loss
Wednesday to France. ``We will be motivated, and I pray the Dutch
won't be. It will be a difficult game, but it's better to finish
third than fourth.''
</P>
<P>
   The only real drama will be provided by Suker, who needs one
goal to break a tie with Italy's Christian Vieri and Argentina's
Gabriel Batistuta as the World Cup's scoring champion. Bulgaria's
Hristo Stoichkov went into the '94 third-place game at the Rose
Bowl in a similar situation, but his side was thrashed by Sweden,
4-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Croats, whose stunning run to the semifinals was one of the
primary storylines of the Cup, may have more desire to prosper.
This was their first World Cup, their first opportunity to
participate since breaking off from Yugoslavia seven years ago, and
their success has alerted the world to their tiny country's
existence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can be really proud of what we achieved,'' Coach
Miroslav Blazevic said. ``But I still can't get rid of the
impression that we could have done more.''
</P>
<P>
   Finishing third, in a small way, would be more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll give everything,'' defender Igor Stimac declared, ``to
capture third place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
