<SLUG> BC-MARINE-FLIERS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIALS ORDERED FOR 2 MARINE FLIERS IN GONDOLA ACCIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: SUBS to attach 10 grafs of new information to end of original
text)  (mk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A senior Marine Corps general Friday ordered a court-martial on
the most serious possible charges for the pilot and the navigator
of an electronic warfare jet that hit a ski lift cable in Italy in
February, killing 20 people.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gen. Peter Pace, commander of the Marines in the Atlantic
fleet, also said that he wanted to conduct a hearing personally to
discipline the commander of the squadron, the executive officer,
the director of safety and the operations officer for dereliction
of duty. They could face loss of pay, confinement to base and
official reprimand.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot, Capt. Richard Ashby, 31, of Mission Viejo, Calif.,
and the navigator, Capt. Joseph Schweitzer, 30, of Westbury, N.Y.,
face charges of involuntary manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   The case, which has been the subject of three Marine Corps
reports and seven days of public hearings, has raised difficult
questions about not only the conduct of the crew, but the safety
and soundness of management in the Marine Corps, the Air Force and
the Defense Mapping Agency and its successor, the National Imagery
and Mapping Agency. Those questions will now be argued in detail at
a court-martial at Camp Lejeune, N.C., probably beginning this
fall. ``We know this is going to be a knock-down drag-out,'' said
Frank Spinner, the civilian lawyer for Ashby.
</P>
<P>
   The plane, an EA-6B Prowler based temporarily in Aviano, Italy,
for duty over Bosnia, was on a training flight through the Italian
Alps when it hit the cable near Cavalese. The incident has strained
American relations with Italy, and a Marine Corps officer who was a
member of a Marine Investigation Board that first looked into the
incident hinted that there had been political pressure to come down
hard on the crew.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton administration officials insisted that the White
House and State Department had not brought pressure on the Marine
Corps to seek tougher penalties as a means of appeasing the Italian
government. ``This call was made by the Marines,'' an official
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby was sitting in the front cockpit, at the single set of
flight controls. Next to him, functioning as mission planner and
navigator, was Schweitzer.
</P>
<P>
   A hearing officer recommended this month that only Ashby face
the most serious charge, involuntary manslaughter, a crime that
involves ``culpable negligence'' and carries a sentence of up to 10
years for each of the 20 counts. He said Schweitzer should face the
lesser charge of negligent homicide, which carries a maximum
penalty of three years for all counts together.
</P>
<P>
   But Gen. Pace ruled that both should face the more serious
charge. He agreed with the hearing officer that they should also
face charges of damage to military property, damage to private
property and dereliction of duty.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing officer, Lt. Col. Ronald Rodgers, said that two
officers in the rear cockpit, who did not have a view out the front
and had limited information about the plane's altitude, should not
be court-martialed, and Pace accepted that recommendation Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But Rodgers also said in his report, released July 2, that he
had ``substantial doubt'' that any of the men could be convicted
because of errors by others, a position stressed by the defendants'
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Spinner, referring to the disciplinary hearing for the other
four officers in the squadron, said, ``By initiating disciplinary
action against these individuals, that suggests that Gen. Pace
agrees there was systemic error, which takes the spotlight off
Ashby and the crew and says, `Hey, there are other problems
here.'''
</P>
<P>
   David Beck, a civilian lawyer representing Schweitzer, said,
``We're not applauding that these four individuals face
punishment.'' But he said of his client, ``Joe is encouraged that
they are looking at other factors.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Prominent among those factors was very poor communications
between the Air Force, which has a permanent presence in Aviano,
and the Marine Corps electronic warfare squadrons, which rotated
through every six months. Rodgers said in his report that at one
point, an Air Force officer at Aviano telephoned the Marine Corps
aviators to say that they should empty their mailbox, into which
the Air Force was depositing safety documents, and the Marine
squadron was unaware that such a mailbox existed.
</P>
<P>
   A document in the hands of the Air Force, a copy of which was
later discovered at the room where the Marines' prepared for
flight, showed that minimum altitude on the route that the Prowler
flew that day was 2,000 feet. But nearly everyone in the squadron
believed it was 1,000 feet, investigators found. And there was no
system for updating old flight information and making sure that
everyone had read it, according to investigators.
</P>
<P>
   That is likely to be at least part of the basis for the
dereliction of duty charge against the squadron's commanding
officer, Lt. Col. Richard Muegge, and three other officers in the
squadron at the time of the accident, Lt. Col. John Koran III, then
the executive officer, or second in command; Maj. Kirk Shawhan,
then the operations officer, who drew up flight schedules, among
other duties, and Maj. Max Caramanian, then director of
standardization and safety.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Gen. Pace, Lt. Col. Ellen Haddock, said that
the names of officers facing discipline below the level of
court-martial were generally not made public, but that they were in
this case because of the high level of interest and seriousness of
the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Under military rules, the four could refuse administrative
punishment and face the possibility of court-martial.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors argued in preliminary hearings that the four members
of the Prowler crew were reckless and negligent, and Rodgers agreed
that the performance of the pilot and navigator were flawed.
</P>
<P>
   But defense lawyers said there were other factors, including a
map prepared by the Defense Mapping Agency and used by the crew to
plan the mission. Although the ski lift was more than 30 years old,
it did not appear on the map. In fact, very few Italian ski lifts
do.
</P>
<P>
   The mapping agency said shortly after the accident that it only
listed ski lifts with towers that rose 100 feet. On this ski lift,
to Mount Cermis, the towers are much lower, although the cables
rise nearly 400 feet above the terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers said in his report that the mapping agency had copied
some of its data from the wrong Italian map. Beck, the lawyer for
Schweitzer, said Friday that the ski lift is still not on the map,
nor on an updated document published monthly.
</P>
<P>
   Beck said, ``There is no criminal problem for doing what is the
norm in the community, for doing it with the dad-gum information
that the superiors provide.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
