<HEADLINE>
BIGGEST NAMES TOP ALL-STAR LIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brazil's Ronaldo, France's Zinedine Zidane and six of their
teammates lead the 16-man World Cup All-Star team announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldo, the reigning world player of the year, was joined by
fellow Brazilians Rivaldo, Dunga and Roberto Carlos on the squad,
which was selected by the FIFA Technical Study Group. Zidane is one
of four Frenchmen, joining goalkeeper Fabien Barthez and defenders
Marcel Desailly and Lilian Thuram; forward Thierry Henry was one of
six reserves.
</P>
<P>
   The Netherlands placed three players --- Frank de Boer, Edgar
Davids and Dennis Bergkamp --- on the team, with goalkeeper Edwin
Van der Sar a reserve, and both of Denmark's Laudrup brothers,
Michael and Brian, also were selected.
</P>
<P>
   The full team:
</P>
<P>
   Goalkeepers: Fabien Barthez (France) and Jose Luis Chilavert
(Paraguay).
</P>
<P>
   Defenders: Marcel Desailly (France), Frank de Boer
(Netherlands), Carlos Gamarra (Paraguay), Roberto Carlos (Brazil),
Lilian Thuram (France).
</P>
<P>
   Midfielders: Edgar Davids (Netherlands), Dunga (Brazil), Michael
Laudrup (Denmark), Rivaldo (Brazil), Zinedine Zidane (France).
</P>
<P>
   Forwards: Dennis Bergkamp (Netherlands), Brian Laudrup
(Denmark), Ronaldo (Brazil), Davor Suker (Croatia).
</P>
<P>
   Reserves: Edwin Van der Sar (Netherlands, GK), Thierry Henry
(France, F), Jay-Jay Okocha (Nigeria, MF), Michael Owen (England,
F), Juan Veron (Argentina, MF), Christian Vieri (Italy. F).
</P>
<P>
   Moroccan man in the middle
</P>
<P>
   Morocco's Said Belqola has been assigned as referee for Sunday's
World Cup final between France and Brazil at the Stade de France,
the first African to earn the honor in the tournament's 68-year
history.
</P>
<P>
   Belqola, 41, an international referee since 1993, officiated the
U.S.-Germany and Argentina-Croatia clashes. The customs official
also worked at last year's Tournoi de France warmup and the African
Nations Cup earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   England's Mark Warren and South Africa's Achmat Salie will serve
as linesmen, with Saudi Arabia's Abdul Rahman Al-Zeid the fourth
official.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
