   MUTFUND-LIFE-STYLE-NYT (Undated) _ When mutual fund companies
started pushing so-called life-style and life-cycle funds, they
seemed like sure-fire hits: single funds that were meant to
simplify the decision-making process for befuddled investors.
Essentially, these funds would plunk an investor into a portfolio
with a mix of stocks, bonds and cash tailor-made to his investing
time horizon, eliminating the need to concern himself with
complicated issues like risk or asset allocation. The problem is
that investors, by and large, haven't warmed up to the idea. By
Abby Schultz.
