<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-BOMB-PLOT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE ARREST NINE IN LONDON BOMB PLOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By WARREN HOGE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In a coordinated sweep, the police in Ireland and
England arrested nine people Friday and said they had foiled a plot
to bomb central London, with only moments to spare.
</P>
<P>
   John Grieve, the head of Scotland Yard's anti-terrorist branch,
said three of the men had been caught with ``explosive devices'' in
their possession, apparently in bags and backpacks. One was seized
as he tried to enter University College London, a possible target.
``We believe these terrorist devices were intended to be used in
London within minutes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The police said the suspects, who were not immediately
identified, were members of the 32 County Sovereignty Committee, a
dissident hard-line Roman Catholic group opposed to the peace
settlement in Northern Ireland, and to support for the settlement
by Sinn Fein, the political wing of the Irish Republican Army.
</P>
<P>
   The name envisions the six counties of Ulster united with the 26
counties of the Irish Republic. The group's best-known member is
Bernadette Sands McKevitt, the sister of Bobby Sands, a famous
martyr to the Irish republican cause who died in May 1981 in a
hunger strike defying British treatment of Irish prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday afternoon's raids, the Irish police arrested a man and
a woman in Dublin and another man in Dundalk on the border with
Northern Ireland. The English police and members of the MI5
security force seized a woman on Oxford Street, London's main
shopping area; a man and a woman outside the new British Library
near St. Pancras train station; the man entering the university
language-study building on Gower Street; and two men across
Blackfriars Bridge on a street outside a supermarket in the South
London borough of Southwark.
</P>
<P>
   The London suspects were described as looking like college
students, carrying backpacks and dressed in jeans and sneakers.
Witnesses gave dramatic descriptions of the police leaping from
their patrol cars with guns drawn and of their own surprised
reactions to the sudden disruption in the normal hum of activity on
downtown streets.
</P>
<P>
   John Watkins, 30, a shopkeeper, said he had been looking out the
window of his secondhand furniture showroom on London Road in
Southwark when he saw two cars swerve to the corner and stop
abruptly.
</P>
<P>
   ``About eight blokes got out, obviously the old Bill with caps
and flak-jackets,'' he said. ``They went for a guy with a rucksack,
wearing jeans and a little denim jacket. They just told him, `Get
on the floor.' There were 10 guns pointing at his head.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth McAteer, 71, saw the scene and said: ``I thought they
were making a film. There was a man lying on the floor face down
with a bag by him. There was a whole lot of police with guns. There
was a lot of shouting going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosemary Wholey, out walking with her 14-year-old granddaughter,
said: ``There were police everywhere. It was a mad sight. Two
police cars raced down the road outside my house and one crashed
into a barrier, they were in such a hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   The police wrapped the hands of the men they captured there in
plastic _ presumably to allow forensic tests later _ before
bundling them into a car and driving away at high speed.
</P>
<P>
   The arrests in London appeared to have been set off by
information gathered by the Irish police in Dundalk earlier in the
day. The splinter groups that have not gone along with the
cease-fires adopted by the main paramilitary groups in Northern
Ireland have had little success in carrying off promised violent
operations as the police have repeatedly seized bombs, explosive
chemicals and mortar launchers before they could be used.
</P>
<P>
   Grieve, who is deputy assistant commissioner of Scotland Yard,
said, ``This evening's arrests are the result of prolonged
investigation into dissident criminal Irish republican terrorist
groups, and a successful surveillance operation carried out by the
Metropolitan Police and MI5 which had thwarted an imminent planned
terrorist attack in London.''
</P>
<P>
   The coordinated action drew praise from the prime ministers of
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   In London, Tony Blair said, ``This has clearly been a very
important and successful operation and further reflects the close
cooperation that exists between the security forces in the United
Kingdom and Ireland, as together we defeat terrorism wherever it
may exist.''
</P>
<P>
   In Dublin, Bertie Ahern paid tribute to the ``extremely
effective cooperation'' the joint operation demonstrated, and said
the two governments would ``tackle the terrorist threat from
whatever source.''
</P>
</TEXT>
