A0074 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NASCAR-POLE-COX     07-10 0372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-POLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Craven finds Loudon's still his lucky track
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ Three months ago Ricky Craven didn't know if he'd
ever run another lap on the Winston Cup circuit. Friday, he showed
he could in most dramatic fashion, winning the pole for Sunday's
Jiffy Lube 300 at New Hampshire International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Craven, in his familiar No. 50 red Monte Carlo, was the last
driver out and blew away the competition with a lap of 128.394 mph.
It was his first appearance on a NASCAR track since being diagnosed
with post-concussion syndrome, brought on by crashing into the wall
at Texas Motor Speedway a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told everybody I was going to come back and have fun, and
this is my idea of fun,'' said the 32-year-old Craven, who grew up
in nearby Newburgh, Maine. ``I wanted to run well, I wanted to have
a good strong performance. I knew as the thing unfolded I had a
shot at the pole, and we got it.''
</P>
<P>
   In winning the pole, his career third but first since 1996, also
at Loudon, Craven denied his teammate Jeff Gordon his sixth pole of
he year.
</P>
<P>
   This day's run for the pole had more twists than a pretzel. A
damp track played havoc early with the first wave of qualifiers,
leaving them miserably damp and bunched from positions 26 through
44.
</P>
<P>
   ``You knew what was going to happen out there,'' Gordon said.
``I'm glad we drew a later number. Sometimes it goes your way and
sometimes it doesn't. It certainly worked in our favor today.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody was so fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the same for everybody, at least in the beginning,''
said Jeremy Mayfield, who failed to qualify at 26th. ``When you get
rain drops hitting your windshield, that kind of knocks your
confidence down a little. But, I'm sure we'll get back up front
Sunday sooner or later. It was just one of those days where some
people got lucky and others didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   At least, it didn't cost him any money. Team owner Andy Petree
was fined $2,000 and the qualifying time of his driver, Ken
Schrader, was disallowed. Added weight fell from the car during his
qualifying run.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 2111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
