<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0358 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0078 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONGKONG-AIRPORT-NYT &LR;      07-10 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-AIRPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG'S LATEST LETDOWN: AIRPORT'S NOSEDIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MARK LANDLER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ It could not have had a more auspicious beginning,
with inaugural flights by Chinese President Jiang Zemin and
President Clinton, both of whom said they were duly impressed. But
then, world leaders don't have to line up at check-in counters,
claim their bags or sprint to far-flung gates.
</P>
<P>
   For everybody else who traveled through Hong Kong's lavish new
airport this week, the experience was less impressive than
bewildering. Planes were delayed, gates were mixed up, baggage was
lost, toilets backed up, flight information boards went dark and
crates of seafood rotted on the tarmac.
</P>
<P>
   To say that Hong Kong International Airport has had a turbulent
takeoff does not capture the bizarre string of mishaps that have
afflicted this $20 billion project since it opened Monday. Nor does
it evoke the outrage and embarrassment that people here feel about
what was supposed to be the pride of Hong Kong _ and has instead
become a colossal public-relations nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was complete chaos,'' said Peter Cleary, an American lawyer
who has lived in Hong Kong for 14 years and takes pride in its
reputation for brisk efficiency. Monday Cleary landed at the
airport at 10 p.m., was stuck on his plane for nearly two hours
while the pilot tried to find a gate, and finally collected his
bags at 4:30 a.m., after wandering the terminal for hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was incredibly shoddy, and I'm not a grouch by
nature,'' Cleary said. ``To call this teething problems is
farcical.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, under intense public pressure, Hong Kong's chief
executive, Tung Chee-hwa, said he would appoint an independent
panel to investigate the problems and determine who was
responsible. In the meantime, Hong Kong's top civil servant, Anson
Chan, pleaded with the public not to be too harsh on the airport
managers, as they labored to fix the problems.
</P>
<P>
   But the managers had the extreme misfortune of stumbling the
week after Hong Kong's first democratically elected legislature
since the handover took office. Grabbing a ripe opportunity for
political theater, the lawmakers on Thursday hauled in the chief
executive of the Airport Authority, Hank Townsend, for a 90-minute
inquisition, during which he was repeatedly urged to resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was meant to be a first-class project, but it has turned
into a ninth-class airport and a disgrace,'' said Lau Kong-wah, a
member of Hong Kong's main pro-Beijing party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our airport has become the laughingstock of the world,'' Lau
said, shooting a baleful glance at Townsend, a 65-year-old American
executive who came from Bechtel Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Townsend did not return telephone calls, but a spokesman for the
airport, Clinton Leeks, apologized for the foul-ups. He added that
the problems in the passenger terminal were abating.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is, people here are not in a generous mood. Hong
Kong's economy is sliding into its worst recession since World War
II, with soaring unemployment, a swooning stock market and a
crashing property market. Aside from a brief burst of enthusiasm
during the visits of Jiang and Clinton, Hong Kong has had a
listless year since it reverted to China last July.
</P>
<P>
   The government clearly hoped the new airport would be a tonic
for the city and a symbol of its brighter future. Certainly, the
project has an only-in-Hong-Kong feeling to it: Engineers chopped
the tops off two small islands, filled in the water between them,
and put a massive airport on top. They also built a web of bridges,
tunnels, and highways to transport people 21 miles into town.
</P>
<P>
   The government even turned the transition from the old airport
to the new one into a sideshow _ with a vast overnight move of
equipment through Kowloon that officials delighted in comparing to
D-Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government built up public expectations so much before the
event that people were expecting perfection,'' said Ian Perkin, the
chief economist at the Hong Kong General Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   There was also a whiff of hubris. Malaysia opened a new airport
two weeks ago in Kuala Lumpur _ with state-of-the-art technology
similar to that in Hong Kong _ and suffered major problems. Yet
Hong Kong plowed ahead with its plan to open its airport
immediately after the first anniversary of the handover.
</P>
<P>
   Perkin said the airport fiasco will hurt more than Hong Kong's
image. The airport's largest cargo handler said Thursday that it
was imposing an eight-day embargo on all imports and exports,
except food, medical supplies and newspapers. Perkin estimated that
the embargo would cost Hong Kong nearly $800 million in lost
exports.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when people here believe Hong Kong must fight to
retain its status as a special city within China, they say it can
ill afford such a loss. The prospect of companies bypassing Hong
Kong because it does not have convenient transportation facilities
is particularly galling to business executives here.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel it is shameful for Hong Kong to have spent so much
money and so many years on that project,'' said Peter Lam, the
co-host of ``Teacup in the Storm,'' a popular radio call-in program
in Hong Kong. Lam said he was deluged by calls from listeners eager
to fix blame for the troubles. ``Callers feel that the Airport
Authority has been arrogant,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For all the hand-wringing in Hong Kong, outsiders have been more
understanding about the airport's woes. Neil Sogo, a 37-year-old
Japanese businessman who arrived here Wednesday on a flight from
Tokyo, said he waited more than an hour for his bags, which he
found only after reading a handwritten sign. Still, he said, ``I'll
give it six months, and come back and try it again later.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Sogo added, the line at Immigration was short. ``Nobody
is coming to Hong Kong,'' he said with an apologetic smile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
