<HEADER>
A0084 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-SETTLEMENT-CO     07-10 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-SETTLEMENT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge calls meeting with tobacco lawyers
 &HT;    By Osler McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Lawyers on all sides of the pending $15.3
billion Texas tobacco settlement have been called to meet Monday
with the federal judge supervising the litigation in what appears
to be the judge's push to finish negotiations in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the people called to Texarkana said U.S. District
Judge David Folsom had told them to bring their suitcases. Folsom
chuckled Friday at the suggestion he may lock the lawyers and two
state legislators in a room to work out agreements on sticking
points that are holding up a finished deal.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge would not say why he called the status conference
in his chambers Monday morning instead of arranging a conference
call. ``I always try to get the parties to work out their
differences,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two legal challenges have waylaid the settlement, one objecting
to the possibility of $2.3 billion in legal fees Folsom awarded to
private lawyers who sued tobacco companies for the state and the
other seeking a share of the settlement for certain Texas counties
and public hospital districts.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Dan Morales said he was planning to be in
Texarkana on Monday and Tuesday and was prepared to leave his
assistants there longer while he met out-of-state Wednesday in
another stage of negotiations with cigarette makers to enhance the
Texas settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Morales announced in mid-January the Texas settlement _ the
largest among states that have settled lawsuits against the tobacco
industry for spending public money to treat poor people for
smoking-related diseases. By early February, Gov. George W. Bush
and seven legislators sued to intervene, protesting the 15 percent
of Texas' recovery that the private lawyers would get, which was
the percentage Morales had agreed with them to pay. Before Bush
intervened, Republican attorney general candidate John Cornyn sued
in state court to challenge Morales' authority to hire five law
firms to handle the case on contingency fee contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Seven Texas counties and hospital districts also sued to
intervene, contending the tobacco settlement should pay expenses
for treating poor people not covered by the Medicaid program.
</P>
<P>
   Folsom called together Morales, Bush's lawyers and attorneys
representing the seven legislators and counties and hospital
districts. The judge also summoned state Sen. Bill Ratliff and
state Rep. Rob Junell, the chairmen of budget-writing committees in
the Legislature, who have been involved with negotiations on the
county issue.
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff, R-Mount Pleasant, leads the Senate Finance Committee
and Junell, D-San Angelo, heads the House Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider this a very helpful development,'' Morales said.
``I think that we've now reached the point and we are now
sufficiently close on all the outstanding issues that the court's
active interaction in terms of pushing us that final yard or two
across the goal line will be very beneficial.''
</P>
<P>
   Morales said he was hopeful that negotiations through the
weekend may result in a united position before the Monday
conference. The counties and hospital districts that have asked to
intervene, all of them large, have been working for a formula that
would distribute tobacco settlement money to all 254 Texas
counties.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller counties have pushed for reimbursement on a population
basis. The larger counties have wanted payment on a pro rata
method, to reflect their larger share of treatment.
</P>
<P>
   For more than two weeks, attorneys for Morales, Bush and the
legislators have said they were close to resolving the dispute over
attorney's fees. That pending deal reportedly would leave an
arbitrators' decision on how much the tobacco makers pay the
private lawyers _ a process set out in the settlement _ immune to
attack. In return, Morales would agree to drop motions to fine
Bush, the seven legislators and their attorneys as much as $25
million for interfering with the tobacco negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and the legislators would be able to challenge the
difference, if any, between the amount the arbitrators order
tobacco to pay and the 15 percent the judge granted to the private
lawyers. Both Bush and the legislators argue that Texas would be
liable, from the settlement proceeds, for the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``My view is the attorney fee issues are essentially resolved,''
Morales said. ``There's an understanding among all parties that the
real hangup is the county issue. That is what is preventing
finality.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does us no good to resolve the attorney fee interventions
and . . . other issues if we still have counties unresolved. That
is the one issue that the industry insists be put to bed before
they will give us finality.''
</P>
<P>
   Morales' Wednesday trip will continue discussions with the
cigarette makers that could boost the $15.3 billion Texas deal by
$2 billion, based on the later settlement by Minnesota. The Texas
agreement allows it to renegotiate better terms won by other states
in later negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Forty states and Puerto Rico have sued the tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
