<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0085 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-BRAZIL-$     07-10 1396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-BRAZIL-$ADV12-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BRAZIL, ONLY VICTORY IS ACCEPTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 12) 
(jt) 
 By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   OZOIR-LA-FERRIERE, France _ After Brazil lost a soccer match to
the lowly United States last February, the entire nation fell into
a panic. Brazil is, after all, so consumed with soccer that it
would later show the team's departure for the World Cup on live
television and close the stock exchange in Sao Paulo for its
opening match against Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   In May, as Brazil continued slouching toward soccer's
quadrennial world championship tournament, losing unacceptably at
home to Argentina, 66-year-old Coach Mario Zagallo was viciously
attacked by the country's sports media. Lance, a daily sports
newspaper in Rio de Janiero, called the coach ``incoherent'' and
said the only way to cure Brazil's impotent play was to ``give them
Viagra.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, now that Brazil has again made its way into the World
Cup championship match, there is hardly an empty seat on the
bandwagon. Criticism has faded into frenzied expectancy. Sunday
night, in the northern Paris suburb of St.-Denis, Brazil will face
France in the championship game. If most of the 80,000 fans at
Stade de France will favor the home team, history will be on
Brazil's side. Already it owns an unprecedented four World Cup
titles, and it is favored to claim a fifth.
</P>
<P>
   As Brazil has advanced through the monthlong tournament, 3,000
fans have shown up here daily for practice at Stade de
Trois-Sapins, willingly paying $7 for parking, banging their drums,
blowing bugles, sounding air horns, chanting ``Ro-nal-do,
Ro-nal-do'' for the star forward and screaming at their heroes like
teeny-boppers greeting the Beatles. Entry for spectators is free of
charge, but capacity is limited, and fans said tickets for
practices this week were being scalped for $17.
</P>
<P>
   Practices have been telecast back to Brazil, and as many as
1,500 reporters have crowded around the tiny stadium, penned like
cattle, photographers using stepladders and radio reporters
conducting live interviews on their cellular phones.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the defending champion so fascinating is that victory
is the only acceptable outcome against France. Adulation will
quickly turn to disgust and despair with a loss. Brazil's 160
million citizens also consider themselves to be coaches; years ago,
Brazil's national team was actually coached briefly by a
sportswriter. The tension between expectation of victory and
intolerance of defeat is as indelibly part of this team as the
samba rhythm to which it plays.
</P>
<P>
   That strain was visible on Zagallo's weathered face after a taut
victory on penalty kicks over the Netherlands in Tuesday's
semifinal. Zagallo was so overcome that he left the field in tears.
He said he had begun taking tranquilizers to calm his nerves.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we win, I don't expect them to build a statue for me,''
Dunga, the team's irritable captain, said of Brazil's rabid fans.
``But if we lose, they'll kill me.''
</P>
<P>
   When the tournament began, the knock on Brazil was that it had
great players but not a great team. But that is also what makes the
squad so endearing. Sure, Brazil is inevitably glamorous, but it
has reached the championship game having endured evident flaws and
disquieting struggles.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil has one superstar in Ronaldo, who is considered the
world's greatest player and who churns toward the goal with a
middleweight's power and a halfback's speed. And there are young
magicians like Rivaldo, who necessarily straddles selfishness and
unselfishness, and Denilson, who seems to have the ball tethered to
his feet like a yo-yo. But the foundation of the team has been
built on the overlooked and the underappreciated.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil has reached this point, not with the splendid dominance
of previous World Cups, but with many players who were thought to
be too old and slow or too inexperienced and unprepared. It has
overcome internal bickering and incessant external criticism. And
it has survived the loss of Romario, the most valuable player in
the 1994 World Cup, who was sent home with a leg injury.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Brazil has relied on players like Bebeto, the
34-year-old forward taken out of mothballs to score three goals,
only one fewer than Ronaldo. It has relied on its balding
goalkeeper, Taffarel, who, sensitive to criticism, quit the team
temporarily in 1995 and briefly played on a church team. It has
relied on Ze Carlos, a defender who was selling watermelons a year
ago to supplement his soccer income and who had never started a
match until the crucible of the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's least celebrated starter, the midfielder Cesar Sampaio,
was ignored in 1994 and appeared to have steered his career into an
international dead end in Japan's professional league three years
ago. But he has become one of the team's most reliable scorers.
While every day seems like Carnival with this raucous sideshow of a
team, Sampaio prefers the quietly religious life, leading Bible
study sessions.
</P>
<P>
   The captain is the crusty 34-year-old Dunga, a midfielder who
runs this team with his long passes and his short temper. Brazilian
fans said he is nicknamed for one of Snow White's seven dwarfs _
Grumpy, no doubt _ and he nearly came to blows with Bebeto in the
middle of a first-round match against Morocco. But his sheer will
is the adhesive that holds this team together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like players who bring confidence to a team,'' said Pele,
the greatest Brazilian World Cup star of them all. ``They shout at
players, fight with players, bring them to the game.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Zagallo has been involved in all four of Brazil's World Cup
titles _ as a player in 1958 and 1962, as head coach in 1970 and as
an assistant to Carlos Alberto Parreira in 1994. Curiously, though,
Zagallo's success has never brought great trust from Brazil's fans.
</P>
<P>
   He is second-guessed constantly by Pele and other former Brazil
stars. After the loss to the United States, Zagallo was called
``second rate'' by Carlos Alberto, captain of the 1970 championship
team. Earlier this week, Pele lamented that Brazil's players
``don't exactly know what to do when they get the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Individually, they are a very good team,'' Pele said Friday.
``But Zagallo didn't have enough time to train the team. Parreira
had six months in 1994. Zagallo had 20 days.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, criticism is nothing new for a Brazilian coach.
Parreira's own mother criticized him for not playing Ronaldo, who
was then 17, during the 1994 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   With four goals in this World Cup, Ronaldo has not threatened
the tournament record of 13, set in 1958 by Just Fontaine of
France. But neither at age 21 has he crumbled under the burden of
expectation, this son of a mother who worked in an ice-cream parlor
and a father who struggled with alcohol, this megastar whose first
efforts at the junior level were thwarted in the Rio suburbs
because he could not afford bus fare. He has demonstrated the
footwork of a tango dancer, precise, unselfish passing and a
relentless charge toward the goal that the Netherlands could not
stop even by grabbing his jersey and the waistband of his shorts.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil has conceded seven goals in this tournament, compared
with three in 1994. But that team surrendered much of its flair for
the vise-grip pragmatism of defense. Zagallo has liberated this
team from its marionette strings and allowed it to entertain as
well as to win.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been great balance _ Ronaldo has four goals,
Bebeto, Rivaldo and Sampaio have three apiece _ a more organized
midfield and mesmerizing freelance work. Against the Netherlands,
the 20-year-old prodigy, Denilson, stepped over the ball four times
in one exquisite sequence, dancing an elusive jig as he sought a
detour around a defensive roadblock.
</P>
<P>
   Zagallo remains supremely confident about his place in history,
despite the public battering he has absorbed and the apparent toll
it has taken on his nerves. Defiantly, he has guaranteed victory
over France.
</P>
<P>
   ``The World Cup is safe in our hands, with our faith and our
courage,'' Zagallo said. ``When you open the pages of a history
book after I'm far from here, there will be living pages. There
will be the name of a man called Zagallo.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 2117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0361 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0087 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUBIN-FUTURE-NYT &LR;      07-10 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUBIN-FUTURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUMORS GROW: RUBIN WILL LEAVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On Wall Street, Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin is
probably the only member of the Clinton administration described in
consistently admiring terms.
</P>
<P>
   So it is no wonder that every time a rumor surges through the
markets that Rubin, who grew up on the Street, is thinking of
stepping down, traders tremble at their terminals. And there have
been plenty of such rumors over the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   These days, though, the rumors are emanating not from the
trading floors but from some of the secretary's Cabinet colleagues.
Right or wrong, it is accepted wisdom among them that he is
planning to leave Washington by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The week after the midterm elections,'' predicted one.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to go months ago,'' insisted another, ``but he
couldn't resign while Asia was coming unhinged.''
</P>
<P>
   A third said it was widely assumed that Rubin would leave,
although no one had heard that from him directly.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Treasury, midlevel officials are already handicapping
the chances of prospective successors, particularly those of
Rubin's deputy, Lawrence Summers, the onetime Harvard economist who
is clearly tempering his quick tongue and toning up his sometimes
haphazard attire to appear more, well, Rubinesque.
</P>
<P>
   Summers does not have a lock on the job. Some give an edge to
James Johnson, the longtime Washington power broker and departing
head of Fannie Mae, the federally chartered home mortgage
association. There is also lingering talk of Franklin Raines, who
recently resigned as director of the White House Office of
Management and Budget to succeed Johnson. Raines was reportedly
eager to leave the administration but might find Treasury
irresistible if President Clinton asked.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin hates travel, and some view his recent journey surveying
the economic devastation in Asia and a weeklong trip to Africa that
begins Saturday as farewell tours.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary himself is not exactly clarifying the situation.
Talking to him about his future is a bit like trying to extract
from him an inkling of when the United States might next intervene
in the currency markets. Good luck.
</P>
<P>
   He will tell you what his wife, Judy, thinks: Her dislike of
Washington and its pretensions is legendary, and she has voted with
her feet for the last five and a half years, remaining in New York.
( Rubin travels frequently between the two cities, by either
shuttle or executive jet.)
</P>
<P>
   He might also muse, but briefly, about the merits of staying or
going, about his continuing fascination with this moment of
bewildering global market instability and about the personal toll
of what he terms a difficult life style.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of important and interesting issues I'd like
to be involved in going forward,'' he said. ``On the other hand,
there are countervailing considerations.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, borrowing terminology from the deliberate obfuscation he
employed last week in talking about when to prop up the Japanese
yen, he added, ``I'll do what seems to be appropriate and not do
what doesn't seem appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   His closest confidants say Rubin will decide in the next few
months, perhaps while fly-fishing this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the administration believe that he can be persuaded to
remain with some combination of presidential arm-twisting and fears
that his departure could further unnerve edgy markets. In fact, his
aides try to dissuade reporters from writing about the rumors of
his departure at all, for fear that the articles alone could uncork
the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Rubin has become the market,'' one top Japanese diplomat
complained the other day during a visit to Washington, arguing that
the secretary's thumbs up or thumbs down on Japan's latest economic
contortions was the only signal investors were looking for.
</P>
<P>
   All this argues in favor of Summers' candidacy. He has long
played the role of Rubin's alter ego and debating partner, and has
become an increasingly fervent believer in the Rubin world view
that the power of markets must be respected by governments. Indeed,
it is Rubin's brand of market-driven economic conservatism that has
become the orthodoxy of the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   But Summers' relationship over the years with Vice President Al
Gore has reportedly been rocky, and Gore will presumably have a
major voice in who sets economic policy during his run for the
presidency. Further, Summers angered many in Congress during the
bailout of Mexico with his lectures about America's
responsibilities as the guardian of the global economy.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, however, the deputy secretary has become a much more
careful political animal. He also got a major boost recently when
Rubin talked to The New Yorker about what a fine Treasury secretary
he would make someday, comments that added fuel to the latest round
of Rubin rumors.
</P>
<P>
   There is another reason Rubin might go: Much of the time, the
Treasury secretary's job is not much fun these days.
</P>
<P>
   Twice in the last two months, federal judges have rejected the
Treasury's effort to create a ``protective function privilege'' for
the Secret Service that would have kept Whitewater independent
counsel Kenneth Starr from questioning agents who guard Clinton
about what they might have seen occur between the president and
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm completely comfortable with our position on this,'' Rubin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the embarrassment of the hearings on the IRS that
resulted in legislation forcing the Treasury to share authority
over the IRS with an outside board. Rubin and Summers made clear
their distaste for the bill last fall, then did a complete
turnabout when the inevitability of its adoption became clear.
</P>
<P>
   But Rubin's biggest frustration has been the unwillingness of
Congress to increase the U.S. contribution to the International
Monetary Fund, the international agency battling the global
economic contagion sweeping from Asia to Russia to Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ``His patience with the Hill is a lot thinner than it was,'' one
aide noted recently.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as another administration official who works with Rubin
often points out, reading his mind is like forecasting the markets,
and just as risky.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loves his job,'' this official said. ``He remains
fascinated by what he does and shows no sign of any intellectual
apathy. You can't say that about many people in Washington.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
