<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-VECSEY-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SPORTS COLUMN: THE WORLD CUP FROM 1 to 10  
(For release Sunday, July 12) 
(jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ One of the great traditions of soccer is rating the
players (and the officials) after each game. This is serious
business. When he was playing for Napoli, the addled Diego Armando
Maradona once threatened to kneecap an Italian reporter who had
assigned him a 3 in the scale of 1 to 10 (but in which 8's are
extremely rare).
</P>
<P>
   In the spirit of La Gazetta dello Sport and L'Equipe and other
journals, I now deliver my highly personal ratings on the World
Cup, which holds its championship game tonight.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL _ The Brazilians are the core of their sport, the way the
Montreal Canadiens and Boston Celtics and Notre Dame used to be in
theirs. Nobody resents the presence of Brazilian players or fans,
who turn every city, every World Cup, into Carnaval. Brazil will
win its fifth World Cup, on sheer talent and institutional history.
Muito obrigado. Thanks, so much.7.5.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE, THE TEAM _ They came into this World Cup with a
reputation for being faint-hearted fold artists, but they have been
charismatic and professional. It cannot all be attributed to being
the home team. I think the loss of Laurent Blanc for the needless
red card will hurt Les Bleus. 7.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE, ITSELF _ It is perhaps the most compactly complete and
beautiful country in the world. Paris is more beautiful than ever,
Lyon and Nantes and Aix-en-Provence were delightful, and, in this
jet-and-television-and-Internet era, the people are far more
flexible about visitors' ghastly French. Even with their smoking
habits: 7.5.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN SOCCER ESTABLISHMENT _ Having praised U.S. officials
for retaining Steve Sampson last year, I say we must call it a
collective national failure. The United States is just not there.
Sampson thought he had somehow become a genius. The older players
overrated themselves, and set a bad example. The younger players
did not have the heart of the older players. And the leadership let
it happen. Don't hold your breath for qualification in 2002. For
this year: 3.5.
</P>
<P>
   THE SKILL PLAYERS _ When I was a dreadful fullback in high
school a thousand years ago, I thought scorers were instruments of
the devil for the way they dribbled around me. In my mature years,
I have come to appreciate every goal they can conjure up. For touch
and instinct, I give thanks for Zinedine Zidane, Youri Djorkaeff,
Rivaldo, Ronaldo, Roberto Baggio, Patrick Kluivert, the Laudrup
brothers, the Nigerian brothers, and most of all Michael Owen,
whose quick feet and brash opportunism turned on the crowds. In the
informal way of saying thank you around Owen's native Chester, on
the border of Wales: Ta. 8.
</P>
<P>
   THE HACKERS _ There were kickers, shirt-grabbers, back-passers,
and coaches who feared losing so much that they plotted defensive
formations. I could have sworn I saw a team in red, white and blue
using three defenders, six midfielders and one lone striker. For
negative soccer: 3.
</P>
<P>
   THE REFEREES _ They were all over the place with their calls,
reacting to daily revisions and complaints and orders and updates
from FIFA central, soccer being invented on the run in the middle
of a World Cup. I give the refs a 4. No, make that a 6. Maybe a 3.
Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   BEST DOUBLE DIP _ Exiled Iranian fans who wore T-shirts
protesting the current regime, and then cheered the 2-1 victory
over the hapless Yanks. 7.
</P>
<P>
   FRENCH RAILROADS _ Watching the beautiful countryside floating
by at 100 miles an hour or more, I wanted to never get in an
airplane again. I love the train stations, with their bars and
newspaper kiosks, in the hearts of the old cities. Bon voyage. 8.
</P>
<P>
   BEST GAME I SAW _ Nigeria 3, Spain 2 on a chilly, rainy
afternoon in Nantes. Those two teams went at the goal for 90
minutes, nonstop. 7.
</P>
<P>
   BEST HALF I SAW _ England 2, Argentina 2 on a hot night in
St-Etienne. Then the idiotic foul by David (Red Card Spice) Beckham
turned the game into a defensive trudge. 7.5, followed by a 4.
</P>
<P>
   THE PEOPLE _ The Portuguese concierge in our building, the
African cabbies, the Vietnamese man who runs the Saigon restaurant
in Aix, the immigrants who work hard and make this country run. The
French street cleaner who found my World Cup credential and called
the New York Times bureau to return it. The people who cooked the
excellent $10 plats-du-jour in the cafe right below our apartment.
The old ladies who would stop and offer directions. Je vous
remercie. 9.
</P>
<P>
   THE VOLUNTEERS _ At the Press Centers, they all spoke three or
four languages. They knew how to get information. They were worldly
and adult. I wish they had been in Atlanta in 1996. Another 9.
</P>
<P>
   THE ORGANIZING COMMITTEE _ For the modern technology, the good
signs, the thoughtful juice and water on hot nights, a definite
7.5.
</P>
<P>
   THE ORGANIZING COMMITTEE _ For allowing journalists to smoke
incessantly in every press center I saw, including cramped offices
where we had to grovel for tickets. I'm sending you my dry-cleaning
bills, and if I come down with emphysema or asthma or worse, you'll
be hearing from my lawyer. 0.
</P>
<P>
   FIFA _ For making it difficult for a soccer-loving columnist to
cover my fifth World Cup, not making sure we all have seats for
games and access to interviews after games, for not providing news
conferences or reliable information on practices, for falling even
further behind the press-information skills of all major leagues in
North America: 2.
</P>
<P>
   THE WORLD CUP _ Having expanded the tournament from 24 to 32
teams, FIFA now recognizes it is too long at 33 days. However,
there has been a laudable attempt to include African, Asian and
North American teams, even if they are bumped out early, plus a
noticeable recruitment of talented third-world officials. FIFA has
set up serious problems by splitting the 2002 World Cup between
Japan and South Korea. Despite the bumbling and the arrogance, this
is still the greatest sports event in the world. 7.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
