   &UR; General Features &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ALTERNATIVE-TRADE (Undated) _ ``Alternative trade
organizations'' _ mail-order groups devised to improve local
economies in developing nations, were popular in the 1980s and
early 1990s. But tougher competition has taken its toll, with only
four such groups with sales of more than $1 million remaining in
the U.S. today. By Sara Silver.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-PENSIONS (Undated) _ Nearly 1,400 Americans are
collecting pension benefits because they found their names on an
Internet site created by the Pension Benefit Guaranty Corp., the
federal agency that insures pensions. The agency posted the names
of about 8,600 people who have not applied for benefits due to them
from plans the agency now administers. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Invest &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-INTERNET (Undated) _ It was a wild week on Wall Street
for Internet stocks. But because many of these fledgling companies
may be years away from actually making money, the sight of their
stocks skyrocketing one day and plummeting the next is enough to
make investors wonder if the Internet is paved with gold or just a
high-technology version of the tulip craze. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-INFLATION-BOND (Undated) _ More about the new
inflationed-protection savings bonds the Treasury unveiled this
week. By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-AURORA-FOOD (Undated) _ Aurora is a high profile example
but it hasn't done well. Tropicana, a rumored food IPO, may not go
that route because parent Seagram thinks there's a better way
(private sale). A look at what drove Aurora to the IPO trough and
what's keeping Seagram away. By Sana Siwolop. Photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-BADNEWS (Undated) _ It has become increasingly unusual
for Wall Street securities analysts to deliver bad news on a stock.
Even more unusual is when they not only quit recommending a stock
but call their past advice to buy it a blunder. Such is the case
with the share price of Agco Corp., a leading farm equipment maker.
By Rick Gladstone. Graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-AGING-ADVICE (Undated) _ Investment advice for Generation
A, the 80-somethings, fastest growing segment of the population.
Graphic. By Laura Pedersen-Pietersen. Graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mutfund &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MUTFUND-BLUECHIPS (Undated) _ Larry Puglia has turned in quite a
performance with the T. Rowe Price Blue Chip Growth fund. He tells
us why he can still outperform despite the fact that Blue Chips
look pricey. Photo. graphic. By William R. Long.
</P>
<P>
   MUTFUND-DICARLO (Undated) _ Profile of Michael DiCarlo, well
known manager of the once top performing John Hancock Special
Equities fund, who lost his bearings. By Carole Gould.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Spend &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CHILD-CARE (Undated) _ A growing number of companies pay
for child care when their employees must travel as part of their
jobs. But some question whether a benefit like this helps employees
have a more satisfying personal life, or simply keeps them on the
job and away from home longer. By Julia Lawlor.
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-NAVAJO-FOUNDATION (Gallup, N.M.) _ The Southwest Indian
Foundation enjoys a sterling reputation on the Navajo Reservation,
where it is a refuge of last resort for needy families. But it is
the group's direct-mail catalogue which the outside world sees, and
which raises questions about the mixing of charity and business.
Photo. By Jon Christenson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Auto Stories &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAR-SMART (Undated) _ A lot of convertibles shake, rattle and
roll. They leak and squeak, and, without the integral bracing of
solid tops, they flex like sponges when you wring them out on
bouncy roads. Outside the Sun Belt, they require 6 to 10 months of
compromise for 2 to 6 months of wind-blown freedom. This accepted
wisdom is fast becoming out of date. Photo. By James G. Cobb.
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT-CARS-BMW (Undated) _ A feisty terrier in a dog-eat-dog
business, BMW knows something about survival of the fittest. Its
ever-mutating 3-Series, which accounts for 44 percent of overall
sales, has become a genus with 31 species sold around the world.
Graphic and Photo. By James G. Cobb.
</P>
