<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0091 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIEMENS-PHONES-COX     07-10 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIEMENS-PHONES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Austin plant to make new Siemens phones
 &HT;    By Bruce Hight
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Siemens, the big German telecommunications
manufacturer, has tapped its 500-employee Austin plant to
manufacture a new line of cordless phones it hopes will broaden the
market for such phones beyond families and into home offices and
small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The Austin factory, at 2205 Grand Avenue Parkway, now makes
telephone handsets for private branch exchanges (PBXs) used by
businesses to handle telephone traffic, but that production is
being shipped to Leipzig, Germany, said Kristine Ryan, a
spokeswoman for Siemens.
</P>
<P>
   Production will begin on the new cordless phones in early
September and sales are expected to begin in the last quarter of
the year, in time for Christmas, Siemens officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The market for the phones is potentially a huge one: Siemens
estimates the small office and home office market has about 9
million potential buyers.
</P>
<P>
   The phones' base desk station can handle two phone lines and has
built-in features like Caller ID, an answering machine and a fax
machine connection and one cordless phone. However, the system can
handle up to eight cordless phones, and those can be used as an
intercom. The talking range within a building is about 200 feet.
Suggested retail price is about $400, and additional cordless
handsets will be $129. To get beyond the household and into the
office the phone was designed with two significant improvements
over similar systems to meet the higher demands of business: sound
quality as good as wired phones and security to avoid
eavesdroppers, said Marina Jarvis, a senior product manager for
Siemens who helped develop the product.
</P>
<P>
   Such differences, Jarvis said, come in part from using a higher
frequency _ 2.4 gigahertz. Other cordless systems, she said,
operate at 900 megahertz. The higher frequency is less subject to
electronic interference.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the new phone will use a voice-encoding technology to
block unwanted lurkers from listening in on conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Hodges, a telecommunications consultant who works with
Austin-based Technology Futures Inc., a consulting firm that
specializes in studying trends in technology development, said the
new Siemens cordless phone sounds more evolutionary than
revolutionary, but nevertheless is a significant step ``toward an
untethered future.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans are getting ever more accustomed to using phones
without being limited by connecting wires, Hodges said. That's true
both of cordless phones, which have a very limited range, and
wireless telephones, like cellular and PCS systems, which have
enormous range.
</P>
<P>
   For small businesses and home offices, Hodges said, Siemens'
cordless phone systems will offer a significant cost savings in not
having to wire an office or rewire it when someone moves a desk or
to a different room.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan said the cordless phone system would be sold through
specialty catalogs aimed at small business and high-end residential
users, retailers such as office stores and telephone companies.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
