<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   OPTIMISM ON EARNINGS BOLSTERS STOCK MARKET
</P>
<P>
   Optimism about earnings prospects returned to the stock market,
driving the major market measures higher. Investors were
particularly upbeat about the outlooks for banks and other
financial companies and for consumer goods companies.
</P>
<P>
   After falling on Thursday on DuPont's warning about
second-quarter earnings, the Dow Jones industrial average gained
15.96 points in a seesaw session, closing at 9,105.74. American
Express, Procter &AMP; Gamble and J.P. Morgan led the advance. For the
week, the Dow was up 80.48 points. The Nasdaq set its third
consecutive record, climbing 3.22 points, to 1,943.04. The Nasdaq
was up 2.6 percent for the week.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA SEEKS EXPANDED ASSISTANCE
</P>
<P>
   Russian President Boris Yeltsin urged Western leaders to support
a multibillion-dollar package of financial assistance to defend the
ruble. Russian officials said they were now seeking assistance of
$20 billion or more, at least $10 billion of which it hopes would
come from the International Monetary Fund. The request reflects
Moscow's concerns about its rapidly deteriorating economy.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING RAISES JET PRICES BY 5 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Boeing increased the base prices of its multimillion-dollar
passenger jets by 5 percent, the first such increase since 1975.
But analysts and airlines immediately questioned the impact of the
move since nearly all of Boeing's customers pay steep discounts on
the company's list prices.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER PRICES FELL IN JUNE
</P>
<P>
   Producer prices fell in June for the first time in three months
as energy costs retreated, the latest evidence that inflation is
not a threat. The Labor Department said that producer prices
dropped one-tenth of 1 percent. The core rate, which excludes food
and energy costs, rose two-tenths of 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   SPECULATION GROWS ABOUT RUBIN
</P>
<P>
   Rumors have circulated on Wall Street before that Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin is thinking of stepping down. But now
speculation is coming from some of the secretary's Cabinet
colleagues. Right or wrong, it is accepted wisdom among them that
he is planning to leave by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   SOFTWARE MAKER SEES SLOWDOWN
</P>
<P>
   SAP AG of Germany, the world's leading maker of
business-management software, disclosed Friday that rising labor
costs and weaker Asian currencies crimped profit growth in the
second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   IRS REPORTS SHOW FLAWS
</P>
<P>
   The Internal Revenue Service released an internal report that
found widespread overzealousness in the way the agency seized
property from delinquent taxpayers. The agency also issued a review
that repeated earlier findings that the IRS had put statistical
enforcement goals ahead of insuring that taxpayers were treated
fairly during audits.
</P>
<P>
   JOBS DISPUTE LOOMS AT UPS
</P>
<P>
   In a move that threatens to reopen a dispute that led to a
strike last summer, United Parcel Service told the teamsters' union
that it would not create 2,000 full-time jobs as promised in a
settlement that ended the strike.
</P>
<P>
   BOND PRICES FOLLOW DOLLAR DOWN
</P>
<P>
   Treasury prices slipped lower in thin trading, hurt by a weaker
dollar. The yield on the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose to
5.62 percent from 5.60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   INQUIRY VOWED ON HONG KONG AIRPORT
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's chief executive, Tung Chee-hwa, said he would
appoint an independent panel to investigate the problems that have
plagued Hong Kong's new $20 billion airport. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
