<HEADLINE>
IRS REPORT CITES ABUSES IN SEIZURES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Del.)  (lh) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One day after Congress gave final approval to
legislation overhauling the Internal Revenue Service, the tax
collection agency released an internal report Friday that found
widespread problems in the way it seized property from delinquent
taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate internal review also released Friday, the IRS
reiterated earlier findings that the agency had put meeting
statistical enforcement goals ahead of ensuring that taxpayers were
treated fairly during audits. The reports were the latest in a
series done by the IRS following Senate Finance Committee hearings
last year in which the agency was accused of harassing and
intimidating taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. William Roth, R-Del., who is chairman of the Finance
Committee, said Friday's reports were a ``stunning confession of
the sins of the IRS'' and validated contentions in Congress' that
the agency needed a top-to-bottom overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   ``In spite of the fact that I heard about problems in the
committee's hearings and in thousands of letters from taxpayers,
these reports are still astonishing in the scope of the taxpayer
abuse they confirm and in the fact that the reports are from the
agency itself,'' Roth said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted 96-2 Thursday to approve a bill that creates a
host of new protections for taxpayers who get into disputes with
the IRS and establishes an outside board with broad authority over
the tax agency's operations. President Clinton said he would sign
the bill, which was approved overwhelmingly by the House last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Keith, a spokesman for the IRS, said the timing of the
release was a coincidence. He said the agency had completed the
report earlier this week, and released it Friday after spending
several days removing any references that might identify particular
taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   In a review of 467 cases in which the IRS seized cars, homes,
cash and other assets from taxpayers, the report found that agents
had failed to follow proper procedures 130 times.
</P>
<P>
   The problems, the report said, included failing to pursue
alternatives to seizures, failing to notify taxpayers before
seizures, taking assets worth little more than the costs of seizing
them and ignoring mitigating circumstances that created hardships
for the taxpayer.
</P>
<P>
   In one case documented by the report the IRS seized a 1986 truck
from a taxpayer without the required in-person warning. The truck
was then sold by the IRS for $425, netting the government $7 after
accounting for the $418 expenses involved in seizing the truck.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Another case involved a contractor who had suffered a heart
attack two years earlier, and was suffering from high blood
pressure and bleeding ulcers. The taxpayer's file showed he had
been cooperative in attempting to pay his overdue tax bill,
providing all requested information and even charging his credit
cards to their maximum to get cash for the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   Although the IRS recommended at one point that the tax debt be
classified as uncollectible _ the equivalent of dropping the case _
the recommendation was never processed. Ignoring notification
requirements and procedures governing potential taxpayer hardship
and the likelihood that a seizure will bring in little money, the
collections division seized the man's car, and released it only
after the man agreed to an installment payment plan that will last
more than 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Other cases cited in the report involved collection actions
against taxpayers who were disabled by cancer, a seizure action
against grandparents who were raising two grandchildren and paying
major medical expenses, and a revenue agent who seized $500 worth
of goods from a grocery store owned by a taxpayer whose wife had
fallen ill and could no longer work.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the report, the IRS said it was taking a number
of steps, including developing a comprehensive check sheet
identifying all legal and procedural requirements for seizures and
sales of property and improving training materials. The agency said
it would also incorporate ``reasonable alternative collection
methods'' into its procedures.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's review of the use of statistics by audit managers
found widespread violations of IRS regulations intended to avert
the establishment of production quotas or goals that would lead
auditors to inflate tax liabilities or pressure taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   The examination division's management philosophy ``focused
primarily on enforcement statistics, which fostered improper use of
enforcement statistics,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the IRS said it had already stopped ranking the
performance of regional and district offices to reduce pressure to
compete internally to post the best revenue-collection numbers.
Starting this year, management evaluations will not include
enforcement results. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
