<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0099 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-10 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CALL FOR RENEWAL OF THE LEFT WITHOUT RELIGION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)  (bl) 
 By PETER STEINFELS    
 C.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Religious ideas, leaders, organizations and appeals have been an
integral part of American reform politics. Turn-of-the-century
progressives and even many socialists were imbued by liberal
Christianity and influenced by the Social Gospel movement. The
labor movement and the welfare state drew heavily on Jewish and
Roman Catholic communal traditions. Black churches were the
birthplaces and command centers of the civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   Now an eminent philosopher, whose maternal grandfather, Walter
Rauschenbusch, was the theological genius of the Social Gospel, has
issued a vigorous plea for the reconstitution of a broad, pragmatic
and reformist left in the United States. And one of the most
interesting things about this plea is the place it makes _ or does
not make _ for religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Achieving Our Country'' (Harvard University Press, 1998) is
the plea, and its author is Richard Rorty, a scholar often called
the leading gadfly of contemporary philosophy. This may be an
understatement, like calling the lethal iceberg the leading gadfly
of the Titanic.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of ``Achieving Our Country'' is Rorty's critique of
the ``cultural left.'' Barricaded in the university, this left has
isolated itself, he asserts, from the bread-and-butter issues of
economic equality and security and the practical political
struggles that once occupied the American reform tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Rorty, who is leaving the University of Virginia to become
professor of comparative literature at Stanford, sees leftist
intellectuals as launching increasingly abstruse and theoretical
assaults on the original sins of Western society, from capitalism
to heterosexism.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, controversies are seeded like land mines in every
paragraph of this short book. Conservatives have already fumed over
Rorty's nearly total silence about conservative ideas, as though it
were beyond the thinkable that grappling with them might have
anything to do with reconstituting a vital left.
</P>
<P>
   An even more intriguing absence in Rorty's vision of a renewed
left is religion. One might say that while ``Achieving Our
Country'' never rules out a place for religious forces in a
reformist coalition, it simply does not allude to them. But the
truth is still more complicated.
</P>
<P>
   In the book's first chapter, the author expounds a concept of
legitimate national pride that he hopes could reanimate a reformist
left. This national pride springs from a vision of America that
Rorty ascribes to Walt Whitman and John Dewey, a utopian vision in
which a nation free of caste and class would ``replace God as the
unconditional object of desire.'' For the poet and the philosopher,
America and democracy meant ``a new conception of what it is to be
human _ a conception which has no room for obedience to a nonhuman
authority.''
</P>
<P>
   It requires no complex reasoning to recognize why such an
animating vision would create problems for religious believers.
Indeed, for Jews, Christians and Muslims, some of this language
seems to meet the technical definition of idolatry.
</P>
<P>
   Rorty is not at all unaware of the power of religion as a moral
force in the United States. In a recent telephone conversation, he
acknowledged that ``in the foreseeable future the churches are as
likely to be on the right side as the wrong side'' in political
struggles. But that cannot alter his conviction, he said, that ``in
the final stages of democracy we won't need religion anymore.'' He
added that such a conviction may be ``off-putting, but I deeply
believe it _ I find the idea inspiring.''
</P>
<P>
   This conviction is, of course, consistent with Rorty's
longstanding position, argued in books and essays that even his
critics find dazzling, that all efforts to seek rational grounding
for moral claims, whether in some objective facts ``out
there,''some common human nature or some universal principles, are
futile hangovers from immature longings for religious certitude.
</P>
<P>
   So it is not surprising that religion does appear in ``Achieving
Our Country'' after all _ as a term of condemnation. Whenever Rorty
wants to chastise the ``cultural left,'' he accuses it of
abandoning secularism, getting religion or turning metaphysical.
</P>
<P>
   What is most interesting about all this is the tone. Despite
protestations of pragmatism, there is no sense that Rorty has
assessed the realistic prospects of making ``Whitmanesque
hypersecularism'' the centerpiece for building a broad reformist
coalition in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Nor, on the other hand, is there any sense that the author has
coolly decided to rally academic leftists at the cost of alienating
religious ones, who might understandably resist enlisting in a
battalion that has already emblazoned religion's epitaph on its
banners.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the anti-religious sentiments of ``Achieving Our
Country'' are matter-of-fact, unself-conscious, presented in the
untroubled tone that people often use in criticizing a group they
cannot imagine is even in the room.
</P>
<P>
   Is this the reality? Does religion _ except in a negative sense
_ simply fall outside the horizons of discussions about the
intellectual left and its future?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not too much should be concluded from a one-of-a-kind
thinker like Richard Rorty. It is interesting, however, that when
asked whether anyone else had raised questions about his book's
treatment of religion, Rorty said no.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
