r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-BOAT-TEX     07-10 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-BOAT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREG RAY TO REPLACE INJURED BILLY BOAT FOR A.J. FOYT'S TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Greg Ray is resuming his Indy Racing League
career today as ``hired gun'' driver for team owner A.J. Foyt.
</P>
<P>
   Ray, of Plano, will replace the recuperating Billy Boat in
Foyt's car beginning with the Pep Boys 400K at Dover (Del.) Downs
International Speedway on July 19. Ray also is scheduled to drive
Foyt's No. 11 Conseco Dallara/Aurora under the lights at Charlotte
Motor Speedway in Concord, N.C., on July 25, as the IRL reels off
two races within six days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm coming in as a hired gun while Billy is away,'' Ray said
yesterday, before heading to A.J. Foyt Enterprises in Houston for
the weekend. ``I'm very excited and want to drive A.J.'s car. It's
a pretty big honor. But by no means am I after Billy's seat. I'm
just doing the best I can to further my career. And I wish Billy a
speedy recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   Boat, winner of the True Value 500K at Texas Motor Speedway here
June 6, sustained a broken left leg and fractured pelvis in a crash
during the most recent Pep Boys IRL race at New Hampshire
International Speedway on June 28. Boat's doctors have listed his
recovery timetable at eight weeks. But Boat, pole sitter for the
Indianapolis 500 in May, said yesterday that he plans to keep his
downtime to a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be back for Pikes Peak for sure,'' said Boat, referring
to the season's eighth race at Pikes Pike International Raceway in
Fountain, Colo., on Aug. 16. ``That's definite. Anything sooner
will be a bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the fortunes of Boat and Ray have been linked at two
of the season's biggest events. Despite sponsorship problems, Ray
qualified second to Boat at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway. And
Boat's victory at TMS came at the expense of Ray, who finished
0.928 seconds ahead of the No. 97 Dallara/Aurora owned by Thomas
Knapp.
</P>
<P>
   Those efforts impressed Foyt, first four-time winner of the Indy
500, whose team also includes Kenny Brack of Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greg had some fine runs this year at Indy and Texas,'' Foyt
said. ``We had to work hard to beat him at both places. It was a
logical choice to have him drive for us now.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray said he, Foyt and team manager Tommy LaMance had been
negotiating for 10 days. A lack of sponsorship prompted Ray and
Knapp to skip the race in Loudon, N.H. Ray and Knapp were planning
to return to the series at CMS and also run at Atlanta Motor
Speedway (Aug. 29), the second race at TMS (Sept. 20) and the
season finale at Las Vegas Motor Speedway (Oct. 10).
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have a full sponsorship for the Charlotte race, so
it would have been hard on us,'' said Ray, who had his seat flown
from Knapp's shop in Indy to Foyt's in Houston to be fitted into
the No. 11 car. ``Now I can focus on doing a good job for A.J. and
go back to my car with Tom.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray said Knapp, who also serves as his engineer, is not included
in the deal with Foyt.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I do a good job at Dover and Charlotte and Billy's still
not in full health, maybe I would do Pikes Peak for them,'' said
Ray, whose nine IRL starts have been highlighted by the 18 laps he
led at Indy on May 24. ``Billy's recuperating pretty quickly, so it
depends on his health and well-being.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
