<SLUG> BC-PINKERTON-MOVE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINKERTON'S NOT SECRETIVE ABOUT HEADQUARTERS MOVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The corporate parks framed by oak trees and bike
paths in Westlake Village are about to get another transplant from
the city of Los Angeles: Pinkerton's Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The worldwide security services company, which provides security
for the Academy Awards ceremony among other assignments, signed a
10-year, $16 million lease at the 30-acre Westlake Spectrum
complex, property owner The Johnston Group of Calabasas announced
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-September, Pinkerton's will be moving into one building
and part of another facility at the Westlake Spectrum, taking over
68,000 square feet. The Johnston Group is spending more than
$1million to renovate the two buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Pinkerton's currently occupies a high-rise building on Ventura
Boulevard in Encino, a Los Angeles suburb located 16 miles
northwest of downtown, with the Pinkerton's name across the top.
The building will be subleased since the company's lease doesn't
end for a few more years, according to property owner TrizecHahn, a
Toronto-based real estate firm.
</P>
<P>
   The $2 million move will transfer more than 200 jobs out of Los
Angeles to Westlake Village, located 35 miles northwest of
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Pinkerton's officials said the company had outgrown its Encino
offices when they announced this spring the search for a new
headquarters. Pinkerton's officials were unavaible for comment
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Cal Johnston, chairman of The Johnston Group, said he believes
the business-friendly attitude of city leaders in Westlake Village
drew Pinkerton's to the upscale community.
</P>
<P>
   ``They considered a number of facilities along the (Ventura
Freeway) corridor,'' he said. ``In some of the other communities,
some members of the (city) council have not been as responsive.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Westlake Village's City Council _ which is
currently building a new City Hall, library and community center at
the Spectrum Complex _ agreed that it would let tenants share its
60 parking spaces during business hours.
</P>
<P>
   The city will reclaim the spaces in the evenings and weekends
for council hearings and community events. In return, the corporate
tenants also will share their parking spaces during special events
that draw big crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles also charges more taxes and fees than many cities in
the region. However, a spokesman for Mayor Riordan's L.A.'s
Business Team said the city is studying ways to cut its taxes to be
more desirable to companies.
</P>
<P>
   Pinkerton's move will enhance Westlake Village's reputation as a
center of corporate headquarters, said Tom Parker, president of The
Emerald Group, an international security management and
investigations firm. Food manufacturer Dole is already in Westlake
Village and footwear maker K-Swiss Inc. will soon move from the
L.A. suburb of Chatsworth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Westlake Village is a very pleasant place for one's corporate
headquarters,'' Parker said. ``There's no smog or congestion.''
</P>
<P>
   The town is big enough for the two security firms, he said,
because their businesses are in different niches: The Emerald Group
focuses on executive theft or fraud within companies, while
Pinkerton's provides security personnel and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1850, Pinkerton's employs more than 47,000 people and
has 250 offices worldwide. Annual revenues exceed $1billion. The
company counts more than 80percent of the Fortune 1000 companies as
its clients. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
