<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-PRIEST-ABUSER-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHURCH AGREES TO PAY VICTIMS OF SEX ABUSE BY PRIEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CAROL MARIE CROPPER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ In what is thought to be the largest such settlement
ever, the Roman Catholic Diocese of Dallas agreed on Friday to pay
$23.4 million to eight former altar boys and the family of a ninth,
who were victimized by a priest in the 1980s and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the settlement, the diocese promised to bring in
professionals to examine its practices and to make recommended
changes to prevent such abuse in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement settles the last complaints against Rudolph
``Rudy'' Kos, a former priest now serving a life sentence for
abusing boys in three churches in or near Dallas. One of the nine
plaintiffs to receive Friday's settlement is the family of a young
man who committed suicide. The diocese had agreed to pay three
other Kos victims $7.5 million in April.
</P>
<P>
   The settlements came after a Dallas jury last summer awarded a
record $119.6 million, plus interest, to 11 plaintiffs, a record in
a sexual-abuse case against a church. A 12th victim filed suit
after that award and was included in Friday's deal.
</P>
<P>
   Windle Turley, an attorney for the plaintiffs covered by
Friday's settlement, said his clients agreed to take so much less
than the jury awarded because they knew the diocese could not
afford the larger amount. ``It has never been the intention of
these individuals to destroy the diocese,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The bishop of the diocese, Charles Grahmann, issued an apology
in announcing the payment.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the victims and their families, I once again want to
apologize on behalf of the diocese,'' he said in a written
statement. ``Based on what we know now, the decisions made
concerning Rudy Kos were errors in human judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret very much what happened, and I am deeply sorry for
your pain,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs had pointed out that Kos had served a year in a
juvenile detention center for molesting a neighbor and that his
ex-wife, in a deposition, said she informed a diocese
marriage-tribunal official of her former husband's sexual interest
in boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hierarchy of the Dallas diocese ignored the problem _ with
Kos and some other priests,'' said Pat Lemberger, whose son, Jay, a
former altar boy, committed suicide at age 21. ``They knew
something was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not jumping for joy,'' he said of the settlement. ``No
matter what they do _ how much money they give me _ it's not going
to bring my son back.''
</P>
<P>
   Another plaintiff, now a 32-year-old businessman in Dallas, said
he was first abused by Kos when he was in elementary school.
Finally having the church recognize what happened was better
therapy than the years he has spent with professionals, said the
plaintiff, James Sibert. ``That's the last step in my journey.''
</P>
<P>
   The diocese will have to borrow money and sell property to make
up the settlement portion not covered by its insurance, according
to Grahmann.
</P>
<P>
   He also pointed out that the diocese _ which covers 64 churches
and seven missions in nine North Central Texas counties _ had
already set up a conduct review board with psychologists, a
law-enforcement officer, an attorney and a priest to handle
allegations of misconduct.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Kos case was not the only sexual-abuse lawsuit the diocese
has had to contend with recently. In February it settled suits
involving two other former priests and five plaintiffs, agreeing to
pay $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Sexual-abuse claims have become common in Roman Catholic
dioceses, according to Thomas Economus, a priest who is president
and co-founder of The Linkup, a group formed to help victims of
sexual abuse by clergy, based in Chicago. Because of this,
insurance companies have begun refusing coverage, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Roman Catholic church has responded to the problem by
choosing to hide it, deny it or litigate rather than rushing to the
aid of victims, Economus said. But Bill Ryan, spokesman for the
National Conference of Catholic Bishops, disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church is not closing ranks,'' he said. ``The church is
dealing with this in an open manner and is making every effort to
root out this kind of problem and address it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
