<SLUG> BC-BOEING-PRICE-HIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING RAISES BASE PRICES FOR COMMERCIAL AIRCRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seeking to improve its long-term financial performance, Boeing
Co. said Friday that it had increased the base prices of its
multimillion-dollar passenger jets by 5 percent, the first such
increase since 1975.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts and airlines immediately questioned the impact of
the move since nearly all of Boeing's customers pay steep discounts
on the company's list prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Boeing was hoping to impress Wall Street, I, for one, am
hardly impressed,'' said Byron Callan, an aerospace analyst with
Merrill Lynch in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing said that it had recently begun telling customers that
orders negotiated after July 1 would reflect the new prices. Those
prices previously ranged from $30.5 million for the 100-seat 717
jetliner to $176.5 million for the largest 747 jumbo jet.
</P>
<P>
   Any new revenue Boeing would receive would not be booked until
after 2000 because of the long lead time between ordering and
delivering airplanes, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, which is the world's largest aerospace company and the
country's single largest exporter, has been struggling since last
fall to overcome production problems that last year resulted in its
first annual loss in 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors and analysts have criticized the commercial
airplane division for cutting its prices too deeply to avoid losing
orders to its rival Airbus Industrie, the European consortium.
Friday's news appears to contradict Boeing's previous contention
that the way to improve its profits was to cut costs, not raise
prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are raising prices, what does that say about your
efforts to reduce costs?'' Callan said.
</P>
<P>
   Janice Hayes, a Boeing spokeswoman, said the increases simply
brought Boeing's base prices more in line with those of Airbus,
which she said were 2 to 6 percent higher than Boeing's.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing also changed the formula it uses to adjust its prices for
inflation between the time an airline places its original order and
when the aircraft is delivered, a period that can be several years
with large orders.
</P>
<P>
   While Ms. Hayes acknowledged that Boeing regularly gave its
customers discounts, she said the new base prices would raise the
starting point of the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   But Tony Molinaro, a spokesman for United Airlines, which is
about to place an order for short-haul jets, was skeptical. ``If
they start the negotiation from a higher point, that is their
prerogative,'' he said. ``We will see how it competes against
Airbus.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 2144EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
