<SLUG> BC-WAYNE-WILLIAMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVICTIONS UPHELD IN MURDERS IN ATLANTA 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By RICK BRAGG    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A Butts County circuit judge Friday denied a request
that he overturn the 16-year-old murder convictions of Wayne
Williams, the Atlanta man sentenced to life in prison in 1982 in
the murders of two adults and blamed but never indicted in the
series of child killings here in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Williams have argued for years that prosecutors
withheld evidence in the state's case against him, including
wiretaps that implicated others, a claim that they had hoped would
result in the dismissal of his conviction and a new trial.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Judge Hal Craig ruled that Williams' conviction would
stand. The judge sided with state prosecutors who have insisted
that such claims are irrelevant when weighed against other,
substantial evidence of Williams' guilt.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Whatley, one of Williams' lawyers, said he would ask the
judge to reconsider his decision. If the judge does not, Whatley
said he would appeal the ruling to the Georgia Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   If Craig had dismissed Williams' convictions, he would probably
have been tried again in Fulton County, where police used the
arrest and conviction of Williams, then 23, to close the case on
the child killings.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was found guilty of killing two adults, Jimmy Ray Payne
and Nathaniel Carter, but investigators also linked him to 10 other
killings in the child murders investigation. Atlanta police would
blame him for 24 killings in all.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' lawyers have argued that the Ku Klux Klan was linked
to at least one death, and that statements by witnesses were kept
from the jury.
</P>
<P>
   But in court papers, state prosecutors argued that hundreds of
witnesses and items of evidence created an overwhelming case
against Williams, and that any information not known by the defense
would not have altered the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Craig, in his ruling, noted that ``nothing has weakened the
testimony about the scratches down petitioner's arms, consistent
with defensive marks left by strangling victims.''
</P>
<P>
   He wrote that other evidence linked Williams to the two murdered
men, including fibers pulled from Williams' home and automobiles
that matched those found on the victims' bodies, ``the strongest
scientific link in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   He also wrote that inconsistencies in Williams' testimony, blood
evidence linking him to the crimes and other evidence had not
changed.
</P>
<P>
   Two investigators in the case said recently they did not believe
that Williams was guilty. DeKalb County Sheriff Sidney Dorsey and
Fulton County Police Chief Louis Graham, who were homicide
investigators in Atlanta at the time of the killings, told
``Dateline NBC'' that they believed Williams was innocent of the
crimes he was charged with, and those he was only suspected of. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 2145EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
