<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-CANUCKS-RICHTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANUCKS MAY CHASE RICHTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bobbing and weaving between the Rangers and Mike Richter
more or less continued Friday, with Richter contemplating the
Rangers' latest contract offer, made last Wednesday, for a
three-year deal worth between $5 million and $5.4 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   But neither the team nor Richter, who is an unrestricted free
agent, reported any significant progress in the negotiations.
Meanwhile, there was speculation in Vancouver on Friday suggesting
that the Canucks might make an offer to the free-agent goaltender.
</P>
<P>
   Richter, a Ranger for nine seasons, was offered a five-year
contract worth $27 million by New York before the free-agent
signing period began on July 1. Richter turned down the deal,
hoping he could attract more money and get a no-trade clause,
either from the Rangers or the Philadelphia Flyers. But the Flyers
opted to sign John Vanbiesbrouck earlier this week, thus limiting
Richter's options.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver has Mark Messier, Richter's old teammate, and Mike
Keenan, Richter's old coach. They could be a magnet to lure
Richter. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 2150EDT &QL; 
