<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0120 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BULLS-AZR &LR;      07-10 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BULLS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVE HEARTS READY TO RUN WITH THE BULLS _ 1ST TIME IN AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESQUITE, Nev. _ Ron Beier recalls as the greatest adrenaline
rush of his life a fleeting moment a decade ago as he ran the
narrow streets of Pamplona, Spain.
</P>
<P>
   A huge, 1,500-pound red bull with sharp horns drew a bead on
Beier, a former Phoenix-area firefighter, and charged from 40 feet.
As Beier did a feint, the bull's horn swiped him across the thigh.
He said he was so pumped that he never felt the blood streaming
down his leg.
</P>
<P>
   So, Beier was one of the first to send in his $50 entry fee when
he heard that the running of the bulls was coming to this country
for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   About 500 participants will gather today in this gambling mecca
on the Arizona border to test their meddle against a dozen rodeo
bulls from a Utah ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that summer temperatures here are straight out of
Death Valley. Or that Nevada transportation officials refused to
let it be run on Mesquite's casino row because of public safety
concerns. Or that no one really knows if these ranch bulls of
Brahman and Angus bloodlines have enough of a mean streak to make
the event entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   That's the fun of it all, says promoter Phil Immordino of
Phoenix, who timed the event to coincide with the famed running of
the bulls in Pampolona during the Fiesta of San Fermin. At least 13
people have been killed at that event, made famous in Ernest
Hemingway's novel ``The Sun Also Rises,'' over the past 75 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just kind of rolling the dice here the first time
around,'' said Immordino, who also had pitched the idea of a bull
run to city officials in Phoenix and Long Beach, Calif., before
deciding that ``I had to go through too many hoops.''
</P>
<P>
   But the idea was embraced by Mesquite Chamber of Commerce types,
eager to attract visitors during the caldron of summer.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Immordino isn't leaving much to chance in the bull
run, which will be held on a quarter-mile stretch of dirt road on
the Oasis Resort Ranch on the Arizona side of the border.
</P>
<P>
   Movie-set props have been brought in to make the 40-foot-wide
course look like a town. Six-foot high barriers line the parameters
of the run area, with exits every 100 yards for runners who feel
the bulls are too close for comfort. Rodeo clowns will act as
diversions for the bulls should the animals get too cantankerous.
</P>
<P>
   As of late Friday afternoon, he said about 500 people had signed
up. Immordino said he was considering two separate runs of 300
people each if there are another 100 or so late entries.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the event earlier had predicted that up to 25,000
people would watch the running of the bulls but Immordino said,
``I'll be content if 5,000 people show up.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he decided on a 10 a.m. start because of the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Mesquite's isolation and the warm temperatures also have acted
as a deterrent to animal-rights groups like People for the Ethical
Treatment of Animals, who had sought to boycott the event through
numerous postings on the Internet. One boycott organizer said
Friday that she had received fewer than only 10 responses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those people also picket dog shows. They are nuts,'' Immordino
said. ``They are afraid to find out the facts. It's people in peril
here, not animals.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which is just fine with Beier, the veteran bull runner,
who also has run in similar events in Mexico. He said he plans to
use the traditional clothes of Pamplona in his Mesquite run _ white
pants, red shirt and sash and maroon beret.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always a little nervous because you don't know if the
bulls will move in a pack or individually or whether other runners
will knock you down,'' Beier said. ``But let's give it a whirl and
see what happens.'' &QL; 
Mark Shaffer can be reached at 444-8057 or at
mark.shaffer(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 2150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
