A0123 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK11-COX     07-10 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No lead's too big to Cox
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Opening the night with a season-high 13 1/2-game lead in
the NL East, Braves manager Bobby Cox has already gone to some
lengths to reach an understanding with the clubhouse over what such
a huge lead means. And what it means, at least in the manager's
office, is zilch.
</P>
<P>
   ``You either go all out,'' said Cox, ``or you don't play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves haven't led the division by this much since the last
day of the 1995 season, when they finished 21 games ahead of New
York and Philadelphia. Before he got very far into the second half,
Cox used a team meeting to downplay the franchise's best start
ever. Cox might know better, too. When managing in Toronto, he led
the Blue Jays to an early 10-game lead in 1985 and wound up winning
the division by two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to play every game like you're one ahead of
everybody,'' Cox said. ``I told them that last night. We mentioned
all that to them. We haven't won anything. A 30-game lead is
nothing. There won't be any half-ass playing. ...That's exactly
what I told them. You think you got a big lead? You got nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have been in first place since April 20 and have
maintained at least a six-game cushion since June 1, but did not
take a double-digit lead until July 3. A three-game sweep of the
Mets pumped the advantage to 12 1/2 games at the All-Star break. Of
the six previous years Atlanta had ever led a division at the
midway point, the biggest bulge was just 6 1/2 games, that one
coming just last year.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps such strong wording is surprising coming from Cox, given
his run of six division titles in seven years. but he also knows
that the club is carrying 15 players that weren't in the clubhouse
for the team's 1996 World Series. It was almost a warning for the
newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason you don't give this thing intensity every
night,'' the manager said, ``absolutely no reason for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Klesko on the mend
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Klesko was greatly improved during batting practice Friday
and as long as he feels comfortable sprinting, the left fielder
could be back in the lineup tonight. He took some early sessions in
the cage and swung nothing like the tentative hacks he took
Thursday. ``If I can't run well, like if I can't run down a fly
ball, I'm not going to jeopardize the team just to get back out
there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Step by step
</P>
<P>
   Now that John Smoltz has put together three 100-pitch games
without elbow trouble _ a first this season _ and was able to throw
his hardest yet in Thursday's 6-4 win, the right-hander has a new
goal: a string of 10 starts without complications. Thursdaymarked
his fourth start since coming off the DL (2-1, 3.33 ERA) and his
first since cortisone injections for his back July 2. After missing
the first two weeks of the season, Smoltz went just eight games
before going on the DL again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to pitch 10 games in a row and get on a roll that
way,'' he said. ``(Thursday) the ball was coming out easy. I
surprised myself. (Ten starts) is my goal. We're still on a plan to
be somewhat cautious and not go overboard with pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Andruw Jones was back in center field and Cox considers
Thursday's tardy return (along with rookie Randall Simon) to the
club to be old business. ``They made a mistake,'' said Cox. ``Not
going to hold it against them.'' ... Reserve outfielder Curtis
Pride has had the four remaining stitches removed from his left
index finger and is eligible to come off the DL Monday, which is an
off-day. ``Maybe we'll send him to one Triple-A game,'' said Cox.
``I don't know. Wouldn't hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
