<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0384 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0127 &Cx1f; tic-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INCOMEGAP-AZR &LR;      07-10 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INCOMEGAP-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHASM BETWEEN RICH AND POOR GROWING IN ARIZONA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RUSS WILES  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you thought the Grand Canyon referred only to Arizona's most
famous natural wonder, you'd be wrong. There's also a wide _ and
growing _ chasm between the state's richest and poorest people.
</P>
<P>
   That's one highlight from a new study that gives the state
generally low grades overall for economic success and especially
poor marks on measures of affluency.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona received two C's and a D on the latest report card from
the Corporation for Enterprise Development in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   That's down from two C's and a B last year.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing the study had to say about Arizona was that the
state's highway bridges are in better shape than those anywhere
else in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most glaring weakness was in equity measures that reflect
the poverty rate and the income gap between rich and poor
households, which is already big and increasing,'' said Daphne
Clones, a senior policy analyst for the non-profit
economic-development group.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona earned the dubious distinction of having the nation's
largest increase in the gulf between rich and poor over a multiyear
study period. The Corporation for Enterprise Development also
ranked the state's poverty rate as fourth-worst and its urban-rural
income gap as fourth-widest.
</P>
<P>
   Those results come as no surprise to Christie Van Wormer, who
struggles to make ends meet by working two part-time jobs totaling
about 55 hours a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone I know works two jobs,'' said the 32-year-old Phoenix
woman, who earns $6.60 an hour at her main job as a retail clerk,
with no benefits. She supplements that by working two or three
nights a week as a waitress.
</P>
<P>
   Van Wormer is struggling to stay out of debt and recently turned
to Consumer Credit Counseling Services Southwest for help. She
hopes eventually to return to school to improve her standard of
living.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't have an education or a specialized skill, then
waiting tables is the best you can do,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Corporation for Enterprise Development found that two-thirds
of all states experienced a widening gap between haves and
have-nots, yet Arizona suffered the worst change in this regard.
The group compared income data from 1994-1996 against results from
1991-1993.
</P>
<P>
   The poor showing also doesn't surprise Tom Rex, research manager
at the Center for Business Research at Arizona State University. He
said he believes the state's wider-than-normal income gap has been
masked by strong overall job growth during the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much does (increasing employment) help the economy if you
import a person from another state to fill it, or if you're
creating jobs that pay $6 an hour?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Colorado and Washington led the nation with straight
A's. Delaware, Massachusetts, Minnesota and Utah were next with two
A's and one B.
</P>
<P>
   West Virginia brought up the rear with straight F's. Arkansas,
Hawaii and Mississippi were only slightly better with two F's
apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Among regional neighbors, Arizona fared worse than California,
Nevada and Utah but better than New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   All states received a grade from the Corporation for Enterprise
Development in each of the following three categories: economic
performance, business vitality and development capacity.
</P>
<P>
   After three years with a C grade for economic performance,
Arizona slipped to a D in the most recent evaluation. The widening
rich-poor gap and high poverty rate hurt the state, as did low
marks in various social measures such as infant mortality, crime,
teen pregnancy and infectious diseases. Among positive factors, the
study noted that Arizona's employment is high and the state posted
the 11th-best increase in average pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Personal) earnings have been average or below average in
Arizona, yet they're likely trending upward,'' Clones said.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona maintained its C grade in business vitality, which
measures competitiveness, industrial diversity, new-business
formation and more. The study identified entrepreneurs as a
strength for the state, which logged the nation's third-highest
growth rate of new companies.
</P>
<P>
   For development capacity, Arizona dropped from a B grade to a C.
This wide category measures educational achievement, technology
resources and banking activity, and a variety of
infrastructure/amenity factors from bridges and mass transit to
housing costs. Bad marks for the state included poor results for
high school graduation, college attainment and
commercial/industrial lending.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, the study revealed the state's technology sector as
vibrant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arizona had solid ranks across all technology indicators,
including the 15th-highest rate of federal research-and-development
dollars,'' according to the Corporation for Enterprise Development.
</P>
<P>
   The group also gave each state a positive, negative or average
mark for tax and fiscal policies, reflecting tax fairness, fiscal
stability and other measures. Arizona earned the top score here on
the three-point scale.
</P>
<P>
   The Corporation for Enterprise Development is a private,
non-profit organization that works with state and local
governments, companies, foundations and others to improve economic
competitiveness and expand opportunities in various communities. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Russ Wiles can be reached at 444-8616 or at russ.wiles(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
