<HEADLINE>
RUFFIANS ARE BEHAVING ENTERING THE DWYER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ Coronado's Quest, the Triple Crown dropout whose
talent and pedigree were undermined by his violent manner, will run
as a presumably reformed rogue against four other 3-year-old colts
in the 81st Dwyer Stakes Sunday at Belmont Park.
</P>
<P>
   His chief rival is expected to be Scatmandu, another horse with
a world-class pedigree and a history of bad behavior that includes
bumping and even biting other horses. He was also reported to have
calmed down this summer, so a well-mannered duel between two
talented colts is expected to be run at a mile and one-sixteenth
for a purse of $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coronado's Quest had a frightful experience the first time he
ran in Florida,'' said Shug McGaughey, who trains the colt, ``and
it just carried on all winter. Maybe he's matured, or maybe just
his familiarity with Belmont helped. But this will be the first
time I've run him where everything between races has gone exactly
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Coronado's Quest, a chestnut son of Forty Niner, won four of
five starts in New York before he went to Florida last winter and
began to throw riders.
</P>
<P>
   He ran second in the Hutcheson and second in the Fountain of
Youth, and both times balked and kicked, even when allowed to be
saddled away from the other horses.
</P>
<P>
   Then he ran fifth in the Florida Derby and first in the Wood
Memorial back in New York, but bowed out of the Kentucky Derby
because he seemed too uncontrollable. But McGaughey decided to
enter him in the Riva Ridge on June 6, the day of the Belmont
Stakes, and he won. Better yet, the trainer reported, ``Everything
has gone perfect from the Riva Ridge until now.''
</P>
<P>
   Scatmandu was purchased last year for $1.2 million by Robert
Waxman and arrived with a bad disposition. He was fractious in the
starting gate, and he bumped other horses in the homestretch. He
even tried to bite them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never really frustrated with him,'' said Johm Kimmel,
his trainer, ``because I knew he had the talent, and it was just a
matter of giving him time. The sons of Storm Cat are very
high-energy horses. It's just been maturing, time and more time.''
</P>
<P>
   Three other horses were entered Friday in the Dwyer: Ian's
Thunder, trained by Todd Pletcher; Rock and Roll, trained by Bill
Mott with Jerry Bailey riding, and Undaunted Mettle, trained by
Gary Contessa. Coronado's Quest will carry high weight of 124
pounds with Scatmandu next at 122.
</P>
<P>
   ISELIN CHANGES LURE SKIP AWAY
</P>
<P>
   It is official: Monmouth Park changed the distance of the Iselin
Handicap on Aug. 30 from a mile and one-sixteenth to a mile and
one-eighth and raised the purse from $250,000 to $500,000, and now
here comes Skip Away.
</P>
<P>
   The track on the Jersey Shore confirmed Friday that it had
tailored the race to the desires of Sonny Hine, who trains the
champion for his wife, Carolyn.
</P>
<P>
   Skip Away will enter the Iselin with a seven-race winning streak
and a bankroll of $8.9 million, about $1 million short of Cigar's
earnings record. Hine said he would be forced to miss the Whitney
at Saratoga on Aug. 8, but would put his superstar in the Woodward
and the Jockey Club Gold Cup at Belmont Park in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   CHIEF BEARHART TO RUN SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   Chief Bearhart, the turf champion of last year, will be the
solid favorite to win Saturday's Bowling Green Handicap at Belmont
in a short field that includes Chorwon and Mystic Knight. They will
run one and three-eighths miles for a purse of $150,000. Chief
Bearhart has won 10 of his 19 starts.
</P>
</TEXT>
