<SLUG> BC-NY-MOVIE-STUDIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG MOVIE STUDIO COMPLEX IS PLANNED IN LOWER MANHATTAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By THOMAS J. LUECK    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Responding to an intense demand for technologically
advanced studios in a city whose broadcast facilities were largely
designed in the radio age, a newly formed development company said
Friday that it would build a complex of five large sound stages on
the border of Greenwich Village and Soho, at Houston and West
Streets.
</P>
<P>
   The project, coming at a time when film production has emerged
as one of the city's fastest-growing industries, is the first of
several studio proposals to attract necessary financing and city
approval.
</P>
<P>
   To be known as Hudson River Studios and scheduled for completion
by January 2000, the project also reflects the challenges of
finding large enough pieces of real estate in Manhattan that meet
the unusual demands of the film industry.
</P>
<P>
   Budgeted at $120 million, the project is to be built on top of
the St. John's Center, a four-story, 60-year-old building
originally designed as a rail freight handling facility but now
used for data processing by Merrill Lynch and other large
companies.
</P>
<P>
   While leaving that structure intact, the studio's developers
said they had designed a rooftop addition that would be larger than
the original building, including some of the city's largest sound
stages equipped to transmit a new generation of high-definition
television. An important advantage of the rooftop setting, they
said, is that their entertainment industry tenants would be sealed
away from fans and curiosity seekers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This project is an important catalyst, but it by no means
provides the number of new stages we need,'' said Patricia Reed
Scott, the commissioner of the Mayor's Office of Film, Theater and
Broadcasting, which has seen a sharp rise in productions and money
spent by the television and movie industry in the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the studios we have now are from another era,'' she
said. ``In a vertical city with some of the highest real estate
costs in the country, it is hard to find large enough spaces.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Benowitz, president of Hudson Rivers Studios, said the
company had already signed 15-year leases for two of the five sound
stages with the producers of ``Guiding Light'' and ``As the World
Turns.''
</P>
<P>
   Both shows have been produced in Manhattan for more than 40
years and sponsored since their inception by the Procter &AMP; Gamble
Co. of Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Benowitz said he expected to reach final agreement within months
with a production company that would lease another of the sound
stages, but he would not say what type of production would be
involved. The two other stages in the complex, including its
largest, which would be suitable for large-scale movie productions,
have not yet been claimed, he said, and may be operated on
short-term agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can think of this as a hotel with five huge rooms,'' he
said, reflecting a business strategy being advanced by others who
have proposed major new production facilities in the city. Unlike
most Hollywood studios, dedicated entirely to their own
productions, the New York City approach is to provide studios,
editing rooms, offices and even sets and costumes, with a variety
of producers coming and going on a pay-as-you-go basis.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other film industry projects being planned or
discussed in the city are expansion of the Kaufman Astoria Studios,
which has operated for decades in Astoria, Queens; a television
production component to Donald Trump's huge Riverside South project
on the Upper West Side, and conversion of the city-owned Hudson
River piers at 54th Street to studios.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Scott said Friday that several production companies and
developers had approached the city about the 54th Street piers and
that details of a plan for that site might be announced within
months. Two Brooklyn entrepreneurs who have proposed a studio in
the Brooklyn Navy Yard have been promised a long-term lease by the
yard's city-controlled authority but must obtain $190 million in
private financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of wannabes out there, and so far we are the
only ones to put our ducks in a row,'' Benowitz said. Financing for
the whole Hudson River Studio project, which is to include an
unusual long-term lease on the air rights over the St. John's
Center, has been committed by United Labor Life Insurance Co., a
pension fund for construction trade unions across the nation, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference at City Hall, Mayor Rudolph Guiliani said
the studio could be built without any change in zoning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
