<SLUG> BC-NY-RANDOM-HOUSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERTELSMANN WANTS TO MOVE RANDOM HOUSE TO TIMES SQUARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ German media giant Bertelsmann AG is negotiating to
move Random House to a new office tower in Times Square, which has
increasingly become a crossroads of media, entertainment and
finance.
</P>
<P>
   If a deal can be struck, Bertelsmann, which recently acquired
the publishing house, would move Random House and its Bantam
Doubleday Dell group into a new building on the east side of
Broadway between 44th and 45th Streets, according to real estate
executives who have been told of the plans.
</P>
<P>
   The potential building site is steeped in Times Square's
theatrical history, and it also sits across the street from
Bertelsmann's 44-story American headquarters. The plans currently
under discussion by Bertelsmann and the landowner, Charles Moss,
call for a tower of about 600,000 square feet to be built atop the
existing building, which houses the Roundabout Theater, a movie
theater and several stores, all of them facing eviction. Moss is
talking with several retailers that might replace the theater
company, which is close to signing a lease for the Selwyn Theater
on 42nd Street, and the other tenants.
</P>
<P>
   According to the executives, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, Bertelsmann would either buy or lease the tower, while
Moss would continue to own and operate the retail space below,
which is festooned with a double row of billboards. Moss and
Bertelsmann are also negotiating over use of the billboards, which
are a source of millions of dollars in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   With the rising demand for space in Times Square, Moss' building
has become valuable and is one of the last low-slung structures in
what is becoming a canyon of skyscrapers. ``If Random House, a
conservative, well-established publisher, is willing to go to Times
Square, there's no question it's the place to be,'' said Ira
Schuman, a real estate broker with Julien J. Studley Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate executives cautioned that a deal had not been
signed. ``We're at a critical juncture,'' said one person involved
in the negotiations who insisted on anonymity. ``I think it'll
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss, who lives in Aspen, Colo., and whose family has operated
vaudeville theaters, nickelodeons and movie palaces in Times Square
for three generations, did not return calls requesting comment, nor
did Bertelsmann chief operating officer Robert Sorrentino.
</P>
<P>
   Random House is now based at 825 Third Ave., near 50th Street,
but its lease expires in about two years.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of another tower in Times Square did not bring joy
to the Municipal Art Society, which has long been critical of the
proliferation of tall buildings. The society has opposed a proposal
being debated by the City Council to change the zoning in Times
Square in such a way to allow even taller towers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Light and air is being diminished as the low sites get
developed,'' said Philip K. Howard, chairman of the Municipal Art
Society. ``The broader issue here is the overall density permitted
not only in Times Square but in many neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a few years ago, many New Yorkers regarded Times Square as
a place to be avoided. But now Disney, Madame Tussaud's and others
are crowding in. Douglas Durst, a developer, is completing a 1.6
million square foot tower on the east side of Broadway, between
42nd and 43rd Streets, that will house Conde Nast Publications and
the law firm Skadden Arps Slate Meagher &AMP; Flom.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street, on the west side of Seventh Avenue, between
42nd and 43rd Streets, demolition will begin soon for a 30-story
headquarters for the Reuters news agency. Mortimer Zuckerman's
Boston Properties recently bought two nearby sites where the
developer hopes to build two more office towers.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last century, Moss' property, which comprises an acre
of land, has been home to Oscar Hammerstein's Olympia Theater
complex, Bond's clothing store, the International Casino and his
father's Criterion Theater. Last year, Moss, who bought the site 21
years ago for $4 million, notified his tenants that he was
terminating the leases. He has been debating what to do with the
property ever since.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
