<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-NAPALM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAVY AWARDS $9 MILLION NAPALM CONTRACT TO HOUSTON-AREA COMPANY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Calif.) 
(see optional trim, optional ending) 
 
By RUTH RENDON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A Houston-area company Friday was awarded the contract
to recycle millions of gallons of Vietnam-era napalm, clearing the
way for the first shipment to arrive next week.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to let the GNI Group Inc. recycle the firebombs
didn't surprise many people in Deer Park, an industrial city of
30,000 that is home to dozens of petrochemical plants about 10
miles east of downtown Houston. But some area residents expressed
worry and disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   City leaders and U.S. Navy officials said, however, that most
people have reacted positively to the prospect of a local company
getting the $9 million contract. They said they believe much of the
opposition stems not from public-safety concerns, but from memories
of napalm's use in the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   About 22,000 gallons of the jellied gasoline, the first of many
shipments, is to be brought next week to GNI's facility in Deer
Park's Industrial District, said Robin Yocum, a spokesman for the
Battelle Memorial Institute, the Navy's prime contractor for the
project.
</P>
<P>
   Yocum said the shipment will be brought by rail from California
to a Pearland railyard, then travel about 22 miles by truck to the
recycling facility. The project is expected to take about two
years.
</P>
<P>
   Two other companies _ Chemical Waste Management, near Port
Arthur, and Waste Control Specialists, in the El Paso area _ also
contended for the contract and are still negotiating for the
position as a backup site to GNI.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a sad, dark day when our own United States government
can use the same weapons that were designed and produced to kill
people in a war now to incinerate them in our communities, which
will kill us when we breathe the toxic ash,'' said LaNell Anderson,
a real estate agent in nearby Channelview.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing we can do to stop this, is there?'' asked
Teresa Vickery of Deer Park.
</P>
<P>
   Vickery, who has a 3-year-old son, said she may put her house up
for sale because of the napalm contract.
</P>
<P>
   About 34,000 bombs, or 3.4 million gallons, of napalm have been
stockpiled at the Fallbrook Naval Weapons Support Facility near San
Diego. The Navy has unsuccessfully tried to dispose of the
substance for years, including earlier this year when a
12,000-gallon shipment headed to an Indiana contractor was turned
back because of public pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Public outcry has been scarce, however, in Deer Park. City
leaders said they have received about a dozen calls about the
napalm and only two were negative.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 people, many from outside the city, attended a public
meeting Wednesday to hear about the project.
</P>
<P>
   The napalm will be carried from California to Texas by
Burlington Northern and Santa Fe Railway Co.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very apparent that Texas industries have done such a
good job of creating an area surrounding the Houston Ship Channel
that is so totally polluted that now the entire world believes that
the Houston region is the dumping ground for our nation,'' said
Anderson, 54.
</P>
<P>
   She said Channelview residents get the brunt of the toxic
emissions from Deer Park's chemical facilities because of
prevailing winds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The operation at Fallbrook entails removing the napalm from its
aluminum canisters and placing it in 6,000-gallon isotankers _
double-sided, stainless steel containers. The containers are
commonly used to transport flammable liquids and wastes.
</P>
<P>
   Napalm is 21 percent benzene, 33 percent gasoline and 46 percent
polystyrene. It has a honey-like consistency and is flammable, but
not explosive because the detonators have been removed from the
canisters, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Hazardous-waste experts say that, with the detonators removed,
napalm is more stable than gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   The 2.5 million pounds of canisters are to be shredded and
placed in 55-gallon drums.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Fallbrook facility is operating, about two isotankers
per day will be shipped to Deer Park, Yocum said.
</P>
<P>
   GNI is to be paid $8 million to recycle the napalm and $1
million for the aluminum, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that napalm is involved has drawn heavy attention to
this project, said Carl V. Rush Jr., president and chief executive
officer of GNI.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are accustomed to handling materials of this nature,'' he
said. ``We do it safely and responsibly and that's how we will
handle this project.''
</P>
<P>
   GNI plans to process the napalm so that it can be recycled for
use as an alternative fuel, a company spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Ken Bentsen, D-Houston, who helped organize
Wednesday's meeting, said he will work closely with federal and
state regulatory agencies to make sure the napalm is transported
and disposed of safely.
</P>
<P>
   Deer Park City Manager Ron Crabtree said he, too, will monitor
the work.
</P>
<P>
   Vickery, the Deer Park mother who expressed safety concerns,
said she attended Wednesday's meeting but has not been reassured.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too much to have to deal with. Ever since this has been
going on I've been having nightmares,'' said Vickery, 36, a senior
medical secretary at Texas Children's Hospital. ``I have separation
anxiety because I leave my child here and I go to work. Anytime
they have an explosion they close down (Texas) 225. (The napalm
project) is just another thing to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Cmdr. Priscilla Baird said recycling the leftover napalm is
the most responsible and efficient action the Navy can take. She
said the Navy could not dispose of it by detonating the canisters
in an open range because ``they are not bombs. These are just
chemical products.''
</P>
<P>
   The Navy began storing napalm canisters at Fallbrook in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 25 years of storage, the canisters are beginning to
degrade and leak, which could contaminate the environment,'' Navy
officials said in a prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
