<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0134 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      07-10 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR.    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOP in Georgia Has Race On Its Mind
</P>
<P>
   State and national Republican leaders usually shy away from
taking sides in primary contests. But Speaker Newt Gingrich figures
the July 21 race in Georgia's 2nd Congressional District is a
different case. Ditto for Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,
R-Miss.; the former Republican national chairman, Haley Barbour;
the former chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Colin Powell; the
Republican vice-presidential nominee in 1996, Jack Kemp, and other
party luminaries.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   The 2nd District, covering Georgia's rural southwest corner, has
been represented in Washington for the past six years by a
Democrat, Sanford Bishop Jr. He is black, but in each of the past
three elections he readily demonstrated that he could win white
votes, most notably in the 1996 election after redistricting that
reduced the district's black population to about 40 percent from
nearly 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Republicans think Bishop is vulnerable this fall, given
the electoral momentum the party has gained in the South over the
past few years. But which Republican to send up against him?
</P>
<P>
   Two candidates are on the ballot: Joe McCormick, a 35-year-old
Albany businessman, and Dylan Glenn, 29, a former Capitol Hill and
Bush White House aide from Cusseta.
</P>
<P>
   McCormick is white. Glenn is black.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that the Republican Party has relatively few black
members in the country as a whole, with the shortage most acute in
the Deep South, Glenn faces a particularly tough first round. But
his supporters argue that he deserves to be nominated because if a
black Democrat can win the Georgia 2nd, so can a black Republican.
Moreover, Glenn supporters contend that if Republicans get behind
him, whether he wins or loses the party stands to gain needed
stature with black voters around the country.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Georgia Republican Party, Rusty Paul, has
urged party leaders to remain neutral in the primary, especially
national leaders. But taking a longer political view, Gingrich, who
hails from Georgia, and a dozen or more other major party figures
like Barbour and Kemp have nevertheless spoken out on Glenn's
behalf, with some attending rallies and holding fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a head coach, you need to make sure the best people get to
play,'' the speaker said at a Glenn fund-raiser in Atlanta on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A Gingrich aide, Mike Shields, honed that point a bit finer. He
called Glenn ``a bright young star'' who would help the Republican
Party ``reach out to minorities and get our message out to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Illinois Democrats Spur Their Candidate
</P>
<P>
   Some leading Democrats in Illinois are worried that Rep. Glenn
Poshard's campaign for governor is flagging, and they have begun
urging him to pick up the pace and sharpen his attack.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, State Rep. Carol Ronen of Chicago, a member of
the Democratic State Central Committee, sent Poshard a letter in
which she warned that many liberal voters in the Chicago area,
often the key to Democratic success in statewide races in Illinois,
``might fail to support your candidacy without some assurance that
you are interested in their votes and open to their concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   She urged Poshard, a social moderate from rural southeastern
Illinois, to ``reassure voters that you are in the mainstream, not
on the fringe,'' by forcefully speaking out for family planning,
early childhood education and health care, ``reasonable'' gun
controls and strong anti-discrimination laws.
</P>
<P>
   At about the same time, a number of the state's top Democratic
campaign consultants and union representatives, along with some
aides from various state legislative offices, sent Poshard a
similar message. They warned that if he did not move more
aggressively there was no chance he could overtake the Republican
nominee, Secretary of State George Ryan, and end 22 years of
Republican occupation of the Illinois executive mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan, a mainstream Republican, is much better financed than
Poshard, who refuses _ to the despair of some supporters _ to take
money from political action committees. Further, Ryan faced no
serious primary opposition, while Poshard struggled through a
divisive primary against tough black and staunchly liberal
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to his critics a few days ago, Poshard said he was
trying to ``build back bridges'' after the primary and had begun to
buy advertising time on television and radio. He also said he would
reconsider his opposition to building a third major airport south
of Chicago _ opposition that has disappointed many unemployed
blacks in that area, along with their congressman, Rep. Jesse
Jackson Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland Governor Gets Lesson in Unity
</P>
<P>
   When Louis Goldstein, Maryland's longtime state comptroller,
died last week, leaving one of the state's most politically
powerful posts open, Gov. Parris Glendening, a Democrat involved in
a tough re-election fight, thought he saw an opportunity to give
his campaign a boost. He talked former Rep. Michael Arnes, his
campaign chairman, into jumping into the contest to succeed
Goldstein.
</P>
<P>
   The governor figured that with Barnes at his side on the
Democratic ticket, there would be a better chance, in both the
September primary and, hopefully, the general election, to carry
Montgomery County, Barnes' home turf and one of the most populous
and heavily Democratic parts of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   What the governor did not figure on was former Gov. William
Donald Schaefer.
</P>
<P>
   Schaefer, an irascible, irrepressible fellow Democrat, asked
Glendening to back him for the comptroller's job. When he was
turned down, Schaefer jumped into the contest on his own and
demonstrated in less than 24 hours that he had far more support and
enduring popularity in the party than Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   No, he told the governor at that point, he would not back out in
the interest of party unity. Worse, he hinted darkly at perhaps
supporting some other Democrat for governor.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Barnes dropped out, talking party unity. And no
sooner was he gone than Schaefer was talking unity, too.
</P>
<P>
   Then Glendening joined in.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing with Schaefer at a news conference, laboring mightily
to make the best of the politically embarrassing bargain he had
been forced to strike, the governor declared: ``We're running
together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
