<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PA-TRANSIT-STRIKE-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGREEMENT ENDS PHILADELPHIA TRANSIT STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ A 40-day strike that shut down the network of
buses, trolleys and subways serving 435,000 passengers a day here
ended Friday when the transport workers union and the regional
transit authority announced that they had reached a tentative
agreement on a new contract.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was made Friday evening by the Southeastern
Pennsylvania Transportation Authority, or SEPTA, and Local 234 of
the Transport Workers Union.
</P>
<P>
   Service is to be restored starting at 4 a.m. Saturday, and to
persuade people to return to the habit of using public
transportation, rides will be free through Tuesday, the transit
authority said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased to say SEPTA is coming back to life again,'' said
Jack Leary, the general manager of the United States' fifth-largest
transit system, The Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   The strike by the local's 5,000 members was the fifth work
stoppage in 21 years by SEPTA workers who run and maintain buses.
It did not affect commuter trains serving the suburbs, though bus
lines in the suburbs were shut down.
</P>
<P>
   Among the people happiest about the settlement are sure to be
those drivers who have endured six weeks of gridlock and rush hours
that extended two hours longer than usual.
</P>
<P>
   The three-year contract expired on March 15, but both sides
continued negotiations for 11 weeks before the strike began on June
1. The main sticking points in negotiations included the hiring of
part-time workers, work-rule changes to allow the greater use of
part-time workers, changes in workers' compensation, and plans to
adopt a zero-tolerance policy for drug and alcohol use.
</P>
<P>
   During talks before the strike, management negotiators said they
needed fundamental changes in workplace rules to keep the system
operating at peak efficiency. They cited decreasing federal
transportation subsidies and declining ridership _ down 5 percent
since the last strike, 14 days in 1995 _ as major reasons to
rewrite rules that in some cases have been on the books for more
than 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   At one point earlier Friday, the transit authority and the union
called a news conference to announce a tentative agreement, only to
call it off. They reversed themselves within two hours, and
announced the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The sticking point that delayed the announcement was the hiring
of part-time workers, a union official said, adding that
negotiators had dealt with the problem by agreeing to submit to
binding arbitration on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hard and difficult battle, a lot of bitterness and
hard feelings,'' said Steve Brookens, the president of the union,
The Associated Press reported. ``But make no mistake about it. Our
members are the best. We deserved everything we got.''
</P>
<P>
   Brookens would not discuss details of the contract, which were
to be announced to members at a meeting Saturday morning before a
vote on the agreement by the rank and file on July 24.
</P>
<P>
   The 40 days of the strike saw dozens of mass demonstrations, a
pair of lawsuits, court injunctions and sporadic negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   In late June, after a SEPTA employee was shot with a pellet gun
outside union headquarters, the City Council president, John
Street, filed a lawsuit seeking to force the two sides into
marathon negotiations under a court-appointed supervisor.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The strike has been the second-longest by the union against the
transit authority. In 1977, the union struck for 44 days over wages
and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The strike was especially demoralizing because Philadelphia has
been marketing itself as a reborn urban center, rich with tourist
attractions, vibrant night life and world-class cultural sites. And
the city had become one of a half-dozen contenders for the
Republican National Convention in 2000. The city has not been the
host of a national political convention in 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   While the Republican site-selection committee did visit the city
on the opening day of the strike, the city remains in contention
for the convention. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
