<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE BODY FINALLY HAS A HEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was a time when the announcement of a new
commissioner of baseball was greeted with banner headlines, like
the naming of a pope or the election of a president. The naming of
the man who led the national pastime was a solemn affair tied to
the sanctity of the game.
</P>
<P>
   When baseball's owners announced Thursday that Bud Selig would
go from acting commissioner to commissioner, the news was almost
like that proverbial tree falling in the forest. Few heard; of
those who heard, few listened; and of those who listened, few
cared. The news was overtaken by Don King's acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   The common wisdom about the lack of attention is that the
announcement was anticlimactic: Selig has been acting commissioner
for so long _ since 1992 _ that the elevation was a mere formality.
As Felipe Alou, the Montreal Expos' manager, said Friday. ``What is
he going to do new?''
</P>
<P>
   For starters, Selig is going to move at least part time to New
York from Milwaukee and give baseball the commissioner's presence
it has lacked. Not an ideal situation, but it's a start.
</P>
<P>
   Selig was essentially thrust into the commissioner's role in
September 1992, two days after the club owners forced Fay Vincent
to walk the plank in the best interests of baseball. In the
intervening years, baseball effectively ran itself while Selig
played the hokey-pokey, with one foot in ownership and the other
foot in the ill-defined commissioner's office.
</P>
<P>
   As owner of the Brewers, he stood by as his Milwaukee team was
switched to the National League; as acting commissioner, he guided
the owners into voting for divisional play and wild card berths for
1995.
</P>
<P>
   Upon assuming the duties in the commissioner's office in 1992,
Selig said, ``I hope it's relatively short term, but if you ask me
what short term is, I don't know.'' Two years later, Selig was
still there, but not there, saying: ``I have no permanent interest
in this job. I have many other things in life I want to do.'' Three
days later, he said he still wanted no part of the job on a
permanent basis: ``I have no permanent interest in this job.''
</P>
<P>
   As recently as last year, Selig protested: ``All I'll say is, I
haven't changed my mind since Sept. 9, 1992.'' But this week Selig
sounded resolute: he wanted this position. He predicted that
baseball was about ``to move into the greatest renaissance in the
history of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou, the Expos' 60-year-old manager, said he thought Selig's
elevation was good for a game that finally seemed to be going in
the right direction. Alou, who played major league baseball for 17
years, ended his career with the Brewers and played under Selig.
``He has a lot of knowledge about the inner workings of the game,''
Alou said. ``He knows more about the insides and outside of
baseball better than any commissioner who's been in the position.
That's why I say he has a great opportunity to really do
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou was asked who the commissioner was when he broke into the
majors in 1958. ``I don't know,'' he said. ``I can't remember. Ford
Frick?'' Yes, Frick, the front man the owners hired in 1951 to do
essentially what they have hired commissioners to do ever since:
represent the game and keep their noses out of its wheeling-dealing
aspects.
</P>
<P>
   Alou said that when he broke into baseball, the game was filled
with pressing issues, though none that the commissioner took on:
black and Latin ball players had to battle discrimination on and
off the field. Players in general, black, white and brown, were
treated as chattel on baseball's plantation.
</P>
<P>
   It would be more than a decade before Curt Flood challenged
owners' dominance with a lawsuit testing the standard contract's
reserve clause. By the time Alou retired as a player in 1974, Bowie
Kuhn was the commissioner. With the exception of A. Bartlett
Giamatti, who banned Pete Rose from baseball, the commissioner has
been a gofer for owners.
</P>
<P>
   So why have one? For all the criticism the game has taken since
Vincent's resignation, baseball probably has the right idea. The
owners, in their self-serving, strong-armed manner, navigated
baseball through a dreadful strike and devised an exciting playoff
system that gives even a bumbling team like the Mets a chance to
make post-season play. When you get right down to it, a
commissioner is essentially a high-priced overseer whose job is to
patrol the manor, make sure the workers are working, make certain
the appropriate portion of profits is flowing into the owner's
coffers.
</P>
<P>
   If you're going to hire someone to do your bidding, might as
well hire someone whose interests are your own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
