<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0398 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0152 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV12-B     07-10 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV12-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FAME-GIVERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 12 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   About this time every year, investment banker Herb Allen holds
his big media conference in Sun Valley, Idaho. Some 100 Bigs
arrived last Monday for a few days of horseback riding, whitewater
rafting and schmoozing.
</P>
<P>
   Remember when Warren Buffett brokered the sale of ABC television
network and the rest of Capital Cities to The Mouse (as Walt Disney
Co. is known in the trade) during a stroll in the parking lot?
Nicely timed, it coincide with this year's &UR;  &LR;  Allen conference was
the news that editor Tina Brown soon would be departing the New
Yorker for Disney's world.
</P>
<P>
   The 44-year-old Brown is joining the huge entertainment
conglomerate to develop a magazine, tv shows and films for its
Miramax unit. She is leaving after six years in the top job at
America's e most successful general interest magazine _ editorially
successful, at least. Under Brown, the New Yorker continued to lose
money.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is only the latest editor to move nearer the apex of the
fast-integrating news-entertainment complex. Michael Kinsley _ for
years the editor of the New Republic _ two years ago created Slate,
a digital magazine for Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, Norman Pearlstine, who during the 1980s had been
magaging editor of The Wall Street Journal, was hired by
Time-Warner to oversee its magazine group and explore its synergies
with the Cable News Network, Warner Brothers films and the
Internet. (The ultimate responsibility for the Time/CNN ``nerve
gas'' fiasco was his.)
</P>
<P>
   The famous firewalls between the business and ``content'' sides
(formerly the news sides) of these enterprises remain, at least to
the extent that these mega-editors don't attend the Sun Valley
conference. Instead, it is the money folk who get the invitations _
Bill Gates, Katharine Graham, Warren Buffett, Rubert Murdoch,
Sumner Redstone, Michael Eisner, Edgar Bronfman, David Geffen,
Barry Diller, Michael Bloomberg and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether these media magnates seem to wield an awful lot of
power. Are they about to assume control of all that we see, read,
and think?
</P>
<P>
   Recently I have been reading Tyler Cowen's book, ``In Praise of
Commercial Culture,'' and I am somewhat buoyed by it. A specialist
in the economics of fame and the arts, Cowen is professor at George
Mason University in Fairfax, Va.
</P>
<P>
   He argues that market forces stimulate the production of
culture, high and low, and that far from homogenizing taste, they
tend to produce art that is more specialized and diverse than it
would be otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   In three especially lively chapters, Cowen traces the markets
for the written word (where the printing press has been around for
centuries,) music (where recording technology only relatively
recently became available) and painting (where reproductive
technology counts for much less.) It is the history of music, with
its multiple and changing means of delivery, that I found the most
encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   In ``From Bach to the Beatles,'' Cowen tells the story of the
development of two quite distinct musical traditions: the rise of
Western music, and the musical revolution &UR;  &LR; from Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The economics of classical music are relatively well-understood.
For a long time after the Renaissance, composers depended on rich
patrons for work _ one Weimar prince actually threw Bach in jail
when he tried to move to a better job. Private commissions
permitted composers like Mozart and Haydn a greater degree of
freedom. And sheet music publishing made Beethoven into the first
genuinely autonomous star (``...People no longer bargain with me; I
ask and they pay.'')
</P>
<P>
   During the 19th and early 20th centuries, popular music
flourished, while classical music (like many others things) became
professionalized. Brahms wrote compositions too complicated to be
performed at home; the German government supported Wagner's opulent
visions; Stravinsky and Schoenberg relied on foundation support.
The advent of recording and the rise of radio broadened the market
and yielded more diverse _ and more obscure _ compositions.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, African music that had been imported to the New World
had begun to make its influence felt. ``Slavery was a disaster for
its victims, but it revolutionized world music,'' Cowen writes, and
most contemporary poular musical forms _ blues, rhythym and blues,
rock and roll, soul, jazz, swing, bebop, bookie, ragtime, calypso,
samba, forro, son, ska, reggae, salsa, merengue, plena and rap _
flow out of it. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Like their classical counterparts in earlier centuries, the men
and women who made blues and jazz ``needed to establish markets,
overcome resistance to new musical sounds and develop innovative
means of distributing their creations,'' Cowen writes.
</P>
<P>
   No incident in Cowen's account is more telling than the the
story of the ``payola'' scandals of the 1950s, when producers
resorted to bribery to purchase airtime for their artists. ``The
Yellow Rose of Texas,'' ``Love is A Many-Splendored Thing'' and a
piano rendition of ``Autumn Leaves'' were the big hits when the
scandal started. &UR;  &LR;  Chuck Berry's ``Maybellene''  &UR;  &LR; gives disc jockey
Alan Freed partial song-writing credit to this very day _ a sly
inducement to play the song. Such is the power of money to benefit
novelty _ and the story of the rise of rap music from the Bronx
party culture of the 1970s is not much different, Cowen says.
</P>
<P>
   The picture of the art markets that emerges from ``In Praise of
Commercial Culture'' is a reassuring one. Art markets consist of
artists, consumers and middlemen, or distributors, Cowen says. The
artists work for fame, self-fullfillment and riches. Consumers seek
``to live out our days in the the perpetual undertide of ecstasy''
that is the purpose of all culture (in John Cowper Powys' memorable
phrase.)
</P>
<P>
   Distributors, like the Media Chieftains who gathered last week
in Sun Valley, exist to bring artists together with audiences. But
rich as they are, these middlemen are powerless to invent the new
forms and novel interpretations of old ones that are artists'
enternal quest.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, it is the consumers of art and their agents, the
critics, who are the ultimate givers of fame. That is the point of
the African musical revolution _ consumers know a life-enhancing
development when they hear it.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it is less than possible than ever before to create the
monopoly on commercial culture that is the objective of
totalitarian states. Within wide bands of fad and fashion, people
are going to decide for themselves what they like.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 2233EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
