<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-RUELAS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUELAS WORKING TOWARD ANOTHER TITLE SHOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was a fight that produced conflicting fallout
for Gabriel Ruelas: frustration and liberation.
</P>
<P>
   Ruelas and Arturo Gatti engaged in one of the most thrilling
bouts of 1997, a bout Gatti won by fifth-round knockout to retain
his IBF junior lightweight championship in October in Atlantic
City, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   It was almost Gatti who fell. Ruelas had the champion badly hurt
in the fourth round before Gatti landed the crushing left hook that
put the challenger, perhaps too bold in his attack, down and out.
</P>
<P>
   Ruelas (44-4, 23 knockouts) was that close to his second world
title and the money that comes with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``No other loss stands out like the Gatti loss to me,'' said
Ruelas, who faces Troy Dorsey today in San Antonio, his first bout
since fighting Gatti. ``It's probably because I felt I was so close
to victory and not able to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That'll stay with me for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   So will what he accomplished in the fight.
</P>
<P>
   Ruelas, 27, was still experiencing the traumatic effects of the
1995 bout in which he delivered the blows that killed Jimmy Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   Ruelas said he had come to terms with the tragedy long ago and
was ready to resume his career in earnest. However, observers who
had seen so many fighters in Ruelas' position fall apart had their
doubts.
</P>
<P>
   So many believed he'd never be the same. He admitted he wondered
whether he could possibly be right and everyone else wrong _ until
the Gatti fight, in which he threw punches with abandon against one
of the toughest fighters in the world.
</P>
<P>
   He convinced himself _ if not most of those who saw the fight _
that he was back, that he was again the fighter who thrashed
then-unbeaten Jesse James Leija to win the WBC super featherweight
title in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that fight had the biggest effect on people around
me,'' he said. ``I don't think people are as concerned about it as
they were. And I'm not either. It made me really believe that if I
train real hard, I could be a world champion again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big turning point, not only in boxing but in my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorsey, the former IBF featherweight champion, is rugged but
limited and a notorious bleeder. He's a 6-1 underdog in today's
bout, one of three featuring former champ vs. former champ.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming he wins, Ruelas could get another shot at a
championship. He plans to move up to the 135-pound lightweight
class after this fight.
</P>
<P>
   His promoter, Dan Goossen, threw out such weighty names as
Naseem Hamed, Angel Manfredy, Shane Mosley and, yes, Gatti, as
possible future opponents but none are in the works.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, it seems there's plenty of life in his up-and-down
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guarantee you this: If Gabriel wins on Saturday, watch
out,'' Goossen said. ``He'll be at his peak, the prime of career.
He's been through so much adversity. If he's successful Saturday,
there'll be no other situation in his career that he won't be able
to overcome.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 2234EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0400 </DOCNO>
