<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0154 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAVES-MAIN11-COX     07-10 0440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-MAIN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marlin rookie ends Braves' streak at nine
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Jesus Sanchez is 23, just 5 feet 9 and is listed at 153
pounds. Friday night, he beat up the Braves with one left hand.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's nine-game winning streak met an unlikely end, the
rookie Sanchez shutting down the hottest team in the National
League 3-1 in a game that had Denny Neagle seeking the heavens for
answers.
</P>
<P>
   The loss ended the Braves' longest winning streak in three
years. The last Atlanta loss came exactly two weeks before, 6-4 to
Toronto on June 26.
</P>
<P>
   Neagle (9-7) held the last-place Marlins scoreless for almost
seven innings while the Braves advanced four men into scoring
position and brought in none of them. Then in the seventh, Neagle
retired the first two men he faced before suddenly finding himself
trailing 1-0. Cliff Floyd singled, stole second on a high throw by
catcher Javy Lopez and then came around on a single by rookie Dave
Berg, who had been hitting .450 with runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   The run ended a three-game mastery Neagle held over the Marlins,
who had not scored against him in 22 previous 22 innings dating
back to an Aug. 2, 1997, start here.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's bullpen gave up two runs in the eighth, one on Mark
Kotsay's RBI single off John Rocker, the second on a Rocker wild
pitch that allowed Edgar Renteria to score from third.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez (4-6) allowed five hits and one walk while striking out
five over eight innings. In his previous appearance against the
Braves, Sanchez threw five shutout innings before giving up four
runs in the sixth. No so this time. In just his 15th start, he ate
up the Braves' Nos. 3,4 and 5 hitters the first three times through
the order (0-for-8) while striking out Chipper Jones twice.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves allowed three excellent early scoring changes to get
away, stranding three men at third base in the first five innings.
In the first, Gerald Williams turned a flare down the right field
line into a double but died at third on Lopez's inning-ending
ground-out. Neagle then opened the third inning with a single,
moved to second on Walt Weiss's sacrifice but was also stranded at
third on Williams' ground-out and Chipper Jones' strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, Tony Graffanino, struggling in a 2-for-25 slump,
singled, was sacrificed to second by Neagle, went to third on a
wild pitch and watched Weiss end the inning on a fly-out. Through
the first five innings, the Braves were 0-for-5 with runners in
scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
