<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0404 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0164 &Cx1f; tab-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OIL-WARS-LATINTRADE-N     07-10 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-WARS-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OIL WARS
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-996-0075 or fax at 310-996-0089; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``i''
international and ``f'' financial files.) 
 By CLAIRE POOLE 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    HOUSTON _ Mexico and Venezuela have never been the best of
friends, especially when it comes to their chief export and revenue
generator, oil.
 &HT;    That's especially true now, as they're both chasing deals with
U.S. refineries to process their oil and get it to market.
 &HT;    Venezuela and Mexico have bumped up their oil production in
recent years. But they both produce a lot of heavy, high-sulfur
crude, and neither has the capacity to process it nor the
investment to build new refineries.
 &HT;    By buying into or signing joint-venture deals with existing U.S.
refineries, not only do they find a way to refine their crude, they
instantly gain access to U.S. markets.
 &HT;    ``Securing an outlet for these kinds of crude facilitates the
marketing,'' says Rafael Quijano, managing partner of Latin
American Petroleum Intelligence Services, a U.S.-based consulting
firm.
 &HT;    U.S. energy companies also win. Plagued by overcapacity and
lower oil prices, the oil-refining sector hasn't exactly been
brimming with profits lately. So by striking deals with their
southern neighbors, not only do these companies snare long-term
supply contracts, they bring in new investment to improve their
plants.
 &HT;    ``Margins have been very slim. And the capital that it takes to
process some of these barrels is so enormous that it exceeds the
ability of most companies to finance it,'' says Ray Ory, president
of Vector Associates, a U.S.-based consulting firm. ``So these
deals are viewed as a necessary evil.''
 &HT;    Mexico's state-owned oil company, Petroleos Mexicanos (Pemex),
inked one of the first such agreements in March 1993, when it
hooked up with Dutch-British giant Shell Oil Co. to jointly own its
Deer Park refinery near the Houston Ship Channel. As part of the
deal, Pemex provided 150,000 barrels per day of heavy Mexican crude
in exchange for 45,000 barrels per day of unleaded gasoline.
 &HT;    In 1995, the plant completed a US$1 billion improvement program,
including a new coker. Initially, most of the gasoline was shipped
back to Mexico; it's now being sold in the United States.
 &HT;    Shell wouldn't comment on future such deals, but is open to the
possibility.
 &HT;    ``Our 50/50 joint venture in the Deer Park refinery [is] a
win-win for both Shell and Pemex,'' Shell spokesperson Sarah Payne
says.
 &HT;    Pemex clearly wants to do more. It is in talks with U.S.-based
Mobil about a joint project at its 320,000-barrel-per-day Beaumont,
Texas, refinery, which already processes some crude from Mexico.
 &HT;    Venezuela's state-owned oil company, Petroleos de Venezuela
(PDVSA), has been particularly aggressive. Over the last several
years, it has purchased nearly 1 million barrels a day of U.S.
refining capacity. ``We cannot do it on our own,'' says Nelson
Olmedillo, a senior adviser at PDVSA Services in Houston. ``We need
the capital investment, technology and the markets.''
 &HT;    Its deal-making has picked up lately. Last November, PDVSA
finalized a joint venture with Mobil in which it will own 50% of
its 100,000-barrel-per-day refinery in Chalmette, Louisiana. The
two plan to extract and process extra heavy crude oil from the
Cerro Negro area of the Orinoco belt and market it in the United
States. Total investment: $2.5 billion, $800 million of which will
be spent to upgrade the refinery.
 &HT;    Then, in February, PDVSA announced it would acquire half of a
500,000-barrel-a-day refinery in St. Croix, the U.S. Virgin
Islands, owned by New York-based Amerada Hess Corp. for $625
million. The deal calls for PDVSA to supply about 270,000 barrels a
day of heavy Venezuelan crude for processing into gasoline.
 &HT;    At press time, PDVSA was also in discussions with U.S.-based
Phillips Petroleum about a joint venture to build and own a
58,000-barrel-a-day coker at its refinery in Sweeny, Texas. Under
the agreement, the two would own the coker 50/50 and PDVSA would
supply up to 165,000 barrels of heavy crude per day to be processed
at the refinery.
 &HT;    Other deals are expected. The only thing that could halt the
deal-making is the Latin American oil giants taking too big a bite
of the U.S. refining industry. ``If Venezuela were to own a certain
percentage of the industry, it could trigger some debate as to how
big is big,'' Vector's Ory says. ``But right now, they need each
other.''
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</TEXT>
