<HEADER>
A0172 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-IMPLANT-NYT &LR;      07-10 0355
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-IMPLANT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A SETTLEMENT ON IMPLANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (also see SCI-IMPLANT-ASSESS)  
 (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in editorial for Saturday, July 11:
</P>
<P>
   The tentative $3.2 billion settlement agreement between Dow
Corning Corp. and lawyers for thousands of women who claim they
have been made ill by silicone breast implants seems a prudent
financial move for both sides.
</P>
<P>
   A settlement would allow the company to emerge from Chapter 11
bankruptcy and plaintiffs would get compensated for suffering and
for the costs of getting the implants surgically removed. A legal
settlement does not resolve scientific questions about the safety
of the implants. But those questions could not have been fully
answered in a court of law, even if the cases had gone to trial.
</P>
<P>
   How juries would have weighed evidence about the cause or extent
of the injuries is anyone's guess. Localized pain, disfigurement
and complications from ruptured implants have been documented. But
whether the implants cause autoimmune diseases is greatly disputed
by the company, a stance supported by several studies showing no
link between silicone and systemic illness. Yet even those studies
deal with probabilities and do not rule out all risk of harm.
Neither side evidently wanted to go through with the gamble of
litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Three other manufacturers made the same calculation and settled
in 1995, paying out an average of $26,000 per woman. Dow Corning,
once the leading manufacturer of silicone implants, faces the
greatest financial exposure. It filed for bankruptcy protection in
1995 against the 19,000 damage suits that had been filed against
the company. The proposed accord will still need to be approved by
two-thirds of some 170,000 claimants, the company's other creditors
and the bankruptcy judge.
</P>
<P>
   The legal system, which is not meant to advance scientific
inquiry, functioned in this case as it typically does. It forced
both sides to decide what outcome they could live with and left the
search for truth as measured by a scientific standard to other
arenas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 2248EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0408 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0174 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MISSING-PROBE-NYT &LR;      07-10 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MISSING-PROBE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE SAY MISSING WOMAN AND CON MAN ARGUED 
</HEADLINE>
   (also see NY-MISSING-MILLIONAIRE)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shortly before Irene Silverman, an Upper East Side
socialite, vanished Sunday morning, she was seen in an angry
confrontation with a convicted con artist who had rented an
apartment in her mansion on East 65th Street, an investigator said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A witness told police that Mrs. Silverman exchanged shouts with
the convict, Kenneth Kimes, 23, outside the first-floor office of
her mansion about 10:30 a.m., the investigator said, speaking on
condition of anonymity. When Mrs. Silverman tried to take the
elevator to her living quarters, Kimes stopped her in the hallway
and led her into his apartment, the investigator added.
</P>
<P>
   When the argument began, Mrs. Silverman ordered her maid to walk
the dog in her roof garden, the investigator said. Kimes later
phoned the maid and asked her to come to his $6,000-a-month suite
and clean it, the investigator said the witness had reported. The
maid refused, and Kimes later called and ordered her to ``Get out
of the house with the dog,'' the investigator said, quoting the
witness' statement.
</P>
<P>
   The witness' statement came as teams of police officers searched
the Garden State Parkway for signs of Mrs. Silverman and
investigators from three states and the Bahamas examined a sheaf of
financial records and other items found in Kimes' car.
</P>
<P>
   Kimes and his mother, Sante, 63, were carrying Mrs. Silverman's
identification when they were arrested Sunday night on an unrelated
charge of writing a bad check, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The Kimeses, who investigators say took a notary public to Mrs.
Silverman's office last Wednesday and asked her to sign a power of
attorney form, are also considered suspects in the Los Angeles
slaying of their former business partner, David Kazdin, Los Angeles
police say.
</P>
<P>
   Kazdin was found in a Los Angeles garbage bin March 14, fatally
shot in the head, shortly after the Kimeses obtained a fraudulent
$280,000 loan on property he had owned, according to Los Angeles
police and financial records.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities in the Bahamas want to question the Kimeses
about the 1996 disappearance of a Middle Eastern banker who had
befriended Sante Kimes.
</P>
<P>
   In New York on Friday, detectives assembled a list of the names
of business associates to determine whether any had vanished or
been bilked of their assets. Investigators, who spoke on condition
of anonymity, said the documents found in the car contained names
of more than 10 business associates, but there was no evidence that
any were missing.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives were also seeking a search warrant Friday to examine
the Kimeses' laptop computer, which was found in the trunk of the
car along with the financial documents, a 9-millimeter Glock
handgun, nearly $30,000 in cash, a box of .22-caliber ammunition
and at least 10 wigs, in several styles and colors.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the Kimeses at a news conference Friday, Police
Commissioner Howard Safir said, ``They are apparently a very
violent couple.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said investigators believe that the Kimeses were on the
Garden State Parkway between 1 and 6:30 p.m. Sunday. New Jersey
troopers searched rest stops and service areas along the roadway
Friday, said John Hagerty, a spokesman for the New Jersey State
Police.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
