<HEADER>
A0181 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-PITTS-NYT &LR;      07-10 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-PITTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIJAH PITTS, 60, PACKERS RUNNING BACK, BILLS ASSISTANT HEAD
COACH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark., N.Y., Wis.)   (bl)  
 By RICHARD GOLDSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Elijah Pitts, a running back for the Green Bay Packers during
their glory years of the 1960s and the assistant head coach of the
outstanding Buffalo Bills teams of the 1990s, died July 10 at Mercy
General Hospital in Buffalo, N.Y. He was 60.
</P>
<P>
   He had been suffering from abdominal cancer and had been on
medical leave from the Bills since October.
</P>
<P>
   Pitts played for the Packers from 1961 to 1969 and again in 1971
during the Vince Lombardi era, when Green Bay won four National
Football League championships and two Super Bowls. He scored on
touchdown runs of 5 yards and 1 yard in the Packers' 35-10 victory
over the Kansas City Chiefs in Super Bowl I on Jan. 15, 1967.
</P>
<P>
   He was an assistant coach in the NFL for more than two decades
and took over as the Bills' acting head coach for three games
during the 1995 season when coach Marv Levy was being treated for
prostate cancer. The Bills went to four Super Bowls, losing them
all, during his years in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Pitts hardly seemed destined for a long career in pro football.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a sharecropper, he grew up in Mayflower, Ark., a town
with a high school so small that it did not have a football team.
He attended high school 12 miles away in Conway, Ark., was a
football star there and was offered scholarships by a number of
colleges. But he decided to stick close to home, playing for
Philander Smith College in Little Rock, a school with several
hundred students.
</P>
<P>
   Pitts was picked by the Packers in the 1961 draft as only a
13th-round selection and had to compete with the star runners Paul
Hornung and Jim Taylor. ``I went with the attitude that I was as
good as anyone,'' Pitts would recall.
</P>
<P>
   He made the Packers as a backup runner, but he was such an
aggressive tackler that Lombardi soon selected him as captain of
the special teams.
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, when Hornung was hampered by an injury, Pitts teamed up
with Taylor, the fullback, in the starting backfield, and in the
NFL championship game against Dallas in the Cotton Bowl he was
Green Bay's leading runner. In gratitude for his performance in the
inaugural Super Bowl, the Packers pictured him on the cover of
their 1967 guidebook, running behind a block by the lineman Fuzzy
Thurston. Pitts ran for 28 touchdowns during his career and was
named to the Packers' Hall of Fame in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   During his playing days, Pitts never thought of becoming a
coach, but he went on to be an assistant with the Los Angeles Rams,
the Bills and the Houston Oilers of the NFL and the Hamilton
Tiger-Cats of the Canadian Football League between 1974 and 1984.
He returned then to Buffalo as an aide in charge of running backs
and special teams, and he became the assistant head coach in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Pitts, who lived in Buffalo, is survived by his wife, Ruth; two
sons and a daughter. His son Ron was a cornerback for the Packers
and the Bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I apply some of Lombardi's teachings,'' Pitts said in the
mid-1980s. ``Not in the way he would, but in my own way.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Lombardi's tenet that ``fatigue makes cowards of us
all'' made the greatest impression on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell it to my players,'' he noted in an interview for
``Distant Replay,'' by his former Packers teammate Jerry Kramer
with Dick Schaap (Putnam's, 1985). ``If you're tired, you're a
coward.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitts could hardly have considered himself lacking in courage,
given the odds he faced in making the Packers. But when he was once
asked whether the intimidating Lombardi had scared him the first
time he heard him, Pitts responded: ``He scared me the last time I
heard him, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 2249EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0415 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0184 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SUBWAY-FUTURE-470&AMP;     07-10 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SUBWAY-FUTURE-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOWING OFF THE SUBWAY CAR OF THE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At first glance, New York City Transit's subway train
of the future looks a lot like the train of the present.
</P>
<P>
   At least that was the impression of many of the people who
gathered Friday to see a wooden mock-up of the front half of the
new subway car at the transit agency's maintenance yard on 207th
Street in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   A prototype of the train has already been running along the
Eighth Avenue line, and the model on display Friday incorporated
changes that resulted from public comments about those cars.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the people who examined the new model noted Friday that
although it looked like other subway cars on the outside, there
were many changes inside. Transit officials hope those changes will
make for smoother riding in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The transit agency hopes to buy 1,081 of the cars, using them to
replace older models on the lettered subway lines. Transit
officials plan to have all the new cars in place on these lines by
2001.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Timone, a Bronx man who uses the subway primarily to
shuttle between home and the doctor's office, said he liked the new
design, except for one detail. ``There should be no bumps in the
seats,'' Timone said. ``When you are as fat as me, that is really
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Timone was commenting on the sloping indentations in the new
seats, one of several changes. Other innovations include fold-up
seats to accommodate wheelchairs, an emergency intercom system that
allows passengers to talk to the conductor, electronic maps and
information displays, new handrails, including some that hang from
the center of the train, and curved handholds.
</P>
<P>
   The changes were well received by most of the people who visited
during the five-hour open house, though not everyone was pleased.
</P>
<P>
   William Stanford of the Bronx said he disliked the electronic
technology in the train, which will, among other things, tell
riders which stop is next. Transit officials hope the displays will
carry advertisements, announcements, the time and other information
for riders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget these display messages,'' Stanford said. ``Come on,
this is a train, not an answering machine or a clock. Do it the old
way, not this new and confusing way.''
</P>
<P>
   He also called for something that is a rare commodity in New
York City subway stations and on streets. ``Put bathrooms on the
cars. If you can do it on a Greyhound, you can do it on a train,''
Stanford said.
</P>
<P>
   The open house attracted more than 100 people, mainly subway
enthusiasts, retirees and schoolchildren who were off for the
summer. Albert O'Leary, a spokesman for New York City Transit, said
that in the next few weeks the agency plans to compile the answers
to a 10-page questionnaire that visitors filled out about the cars.
``The point is to make our customers as happy as possible,''
O'Leary said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The full-scale mock-up was designed based on focus-group
suggestions and changes being made in other cities, transit
officials said. The transit agency contracted with Sigi Meeslinger
and Masamichi Udagawa of Antenna Design New York Inc. to develop
the prototype.
</P>
<P>
   Udagawa said the new train's most important features are the new
information display systems, including an electronic map that
indicates the train's location at each stop and a monitor that
gives riders information such as which way the train is going.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary said that although there are many changes in the new
cars, riders can expect only so much, because ``fundamentally, when
it comes out of the wash, it is still a big subway train.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
