<SLUG> BC-NY-GOLDBERG-HOTELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
5-HOTEL MINI-EMPIRE IS SOLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By NICK RAVO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A New York real estate investor who in the last
decade has turned five small, troubled hotels in Manhattan into
luxury properties has sold his mini-empire to Credit Suisse First
Boston, the global investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   The investor, Bernard Goldberg, sold the properties _ the
Mansfield, the Shoreham, the Hotel Wales, the Roger Williams and
the Franklin _ for an estimated $132 million, said an official in
the real estate industry who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time to move on to larger properties, and I don't think
I could manage these five and also acquire two or three much larger
properties in New York,'' said Goldberg, the chief executive
officer of Gotham Hospitality Group.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg added that he had nearly closed on a deal to buy a
large Manhattan hotel, the name of which he said he would not
disclose until next week. He recently made an unsuccessful bid on
the Chrysler Building, hoping to operate a 500-room hotel in the
Art Deco landmark that would have been called the Hotel Chrysler.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of Goldberg's hotels comes as the hotel industry in New
York is booming, with occupancy rates of more than 80 percent,
average nightly room rates nearing $200 and several hotels charging
an average of more than $500 a night.
</P>
<P>
   The prices for rooms at Goldberg's five hotels _ which are
scattered throughout Manhattan, including the Upper East Side and
near midtown _ range from $165 to $325 a night. Not long ago,
however, before the hotelier took over and renovated the
properties, they charged as little as $49 a night and sometimes
housed homeless families.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only buy undervalued properties,'' said Goldberg, who added
amenities to his hotels like larger lobbies, chamber music concerts
and CD players in the rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Dexter Wood, a hotel analyst with Price Waterhouse Coopers, said
that even though Goldberg intends to reinvest in the hotel
business, the sale of his five properties ``has to be an indication
of the industry being at or near a top.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Credit Suisse First Boston, Lance Graber, a
director, disagreed. ``It is an opportunity that was presented to
us that has real upside potential and is consistent with our
business plan with regard to real estate,'' Graber said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the bank keeps a low profile about its real estate
investments. ``We have nothing to gain by publicizing,'' he said.
He noted, though, that the bank owns or co-owns several other
hotels outside New York.
</P>
<P>
   Unique Hotels &AMP; Resorts Inc., a management company that
specializes in small, high-end hotels and resorts, will operate the
hotels for Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   L.K. Prevette, co-managing director of Unique Hotels, which is
based in New York and Los Angeles, said the company planned to make
few changes to four of the five Manhattan hotels. But the Hotel
Wales, known for its turn-of-the-century decor, will receive a
multimillion dollar renovation, because it was last renovated 10
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have a central reservations system and make
improvements to the telephone systems,'' Prevette said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goldberg has done a nice job with the decor and style of the
properties,'' he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
