<HEADLINE>
NBA STARS NOT LOCKED OUT HERE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SHANDEL   RICHARDSON  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Talks of an NBA lockout circulated for
several months. So it was no surprise to Gino Kwok, president of
the Fila Summer Pro League, when it finally happened July 1.
</P>
<P>
   And it was his foresight that has allowed Fila to be able to
sponsor the only summer league with pro players.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prospects of a lockout were there,'' Kwok said.
``Everybody could see that there was big talk that was going to
happen. So we went forward organizing it both ways if there was
going to be one, or if there wasn't going to be one.''
</P>
<P>
   The SPL is set to begin its 29th season at 12:15 today at the
Pyramid at Long Beach State. Through July 26, more than 120 players
are expected to participate. Indiana Pacers guard Jalen Rose,
Orlando Magic forward Bo Outlaw and Boston Celtic forward Antoine
Walker are a few NBA stars expected to compete.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket prices are $7 for general admission and $20 for
courtside. Children under 5 are admitted free when accompanied by
an adult. Game times each day are 12:15, 2:30, 5 and 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   There are 12 teams scheduled for play, but because of the
lockout, there is little NBA involvement. Under lockout rules, no
trades, free-agent signings or summer camps are allowed.
</P>
<P>
   NBA teams aren't allowed to bring their own group of players, as
has been the case in the past. Coaches and all other NBA personnel
are allowed to attend the games but cannot interact with the
players.
</P>
<P>
   Teams are sponsored by corporations and agents, such as Arn
Tellem and Leigh Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're like Switzerland,'' Kwok said, ``in a sense that we're
not really run by one or another. It provides them the perfect
environment to continue playing in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players are here in a neutral territory doing what they
have to do in the summertime. We support both of them. We hope they
are able to resolve this as quickly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   In its history, the league has been a proving ground for several
NBA stars. In 1996, then-17-year-old Lakers guard Kobe Bryant
played his first game as a professional.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Rodman, Karl Malone and Nick Van Exel are among the
league's alumni, but the league is generally a common ground for
the younger players struggling to make the NBA, CBA or a foreign
professional league.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably a bigger concern to guys that are free agents
and rookies fighting for playing time,'' said second-year Indiana
Pacers forward Austin Croshere. ``Whereas someone like Reggie
Miller or Antonio or Dale Davis, those guys are under long-term
contracts and are established. Someone like me, who's fighting for
time, obviously I want to improve as much as I can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
