<SLUG> BC-HMO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIZENS GROUP CHALLENGES GOVERNOR ON HMO CONTRIBUTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MIKE MCCLOY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A citizens group called on Arizona lawmakers and Gov. Jane Hull
on Friday to shake off $1 million in campaign contributions and
reform the health-care industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the industry that gives the most money in the state to
candidates for public office,'' Louis Rhodes of Arizona Citizen
Action said at a news conference to announce the formation of
Arizonans for HMO Reform. ``We've got to reform the HMO process.''
</P>
<P>
   The coalition is asking all candidates to pledge support for
quicker care, more time in the hospital for women's ailments,
malpractice liability for HMOs that deny care, and more access to
specialists.
</P>
<P>
   The creation of Arizonans for HMO Reform comes as Congress,
President Clinton and other policymakers are proposing so-called
``patient's bill of rights'' legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Rhodes on Friday was Ken Moore of the National Council
of Senior Citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just about everyone I know has had a problem with an HMO,''
Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   However, records supplied by the Arizona Department of Insurance
indicate that only one in 1,800 managed-care patients had a beef
last year. The department received 413 complaints from the 746,000
patients enrolled by the dozen health-maintenance organizations
doing business in the state, Erin Klug, chief market conduct
examiner, said.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes released an analysis of campaign contributions from
lobbyists dating to 1995, contending that they have supplied more
than 11 percent of Hull's election funds, contributions that he
said protected managed care from regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hull, son of the governor and her campaign manager,
rebutted the contention, saying she has collected no more than 3
percent of her $1 million campaign fund from the health-care
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're putting out wrong information to promote socialized
medicine,'' Mike Hull said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a person who could debate that there's unhappiness
with HMOs,'' he said. But he accused Arizona Citizen Action of
mounting a political attack on behalf of Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Former Phoenix Mayor Paul Johnson, Democratic primary candidate
for governor, proposed legislation last month to increase patient
rights under managed care.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes said his group's proposal is similar to Johnson's but
independent of it. Rhodes said that HMO benefits have been limited
because lobbyists for the health industry have ``purchased access
to elected state officials.''
</P>
<P>
   The report by Arizonans for HMO Reform named Allan Stanton as
the leading contributor _ giving more than $3,000 to Arizona
elected officials since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton noted, however, that his total comes to only $3 a day
and that he represents a dozen clients besides Blue Cross-Blue
Shield of Arizona. Those others include railroads, General Motors
Corp., Robson Communities and Raytheon, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Citizen Action also listed lobbyists Don Isaacson and
Joe Abate as major contributors to candidates, saying each gave
$1,625 over the past three years to head off regulation of HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   Said Isaacson, who lobbies for St. Joseph's Hospital and Medical
Center, ``I don't represent an HMO, and haven't for 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Abate's clients include 10 health-care provider groups, such as
dental hygienists, podiatrists, psychiatrists and even
veterinarians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost all of them fight the HMOs,'' Abate said. ``They're for
more patient protection and reform.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Mike McCloy may be reached at 444-8111 or at mike.mccloy &LR; pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
