<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ROD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAMES ROD, 53, WARDEN OF MARSH SANCTUARY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa, Idaho)  (lb) 
 By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ James Rod, a naturalist who revealed the secret world
of Hudson River snapping turtles, muskrats and cattails to
governors and schoolchildren alike as warden of a protected marsh
in Garrison, died July 4 at Mount Sinai Medical Center in New York
City. He was 53.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of death was cancer, said his brother Douglas, of
Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   James Rod became manager and warden of the Constitution Marsh
Sanctuary, a 270-acre preserve managed by the National Audubon
Society, in 1982. In every season he could be found leading a canoe
tour or dipping a seine in that secluded backwater on the east bank
of the Hudson, 50 miles north of New York City in Putnam County.
</P>
<P>
   Rod's studies of cadmium contamination in the marsh's muskrat
population helped prompt the federal Environmental Protection
Agency to order a $100 million Superfund cleanup at a defunct
battery factory that abutted the preserve, New York state
environmental officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The cleanup was completed last year, and Rod helped cultivate
thousands of cattail seedlings to plant where tainted mud had been
dredged. Along with leading countless school groups and
bird-watchers through the marsh over 16 years, he frequently acted
as a wildlife guide to Gov. George Pataki, who lives two miles from
the marsh.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot more high-profile figures in conservation,''
Pataki said, ``but there was no more knowledgeable or caring a
figure than Jim Rod. He taught me an awful lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Recalling one tour of the marsh, before the cadmium cleanup,
Pataki said: ``We were out there in canoes one time, and he said,
`Look for the muskrats.' There weren't any. And that was the whole
point.''
</P>
<P>
   The marsh, tucked in a bay created when railroad tracks were
laid along the Hudson in the 19th century, is a refuge for more
than 200 bird species, 45 kinds of fish and several reptiles,
including an ugly, sometimes nasty creature Rod was particularly
fond of, according to his family and friends: the snapping turtle.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Rod, who is 51, said his older brother began taking
snapping turtles and other creatures to their home in Ames, Iowa,
when he was 5 or 6. Soon, the boys started a ``neighborhood zoo''
in the garage, he said. ``Jim was scaring little girls with
snapping turtles 40 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   That early fascination with wriggling things led to
undergraduate studies in wildlife biology at Iowa State University.
Rod dropped out before graduating, later earning a bachelor's
degree in journalism at Iona College in New Rochelle.
</P>
<P>
   He received a Bronze Star and Air Medal for service in Vietnam
in the Army's 173rd Airborne Brigade.
</P>
<P>
   When Rod started work at the marsh, it was a rarely visited
preserve, known mainly to duck hunters. But soon, with rounds of
fund raising and hammering, Rod and a small crew built meandering
boardwalks, bird-watching blinds and a small education center that
is visited by 5,000 people a year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his brother, he is survived by his mother,
Pauline Rod, of Ames; his wife, Dee Hughes, of Garrison; another
brother, William, of Ames, and a son, Terry Totemeier of Idaho
Falls, Idaho.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-98 2324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980710.0423 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0305 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-DEVILRAYS-N     07-10 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-DEVILRAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG BALL CARRIES YANKEES OVER DEVIL RAYS, 8-4 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Chuck Knoblauch swings at the first pitch
about as often as the Yankees lose. Taking pitches is part of what
he does, part of why he has still been an effective offensive
player as a leadoff man, despite a plummeting batting average.
</P>
<P>
   But Knoblauch apparently got tired of making outs and made up
his mind to swing at the first pitch in his at-bats Friday night.
In the process, he catapulted the Yankee attack. Knoblauch whacked
a game-tying three-run homer in the sixth inning against Tampa Bay,
and the Yankees got a game-breaking three-run homer from Scott
Brosius in the eighth as they beat the Devil Rays, 8-4.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Yankees' eighth consecutive victory, their 12th in
their last 13 games. They have won 63 and lost 20 and are four
victories better than the 83-game record of the legendary 1927
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Hideki Irabu, in danger of being replaced in the rotation by
Ramiro Mendoza, barely pitched well enough to win but still
improved his record to 7-3. It was Knoblauch who bailed him out
with his bat.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch's average had dropped to .263 by the All-Star Game
break, but he said he felt much better Thursday, after returning
from the break. He had had a chance to get away from the game,
flying to Minnesota to repair water damage in his house there,
ripping up water-logged carpets with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   But things hardly seemed improved for him on Thursday. Knoblauch
lined out in his first at-bat, hit another hard grounder for an out
in the second inning, struck out in his final two at-bats and
nearly committed a costly throwing error. Afterward, manager Joe
Torre said that maybe Knoblauch was a little frustrated; he just
needed something good to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch made his own luck Friday night, swinging at the game's
first pitch, swinging at the first pitch again in the third; he was
going to remain aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay was ahead by 3-0 in the fifth inning, and Wilson
Alvarez had not allowed the Yankees a hit. But after hitting
Brosius on the elbow with a fastball, Alvarez yielded a single to
Joe Girardi. Alvarez then tried throwing a fastball past Knoblauch,
who smashed it to left, about 10 feet over the wall, his first home
run in 135 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees added two runs in the sixth, and Brosius finished
off the Devil Rays two innings later.
</P>
<P>
   Asked on Thursday whether Irabu might be replaced in the
rotation, Torre said all options had to be considered, a nice way
for a manager to say, yeah, the guy could be in trouble. After all,
Irabu had allowed eight home runs in 11 2/3 innings in his previous
three starts, and beyond that, he seemed unsure.
</P>
<P>
   Torre seems convinced Irabu is healthy, but is much less certain
about Irabu's mental approach.
</P>
<P>
   If Irabu was, in fact, pitching to keep his job in the rotation
Friday night, he offered an inconsistent performance against the
league's worst- hitting team _ but ultimately made the pitches
needed to win.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay scored single runs in the second, third and fourth
innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays scored their first run after Al Clark, the home
plate umpire, missed what appeared to be a called third strike
against a pivotal hitter in the inning, and Mel Stottlemyre, the
pitching coach, had to go to the mound to calm Irabu afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay's second run was no fluke: Fred McGriff anticipated a
fastball, correctly, and blasted a home run over the left field
wall, his first in Tampa Bay since April 28.
</P>
<P>
   With two out in the fourth inning, Dave Martinez hit a looping
liner to center field, where Chad Curtis rushed in, attempted a
shoestring catch _ and missed.
</P>
<P>
   Like a pebble skittering across ice, the ball bounced off the
artificial surface and rolled and rolled, to the deepest part of
the park, banging against the wall in center field 415 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Tim Raines retrieved the ball and Derek Jeter
relayed home, Martinez was across home plate with a dive, the first
inside-the-park home run in the Devil Rays' short history.
</P>
<P>
   After the Yankees tied the game in the fifth, Tampa Bay
sandwiched a single and a walk around a throwing error by Jeter,
loading the bases. Behind two balls and one strike, Irabu
challenged Paul Sorrento with a fastball; Sorrento fouled it
straight back, just missing.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu threw a ball high, for a full count, then came back with a
diving split-finger fastball that Sorrento swung over and missed.
</P>
<P>
   If Irabu stays in the rotation and revives his season, he might
look back on this as a pivotal pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez then ended the inning by bouncing to short and into a
double play _ the end of a devastating inning for the Devil Rays,
no runs after loading the bases with nobody out. The Yankees
swarmed the top step of their dugout to greet the infielders. It
was as if they knew they had won the game right then.
</P>
<P>
   Errors by shortstop Kevin Stocker and third baseman Wade Boggs
in the sixth provided the Yankees with two runs and a 5-3
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu was relieved in the bottom of the inning, with one out,
and after Graeme Lloyd pitched out of the jam left for him, Irabu's
final line was no better than respectable: 7 hits, 4 walks, 3 runs
and 5 strikeouts in 5 1/3 innings. He had thrown 102 pitches, only
59 strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' rotation has failed to produce a quality start in
only seven of the last 33 games, and Irabu is responsible for four
of those seven.
</P>
<P>
   But for the first time since June 10, Irabu won. And once again,
the Yankees won. No matter who pitches or who hits or who they
play, they win.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   The loss for Tampa Bay was its eighth in a row. The first-year
Devil Rays trail the Yankees by 31 1/2 games in the American League
East.
</P>
<P>
   Ramiro Mendoza pitched two and two-thirds scoreless innings in
relief and earned his first save of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night's game, matching David Cone (12-2) for New York
and Rolando Arrojo (10-5) for Tampa Bay, is a sellout _ the Devil
Rays' first since opening day.
</P>
<P>
   The inside-the-park homer by Dave Martinez was the first against
the Yankees since Aug. 8, 1996, when Minnesota's Roberto Kelly hit
one off Dwight Gooden at the Metrodome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
