<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-STADIUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR REJECTS SUGGESTION FOR GUARANTEE ON YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani on Friday rejected George
Steinbrenner's suggestion that the city guarantee a record number
of ticket sales this season at Yankee Stadium if the team stays
there, saying it was ``not the right way to negotiate.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said it would be unfair to ensure record profits for
the Yankees without doing the same for every other business in the
city.
</P>
<P>
   ``It opens up an area of negotiations that other businesses
would then want,'' Giuliani said during a news conference at City
Hall. ``Every business wants to be more and more profitable. You
don't want to put the city in the position of guaranteeing that
profitability.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Steinbrenner said that he would consider keeping
the Yankees in the Bronx if attendance reached 3 million this year
_ about 6 percent more than the team is on pace to draw, and 14
percent more than the team's previous record _ and can be
guaranteed to stay at that level.
</P>
<P>
   The statement was seen as a softening of Steinbrenner's
insistence that his team cannot make enough money in the Bronx,
because worries about crime and traffic keep potential spectators
away. He has pressured city officials to build a new stadium on the
West Side of Manhattan, and Giuliani has enthusiastically taken
steps toward such a project, saying that while he wants to keep the
team in the Bronx, his primary goal is to keep it somewhere in the
city.
</P>
<P>
   But the City Council speaker, Peter Vallone, and the Bronx
borough president, Fernando Ferrer, have repeatedly denounced the
plan, saying that the Yankees should stay in the stadium that they
have called home for 75 years.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone, who is seeking the Democratic nomination for governor
this year, has sought to put a referendum on the November ballot
that would block a West Side stadium. That effort started a bitter
dispute between him and Giuliani over the city budget that is still
being fought out.
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday, Giuliani praised Vallone for not taking
Steinbrenner's request seriously. Vallone told reporters on
Thursday that asking the city to guarantee 3 million fans was
``like asking George Steinbrenner to guarantee 100 wins every
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said that Steinbrenner had thrown ``a sucker punch''
and that Vallone had understood how to avoid it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a time in which I probably agree with the speaker,''
Giuliani said Friday. ``I think the speaker's reaction to it,
despite our disagreement over a resolution, indicates the great
experience that he has in city government negotiating.''
</P>
<P>
   Vallone said he saw the mayor's comments, taken along with
Steinbrenner's new willingness to discuss staying in the Bronx, as
a small triumph. Both suggest that the two men are coming around to
his point of view, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to think we're all moving in the right direction
now,'' Vallone said. ``Hopefully we will all be sitting down and
talking soon to figure out the most viable way of keeping the New
York Yankees in the Bronx.''
</P>
<P>
   But a spokesman for Steinbrenner, Howard Rubenstein, said that
Steinbrenner would come to a decision on his own about where he
wanted his team to be, and that he would not announce it until
fall. Selling 3 million tickets this season would be a reason to
discuss staying in the Bronx, but Steinbrenner does not really
believe so many tickets can be sold, Rubenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if the 3 million is reached, that doesn't necessarily
close a deal,'' Rubenstein said. ``All George was saying was: `Put
up or shut up. If you can guarantee 3 million, then we can talk.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
