<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0310 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MILLIONAIRE-SUSPEC     07-10 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MILLIONAIRE-SUSPECTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINKS SEEN BETWEEN HOUSE FIRE AND CASE OF MISSING MILLIONAIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Nev., Calif., Fla.)  (Eds: See also NY-MISSING-MILLIONAIRE) 
(mk) 
 By JAMES RISEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the house at 2121 Geronimo Way in Las Vegas was
damaged in a suspicious fire last January, it did not take long for
agents from Fireman's Fund Insurance Co. to begin an investigation
of a policy written only two weeks earlier to a man named Robert
McCarren.
</P>
<P>
   But McCarren was not an average homeowner in the plush
neighborhood of $300,000 homes abutting the Las Vegas National Golf
Club.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, police and private investigators now say McCarren was
picked out of a Las Vegas homeless shelter by Sante Kimes, a con
artist suspected in the disappearance of at least three people, and
put squarely in the middle of a scheme to defraud the insurance
company and a bank of hundreds of thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   And, the investigators say, Ms. Kimes went so far as to prepare
him for an interview with an investigator from the insurance
company and to threaten him if he did not stick to the story she
had written.
</P>
<P>
   To investigators in Nevada and New York, the story of 2121
Geronimo Way seems like a mirror image of what they believe to be
the case in the disappearance of Irene Silverman, a Manhattan
millionaire: fraudulent efforts to quickly transfer the ownership
of valuable real estate _ followed by murder.
</P>
<P>
   After officials in Las Vegas determined that the house had been
deliberately burned, Fireman's Fund contacted McCarren to set up an
interview. He agreed to the meeting, according to an investigator
familiar with the case, but insisted that it be held in the lobby
of an airport hotel in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   According to that investigator, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity, the company was unaware that the location had been
chosen so that Ms. Kimes and her son, Kenneth Kimes, the real
owners of the house, could sit nearby and listen to the
conversation. They wanted to make sure that McCarren didn't confess
to being a front man for their elaborate scheme, the investigator
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kimes and her son are in custody in New York City, held on a
Utah warrant involving a bad check. And just as New York police are
trying to unravel the disappearance of Mrs. Silverman,
investigators are piecing together the remarkably complex tale of
the Las Vegas home.
</P>
<P>
   As early as 1992, Ms. Kimes filed court papers indicating that
her family had transferred the ownership of the house to David
Kazdin, a Los Angeles businessman acquainted with Ms. Kimes for a
long time. But insurance investigators now believe that Kazdin did
not know that he had been listed as the property's owner.
Investigators said they believe that Ms. Kimes put the home in
Kazdin's name so that it would not be seized as part of any civil
lawsuits or criminal proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Late in 1997 or very early this year, investigators say, Ms.
Kimes took out a new mortgage on the home with a bank in Florida,
using Kazdin's name.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after obtaining the mortgage, investigators say, Ms.
Kimes decided to change the name on the title. This time, they say,
she found McCarren, an indigent man who was at a homeless shelter
in Las Vegas, and had him listed as the new owner. The documents
making the transfer were notarized by Nanette Wetkowski, a notary
public who was a business associate of Kimes.
</P>
<P>
   After transferring ownership to McCarren, Ms. Kimes used his
name in January to buy an insurance policy on the home. The house
was burned on Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   In the days before McCarren's meeting with the insurance
investigator, Ms. Kimes grilled him mercilessly, demanding that he
memorize the script she had prepared on how to respond to the
investigator's questions, according to police officials in Los
Angeles. McCarren later told police that when he made mistakes in
their practice sessions, Ms. Kimes would beat him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sante Kimes is an incredibly manipulative and controlling
woman,'' said an insurance investigator familiar with the case.
``And she intimidated and manipulated McCarren, and she tried to
manipulate and control everyone else she came in contact with.''
</P>
<P>
   But while McCarren got through the first interview with the
insurance company officials, the scheme was beginning to unravel,
officials said. Given the suspicious nature of the case, Fireman's
Fund refused to pay out on the insurance claim on the Las Vegas
home.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, an official from the Florida bank contacted Kazdin,
who told the official that he had not applied for a mortgage on the
house and did not know what he was talking about, investigators
say.
</P>
<P>
   But by that time, investigators say, Ms. Kimes had wired the
money _ at least $200,000 _ from the mortgage to an offshore bank
account in the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Kazdin was found dead in a Dumpster at Los Angeles
International Airport, and some investigators suspect that he may
have confronted the Kimeses about the house after being contacted
by the Florida banker.
</P>
<P>
   McCarren, meanwhile, became increasingly afraid of the Kimeses,
especially after he heard about Kazdin's killing, police say.
Investigators say the Kimeses were holding McCarren captive in Los
Angeles, but he broke free and contacted Los Angeles police.
Investigators said they believe that these developments prompted
the mother and son to embark on a cross-country trek that
ultimately led them to an elegant Manhattan town house on East 65th
Street.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
