<HEADER>
A0313 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COL-CHILD-WELFARE-     07-10 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-CHILD-WELFARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: DANGER SIGNS, BUT NO SENSE OF URGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the corner of Alice Herb's living room is a box
for a game her grandchildren play whenever they visit her in
Greenwich Village. It's called ``Snafu _ the Maze Game That Runs
You Ragged.'' ``Push the buttons,'' the instructions read. ``Spin
the dials.'' If she had to spin her wheels, Grandma could probably
win with ease; she has had practice in another labyrinth.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Herb is a lawyer and ethics consultant to a group of health
and social-service providers in Brooklyn. Since late February, she
and several agencies have asked the city's Administration for
Children's Services to remove two children from the home of a
19-year-old client of the agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The mother, they said, appeared incapable of adequately feeding,
clothing and protecting her children. They said she had been
attacked, in front of the children, by a man who forced his way
into her filthy apartment. Often, they added, the children, 2 and 5
years old, had come to office visits unkempt or agitated.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Herb said she never received a reply to three detailed
letters written to the administration's general counsel and to
Nicholas Scoppetta, its commissioner. She was also upset that even
though she and the four service providers who worked with the
family recommended that the children be removed from their home,
child-welfare officials decided otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Herb and several of her colleagues are dumbstruck by what
they see as a breakdown in communication with child-welfare
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get strong recommendations from four agencies, you'd
think there would be some meat to the claims,'' Ms. Herb said.
``There are warning signs. These are two children that can be saved
except for the ridiculous policy of keeping them with the mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Child-welfare officials who reviewed the case said they had been
in touch with the mother and ``all the right people'' from the
beginning. They said that the letters prompted an investigation.
But they also said that among the representatives of four
social-service groups that met on Feb. 20 to discuss the case, not
everyone agreed that the children needed to be removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have responded to their concerns,'' said Leonora Weiner, a
spokeswoman for the administration. ``The casework has been
thorough, and we are still monitoring the family.''
</P>
<P>
   But four people at the February meeting insisted that the
service providers who attended were unanimous in recommending that
the mother give up custody. They said that one of them, a
caseworker from Covenant House, which provided counseling and other
services to the mother under a contract with the city agency, was
later overruled by her supervisor. A spokeswoman for Covenant House
declined to comment, citing client confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   Officials would not say for the record who were ``the right
people'' they consulted on the case. Dr. Jeffrey Birnbaum, a
pediatrician on the faculty of the State University of New York
Health Science Center at Brooklyn, said he was not among them. He
could have told investigators how he treated the mother when she
came in with a black eye after an attempted rape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had an agency not respond in such a way,'' said
Birnbaum, who wrote to Scoppetta in early May. ``I've had cases 10
times more complicated than this where a supervisor in a field
office responds front and center. Here, we haven't gotten
sufficient response.''
</P>
<P>
   Isabel Adon, a caseworker who assists him, said that she had
tried repeatedly to contact a city caseworker and supervisor, but
that they had seemed irritated on the three occasions she reached
them. She said they had been upset that she and her colleagues had
written to their bosses.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't even know the mother was in the hospital,'' Ms.
Adon said of her last call on April 21. ``The situation
deteriorated as to why I was doing this to them. After that I made
calls and got no answer. The communication just died out.''
</P>
<P>
   The mother has since enrolled in the Job Corps in Massachusetts.
She placed her children in the custody of their grandmother, who
lives in a studio apartment with two of her own children. Birnbaum
wonders what will happen if the mother returns to New York. He also
wonders if the agency will ever respond to him directly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's stuff going on now we could be telling them,'' he
said. ``We're trying to serve as supplemental sources of
information, and we need to have feedback on what they're doing.
We're trying to make sure they don't have a disaster on their
hands, because we see things that are going on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
