</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- July 10, 1998 -- NY-MISSING-MILLIONAIRE-3,
7-10 -- Irene Zambelli Silverman, the wealthy 82-year-old widow who
disappeared from her Manhattan mansion last Sunday, is now feared
dead. Police Commissioner Howard Safir with pictures Friday of
Kenneth Kimes, Sante Kimes and a third suspect in the case. (James
Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- July 10, 1998 -- NY-MISSING-MILLIONAIRE-2,
7-10 -- Irene Zambelli Silverman, the wealthy 82-year-old widow who
disappeared from her Manhattan mansion last Sunday, is now feared
dead. Police say the circumstances surrounding a suspicious fire at
this house in Las Vegas may help explain her disappearance. (Monica
Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- July 10, 1998 --
NY-MISSING-MILLIONAIRE-1-B&AMP;W, 7-10 -- Irene Zambelli Silverman in
1983 at her home in Manhattan. She and her husband bought the
limestone mansion in 1957. The wealthy 82-year-old widow, who
disappeared last Sunday, is now feared dead. (Keith Meyers/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) VIENNA, Austria -- July 10, 1998 -- NY-MATH-TEACHERS-2,
7-10 -- Elke Rogl, who studied math and physics at the University
of Vienna, may teach in New York City. She is standing beside a
bust of Ludwig Boltzman, 1844-1906, a famous mathematician and
theoretical physicist, at the University of Vienna. (Josef
Polleross/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- July 10, 1998 -- NY-MATH-TEACHERS-1, 7-10 --
New York officials, who might hire as many as 50 Austrian teachers,
watch a Viennese educator on a teleconference monitor recently.
``If you can read this,'' brochures distributed in Austria last
month beckoned in English, ``have we got a deal for you!!!'' Since
then, nearly 300 Austrians have called the Ministry of Education in
Vienna requesting applications for the full-time jobs being handed
out by the New York City Board of Education. (Ruby Washington/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- July 10, 1998 -- NY-MICRO-LOANS, 7-10 --
Ivette Alvarez in her Brooklyn workshop, which makes statues and
religious figurines out of plaster. She and her husband, Eddy,
opened the factory with microcredit loans, which have helped combat
poverty in developing countries like India and Ecuador, according
to the World Bank. (J. Emilio Flores/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) MEDFORD, Mass. -- July 10, 1998 -- MEET-SPICE-BOS, 7-10
-- From front to rear, Anne LeBlanc, 8, and her friends, Jennifer
Belbin, 9, Jessica Wright, 9, and Tabitha Belbin, 8. The four girls
were chosen to meet the Spice Girls backstage before the group's
concert at Great Woods. ``I wanted Sporty Spice to see my outfit,''
says Ann, who persuaded her mother to allow her to wear blue eye
shadow. ``I've never dressed up or gone anywhere like this
before.'' (John Blanding/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) WASHINGTON -- July 10, 1998 -- DC-MEDALOFHONOR-FLOATER,
7-10 -- More than 30 years after his acts of valor in Vietnam,
Robert Ingram is awarded the Medal of Honor on Friday by President
Clinton. Ingram was a Navy corpsman when he accompanied a platoon
of marines into battle and ministered to the wounded even though he
had been shot four times, including in the head. The Navy said the
delay occurred because it lost the paperwork for his medal. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WASHINGTON -- July 10, 1998 -- DC-MARINE-BAND-FLOATER,
7-10 -- The Marine Corps Band commemorates its 200th anniversary
Friday by parading across the South Lawn of the White House,
playing ``Semper Fidelis.'' The band, nicknamed The President's
Own, also played ``Unforgettable,'' which is said to be a favorite
tune of the couple in residence. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- July 10, 1998 -- RUBIN-FUTURE, 7-10 --
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, left, conferring with aides,
including Deputy Secretary Lawrence Summers, second from left, and
the secretary's chief of staff, Michael Froman, right. Right or
wrong, it is accepted wisdom among his Cabinet colleagues that
Rubin is planning to leave Washington by the end of the year.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) LEMONT, Ill. -- July 10, 1998 -- SWAMI-STATUE, 7-10 -- A
statue of Swami Vivekandanda, the founder of the Vendata Society,
is moved into place Monday at the Hindu temple at Lemont. The
statue is to be dedicated on Sunday and is expected to draw
thousands of Hindus. (Todd Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- July 10, 1998 -- JACKSON-MUSIC-REVIEW,
7-10 -- Janet Jackson in concert Thursday at the MCI Center in
Washington. Long after the other masters of the 1980s pop spectacle
have withdrawn Q Madonna to motherhood, Michael Jackson to
fatherhood Q Ms. Jackson has not just persevered but thrived. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- July 10, 1998 -- DAD-STUDIES-B&AMP;W, 7-10 -- It
seems self-evident to just about anyone who has ever had a father
that a caring, involved dad is good for a child. But try proving
it. The studies that do exist fail to cast much light on why
fathers really matter, something that most researchers concede
tells more about their methodological weaknesses than about the
importance of fatherhood. (Librado Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) GALLUP, N.M. -- July 10, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 12
-- SPEND-NAVAJO-FOUNDATION-2, 7-10 -- The Southwest Indian
Foundation is a refuge of last resort for needy families. But the
group's direct-mail catalog raises questions about the mixing of
charity and business. ``We would not be able to do the amount of
charitable work we do if it were not for the business,'' says
William McCarthy, the foundation's head, standing in front of a
cultural center the foundation opened last year in Gallup. (Steve
Northup/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) GALLUP, N.M. -- July 10, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 12
-- SPEND-NAVAJO-FOUNDATION-1, 7-10 -- At a ceramic workshop set up
by the Southwest Indian Foundation, Gloria Dennison, Petra Reed and
Conrad Thomas paint pottery. The foundation enjoys a sterling
reputation on the Navajo Reservation, where it is a refuge of last
resort for needy families. But it is the group's direct-mail
catalog which the outside world sees, and which raises questions
about the mixing of charity and business. (Steve Northup/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- July 10, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 12 --
FARAH-VENATOR-PROFILE-2-B&AMP;W, 7-10 -- In 1954, shopping often
included a visit to a Woolworth store for anything from baked goods
to nail polish. Since Robert Farah became chief executive of the
Woolworth Corp. in 1994, he has reduced the company's overall debt
to $440 million, from $1.2 billion, and, in perhaps his most
dramatic move, closed its fabled dime stores. (New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) BALTIMORE -- July 10, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 12 --
SUB-MUTFUND-BLUECHIPS, 7-10 -- In buying a stock, Larry Puglia,
lead manager of T. Rowe Price Blue Chip Growth, considers a
company's ``self-sustaining growth rate.'' Since Puglia helped
start the fund in 1993, it has had an average annual return of 25.1
percent, through July 3, according to Morningstar Inc., the
financial publisher in Chicago. (Ann Grillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- July 10, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 12 --
WOMEN-PLASTIC-SURGERY, 7-10 -- Dr. Michelle Copeland, one of the
few plastic surgeons who are women, in her Fifth Avenue office.
Women account for only about 4 percent of all the board-certified
plastic surgeons in the United States, according to the American
Society for Aesthetic Plastic Surgery. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- July 10, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 12 --
KEEVE-FILMS , 7-10 -- In his half-dozen years as a filmmaker,
Douglas Keeve, a former fashion photographer whose 1995 film,
``Unzipped,'' documented the work of designer Isaac Mizrahi, has
turned his penchant for voyeurism into a flair for comedic truth
telling. ``Douglas has a way of peering beneath fashion's skirts Q
and that can be very enticing stuff,'' says Gabe Doppelt, the VH-1
producer who commissioned Keeve's latest documentary. (Frances
Roberts/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- July 10, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 12 --
FARAH-VENATOR-PROFILE, 7-10 -- Roger Farah has been trying to
revitalize Venator Group, the company once called Woolworth, by
concentrating on sales of sports equipment. Since Farah became
chief executive of the Woolworth Corp. in 1994, he has reduced the
company's overall debt to $440 million, from $1.2 billion, and, in
perhaps his most dramatic move, closed its fabled dime stores.
(Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) LOS ANGELES -- July 10, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 12 --
STEPHANIE-POWERS-MONEY, 7-10 -- Stefanie Powers, at her home in the
Benedict Canyon area of Beverly Hills with Papuga, her parrot.
Organizing her own finances has not been as easy for Stefanie
Powers as triumphing over TV bad guys. ``I used to qualify my
questions by saying: 'Here is this dumb question,' `` saysMs.
Powers, 55. ``Today I am less insecure. I am more able to say,
'Excuse me. I don't understand that, and if I don't, how can the
average investor?' `` (Kim Kulish/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- July 10, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 12 --
INVEST-AURORA-FOOD, 7-10 -- Even solid brand names, like those
owned by Aurora Foods, have not brought a feeding frenzy to recent
initial public offerings of shares. Aurora plunged into the IPO
market last month and has seen its stock almost stand still. (Naum
Kazhdan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- July 10, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 12 --
CAR-SMART, 7-10 -- Few cars shatter ragtop myths quite as
thoroughly as the 3-Series BMW. The rigid structure that makes
solid-top Bimmers so riveting serves the convertibles well, too.
The soft-top 323 is stable and responsive, comparing favorably with
the coupe. It does weigh 200 pounds more, and it feels even
heavier. It moves a little slower and skips a bit on rippled
pavement. But the body stubbornly refuses to shudder. (New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- July 10, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 12 --
ABOUT-CARS-BMW, 7-10 -- The BMW 323is: Six cylinders for a lower
price. A feisty terrier in a dog-eat-dog business, BMW knows
something about survival of the fittest. Its ever-mutating
3-Series, which accounts for 44 percent of overall sales, has
become a genus with 31 species sold around the world. (New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
