<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0317 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC--WORLDCUP-HNS &LR;      07-10 1423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC--WORLD </SLUG>
 CUP-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Cup provides vivid moments
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOHN P. LOPEZ &QL; 
PARIS _ Some Croatian fans are sitting in a bar near the
Champs-Elysees just a few hours after their team lost a
heartbreaking World Cup semifinal game to France.
</P>
<P>
   Much to their surprise, in walk three Croatian players. The
players walk up to the fans and begin thanking them for their
support, signing autographs and shaking hands.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the Croatian players give the fans some money when they
realize the fans were desperately trying to get home after spending
everything they had on scalper's tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Click.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the World Cup pictures we should save.
</P>
<P>
   It's nearly 1 a.m. at a Paris subway station near the Gare de
Lyon, when hundreds of Mexican fans flood the station after
arriving by bullet train from the Mexico-South Korea game.
</P>
<P>
   A small group of South Koreans are among the throng, holding
Korean flags and quietly, curiously watching the Mexicans sing
wildly about their team's victory.
</P>
<P>
   The South Koreans, about 10 of them, softly begin chanting,
``Viva Mexico, Viva Mexico,'' as if to say congratulations to the
partying mass.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexicans break into a thunderous round of applause when they
hear the cheer, then begin chanting ``Viva Korea'' in return. The
subway arrives, they stuff themselves into the train together and
the last train of the night speeds away into the darkness.
</P>
<P>
   Click. Save another picture.
</P>
<P>
   It is time for the national anthems to be played before the
England-Tunisia match in Marseille. Hours earlier, a group of
English hooligans and local thugs bloodied the streets with ugly
rioting.
</P>
<P>
   As if to make a statement that not all English fans are
hooligans, the huge contingent of English fans at Stade Velodrome
sing God Save the Queen to a deafening level. Later, during the
game, a group of English fans hold up the flag of St. George
inscribed with the words, ``We're sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Click.
</P>
<P>
   A bus stuffed with Iran supporters barrels around a corner near
Stade Gerland hours before the highly charged United States-Iran
game. An Iranian flag falls out of one of the bus's windows.
</P>
<P>
   The bus stops, but before anyone can get off to retrieve the
flag a young American picks it up and hands it back through the
window.
</P>
<P>
   Click.
</P>
<P>
   It is a stuffy, long, sad ride on the bullet train from
Saint-Etienne to Lyon after Scotland yet again was eliminated from
the tournament in the first round. Scottish fans are sitting
together, talking quietly about the sad streak of never advancing
in the sport they cherish.
</P>
<P>
   A pair off Scottish fans still wearing red wigs, kilts and
tassled shoes stand and shout encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on, we are Scotland,'' one of them shouts. And the two
begin kicking their feet and singing, ``Hey, hey, hey, Scotland!''
</P>
<P>
   For the next hour, the train rocks with songs.
</P>
<P>
   Click.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after eliminating the Argentines from the competition in
a tough quarterfinal game, several Holland players put a different
spin on the tradition of applauding their fans.
</P>
<P>
   After raising their arms over their heads and applauding the
Dutch fans, the Dutch players walk toward the grandstands where
Argentina's fans are still standing stunned and silent over the
elimination loss.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch players begin applauding their rival's great support
and get warm applause in return.
</P>
<P>
   Click.
</P>
<P>
   It is the gut-wrenching moments of the second half of a
semifinal game between France and Croatia. France is looking for a
hero and out of nowhere comes Lilian Thuram.
</P>
<P>
   He is a tall, thin black man, a native of Guadeloupe who
immigrated as a child with his mother to France. Thuram flashes
upfield and somehow unleashes a magnificent shot that rips the net
and gives France a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   During the ensuing celebration, French defender Laurent Blanc,
who is white, wraps both hands around Thuram's neck, leans forward
and softly touches foreheads with Thuram. The moment probably did
more for the sometimes-strained race relations in this country than
any words could.
</P>
<P>
   Click.
</P>
<P>
   Save these pictures and all the others that 32 days, 62 matches
and countless World Cup moments provided.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only say that it has been a success in every way,'' said
Michel Platini, the famous French soccer star who served as
president for France '98. ``It is an enormous responsibility and a
great weight on our shoulders to organize and stage the World Cup,
but I think by any standard, people have been very satisfied with
how it has gone.''
</P>
<P>
   There remain a few pictures to be taken before the 1998 World
Cup comes to a close. Most notably, Sunday night it will be France
or Brazil holding up the World Cup trophy.
</P>
<P>
   But even before that tempting match kicks off, or today's
third-place game between Croatia and the Netherlands, the pictures
that this World Cup will leave behind figure to be lasting and
mostly good ones.
</P>
<P>
   It was a tournament that promised much more wide-open soccer,
the emergence of new stars, dramatic moments, safe and full
stadiums and colorful moments for the world to remember.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part it fulfilled the promise, with the exceptions
being a handful of bloody scenes involving English and German thugs
that led to numerous arrests and injuries, including the beating of
a French officer who remains in a coma.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing our security force could do to stop those
incidents from starting,'' said Jacques Lambert, managing director
of France '98. ``But (security) reacted swiftly and took control. I
wish we could have had a perfect record for security, but that was
impossible. I think overall, it was very successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, no matter what happens in the dream match between the
host nation and the world's greatest soccer power Sunday, the World
Cup likely will be deemed successful, too.
</P>
<P>
   On the field, the games were at times dramatic in a thespian
sense _ players taking dives and flailing their arms hoping to get
calls from trigger-happy referees.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact Federation Internationale de Football Association
president Sepp Blatter urged officials to use more yellow and red
cards against illegal tackles did lead to more open games.
</P>
<P>
   To date, there have been 21 players red-carded (ejected) and
more than 160 yellow warning cards drawn. As a result, teams
averaged nearly 2.8 goals per game in this tournament, up from four
years ago. Shots on goal also increased by 20 percent from four
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the referees hadn't been making those calls, we wouldn't
have seen some of the great goals we've seen,'' English soccer
legend Bobby Charlton said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the more memorable 1998 goals that likely would have been
stopped by hard tackles in past tournaments were the run by
England's Michael Owen through the Argentine defense, Luis
Hernandez's late dash for Mexico against Holland and Ronaldo's
impressive run through the Denmark defense in the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's given people a better chance to just play football,''
Brazil coach Mario Zagallo said. ``The level of play during this
World Cup has been very high. The Africans have played well and the
Europeans have been moving the ball around better and better.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, individual stars have shined.
</P>
<P>
   Owen, 18, figures to be an English force for years. Paraguay
goalkeeper Jose Luis Chilavert probably can name his price on the
international market after the performance he had in France.
</P>
<P>
   Croatia's Davor Suker is another previously unheralded player
who created a stir here. So did the Danish Laudrup brothers,
Michael and Brian. And there were Italy's Christian Vieri, Chile's
Marcelo Salas and, of course, France's Thuram.
</P>
<P>
   There remain a few sticking points that FIFA leaders hope to
iron out before the 2002 World Cup in South Korea and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Deciding elimination games that end in a tie with penalty kicks
is something nobody seems to like. But no one has come up with a
suitable alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Also, FIFA promises to keep tinkering with tackling rules in
hopes of making the game even more offense-oriented and less
entrenched with old-style defensive tactics. Blatter has expressed
a preference for penalizing not just back tackles, but tackles from
all angles that are ruled inappropriate or intentionally malicious.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Blatter said he was, ``completely happy'' with France's
staging of the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   And now it will be France-Brazil in the final. The world should
get its cameras ready.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
