<HEADLINE>
MORE ICE IN VALLEY'S FUTURE?  
 COYOTES HOPE TO BUILD 3-5 PUBLIC SKATING RINKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - After the ice rink at Metrocenter was turned into a
mini-amusement park, there were only two places left in the Valley
for the public to skate, youth and adult hockey leagues to play and
aspiring figure skaters to train.
</P>
<P>
   But imagine state-of-the-art rinks, complete with full-size
restaurants and impeccable locker-room facilities, popping up all
over the metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa? Peoria? Ahwatukee? Chandler? Central Phoenix?
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we'd like to ultimately surround the Valley. That's
going to be our goal,'' said Mike O'Hearn, who on Friday was
promoted by the Coyotes to president of B.G. Ice Incorporated, a
business extension of the Valley's NHL team that could build as
many as three to five new rinks in the area within the next five to
10 years.
</P>
<P>
   As vice president of hockey operations/facilities last season
for the Coyotes, O'Hearn helped get the team's Scottsdale-based
headquarters and training facility off the ground and tackled the
political battles that went with it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Cellular One Ice Den is one of the hottest new
attractions for public ice consumption. Apart from when the Coyotes
use the two-rink building, it is open for public use 90 percent of
the time, day and night.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes' goal, O'Hearn said, is to spread the wealth around
the Valley so ice time doesn't become too congested. Exact
locations for the potential new sites and dates for completion have
yet to be determined, but each will include upscale ice surfaces,
in addition to Team Shops and, ultimately, frequent appearances by
Coyotes players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been able to generate a lot of grass-roots interest
here, and these types of facilities will enable us to do even
more,'' O'Hearn said. ``Think about it: Of the four major
professional teams (in the Valley), we're the only one that enables
the public to literally come to our front door and be a part of our
family.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Hearn, who has spent 12 years with the franchise, previously
serving as a broadcaster and assistant general manager, also
figures to be a point man in the Coyotes' pursuit of a new arena in
the Valley should acceptable renovations for hockey not be made at
America West Arena within the next two to three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose if it came to that, yes, I'd be involved,'' O'Hearn
said. ``(Coyotes Owner) Richard (Burke) and (team president) Shawn
(Hunter) are dealing with those possibilities. If the decision from
the organization is to move in that kind of direction, hopefully
they'll come back to me and use some of the things I've learned
from this last process here in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think we're a long leap yet from that.''
</P>
<P>
   B.G. Ice Inc., which includes the name of Burke and former
partner Steven Gluckstern, will be renamed to Coyotes Ice LLC or
Coyotes Ice Futures LLC within the next several weeks. &QL; 
Note &QL; 
Chris ``Frosty'' Scoppetto, an assistant equipment manager for the
Coyotes the past two seasons, has resigned to accept a similar
position with the expansion Nashville Predators, who will begin NHL
play in October. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
