<SLUG> BC-NJ-COP-MURDERED-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE OFFICER AND FRIEND ARE FOUND SHOT TO DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (lb) 
 By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERSEY CITY, N.J. _ A decorated veteran of the Jersey City
police department and a friend were found shot to death in the
officer's apartment Thursday, and a prime suspect, the officer's
former roommate, apparently killed himself in rural Pennsylvania,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The officer, Daniel Talty, 48, and his friend, Joseph
Plascencia, 35, of Bayonne, were shot several times each in the
head and chest as they prepared to wallpaper a room in Talty's
ground-floor apartment near the Bayonne border, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   The killings apparently occurred late Sunday or Monday, after
Talty returned from a holiday weekend at the Jersey shore, but the
bodies were not discovered until Thursday night, after Talty failed
to report for work and his colleagues grew concerned, the
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Talty's car, a late-model Mercury Marquis, and a snub-nosed .38
caliber handgun he oned, were missing. The car and a gun that
appeared to be Talty's were found Friday afternoon in a farmer's
field near Harrisburg, Pa., said Daniel Gibney, chief of
investigations in the Hudson County prosecutor's office.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the car was the body of a man, tentatively identified as
Mark Polidoro, 42, who resigned from the Jersey City Police
Department four years ago and has been unable to hold steady work
since then, Gibney said. He said that the man died from a
self-inflicted gunshot wound to the mouth, but that no suicide note
was found.
</P>
<P>
   Gibney said the car had been parked in the field since Tuesday,
but that the farmer did not report it to the Pennsylvania State
Police until Friday. By then, the Jersey City police were already
searching for Polidoro and had issued an alert for the slain
officer's missing Mercury.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said they believed only one weapon was used in
the murders, but they were not certain it was Talty's handgun.
</P>
<P>
   The Jersey City police chief, William Thynne, said Talty, who
was divorced and had two grown children, had invited Polidoro, a
friend for years, to live in his apartment several months ago
because he was jobless and Talty felt sorry for him. But in late
June, the chief said, Talty told Polidoro to leave, because his
life remained in disarray.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly afterward, Talty told friends he had become uneasy about
Polidoro. ``He was acting irrationally, and Talty was concerned,''
Gibney said of Polidoro.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Bret Schundler and Thynne praised the slain officer, a
25-year veteran of the force who had received 13 commendations and
excellent service awards and was once honored by the New Jersey
Legislature for his work with troubled youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a credit to his department, his family and his
friends,'' Schundler said. ``He will be missed by us all.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Thynne said: ``He gave up many hours of his own time and
dedicated it to the children. I can't say enough good things about
this officer.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, the state Senate and Assembly issued a proclamation
naming Talty New Jersey's ``Police Officer of the Year'' for
helping create two police-sponsored programs _ ``We Care for Kids''
and ``Protect Our Children'' _ for teen-agers veering toward
delinquency, said Lt. Michael Louf, an aide to Thynne.
</P>
<P>
   Under those programs during the 1980s and early 1990s, Talty, on
his own time, helped organize athletic events, counseling sessions,
and other events for youths in a multicultural, multiracial
neighborhood, Louf said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Talty was assigned to a police substation at
the Newport Center Mall, a sprawling, 12-year-old shopping center
of 140 stores on the revitalized Jersey City waterfront on the
Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a good friend to the managers,'' said Jim Roberts, the
mall's marketing director. ``A lot of them left early today when
they heard the news. He's going to be very missed and difficult to
replace.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Friday that Talty had failed to report for duty
on Monday and Tuesday, but that his colleagues would not have
noticed his absence, because he normally worked alone at the mall.
His days off were Wednesday and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow officers became uneasy after they were unable to reach
him by phone several times during the week, officials said.
Finally, two went to his home late Thursday and found the bodies
after the landlord, a Jersey City police officer, let them into the
locked apartment, officials said. Both bodies were found in the
kitchen, officials said, and there were no signs of forced entry.
</P>
</TEXT>
