<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-EXPOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS LOSE 5TH STRAIGHT, 8-6 TO EXPOS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was expectation in the air at Shea Stadium
Friday night on the eve of Todd Hundley's return from elbow
surgery. There was a trade for a pitcher, Greg McMichael, whom the
Mets had traded away 36 days before. There was a big, noisy crowd
on hand waiting not-so-patiently for a late-night merengue concert.
</P>
<P>
   There was also a baseball game, and a pretty wild one. The Mets
survived two lost arguments and a four-run deficit to rally for a
brief lead before the Montreal Expos rallied for three runs off
John Franco with two out in the top of the ninth for a demoralizing
8-6 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The defeat was the ninth in 11 games for the reeling Mets
(44-41), who have lost five straight games.
</P>
<P>
   Franco (0-4), the losing pitcher in the Mets' last three games,
probably deserved better. The Expos left the bases loaded in the
eighth when pinch-hitter Mike Hubbard grounded sharply into a force
play at third. But that was after Montreal had been denied a run
when Chris Widger had to settle for a ground-rule double when his
two-out shot off Franco with a runner on first skipped over the
center-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos tied the game at 6-6 in the top of the ninth on a
one-out infield single to short by Vladimir Guerrero, a two-out
single to right by Rondell White through a hole in a shifted
infield, and a high-chop infield single from Mark Grudzielanek on a
ball that got caught in third baseman Edgardo Alfonzo's glove,
allowing the tying run to score. Shane Andrews followed with a
two-run triple to deep center field on a full-count pitch. And the
Mets were on their way to another crushing defeat.
</P>
<P>
   That the Mets even needed Franco was something of a surprise
after the Expos jumped on Masato Yoshii for four early runs. The
first three came during in the third on Guererro's 16th homer, a
420-footer. Montreal picked up another run in the fourth on a
lead-off triple by Grudzielanek and Widger's successful suicide
squeeze.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets rallied for three runs off Carlos Perez on a
two-out run-scoring single by Yoshii (it was his second major
league hit); a misplayed fly ball in right-center field off the bat
of Bernard Gilkey that dropped for a two-base error to score Yoshii
from first, and a run-scoring single by Alfonzo.
</P>
<P>
   An inning later, the arguments began. With one out in the sixth,
Mike Piazza rocked a ball to deep left-center that manager Bobby
Valentine thought had cleared the fence before bouncing back into
play. The umpires ruled that Piazza had to settle for a double,
however. One pitch after Valentine had lost the argument, Butch
Huskey drilled a run-scoring double, tying the game at 4-4.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with two out and nobody on in the top of the seventh, F.P.
Santangelo tried to bunt. The plate umpire, Jerry Meals, ruled that
the ball had first hit Santangelo's bat. But after Santangelo
argued vehemently, the umpires conferred and ruled that Santangelo
had been hit by the pitch. That brought Valentine out of the dugout
again, again to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   On Yoshii's first pitch after the argument, Orlando Cabrera
drilled a run-scoring double to left for a 5-4 Montreal lead,
before Bill Pulsipher came on to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   Rey Ordonez led off the bottom of the seventh with a single off
Perez and pinch-hitter Todd Pratt hit a run-scoring double. On came
the right-hander Miguel Batista to face the left-handed-hitting
Gilkey. He responded with a run-scoring single, one of his three
hits, to give the Mets their first lead.
</P>
<P>
   But Franco and the Mets just could not hold on.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   Despite the objections of the Yankees' owner, George
Steinbrenner, the home- and-home weekend series between the Mets
and Yankees on next year's schedule will stand as designed. The
teams will play June 4-6 at Yankee Stadium and July 9-11 at Shea
... Al Leiter, who is on the disabled list with a slight tear of
the patella tendon in his left knee, threw 50 pitches from a mound
Friday and remains on course to make his first start back on July
18. ``Al looked great,'' manager Bobby Valentine said. ``He felt
good, too.'' Said Leiter, ``I was able to throw with no pain.'' ...
Valentine chose to wait until Saturday to announce which field Todd
Hundley will play Saturday night. ``I'd just like to get him
here,'' Valentine said. ``Once he gets here, I think he'll be fine.
What we've missed from last year is that other guy in the outfield.
Last year, we were getting a lot of production from Carl Everett.
Hopefully, Todd will add to our overall production. If he's fine,
he's good and he's better than anything we've had, maybe better _
depending on how fine _ than any other outfielder. If he's not
fine, then I don't know what to do. But everything I've read in the
reports says he's fine.'' ... Carlos Baerga was out of the starting
lineup with a tight right hamstring. ``I don't know how one more
day after three days off is going to do,'' Valentine said. ``If
it's that close to where he can't run, it's that close to being
pulled. So I definitely have a concern.'' But Baerga did not seem
concerned. ``It's tight, that's it,'' he said. ``I can run, just
not at full speed. I'm playing tomorrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
